<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYSOC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LOSES STEAM IN SOCCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Clive Charles pounced on his opportunity.
Which was more than you could say for his team Tuesday night. The
U.S. men's soccer coach was asked how far Americans have come in
closing the ``talent gap'' with the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for someone to ask that question,'' Charles
said. ``I'm not going to talk about gaps. The gap is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   One wouldn't have known it from the 3-1 drubbing Spain inflicted
on the U.S. before 39,800 spectators on a cool, rainy evening at
Sydney Football Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., so resilient in advancing to the semifinals, dissolved
before the talented Spaniards and now plays for the bronze medal
against Chile on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Spain plays Cameroon for the gold on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Charles conceded his team was ``a yard behind'' throughout the
lopsided game but attributed much of it to fatigue from a punishing
schedule that included a 120-minute game Saturday night. ``The gas
tank was empty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles' players were more inclined to concede they ran into a
better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys on that team who are going to be
making a lot of money soon,'' U.S. defender Jeff Agoos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran out of legs, then we ran out of ideas,'' forward Josh
Wolff said. ``They scored on two of the first three chances. That
tells you what kind of stage we're on.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain was quicker, more cohesive and sure on the ball. The
Americans had trouble stringing together passes or even holding the
ball for more than a touch or two. A display of the sort that
brought back decade-old memories for followers of U.S.
international soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That final ball was never really there,'' Charles conceded.
``That first touch was never really there, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain and its collection of first-rate talent had much to do
with that. Most impressive was AC Milan striker Jose Mari, who
scored a goal and set up the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from a minus to a plus-plus,'' Spain coach Inaki Saez
said of Mari.
</P>
<P>
   Spain took control quickly. Jose Mari stripped U.S. defender
Danny Califf at midfield, brought the ball to the right side of the
box and crossed it to forward Tamudo, who needed only to extend his
leg to redirect the ball into the goal in the 16th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Spain went up 2-0 in the 25th minute. Califf fell while
defending Jose Mari at the top of the box and the Spaniard rolled
the ball through Frankie Hejduk's legs and into the path of Angulo,
who beat goalkeeper Brad Friedel from close range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is an easy game when you score early,'' U.S. midfielder
Peter Vagenas said.
</P>
<P>
   Agoos said Califf shouldn't bear too much blame. ``You're
talking about a guy making $30,000 in the MLS, trying to mark a
couple of guys who are going to make hundreds of thousands,'' Agoos
said. ``Spain has world-class strikers.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. closed to 2-1 in the 42nd minute when Angulo knocked
over Hejduk in the box, and Vagenas converted the penalty _ his
third in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks appeared to be back in it, but they never generated a
serious scoring threat in the second half as Spain dropped nine
players into the defense. The modestly talented U.S. midfielders
couldn't negotiate the thicket of Spaniards down the middle of the
field, and Wolff, the top U.S. scoring threat, was marked into
invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   Spain clinched in the 87th minute when Jose Mari put in a
deflection off the hands of Friedel, who had blocked a shot by
Tamudo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. played without midfielder Ben Olsen, who has a bad
ankle. Charles also made two quick substitutions, bringing on
Landon Donovan and Sasha Victorine in the 39th minute for Ramiro
Morales and Chris Albright, after it was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Donovan nor Victorine was a factor in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Charles spoke of the necessity of getting over the defeat and
focusing on the bronze-medal game. Winning a medal of any sort
would be a tremendous achievement for U.S. men's soccer, even if
this is, essentially, the nation's under-23 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even talking about this game,'' he said of Tuesday's
defeat. ``Now we have to try to win the bronze medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vagenas: ``If we can win the bronze, I'll hang the gold
medals around the Spanish guys' necks and not feel bad about it at
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
