<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TO FACE ASU WITHOUT ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ UCLA will be without strong safety Marques
Anderson against Arizona State while he recovers from an
undisclosed medical procedure he will undergo later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the outpatient surgery, which is planned for
Thursday, is neither life-threatening nor serious and is not
related to football. He said he didn't want to disclose the ailment
because of privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who had been the star of the defense in the first
three games, had a poor game against Oregon. He missed four
tackles, was called for a face-mask penalty and beaten for a key
fourth-down reception on the Ducks' go-ahead scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said his ailment had no effect on his performance
against Oregon. UCLA coach Bob Toledo disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurt and it was affecting his performance,'' Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he saw doctors Monday and they advised him to have
the surgery done immediately rather than wait until next week when
the Bruins have a bye.
</P>
<P>
   Either Audie Attar or Jason Stephens will replace Anderson in
the lineup. Attar was auditioned at the spot on Tuesday and
Stephens will get his turn today.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coleman recovering: If you don't have any expectations, then
you can't be let down. That's the view defensive end Kenyon Coleman
is trying to take while he recovers from last week's arthroscopic
surgery to remove torn cartilage from his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I have a chance to return,'' said Coleman, who was
injured against Michigan, underwent surgery last Tuesday and was
expected to be out four to six weeks. ``I don't want to be
disappointed. I'm not a doctor. I don't want to diagnose it. I know
(redshirting) is an option, but it's too early to think about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, one of two senior captains along with guard Oscar
Cabrera, has stitches in his left knee. But he seemed happy to be
wearing his practice jersey and walking gingerly around Spaulding
Field on Monday for the first time since he was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bummed out,'' said Coleman, who has been invited to play
in the Senior Bowl, a postseason all-star game that NFL teams use
to evaluate talent. ``I'm glad I can be out here (instead of)
sitting in my room taking painkillers.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Gloger arrives: Basketball player Spencer Gloger, who left
Princeton 10 days ago and returned home to Mission Viejo with the
intention of transferring to UCLA, signed a grant-in-aid on
Tuesday, two days before classes begin.
</P>
<P>
   Gloger, who will redshirt this season, has three years of
eligibility remaining. A 6-foot-7 guard, he started 28 games for
Princeton last season and averaged 12 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Game wanted: UCLA has officially agreed to play at Kansas the
second week of next season, filling a date left open this summer
when Missouri backed out of a home-and-away series with the Bruins.
UCLA is still looking for a season-opening game in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
