<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES CLINCH DIVISION IN 7-1 WIN OVER METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stands were speckled by the eighth inning, more
empty than filled. There was no reason to stay on a raw night when
the Mets played dead and their rival, the Atlanta Braves, buried
their hopes for a division championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves clinched the National League East title Wednesday
night with a 7-1 victory over the Mets, who still could clinch the
wild card with losses by Arizona and Los Angeles. It would be the
second season in a row in which the Mets captured the wild card,
but the Braves, as usual, can do better: they have now won nine
consecutive division crowns.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves (94-63) lose the rest of their games and the Mets
(89-68) win theirs, the teams would be tied for first place. The
Braves would be awarded the division championship because they won
the tie breaker Wednesday night with their seventh victory against
the Mets this year, ensuring them of a victory in the season
series.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Braves and the Mets end the season with the same
record, there would be no playoff for the division title because
both teams would have already qualified for postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have overcome substantial deficits to beat the Braves;
they trailed, 8-1, in the eighth inning on June 30 before mounting
a 10-run rally to win. But John Rocker was unavailable for that
game, and the controversial left-hander confounds the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, whose presence again necessitated several hundred police
officers, relieved Kerry Ligtenberg with two outs and two runners
on in the eighth. As he reached the mound, a beer bottle landed a
few feet behind the mound; Gary Cederstrom, the first-base umpire,
pointed out the fan who threw it, and the fan was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's first pitch was high, well out of the strike zone. But
he recovered and got Robin Ventura to fly to center, ending the
inning. In the ninth, the Mets singled twice off Rocker, bringing
life to the bundled-up fans who remained.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Bordick lined out to left, Jorge Toca struck out and
Todd Pratt grounded to third, where Chipper Jones tagged out Bubba
Trammell. Rocker pumped his fist, but there was no pile-on
celebration: the Braves are used to this.
</P>
<P>
   The winning pitcher for Atlanta was John Burkett (10-6), who
allowed three hits and one run in six innings to beat the Mets for
the third time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett's bat brought in the first Braves runof the game, after
Leiter appeared to have escaped trouble in the fifth. With one out,
Reggie Sanders doubled down the left-field line for his second hit
of the game. Leiter fanned Walt Weiss for the second out. But he
left a fastball up to Burkett, who punched it into right field for
a single. Sanders scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Furcal followed with a grounder between third and short,
reaching base on a single when Bordick's throw to second
short-hopped Edgardo Alfonzo. There were runners on first and
second with the middle of the order soon to bat, but Leiter got
Andruw Jones to ground out. Leiter would get only one more out.
Chipper Jones ripped a slider over the wall in left center to lead
off the sixth, increasing the Braves' lead to 2-0, and Andres
Galarraga followed with a hard-hit groundout to Alfonzo, who ranged
close to second base to field it.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez doubled to left past a diving Robin Ventura, and
Leiter walked Brian Jordan. Dave Wallace, the pitching coach,
visited the mound, but Leiter, after getting ahead of Sanders,
issued another walk to load the bases. Weiss chopped a ball softly,
between third and short, a troublesome area.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura charged it on an angle and threw home as he turned his
body toward the plate. It was a hurried, awkward throw, rare from a
Gold Glove winner like Ventura, and it was so wild that a diving
Mike Piazza could not get a glove on it.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez and Jordan scored, Sanders and Weiss took extra bases, and
Leiter left the game trailing, 4-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
