<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CLAIBORNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERRY CLAIBORNE, 72, COACH OF ALL-STAR SCHOLARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Va., Md., Ky., Texas, Mo., Ala.)   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Claiborne, who turned out good teams but even better
classroom stars in 28 years as the head football coach at Virginia
Tech, Maryland and Kentucky, died Sept. 24 at a hospital in
Nashville. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack after complications from two
abdominal operations last week, his son Jonathan said.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne was enshrined in the College Football Hall of Fame on
Aug. 11 but was too ill to attend the dinner in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne was the head coach for 10 years at Virginia Tech
(1961-70), 10 years at Maryland (1972-81) and 8 years at Kentucky
(1982-89). When he retired with a record of 179-122-8, he ranked
fourth in victories among active major college coaches, trailing
only Bo Schembechler of Michigan (234), Joe Paterno of Penn State
(219) and Bobby Bowden of Florida State (193). He took 11 teams to
postseason bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his players were Academic All-Americans and 87 made the
Southeastern Conference all-academic team. In his last season,
Kentucky won the College Football Association's Academic
Achievement Award as the major team with the highest graduation
rate, 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As John Clay wrote in The Lexington Herald-Leader: ``He was just
an old-fashioned coach with old-fashioned values who had the one
thing a lot of coaches and administrators preach, but too few
actually have. He had integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Prince, who played for Claiborne at Maryland from 1983 to
1986, said: ``He had his morals and his goals set in stone, and he
never bent for them. He had a strong faith. He didn't drink. He
didn't cuss.''
</P>
<P>
   When Claiborne retired, William F. Reed wrote in Sports
Illustrated: ``He wasn't glib like Lou Holtz or slick like Barry
Switzer or a constant contender for the national championship like
his mentor, Bear Bryant, but he loved football with all his heart.
He loved the contact on the field and the challenge of beating the
other guy both physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry David Claiborne was born Aug. 26, 1928, in Hopkinsville,
Ky., the eighth of nine children. He earned high school letters in
football, basketball, tennis and track, then went on to Kentucky,
where he played end, blocking back and defensive back under the
legendary Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, he earned a degree in mathematics and physical
education with high distinction. Then he coached football for two
years at a military school and nine years (eight under Bryant) as
an assistant at Kentucky, Texas A&AMP;M, Missouri and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   His prowess, especially on defense, earned him head-coaching
jobs, but conditions were never ideal. Virginia Tech was then a
small college playing big teams. He recalled that at Maryland, ``We
didn't even have a room big enough for a team meeting, and we had
to lift weights outside because there wasn't enough room inside
anywhere.'' At Kentucky, where he inherited a program in turmoil,
basketball was king.
</P>
<P>
   Several football players had been arrested on various charges.
The team was under National Collegiate Athletic Association
probation for recruiting violations. Discipline and academic
concerns were paltry. And the team had gone through four
consecutive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His first Kentucky team did not win a game, losing 10 and tying
one. His next went 6-4-1 and played in the Hall of Fame Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be remembered as a guy who did the best he could
with what he had, and that we tried to run a program that was
within the rules,'' Claiborne once said. ``Our rules were that if
that rule didn't make the kid a better person, a better student and
a better athlete, then we'd throw out the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1989 season, at age 61, he retired, saying his heart
was no longer in the game. His wife, the former Faye Hooks, whom he
married in 1951, said later that she thought Alzheimer's disease
was the reason.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; two sons, David of San Francisco and
Jonathan of Baltimore; two daughters, Katie Newell of Landenberg,
Pa., and Eileen Claiborne of Portland, Ore.; four grandchildren;
two step-grandchildren; and five siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tough, but he was fair,'' his wife said, ``and his
players loved him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   And his son Jonathan once said: ``He's somebody who really
practices the American ethic, that if you work hard, good things
will come to you. He did that, and he did it his way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
