<HEADLINE>
2000 A BANNER YEAR FOR BIRTHS IN L.A. COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
bc-BABY-BOOM-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JORDAN SMITH AND ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hospitals across Los Angeles report a baby boom
of millennial proportions: Births have risen by nearly 10,000
across the county during Y2K and up to 25 percent at some area
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Births for the year rose from 82,718 in the first eight months
of 1999 to 92,244 through August this year, the county Department
of Health said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But why is not exactly clear.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it may be the millennial madness couples who wanted to
have babies in the year 2000 while others speculate that a strong
economy may make now the perfect family planning time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something special that I wanted to have my last baby in
the year 2000,'' said 29-year-old Manuel Valencia, whose wife
Evangelina Castillo, 27, had a son on Monday at Northridge Hospital
Medical Center's Sherman Way campus.
</P>
<P>
   Other San Fernando Valley hospitals have reported up to 25
percent increase in births in September alone.
</P>
<P>
   Officials agree September is already the busiest month for
births, but many are still amazed by the numbers being reported
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eldridge H. Pearsall, who works at a Prenatal Woman's Center
at Northridge Hospital, said he has noticed the boom of babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was one of those demographic things that happen
every few years,'' he said. ``As the economy gets better, people
have more babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Eusebio, a licensed vocational nurse who works at the
hospital's maternity ward, said the month of September has been
especially hectic on the maternity ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost closed the department one day because we didn't have
room,'' she said. ``These are the babies made over the holiday
season,'' she said, adding that the upsurge could also be
attributed to some parents wanting to have millennium babies.
</P>
<P>
   For 40-year-old Patricia Arguelles of Lake View Terrace, giving
birth to a son on Monday in the year 2000 was a surprise gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pregnancy was totally unexpected,'' she said. ``I thought I
was done 10 years ago, and it happened he was born on the year
2000. That's incredible!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God blessed us with him on this year,'' she said of
her newborn son, Francisco Nathaniel Arguelles.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's Sherman Way campus has delivered 170 births in
September, up from the average of 125 to 150 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're opening up another area of the hospital to handle the
overflow of births,'' said Lori Solomon, a spokeswoman for
Northridge Hospital. ``It was a very happy millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   At Providence Holy Cross Hospital in Mission Hills, the hospital
is predicting a 25 percent increase in births in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of today, we've delivered 125 babies,'' said Tiffany
DeVall, a hospital spokeswoman. ``Over the past five years we've
delivered between 95 and 125 babies in September. So, this has been
a busy month for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley Presbyterian has seen only a small increase in births
this month, said spokeswoman Kelly Tarelka, but overall, births are
up 20 percent for the year 3,500 so far in 2000, versus 3,000 total
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cedars-Sinai Medical Center one of the city's largest hospitals
has also recorded increased births, about 10 percent this year,
according to spokeswoman Tasha Johnson. Cedars has delivered 4,259
babies so far in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``August and September always seem to be the biggest times
anyway think about it, holidays, celebrations,'' she said. ``But
why there are more this year in general? We don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
