<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVLIRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS LOSE TO HEAD TO THE PLAYOFFS WITH QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The New York Yankees have fielded a
slumping player here or there since they resumed their postseason
greatness four years ago, and sometimes their pitching staff has
been a little thin. But they have never had a hole as big as the
one they are expected to haul into the playoffs next week.
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever know about it if the Yankees are fortunate. If
they are lucky, their starting pitchers will pitch deep into games
and hand a big lead to three veteran relievers. But if patient
opponents wear down the Yankees' starters or a game lingers into
extra innings, then Manager Joe Torre will have to reach deep into
his bullpen, and even if he professes confidence in it, he cannot
have any idea of what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has been reluctant to discuss his postseason plans as the
Yankees stagger toward the playoffs. Orlando Hernandez allowed two
hits over eight innings Wednesday night, but after the Yankees'
Jorge Posada tied the score at 1-1 with a homer leading off the
ninth, Fred McGriff hit a game-winning single off Mike Stanton with
two out in the bottom of the ninth and Tampa Bay beat the Yankees,
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The loss prevented the Yankees from wrapping up the American
League East title, but they clinched at least a tie when the
Orioles defeated the second-place Toronto Blue Jays, 2-1, in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trailed, 1-0, when Paul O'Neill led off the eighth
with a single and Bernie Williams ripped a double, putting the
potential tying and leading runs in scoring position with nobody
out. David Justice rocked a liner to right field, where the
strong-armed Jose Guillen set himself and threw home, on several
bounces, and catcher John Flaherty tagged out O'Neill as he tried
to score standing up.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Hernandez relieved the Devil Rays' Albie Lopez to start
the Yankee ninth and Posada hit his 28th homer to tie the game. But
after Jeff Nelson walked Randy Winn to lead off the bottom of the
ninth, Winn advanced to second on a sacrifice and scored the
winning run when McGriff singled.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have six solid pitchers, including the starters
Roger Clemens, Andy Pettitte and Hernandez, and the relievers
Mariano Rivera, Mike Stanton and Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The other four pitchers _ the starter Denny Neagle and three
relievers _ are as mysterious as the meat served in college
cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   One week from now, Torre might have to turn to his bullpen in
the middle innings and choose among Jason Grimsley, Dwight Gooden,
Randy Choate or David Cone, without any real sense of what he's
going to get. ``They don't have anywhere near the kind of depth
they had the last few years,'' one scout said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
