<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDY MORGAN COMMITS TO PLAY AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC received an oral commitment Tuesday from wide
receiver Chris Morgan of Taft High in Woodland Hills, the latest in
a line of football players for the Trojans who also run track.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan (6-foot, 170-pounds) is the defending state champion in
the 110-meter high hurdles, and his top mark of 13.94 seconds last
season was 13th-best in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He has 15 receptions this season for 247 yards and three
touchdowns and he had 24 catches for 409 yards and two touchdowns
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is the second wide receiver to commit to the Trojans this
week. William Buchanon of Oceanside decided to attend USC on
Monday. USC has eight commitments.
</P>
<P>
   __ Problem areas: Special teams were a primary focus of
Tuesday's practice and Hackett said USC would spend more time on it
every practice this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we may be able to make PATs,'' he joked. ``And maybe
block the punt rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Norm Katnik and Zeke Moreno both continued to work on punt
snaps. Against San Jose State, Katnik debuted as USC's punt-snapper
to give Moreno a break. One of the goals this week is to snap the
ball faster to punter Mike MacGillivray, who had a punt blocked
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball comes back pretty slow from what he's used to,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Team captains: USC players selected team captains for the
remainder of the season. Center Eric Denmon and tailback Petros
Papadakis are the offensive captains and tackle Ennis Davis and
linebacker Moreno are the defensive captains.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who suffered leg
cramps at the end of the San Jose State game, missed most of
Tuesday's practice because he had tightness in his calf muscle. He
is expected back today.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Trevor Roberts (sprained foot), who has not
played all season, practiced and said he will see his first action
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kris Richard, who played with a sprained knee last
week, said he expects to start against Oregon State, although he
might have to wear the knee brace he wore against San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Easy schedule: Oregon State coach Dennis Erickson hasn't been
too impressed with the Beavers' 3-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really played anybody, to be honest with you,''
Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State has defeated Eastern Washington, New Mexico and San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Redshirt issues: Hackett said the Trojans intend to play only
two freshmen _ tight end Alex Holmes and wide receiver Keary
Colbert _ this season. One player who will not officially redshirt
until after the season is No. 3 quarterback Matt Cassel of
Chatsworth. He will make every road trip, in case of an injury at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Several other freshmen expected to play, notably offensive
lineman Joe McGuire (back) and strong safety Matt Grootegoed
(mononucleosis), are redshirting because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   __ Last word: San Jose State nearly defeated the Trojans, but at
least one player _ Moreno _ refused to give the Spartans his full
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that some of the San Jose State players
were talking trash,'' Moreno said. ``But that's why they are there.
I'm humble enough to say that they played a great game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
