<HEADLINE>
VOTE USING TOUCH-SCREEN PLACES
</HEADLINE>
bc-VIDEO-VOTE-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It will be tough to come up with excuses for not
voting in the upcoming election now that Los Angeles County is
installing walk-in, computerized ``touch screen'' voting places
that will be open during the three weeks before the Nov. 7
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone registered to vote can do so at any of the nine special
voting places being set across the county,
Registrar-Recorder/County Clerk Conny McCormack announced. They are
expected to open Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   She said the new voting places would essentially open the polls
for several weeks, allowing more time for voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope turnout increases by making the process more
voter-friendly,'' McCormack said. ``If this becomes popular, which
we expect it will, we can open more sites and expand.''
</P>
<P>
   To vote at the special sites, registered voters don't need
documentation - just their name and address, and then they can cast
their ballot on the touch-screen computers, said county spokeswoman
Marcia Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Opening walk-in voting places for several weeks before the
elections has proved successful in raising voter participation in
some other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, more than one-third of the voter turnout the last
presidential election was attributed to early walk-in voting, made
available two weeks before elections to all voters since 1987, said
Jane Dees, spokeswoman for the Texas Secretary of State's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside County will be the first in California to replace
punch cards with touch-screen computers at every one of its 900
polling locations in November, spending some $14 million in the
process, McCormack said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that making the terminals available at all 5,000 Los
Angeles polling sites could cost roughly $90 million to $100
million. Whether Los Angeles decides to expand on the sites will
depend largely on how popular they become, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take things one step at a time,'' she said, adding
that the Secretary of State's Office will also be testing
experimental on-line voting in several counties, not including Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has contracted with Global Election Systems, which
has been certified by the state, to provide the computer services.
Other counties using the touch-screen computers at designated sites
include Marin, Monterrey, San Mateo, Trinity, and Tulare.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack said another potential touch-screen advantage is
cutting down on the manpower needed to count absentee ballots, and
speeding up the vote tally.
</P>
<P>
   Absentee voting in Los Angeles County has increased in recent
years. In the March 2000 primary, roughly one in six voters cast
their votes by mail, according to the Secretary of State's Office.
Statewide, absentee votes represented 23 percent of all votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of absentee voters shot up in the 1980s when the
requirement to show cause were eliminated,'' said Alfie Charles,
spokesman for Secretary of State Bill Jones. ``People like
convenience. They like the time flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura said the county expects some 500,000 to submit absentee
votes in the November elections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO VOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``Touch screen'' voting places at the following locations will
be open from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. on Monday through Friday from
Oct. 16 to Election Day, Nov. 7, and on the last two Saturdays and
Sundays before the election:
</P>
<P>
   Van Nuys - Registrar-Recorder/County Clerk office, 14340 W.
Sylvan St.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster - County Regional Center, 335 A East Avenue K-6 Main
Entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Norwalk - Main Registrar-Recorder office, 12400 Imperial
Highway, Third Floor.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills - Courthouse, 9355 Burton Way, First Floor.
</P>
<P>
   East Los Angeles - Centro Maravilla Community Center, 4716 E.
Cesar Chavez Blvd., Building B.
</P>
<P>
   Florence/Firestone - Registrar-Recorder's Office, 7807 S.
Compton Avenue, Second Floor.
</P>
<P>
   West Los Angeles - LAX Courthouse, 11701 S. La Cienega
Boulevard, Sixth Floor.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Los Angeles - City Elections Office, 700 E. Temple
Street, basement.
</P>
<P>
   West Covina - City Hall, 1444 W. Garvey Avenue, First Floor.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
