<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GOLD IS A FITTING END TO THE SUMMER OF VENUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Just after tucking away a nervous match
point, Venus Williams was trotting around the tennis court with a
racket in one hand and an American flag in the other. An
ambidextrous celebration for the ubiquitous Williams.
</P>
<P>
   For an entire summer, she has been everywhere, equally dominant
on different continents and under any circumstance. Upon her 32nd
victory in a row on Wednesday, Williams added a gold medal to the
Summer of Venus collection while undoing the Russian Elena
Dementieva, 6-2, 6-4, at the Olympic tennis center.
</P>
<P>
   It was typical Williams. In the fifth game of the second set,
Dementieva actually had fate going her way as she smacked a
backhand into the tape and watched it flop into Venus Williams's
side.
</P>
<P>
   A cheap point, any point, and it would have lifted Dementieva's
dragging spirits. But appearing out of nowhere, there was Williams,
darting from the baseline to within two feet of the net, slipping
her racket under the ball like a flapjack cook and flicking a get
right back to her opponent. Stunned by the development, unsure of
just what angle to take, Dementieva whacked the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has become the tour's dream squisher. One after one,
opponents have come at Williams with optimism only to leave
devastated. In a couple of weeks, Williams will gather her
back-to-school pencils and notebooks and plop down in a fashion
design class. And if a teacher or classmate should ask, ``So, what
did you do last summer?'' she can present the show-and-tell of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Her run of trophies began in July, back when she ended her
fortnight at Wimbledon by joyously spinning around the Center Court
lawn in victory while her father flashed a sign in the players' box
that read: This is Venus' party, no one else is invited.
</P>
<P>
   The private party continued through the summer, spilling over
into the U.S. Open, and then crashing in on Sydney. On Wednesday,
Williams was in position to create an opportunity only one other
player in tennis history has achieved: play for a gold medal in the
singles and in doubles. In 1924, Helen Wills won both. On Thursday,
Williams will join her sister, Serena, to play the Dutch pair of
Miriam Oremans and Kristie Boogert in the gold medal doubles match.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the team was supposed to perform. With the exception
of Lindsay Davenport _ who had to withdraw from the Olympics after
a foot injury _ the Americans have been as dominant as advertised.
On Wednesday, Venus Williams stood with the gold, and Monica Seles
was draped with the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, doubles player Lisa Raymond might be unimpressed. She
was the one left off the blueprint in Billie Jean King's design for
the Dream Team of tennis. The Americans were constructed to win.
Davenport's injury might have prevented the sweep of their
fantasies, but everything else has fallen into place for the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The only one in Venus Williams's way of a big finish to her
summer was the unassuming Russian. Dementieva is equally blonde and
sleek, but she's the un-Kournikova. At the end of August, She
arrived at the U.S. Open without sponsors, clothing deals or
million-dollar endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, she separated herself from Kournikova in another way.
Before anyone realized it, she had plowed her way through to a
Grand Slam semifinal, and gave Davenport a handful before exiting
the scene. Unlike Kournikova, her talent had turned heads. Unlike
Kournikova, she chose to play for her country in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   So, her arrival in the gold-medal game was not all that
surprising. With slashing ground strokes and a solid serve,
Dementieva was at least equipped to give Williams a difficult run
for her gold.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as she pummel the side pockets of the court with her
inside-out forehands, as much as she pumped backhands down the
line, Williams was unfazed. When on the run, able to uncoil her
body for maximum power, Williams is at her best.
</P>
<P>
   The proof was in the first set. Despite a couple of hiccups in
her serve, Williams turned her opponent's best shots into winners
for herself, gradually wore down Dementieva's confidence and came
away with a 6-2 first-set certification of her dominance. One day,
Dementieva might develop a strategy. But on this day, she was just
another bystander during the Summer of Venus.
</P>
</TEXT>
