<HEADLINE>
THE MYSTERIOUS TALE OF A TAPE THAT WAS STOLEN GETS STRANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The campaign of Gov. George W. Bush asserted on
Tuesday that leaked information about a federal investigation into
stolen debate materials had raised questions about whether the
probe was proceeding in an fair manner.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign issued its complaint on Tuesday in response to a
story by the Dallas Morning News in its online editions saying that
the FBI was focusing its investigation on an employee of an
Austin-based media firm that is producing Bush's campaign
commercials, Maverick Media.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications
director, said the campaign was convinced the employee, Yvette
Lozano, was innocent. And she asserted that the release of
confidential information about the investigation had raised
questions about political tampering by the Clinton administration
to help Vice President Al Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises questions about whether the investigators are
being allowed to conduct an objective investigation,'' Hughes said.
She added that the campaign manager, Joe Allbaugh, had raised
similar concerns in a telephone conversation on Tuesday afternoon
with the FBI director, Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, an FBI spokesman refused to say whether or
not agents had interviewed Lozano. ``All I can say is we have
initiated a preliminary investigation,'' said the spokesman, Paul
Bresson. ``At this point, we can't even determine if any federal
laws have been violated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kym Spell, a spokeswoman for the Gore campaign said on Tuesday
night, ``We have a great deal of faith in the FBI investigators who
are on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``For Karen Hughes to suggest otherwise is not just
an attack on the Gore campaign. It's an attack on the FBI. And it
raises question about why the Bush campaign doesn't want the FBI to
get to the bottom of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI opened its investigation after former Rep. Thomas
Downey, who has assisted Gore in debate preparations, turned over a
package he had received on Sept. 13 containing a video of a mock
debate between Bush and Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., as well as some
briefing books. The package carried an Austin postmark.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Gore campaign suspended a 28-year-old campaign
worker who had bragged to a friend that the Democrats might have a
``mole'' inside the Bush campaign. Gore's aides said that the
suspended worker, Michael Doyne, had made the story up.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hughes complained that the FBI did not seem to be
taking Doyne's case seriously enough. ``I hope the FBI and the
federal law enforcement agencies would follow up on that boast by
looking at computer hard drives to determine whether in fact there
is any substance to those comments,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   She also rejected out of hand assertions by Molly Beth Malcolm,
chairwoman of the Texas Democratic Party, that the pilfered debate
materials were actually sent to Downey by Karl Rove, Bush's chief
political consultant. Democrats contend Rove bugged his own
campaign office during the 1986 gubernatorial campaign in order to
cast aspersions on the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News reported that Lozano could be seen on a
Postal Service surveillance videotape mailing a package on Sept.
11. Lozano told the paper on Tuesday that she was returning a pair
of $19.99 Gap khaki pants for her boss. To back her story up,
McKinnon produced the pants Gap had sent him in exchange for the
returned pair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
