<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS WON'T CELEBRATE WILD CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sports of The Times)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets had a Hamlet dilemma Tuesday night: to be or
not to be celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets can win Wednesday night's game with the division
champion Atlanta Braves after Tuesday night's 7-1 loss, they would
clinch the wild-card berth in the National League playoffs for the
second straight season. But don't expect them to rush to the mound
in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not celebrating,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general
manager, said. ``Our goal is to win the division. The wild card is
a fallback.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets would be allowed to smile. ``And they can hug each
other,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they would be in the playoffs, looking forward to
opposing either the San Francisco Giants or the St. Louis Cardinals
in a National League divisional series next week.
</P>
<P>
   And if both the Arizona Diamondbacks and the Los Angeles Dodgers
also lost later Tuesday night, the Mets clinched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow,'' Phillips said with a sarcastic smile, ``we'll show
up before the game and have tea and crumpets.''
</P>
<P>
   But champagne sprays in the clubhouse, no matter what. Not for
clinching the wild card. And that's as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   If you're on a wild-card team, it would be embarrassing to even
wave two fingers, as if to say, ``We're No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all a wild card is: the second-place team with the best
record. It's even incorrect to say that any team has ``won'' the
wild card because the team hasn't really won anything. All it has
done is ``earn'' the wild card. Even a divisional champion hasn't
really won anything to celebrate. The Braves understand that. When
they clinched their ninth consecutive divisional title Tuesday
night, they hardly whooped.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card is baseball's consolation prize. You don't
celebrate a consolation prize. You just accept it. Say ``thank
you'' and try to win the big prize, the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Those in favor of a wild-card celebration remember how the Mets
celebrated their wild card a year ago, but that was a different
scenario. More emotional. More unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Entering that final weekend, the Mets thought they had no
chance. But when they won their last three regular-season games
against the Pittsburgh Pirates at Shea and the Reds collapsed in
Milwaukee, the Mets were suddenly in Cincinnati for a one-game
playoff that Al Leiter won with a two-hit shutout.
</P>
<P>
   That sudden success deserved to be celebrated, but still with
some restraint because those Mets hadn't really won anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although those Mets ambushed the Arizona Diamondbacks in the
divisional series, they still hadn't really won anything. And when
they lost the NLCS to the Braves in six games, they definitely had
not won anything.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the wild card is just a steppingstone across the
raging river that is baseball's postseason.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the Florida Marlins used that steppingstone, then
knocked the first-place Braves out of the NL playoffs and went on
to win the World Series, the only wild-card team to get to the
other side of that raging river.
</P>
<P>
   So these Mets know it can be done because it has been done.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card, as popular as it is these days in the American
League's five-team dogfight (Seattle or Oakland, Cleveland, Toronto
and Boston), also has a weakness: the lack of urgency for a team to
try to finish in first place if it is comfortably ahead in the
wild-card race, as the Mets were even before their three-game
series in Atlanta a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they were virtually certain to retain the wild card, the
Mets seemed to shrug off losing the first two games in Atlanta a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a baseball team had to finish first in its
league or in its division to qualify for the postseason. The wild
card was introduced in 1994, although a wild-card team was never
determined that year when the final two months of the regular
season and the entire postseason, even the World Series, were
canceled by a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball purists still wish the wild card did not exist. Major
League Baseball has postponed serious discussion of a proposal to
split 32 teams into eight divisions of four teams each, with only
the eight first-place teams qualifying for the playoffs. Maybe
someday that proposal will be adopted. If it is, there won't be a
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   And there won't be a reason to wonder if a team should celebrate
or not celebrate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
