<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-OPEC-MEETING-SFCHRON &LR;      09-27 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEETING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OIL PRICE FEARS HAUNT OPEC MEETING  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ As an unusual collection of sheiks, emirs, presidents
and other potentates gathers Wednesday in Venezuela to talk about
oil, power and money, the rest of the world is looking on nervously
but also with a bit of hope.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day summit in Caracas by the 11 member nations of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has consumers in the
United States and elsewhere wondering whether more bad news is
ahead for gasoline and heating-oil prices, which have risen to near
10-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC meeting marks a new phase in the growing international
struggle over oil. Western nations are increasingly jittery about
Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez's campaign to unify OPEC, sustain
oil prices _ which have more than tripled since he took office last
year _ and return the organization to its 1970s position of power
and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent price shocks, however, not all is gloomy for
the West.
</P>
<P>
   There have been signals recently of cooperation across the
formerly vast chasm between the world's petroleum producers and
consumers, and Chavez deserves much of the credit, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1999, he has helped bring a semblance of
unity to OPEC, which had been virtually paralyzed since the early
1980s. Venezuela, in fact, was known previously as the most
notorious ignorer of OPEC production quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's aggressive advocacy of price stability _ to the extent
that OPEC can influence it _ has opened the way for a dialogue on
how to minimize the violent price swings that have caused severe
economic damage among both producing and consuming nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a fair price _ one that is not too high or too low,
but is stable and convenient for both producers and consumers,''
said OPEC President Ali Rodriguez, who is Venezuela's oil minister
and was once a leftist guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that OPEC wants to bring oil prices from their
current average level of $31.87 per barrel down to the group's
stated goal of a dependable price ``band'' that floats between $22
and $28. Adoption of the band has been a prime achievement of
Chavez and Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Whether OPEC can _ or really wants to _ work with consumer
nations for the benefit of all may become clearer amid the summit's
pomp and ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Heads of state from Iran, Nigeria, Indonesia, Qatar and Algeria
arrived in Caracas Tuesday. Also taking part are royalty and other
top officials from Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait,
Iraq and Libya, as well as the oil ministers from nonmembers
Mexico, Russia, Norway and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez initially raised eyebrows by inviting Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein and Libyan leader Moammar Khadafy _ archenemies of
the West _ but they declined out of fear of assassination attempts
should they venture abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints by some that the summit is a publicity stunt
aimed at raising Chavez's global profile, the mood in the
Venezuelan capital is triumphal, with art festivals dotting the
city and fireworks crackling in the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and common citizens alike say the summit
culminates what they see as their nation's long-deserved ascent to
world prominence. Public support for Chavez, who won re-election in
May, appears to have received a big boost.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is the first since 1975 for heads of state from
OPEC, which produces up to 40 percent of the world's petroleum and
holds 75 percent of proven reserves. Although OPEC oil ministers
have met regularly to discuss prices, their nations' bitter
disputes _ for example, the bloody 10-year war between Iran and
Iraq, and Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait _ have prevented the
organization from effectively controlling prices or assuming any
larger diplomatic importance.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say that Chavez and Rodriguez have been working hard
behind the scenes to keep these rivalries from boiling over into
outright conflict at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can keep the leaders from each other's throats and
have them come out with a bland declaration that everybody signs,
the summit will have been a great success and OPEC will be
strengthened,'' said one Caracas-based diplomat who requested
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC member nations come to the conference with their own
priorities. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --Iran, Iraq and Libya head up the contingent opposed to any
lowering of prices that might benefit the West; all three also &LR; 
 &LR; suffer from serious economic problems that are partially mitigated
by the current high prices.
</P>
<P>
   --Saudi Arabia, with by far the largest proven reserves, is
usually accommodating to Western requests to step up production, in
large part because it relies on the U.S. military for protection.
</P>
<P>
   --Nigeria, desperately poor and riven by ethnic and religious
unrest, is already producing at maximum capacity, so it cannot take
advantage of any increases OPEC agrees to.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting Washington's uneasiness about the turbulent politics
surrounding oil, American diplomats have kept mum about the summit
except to repeat their frequent calls for stepped-up production. In
fact, it has been U.S. policy to have no direct diplomatic contact
with OPEC, calling it an anti-competitive, anti-free-market
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But that stance weakened last week, when Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson called Rodriguez to give him advance notice of President
Clinton's decision to release oil from the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture worked. Rodriguez publicly thanked Richardson for
the courtesy and expressed support for Clinton's move _ quickly
undercutting a groundswell of opposition from other OPEC members,
including normally pro-U.S. Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for cooperation are aided by the fact that current tension
between oil-consuming nations and OPEC ``is different from the
conflict in the 1970s,'' said Daniel Yergin, president of Cambridge
Energy Research Associates and a Pulitzer Prize-winning author on
oil politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North-South confrontation is mostly history. OPEC nations
don't want to be left out of the new economy,'' he said. ``Most
producers are well aware of their interdependence with consuming
nations. Some have a considerable part of their national wealth
invested in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Yergin and other analysts say that despite OPEC's newfound
pragmatism, its members have little room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Oil producing nations _ OPEC members and nonmembers alike _ have
less extra production capacity than at any time since the
mid-1970s. So when speculators drive up prices, as they have
feverishly in the past several months, price bubbles result, and
OPEC is helpless to pump more crude to drive the levels down.
</P>
<P>
   It also leaves oil producers vulnerable. Price crashes after
speculative run-ups in the early 1980s, the early 1990s and again
in 1998 devastated producing nations _ as well as U.S. domestic oil
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, for whom oil revenues make up 60 percent of gross
domestic product, was thrown into a deep recession by each price
drop. The ragged slums stretching all  &LR; around Caracas and other
cities are still full of jobless workers who were driven into
poverty as a result. The official unemployment rate is 15 percent,
and somewhere between 60 and 80 percent of Venezuela's 23 million
people live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the price crashes forced domestic oil
producers to abandon much-needed investment programs, leaving them
unable to raise production when prices soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil market is strong, volatile and illogical,'' said Alan
Viergutz, an oil analyst in Caracas. ``Speculation needs to be
brought under control.''
</P>
<P>
   This, however, would seem to be possible only when excess
capacity becomes available. The effect since Clinton ordered the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve release _ prices have fallen nearly $6
from last week's high of $37.80 _ may be an example.
</P>
<P>
   As for the increased cooperation between consumers and producers
that OPEC talks about, Viergutz observed: ``The big question in the
long term is whether that will occur. In the short term, it's where
prices are going to wind up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although OPEC leaders have frequently reaffirmed their desire to
hold oil prices within the $22-28 band, they often complain of
being ignored when they press their argument that the high fuel
prices in consuming nations are caused largely by taxes and complex
environmental regulations on fuel quality.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez points out that while crude oil prices have dropped 41
percent in real terms since 1991, European Union nations have
raised oil taxes by an astronomical 350 percent. OPEC leaders note
bitterly that the $30 to $35 they receive for a barrel of oil is
far less than what the British government earns through its gas tax
_ the equivalent of about $140 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez told a nationwide radio audience Sunday: ``How nice it
would be if (Western nations) also lowered prices for the things
they sell us, lowered the prices of computers, of medicines, of
cars _ and the interest rates on foreign debts.''
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Secretary-General Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria insisted the
same day: ``We are not going to allow ourselves to be pushed into
(releasing) more oil than the market needs. The last time we did
that, the prices went down to $10 a barrel _ and nobody was sorry
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done our part. We hope they cooperate by lowering
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Compromise on these issues may be harder to reach than simply
agreeing on strategic oil releases that could keep prices stable.
At a meeting last weekend in Prague, the world's wealthiest nations
ruled out lowering oil taxes and insisted that more oil be pumped.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez made clear in a televised address Monday night that
the time for taking orders has passed: ``OPEC is rising up again
from its fallen position on the ground, and Venezuela has played a
fundamental role. The balance of the universe is at stake here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
