<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EDUCATION-CAMPAIGN-SF     09-27 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH, GORE PUT EDUCATION PROPOSALS TO TEST  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Presidential candidates Al Gore and George Bush
sound remarkably alike as they crisscross the country, talking
about their education policies.
</P>
<P>
   Education is at the center of their campaigns, and they use the
same buzzwords: accountability, basic skills, parental choice,
class-size reduction.
</P>
<P>
   At Sequoia High School in Redwood City Tuesday, Bush said the
nation must ensure every child in every public school is challenged
by high standards and has the opportunity to pursue their
educational dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore wants ``revolutionary improvements'' in
schools to be America's ``No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath generalities are some major differences in how the
Democratic vice president and the Republican governor of Texas
would change the nation's more than 90,000 elementary and secondary
schools _ about $120 billion in differences.
</P>
<P>
   That is the amount separating the $47 billion Bush wants to give
schools over the next 10 years and the $170 billion Gore wants to
spend on programs and tax incentives, an amount that would increase
federal education spending by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pouring that kind of money into public schools would be a major
change for the federal government _ its financial involvement in
the nation's school systems is fairly small.
</P>
<P>
   In California, federal money represents just 9 percent of the
nearly $50 billion spent on kindergarten through Grade 12 public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a role for the federal government,'' said Marian
Bergeson, former education cabinet secretary for GOP Gov. Pete
Wilson. ``It should facilitate efforts at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing federal money after federal programs that are
operated out of Washington has traditionally shown no improvement
in student performance,'' Bergeson said in defense of Bush's
education policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spending priorities are $8.2 billion to increase grants
to low-income students and $5 billion to help poor children in
kindergarten through Grade 2 learn to read.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $2 billion would help low-income parents pay for
after-school programs for their children.
</P>
<P>
   He would also require students in Grade 3 through Grade 8 to
take standardized math and reading tests annually much as
California already requires of its second-graders through high
school juniors.
</P>
<P>
   Students in low-performing schools could receive vouchers for
private schools or tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's two biggest-ticket items are $20 billion more for special
education and $50 billion to offer preschool to every 4-year-old, a
major new federal entitlement program.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to increase access to computers, rehabilitate
dilapidated schools, hire more teachers and pay them more money,
including $5,000 bonuses to teachers at schools who meet academic
performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gives states more control over education policy. States
would set their teacher certification standards. They would set the
performance standards for their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would take some 60 federal programs and lump them into five
broad categories to give states more spending flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   But, in his quest to woo the middle-of-the-road voter Bush
breaks with the more conservative elements of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bob Dole ran on a GOP platform that called for
the elimination of the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year's Republican National Convention, Bush
intervened to make sure that was not in this year's platform.
</P>
<P>
   He even calls for an expansion of the department's authority by
giving it control of Head Start, the preschool program for
low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush favors vouchers but their use would be limited to
low-income students in schools that do not improve after three
years. The money, $1,500, could be used to pay for tutoring or
cover some of the costs of a private school.
</P>
<P>
   Gore opposes vouchers. But like Bush, he champions some
traditional GOP ideas, such as rewarding schools that show academic
improvement and punishing those that do not.
</P>
<P>
   He also trumps Bush on charter schools _ public schools
independently run by parents or community groups.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to double the number of charter schools at a cost of
$300 million. Gore would triple them for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   State Superintendent of Public Instruction Delaine Eastin, a
Gore backer, chides Bush for his tax cut, which reduces how much
can be invested in schools.
</P>
<P>
   She praises Gore for investment in preschool programs and his
commitment of $8 billion in tax incentives to encourage repair of
aging schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is a better vote for children,'' Eastin said. ``Having a
massive tax cut before you pay off the deficit is pushing off the
debt to our children. It's immoral for us not to pay down the
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion we ought to really worry about these old
schools whether in San Francisco or Hayfork seems to me something
the Gore people have acknowledged and the Bush people haven't,''
Eastin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeson counters that much of the recent changes in
California's education system are modeled on changes instituted by
Bush in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is very consistent with the direction we've taken,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
