<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MICROSOFT-SCOTUS-SFCH     09-27 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SCOTUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SUPREME COURT REJECTS GOVERNMENT REQUEST OF QUICK REVIEW
OF  MICROSOFT CASE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS and CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp., facing a possible breakup of the
company by antitrust authorities, scored an important tactical
victory Tuesday as the U.S. Supreme Court rejected a government
request that it take up the landmark case against the software
giant.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the case will go to a federal appeals court, which is
widely seen as a friendlier venue for Microsoft's claims that it is
nothing more than an aggressive competitor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, by prolonging the judicial process, Microsoft
will be able to argue that circumstances have changed and that it
is no longer the dominant player it once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big win for Microsoft,'' said Hillard Sterling, a
Chicago antitrust lawyer. ``Time is clearly on Microsoft's side as
competitive forces evolve in these markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust case is viewed in Silicon Valley as a litmus test
for the frequently cutthroat business practices that characterize
the high-tech industry _ practices that some say stifle competition
and limit consumers' choices.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia said it wants
both sides to propose schedules for future hearings by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most legal experts expect the case to eventually make its way to
the Supreme Court, perhaps a couple of years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But by having the Court of Appeals take a crack at it first,
Microsoft is hoping to get some of the complex legal matters out of
the way so the high court can address loftier questions concerning
the role government should play in ensuring a competitive
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This favors Microsoft because it's what Microsoft wanted,''
said Allan Van Fleet, a Houston antitrust lawyer. ``Every day that
there's not a final judgment is another day Microsoft is not
exposed to a breakup order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today is the day that divestiture died as a
solution,'' said William Kovacic, a law professor at George
Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; New Developments
</P>
<P>
   Although the appeals court will continue to examine issues that
were at the core of the government's case when the antitrust
proceedings began in 1998, legal experts said the court's judges
will not be able to overlook subsequent developments.
</P>
<P>
   These developments, including America Online's acquisition of
Netscape and pending takeover of Time Warner, and the growing
popularity of the Linux operating system, could affect their
perception of the case, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, for one, is counting on just such a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has completely changed since the case was first
filed,'' said Jim Cullinan, a spokesman for the company. ``I mean,
no one talks about browsers anymore, and that was the heart of the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Microsoft remains ``very confident'' that it will
prevail in the court of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Department of Justice, which had argued that
the case is too important to the U.S. economy to wend its way
through the appellate process, put on a brave face Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to presenting our case to the court of appeals
as expeditiously as possible,'' said Gina Talamona, a spokeswoman
for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is appealing a ruling earlier this year by U.S.
District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson that the company
illegally protected its Windows operating system and Internet
Explorer browser by bullying technology firms into excluding rival
software.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ordered that Microsoft be split into two different
companies, one centered on Windows and the other on all its other
products, including the Office suite of applications.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup order was subsequently placed on hold pending the
outcome of the appellate process.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court voted 8 to 1 to prevent having the case
hop-scotch over the appeals court, as the government and 19 states
had sought. Only Justice Stephen Breyer dissented, saying ``the
case significantly affects an important sector of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, Chief Justice William Rehnquist said he
saw no reason to disqualify himself even though his son is a
partner at a Boston law firm that works for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates will be cheered by
the high court's decision is that the court of appeals issued an
earlier ruling in Microsoft's favor.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the court ruled that Judge Jackson had misstepped
in ordering Microsoft to detach its Web browser from the Windows
operating system. The appeals court said Microsoft had not violated
antitrust regulations by bundling the two products together.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, the Chicago lawyer, said the appeals court will react
with ``great skepticism'' to Jackson's final ruling, which all but
ignored the earlier appellate decision.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; A Favorable Forum
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ``has every indication of being a more
favorable forum to Microsoft,'' agreed Daniel Wall, a San Francisco
antitrust lawyer and a former clerk for the appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of the seven appellate judges' political leanings
and past decisions, he said, ``It is fairly predictable that four
of them will be philosophically inclined toward Microsoft's
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this means that they're going to win,'' Wall
emphasized. ``It's just a pretty good forum in which they can feel
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Sims, a Washington antitrust lawyer, said that ``it's
hard to say anything other than that this a reasonably technically
competent court'' and that ``it's hard to find it strongly biased
one way or the other in favor or against government actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling said Microsoft will undoubtedly draw the appellate
court's attention to an often-cited quotation from Learned Hand, an
influential federal judge who passed away almost four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hand wrote that ``the successful competitor, having been urged
to compete, must not be turned upon when he wins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the crux of Microsoft's argument,'' Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Justice Department also can exploit Hand's wisdom by
noting his belief that ``great industrial consolidations are
inherently undesirable, regardless of their economic results.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Sterling said Microsoft probably will be victorious
in both the court of appeals and the Supreme Court. ``Judge
Jackson's decision just doesn't hold water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Fleet, the Houston lawyer, said an ultimate high court
ruling will depend heavily on how much sway Justice Breyer has over
the proceedings. Breyer, he said, ``is a believer in antitrust laws
being enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a potential wild card looms in November's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Economides, an economics professor at New York
University's Leonard N. Stern School of Business, said he thinks
that whoever wins the election may choose to weigh in on the
Microsoft case and seek an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either Bush or Gore may find a way to compromise,'' he said.
``They both know that the markets move much faster than the legal
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, at least, was quick to express its pleasure with
Tuesday's ruling. Microsoft's stock rose $1.44 to close at $62.69.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
