 DUMB AND DUMBER IN DALLAS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ All the news that flits into print...
<P>
   --Dumb: Terrell Owens classlessly taunting the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   --Dumber: Owens' agent reading a prepared statement of
contrition that sounds as much like Owens as this column sounds
like the Gettysburg Address.
</P>
<P>
   --Cutting across Union Square Saturday, Shelley Daniels asked a
stranger, ``Today's the 23rd, right?'' Stranger said, ``I'm sorry,
I don't know. I'm not from around here.'' Some strangers are
stranger than others.
</P>
<P>
   --Florida native Eric Eisen, reading Tuesday's Chronicle, was
shocked to see that Everglades devastation is worse than he
thought. On our map, Fort Myers got sucked all the way to the east
side of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Eric, this is quake country, we're not all hung up on
geographical absolutism.
</P>
<P>
   --Maybe the ultimate redundancy, compliments of Arthur Louis:
Poor but honest.
</P>
<P>
   --You got your new car registration sticker, now you're worried
that someone will peel-and-steal it from your plate. DMV says
that's a common crime. David Morris advises: Slice your sticker
several times with a razor blade.  &UR; After  &LR; you apply it to plate,
silly.
</P>
<P>
   --Gordon Brownell notes that Supe candidate Meagan Levitan (3rd
Dist.) says in a letter to SF Weekly, ``I ... look forward to
working closely with the size community.'' The  &UR; size community? &LR; 
Yes, I live at the corner of Portly and Stout.
</P>
<P>
   --Gov. Davis allows the parole of a woman who killed to save
herself. Gov says she must submit to marijuana testing.
</P>
<P>
   The woman did 15 years for a crime she'd probably get probation
for now. Why the pot testing? What's she going to do, get stoned
and kill a bag of glazed doughnuts?
</P>
<P>
   --Old-style S.F. class with a fresh face: The Hotel Mark Hopkins
unveiled its extensive remodel job. These are some sweet suites.
Bring the big plastic: The Cyril Magnin Suite goes for $3,000. Per
night. But the closet alone sleeps six.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street at the Fairmont, in the lobby men's room: A
pair of signed lithographs by Clase Oldenberg, it says on the
cards.
</P>
<P>
   My art adviser Clawed Money says, ``Imagine how much more
valuable they would be if they were the work of big-time
sculptor/pop-artist Claes Oldenburg.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the hotel has a lot of Claes.
</P>
<P>
   --I'm so glad Terrell Owens didn't score a third TD on Sunday. I
hear he planned to moon the Dallas Cowgirls. A felony in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   --Cranking up the volume: Two miles away from the Giants'
ballpark Sunday, windows were rattling from the PA music. Says
Cuffs Corbett, ``Pac Bell Park is the city's boom box.''
</P>
<P>
   --And you are a true fan if you find yourself walking down the
street whistling and woofing ``Who Let the Dogs Out?''
</P>
<P>
   --Does this guy own the hotel? At the Sir Francis Drake, doorman
Tom Sweeney's photo is on the room keys, luggage tags, postcards
and posters, and the Sky Room offers a Sweeneytini. And VIP guests
receive a Beefeater-garbed Sweeney doll. Please, no voodoo, Tom's
loading your luggage as fast as he can.
</P>
<P>
   --An ``F'' in flag to Kaiser Elementary in the Oakland hills.
First few weeks of school, no flags. Then, state flag flown  &LR; above &LR; 
American flag. And both left on pole overnight.
</P>
<P>
   --And an ``F'' in fairness to Oakland schools. At middle schools
in the poorer neighborhoods, all elective classes (art, music,
computers, etc.) got the axe.
</P>
<P>
   --Tiny Treasures of the Town, No. 4,739: The Light Opera Gallery
(460 Post), where for 30 years Eric Sinizer has catered to the
fancier of hand-crafted kaleidoscopes and Russian lacquer boxes.
Today, glass artist Steven Lundberg shows and talks his art.
</P>
<P>
   --At Betelnut on Union St., Judi Basolo wondered about the
decorative Japanese sign hanging in the bar. Judi's friend
translated: ``Diarrhea cures available here.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Judi, ``Give me an Imodium-mai-tai.''
</P>
<P>
   To go?
</P>
<P>
   --Art mocks life at tomorrow night's Mime Troupe production of
``City For Sale.'' See artists displaced by the dot-com tsunami,
mayor savagely satirized. At Cell Space, 20th and Bryant (call 415
863-9834).
</P>
<P>
   --In Cincinnati, some stores had to pull Wheaties off the shelf
because of an odd smell in the boxes, which feature the likeness of
local baseball hero Ken Griffey Jr. I guess the cereal's new slogan
is, ``Better smell your Wheaties.''
</P>
<P>
   --``Empty Chairs on Trial'' said the headline on the story about
Serbs trying Clinton and NATO in absentia for war crimes. Doug
Robertson wonders, ``If they are found guilty, will the chairs get
the chair?''
</P>
<P>
   --Tonight's Olympic best-bet: The freestyle high-dive
competition among steroid cheaters wearing flaming Speedos.
</P>
<P>
   --Lunch bummer: Levi Strauss, after years of welcoming all
comers to its company cafeteria at Levi Plaza just off the
Embarcadero, slammed the door on all but Levi employees.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of disappointed folks are now bringing brown bags and
sittin' on their Dockers by the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   --Yes, Bill Burke, the TV cameras  &UR; are  &LR; being installed around
the Chronicle newsroom for ``Son of Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   --Barnes and Noble's online university offers a course in Jerry
Garcia &AMP; the Dead. Textbook is local guy Blair Jackson's
now-in-paperback ``Garcia: An American Life.'' (No, not  &UR; Jeff &LR; 
Garcia.)
</P>
<P>
   Too academically challenging for me. I'm majoring in Herman's
Hermits.
</P>
