<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-EVOLUTION-TEACHING-SF     09-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-TEACHING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA SCORES HIGH MARKS FOR TEACHING EVOLUTION  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   California is among just six states that received high marks for
their teaching of evolution, while 19 states faired poorly and
Kansas flunked out, &LR;  with a curriculum deemed ``disgraceful,''
according to a new report that promises to fuel the ongoing debate
between science and religion.
</P>
<P>
   The report commissioned by the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation and
released Tuesday by the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, considers how well evolution is included in the state
science education standards of 49 states and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The states were each given a letter grade, with California and
five other states, Connecticut, Indiana, New Jersey, North Carolina
and Rhode Island, receiving a perfect 100 percent. They ranked high
for introducing at least some of the basic processes of biological
evolution early on, building on them later, making evolution the
centerpiece of the life sciences and maintaining the continuity of
historical sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five other states received grades between an A and C,
from very good to satisfactory. But six states _ Arkansas,
Kentucky, Wisconsin, Virginia, Alaska and Illinois _ rate an
unsatisfactory D, and 13 others an F or worse, which the report
says indicates their ``standards are quite useless for purposes of
teaching evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The states with a failing grade were: Wyoming, Maine, Ohio,
Oklahoma, New Hampshire, Florida, Alabama, North Dakota, Georgia,
Mississippi, West Virginia and Tennessee. Kansas's grade was
F-minus.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa was not included in the report because it allows local
districts to set education standards.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Johnson, a professor of law at UC Berkeley and an author
of books about evolution, was critical of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a pile of nonsense and the enlistment of the
cultural and financial power of the scientific enterprise in a
program of indoctrination and not education,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He called it part of an ``anti-religious movement'' that forces
students to trust science.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taught an ideology. They are told to believe and not
to ask any questions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the report, Lawrence S. Lerner, a professor
emeritus at the California State University at Long Beach produced
the report for the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation, calls ``creation
science,'' a ``pseudoscientific rival to evolution that the courts
have repeatedly held to be thinly veiled religion.'' He said that
objections to the teaching of evolution are expressed in elementary
and secondary education in various ways. In some states, the
fundamental concepts and facts are covered only briefly but the
word ``evolution'' is carefully avoided in favor of ``change over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In others, the ``subject is avoided altogether or barely
mentioned, reducing the sciences _ especially the biological
sciences _ to disjointed lists of facts,'' he says in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The teaching of evolution in schools evokes bitter controversy,
Lerner says, and indeed the issue has galvanized states in the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Board of Education made national headlines last year
when it dropped the big-bang theory of the origin of the universe
and revised science teaching standards to emphasize creationism
over evolution.
</P>
<P>
   In giving Kansas the lowest grade of all the states, Lerner
calls the state's science education standards a ``disgraceful paean
to antiscience.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Holloway, former chairman of the Kansas State Board of
Education, said the report was deceptive and ``very unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly they have an ax to grind about evolution,'' she told
the Associated Press in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's D-rated science standards earn a comment from Lerner
that ``It appears that young Kentuckians are to be sheltered from
any exposure to evolution and other dangerous words and theories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a problem for science literacy in this country,'' said
Molleen Matsunura,(cq) &LR;  of the National Center for Science
Education in Berkeley. ``It is not new, but it is something to
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that college science professors are reporting students
coming in unprepared, having never heard of evolution, and that
students who do not learn evolution will not pass the science
subject section of the SAT or the Advanced Placement test.
</P>
<P>
   Her organization, the National Center for Science Education,
which defends evolution in public science education, has gotten
involved in an average of 56 local or state debates over
creationism versus evolution every year. The issue has heated up so
much that by July 31 this year the organization had recorded 55
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   They have opposed a public school teacher who insisted on
telling students about his summer search for Noah's Arc, a school
board candidate who wanted creationism to be taught in county-run
education programs, and a teacher who invited a minister to teach
creation science in his public school class.
</P>
<P>
   Matsunura said California ranked high in the new study because
the State Board of Education has adopted a curriculum framework and
science standards that include the teaching of evolution. It also
approved a policy in 1989 stating that ``discussions of any
scientific fact, hypothesis, or theory related to the origins of
the universe, the earth, and of life'' are appropriate to the
science curriculum, while discussions of ``divine creation,
ultimate purposes, or ultimate causes'' are appropriate to the
history, social science and English curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Matsunura said it is important that teachers have their school
boards behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California and other states there are teachers who are
given a hard time by parents who do not want evolution taught. The
teachers can say, `I have to teach it because it is in the
standards,''' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
