<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DELIVERS HIS EDUCATION MESSAGE IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush came to the
Bay Area to send an education message Tuesday, but he repeatedly
downplayed the role of the federal government _ at one point
telling a questioner to ``write your governor'' with concerns about
teacher salaries.
<P>
   Bush's campaign touted his trip as an swing aimed at criticizing
what he has called the ``education recession'' under the
Clinton-Gore Administration. But it was also a junket to scoop up
campaign cash, with the governor scheduling three fund-raisers in
Silicon Valley and Bel Air which swept up $1.4 million for the
state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   With 41 days until the election, Bush -- though down double
digits in the polls here -- continued to insist he will campaign
and fight hard in California, and his campaign confirmed his plans
to return here in October.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas Governor's message in campaign events also
underscored the challenges of focusing on education as the lead
issue in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared at Sequoia High School in Redwood City flanked by
nearly two dozen high school students sitting at bright purple
I-Mac computers. But the teenagers mostly provided a backdrop. Only
one asked a question of Bush, who focused on answering questions
from an audience of local supporters and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Later, two students complained that Bush campaign volunteers
confiscated their Gore-Lieberman placards during the presidential
candidate's visit, and Principal Morgan Marchbanks said two
students appeared ``genuinely upset'' that Bush volunteers had
taken signs out of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting his outlook to that of Vice President Gore, Bush
told the crowd of about 200 there that the nation seeks ``a
president who is willing to talk about the hope and promise of
education, and mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for ``high standards, local control of schools,'' and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the old tired argument that measurement is too
intrusive, that measurement is racist,'' he said.``Let me tell you
what's racist: racist is moving children through the system without
understanding whether they can read or write, add and subtract.
That's racist. That's discrimination as far as I am concerned,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But in taking questions from the audience, Bush appeared to step
on his own education message.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do to raise teacher salaries, Bush agreed
teachers should be well paid. Then, he said: ``I would be wary of
some people running for federal office saying vote for me, ``I'm
going to make sure your teachers are well taken care of. There's
just not enough money of the federal level .... Therefore, I would
suggest you write your governor and make sure he makes education
the number one priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his support for school vouchers on a day in which
Gore announced his opposition to Proposition 38, the controversial
initiative on school vouchers, Bush did not take a position.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 38 would provide a $4,000 voucher to every family
sending children to private schools, regardless of their income.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state of California wants to do that, it's up to the
state of California,'' Bush said. ``I believe in local control of
schools. I don't believe the federal government ought to be telling
...California or the state of Texas how to run your business.''
</P>
<P>
   Another questioner wanted to know what he would do to reduce
class sizes, and Bush repeated his theme that was not the
president's job. ``Again, class size is really going to be up to
funding at the state level,'' he said. `(That's) really a function
of the public school budget...that's going to be up to the state of
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also made some flubs which appeared to mar his message.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on troubles in America's classrooms, he said, ``If you
don't diagnose an issue, you can't solve it.``
</P>
<P>
   On his approach to Israel, Bush said, ``I will have a
foreign-handed foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush appeared extremely upbeat about his prospects in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   To one questioner, he said, ``Now's your chance. You could be
talking to the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, the Texas Governor referred to `Vice President
Cheney and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was even more upbeat about his prospects in both a drop-by
at a Redwood City campaign headquarters and before a crowd of high
tech leaders at the home of Autodesk CEO Carol Bartz in Atherton.
``I'm here because I believe I can win the great state of
California,` he told the $1,000 a plate donors. `I like a good
competitive race. I think it brings out the best in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, a Bel Air fund-raiser at the home of entrepreneur David
Sapperstein, included meeting with local rabbis. The Bush campaign,
which had lately criticized Gore for dining with entertainment
bigwigs -- carefully noted that it included ``people from all
different sectors, from all over the city,'' and no major
entertainment figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Governor later appeared on the Larry King show in Los
Angeles, Bush was asked if he were worried about the debates, Bush
said, ``Not yet....I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said the reports of a campaign ``mole`' inside the Bush
campaign -- including a tape of Bush's debate practice session,
were disturbing. ``It's not one of my supporters. Somebody who's
for me is not going to be sending tapes to the Gore campaign,'' he
said. `We're gong to get o the bottom of it..and I look forward to
finding out who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle reporter Julie Lynem contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
