<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD BACK BUT NOT PLEASED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield was told by back specialist Jae
Chon that he wouldn't further irritate his back by playing, so he
was in the lineup for the first time in six games and back chasing
Duke Snider's single-season Los Angeles Dodgers home run record.
</P>
<P>
   And while Sheffield said his back felt much better and he was
glad to finish the season on the field rather than the trainer's
table, he also looked back on the Dodgers' disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a better season (than 1999),'' said
Sheffield, whose fifth-inning homer was his 42nd, one shy of
Snider's mar ``I know expectations were higher, which they should
have been. We're playing better than we did last year, but we just
didn't play better at the right times. Everything is about doing it
right when it counts and that's the way it's always been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do it in the first half. You have to do it in the
second half. It seemed like we picked up our play at the end, but
it seems like it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dodgers are playing their best baseball of the
season. Their starting pitching has been spectacular: a combined
1.73 past 14 games. That helped catapult them to a season-high 10
games over .500 entering Tuesday's game against San Francisco, the
first time in three seasons they've reached that level.
</P>
<P>
   Dreadful at home most of the season, the Dodgers were 8-2 with
three games remaining on the homestand. They also had won eight of
their last nine.
</P>
<P>
   How important is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I throw it out,'' Sheffield said. ``That's how it's always
been since I've been here. For three years, we've played this way
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield needed five walks to ensure him of his second straight
season of at least a .300 batting average with 30 homers, 100 runs,
100 RBI and 100 walks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Today's start by rookie right-hander Luke
Prokopec will be his last scheduled one of the season. Rookie
right-hander Eric Gagne, who left his last start after getting hit
on the right wrist, is slated to start Saturday in San Diego. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The tentative 2001 schedule, which must be OK'd by the players
association, has the Dodgers opening the season with a seven-game
homestand. It begins with a single game against Milwaukee on April
7, followed by three-game series against Arizona and San Francisco.
Originally, the Dodgers were going to open with one game at
Milwaukee, but the commissioner's office changed it upon request. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Tests on right-hander Ismael Valdes' right pinkie, in which he
experienced numbness that forced him to miss his start two weeks
ago, were negative. . . . Right-hander Carlos Garcia and shortstop
Joe Thurston were named the organization's minor-league pitcher and
player of the year, respectively. Both played at Class A San
Bernardino of the California League. Garcia was 17-7 with a 2.48
ERA and Thurston batted .303 with 70 RBI and 43 stolen bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
