u s BC-SCOTUS-GOLFCARTS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GOLFCARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE ON USE OF GOLF CARTS GOES TO HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking up its first case on the relationship
between disability law and professional sports, the Supreme Court
announced Tuesday that it would decide whether the golfer Casey
Martin has a legal right to use a cart rather than walk the course
during PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was a setback for the 27-year-old Martin, who
has a circulatory disorder in his right leg that makes it painful
and difficult to walk any appreciable distance. After the Tour
barred him in 1997 from riding a cart, saying it would give him an
unfair advantage in competition, Martin sued under the Americans
With Disabilities Act and won his case before two lower federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour filed a Supreme Court appeal in July, arguing that
the lower courts had invoked the federal law in a context where it
did not belong. ``It is essential to the nature of high-level Tour
events that all competitors, without exception, play by the same
rules,'' the PGA Tour said in its appeal to the justices. The court
will hear the case in January and decide it by early next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans With Disabilities Act prohibits discrimination on
the basis of disability in ``any place of public accommodation.''
</P>
<P>
   The statute defines discrimination as ``a failure to make
reasonable modifications in policies, practices, or procedures''
unless those modifications ``would fundamentally alter the nature''
of the activity.
</P>
<P>
   Given those phrases, the Martin case presents two basic
questions to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   First, is a golf course a ``place of public accommodation'' for
professional golfers during a tournament? The law itself lists golf
courses as examples of places of public accommodation, but the PGA
Tour is arguing that the definition applies only to the spectators'
areas, not to the competitors' area behind the ropes that the
public has no right to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The second question is whether, assuming the law does apply
behind the ropes, use of a cart represents such a fundamental
change in the nature of the competition that it cannot be
considered a ``reasonable modification.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour argues that walking a course four times during the
four days of a tournament _ a total distance of 25 miles or more _
is itself a test of stamina and endurance that is an inherent part
of the sport. The Tour told the justices that it was
``unprecedented for a federal court to order that a professional
athlete be allowed to compete without adhering to the full set of
substantive rules applicable to other competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's lawyers, not surprisingly, framed the issue quite
differently. Competition in golf is shot-making, not ``a race
against the clock or against human endurance,'' they told the court
in their unsuccessful effort to persuade the justices not to hear
the PGA Tour's appeal. ``If no rule of competition, regardless of
its purpose, can be modified to permit participation by people with
disabilities, then _ ironically _ sport would become the only
industry in America permitted to construct barriers to access that
are unrelated to performance,'' Martin's lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling for Martin last March, the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the 9th Circuit, in San Francisco, noted that even with a cart, he
had to walk about 25 percent of the course, because the cart often
cannot be driven directly to the ball. The pain of walking that
distance, as well as constantly getting in and out of the cart,
meant that Martin was hardly spared the fatigue shared by golfers
without his disability, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, it would have been surprising for the Supreme Court
to take up a case involving at most a handful of competitors in a
single sport. But almost simultaneously with the 9th Circuit's
ruling in Martin's favor, the federal appeals court in Chicago came
out the other way in a case involving Ford Olinger, a club pro from
Indiana who has a degenerative hip condition. The disagreement
between the two courts on the same issue probably persuaded the
justices of the need to issue a ruling. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
