</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LIEBERMAN'S TWO RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Sept. 27:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman has only a month to end his safety-net
campaign in Connecticut, where he is running for a third term in
the Senate as well as for vice president on Al Gore's ticket. His
Democratic colleagues in the Senate are pressing him to drop the
Senate re-election bid lest his seat be lost if the national ticket
wins. Even his own constituents oppose his dual candidacy by a
narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman should take the hints and resign quickly from the
Senate race. That would give state party leaders a chance to put
another candidate or candidates on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   With a line that sounds more self-protective than
public-spirited, Lieberman has maintained that if he drops out of
his Senate race this late, voters will be deprived of a primary
before the Nov. 7 election. But if he wins the vice presidency,
Connecticut voters are deprived of any choice at all for as much as
two years under the state's flawed election law. One person _
Connecticut's Republican governor _ would choose the new senator
from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has mistakenly refused to budge from his position,
saying that he and the people of Connecticut have ``agreed to
disagree'' on this issue. This situation may suit Lieberman's job
security needs, but it does not serve democracy or his Connecticut
constituents well.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
