<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKERS HAS WHAT DODGERS CAN'T OFFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I can think of, oh, a baker's dozen reasons the
Los Angeles Dodgers and their fans might dream of having Dusty
Baker as their next manager, assuming it's true that Davey Johnson
is about to be mercifully relieved of his duties.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is the best manager in the National League, proving it
again this season, rallying the San Francisco Giants from a
nine-game deficit to the West Division title. He's a popular
ex-Dodgers player, a Southern California native. He might be
available, since his Giants contract is up. And so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention he's the best manager in the National League?
</P>
<P>
   What I can't think of is a single reason Dusty Baker would want
to come here.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a smart guy like this ever leave the greatest managing
job there ever was?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, speaking about his future before Tuesday night's
Giants-Dodgers game, Baker didn't rule anything out and didn't rule
anything in. Leaving all bargaining chips on the table is smart
business for anyone who's about to enter contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess other people are thinking about it. I'm not thinking
about it,'' he insisted in the visiting manager's office at Dodger
Stadium. ``I'm just doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   But I'll say it: Baker-to-the-Dodgers simply isn't going to
happen. He knows it. And they know it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the difference between managing the Giants and managing
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 1995 and 1996, Baker managed the Giants to consecutive
sub-.500 seasons. They finished last in 1995 and 1996. He says he
didn't worry about getting fired, and he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Johnson is managing the Dodgers to a record that stands
11 games over .500 after Tuesday's 4-0 victory. He could wind up
with 89 wins _ the way they're playing now that it doesn't matter.
They have a shot to finish second. It's considered a foregone
conclusion that Johnson will be fired.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Baker survived those losing seasons is that he was
coming off a 103-victory performance as a rookie manager in 1993.
One reason Johnson probably won't survive this winning season is
that he was coming off an 85-loss season in his first try with the
Dodgers in 1999. Beyond that, though, it's a matter of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodgers manager is expected to win, and ever since the
O'Malley family sold out, it's or-else. A Giants manager is
expected to do his best with an underpaid roster of cast-off
players and yearn silently for a job with a richer club.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the low expectations have persisted, along with the
Giants' ``overachiever'' image, even though they've won more games
than anybody else in the NL West in the nearly eight seasons since
Baker was promoted from batting coach to manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on both sides. I played on the largest-market team
there is,'' Baker said of his eight seasons as a Dodgers
outfielder. ``We went to spring training expecting to win _
everybody expected us to win. I remember, playing here in L.A., one
year we lost to the Yankees in the World Series, and we were afraid
to go outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations are now the problem of an old friend of
Baker's _ Johnson, who dressed next to him and batted behind him
with the Atlanta Braves in the early 1970s, and who became a friend
and offseason fishing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were high expectations and when things don't work out,
somebody has to take the blame,'' Baker said, referring to the
Dodgers of 2000. ``When the team wins, everybody gets credit, and
when the team loses, you (the manager) get the blame. . . . When
you lose, (people think) it's like you've lost your desire or
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boils down to what kind of players you've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he is not flattered by the speculation that he'll
replace Davey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me,'' Baker said. ``I've got a job. I'm happy where
I am. It bothers me (because) they've already got a manager who's a
friend of mine. That's not fair to him and it wouldn't be fair if
it happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the point is that in San Francisco, it isn't going to happen
to Baker anytime soon. Why would he want to go anywhere and why
above all would he want to come here? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
