<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYTRKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES ADVANCES IN 200 HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ If Marion Jones was burdened by the scandal
enveloping her husband C.J.Hunter, she showed no signs of it today.
</P>
<P>
   In her first appearance on the track since public confirmation
came that Hunter had tested positive for the banned steroid
nandrolone, Jones won her heat in the 200-meter dash to advance to
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The former Thousand Oaks High standout was greeted warmly by the
Olympic Stadium crowd when her preliminary heat was introduced. So
sustained was the applause, it was as though the Australians wanted
Jones to know they are not going to cast stones at her for the sins
of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 24, broke well from the blocks and built a comfortable
lead before shutting down a few meters from the finish, the better
to conserve her energy for the long jump preliminaries that awaited
her later today.
</P>
<P>
   She was timed in 22.75, just ahead of Cydonie Mothersill, whose
strong finish brought her to within .03 seconds of the coasting
heat leader.
</P>
<P>
   Running in a later heat, Beverly McDonald of Jamaica posted the
fastest time of the morning with a 22.50. She was .03 seconds
faster than Susanthika Jayasinghe, who is from Sri Lanka but lives
and trains in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Jones qualified sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stated all along I think this is going to be the most
difficult day for me,'' said Jones, who already has won a gold
medal in the 100 meters. ``I tried to conserve a bit of energy in
that first round of the 200 (to save herself for the long jump).''
</P>
<P>
   Van Nuys resident Inger Miller, who was expected to offer the
stiffest challenge to Jones, pulled out of the 200 because her
strained hamstring isn't healed. So strong are the ill winds now
swirling around these Games, Miller reportedly is feeling pressure
to compete in the 400 relay relay no matter her fitness level lest
she be painted as a possible drug cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six athletes here have been outed for
performance-enhancing drug use (19 more than in the past three
Summer Games combined). The latest to fail a doping test was
Mihaela Melinte, the world-record-holder and reigning world
champion in the hammer throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanian was apparently the last to know. She was on the
track today, preparing for her qualifying throws when a track
official escorted her away. An IAAF spokesperson said the Romanian
Federation had been informed of the result and that it was the
responsibility of the Romanians to pass the information on to
Melinte.
</P>
<P>
   The number of failed drug tests is a serious matter, which makes
some of the offenders' excuses downright farcical. A Uzbekistan
track coach claimed the vials of human growth hormone he was trying
to smuggle through the airport here were to treat his baldness; a
German runner swore someone must have spiked his toothpaste with
steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Jones offered a public statement of support for Hunter Tuesday,
holding his hand at a press conference and saying stoically, ``I
have total and complete respect in him and believe that the legal
system will do what is needed to clear his name.''
</P>
<P>
   She was gracious with reporters today, but begged off after
answering two questions so she could cool down and prepare for the
long jump.
</P>
<P>
   In other events today, Camarillo High graduate Marla Runyan
advanced to the semifinals of the 1500 but just barely. She failed
to finish in the top six in her heat and was the next-to-last
runner to advance on the basis of time (4:10.83).
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two laps were very, very slow,'' she said. ``Maybe I
shouldn't have let that happen. I was really running within myself.
My goal was to finish in the top six (in the heat) and get into the
semifinal. As long as I make it in. That's all I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Favor-Hamilton led all 1,500 qualifiers with a time of
4:08.08. The top U.S. finisher from the U.S. Trials, L.A. native
Regina Jacobs, pulled out of the competition before the start
because of a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Drossin, a former Agoura High standout, ran 36th in the
10,000 meters and failed to advance. Drossin, who has had an
Achilles injury, had a time of 34 minutes, 40 seconds, nearly three
minutes slower than her winning time at the Trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
