<HEADLINE>
POSTCARD FROM THE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   G'day from Australia, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if David Letterman and Jay Leno co-hosted a late-night
talk show, and you've got a pretty fair idea what kind of
entertainment Australians are tuning into en masse during these
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Roy and H.G. are two comedic curmudgeons who cast a wry eye on
the Games for two hours every night, starting at 11 o'clock, on the
official Olympic channel.
</P>
<P>
   Forget performance-enhancing drugs; the biggest controversy of
these Games, as advanced by Roy and H.G., is the Australian Olympic
Committee's snub of the wombat as its officially licensed mascot in
favor of the boxing kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   Egged on by the two talk-show hosts, swimmer Ian Thorpe carried
a stuffed wombat to the awards stand after one of his races,
creating the sort of furor that hasn't been seen on an Olympic
awards podium since Nike spokesman Michael Jordan draped the U.S.
flag over his U.S.-allocated Reebok sweats in Barcelona in 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catch ya' later, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse
</P>
</TEXT>
