<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE RESUMES CAPTAINCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rob Blake returned to the ice Tuesday night with
the captain's ``C'' back on his Los Angeles Kings jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who recently resigned the position in a contract dispute,
approached coach Andy Murray an hour before the start of the Kings'
2-0 victory over the Phoenix Coyotes with a request Murray had been
hoping to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the captain here and I want to remain the captain as long
as I am a King,'' Blake said. ``This will not change the
negotiations. This is a business. But I think I took it way to
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Murray: ``That `C' always will be Rob's whether he is
wearing it or not. I hoped he would reconsider and I wanted him to
know that he didn't do something that couldn't be undone. Now he
has and we are very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake, 30, reclaimed the captaincy he has held the past four
seasons even though there has not been movement on a new contract.
He will be an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season and
resigned as captain after the Kings made a ``take it or leave it''
offer at the beginning of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Although the three-year $22.5 million offer wasn't far from the
$24 million Blake is seeking, he was angered the by the ultimatum.
The club left open the possibility of his return to captain and
decided not to name his replacement until the Kings' first game,
Oct. 6 at Washington. Left-winger Luc Robitaille, an alternate
captain last season, was expected to get the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice to see him make this decision, but it does not affect the
negotiations,'' said general manager Dave Taylor, who added he has
not spoken to Blake's agent Ron Salcer since talks broke down two
weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake's decision comes on the same day NHL MVP and top
defenseman Chris Pronger of St. Louis decided to end his attempts
to get a new contract. Pronger, not eligible for unrestricted free
agency until the 2006, was looking for a six-year deal for $10
million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who finished third in the voting for top defenseman, has
been a fixture in Los Angeles since he joined the Kings at the end
of the 1989-90 season after a college career at Bowling Green. He
lives year round in Manhattan Beach and replaced Wayne Gretzky as
captain to begin the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hot rookie: With the off-season losses of Garry Galley (free
agency) and Sean O'Donnell (expansion), retooling the defense has a
been a priority in the Kings training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Lubomir Visnovsky, drafted in the fourth round last June, has
been the most impressive newcomer. He scored the Kings' first goal
Tuesday night. Visnovsky, who scored 21 goals in 52 games last
season in his native Slovakia, picked up a loose puck inside the
Coyotes blue line and beat goaltender Sean Burke low to the stick
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speed and energy have really stood out in camp,'' Murray
said. ``This is his first year in the NHL but he really has shown a
lot of people that he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick Whistles: Craig Johnson, who missed the first two camps
of camp with a staph infection in his left ankle, scored the Kings'
second goal. Goaltender Jamie Storr went the distance and stopped
20 shots to record the shutout. . . . Unlike Saturday night, when
Ziggy Palffy and Marko Tuomainen were knocked out of the game as
the result of uncalled slashes, officials cracked down Tuesday.
Three slashing penalties were called on Phoenix in the first two
periods. Glen Murray and Bob Corkum were whistled for slashing
midway through the second period, giving the Coyotes a
five-on-three advantage for 30 seconds. . . . Ian Laperriere,
sidelined throughout training camp while rehabbing from
reconstructive surgery on his right knee, skated in uniform before
Tuesday's game. He will not be activated until Friday's game in San
Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
