<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTTON TUTORS YOUNG QBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brad Otton was pretty much done with football.
</P>
<P>
   The former USC quarterback, who led the Trojans to a 17-3
victory over Northwestern in the 1995 Rose Bowl, figured his
football career was over after a knee injury forced him to give up
his dream of playing in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   However, CSUN coach Jeff Kearin gave him an opportunity to get
back into the game and he took it: He has agreed to work with the
Matador quarterbacks after turning Kearin down last year.
</P>
<P>
   A couple weeks ago, Otton showed up on campus to visit former
USC assistant coaches Kearin and Dave Robinson and ended up at a
practice. He liked what he saw and on Tuesday joined the staff as
an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wanted to see if I enjoyed the coaching thing and so
far I do,'' Otton said. ``Being with Jeff and Dave, with the way
they run the team, I wanted to be around that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin is the head coach but also the offensive coordinator.
Otton's assistance will free Kearin to focus on other things for
which he normally doesn't have time.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, who played one year as a quarterback at the University
of San Diego, said Otton understands the nuances of the game well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings, obviously, hands-on gamesmanship on a level that we
don't have with me,'' Kearin said. ``He can really teach the
younger guys the game and can really refine (Marcus Brady's)
abilities. Brad Otton was a fierce competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Idaho State escapes with win:! Idaho State, CSUN's opponent
on Saturday, survived a scare from Sacramento State last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, Sacramento State drove to Idaho State's
1-yard line when senior running back Charles Roberts fumbled,
preserving Idaho State's 41-39 victory.
</P>
<P>
   __ Amerson's condition improves: Wide receiver Drew Amerson's
status was upgraded to day-to-day, and there's a chance he could
play against Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   Amerson, who hyperextended his right knee against Southwest
Texas State and didn't play against Northern Arizona, has been
cleared by doctors to play this week. At first, he was told he'd be
out three-eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran him around a little (Tuesday) and we'll see how he
feels (today),'' Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   Amerson, who ran some routes, said he's not experiencing much
pain. He wants to play in Saturday's game at North Campus Stadium
but he doesn't want to come back too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Amerson said. ``Hopefully, I'll play but I don't
want to push it and hurt it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Extra running Several players had to run more than they
would've liked on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them repeatedly failed to start behind a designated line
during wind sprints and Kearin made them run until they got it
right. Afterward, he lectured the team about paying attention to
detail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
