<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PERU-PANAMA (Panama City) _ An interview with the foreign
minister on Peru's decision to allow its intelligence chief to seek
asylum here. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILM (Undated) _ As the Senate prepares for
hearings on violence in films, documents show that moviemakers have
been marketing movies to people too young to attend the movie under
the ratings system. Those documents show that some of the biggest
companies in Hollywood routinely recruited scores of teen-agers and
children as young as 9 to evaluate story concepts, commercials,
theatrical trailers and rough cuts for R-rated movies. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUN-IMAGES (Undated) _ A NASA satellite has taken the most
detailed pictures ever of fiery magnetic loops on the sun, perhaps
solving the mystery of why the sun's corona, or atmosphere, is
nearly 1,000 times as hot as its surface. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   N.C.-TEACHERS-MONEY (Concord, N.C.) _ In North Carolina, money
is the new incentive for student performance. Teacher bonuses of
$1,500 for all teachers, including the gym teacher, and student
shopping discounts are tied to test scores. As California and
others move down the same path, North Carolina's experiment is
being watched. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   GA-RACE-RELATIONS (Atlanta) _ In the Buckhead neighborhood here,
tensions between young black clubgoers and affluent white residents
have raised racial animosity in the city. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ Researchers have found that a
previously unknown gene seems to increase the chance of developing
Type 2 diabetes, the most common form of the disease. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-DETRACTORS (Undated) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's
iconic celebrity has pushed open a door through which no other
first lady has dared pass. Yet her role as first lady creates an
obstacle to her winning a seat in the Senate. One of three New
Yorkers has an unfavorable opinion of her. Nationally, four of 10
Americans disapprove _ and their willingness to spend money to keep
her out of Congress is a principal reason why the New York Senate
race is shaping up as the most expensive in the nation's history.
By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STRATEGY (Los Angeles) _ A Political Memo: As he tries to
topple an incumbent vice president after nearly a decade of
prosperity, Gov. George W. Bush has taken on the daunting task of
trying to convince the public that the nation is on the brink of
crisis. This week he is talking about an ``education recession.''
And laced through his stump speeches are references to rising crime
rates, stagnant farm prices and soaring oil costs. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PA-SENATE (Harrisburg) _ The Democrats' estimate that Sen. Rick
Santorum is ripe for defeat has not been born out so far in a rough
political year for his challenger, Congressman Ron Klink. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-OUTLOOK (San Francisco) _ Microsoft has long
maintained that the government antitrust case would do nothing to
alter its business practices or long-term strategy. And Tuesday, as
it won at least a procedural victory in the case, the company had
another opportunity to make its point. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING (Undated) _ A little-noticed Securities and
Exchange Commission rule that goes into effect next month should
make it easier for corporate insiders to sell their companies'
stock without running afoul of insider-trading law. While the new
provision could theoretically affect many of the estimated 16
million Americans who own shares in the companies they work for,
its biggest impact will be on senior managers eager to unlock the
wealth of their stock-and-options riches without veering into legal
trouble. By Geanne Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD-DRUG (Undated) _ Unable to manufacture enough of a new
drug for hemophiliacs, the Bayer Corp. has taken the unusual step
of asking patients to apply directly to the company to receive the
drug rather than getting it from a pharmacy or another distributor.
By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   REGISTER.COM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Things have not been
working out so well lately for Register.com. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   GUNCONTROL-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The Advertising Council and
the National Crime Prevention Council began distributing a public
service advertising campaign this week advocating safe gun storage.
By Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STREISAND-ARTISTRY (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook on Barbra
Streisand, who is performing sold-out concerts this week in New
York. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP-AUDIENCE (New York) _ The patrons of the Brooklyn
Museum's new exhibit, ``Hip-Hop Nation: Roots, Rhymes and Rage,''
looked markedly different from the museum's typical weekend crowd.
They were younger and more ethnically diverse, and a striking
proportion of them said they had a personal connection to the
material on display _ whether they were record company executives,
former graffiti writers, young aspiring deejays or teenagers who
simply said they had never known life without hip-hop. By Nina
Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS-NEW-ACCESS (Undated) _ Two major photography institutions
_ the George Eastman House in Rochester and the International
Center of Photography in New York City _ have entered an alliance
that will give New Yorkers more access to one of the world's
greatest collections of photographs and motion pictures. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ROCK-CONCERT (Beijing) _ At the first mega-band rock
concert allowed to grace a stadium in the nation's capital since
the spring of 1989, a horde of bands making up for lost time forced
themselves upon a crowd that, at certain moments, didn't seem to
know what had hit them. By Jonathan Ansfield.
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE-SYMPHONY (New York) _ On the Nashville Symphony at
Carnegie Hall. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ For many Americans, Iran conjures
up the hostage crisis, terrorism, the crowds chanting ``death to
America'' and the fierce Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini denouncing the
United States and Israel. Elaine Sciolino, a New York Times
correspondent, shows a different Iran in ``Persian Mirrors.''
Reviewed by Ira Lapidus.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's probably fitting that
Takeshi Kitano goes by the nickname Aniki in his yakuza spectacular
``Brother,'' because he stirs up some serious anarchy on the Los
Angeles crime scene. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BEST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ If you thought yuppie arrogance and
entitlement had been satirized to death, you haven't met Hamilton
and Meg Swan (Michael Hitchcock and Parker Posey), the hysterically
doting dog owners who have the funniest scenes in Christopher
Guest's dog-show mockumentary, ``Best in Show.'' Reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   TWILIGHT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ With ``Twilight: Los Angeles,''
the documentary and video maker Marc Levin has transformed Anna
Deavere Smith's much-honored performance piece ``Twilight: Los
Angeles, 1992'' into something both more and less than itself.
Reviewed by Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd on goofy girl games.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman comments on the tapping
of the nation's strategic oil reserve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column &UR;  &LR; on
the Mets and Braves, who play the first game of a three-game series
at Shea Stadium Tuesday night. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGS (Sydney) _ As C.J. Hunter, the husband of Marion Jones
seeks to clear his name, the entire system of drug testing in the
United States has come under fire from international Olympic
officials who consider the Americans hypocritical, laggard and
deceptive in their handling of doping cases. U.S. officials are
firing back. The recrimination has symbolized the messy state of
drug testing internationally and the lack of trust and cooperation
that undermines renewed efforts to curb the widespread use of
performance-enhancing drugs. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Caryn James assesses NBC's Olympic
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Sports of The Times Column on
the Olympics' most notable couple, C.J. Hunter and Marion Jones,
husband and wife as well as track star and coach, and now two
people making news for very different reasons. By William C.
Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-FOODS (Westport, Mass.) _ The southern coast of New
England is the source for oysters so fine they are sold by name,
and for wines that are served in some of the leading restaurants in
Boston and New York. One of the best American blue cheeses is made
here, not far from centuries-old apple orchards and farms that are
experimenting with cutting-edge technology in fish farming. In
Westport, they have a plan to preserve their rural coastline and to
make the region as famous for its food and wine as Sonoma County in
California or the Hudson Valley in New York state. By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER-RESTAURANTS (Undated) _ For truly observant Jews, kosher
restaurants were traditionally the only alternative to staying home
or going to grandma's. Now those old-fashioned places have given
way to more modern kosher options _ Chinese, Japanese, Indian,
Mexican and French steakhouses among them. And the newest additions
to the kosher scene are high-end restaurants featuring ambitious
dishes like bison, rack of lamb and whole roasted sea bass, with
wine lists and elegant surroundings. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER-CHEFS (Undated) _ Chefs who are finding new ways to make
kosher food stylish are not pushing the limits of dietary laws but
instead are simply rethinking their approach to it. By Melissa
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-OVENS (Undated) _ The new breed of oven combines
conventional and microwave technology to roast a chicken in 30
minutes, and roast it well. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-COOKBOOK (Undated) _ It's not a stretch to call Faye
Levy's 625-page volume, ``1,000 Jewish Recipes,'' a culinary bible.
It may be the only Jewish cookbook you'll ever need. Reviewed by
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL-FOOD-LAWS (Undated) _ Before Congress adjourns next month
it may vote on a bill that would prohibit state and local
governments from passing food safety laws that are tougher than
federal laws, as well as void any such laws that already exist. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Chef Eberhard Mueller's
poached halibut with herb vinaigrette. Written with Jack Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Scallops with curried
tomatoes. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: Legislation,
interstate wine shipping and the Internet. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: On the language used to
describe wine. By Erik Asimov.
</P>
