<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3163 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-27 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PLEASE, MAY I HAVE THE ENVELOPE?(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Dear Letter Writer,
</P>
<P>
   It's not the same since you purchased a computer. We must all
move forward, of course. Technology is a grand thing. But I can't
help but long for the days when correspondence required paper and
pen, and letter-writing was an art form. Life was simpler then.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   I recall a note received from a Mr. A.A.H. of Sun City, for
example. He included in the envelope an advertisement he'd clipped
from the morning paper. It was a promotional ad featuring a
photograph of the local columnist under the headline, ``Montini
will move you.'' Beneath it, in bold handwritten script, Mr. H.
added, ``So will a good enema {hellip}and it's not such a big
pain!!''
</P>
<P>
   Computer mail doesn't allow for such creativity. No clipped
photographs from magazines or imaginative pencil drawing (including
more than one of me and a barnyard animal, though I've never lived
on a farm.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I get sideways happy faces made with a colon and a
parenthesis mark.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing sent to me via computer to match the four-page
manifesto printed in capital letters on school stationery from Mr.
J.H. of Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He took the time to attach a page
from his local newspaper, which occasionally reprints columns from
(beginitalic)The Arizona Republic.(enditalic) He began:
</P>
<P>
   ``Montini, I thought it was you when the stench of putrid dog
vomit arose from today's paper.''
</P>
<P>
   On and on it went. I read it with admiration and appreciation
because it took time, unlike the few seconds of clicking on the
keyboard that creates an electronic letter.
</P>
<P>
   Gone as well are variations in stationery, from thin pages with
lacy borders to rough-edged parchment, slightly stained, torn from
the roll at a butcher's shop. And there are no more note cards
embossed with flags, hot air balloons, kittens or clowns. No finely
designed letterhead, except from purveyors of junk mail, like law
offices or politicians. And no postcards, some depicting exotic
lands, still others depicting exotic behavior. Or even simple white
rectangles like the one from Mr. R.G.E. of Scottsdale, which is
taped to the computer on which I type these words. It reads: ``I'm
78 and I enjoy 95percent of your columns - try to work on the other
5percent!''
</P>
<P>
   There is no rush to an actual letter. It's made slowly and
travels slowly. Not computer mail. A letter that is shipped in an
instant and received in an instant carries with it the expectation
of instantaneous response.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't possible for someone like me, whose mind clops along
the information superhighway like an Amish horse and buggy.
</P>
<P>
   These days, mail arriving in envelopes tends to come from two
groups: Those who are retired and those who are in prison. In each
case, they always include their addresses and they always sign
their names. On the other hand, cowards find plenty of cover in the
bushes of cyberspace, which makes them easy to ignore. Unlike Mr.
G.S. of Phoenix, who printed his name above his signature ``to make
sure you can read it, because as long as you keep signing your name
to the (expletive) you write, I'll keep signing me. Deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, &QR;
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini &QR;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
