<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-TRANSPLANTS-B     09-27 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-TRANSPLANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTRANSPLANT, NOVARTIS TEAM UP ON TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BioTransplant Inc. and Novartis Pharmaceuticals are forming a
Boston company that will seek to commercialize the transplantation
of organs from pigs to people.
</P>
<P>
   Under their agreement, announced Tuesday, Novartis will provide
$30 million in research funding over the next three years, along
with its proprietary technology in human organ rejection and
breeding pigs for organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, a Swiss firm, will own 67 percent of the
yet-to-be-named company and retain all commercial rights.
</P>
<P>
   BioTransplant, which has bred miniature swine for organ
transplants and has a proprietary technology for ``reeducating''
the body's immune response to allow it to tolerate foreign cells,
will own 33 percent of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   BioTransplant, which will receive royalty payments from Novartis
sales, will also provide office space at its Charlestown
headquarters to incubate the new company until it finds its own
offices and laboratories in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will begin operating Jan. 1. Its goal is to
start testing pig organs in humans in 2004. Such testing, and later
commercial transplants, would require approval from the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The venture will face some major competition. Nextran, of
Princeton, N.J., a subsidiary of Baxter Healthcare, is also working
on transplanting pig organs to humans. Another rival is Alexiion
Pharmaceuticals Inc. of New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the new Boston company will be Julia
Greenstein, currently BioTransplant's chief scientific officer. The
research director will be Henk Schuurman, the key scientist at
Imutran Ltd., a Novartis subsidiary in England that has developed
animal organ models for transplants. Schuurman plans to move to
Boston. Greenstein said she did not know how many other Imutran
employees will be asked to relocate to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, researchers have looked to using animal
organs _ hearts, kidneys, lungs, and livers _ to replace failing
organs in humans, a process known as xenotransplantation.
Nationwide, more than 50,000 people are on waiting lists for organ
transplants. Many die while waiting for an organ.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues with which researchers have grappled are
preventing human rejection of animal tissue and ensuring that
animal organs don't transmit diseases to humans.
</P>
<P>
   By using their complementary technologies to create a single
business _ and sharing the financial risk _ BioTransplant and
Novartis hope to commercialize the transplanting of animal organs
to humans more quickly than if they were working separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``By joining the two approaches together, we hope to bring
forward the day when xenotransplanation will become a clinical
reality,'' said Paul Herrling, head of global research for
Novartis, based in Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's announcement, Imutran and BioTransplant had
joint development projects in xenotransplantion, but there were
organizational impediments to working more closely, said Elliot
Lebowitz, BioTransplant's chief executive. Lebowitz will serve as a
corporate director of the new venture, as will Corinne Savill,
Imutran's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Lebowitz, who formed BioTransplant nine years ago, said
scientific advances and high costs forced the company to find a
partner. He the new company will be able to launch clinical trials
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Organs for transplants, he explained, might come from
BioTransplant's miniature swine _ 250-pound pigs with human-size
organs that do not produce a porcine virus that can infect human
cells. The smaller pigs were bred from swine that weigh about 1,000
pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-DOPING-ART-BO     09-27 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-DOPING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DRUG MAKERS BATTLE BAD SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a story that keeps repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   A company spends years and many millions of dollars to develop a
drug to treat a serious medical condition, a drug that saves lives
or dramatically improves them. Then, athletes take the drugs and
use them to boost performance.
</P>
<P>
   California's Genentech Inc. toiled for nearly a decade to
pioneer Protropin, the first recombinant human growth hormone to
help children with hormone deficiencies reach normal adult heights.
It became a wildly popular performance enhancer _ Uzbekistan coach
Sergei Voynov was caught trying to smuggle 15 vials of the hormone
into Sydney for the Olympics, claiming he used it to help reverse
his baldness.
</P>
<P>
   Another California biotech Amgen Inc. devoted nine years to
Epogen, a product that has allowed thousands of kidney patients
with chronic anemia to lead normal lives. It became one of the most
abused sports-performance drugs in history.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure Corp. poured 16 years into Hemopure, a product that
could drastically reduce the need for blood transfusions. It hasn't
even reached the market, and rumors are already flying that it is
the next big performance booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies in general are trying to create better public
health and better quality of life,'' said Carl Rausch, Biopure's
president and chief executive. ``We're dealing with people who are
sick, not people who are well. We all frown on the use of these
products by healthy athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   But as reports and rumors circulate, the companies find
themselves in the spotlight, defending their public images,
fielding complaints about a lack of controls, and balancing social
and corporate responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Both Genentech and Amgen have faced criticism over the years for
refusing to develop tests or alter their drugs in ways that would
make their use easy to detect. Because the products are similar to
hormones produced naturally in the body, they are difficult to
identify in drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   New tests checking for the presence of Epogen in blood and urine
are being used at the Olympics for the first time this year. There
are still no tests to detect human growth hormone products made by
Genentech and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But companies say it is unreasonable to ask that they divert
money and resources from their legitimate drug development efforts
to help organizations like the International Olympic Committee
police abuse by elite athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not Genentech's focus,'' said company spokeswoman
Betsy Rosenberg. ``Our focus is developing and marketing our
products for their intended medical purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech has worked with organizations such as the American
Association of Endocrinologists on efforts to educate people about
the risks of misusing human growth hormones. But aside from
endorsing such efforts, the company stays out of the fray, simply
reinforcing the intended medical uses for its products.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen spokesman David Kaye said the company did not condone
Epogen's use as a sports-performance drug. Beyond that, he said,
the company had no comment about the abuse of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Los Angeles Times article, however, Kaye said he was
aware of calls for the company to add a chemical marker to Epogen
to make it easily identifiable in tests. Amgen rejected the idea,
he said, because it would be costly and could require new
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing the drug would change what is put into the human
body,'' Kaye told the newspaper. ``We're not in the drug-testing
business. We develop human therapeutics for sick people.''
</P>
<P>
   Amgen has made efforts to educate athletes and the public about
the appropriate use of Epogen, including hosting programs timed to
coincide with major sporting events on the risks of abusing the
drug as a performance enhancer.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure made a test available to detect the presence of its
products in the blood in response to recent media reports and
requests from IOC-accredited labs. The test detects both Hemopure
and Oxyglobin, a similar product approved to treat anemia in dogs.
But unlike the other companies, Rausch said, Biopure had already
developed the test to evaluate the efficacy of its products in
clinical studies.
</P>
<P>
   If the company didn't have a test, Rausch said, he isn't sure it
would develop one for the purpose of policing athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the nature of our product, we realize that this
issue is going to continue to be a problem so we wanted to make the
test available,'' Rausch said. ``But companies shouldn't bear the
burden of controling the misuse of these products. It should be
shared.''
</P>
<P>
   Rausch bristles at the suggestion by certain sports officials
that the companies aren't closely monitoring their products. An IOC
executive board member was once quoted in The New York Times
saying: ``If they're not careful and don't apply more stringent
controls, and the public perceives that drugs are bringing down the
character of sports, their reputation is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Hemopure is still in testing, Rausch said, the company
tracks every unit of the product it sends out. He said it is highly
unlikely that any athlete could have gotten the product. And the
only way the product could have gotten to the black market is if
someone had diverted it illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Even with products like Oxyglobin that are already on the
market, he said, government regulations require strict monitoring.
Companies like Biopure, Genentech, and Amgen only sell prescription
products to approved institutions such as hospitals and veterinary
and physicians' offices. And those institutions are required to
monitor their inventories and dispense them only to licensed
practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controls, Rausch realizes prescription drugs
sometimes wind up in the wrong hands for the wrong purposes. But,
he said, companies are doing what they can to prevent the misuse of
their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly isn't how we intended the product to be used,''
he said. ``We certainly don't condone it. There are risks to almost
any medical treatment. A healthy person doesn't need to take those
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hoberman, a sports historian and professor at the
University of Texas at Austin, said companies should be expected to
cooperate in efforts to curb abuse of their products _ within
reason. It's reasonable, he said, to ask companies to participate
in educational efforts, make available existing tests, or aid
outside efforts to develop a test. It's not reasonable, however, to
ask that they develop tests, alter products, or make costly
adjustments to their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the rights of the elite sports community to ask the
rest of society to help police itself?'' Hoberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Yesalis, an epidemiologist at Pennsylvania State
University who has studied and written about athletic doping,
argues that sports organizations like the IOC should take
responsibility for policing their own athletes. The IOC, he said,
has spent only token sums of money on research to develop effective
drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, the abuse of performance-enhancing drugs by
elite athletes has reached epidemic proportions. With the help of
an underground network of so-called medical advisers, athletes are
constantly scanning the horizon for new drugs that will help them
beat competitors and drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a highly competitive society, and when there's a
lot at stake, people cross over the line,'' Yesalis said. ``I
really beat up on drug companies about steroids. But these drugs
aren't going to kids on the street. Why should drug companies pay
the tab for the misdeeds of elite athletes?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
