<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      09-27 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVINGS UNLIKELY TO SUPPLY $60,000 A YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I hope to retire by age 60 and draw $60,000 annually for my
retirement income. Do you think my goal is achievable? Should I be
doing anything different? What about a Roth IRA?
</P>
<P>
   S.T., Pontiac, Mich. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you are going to require $60,000 a year, my guess is that
retiring at 60 is probably not realistic. You did not specify your
earnings, so I can't calculate a likely accumulation. But I made a
guess, based on the fact that most people feel they can get along
on a little less in retirement than they require before then. I
made a calculation based on an $80,000 salary, which would work out
to total contributions of $1,600 a month, 18 percent of which would
come from you and 6 percent from your employer. If you average 10
percent investment returns over the next 8 years, you would
accumulate $548,433.
</P>
<P>
   But to be able to withdraw $60,000 a year _ and leave a little
bit of money in growth instruments to protect yourself against
later inflation _ you should have about $1 million saved. To get
from your current $141,785 to $1 million in eight years, you'd have
to save $4,688 a month.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the first calculation is probably closer to the
mark. If you are indeed saving $1,600 a month, you would cross that
$1 million line about two months before age 65. At age 65, the pool
would be $1,028,192.
</P>
<P>
   You can work out a projection yourself, using the various
figures I have supplied as benchmarks. If you are going to be
eligible for Social Security, you can also plug that income into
the calculation, using either the figures for age 62 or 65.
</P>
<P>
   You don't specify which of the three Dodge and Cox funds you are
using. If the Income fund is in the portfolio, you would do well to
move to Dodge and Cox Balanced fund or Dodge and Cox Stock fund. If
you think you can amass the required savings pool by age 60, the
Balanced fund would be my choice. However, if you believe you will
retire closer to age 65, Dodge and Cox Stock fund would be my
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of which of those three funds you are using, your
portfolio relies too much on domestic large-cap stock funds. I
suggest you go over the menu provided in your retirement account.
If you have options in the small- and midcap arenas, I would move
about 25 percent of the portfolio to these sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a Roth IRA would be nice, particularly if you can
afford to forgo the tax deferral by moving $2,000 a year from your
retirement plan to the Roth. This would increase your taxable
income by $2,000 a year but give you a pool of tax-free savings to
draw upon in retirement. Since the Roth allows for no taxes on the
investment growth in the account, you want to make your most
aggressive investment in that account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a social worker and have not contributed to any of my
funds for six years, due to unemployment. I recently obtained a
job. I am able to save only $100 a month. Should I change to funds
that will enable me to build more savings?
</P>
<P>
   V.M., Salem, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I have to say that I hope this will be your wake-up call.
There is nothing wrong with your selection of funds; in fact, your
portfolio is better balanced than most. But you should look hard at
your budget and your priorities and decide whether you can save
more. At the current pace, after 20 years you would have $190,838 _
with the buying power of a little less than $96,000 in today's
money (provided that inflation averages 3.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have a small pension and Social Security benefits,
that's a sum which will not provide you with much in the way of
financial security.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention how the funds you hold have been saved.
Certainly, in the future, your savings should be in the form of
contributions to a traditional IRA. This will not only shelter the
growth in the accounts from current taxation, but allow you an
income tax deduction of up to $2,000, provided your earnings exceed
the amount deposited.
</P>
<P>
   If you really can save no more than $1,200 a year _ and if your
existing retirement savings are in taxable accounts _ you could
move $800 a year from your taxable accounts into the IRA, thus
increasing your tax deduction and getting them into a tax-deferred
status.
</P>
<P>
   As a hint about what might be a good course, if you can manage
to fully fund your IRA with new savings each year, it would require
monthly contributions of $166. If your monthly contributions were
$166 instead of $100, the 20-year growth projection for your
savings would be $241,466.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, I suggest that you calculate your savings level as
a percentage of earnings. That way, every time you get a raise (no
matter how small) you increase your savings _ and of course if you
could bump the percentage a bit higher, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We get $219 a month from our CD, which we use. We pay $1,000
a month, plus interest, against our home equity loan. Would it be
better to pay off the loan and save all the interest we are paying?
</P>
<P>
   W.J., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. On paper, you'd be better off cashing in the CD and paying
off the loan. The current prime rate is 9.5 percent, which means
there is a spread of 3.13 percentage points between what you get
from your CD and what you pay on your loan. But there are two other
factors to consider.
</P>
<P>
   One is whether you would face a penalty upon cashing in the CD.
If so, consider what effect it would have on the arithmetic. It
probably would be small. But if it's only a matter of months before
you could cash it in without penalty, it would probably be worth
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The second factor is squishier. It amounts to whether you feel
you have the discipline to replace the CD account, just as if you
had been making extra payments against the principal of the home
equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that you are paying about $1,316 a month for principal
and interest on the loan. You are getting $219 a month from the CD,
giving you a net outflow of $1,097. If you were to pay off the loan
and then contribute $1,097 a month to a CD account, you would
accumulate $51,394 over the 40 months which you would need to pay
off the loan, following your current schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The example is a bit skewed, because if you follow your current
practice, the amount of interest would be lower each month, falling
by about $8 a month. Nonetheless, even if I went through 40 months
of calculations, you would end up better off by prepaying the loan
than by going with your current schedule.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you lack the discipline to replace the CD
capital and simply allow yourself a more lavish lifestyle over
those 40 months, you would end that period in worse shape than if
you followed your current practice.
</P>
<P>
   The final factor is whether you might need that $40,000 pool to
protect yourself against emergencies. If you have no other assets
that you might draw upon, you might consider a midway strategy,
prepaying a good deal of the loan in a lump sum and retaining some
funds in the CD account for emergencies. You could then continue
the payment schedule as you have been doing, and then set to work
to rebuild the CD account once the home equity loan is paid back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
