<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-OUTSOURCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON STRUGGLES WITH NEW-ECONOMY WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. says no forward-looking business today could accept
the demands Raytheon faces from 2,700 blue-collar employees who
went out on strike last month.
</P>
<P>
   From their picket lines outside the Lexington, Mass. defense
contractor, the strikers are mainly seeking job-security
guarantees. But such guarantees are a feature of the old economy.
These days, the company says, security comes only from pleasing
customers like the Pentagon by delivering quality high-tech
products.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon is busy cutting costs, meanwhile, by sending more of
its manufacturing work to plants in Arizona or to non-union
subcontractors. Striking union members fear they are getting the
cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Raytheon appears much more concerned with hiring
software engineers these days than with appeasing its blue-collar
work force, no matter how skilled. On its Web site, the company
lists openings for 1,718 jobs, many of which carry techie titles
such as software configuration analyst or physics engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, though executives insist privately they are committed to
keeping manufacturing work in Massachusetts, Raytheon canceled
talks with the union last week for reasons it didn't specify.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the strike may show how reinventing the
78-year-old company for the new economy is proving difficult. Two
years into his tenure, Raytheon's chief executive, Daniel Burnham,
still faces a host of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, Raytheon's stock has yet to recover from the
shocks of a year ago, when it disclosed major problems absorbing
acquisitions. From a high of nearly $75 in July 1999, Raytheon's
widely traded Class B shares closed Friday at $26.25.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated investors say Raytheon has yet to clarify why it
deserves their confidence. Foreign missile sales aren't providing
the revenue they once did. In July, the company unloaded its
heavy-construction unit in Cambridge, Mass. at a fire-sale price,
despite Burnham's onetime promise to rebuild the division.
</P>
<P>
   Even the national defense establishment it once leaned on for
support can't deliver. In May, despite heavy lobbying by President
Clinton, the British military ordered a missile designed by a group
of Raytheon's European competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has announced initiatives relating to
security-software, an online-parts exchange with other aerospace
companies, and a Web site for boaters. But it says these projects
aren't expected to have a major impact on its overall financial
performance in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying issues are still operational, regaining control
of these large and complex government contracts,'' said William
Fiala, analyst for Edward Jones. Raytheon's efforts in sofware
might be laudable, but won't by themselves make a dent in the
problems it faces in its bigger product areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the software initiatives, Fiala said: ``All that's fine and
dandy. But until they get their operations firmed up, it's all for
naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still an old-fashioned metal-bender.''
</P>
<P>
   At Raytheon, Burnham and others say comeback plans are in place.
Speaking to investors in New York last week, Burnham outlined ways
Raytheon plans to become more nimble. Already, he said,
quality-improvement projects generated up to $30 million in
operating income in the first half of the year. And he stressed the
company's backlog grew 20 percent to $25.6 billion at the end of
June compared to the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among major project wins, it counts orders for the Army's
Javelin anti-tank weapon and various classfied projects for the
National Security Agency and other government offices. Altogether,
Raytheon is ``holding to our year 2000 plan,'' Burnham told
analysts, though a spokesman said this doesn't necessarily mean the
company will meet analyst expectations in the closely-watched third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also notes it has a role in nine of the Pentagon's top
10 programs, from integration work on the Air Force's F-22 fighter
(worth up to $4 billion by 2005) to linking electronic systems on
Navy surface ships (worth up to $2 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Raytheon has said its work on the proposed National
Missile Defense program could be worth $5 billion by 2005. And even
if the controversial program isn't undertaken, Raytheon notes it
just won a $1.4 billion contract for another, the Theater High
Altitute Area Defense. ``We're all over missile defense,'' said
communications vice president Phyllis Piano.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also has been scouting for operations where defense
technologies might be transferred to civilian markets. These
include its infra-red sensors division, its optical components
unit, and a division that specializes in wireless communications.
Burnham has told investors that ``we're exploring all options'' for
the units, including joint ventures, spinoffs, or licensing deals.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, the company says it is meeting its hiring goals for
engineers and software specialists, an area in which it had
difficulties in previous quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of these initiatives are pushing up Raytheon's
shares. And last week, more acute problems in its aviation unit
emerged. For one thing, Raytheon announced it expects its Premier I
business jet to be certified by the Federal Aviation Administration
during the fourth quarter, a quarter later than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the stream of aircraft orders it once received from
commuter airlines now seems to be at risk. Last week, Mesa Air
Group of Phoenix said it would return 20 planes to Raytheon's
Aircraft Division and refinance as many as 36 more. Raytheon has
been shopping the entire aircraft division, based in Wichita, Kan.,
which could bring in cash to pay down its debt.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say they are still waiting to see more successes to
offset the memory of the company's disappointing earnings last
year. ``They're in recovery mode,'' said Joe Nadol, analyst for
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``It's not over yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
