<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONLINE-FRAUD-BOS &LR;      09-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE, A SUCKER'S JUST A CLICK AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investigators from the Securities and Exchange Commission first
confronted 15-year-old Jonathan Lebed last spring with evidence he
had used Internet chat rooms to manipulate penny stocks. Lebed's
response?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal?'' he reportedly asked officials.
``Everybody does this.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing, regulators say, is that Lebed wasn't too far
off the mark. As many as half of the people who post messages in
some investment chat rooms are, in fact, passing along bogus
information.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Nestor, director of the Massachusetts Securities Division,
said the case of the New Jersey teen stands out among hundreds of
similar Web-based fraud cases only because of the perpetrator's
youth. And even that's becoming less notable all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a ton of people saying misleading things in chat
rooms any time you log on,'' Nestor said. ``On Yahoo, on Raging
Bull, on any of the others, it's safest to assume the information
isn't true and that people want you to do things out of their own
self-
</P>
<P>
   interest, not yours.''
</P>
<P>
   This month Lebed made headlines when he became the youngest
person ever singled out by federal regulators for allegedly
breaking securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's Philadelphia office spotlighted 27 dubious trades the
high school sophomore made (in custodial accounts opened by his
father) between August 1999 and February 2000. Witout admitting
guilt, Lebed agreed to repay $285,000 he made from 11 of the trades
and to stop the behavior in question.
</P>
<P>
   The nine companies whose stock was involved were forced to deal
with unexplained run-ups and unpleasant fall-offs in rapid
succession, but none suffered permanent damage. The same couldn't
be said for investors who bought during those run-ups.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, Lebed would typically use a computer
in his bedroom to buy hundreds or even thousands of shares in a
thinly traded, over-the-counter stock. He then allegedly used a
variety of screen names to hide his identity and post fictitious
messages in chat rooms, talking up the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he would place a ``limit order'' with his broker,
setting a higher price at which he wanted to unload the investment.
Investors who reacted to Lebed's hot tips would invariably push the
stock price up until it reached the limit order, at which time he
would sell his large block of shares, pocket the profits, and send
the price plummeting again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who buys during the run-up gets mauled,'' said Joe
Borg, director of the Alabama Securities Division. ``There are real
people on the other side of these scams, real victims who lose
quite a bit of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebed was hardly original. People have been running ``pump and
dump'' schemes, as they're often called, for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that stock manipulation is now migrating from
street corners and boiler-room brokerages to the Internet. And the
people behind them are increasingly young and tech-savvy, with
little or no experience in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 31, for example, 23-year-old college dropout Mark Jakob
of El Segundo, Calif., was arrested on wire and securities fraud
charges after creating a fake press release about fiber-optics
company Emulex Corp. and posting it online.
</P>
<P>
   When the firm's share price fell like a rock, Jakob allegedly
made $241,000 in quick profits. (Emulex shares since have recovered
to trade about where they started.)
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks earlier, 23-year-old Arash Aziz-Golshani and
24-year-old Hootan Melamed pleaded guilty to charges that they used
computer labs at UCLA in a scheme similar to Lebed's. The pair
bought thousands of shares in commercial printer NEI Webworld Inc.,
boosted its stock price through hundreds of phony Web postings,
then sold their shares for a $350,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Georgetown University law student Douglas Colt, 24,
his mother, Joanne, and three of Colt's Georgetown classmates were
charged with stock manipulation in another pump and dump case
brought by the SEC. The group settled the charges and agreed not to
commit future violations.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the SEC's evidence in the case was a how-to posting Colt
left on a Web site: ``Buy a bunch of the garbage stock. Tell your
idiot subscribers about how great the stock is, and like sheep they
will run out and buy it. Dump the shares you bought a few hours ago
to all these suckers . . . Laugh all the way to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that allows the new breed of manipulators to prosper,
and that most concerns regulators, is the seemingly vast pool of
neophyte investors who comb the Web in search of hot tips. They're
the sheep, in Colt's terminology, who get sheared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job would be a lot easier if people were more skeptical,
or at least more willing to do their homework before investing,''
said SEC spokeswoman Joanne Cronrath Bamberger. ``There is only so
much we can do to protect people as long as they're willing to
believe everything they read online.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say regulators aren't stepping up their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of its counterparts in other states, the Massachusetts
Securities Division has an Internet Fraud Unit that spends time
scouting investment chat rooms, bulletin boards, and Web sites in
search of fraudsters.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, for its part, created the 14-person Office of Internet
Enforcement in 1998 to train regulators and law enforcement
personnel to track down bad guys online. The agency also has a
240-person ``Cyberforce,'' accountants and securities lawyers who
spend at least a few hours a week scanning for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read about something, call the company or your broker
or your financial planner to verify it,'' Borg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather miss an opportunity than find out I just dumped
$20,000 into something that doesn't exist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
