<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-TIMES-BOS &LR;      09-27 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVERAGE OF LEE CASE HAD FLAWS, TIMES SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a half-page note to readers that defended its coverage but
acknowledged some shortcomings, The New York Times Tuesday
published a highly unusual post-mortem of its controversial and
much-criticized reporting on the Wen Ho Lee espionage case.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the Los Alamos National Laboratory scientist at the center
of the Chinese nuclear spying saga, pleaded guilty to one count of
wrongdoing earlier this month and was released by a judge who
apologized for the government's overzealous handling of the case.
Shortly thereafter, President Clinton expressed his regrets and a
White House aide directly criticized the Times's journalism.
</P>
<P>
   It was a front-page March 6, 1999, Times story by James Risen
and Jeff Gerth _ which sounded a loud alarm about Chinese theft of
nuclear secrets and pointedly compared it to the Rosenberg
espionage case at the dawn of the Cold War _ that triggered what
Committee of Concerned Journalists chairman Bill Kovach called
``the media chase of Wen Ho Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of the perception that Lee has been unfairly treated,
the Times, which, like The Boston Globe, is owned by the New York
Times Co., has generated vocal criticism that it had rushed to
judgment. Several days ago, for example, the Web magazine salon.com
published a story called ``How The New York Times helped railroad
Wen Ho Lee.'' And given the paper's traditional reluctance to air
its dirty linen in public, Tuesday's lengthy editors' note _
co-authored by executive editor Joseph Lelyveld and managing editor
Bill Keller _ had the media world buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an extraordinary thing that they did,'' said
Kovach, who sees it as an attempt to ``be more transparent with New
York Times readers about the choices they make.''
</P>
<P>
   The note sent mixed messages to those readers. On one hand, it
stated that ``we remain proud of work that brought into the open a
major national security problem of which officials had been aware
for months, even years. Our review found careful reporting that
included extensive cross-checking and vetting of multiple sources,
despite enormous obstacles of official secrecy and government's
efforts to identify The Times's sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the editors suggested that the coverage had failed
to ``give Dr. Lee the full benefit of the doubt,'' said the paper
``did not pay enough attention to the possibility that there had
been a major intelligence loss in which the Los Alamos scientist
was a minor player, or completely uninvolved,'' and lamented the
failure to create a tone of ``journalistic detachment from our
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Times editors did not comment Tuesday and the paper's
spokeswoman Catherine Mathis said ``the assessment of our reporting
speaks for itself.'' But observers had differing reactions to that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a mea culpa . . . The prevailing tone for me
was more of a defense and explanation of what they had done,'' said
David Anable, president of the Washington-based International
Center for Journalists. ``My feeling is they got (the spying story)
pretty much right and the balance between slamming a poor harmless
old man and accurately reporting a potentially large breach of
security is difficult when everybody is trying to keep it from
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly better, more declarative ways to say `we
screwed up,' '' said Steven Brill, the founder of Brill's Content
magazine, which ran a November 1999 story assailing the Times's
coverage of the spying case. The editors' note ``reads like it was
written and edited by 20 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovach said he thinks the explanation will enhance the Times's
credibility with readers, but said it might have been better
presented as an analysis piece ``so that whoever wrote it could be
a little less defensive about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anable said the lesson of the Lee story is the burden placed on
the Times by its own clout. ``What happens is everyone else latches
on to the Times, particularly the politicians,'' he said. ``And the
residue washes back over the Times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
