<HEADLINE>
WHEN TILTING AT WINDMILLS PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alternative power ventures spent years tilting at windmills.
What they needed was a few investment bankers on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of alternative power in vogue among investors these
days is more commonly known as distributed power, typically
involving fuel cells or solar power.
</P>
<P>
   And just when you thought investors had run out of things to
throw absurd amounts of money at, these companies are attracting
megamillions on scant actual business.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Evergreen Solar Inc. of Waltham, Mass., which is in
the process of raising $40 million in an inital public offering
that could value the company at $165 million to upward of $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreen's revenues of $1.1 million through the first half of
this year were earned almost exclusively through research, not by
selling the solar products it is in business to make. A good chunk
of the IPO money is intended to fund a manufacturing facility in
Marlborough, Mass. that the company said will make it possible to
ramp up product sales.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Power Corp. of Woburn, Mass. has been even more
ambitious, registering an IPO to sell as much as $115 million in
stock to fund its business of developing flywheel electric storage
systems. Beacon reported revenues of $269,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   What leads Beacon Power to believe it can raise that kind of
money? Perhaps it was the early August IPO of Active Power Inc.,
which also makes a flywheel energy storage system. That offering
was priced at $17 per share, and the stock finished Tuesday at
$64.375, giving the company a market value of $2.4 billion. The
company's revenues through the first half of this year: $861,000.
</P>
<P>
   As an investment trend, distributed power follows a familiar
pattern. The big-picture story is plausible and quite intriguing,
but the prices of individual stocks get bid up and out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like another new-economy plot line, there is good
reason. The popularity of distributed power companies is driven by
two factors: the deregulation of electric utilities and the
increasing demand for extremely reliable power to support a world
of wired computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very large-scale, structural transformations that
are occurring and stimulating development,'' said analyst Hugh
Holman of CIBC World Markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities in a monopoly have been very good at squashing the
development of distributed resources. We're now in the gradual and
somewhat stop-and-go process of prying the power business from
monopolies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holman compares electric deregulation to the process of
telephone deregulation started years earlier, predicting
far-reaching change to come.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative power is described as ``distributed'' because
relatively small or even tiny amounts of generating capacity will
pop up at many places across the old power grid, typically at the
sites of customers who need backup resources or simply want to
produce their own energy.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the alternative power of the old days, most
distributed electricity is environmentally friendly. Fuel cells
generate power by chemical reaction, and solar power converts
sunlight into electricity, using silicon.
</P>
<P>
   The investment pitch for many distributed power companies
emphasizes the increasing demand for electricity, compared with
other forms of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreen Solar's stock offering documents site studies that
estimate electricity as one quarter of domestic energy use 25 years
ago and 37 percent last year _ and that forecast it will grow to
more than 50 percent early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Computers in general and the Internet in paricular drive a piece
of that electric demand. The Internet often requires a kind of
power reliability that even traditional utilities can't promise.
``Five nines,'' or 99.99999 percent reliability, is often the
standard sought by companies that live on the Web and that requires
affordable backup systems that act as safety nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of demand that has to be met,'' said Mark Burns,
a stock anlayst at Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. ``I think people really are
looking for different ways to provide backup power and
reliability.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the high-tech world, the distributed energy business
may find the stock market a place of steep mood swings.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those stocks, particularly shares of companies with
promising fuel cell businesses, boomed in the earliest months of
this year, only to plunge with the tech stock market in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of SatCon Technology Corp., based in Cambridge, Mass.,
soared from a low of just under $8.50 in late December to $40 by
March 10, only to give up about 67 percent of their value in the
next five weeks. SatCon stock has since climbed back to approach
its old highs; it closed at $37.25 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   SatCon has an advantage beyond the operations of its own
business divisions. It owns 32 percent of Beacon Power, which could
be the next hot IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed power may generate plenty of business for new
companies in the years ahead. But there isn't going to be room for
an endless line of billion-dollar players.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
