<HEADLINE>
BIOGEN'S AVONEX MAY SLOW, HALT PROGRESS OF MS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI AND RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early treatment with large doses of Biogen Inc.'s Avonex may
slow or even halt the progression of multiple sclerosis in patients
at high risk for the disease, according to a study in this week's
New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Avonex is a beta interferon developed by the Cambridge, Mass.
company and approved in 1996 for the treatment of multiple
sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   This study is the first to show, however, that the drug might be
useful in delaying the onset of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The 383 patients examined in the 2 1/2-year study showed early
signs of MS but had not yet developed the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that patients given a weekly shot of Avonex were
44 percent less likely to develop the disease than those treated
with a placebo, or dummy drug.
</P>
<P>
   Brain scans also found patients on Avonex had smaller lesions
and were less likely to develop new ones, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen plans to seek approval to sell Avonex to patients at risk
of MS in the United States and Europe, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Food and Drug Administration for that
purpose, the market for the drug would increase greatly.
</P>
<P>
   The company estimates that about 100,000 of the 1 million people
worldwide who suffer from MS could benefit from early treatment
with Avonex.
</P>
<P>
   MS is a chronic disease of the central nervous system that
causes symptoms including balance loss, numbness and paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRM GRANTS WORLD MARKETING RIGHTS FOR GENE-SEQUENCE DATA
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Molecular Oncology, a Framingham, Mass. biotechnology
company, said it has granted Celera Genomics coexclusive worldwide
rights to market the company's gene expression data, known as Sage.
</P>
<P>
   Celera will make the gene expression data available through its
Web-based biological information portal under an agreement that
allows users to combine Sage data with Celera's Genome Reference
Database.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the combination of the two databases will help
Celera's customers better understand how diseases work and allow
them to accelerate the drug discovery process by associating genes
with tissues and disease states.
</P>
<P>
   Sage includes information on more than 2.5 million gene
sequences from a wide range of normal human tissue to the most
prevalent types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Molecular, a division of Cambridge's Genzyme Corp., said
it will provide Celera with additional gene sequences as it expands
the database.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, based in Maryland, announced earlier this year that it
had decoded the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Its database catalogs genes and proteins encoded in the human
genome as well as in the genomes of other organisms important to
understanding normal human physiology and the development of
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Although the financial terms of the deal were not disclosed,
Genzyme Molecular said it is licensing the Sage data to Celera on a
revenue-sharing basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HYBRIDON SELLS DNA MANUFACTURING FOR $15 &LR;   &UR; MILLION
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hybridon Inc. has sold its DNA manufacturing business to a
British company.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million sale of its Milford, Mass. operation to Avecia
of Manchester, UK, will enable Hybridon to focus on Phase II
testing of its antisense cancer drug to treat solid tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most drugs on the market that are designed to interact
with proteins, which control the body's function, antisense drugs
intervene earlier by interrupting the process by which
disease-causing proteins are produced.
</P>
<P>
   Turning antisense technology into marketable medications has
proven more difficult than expected, not only for Hybridon but for
nearly half a dozen other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, only one antisense drug, a medication to
prevent eye damage from common infection in late-stage AIDS
patients, has gained US Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   It was developed by Isis Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Carlsbad,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With the Milford plant sale, Avecia will retain 17 of Hybridon's
37 employees. The remaining 20 will move to a new headquarters in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
