<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-BAYSTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEALTH OF RESOURCES PUTS BAY STATE AT TOP OF BIOTECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When it decided to build a new research site, Swedish
pharmaceutical company AstraZeneca went looking for a location that
offered a wealth of research and scientists. It wanted an area that
was full of energy and entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts made the list of potential sites. So did other
biotech hubs such as San Francisco, San Diego and North Carolina's
Research Triangle as well as Japan, France and Australia. In the
end, however, the company chose Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons, simply put: MIT, Harvard, Brandeis, Tufts,
Worcester Polytechnic, Whitehead Research Institute, Longwood
Medical and Academic Area, UMass Medical Center, the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's basic science research going on in the universities,
clinical research going on in the hospitals,'' said Hans G.
Nilsson, vice president and site general manager for AstraZeneca.
``It's a fantastic, talented pool from which to draw people and
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   AstraZeneca is one of many companies in recent years to join the
state's growing biotech community. At last count, 143 biotech
companies had popped up inside the Route 128 belt, 68 more within
Interstate 495 and another 29 west of I-495. And the numbers are
constantly growing, said Stephen Mulloney, director of
communications and government relations at the Massachusetts
Biotechnology Council.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based pharmaceutical powerhouse Pfizer Inc. opened a
research center in January 1999 in Cambridge. California biotech
giant Amgen Inc. broke ground in November for a new Cambridge
research site. AstraZeneca moved into its Waltham campus in April.
And Merck, a top-tier New Jersey pharmaceutical company, also
decided recently to build a research site in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Established Massachusetts biotech companies like Genzyme Corp.,
Biogen Inc. and Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. are also expanding
in the area. Add to that the number of start-ups within the state's
borders _ more than 25 in just the past two months, Mulloney said _
and the growth is truly remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of qualities here that, over the years, have
coalesced to form a real center: the academic and research
institutions, the hospitals, the venture capital community and the
work force,'' Mulloney said.
</P>
<P>
   The state is the top recipient per capita of research grants
from the National Institutes of Health. Its population ranks among
the most highly educated in the nation. And of the nation's top 100
biotech companies, 20 are based in Massachusetts. That compares
with 16 in San Francisco's Bay Area and nine in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Going by the numbers of companies, Massachusetts has climbed in
the ranking of US biotech hubs to become number one, nudging past
San Francisco in the longstanding rivalry between the Bay State and
the Bay Area. Ernst &AMP; Young's 1999 report on the biotech industry
lists nearly 200 companies in Massachusetts compared to about 180
in the Bay Area. But industry professionals said the differences
are pretty small. Both are known worldwide as the heavyweight
contenders of biotech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close between Boston and San Francisco,'' said Dan
Eramian, spokesman for the Washington, D.C.-based Biotechnology
Industry Organization. ``Both areas have what it takes to be
attractive for biotech.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Mulloney said, state government has aided the
tremendous growth of the biotech industry in Massachusetts through
its support of education, tax credits for research spending, an
emerging technology fund to help small companies finance
investments in equipment and other fixed assets, and the
establishment of quasipublic agencies to support developing
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't always the case, said Michael Hogan, president and
chief executive of MassDevelopment, the largest of those agencies.
In the early 1990s, the state was complacent, assuming the science
generated by its universities would continue to foster and support
the growing biotech community.
</P>
<P>
   ``That complacency allowed some good science and some good
companies to leave the state,'' Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   While some companies looked to California, he said, most
considered relocating to less expensive areas with burgeoning
biotech communities such as Maryland, North Carolina, New Jersey
and even Maine. One of the earliest residents of the Jackson
Technology Park at Devens Commerce Center, formerly Fort Devens
Army base, was a company that had been priced out of Lexington and
was considering a move to Maine, Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   When Hogan heard about Pharma-Eco Laboratories Inc.'s plans to
relocate, he put together a proposal. The Devens site was developed
to offer technology companies a less expensive alternative to areas
in and around Boston, giving the state a chance to compete with
mid-Atlantic and Southeastern states. Hogan said the park offers
lower tax rates, quicker permitting processes, substantial savings
on utilities and access to an experienced manufacturing work force.
</P>
<P>
   Pharm-Eco just completed building a $16 million,
160,000-square-foot campus to house research, development and
manufacturing. The park will also serve as a biotech ``incubator,''
offering 80,000 square feet of lab space for small start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Such lab space is invaluable to companies like Roxbury's IVREA
BioPharmaceuticals, a two-person operation that shares lab space,
equipment and office staff with other biotech start-ups, said
Maurizio Cattaneo, the company's chief executive. A nonprofit
agency, Massachusetts Biomedical Initiatives, helped the company
find the space to conduct its skin cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Cattaneo said he benefits from the sheer number of other
start-ups in the state. They share resources and learn from each
other. California might offer a similar environment, he said, but
less expensive areas _ even those with growing numbers of biotech
companies _ simply can't offer the wealth of expertise and
experience available here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to weigh the pros and cons,'' he said. ``For me,
there is no other place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Larger companies echo his sentiments. Massachusetts has a
network of professionals that know the biotech industry: venture
capitalists who understand a start-up's financial requirements,
patent lawyers, architects and construction crews that can
accommodate the intricate scientific and regulatory demands of
building a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a critical mass of companies in your field is extremely
helpful from a research point of view, a clinical point of view, a
labor point of view,'' said Mara Aspinall, president of Genzyme
Pharmaceuticals, a division of Cambridge's Genzyme Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and California probably offer similar advantages
in that regard and similar drawbacks in terms of traffic and living
costs. But some people are devoutly East Coast and others are
devoutly West Coast, said Kleanthis G. Xanthopolous, chief
executive of Anadys Pharmaceuticals, a company with offices in San
Diego and Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Pfizer, Amgen and Merck are opening offices on
both coasts. Amgen spokesman David Kaye said the company has long
seen Boston as one of the world's top centers for academic research
and commercial drug discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every scientist is going to want to relocate to
California,'' he said. ``To be an active player, we believe you
need to be in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the biotech industry grows, new issues arise. Chief among
them, said Genzyme's Aspinall, is the increasingly difficult
challenge of finding enough talent to fill all the job openings.
Genzyme is growing at about 10 percent a year. Although the company
is hiring all the time, she said, there area always openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a competitive environment, you need to continually evaluate
your strengths and weaknesses,'' she said. ``Because you can be
sure they will change over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulloney of the Massachusetts Biotech Council agreed, adding
that the state will also face increasing competition from smaller
biotech hubs such as North Carolina and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of people casting envious eyes to
Massachusetts,'' he said. ``Right now, people want to come here.
But other regions may begin offering incentives to draw those
companies away.''
</P>
<P>
   That is already starting to happen, although it is rare, said
Joe Donovan, director of the state's economic development efforts
for emerging technologies. One company was lured to another state
by a generous package of land and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan and Mulloney said they don't think Massachusetts should
offer such deals. While the state offers certain research and
investment tax credits, they said, it does not hand out money to
attract companies. But the state can attract biotech companies in
other ways _ most importantly, by supporting science and technology
education to ensure an adequate work force for the growing
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloney also suggested additional support for small start-ups
like IVREA. By allowing young companies that aren't yet profitable
to sell their research and development tax credits to larger
companies, he said, the state could help start-ups raise much
needed cash for their research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in corporate welfare,'' Mulloney said. ``The
big companies only ask for a level playing field. But I think the
state could target specific assistance to the small start-ups that
could be the next Amgen or Biogen. After all, our economy today is
fueled by the R&AMP;D done 20 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
