<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP FOR THE BATTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can employers play a role in the lives of battered workers?
</P>
<P>
   Julie Foshay certainly thinks so. Two years ago, after being
beaten at home and ridiculed at work by a man who was both her
supervisor and live-in companion, the 40-year-old manager went to
see her employer: Richard Millman, president of Textron Systems, a
Wilmington, Mass. defense manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Fiercely private and fearful the abuse would escalate if she
revealed too much, Foshay didn't mention her abuser's name or the
nature of her problem. She simply said she was having personal
problems and needed time to work them out. But Millman seemed to
know she was being battered, and he threw her a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if I was afraid of someone, if I'd been hurt,''
recalls Foshay, now 42, of Boston. ``He asked if the person who
hurt me worked there. He wanted to know if my children were at
risk. Then, he advised that I call the police and leave (with them)
immediately. . . . The next day he transferred me to a different
building, and gave me a special assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Foshay seems surprised by the company's reaction. ``I
still can't get over the response,'' she says. ``I fully expected
to be terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   At another company she might have been.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Textron's Millman was a founding member of
Employers Against Domestic Violence, a fledgling group that has
since grown to include 65 Massachusetts firms.
</P>
<P>
   Created by the law firm Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky and
Popeo and Fleet Bank four years ago, the coalition is among a small
but growing number of employer initiatives that have cropped up
around the country. The reason is clear: domestic violence affects
a company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, companies lose between $3 billion and $5 billion
because of absenteeism, medical bills, and lost productivity due to
abuse, reports the Bureau of National Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Verizon Wireless, in conjunction with the Family
Violence Prevention Fund in San Francisco, is sponsoring a campaign
to familiarize workers and their employers with the resources
available to women or men who are being abused.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the campaign, large black-and-white photographs of
working women whose eyes are hidden by dark glasses or a lock of
hair will be placed on the walls of participating corporations.
Part of the campaign began on Friday, Sept. 15, when Foshay walked
up to a podium at the Omni Parker House Hotel and, in a voice
stripped of emotion, told her story to 200 women and men at the
``Corporate Citizenship Initiative on Domestic Violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Family Violence Prevention Fund, the event
marked the first time Foshay had spoken to a large group about the
violence that had controlled her life.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Foshay hid her feelings and the abuse by adopting a
dual life. By day, she was a Textron Systems manager who seemed to
have it all: a good job, a home in New Hampshire, and two
attractive children.
</P>
<P>
   By night, Foshay struggled to keep the peace, fearing there
would be repercussions at work if she, in any way, challenged her
batterer. The couple rarely left the house; he was jealous of her
friends and members of her family. She was too scared of
displeasing him to venture out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the office, he would assign me work that other people
hadn't completed,'' she said of her four-year ordeal. ``When I was
done, he'd give it back to them and they would get the credit. When
we were alone in his office, he yelled at me, pinched me, punched
me, and spat at me. Then, when I tried to transfer, he said he
could not let me go because I was critical to the department...He
knew where I was at all times of the day. He monitored who I talked
to and read my correspondence. Why didn't I get up and leave?
Because he had terrorized me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to remain in the relationship and keep the abuse a
secret doesn't surprise workplace experts or psychologists. Deborah
Swiss, a management consultant and author of the book, ``The Male
Mind at Work,'' calls battering a silent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women won't tell anyone,'' says Swiss. ``They worry they
will be viewed as troublemakers and that they will be putting their
jobs in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a desperate Foshay sought out her employer and asked
for help. The next day, a security guard was assigned to her new
section, and the locks to her office were changed. She was shown a
protected parking space, and handed a list of four coworkers who
had been asked to assist her. She also received information about
support services and counseling for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I talked to the company president, the people he had
assigned to me began to talk to me,'' Foshay recalled. ``Every day,
someone would come by. This was done unobstrusively. One woman, a
woman I grew to trust, told me I would not have to keep everything
to myself anymore. My head was spinning. I was invigorated by the
freedom I felt that day...I was still scared, but the
thoughtfulness with which my employer handled the situation gave me
the strength to go on and do what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Julie Foshay an exception? Not at all, says Linda Cagle,
Textron's vice president of human resources. ``We've had other
women at work in similar circumstances. We do all we can to keep
them safe, including escorting them home and finding alternative
living arrangements. We have a process in place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Employers interested in obtaining anti-battering posters for
their workplaces should contact the Family Violence Prevention Fund
at www.fvpf.org. Workers seeking counseling or advice should call
1-800-799-7233).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe's staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
