<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WEB-BOGEYMAN-ART-BOS &LR;      09-27 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-BOGEYMAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PREDICTIVE NETWORKS TAKES TRACKING OF NET SURFERS TO NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Devin Hosea, the 30-year-old founder and president of Predictive
Networks Inc., is the boyish face behind what some consider the
Internet's latest threat to consumer privacy.
</P>
<P>
   A digital wizard who learned how to crack software code by age
10, Hosea has been drawing fire from consumer advocates who say his
technology takes online surveillance to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Hosea's start-up company in Cambridge, Mass. has developed
software that builds digital ``silhouettes,'' or profiles, of
Internet users, after tracking their clicks across the Web. For
example, if a Web surfer visits an airline site and then a Boston
museum site, Predictive's profile model might immediately send the
user a pop-up ad for a Massachusetts travel guide from Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Predictive is being closely watched by privacy advocates
because, unlike many similar software companies, it has struck
deals with Internet service providers rather than individual Web
sites. As a result, Predictive's software can follow users of these
ISPs everywhere on the Web, gaining insights into their ages,
incomes, shopping preferences, and hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the whole menu,'' said Hosea, who maintains that his
company protects consumers while allowing advertisers to better
target their audience.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash against Predictive, which launched in May,
highlights the intense debate over privacy on the Web. On one side
are those who believe Internet users should be protected from
companies compiling extensive personal data. On the other are Web
firms that say they are no different from traditional companies in
their desire to research consumer habits.
</P>
<P>
   Hosea believes he is striking the proper balance. He said
Predictive tosses out the list of Web sites that users visit and
keeps only a set of ``scores'' that reveal a customer's implied
demographic information and preferences. No advertiser or ISP can
view the anonymous profiles. Rather, Predictive controls the
silhouettes and sends ads directly to users.
</P>
<P>
   But some privacy advocates remain skeptical of promises made by
Predictive and other Internet companies. They say Predictive does
not properly get ``opt-in'' consent from consumers and does not
have a strict privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates also point to DoubleClick Inc., which
outraged Internet users when it attempted to merge its database of
anonymous consumer information with another database that
identified consumers by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much worse,'' said Andrew Shen, a policy analyst with
the Electronic Privacy Information Center in Washington. ``This is
tracking virtually every move of the Internet user.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy experts also fear Predictive's software will be widely
accepted by ISPs and, later, cable companies. In seven months, the
tiny firm has signed on six ISPs, including AT&AMP;T WorldNet, IDT
Corp., PSINet, and three others it declined to identify.
Advertisers also are lining up, impressed by Predictive's ability
to dramatically improve customer response to ads.
</P>
<P>
   Predictive plans to announce this week that it has received $45
million in a second round of funding led by venture capital firms
Battery Ventures and Advent International. Smaller investors
include Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., the world's largest
telecommunications company, as well as Internet telephony carrier
Net2Phone Inc. and Internet researcher Nielsen/NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 2001, Predictive projects that 10 million Internet
users will be on the receiving end of the company's profiling
software.
</P>
<P>
   America Online Inc. and Microsoft Corp., two giants in Internet
service, declined to comment on whether they might use Predictive's
software or any similar technology in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But here's where both Hosea and privacy experts agree: Big ISPs
that have largely avoided tracking users will eventually adopt
profiling technology to increase their ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Hosea, the son of a nuclear physics scientist, had dabbled in
artificial intelligence at an early age. From a computer in his
father's laboratory at Princeton University, Hosea managed to crack
into a sensitive file. Rather than punishing him, the university
gave him a part-time job writing data-analysis software. Two years
ago, Hosea decided to leave his job as a vice president in GE
Capital's Equity Capital Group to build his own company.
</P>
<P>
   His company's software is downloaded when customers receive
their ISP service. Using artificial intelligence, Predictive does
its best to match Internet users with compatible advertisements. It
works by scoring consumers on 120 different demographical and
preference categories based on Web sites visited. Clicking on a
video-game site, for instance, could result in a low score for age.
But visiting Charles Schwab's site might translate into higher age
and income ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies argue that such digital profiling limits the
number of advertising misfires _ those banner ads that consumers
consider annoying and that advertisers find ineffective. Fewer than
1 percent of customers click on banner advertisements, according to
industry figures. But IDT, one of Predictive's partners, has seen
ads that have drawn 18 percent of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end users say it's a much more pleasurable experience,''
said Michael Packer, domestic operations director for IDT, based in
Hackensack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Hosea believes Web users will let Predictive, which shares ad
revenue with ISPs, watch their every move online in return for
lower Internet-service rates. IDT is now using Predictive's
software for a free service called freeatlast.com, while AT&AMP;T
WorldNet is using the technology in a $4.95-a-month package.
</P>
<P>
   Predictive's business model and approach to online privacy also
helped it win over service providers, ISP executives said.
Predictive allows customers to access their silhouettes. And it
does not send them ads for alcohol, tobacco, firearms, or
pornography. Medical self-help sites and hate-monger sites also are
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Although the software can collect keywords at a search engine
and other data typed on a Web page, the company has restrained
itself. Predictive's privacy board, led by Boston civil-liberties
attorney Harvey Silverglate, has expressed concerns about the
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Hosea also stepped to the side, allowing more seasoned
management to steer the company. Michael Skarzynski, 44, a former
executive at Lucent Technologies Inc., took over as CEO May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Predictive's efforts to reassure consumers, critics say
there are glaring problems with the company's techology.
</P>
<P>
   First, Internet users ``opt in,'' or agree to allow Predictive
to track them, by signing a contract with the ISP. That means that
people who choose not to participate simply do not get the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their threshold for opt-in is meaningless, ridiculous,
extremely unfair, and potentially actionable,'' said Ed
Mierzwinski, consumer program director for the US Public Interest
Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy experts also say Predictive's privacy statement, which
is displayed on its Web site, does not rule out the possibility
that an ISP user name and identification number could be linked to
the anonymous ID number attached to profiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure exactly what they mean when they say anonymous,''
said Jonathan Zittrain, an assistant professor at Harvard Law
School who noticed the clause in Predictive's privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   A Predictive spokesman said the company has not received
personally identifiable information from ISPs and does not intend
to do so. In response to criticism, the firm will rewrite the
clause. ``Predictive Networks is clarifying the privacy policy to
reiterate our operating policy,'' the company said Friday in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Predictive's ISP partners was concerned enough
to strike the clause from its agreement during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I specifically negotiated in our contract that I would not do
that,'' said Harry Lalor, a vice president at Ashburn, Va.-based
PSINet. ``I wanted to stay out of that whole discussion. There's no
way to win, especially for an ISP.''
</P>
</TEXT>
