<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-JUDGES (San Francisco) _ When U.S. District Judge Thelton
Henderson entered law school in 1959, there was only one African
American federal court judge in the country. Today, there are about
150 black federal judges, and they will gather here on Thursday to
celebrate the strides that have been made and discuss further
progress they'd like to see. By VENISE WANGER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOLK-MEDICINE (San Antonio) _ Behind the counter at Casa
Mireles, rows of small white drawers used to store dried herbs are
neatly labeled in black marker with mysterious-sounding Spanish
names. For decades, customers have been going to the botanica
seeking the ingredients for herbal remedies that are part of the
traditional Mexican folk medicine called curanderismo. Why do these
treatments persist in the face of modern medicine. ``Well, because
I think it works. That's why,'' says Ellen Riojas Clark, a
professor in the division of bicultural and bilingual studies at
the University of Texas at San Antonio. By ELDA SILVA.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-NYWOMEN5 (New York) _ Showings of spring 2001 women's
wear came to a end in a swirl of girlishness. Even the usually
subtle Calvin Klein could not resist the pull of soft colors and
sheer fabrics. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SALLY-FIELD (Undated) _ After 35 years in show business,
Sally Field knows all about the limitations and expectations placed
on women. For much of her career, Field traded on being cute and
perky; when that ran its course she went for sexy. In 1985, when
she won her second best-actress Oscar, she famously trilled, ``You
like me! You really like me!'' So it's interesting to hear her say
that what attracted her to ``Beautiful,'' the new comedy that Field
chose as her feature directing debut, was that the female lead
character isn't very likable. By ERIC HARRISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
