<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS28-FILE     09-27 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS28-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Whose voice is it singing ``If you're happy and you know it .
. .'' on the Home Depot commercials for the Olympic Games?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, we struck out. The only information available is that
she's ``a young lady from the Midwest'' who wants to remain
anonymous, said Home Depot spokeswoman Mandy Holton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Georgia Farmers and Consumers Market Bulletin reports
that the National Park Service will open the Jimmy Carter boyhood
farm on Nov. 17. Did the government buy this farm from the Carter
family? If so, what was the price?
</P>
<P>
   A: The farm was sold by the Carter family in 1948, said Paul
Winegar of the National Park Service. The NPS bought it from the
heirs of the people who purchased it from the Carters, he added,
paying ``in the range of $65,000.''
</P>
<P>
   When it opens, visitors will be able to see the restored house
where President Carter lived as a child; his father's store; and
some of the barns and outbuildings, reconstructed to look exactly
as they did when Carter was a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Florida has stopped auto emission inspections. Why has the
EPA permitted this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Florida cleaned up its air, that's why. The emissions testing
program began in 1991 in Palm Beach, Broward, Miami-Dade, Duval,
Pinellas and Hillsborough counties after the Environmental
Protection Agency determined the air there violated the Clean Air
Act. For various reasons _ federal rules requiring cleaner fuels,
cars with more efficient engines, successful work on failing
vehicles to bring them up to standard _ the state's air quality
improved dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state and the EPA reached settlements with
Tampa Electric Co. to reduce nitrogen oxide discharges, eliminating
40 times more pollution than the vehicle testing program.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the EPA gave Florida preliminary approval to remove
the emissions testing program from its clean air plan. On July 1, a
new law mandating the end of the tests took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the focus on the Olympics, I was wondering: Are the
Aborigines of African descent?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. As explained by Encyclopedia Britannica, they originally
came from somewhere in Asia, and have been in Australia for at
least 40,000 years. The first settlement would have occurred during
an era of lowered sea levels, when there was an almost continuous
land bridge between Asia and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that some extremely valuable items, including
artwork and possibly jewels and a great deal of cash, were aboard
the Swissair flight that crashed into the Atlantic off eastern
Canada several years ago. Do you have any information? Was any
effort made to retrieve those items?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the aftermath of the crash Sept. 2, 1998, off Peggy's
Cove, Nova Scotia, widely varying stories circulated about the
valuables said to be aboard the MD-11. One report said nearly 110
pounds of cash and 4 1/2 pounds of diamonds were sent to the ocean
floor; another said a stainless steel tube filled with diamonds
went down.
</P>
<P>
   Very little ever was confirmed, but Swissair officials did say a
Picasso work, ``Le Peintre'' was lost. Reports variously listed its
value at a minimum of $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the crash, an airline spokesman said no gold was
aboard the plane, adding that officials didn't know the value of
the money or jewels because the owners weren't required to declare
a total dollar figure.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, insurer Lloyds of London, which paid out an insurance
policy on the lost gems, announced that it would use a
minisubmarine to search for valuables.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, stung by criticism that it was engaging in
grave-robbing, Lloyds called off the plan and apologized to
victims' families. The crash claimed 229 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In baseball scoring, a K indicates a strikeout. What does the
backwards K mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the scorecard symbol for a strikeout on a called third
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't heard anything for several years now about Terry
Waite, the former Church of England envoy who negotiated for the
release of Western hostages in Lebanon in the 1980s, only to be
taken hostage himself. What is he doing these days?
</P>
<P>
   A: He's involved in several projects in Britain, which include
serving as president of Emmaus, a charity working with the
homeless; supporting a trust helping inmates in British prisons;
and serving as chairman of the YMCA group Y-Care, an organization
he founded to help street children. Most recently, in August,
Waite, 61, traveled with a small group from Northern Ireland to
Liberia to launch a project to bring electricity to a YMCA youth
and community center in the town of Ganta.
</P>
<P>
   Waite was held captive by Shiite Muslims in Lebanon from Jan.
20, 1987, until Nov. 18, 1991. While visiting a hospice in
Plymouth, England, earlier this summer, he told a reporter that he
has no mental scars. ``I don't get flashbacks,'' he said. ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the distance in a straight line between Barrow,
Alaska, and Key West, Fla.?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's 4,290 miles as the crow flies. Straight-path distances
between many locations worldwide can be determined online at
www.indo.com/distance/ or found in the book ``Direct-Line
Distances,'' available at libraries and bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For years I've heard mentions of the ``wreck of the
Hesperus.'' What is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the name of a poem by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow
(1807-82), whose subject was the schooner Hesperus ``that sailed
the wintry sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the warning of an old sailor, its skipper tied his
daughter to the mast when a mighty storm struck. She and her father
died amid the wreckage. The poem ends: ``Such was the wreck of the
Hesperus,/ In the midnight and the snow!/ Christ save us all from a
death like this,/ On the reef of Norman's Woe!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wreck of the Hesperus'' also was the title of a 1948 film
with John Hoffman and Edgar Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know it's been printed before, but can you repeat when and
where the next Winter Olympics will be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Feb. 8-24, 2002, in Salt Lake City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
