</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did we miss something? Isn`t the Miss America pageant always
held in September?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's normally a September fixture, but was postponed this
year because of the Olympics. It will air live from Atlantic City,
N.J., at 8 p.m. Oct. 14 on ABC. Donny and Marie Osmond will repeat
as hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported on July 12 that South Korea is awarding medals
to Americans who served there during the war. I was sent the
application form, which I completed and returned on July 25. I
haven't had a response. Anything further to report?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Air Force Awards and Decorations Section continues to get
``thousands of requests a day,'' a spokesman said, and it's sending
out about 1,000 medals a day. At present, there's a backlog of at
least two months.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 22, the section was evaluating applications received
on July 17. It will be December, at the earliest, before the
section catches up.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime the section is upgrading its telephone system
and, if plans are approved, should be able to tell applicants by
the middle of October the status of their application if they call
and provide their name, Social Security number or service number.
</P>
<P>
   For general information on the Korea medals program, contact the
Air Force Personnel Center, 1-800-558-1404; or online at
www.afpc.randolph.af.mil/awards; or write HQ AFPC/DPPPRA, 550 C St.
West, Suite 12, Randolph Air Force Base, TX 78150-4714. For the
status of medal applications after Oct. 15, call the Air Force
Awards and Decorations Section, 210-565-2432.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In hurricane-naming, what letter of the alphabet is the
farthest ever reached, and what was the name? In other words, has
there ever been a Hurricane Zeus? We can't recall ever going beyond
O for Opal.
</P>
<P>
   A: Under the modern naming scheme, which in 1978 began using
alternating male and female names, the farthest letter reached was
T for Tanya in 1995, said Frank Lepore of the National Hurricane
Center in Miami. There were 19 named storms that year, the second
most active year on record after 1933, when 21 storms occurred
(they were numbered back then, not named).
</P>
<P>
   In no case could there be a Hurricane Zeus, anyway, since the
letters Q, U, X, Y and Z aren't used for storm names.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons, Lepore explained. There aren't enough
names beginning with those letters to allow spares, in case the
name of a storm is retired because of the number of deaths or
amount of damage it produced. And the names must be understandable
in Spanish, French and Dutch. Weather officials wouldn't want the
misprounciation of a name to produce something incorrect or
offensive, for example when garbled in transmission.
</P>
<P>
   In the event that so many storms occur in a year that the World
Meteorological Organization runs through its list, it then would
use the Greek alphabet, Lepore added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Georgia's promotional literature now calls it the Empire
State of the South. I thought Georgia was the Peach State. Can you
clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is nothing new. For years Georgia has had several
unofficial nicknames, including Empire State of the South, because
of its large size and thriving industries. In fact, the Georgia
entry in World Book Encyclopedia has a headline with the name of
the state followed by the wordsThe Empire State of the South in
italics.
</P>
<P>
   Other Georgia nicknames over the years, in addition to Peach
State: Goober State, Cracker State and Yankee-Land of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Charlotte's problems related to big-time
sports mentioned that it had been voted the nation's most livable
city by the U.S. Conference of Mayors. Is this survey available
online?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Conference of Mayors doesn't name the most livable
city in America, said its spokesman, Jubi Headley. However, it does
make City Livability Awards honoring outstanding programs in
cities. There's no list available, Headley added, but you can find
information about the awards online at
www.usmayors.org/uscm/home.asp.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans and Gadsden, Ala., were awarded top honors in the
2000 City Livability Awards Program, incidentally.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a lot of talk in my office about the accuracy of
presidential election polls. Do you have the final results of the
major polls just prior to the 1996 election, as well as the actual
election vote totals?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a USA Today/CNN/Gallup tracking poll conducted Oct. 20-21,
1996, and reported Oct. 23, 52 percent of registered voters said
they planned to vote for Bill Clinton, 33 percent for Bob Dole, and
8 percent for Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll one week before the election showed
Clinton at 51 percent, Dole 34 percent, and Perot 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters daily tracking poll conducted by John Zogby Group
International, released Oct. 31, showed Clinton with 41.9 percent,
Dole 34.2 percent, and Perot 8.6 percent. ``Undecideds'' and the
margin of error accounted for the remaining percentages.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 5 election, Clinton got about 49.2 percent of the
votes (45,628,667); Dole, about 40.8 percent (37,869,435); and
Perot, about 8.5 percent (7,874,283).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently mentioned the long bridge over the Atchafalaya
River in Louisiana. I was told by my fourth-grade teacher in the
1930s that the Atchafalaya was the deepest river in the world. Is
that true?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a widespread belief among Louisianians that the
Atchafalaya is the world's deepest river, but Marc Wellman of the
State Library of Louisiana in Baton Rouge said it's probably not
true. He traced this belief to the fact that engineers building the
U.S. 190 bridge over the Atchafalaya at Morgan City had to rest one
of the piers on a foundation 176 feet below the low-water stage.
</P>
<P>
   Basing his conclusion on several resources, including NASA,
Wellman said he thinks China's Yangtze is the world's deepest
river. As NASA reports, upstream of the Dongting Swamp, the Yangtze
flows through three gorges: Qutang, Wu and Xiling.
</P>
<P>
   The river narrows abruptly in these gorges. Because the great
discharge must be conveyed through narrow cross sections, the flow
depths become enormous, at one point reaching 150 meters (just over
492 feet).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
