<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hum this tune driving downtown
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I almost shot my oatmeal out my nose Sunday morning when I read
in the newspaper that Austin officials have noticed that the
traffic downtown has gotten really bad because of all the lane
closures for construction.
</P>
<P>
   That would be like going to the dump and saying, ``Boy, it sure
smells funny out here.''
</P>
<P>
   What did our leaders expect for Austin, which has progressed
from the Live Music Capital of the World to the Merge Right Capital
of the World?
</P>
<P>
   Because of state law, the 13 telecommunications companies
downtown can keep tearing up streets over and over again to lay
cable, so they can keep up with the competition. The city lobbied
these companies to move downtown. So the streets are constantly dug
up. This comes as a surprise? That's like getting a second dog and
being surprised by an increase in barking.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, driving downtown is a pain in the butt. You've heard
of the University of Texas football mantra, ``Come Early, Be Loud,
Stay Late,'' right? If you're driving in downtown Austin, it's
``Leave Early, Honk Loud, Arrive Late.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is a conspiracy. A poll of 500 people done for
KVUE-TV shows 59 percent of likely voters favor light rail, which
Austin will vote on in November. What better way to make light rail
seem great than to make the cruise through the intersection of
Sixth and Lamar a half-hour ordeal?
</P>
<P>
   The traffic in downtown Austin is so bad it inspires me to
compose. This verse is to be sung to the tune of Petula Clark's
``Downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need a place to get in somebody's face,
</P>
<P>
   ``Just go drive downtown _ DOWNTOWN.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else quite like it when it comes to living
urban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to kill the yuppie who is driving that Suburban.
...''
</P>
<P>
   As usual I have solutions to the problem. Why not turn the area
between 11th Street, Cesar Chavez Street, Guadalupe Street and
Interstate 35 into a parking lot? That's what it has become, so why
not collect fees? Even more fun, why not just turn the whole
downtown area into a -- emolition -- erby? The driver of the last
car running gets to pie Mayor Watson. How about solving this mess
the way we handled lawn watering? Drivers who live at addresses
that end with the numbers 1 or 6 would be allowed to drive downtown
on Tuesdays, drivers who live at addresses that end in 2 or 8 could
drive downtown on Wednesdays, and drivers who cut people off when
they get tipped off, because the guy in front of them is using his
directionals would be shipped back to Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might complain that not being able to go downtown
every day is a hardship. That's like carping about not being
allowed to have a permanent rash.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing the city might consider is turning the catastrophe
into an arts project. I get sick of looking at the same old orange
traffic cones, barricades and warning signs. Why does all of this
road trash have to be orange? What with UT, we're lousy with orange
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't we get art classes at Austin's public schools to paint
the orange traffic cones relaxing earth tones, like maybe taupe,
pumpkin and puce? As in, ``The traffic is so bad it makes me want
to puce.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
