A3305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY0928-COX     09-27 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reflections on loss of innocence
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene at St. Peter's Church in Huber Heights last week was
eerily familiar.
</P>
<P>
   I had been here once before, it seemed: Hundreds of solemn-faced
Catholic school children, in their plaid uniforms, filing into a
cavernous church. All were solemn; the older ones wore crumpled
faces and visible chinks in their armor of adolescent
invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   All looked as if something had been taken away from them.
</P>
<P>
   They had lost a popular schoolmate, eighth-grader Jesica Young,
she of the ever-present smile and a demeanor that principal Feliza
Poling described as ``always up.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also had suffered a collective loss of innocence, a
belief that murder is something that happened somewhere else, to
someone they didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered what that felt like. On a bleak December day in
1968, I filed into Ascension Church in Kettering with hundreds of
my schoolmates for the funeral Mass of 12-year-old Regina
Duchnowski.
</P>
<P>
   During the agonizing days that the Ascension sixth-grader was
missing, we all prayed desperately for her safe return. Her body
was found in a woods two days later, raped and strangled.
</P>
<P>
   Regina had been a playmate of my younger sister Peggy. ``I
always felt that with Regina's death, I lost my innocence because I
knew then that bad things happened to people,'' Peggy recalled. ``I
always thought it was something our parents would protect us from,
and after it happened to her, things weren't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the students at St. Peter's , as they clutched
Kleenexes and held onto each other for dear life, I couldn't help
wondering if they felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   School counselor Barbara Campbell has been meeting with anywhere
from 20 to 50 students every day since Tuesday, when Jesica died
from wounds suffered Monday morning in a bludgeoning attack that
also killed her mother, Martha Madewell, and her mother's
boyfriend, Nathan Marshall. ``The big fear that I've picked up on
is that this could happen to them, especially if there's any
parental strife at home,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've also talked about what good could come out of this _
how they can face issues such as their own mortality and the way
that they treat one another.'' The Rev. Earl Simone eulogized that
the tragedy teaches a difficult lesson, that we can't pretend we
are safe from violence and death.
</P>
<P>
   School officials know the funeral Mass is only the beginning of
the healing process, that they must work with the students in the
weeks and months ahead. They know that, at every eighth-grade
milestone, ``it will feel as if we're missing someone,'' Poling
said.
</P>
<P>
   With time and care, these students may recover their faith and
their bond with each other.
</P>
<P>
   But something else _ that intangible assurance that murder is
something that happens somewhere else, to someone you didn't know _
that, they have lost much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
