<HEADER>
A3306 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY0928-COX     09-27 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web redefining world around us whether we like it or not
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet was designed by American scientists to ensure that
the military had a way to communicate when the nation was being
pummeled by thermonuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Unless pornography, music downloads or Olympic coverage is more
destructive than nuclear war, there's little chance that
governments will ever control Internet content.
</P>
<P>
   Consider when Texas lawmakers didn't like an Internet Web site
that sold access to public information. The state sold the same
information on digital tapes to marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Outlawing this specific practice shut down the Texas Web site
only until it reappeared a few days later as a Caribbean island Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet technology has been freed from the bottle. There's
no putting it back.
</P>
<P>
   It can be viewed as an exciting new frontier in communication,
business, entertainment and education. The Internet also can be
regarded as destroyer of cultures, values and established commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the world will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can log onto the Internet and find how to build a bird
house or a car bomb. People can read racist rantings or the Bible
in seven translations.
</P>
<P>
   Dictators and tyrants who sustain absolute control through
propaganda and deceit now must keep their citizens away from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   China's communist leadership is trying to become a first-world
nation wired for the latest technology. At the same time, communist
leaders are trying to hold back the tide by screening out
unfavorable Internet content. Barring an improbable breakthrough,
China's leaders won't be able to do both.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's advancement of democracy is tempered with the
threat to destroy traditional institutions. This worldwide
communication source could level a lot of good along with the bad.
</P>
<P>
   The auction Web site eBay threatens antique businesses around
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some car manufacturers are considering cutting out car dealers
and selling their products directly to customers on the Internet.
Lawmakers in some states, including Texas, are scrambling to
protect traditional car dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are upset that Wal-Mart and other super stores
have destroyed traditional community businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Customers switched from Mom and Pop businesses to Wal-Mart for
the large selection and discounts offered due to volume buying.
</P>
<P>
   Surely customers would just as quickly abandon Wal-Mart if an
international Internet company offered bigger discounts, greater
selection and convenient 24-hour doorstep delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers will protect traditional business interests up to the
point that dot.com lobbyists give bigger political donations. This
could be a good time for established special interest groups to
support campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee was able to fund the current
27th Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia, in large measure by
selling television rights to the games for $1.3 billion. NBC bought
exclusive rights to broadcast the games in the United States for
$705 million. Viewership is down. People can get instant results on
the Internet Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The technology promises to make life even more difficult for
traditional information and entertainment providers in years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Since anyone in the world can become an instant publisher,
editor, reporter and opinion monger, people will have to learn to
distinguish between fact and fiction, if not outright fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult enough for large daily newspapers to get
everything right when it is written, edited and fact-checked by
layers of trained professional journalists.
</P>
<P>
   For good or for evil, there's no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
