 Attn. Sports Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic stories from The New York Times News Service for
Thursday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASEBALL (Sydney, Australia) _ In a shocking upset, a U.S.
team made up of top prospects, lower-level minor-leaguers and a
former major-leaguer or two shut out Cuba, 4-0, to win the gold
medal. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT-OLY 6.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLING (Sydney, Australia) _ In perhaps the greatest
Olympic wrestling upset ever, Rulon Gardner of the United States, a
first-time Olympian, beat Russia's heavyweight, Alexander Karelin,
ending the Russian's string of three straight gold medals. By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT-OLY 2,3,4,5,7.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Regarding that form of
drug known as ``performance-enhancing,'' there is only one claim
George Vecsey says he would definitely believe from any athlete:
``Personally, Chief, I slurp 'em up like Corn Flakes. I can't wait
to finish talking to you so I can go get me some more.'' That
person I would believe. Sports column. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-RUSSIA (Sydney, Australia) _ To a former Russian
basketball coach who has seen it all, these are not good days. The
Americans, he says, are simply too skilled and strong for the
Russians to keep pace. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-AUSSIE-TOWN (Lithgow, Australia) _ Lithgow, population
15,000, lies at the end of the electrified railroad line from
Sydney, 90 miles to the west. It is not the sort of place the
writer Donald Horne was thinking of when he famously described
Australia as ``the lucky country.'' Remote, economically depressed,
and cursed with dreadful weather, Lithgow is worlds away from the
designer skyscrapers and sun-splashed beaches of Sydney. On a
recent weekday afternoon, a few cars rattled along Main Street,
barely outracing the fog that drifted down from the nearby
mountains. And yet, for all its hard-luck veneer, Lithgow is as
proud, as captivated, and as unabashedly excited about the Olympics
as Sydney. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sports column on the
Australian favorites in the men's doubles tennis final, the
Woodies, Mark Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge, who ended a
distinguished doubles career together with a silver medal before
their home crowd. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-TRACK (Sydney, Australia) _ As Marion Jones progresses
in her attempt for five medals, Gail Devers misses her chance for a
gold in the 110 hurdles, her specialty, as she tears a hamstring
muscle. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT-OLY 8,9,10.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX (Sydney, Australia) _ They come from Kazakhstan,
Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan, the Ukraine and Russia, burly, hard-looking
men who fight with a relentless, intractable boxing style. On the
12th day of the 2000 Olympic boxing tournament, it was the fighters
from the countries formed by the breakup of the Soviet Union that
imposed a new pecking order on the competition. The once invincible
Cuban boxers lost four consecutive quarterfinal bouts and the
Americans got back in the medal hunt with three fighters _ Ricardo
Juarez, Ricardo Williams Jr., and Jermain Taylor _ advancing. By
Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TEN-VENUS (Sydney, Australia) _ With a gold medal to cap her
summer, Venus Williams erases all doubts that she is ready to
dominate the world of women's tennis. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT-OLY 1.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CYC (Sydney, Australia) _ Lance Armstrong loses to his
rival, Jan Ullrichs. By Peter Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TEN (Sydney, Australia) _ Yvgeny Kafelnikov of Russia faces
Tommy Haas of Germany for the men's singles gold medal. (Editors:
Late story.) By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV (Sydney, Australia) _ Laura Wilkinson of the United
States goes for a second gold, this time in the synchronized diving
event. (Editors: Late story.) By Bill Brink.
</P>
