<SLUG> BC-OLY-CYC-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN TEAM PREVAILS IN CYCLING ROAD RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Everything went according to plan for Lance
Armstrong and his U.S. teammates in the Olympic cycling road race
Wednesday. The problem was that things went even better for the
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Ullrich won the race by nine seconds from Alexander
Vinokourov of Kazakhstan, with Andreas Kloeden of Germany three
seconds further back. Michele Bartoli of Italy led in a 10-man
chasing group 1 minute 26 seconds behind Ullrich. Two Americans,
George Hincapie and Armstrong, were in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich completed the 239.4 kilometer (148.8 mile) race in 5
hours 29.08 for an average speed of 27 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The riders completed 14 laps of an undulating course that
stitched together the parklands, golf courses and race courses of
central Sydney before sweeping out through the city's eastern
suburbs and offering the riders a brief glimpse of the Pacific
Ocean at Bronte Beach. On a clear day, the roofless blue sky held
only four buzzing television helicopters and the heady scent of
eucalyptus.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators were sparse in the parks but crowded against the
barriers along the finish line and on the brief slopes at the
beach. The temperature reached 82 degrees Fahrenheit during the
closing laps, not ideal conditions for Armstrong, who often thrives
in the rain and chill _ conditions that bedeviled the women's race
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   The three medalists were part of a much larger breakaway. Midway
through the 13th lap, Ullrich attacked because, he said, the big
group was not working ``in harmony.'' Only Vinokourov and Kloeden
went with him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vinokourov had a different colored shirt on his back,
all three men wore identical white and pink helmets, the colors of
their professional team, Deutsche Telekom. Vinokourov completed his
Olympic training with the German team in Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   The three men worked in harmony, quickly pulling away from a
disjointed pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   The American strategy, said Armstrong, had been to place a rider
in the leading bunch. Then Armstrong would try to jump across late
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go too hard or crash and hurt myself,''
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie caught the big break as the three Telekom riders
escaped and did not realize what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw George I asked him if there was anyone away,''
Armstrong said. ``He said no. I said: `Two guys in the gold medal
group. Sweet!' Then on the last lap I saw the giant video screen. I
saw three guys cycling. I said, `George, who's that?' He said,
`Shoot!'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ullrich won the Tour de France in 1997 at the age of 23. Since
then he has struggled with his weight, starting every season with
more tires round his waist than on his bike, and he has only run
into his best form late in the year. He raced at 154 pounds, almost
7 fewer pounds than at the start of this year's Tour when he
finished a distant second to Armstrong. On the final lap he was so
strong that several times he had to slow and wait for his two
partners. With about two miles to go he finally abandoned them,
powering away to a comfortable victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich's 1997 Tour victory was based on overpowering time
trialing. He finished last season by winning the time trial in the
world championships. His form Wednesday suggests that he will be a
serious threat to Armstrong, the dominant time trialer in this
year's Tour, in Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard to beat him,'' Armstrong said. ``I
really like Jan. There's a mix of anticipation for Saturday with
happiness for Jan. He's a great guy. He deserves to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the tricky time trial course, full of tight
corners, will favor Armstrong over the powerful Ullrich. The
American, who missed the 1997 Tour recovering from testicular
cancer and who cracked a vertebra when he was knocked off his bike
by a car when training near Nice, France, in August, said that he
felt good physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs felt good today, better than I expected,'' Armstrong
said. ``I didn't really train for this race.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was confident of winning a medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``First three definitely,'' Armstrong said. ``Gold will be very
difficult. It will be a real battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ullrich had worked hard for his victory, he was relaxed
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already got my gold medal,'' he said. ``Lance has to go
for his.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
