<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TEN-VENUS-ART-570     09-27 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TEN-VENUS-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS EXTENDS DOMINANCE TO THE GOLD MEDAL STAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT-OLY 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The way Venus Williams dominated Elena
Dementieva with her sling-blade strokes was expected, as was her
customary parade queen's wave to the crowd upon match point, as was
her giddy acceptance of the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   But when the national anthem hit a crescendo Wednesday
afternoon, the statuesque Williams stood at the top of the medal
stand and wiped a tear from her eye. Usually, Williams' rawest
emotions remain hidden beneath her veil of confidence. Wednesday,
she allowed the moment to overwhelm her and appeared humbled by the
Olympic experience.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good look for Williams. Upon her 32nd straight victory
Wednesday, she discarded the superior attitude that has often
marked her post-match personality. After receiving the gold medal,
she praised her Russian opponent's resilience and complimented her
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much more meaningful than I thought,'' said Williams
after wearing down Dementieva, 6-2, 6-4, in the gold-medal match at
the tennis center. ``I felt really emotional. I felt really
excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just really one moment in time, because you see it on
TV, how the competitor bows their head, and they put the medal on.
It was really great. It was me.''
</P>
<P>
   This moment is one reason why she ignored the exhaustion created
by her packed summer schedule. When she arrived in Sydney, she was
tired, but quickly bounced back. She embraced the spectacle of the
opening ceremony, met other athletes during Olympic pin exchanges
and found a little kick of adrenaline as her matches came along.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the only noticeable dip in her enthusiasm registered
when she discussed the injury to her teammate and former gold
medalist from the 1996 team, Lindsay Davenport. The animosity that
grew between the two at the U.S. Open has disappeared. As much as
anyone, Williams did not want to see Davenport go down during the
first week of the Games. If Davenport had been healthy, she might
have joined Williams and the bronze medalist Monica Seles in a U.S.
sweep on the medal stand Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially, we could have all been on the stand _ in any
order,'' said Williams, whose most difficult match along her route
to the final was her three-set victory against Seles. ``I was
fortunate enough to get the gold, but Monica could have won the
match she played against me the other day. She could have won the
gold. One of my only regrets is that Lindsay wasn't here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Venus was _ and then some. Everyone in the crowd received an
up-close look at the one player who has dominated as a solo act
this summer. Just after tucking away a shaky third try at a match
point, Williams took a detour to the players' box. From the U.S.
coaches Billie Jean King and Zina Garrison, she grabbed an American
flag in one hand and held her racket in the other. It was an
ambidextrous celebration for the ubiquitous Williams. For an entire
summer, she has been everywhere, equally dominant on different
continents and under any circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Venus and Serena Williams will play for the gold
medal in doubles. But soon, the summer will end for Venus Williams.
And fall classes will begin. Although she will play some select
tournaments, Williams will enroll in a fashion design class. And if
a teacher or classmate should ask, ``So, what did you do last
summer?'', she can present the show-and-tell of all time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She has a Wimbledon winner's plate and a U.S. Open trophy. The
only thing she didn't take was the No. 1 ranking. Injured for six
months of the season, Williams couldn't catch the consistent
Martina Hingis, who still owns the top ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Venus, she's the more stronger,'' said Dementieva.
``But Hingis plays much better than her.''
</P>
<P>
   That's up for debate. Next year, the intrigue will begin. Can
the clever Hingis finally decode Williams' strength. Will Serena
Williams become her sister's major test? This summer, Venus
Williams had only one opponent to fear: herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I can get a little crazy,'' Williams said. ``I can
make a lot of mistakes and play badly. So sometimes, I'm scared for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, her victory wasn't about herself. When she won,
humility joined her in the medal ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the Wimbledons and the Grand Slams, you have so
many opportunities,'' Williams said. ``But this gold is just every
four years. Who knows, in 2004, I might not be chosen. You never
know what is going to happen. So this is the one moment for me, for
my country, for my family, for the team.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
