<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN     09-27 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: FINAL CHAPTER FOR A PAIR OF WOODIES
</HEADLINE>
 By HARVEY ARATON   
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ They have been known as the Woodies, the
Australian doubles of doubles, though they look nothing alike,
hardly play alike and have based themselves on opposite coasts of
the United States. They formed a partnership 10 years ago, when
Mark Woodforde was 25 and Todd Woodbridge was turning 20. Sixty-one
tournament titles, 11 of them Grand Slams, and one Olympic gold
medal later, they walked on the court here Wednesday afternoon to
thunderous applause, the final chapter to a storybook all but set
in print.
</P>
<P>
   Woodforde, the red-haired southpaw, had planned or fantasized it
this way, the gold medal match on Australian soil. He was tired of
the grind, the road, the raw-boned teenagers with the hunger in
their eyes. He and his American-born wife were expecting a baby
after New Year's. He had to tell Woodbridge, the brown-haired
right-hander, that he was coming to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it, he had said one night, as they picked at dinner,
as the red wine flowed. He, Woodbridge, had been around long enough
to have played championship doubles with Martina Navratilova, with
John McEnroe, who faded off the circuit as the 1980s closed and
left Woodforde looking for a second. He had preferred a
right-hander, a more natural complement, and an Australian, a more
desirable companion.
</P>
<P>
   Had they been best friends? Hard to say, they said. Difficult to
define the relationship because it wasn't as if they went on golf
holidays, or sightseeing tours. It was enough to spend years
jetting to distant outposts and urban centers, practicing on the
side courts, playing the matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stepped off the court,'' Woodforde said, ``you tended
to separate.''
</P>
<P>
   They had had a substandard year in 1999, and started to hear
people imply that their formula for success, whatever it was, no
longer worked. They were proud of their record, of being part of
the great Australian tennis history, of being the Woodies. They
rededicated themselves for one more run, one last emotional ride,
all the way to the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Woodforde broke down after they won the French Open, the one
elusive Grand Slam, last June. When they carried the momentum on to
London and won Wimbledon for a sixth time, he went back to the
hotel and sobbed some more. He said he was all cried out by the
time Wednesday's gold medal match against Canada's Daniel Nestor
and Sebastien Lareau came around because it just felt right, for
both players, when they really thought about how far they had gone,
how they now could finish at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told someone before we went on court that today was going to
be good or really great,'' Woodbridge said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, they both had pregnant wives watching from the
stands. They had a crowd of about 10,000, mostly Australians who
truly believed that Venus Williams' victory in the women's gold
medal match over Elena Dementieva was the junior varsity game. They
sang ``Waltzing Matilda'' and swayed to a mantra of ``Aus-sies ...
Aus-sies.'' They chanted ``Let's Go Woodies,'' and sang, ``If you
really love the Woodies clap your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone loved their chances for gold after they won the first
set, breaking Lareau's serve three times. But the late afternoon
clouds rolled in, and as the day turned gray, the crowd's energy
level took a precipitous drop. Three-of-five-set doubles does not
create the climactic surge of, say, Cathy Freeman start-to-finish
in the 400 meters. It didn't help when the underdog Canadians took
the second set and began to look like the snappier team.
</P>
<P>
   Lareau had raised his level after the first set while Nestor, a
lanky left-hander, was playing so well, better than the Woodies had
ever seen him, it occurred to Woodbridge that Nestor might be a
potential partner if his oral agreement doesn't work out with the
Swede, Jonas Bjorkman. The Canadians took the third set, forced a
fourth-set tiebreaker and didn't even have to strike a gold-medal
clinching shot. Woodbridge double-faulted on match point, putting
the punctuation on the 5-7, 6-3, 6-4, 7-6(2) defeat and one of the
best doubles teams in the history of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   They hugged in the service box, before going to the net.
Woodforde didn't cry this time. His wife, Erin, did, but that was
when her husband was stepping up to the medal stand to have the
silver slipped around his neck, and again when the Woodies walked
off to one last ovation, arms around each other's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   As they say here, they'd given it a go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't change what the results were, what our legacy
is,'' said Woodforde, the good Aussie, the gracious loser. ``Our
partnership will always be gold.''
</P>
<P>
   He is committed to play the Davis Cup final in Spain, without
Woodbridge, who was not selected for the team. Woodforde sighed and
said, ``I kind of wish today was my last match, with Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodbridge was the more emotional one this time, wiping away
tears and saying he was just happy that the Woodies had played
their last match together in Australia, at the Olympics, and not
``some small tournament in some remote corner of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was home, where the heart is, where Geoff Pollard of Tennis
Australia could appear at their news conference to thank them for a
decade of success, for their 1996 gold medal in Atlanta and for
silver this last time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have become icons in Australian sport and deservedly so,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, mate,'' a blushing Mark Woodforde said. ``Thanks.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
