</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-MUSLIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL RANSOM MONEY FLOATS PHILIPPINE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines _ In one of the poorest parts of the
southern Philippines, where incomes average just $200 a year,
expensive, high-powered guns and speedboats suddenly materialized
in subsistence fishing villages, and here in the closest big city,
demand surged for motorcycles, gold jewelry, name-brand athletic
wear, and designer sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   The local economy was so awash in American greenbacks recently
that the floundering Philippine peso actually strengthened against
the dollar in local banks.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden bonanza? It was payday for a band of Muslim
rebels called the Abu Sayyaf, who over several weeks raked in more
than $15 million in ransom for dozens of foreigners and Filipinos
they had taken hostage over the last five months. The kidnappings
created a chain of jobs, from ``spotters'' who scoped out victims
to ``couriers'' who snatched them, from villagers who guarded
hostages to local women who cooked for them _ with each group
awaiting its cut. Even the influx of journalists, diplomats, and
negotiators meant a bustling business for local translators,
drivers, hotels, and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how bad things are here in Mindanao, a region
where half the population lives in abject poverty and the average
person has six years of schooling, that kidnapping as a local
industry jump-started the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it was not the kind of public works program
the government had in mind. Fed up with months of negotiations and
under-the-table payments that emboldened the rebels to take new
hostages, the military attacked rebel bases on nearby Jolo Island
11 days ago. So far, however, the military has been unable to
rescue 17 remaining hostages or capture the rebel leaders, though
officials say the troops have killed more than 100 militants, out
of an estimated few thousand.
</P>
<P>
   But even if government troops manage to wipe out the Abu Sayyaf
entirely, it will almost be beside the point. A Muslim rebellion
has raged in the southern Philippines for 30 years, claiming
120,000 to 200,000 lives and stalling economic growth. Muslim
leaders say unless the underlying causes of the revolt are
addressed _ poverty, lack of education, and perceived
discrimination _ new militants will simply fill the shoes of the
Abu Sayyaf, and one of Asia's most persistent and bloody
insurgencies will drag on for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military campaign is a waste of time. It'll never solve
the problem,'' said Shariff Julabbi, a leader of the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front, the largest group of Muslim separatists. ``The
problem is lack of jobs, lack of development, injustice,
exploitation. . . . The government has to address the roots of the
problem, and that means restoring our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab traders and missionaries brought Islam to the islands that
are now the southern Philippines more than 600 years ago, and it
soon became the dominant religion. Ever since, the Muslim tribes of
Mindanao resisted would-be colonizers, fending off the Spaniards
and battling the Americans until the United States integrated the
region into an independent Philippines in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Muslims represent 5 to 8 percent of the Catholic-majority
country, and many still don't consider themselves Filipino. The
provinces in which they live _ including the two strongholds of the
Abu Sayyaf _ are among the nation's poorest. Mindanao supplies 43
percent of the country's food and is rich in minerals, but its
infrastructure and transport are among the worst in the country,
there is little industry, and even potable water is scarce in rural
areas. Community leaders complain that Manila has neglected the
south, focusing more on killing off the rebels than on boosting
living standards.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim politicians say that neglect extends to the halls of
power: there are no Muslim Cabinet members, only three Muslims
among the Filipino ambassadors to 54 Islamic nations, and just 9
Muslim members in the 230-member House of Representatives, said
Congressman Asani S. Tammang of Sulu province, the main stronghold
of the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims, he said, are regarded by most Christians as
untrustworthy and lazy, and anyone who lives in rebel areas is
branded a sympathizer.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bias is subtle. ``If a Christian commits a crime,
only his name is identified in the paper. But if the offender is
Muslim, the report will specify he is a Muslim,'' he said. Even the
local jail here classifies detainees as Muslims and non-Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tammang says anti-bias statutes and aid programs alone
cannot improve life for Muslims here. Law and order must be
established before economic development can take hold, and that is
why he supports the military campaign to wipe out the Abu Sayyaf.
There is also a more insidious problem: a lawless gun culture, and
a practically non-existent criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Sulu has three regional trial courts, four municipal circuit
courts and one municipal trial court _ but no judges willing to
preside, complained Tammang, a former lawyer. Frustrated citizens
``take the law into their own hands. And without peace and order,
we can't introduce more livelihood programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Taluksangay, 11 miles east of Zamboanga, is one of the
better-off Muslim villages, but even here, says village secretary
Saleh Buhaini, the local seaweed farmers and subsistence fishermen
earn an average of $150 a month.
</P>
<P>
   A dirt road leads to the village square, past the oldest mosque
on the Zamboanga peninsula and a single basketball court, the only
recreational facility for young people. There is a bare-bones
clinic, a one-room daycare center, an elementary school, and a
two-story high school, putting Taluksangay's facilities light years
ahead of those on more remote islands.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even here, 70 percent of the population is illiterate, there
is no dentist or hospital, and a large proportion of villagers live
in single-room wooden shacks on stilts at the water's edge, without
electricity or furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Hajara Jailani, a 50-something unschooled widow who earns
between 25 and 50 cents a day fishing from a small wooden canoe,
laments the ``very big gap (in living standards) between Christians
and us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have land to grow produce. We have only the sea. They are
more educated, they have technical know-how, they are more
advanced,'' she said wistfully. But like many of her neighbors _
and unlike many rebel leaders and politicians who blame Manila for
the poor conditions _ she concludes that ``it's our own fault. We
have not strived very much or tried to educate our people.''
</P>
<P>
   The two village schools are less than 200 yards away from the
cluster of shacks where she lives among a tribe of Muslim sea
gypsies, but only about 10 of their 400 children attend school.
</P>
<P>
   Buhaini encourages villagers to send their kids to school, but
it is an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   There are some, however, for whom is already too late. Salihin
Mahamud, 31, is an elementary school drop-out who earns $33 a month
as a seaweed farmer _ not nearly enough for his wife and five
children. He not only understands why the Abu Sayyaf resorted to
kidnapping to bankroll their revolution, but confides he has
considered joining them himself, ``because I have no other
good-paying work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
