<HEADLINE>
DUE PROCESS LOSES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court rewarded Brandeis
University this week for having crafted a student disciplinary
procedure that is so vague that its commitment to basic fairness
cannot legally be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that is certain to have repercussions in this
college-rich Commonwealth, a sharply divided court held that a
student accused of misconduct has no right to due process unless
the university administration explicitly guarantees it.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for an extracurricular education in justice?
</P>
<P>
   By a 3-2 vote, the state's highest court dismissed a student's
complaint that he had been denied a fair hearing in 1996 when the
Brandeis judicial board found him guilty of sexual misconduct. The
court found unworthy of adjudication David A. Schaer's contention
that the panel of five students and two professors did not
interview him during its investigation, that it considered
``irrelevant and inflammatory'' evidence against him, and that the
record of its closed-door proceeding reduced to only 12 lines the
conflicting testimony of 13 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   None of that matters, the majority held, because ``a university
is not required to adhere to the standards of due process
guaranteed to criminal defendants or to abide by the rules of
evidence adopted by courts.'' College judicial boards might well be
star chambers but, as the court saw it, ``it is not the business of
lawyers and judges to tell universities what statements they may
consider and what statements they might reject.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a laissez-faire attitude might have made some sense in an
era when violating curfew was the worst infraction a college
student could commit. What sense does it make at a time when binge
drinking, date rape, and plagiarism are commonplace on even the
most prestigious campuses?
</P>
<P>
   In a dissent written by Associate Justice Roderick Ireland and
joined by Associate Justice Judith Cowin, Roderick warned that,
``In a hearing on a serious disciplinary matter there is simply too
much at stake for an individual student to countenance the
university's failure to abide by the rules it has itself
articulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland and Cowin found the procedural rules Brandeis laid out
in its handbook on disciplinary proceedings not nearly as ambiguous
as did the majority. By giving a ``strained reading'' to those
rules, he wrote, the majority defied ``common sense'' and let the
university off the hook. ``Brandeis should be required to follow
its own internal rules when imposing serious disciplinary sanctions
on a student.''
</P>
<P>
   In Schaer's case, the college junior was placed on probation,
banned from campus for a summer, and ordered to undergo
psychological counseling for his ``unwanted sexual activity'' with
an old girlfriend. He had testified that the sex was consensual.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago that a victim of rape on most campuses could
expect her report to land in the circular file of the college
police department. Colleges were notorious for minimizing reports
of violence on campus, especially sexual assaults. That is still
the case at some schools, but at fewer now that federal law
requires them to make their police logs public and to report their
crime statistics to the US Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Those hard-won reforms, designed to ensure public safety, need
not be in conflict with the right of the accused to a fair hearing.
In a university setting, especially, isn't it important for young
adults to learn that real justice requires the protection of the
rights of accused and accuser?
</P>
<P>
   The SJC has ruled that campus justice is not a matter for
lawyers and judges. It is up to college communities themselves,
then, to choose: Will they clarify the rights of all their students
or adopt the ambiguous approach to student discipline that just
earned Brandeis a pass?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
