<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-QUESTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION QUESTION OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHALE PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q I'm converting to Catholicism for my husband-to-be, and I
cannot understand purgatory, nor praying to the dead for help. Am I
dense? Can this be?
</P>
<P>
   L.O., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Purgatory and saints can be difficult concepts for
non-Catholics to grasp, but they are essential parts of Catholic
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Purgatory is defined as ``an intermediate state of purification
between death and heaven that provides for the removal of remaining
personal obstacles to the full enjoyment of eternal union with
God,'' according to an article written for the Encyclopedia of
Catholicism by the Rev. J. Augustine Di Noia, a theologian at the
Dominican House of Studies in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that human beings, when they die, have not always
led lives without moral blemish, and so they need to be made fit,
or holy, before spending eternity in heaven with God. So purgatory
is where people are purified in preparation for heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Purgatory has been depicted by artists as a place of fiery
torment, but there is no consensus among theologians as to just
what the experience is like or how long it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what time means after death, so although
purgatory is metaphorically described in terms of time, theologians
talk of an interval,'' Di Noia said in an interview. ``It could be
instantaneous. Nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the second part of your question: Catholics pray to God,
but they pray for the dead, and they pray that the dead who have
been saved, saints, will intercede with God on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Some Catholic devotional prayers are directed at saints _ for
example, the Hail Mary is directed at Mary. But Catholic
theologians say saints cannot directly grant healing or
forgiveness, but can only intercede with God on the worshiper's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for the dead, that they would receive God's mercy and
kindness, and we pray that the saints would intercede, or pray for
us,'' said the Rev. Paul Ritt, a theologian and pastor of Saint
Theresa's Church in Sherborn. ``But it's by Christ's grace that we
receive, not by the grace of saints.''
</P>
</TEXT>
