<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRITER'S WRONG, LONDONERS HARUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Salman Rushdie announced last week that he had
left London for New York because he found the intellectual scene
here ``bitchy'' and ``backbiting,'' London's literati responded to
his criticism by being, well, bitchy and backbiting.
</P>
<P>
   Letterfrom LondonThe writer A.N. Wilson suggested that Rushdie,
who had grown up and later sought sanctuary in London, after his
book ``The Satanic Verses'' earned him a death edict from Iran's
Islamic leaders, was simply washed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's gratitude for you,'' another writer, Jasper Gerard,
said after reading Rushdie's London-dissing comments in The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a Guardian columnist Julie Burchill, the former punk
rock writer who has turned bitchiness into a genre, who really had
a go at Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``the US has done, is doing and will do more damage
to this planet than Nazi Germany,'' Burchill accused Rushdie of
abandoning London because the British have the good taste not to
buy his books anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once more it is naked self-interest attempting to cloak its
dank and shameful crevices in the watered silk of artistic
stimulation,'' Burchill wrote in her weekly column, in which she
routinely denounces Americans as materialistic, arrogant racists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Brits move to America, be they actors, writers or stupid
sportsmen-turned-movie-tough-guys . . . they move there for one of
two reasons, both of which have nothing to do with art,'' Burchill
added. ``They move there because they are rich and greedy for more,
or because, unconsciously, they worship evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of London's more highbrow writers went off on Rushdie years
ago, when he started hanging around with Bono, the lead singer of
U2. Serious writers, they sniffed, don't pal around with rock
stars, especially Irish ones.
</P>
<P>
   But those who admired Rushdie for his writing and his defying
the Iranian fatwa stuck by him _ at least until his
less-than-cordial remarks about London appeared in the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie said London is uninspiring. ``I think it speaks for
itself that, for somebody who lived in England for as long as I
did, relatively little of my work has dealt with it,'' Rushdie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Rushdie's not writing about London or Britain in
general had more to do with having spent the last decade in hiding,
smothered by bodyguards. Rushdie lived in 30 safe houses during the
1990s, avoiding the Islamic extremists who wanted to kill him. As
for ordinary British life, Wilson said, Rushdie had ``less
experience of it than most of us have of outer space.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie is not alone in believing that the United States is a
more stimulating place to live for writers, especially novelists.
Martin Amis, one of Britain's most celebrated novelists, has
suggested that he would abandon London for the States, citing
almost the same complaints as Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
   Burchill is furious with Rushdie, Amis, and Jeanette Winterson,
another prominent British writer who has said she prefers America
to Britain. ``If you want to worship evil and cosy up in the belly
of the beast, you're perfectly free to do so, but please don't
dress it up as love of art,'' Burchill fumed. ``Preferring Britain
to the US, despite all our faults, means that you respect
tolerance, kindness and a refusal to judge people merely on how far
they have made it up the dung heap we call capitalism. Preferring
the US to Britain, on the other hand, reveals a person to be a
blind worshipper of power, money and those crazy go-to-hell golf
slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short,'' Burchill said,``any Briton who emigrates to
America is a pathetic, traitorous little sneak, a disgrace to the
human race that is currently suffering under the studded cowboy
boot of Uncle Sam, and as such deserves to be stripped of their
British citizenship . . . and never allowed back on this sceptered
isle again.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment, apparently, is part of the kindness and
tolerance Burchill considers inherent here and missing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie said he has been re-energized by what he calls New
York's ``famous electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much stuff just asking me to write it down here,''
the Times quoted him as saying. ``You know, all the furniture on
the street. What places are called. Everything has a different
name. Toothpaste isn't called the same thing, coffee isn't called
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But traitors are called the same thing, and for more than a few
British writers, Rushdie has thumbed his nose at them and gone over
to the Philistines.
</P>
<P>
   The Guardian, which used to run an occasional column by Rushdie,
informed its readers that Rushdie's new muses are not nearly as
fond of him. Some New York socialites, the paper reported, are
reluctant to dine with Rushdie at any number of trendy Gotham
eateries, lest those unaware that the fatwa has been lifted try to
make a name for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The paper quoted an unnamed ``literary commentator'' trashing
Rushdie's latest novel, ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' and
describing Rushdie as being so egotistical that he would not allow
changes to be made in the draft. In London, when former friends
start wheeling out anonymous quotes to impugn your integrity, you
might as well pack it in.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene that George Orwell would have loved to capture. And
once did. Salman Rushdie, it seems, is destined to become the
Winston Smith of the London literati: a nonperson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
