u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-27 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEMAN WILLIAMS EAGER FOR THE NEXT GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sacks. The pressures. The lack of a running game. The
inability to punch the ball in from the red zone. The overall
offensive impotence. Traffic and water-flow problems at Foxboro
Stadium. Heck, even the Red Sox' sorry finish.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Most every time, most everyone does, figures Patriots tackle
Grant Williams, a mountain of a young man.
</P>
<P>
   The line maligned? It comes with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every offensive line is the most maligned group on
each team,'' Williams said to laughs in the Patriots locker room.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Williams said, the line needs work, as do other
spots on the team. But he thinks things are improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch the tape and you see playing good, playing good and
then all of a sudden at a key moment, there's a mistake,'' Williams
said. ``We can't do that. It can't happen at those times. There are
things I can do better. Everyone's included in that. It's a
combination of a number of things and areas. We're not bad. But
we're not good enough to make mistakes at crucial times and
overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Bill Belichick talked about a finger-in-the-dike
theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pass protection against Tampa Bay and that wasn't a
problem (against Miami),'' he said. ``You put your finger in the
dike on the running game on first and second down and that's not a
problem. It's a big pass play on third down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Miami, the offensive line gave up two sacks of Drew
Bledsoe, down from three the week before against Minnesota and six
each in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing is getting him hit, and we got him hit some,''
Williams said. ``It doesn't matter if it's a three-step drop or a
seven-step drop, we should take a little more pride and not get him
hit. Myself included. I gave up, I think, one sack but I got him
hit two other times. That shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he sees that improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just see the line coming together a little bit and
getting a little better each week,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a mix-and-match proposition on the offensive line.
Veteran free agents Joe Andruzzi and Sale Isaia have been brought
in at guard in recent weeks to surround center Damien Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 6 feet 7 inches and 325 pounds, was signed as a free
agent in March but injured his knee early in training camp. He
finally got into a game late in preseason and then was somewhat of
a surprise starter in the opener at right tackle. In Miami, he
played part of the game at right tackle, the rest at left tackle
when he replaced Bruce Armstrong, still hampered by his own knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The shifting can make things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have about 20 seconds to adjust in your own little way,''
Williams said. ``I come over and I always ask the guard to help me
keep my head up. Most plays, you can flip-flop over in your head,
but there are some plays that are run only one way. If I've been
running the back side of a run all week and now I'm on the front
side of a run, now you have to refresh your memory a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, you line up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things you can't argue,'' Williams said.
``If they want me to play linebacker, if they want you to start
somewhere in the NFL, you just put your hat on and try to do the
best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams came into the NFL with Seattle as an undrafted free
agent out of Louisiana Tech. Last year, he started 15 games at
right tackle and then had a rough game, along with the rest of the
Seahawks, against Miami in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a two-year, $2.1 million contract here and the
transition has not been the smoothest. First the knee injury. Now
the rough start.
</P>
<P>
   Williams isn't letting it get him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 0-4 but at the same time I feel excited about the future
here,'' he said. ``We're still getting into our systems, and
looking up the road, it only looks better.''
</P>
<P>
   He's talking just a small piece down the street, Williams
insisted, not way off down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here it was for the long haul and I'm still
excited about this season,'' he said. ``I'm not looking forward to
next year. I'm looking forward to this week. I was talking to some
guys and we were ready to line up and go against Denver. You just
want to get to the next one. Watch the tape, see the mistakes. And
I think there was some improvement in some areas, too, and see
those and scout Denver and get ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams saw plenty of the Broncos in his four years with
Seattle and liked playing in Denver. But he also knew his teams
were always in for a tough time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year in Seattle, we won the division and they were as
tough as anyone in that division easily,'' he said. ``They just got
off on the wrong foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrong foot. Sound familiar? The Broncos started last year
0-4. And finished 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Chad Eaton is ready to go again, too. ``The
reason you want to get out there so fast is you want to forget
about what just happened, win or lose,'' Eaton said. ``If you do
win, you want to forget about it and move on and not gloat about
it. If you lose, you want to get out there fast and forget about
it. You don't want it to eat you up. We're at a point now where I
think half the guys want to get out there and the other half are
saying, `What are we going to do?' We have to make sure everyone
has the same attitude: `Let's get back out there and let's finish.'
'' And how to read that attitude? ``You see who comes in at 9 in
the morning and who comes in at 12:30 in the afternoon, you can
tell attitude that way,'' said Eaton. ``You lead by being here at
10 a.m. and lead by example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
