<HEADLINE>
`PEGASUS' OFF TO FLYING START IN HIS RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Impressive. Very impressive. That's the best way to describe the
return to the races of Kentucky Derby hero Fusaichi Pegasus, who
won a race Saturday he had every right to lose.
</P>
<P>
   A $4 million yearling, Fusaichi Pegasus was the toast of the
racing world after he won the Derby May 6. Even a loss in the May
20 Preakness to Red Bullet, who is out for the year with a leg
injury, could not diminish the luster of Fusaichi Pegasus, who was
sold to stud for $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the big bay son of Mr. Prospector had not raced since
the Preakness. He had been on the shelf since wounding a hoof by
kicking a stall wall before the Belmont Stakes June 10. Owner Fusao
Sekiguchi and trainer Neil Drysdale had insisted to skeptics that
Fusaichi Pegasus would run again, with the $4 million Breeders' Cup
Classic at Churchill Downs Nov. 4 the ultimate goal. The colt
reappeared in Saturday's Jerome Handicap at Belmont Park, which is
restricted to 3-year-olds and run at 1 mile.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Jerome, Drysdale, either out of candor or to make
an excuse in advance, threw cold water on his charge's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say he is completely fit, but he has come along faster
than I expected,'' said Drysdale. ``We're going into this race a
work or two shy. It's not necessary for this horse to win this
race. It's just a steppingstone to the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running in this race puts us ahead if weather interrupts his
training. I look for him to move forward off this race, and it puts
him in position to run again before the Breeders' Cup. Hopefully,
he'll regain his spring form, but he might need a race or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale hardly needed to worry, or make excuses, as Fusaichi
Pegasus simply galloped to victory, looking as good as he ever did
in a career that has seen him win six of eight starts, with two
seconds, and earn nearly $2 million. If, indeed, he improves off
Saturday's effort, then everybody else is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The race was run in a rapid 1:34, but Fusaichi Pegasus surged
past the leader, Travers runner-up Albert The Great, turning for
home, and then held off Del Mar Breeders' Cup winner El Corredor,
who closed late. The margin of victory was only three-quarters of a
length, but Fusaichi Pegasus was under a hand ride from jockey Kent
Desormeaux, who won by as much as he pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we hit the eighth-pole, he put his foot down and just
took off,'' said Desormeaux. ``I think I got whiplash from it. He
finished up with something left, and I'm just so glad for the
racing fans that he's back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that marked the return of Fusaichi Pegasus was
his model behavior before the race. One of the few knocks on him
has been that he acted up in the paddock or the post parade. On
Saturday, he was very professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more mature than he was in the spring,'' said
Drysdale. ``I think he handled everything very well. It's far too
early to discuss where he'll go next, but the Jockey Club Gold Cup
($1 million, 1 1/4 miles, at Belmont, vs. older horses) is
certainly one of our options.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a big deal if Fusaichi Pegasus starts in the Gold
Cup, because he likely would meet 4-year-old Lemon Drop Kid, who
has won the Brooklyn, Suburban, Whitney, and Woodward in
succession, and is the leading candidate to be Horse of the Year. A
duel between those two would offer a Breeders' Cup Classic preview,
sans the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it is great for the game to have ``FuPeg,'' as he is
known to his many admirers, back in action. He is a true glamour
horse, both in looks and performance, and not many of those come
around.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Valentine' shows heart
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino may be looking at a difficult season
with the team, but he's definitely on the right track with his
stable. Pitino's Celtic Pride Stable has come up with a very nice
2-year-old colt named A P Valentine, who won a maiden special
weight race on the Jerome undercard. A P Valentine is a son of
Horse of the Year A.P. Indy, out of an Alydar mare. That's about as
good as breeding gets, and the juvenile cost $475,000 as a
yearling. Trained by Nick Zito and ridden by Jorge Chavez, A P
Valentine raced gamely to be third in his debut at Saratoga Sept.
4. That set him up nicely for Saturday, and he whistled home a
winner by more than 4 lengths in the time of 1:23 for 7 furlongs.
What made his tally even more eye-catching was that he beat a very
promising rival in Pure Prize. Owned by Ogden Phipps and trained by
Shug McGaughey, Pure Prize is the first offspring of champion mare
Heavenly Prize, and his sire is Storm Cat, whose stud fee is
$300,000. Pure Prize, who also had been third in his bow at
Saratoga, chased A P Valentine to no avail. It was 12 lengths back
to the third-place finisher . . . Mighty, who won the Louisiana
Derby before injuring a knee in the Blue Grass at Keeneland April
15, was unsuccessful in his return bid. Sent off at even money in
an allowance race at Belmont Friday, the son of Lord At War faded
to fifth, beaten nearly 20 lengths. His future is uncertain . . .
On the local front, kudos go out to owner/trainer Florence Siravo
for the job she did with Lonsdale, a 7-year-old gelding who
dominated the Brass Monkey Starter Handicap series at Rockingham
Park. Lonsdale ran in all seven legs of the series, which began at
a mile and one-16th June 24 and increased in distance each race
until Saturday's final at 2 miles and 40 yards, and he won four of
them, while finishing second in two others. In the concluding
contest, Lonsdale simply cantered twice around the track under
Taylor Hole, who rode him in every leg but one, to score by 3 1/2
lengths. Siravo received a trophy and a $500 bonus for her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
