<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCE THEORY HARD TO SWALLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ One lunch with John Harrington, and we're supposed to
believe that peace is at hand on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   Must have been a Happy Meal. Just can't get enough of those
Pedro fries, can you?
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox spinners were so pleased that Dan Duquette and Jimy
Williams dined together at the same table _ plastic knives, we
assume _ that they posted a story on their Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``DAN DUQUETTE, JOHN HARRINGTON AND JIMY WILLIAMS MEET FOR
THOROUGH DISCUSSIONS,'' the headline read.
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Sox, who pride themselves on keeping things
``in-house,'' this was akin to setting an extra place at the table
for their fans, at least those who know how to click on a mouse.
(Another kind of mouse was spotted running through the Red Sox
clubhouse Sunday, but we digress.)
</P>
<P>
   Back to the last supp- . . . uh, lunch. What was actually said,
we can't tell you. None of the principals was saying, beyond
Duquette informing a Globe editorial writer that he and Harrington
told Williams they expect him back next season, and that no one was
condoning Carl Everett's actions, contrary to the impression left
by Duquette last week.
</P>
<P>
   But we suspect that a bottle of Maalox may have been substituted
for dessert. No owner enjoys being forced to referee a fight
between his GM and manager, especially after the GM insists over
and over in public there is no fight.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams, we are told, did not let this opportunity go to
waste. He gave Harrington a laundry list of grievances he has had
with Duquette, which means, we suspect, that Everett's name wasn't
the only one that crept into the discussion. Wil Cordero, Steve
Avery, Mo Vaughn, Mike Stanley, Steve Ontiveros, and Izzy Alcantara
may have been mentioned at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   Was Williams satisfied that he got a sympathetic hearing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always learned time's a great healer,'' he said before a
game with the White Sox. ``So time heals a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it can close the cavernous wounds exposed by last week's
falling out over Everett is an uncertain prospect at best. There's
no question that while Williams may not have his GM's backing, the
public is fully in his corner. This newspaper even published an
editorial Tuesday urging the Sox to retain Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you say obituary?'' Williams said. ``I never get to that
page.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was evidence that Williams came away from lunch
unconvinced that he is long for this team. One Toronto columnist,
whose lifetime batting average on such matters is close to Manny
Alexander's, ``reported'' Tuesday that Williams had an informal
agreement with Seattle GM Pat Gillick to manage the Mariners next
season.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario of Williams managing the M's is not far-fetched.
Gillick fired Williams in Toronto, but when Duquette hired Williams
for the Sox in November four years ago, Jimy came highly
recommended by Gillick. Yet the notion that the two men already
have an informal agreement, which violates all of baseball's
tampering rules, has about as much credibility as the theory that
dinosaurs never roamed the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do?'' Williams said when asked about the report. ``I don't
know what you're talking about. I have an agreement with the Red
Sox, a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   But just in case Williams doesn't come back, we wanted to give
Harrington a heads-up on a list of successors. These are people,
for one reason or another, we feel would fit right in on Yawkey
Way.
</P>
<P>
   1. Eminem. He and Carl speak the same language.
</P>
<P>
   2. George W. Bush. By November, he may be looking for work. Like
Jimy, he claims to be a baseball man. And he's had lots of
experience raising huge wads of cash.
</P>
<P>
   3. Billy Martin. He's dead. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kevin Kennedy. Yes, the Duke fired him once before, but never
count out a Kennedy in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   5. Carl Everett. Might as well make it official.
</P>
<P>
   6. Jules Asner. The E! girl? Just doing what we can to keep
Nomar happy.
</P>
<P>
   7. Slobodan Milosevic. Soon-to-be-unemployed dictator finds a
kindred spirit.
</P>
<P>
   8. Eddie Andelman. The Boston talk-show maven knows twice as
much as Jimy. Just ask him.
</P>
<P>
   9. Marty McSorley. Perfect guy to enforce clubhouse rules.
</P>
<P>
   10. Hillary Clinton. She's used to people who are unfaithful.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying this is a complete list. But it gives
Harrington someplace to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
