<HEADLINE>
$ADV30 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Saturday, Sept. 30, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time-shifted Olympics finally come to an end on NBC _ ``The
network that brings you yesterday's news tomorrow,'' as NBC's own
Jay Leno said. Given the many time zones between us, we'll still be
watching the closing ceremony after everyone in Sydney has gone
home.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 7 to midnight prime-time events on NBC include the
men's basketball gold medal game and finals in diving and track and
field. Sunday NBC will cover the vast spectacle of the closing
ceremony, including fireworks and performances by Midnight Oil and
Men at Work. Men's marathon coverage is also scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC and CNBC will join the network in covering everything from
soccer to canoeing from 10 a.m. on. Sunday's daytime events include
8 a.m. canoeing finals on MSNBC, as well as boxing, gymnastics and
volleyball finals. (No CNBC coverage on Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movies, Saturday at 8 p.m.: CBS and ABC aren't expecting to
topple the Olympics tonight, apparently. ABC airs ``First Knight,''
a 1995 Arthurian epic with Sean Connery, Richard Gere and Julia
Ormond. CBS, meanwhile, rolls out ``The Pelican Brief,'' the 1993
John Grisham adaptation with Julia Roberts and Denzel Washington.
Neither one's a classic, and both are filling all three hours of
prime time. That's the television equivalent of a white flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''60 Minutes,'' CBS Sunday at 7: 33rd season premiere, but Mike,
Morley and Co. aren't getting older, they're just getting better.
Tonight's stories include an Ed Bradley report on the
Firestone-tire story and a Morley Safer profile of conductor
Michael Tilson Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill,'' Fox Sunday at 7:30: You knew Dubya was
going to show up on this Texas-set animated comedy sooner or later,
right? Tonight's new episode finds Hank and Peggy disagreeing about
this year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Life,'' CBS Sunday at 8: Series premiere _ the first
new show of the season for the Big 3 networks. Heather Paige Kent
stars in this promising family show as a New Jersey thirtysomething
who decides to cancel her long-standing engagement and go back and
get her college degree. Ellen Burstyn and Paul Sorvino play her
parents, Kevin Dillon is her brother and Debi Mazar is on hand as
her best pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels,'' CBS Sunday at 9: Nicholas Cage, Meg Ryan and
Andre Braugher star in this 1998 romantic drama about an angel who
falls for a mortal in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons,'' Fox at 8: Moe, depressed at being turned down
for the Duff Beer calendar, gets surgery that turns him into a hit
with the ladies. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' Fox at 8:30: The boys wreak havoc at
the store, costing Lois her job. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 9: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice,'' ABC at 10: Lindsay whisks Bobby off to a
surprise wedding site _ Fenway Park. Marlee Matlin is this week's
guest defendant. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Swiss Family Robinson,'' ABC Sunday at 7: Jane
Seymour, James Keach and David Carradine star in this 1998
adaptation of the classic shipwreck tale. Airing as ``The Wonderful
World of Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fugitive'' marathon, TVLand beginning Saturday at 6 a.m.:
48 straight hours of David Janssen's flight through 1960s America,
running as a prelude to the new ``Fugitive'' series debuting next
week on CBS. The two-hour conclusion, though, is being held till
next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Society,'' TCM Saturday at 8: Bing Crosby, Grace Kelly
and Frank Sinatra star in this 1956 remake of ``The Philadelphia
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Placid,'' HBO Saturday at 9: No classic, but some R-rated
genre-movie fun, with Bill Pullman, Bridget Fonda and Oliver Platt
pursuing a 35-foot alligator in a Maine lake. Written by
television's David E. Kelley (``The Practice'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Hawaii,'' AMC Saturday at 10:05: Elvis in a lei. From
1961.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Football, ESPN Sunday at 8:30: The weekend's gridiron action
wraps up with the Falcons at the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Hardware Show 2000,'' HGTV at 9: Let it not be
said that television is not useful. A report on all the latest
products, tools and gadgets from the big show in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO at 9: Charlotte and Samantha are at
each others' throats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind the Music,'' VH1 Sunday at 9: Season opener for the
show that put VH1 on the map profiles Cat Stevens, now known as
Yusef Islam, and it won't be just another one of those
rock-and-roll-debauchery-and-rehab tales in which this show seems
to specialize. The man who made 1970s radio staples of ``Peace
Train,'' ``Wild World'' and ``Morning Has Broken'' has become a
devout Muslim, busy with religious and humanitarian activities, and
has been making music again. He's also controversial: When VH1's
crew took Islam to Israel, the singer was barred for allegedly
supporting terrorists, a claim he adamantly denies.
</P>
<P>
