u s BC-OLY-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART     09-27 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A JEWEL OF A COMEBACK ENDS IN GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKTOWN, Australia _ On second thought, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind their angst over a three-game losing streak. The
sports psychologist and his mini-toilet for them to flush after bad
games? Keep it. The same can be said of the ritual they used last
week: taking a shower with their uniforms on, trying to bring about
an exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   None of that matters anymore. The United States is the best
softball team in the world and, Tuesday night, it walked out of the
Softball Center with several souvenirs. All the US players have
Olympic gold medals after their 2-1 win over Japan. The players
tried several times to drape a medal around the neck of head coach
Ralph Raymond, but he kept taking it off and giving credit to them.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that they all deserved the recognition. It started
with Raymond, who elected to pitch ace Lisa Fernandez on no days'
rest. That's right. Nothing. She pitched the US into the gold-medal
game with a win over Australia Monday. Twenty-four hours later, she
was back against the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to come back tomorrow night, she could (pitch)
again,'' Raymond said of softball's best pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who began to cry during the medal ceremony, said she
didn't have her game. Her pitches, which routinely reach 70 miles
per hour, didn't have their usual pop. She said the Japanese knew
what she was throwing. She was irritable, sometimes ``blowing a
fuse,'' with her teammates left to deal with the shrapnel. But as
off as she claimed to be, she gave up only one run all day, and her
center fielder wound up apologizing for that.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Japanese third baseman Reika Utsugi homered to
center. It was a well-hit, low line drive. Laura Berg appeared to
be in position to catch the ball, but she leaped and missed it, and
it landed over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologized to Lisa for that,'' Berg said. ``I've got to find
a way to catch that ball. That's my job. I felt like I owed her
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Since their three-game skid, the Americans have been very
successful at evening the bill with each other. You paid last time?
I'll pick this one up. Not feeling well? I'll handle your chores
today.
</P>
<P>
   So there were a tired Fernandez and her teammates, needing one
run _ against a pitcher who was no-hitting them. Mariko Masubuchi
was on the mound, having no problems through 4 1/3 innings. With an
out in the fifth, she hit designated hitter Michele Smith. Smith
moved to second on a groundout. She scored when catcher Stacey
Nuveman singled.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tie game after five, and smart Australian fans
immediately called their babysitters. This was going to be a late
one. At this level of the sport, runs are cyclical. It seems that
you can watch three up, three down ad infinitum. And with rain on
the way, there was a chance the game wouldn't be completed.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the eighth when the US had two on and one out.
The lead runner was infielder Jennifer McFalls. The batter was _
look at this _ Berg, who was still trying to pay back Fernandez.
The left fielder, Shiori Koseki, was playing Berg shallow. When
Berg lifted a ball to left, further than Koseki expected, the
fielder began to backpedal. That wasn't her only problem. It was
raining, and the grass was slick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she made a valiant effort to get the ball,'' said
Dr. Dot Richardson, the US second baseman who was on first.
</P>
<P>
   She got the ball as she was falling backward. It was in her
mitt, briefly, and then rolled out. McFalls scored and the US won.
The Japanese stayed on the field for a moment, still surprised by a
strange game, a game they lost on what could be classified as a
routine flyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we got some breaks,'' said Berg, who woke up
her family in California (it was close to 3 a.m. there) with news
of the win.
</P>
<P>
   This tournament humbled the US. The Americans finished fourth in
the tournament, and had to travel to the gold-medal game without a
bye. The team found itself in a must-win game against New Zealand.
It lost its 112-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of these Olympics, just as they were at the end of
the 1996 Olympics, the Americans are gold medalists. As the
national anthem played, Fernandez put this team in perspective and
thought of her parents. Her father is a Cuban refugee. Her mother
is Puerto Rican. She began thinking of parental sacrifices and
freedom, and began to cry. A few minutes later, she cried when
retelling the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're free now,'' she said, speaking of her family. But then,
as she told Berg, the softball team is family, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
