<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-27 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY MADE `SURVIVOR' LOOK LIKE KID STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The 16 people who elbowed one another off the island in
``Survivor'' are still being treated as if they actually did
something. Richard Hatch, who won $1 million for turning everyone
on each other until he was the last person left was given his own
day by his hometown of Middletown, R.I. Almost all of the other
participants have been all over the television and have been
swamped with speaking engagements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a storm like I've never seen before,'' said Sherri
Spillane, the agent for six of the ``survivors.'' ``The interest in
everyone is 10 times what you might have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much interest in the selfish self-absorption of
contrived ``reality'' shipwrecks, you can forget what real survival
is like, stories where survival depended on the most intricate of
human cooperation. Our family was jolted back to reality this
summer by movies about Antarctic exploration at the Boston Museum
of Fine Arts and by the Peabody Essex Museum's Endurance
exhibition, which is traveling around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Endurance was the ship that British explorer Ernest
Shackleton used to set up what would have been the first-ever
crossing of the Antarctic continent by foot. The crossing never
happened. The ship and its crew of 28 men became locked in pack ice
within sight of land in January of 1915. The ice floes then carried
them way back off land and hundreds of miles off course.
</P>
<P>
   The crew was stuck in the ice all through the Antarctic winter
of 35-degrees-below-zero temperatures. They drifted until the
shifting ice crushed their ship. They drifted on a makeshift
campground until April 1916, when the ice beneath them began
breaking apart. Then, as if the preceding had not been bad enough,
Shackleton ordered his men into three small boats to reach an
island, dodging waves of boat-crushing ice and being soaked into
frostbite by splashing water that almost instantly froze.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ration of nut food and biscuits was issued, but the men's
thirst was now so intense that few of them could eat it,'' wrote
Alfred Lansing in his 1959 book ``Endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shackleton suggested that they try chewing seal meat raw in
order to swallow the blood. Pieces of the frozen meat were quickly
handed out, and after several minutes of chewing and sucking, the
men obtained enough of the bloody juice so they could at least
swallow . . . They had had no sleep for almost 80 hours . . . But
the conviction that they had to land by nightfall gave rise to a
strength born of desperation. It was pull or perish.''
</P>
<P>
   After reaching desolate Elephant Island, Shackleton still had to
find an inhabited island to be rescued. He and five other men set
out in the James Caird, a 22-foot-long boat _ not much longer a
kayak _ for an 800-mile trip to the whaling stations of South
Georgia Island. The crossing was over the stormiest waters on
Earth, where 50-foot waves are normal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   During a midnight watch, Shackleton's eyes were just getting
used to the dark ``when he turned and saw a rift of brightness in
the sky astern. He called to others to tell them the good news that
the weather was clearing to the southwest. A moment later, he heard
a hiss, accompanied by a low, muddled roar, and he turned to look
again. The rift in the clouds, actually the crest of an enormous
wave, was advancing rapidly toward them. He spun around and
instinctively pulled his head down.
</P>
<P>
   `` `For God's sake, hold on!' he shouted. `It's got us!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Caird survived the deluge. Had it missed South Georgia, the
next, hopelessly far land was 3,000 miles away in South Africa.
With miraculous readings in seas that nearly made their sextant
useless, the crew made it to an uninhabited part of South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   There were still more miracles to perform. The Caird was
damaged, so Shackleton hiked more than 20 miles across a South
Georgia so blocked with glaciers and jagged peaks that it was
thought impassable. He made it to the whaling station. They rounded
up the other three men, and a rescue boat went back to Elephant
Island to rescue the other 22 men.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton's journey gave us a new sense of endurance, one which
makes today's contrived ``reality'' disasters so silly. Our
celebrity circuit loudly rewards selfish ``survivors.'' When
Shackleton reached the whaling station, Lansing wrote that the
workers ``had no medals or decorations to bestow _ only their
heartfelt admiration for an accomplishment which perhaps only they
would ever fully appreciate . . . Of the honors that followed . . .
possibly none ever exceeded that night of May 22, 1916, when in a
dingy warehouse shack on South Georgia, with the smell of rotting
whale carcasses in the air, the whalermen of the southern ocean
stepped forward one by one and silently shook hands with
Shackleton, Worsley, and Crean.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Derrick. Z. Jackson's e-mail address is jackson(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
