<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3479 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PROFILE-FLYNN-ART-2TA     09-27 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-FLYNN-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A LION IN WINTER, RAY FLYNN STIRS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Oh, he's still out every morning, a whir of pink flesh
running through South Boston, jogging and filling himself up with
life and fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been terribly quiet.
</P>
<P>
   And he used to smash right through the days and nights. He was
the state representative and city councilor and mayor who wanted to
save the poor. He ran a city. He hated that he needed sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Ray Flynn?
</P>
<P>
   Well, his local radio show has been off the air for more than a
year now. He heads a group called Catholic Alliance, but it's based
in Washington. He gives speeches for the organization, though they
don't make headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But now Flynn, whose sweeping political life came to a
blistering and emotional end two years ago, is coming back.
</P>
<P>
   He's got a novel, ``The Accidental Pope,'' ready to roll off the
presses.
</P>
<P>
   He has just signed up to host a show on the new American
Catholic Network that will debut in early 2001. It'll be called
``Ray Flynn Live.'' It'll be a bully pulpit. ``It'll be like Larry
King's show,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   And in April of next year comes his book about his experiences
at the Vatican, where he served as US ambassador and clashed with
both the State Department and White House over his
get-out-of-my-way diplomatic style. ``John Paul II: An Inside
View,'' it will be called.
</P>
<P>
   But his most concentrated effort, he now admits, has been his
personal research into the Charles Stuart murder-suicide case that
cast a racial stain on Boston during his reign as mayor. It'll be a
substantial part of a planned memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet with people regularly to talk about the Stuart case,''
he said. ``I had a discussion just last Friday with someone who's
intimate with the whole thing. I've talked to detectives,
prosecutors, BHA officials. A day doesn't go by that I don't think
about it. I've got a lot of information people have never heard.
I'm not doing it to sensationalize. It's no whitewash. It's `just
the facts, ma'am.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Flynn, 61 years old, has turned himself into a writing fool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's opened a new world to me in terms of creativity that I
never knew I had,'' he said of the writing. ``I always considered
myself shy, but now I feel liberated. I'm able to open myself up.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nearly four-hour interview recently at his home, Flynn
talked of his political life, his victories and setbacks, his
family, his hoped-for future, and his personal ghost, Charles
Stuart. By turn, he sounded wistful, contrite, reflective, proud,
defensive, and even poetic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's early morning and the mayor who is no longer the mayor but
who will always be the mayor is reclining in a chair in his South
Boston home. There are black-and-white pictures of Irish-born
relatives on a nearby stand. The home is elegant in an
unpretentious way. His wife, Cathy, is in the dining room, seated
at a table, dressing up a turkey for supper. The autumn light
streaming through the windows is clear as white wine.
</P>
<P>
   There's a framed photo hanging of Ambassador Flynn, Pope John
Paul II, and President Clinton. Other than that, there's nary a
political memento in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said he holds no grudges about his wintry 1998
congressional defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost fair and square,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So let the rattling bones go silent.
</P>
<P>
   But he does admit that when he returned to Boston in 1997 from
the Vatican, the reception was chilly. Many former ambassadors have
jobs waiting for them. They are wooed, chased, welcomed into
soft-carpeted boardrooms. But not Ambassador Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absurd'' is how he defines his dealings with Northeastern
University, where he went through a three-hour interview for the
job of athletic director. ``A friend from my days at Providence
College mentioned to them I might be interested,'' Flynn said. ``It
was my long interest in athletics. I went through an interview and
didn't get the job offer. I don't know. I might not have accepted
it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the powerbrokers were ashamed of him.
</P>
<P>
   To all of Boston, it looked as if Ray Flynn _ a three-time
mayor, ambassador, one-time president of the US Conference of
Mayors _ was begging for local employment.
</P>
<P>
   Brother, can you spare a job?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bit of a secret as to why,'' he said, explaining: ``I
was never the darling of the business community. I took them on.
They couldn't control me. There was no love there.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't figure out the silence, and when he did, he said, it
only made him proud of his political past. ``People should worry
about politicians who get these high-paying jobs. Maybe they've
been playing footsie with this company, with that corporation. The
answer is nobody owned me. John Hancock and Fleet Bank weren't
pounding my door down. I know some people end up on the boards of
oil companies. But I was never the corporate leaders' fair-haired
boy. They got no special land deals from me. Sometimes they were
even offended.''
</P>
<P>
   The political leaders who used to get capital from being around
Ray Flynn seemed to distance themselves as well. ``Senator Kennedy
never called. Senator Kerry never called,'' he said. ``I'm not
going to be calling them up. I only want to be where I'm wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor William Weld did call, offering a job in his Republican
administration. ``I said no.''
</P>
<P>
   So he took a job on WRKO radio. You don't find a lot of
ambassadors gliding from ambassadorships into the rough-and-tumble
world of talk radio. But Ray Flynn needed a job.
</P>
<P>
   A year into that job, he left, and became president of Catholic
Alliance _ a ``pro-life, pro-human rights, pro-poor'' organization
_ speaking out on behalf of issues important to Catholics. He
traveled and gave speeches. Flynn's annual salary is $100,000. It's
good money, though it's not ex-ambassador money.
</P>
<P>
   There was a radio job, Catholic Family Radio, but you couldn't
get it locally. It was broadcast in other regions of the country.
Ray Flynn was reduced to a voice on the radio. And in his hometown,
a Catholic town, you couldn't even pick up the signal.
</P>
<P>
   He had time on his hands. He could finally have dinner at home
with Cathy and the kids. There wasn't that urge to bolt for the
front door as if the city were sinking into a manhole.
</P>
<P>
   But the city remained on his mind. He just couldn't figure out
where it was headed. Did anyone from the Menino administration wish
his counsel, expertise? They didn't. Menino has never called. ``Not
once,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston to which he returned seemed more callous and less
caring. Folks spoke of gentrification as if it were akin to the
saving of human souls. ``It used to be a city of neighborhoods,''
he opined, sounding like a museum piece. ``Nobody talking about the
poor. People talking about Hollywood and Wall Street.'' He didn't
get it. Hollywood and Wall Street. What about the Pine Street Inn?
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the minimum wage went up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton overhauled welfare and a lot of people on welfare found
jobs. And pride.
</P>
<P>
   The country was more boom than bust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Flynn saw only the poor. They were his sixth sense. Ghosts
at the side door.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed too young to be the lion in winter. But the shade was
beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time in his political life, Raymond Leo Flynn
looked inside himself.
</P>
<P>
   He started thinking. And he started writing.
</P>
<P>
   Writers aren't born overnight. Flynn has a co-author, Robin
Moore, who has written more than two dozen books, among them ``The
French Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote a lot of it,'' Moore, who resides in Concord, said of
Flynn and the upcoming novel, to be published in November. ``He put
a lot of autobiographical material in there. For instance, his
problems with the State Department because he was Catholic _ and
they weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, Ray Flynn says, he puts 16 hours in at the writing
desk. ``Writing is tough,'' he allowed, sounding charmingly naive
about a craft that has been known to extract blood.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn says it was the young adults working out at the Boston
Athletic Club who lifted him from his cocoon, who got him to
thinking and writing about his role in the history of his Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of very fine young professional people who go to
the Boston Athletic Club,'' he said. ``Many come from different
parts of the country and they've gone to Harvard, BC, BU. I've had
the opportunity to meet and talk with many of them, and, quite
frankly, they kind of look to me. I often find myself holding
political court with these young people, which I enjoy, which is
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He tells the newcomers to read ``Common Ground,'' by Tony Lukas,
and ``The Boston Irish,'' by Thomas O'Connor. They do. Then they
return to him and ask Ray Flynn about Ray Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw myself as being the most important person in the
city,'' Flynn said. ``I looked at it from the standpoint of someone
given the opportunity to speak for people who have no political
voice. I used every opportunity I could to represent that point of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   There were days in office when Ray Flynn looked unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went on the plane to the Vatican, I had 80 percent
favorability rating by the people of Boston,'' he recalled. ``I was
talking to my friend, L.A. Mayor Tom Bradley. He called me up. He
said, `Ray, can that possibly be true?' I said, `I don't see where
they'd make those numbers up.' I said, `Tom, me getting out there
with the people didn't begin when I was elected mayor of Boston. I
shined shoes as a kid. I sold newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
