<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-BLOOD-PRESSURE-SCREEN     09-27 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-PRESSURE-SCREEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN COULD HAVE BLOOD PRESSURE SCREENED AT THE OBSTETRICIAN'S  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 BY SERENA GORDON  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   If you're an expectant husband, the next time you accompany your
pregnant wife to her obstetrician's office, don't be surprised if
they take your blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Because high blood pressure can go undetected for years,
health-care professionals are always looking for creative ways to
screen people. One of the most novel suggestions comes from a
recent study that says men should be screened for high blood
pressure at the obstetrician's office when they go with their wives
for prenatal checkups.
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure, or hypertension, is called the ``silent
killer'' because symptoms rarely show up until damage has been
done. This can be especially true for men because they rarely see
doctors when they're young, unlike women who often go for annual
checkups.
</P>
<P>
   And younger men are at twice the risk for hypertension, compared
to young women. But researchers from the Washington University
School of Medicine in St. Louis believe they've got the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young men don't visit doctors routinely unless
they're very sick,'' says one of the study's authors, Daniel R.
Martin, a research instructor in medicine at Washington University
School of Medicine. ``We were trying to find a way to make it
easier for these men, and to make them more aware of their
health.''
</P>
<P>
   Making men more aware of high blood pressure is crucial because
one of every four Americans has high blood pressure, according to
the American Heart Association (AHA). And as many as one-third of
those people don't know they have hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   Complications include an increased risk of stroke and heart
disease, along with possible kidney damage, says Martin. Every
year, high blood pressure may be responsible for as many as 250,000
deaths, the heart association says.
</P>
<P>
   But high blood pressure is very treatable and can be controlled
using a combination of diet, exercise and medications, Martin says.
The first step, though, is finding out you have it.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and his colleagues had nurses at four different
obstetrical offices offer men who came in with pregnant women a
free blood pressure check. Almost 200 men, with an average age of
27, agreed to the test. Sixty percent were white, 35 percent were
black and 5 percent were of other racial backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Forty men, or 20 percent of those tested, had high blood
pressure. Only 5 percent of these men knew beforehand they had
hypertension. Results of the study were published in the September
issue of the American Journal of Hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   One high reading alone didn't mean those men definitely had high
blood pressure, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diagnosis of hypertension is not made on one reading. Usually
three readings are taken at different times, but one reading can be
an indicator of a problem,'' says Martin. He acknowledges one of
the study's limitations is that the researchers didn't follow the
patients to see if they were later diagnosed as actually having
hypertension. They did recommend that all of the men with high
readings follow up with their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do obstetricians think of the idea of screening men in
their offices?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good idea. You could theoretically screen a large
population, but practically, it's difficult,'' says Dr. Marcos
Pupkin, chairman of the obstetrics and gynecology department at
Mercy Medical Center in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Pupkin says many offices would have to add staff to do this on a
regular basis. More importantly, he wonders, what is the
obstetrician's responsibility?
</P>
<P>
   What if someone's pressure came back high? Would he need to
refer that person to another physician? Would insurance companies
accept a referral from an obstetrician for a man? Would the
obstetrician need to start a chart to record that the man had been
screened in his office? He says these are just some of the issues
that would need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
