<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BLACK-JUDGES-HNS &LR;      09-27 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLACK JUDGES TO MARK PROGRESS ON THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VENISE WAGNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson
entered law school in 1959, there was only one black federal court
judge in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are about 150 African-American judges in the U.S.
court system, and they will gather in San Francisco Thursday
through Sunday to celebrate the strides that have been made and to
discuss what they would like to see change.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a hard but steady climb for African-Americans in the
federal judiciary, said Henderson, a U.S. District Court judge
here. ``One of the things we judges talked about all the time was
that you could hold a meeting of black lawyers in this little
office I'm sitting in.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, they wouldn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of blacks on the federal bench ``is making
our society more diverse,'' he said. ``It makes justice more
diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet politics may stall the appointment of more black judges to
the bench _ at least for this year _ because of resistance to
President Clinton's nominees by some Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Six African-Americans nominated by Clinton have yet to get a
hearing before the Senate Judiciary Committee, which reviews
nominees before making a recommendation to the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Circuit Judge Ann Claire Williams, chairwoman of Just the
Beginning Foundation, declined to comment on the stalled
appointments, saying it was not the job of the judicial branch to
delve into the legislative branch of government. Although
conference discussions will forgo the issue, it is not likely to be
far from the minds of attending judges.
</P>
<P>
   John Crump, executive director of the National Bar Association,
an organization of black attorneys and judges, said the question of
qualifications always arises for African-American nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will appoint a tax lawyer to the federal district
court,'' Crump said. ``But if you take an African-American who was
a civil rights lawyer, the question will be, 'Is his experience
broad enough?' And everyone knows that a tax attorney's experience
is narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that narrowness that Henderson worries about, because it
could hurt the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just racial diversity,'' Henderson said. Justice
fails to benefit when a person of one thinking sits on the bench,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern that those that are holding up the system have
made a statement that certain kinds of political leanings can't sit
on the bench,'' he said. ``You have to be of a sufficiently
conservative bent to be a federal judge (today), and I think that's
wrong-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference in San Francisco, co-sponsored by the Just the
Beginning Foundation, an organization of black federal judges, will
address such topics as the effect of the criminal justice system on
African-Americans and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was elevated from the U.S. District Court in
Chicago to the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Illinois last year,
said the judges conference was an attempt to educate the public
about African-American contributions to the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through education, people can appreciate the significant
contributions that African-Americans do make in the judiciary,''
she said. ``By telling stories of these outstanding judges, you get
to see they are great judges, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the biennial conference had grown out of a small
gathering of federally appointed black judges eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They were honoring U.S. District Judge James Parsons, who was
retiring after 31 years on the bench. Parsons, appointed by
President John F. Kennedy, insisted that the celebration not be for
him, rather for the integration of the federal bench, Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal since has been to preserve the history of black federal
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories of African-American judges and their struggles are
true American stories,'' she said. ``The judges have triumphed
against much adversity and have come out in a position of respect
in our society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the struggles of the judges and their stories
are inspirational, and it's important for children to have positive
role models ... It's important they see alternative routes to
success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
