<P>
   MILITARY-READINESS (Washington) _ Echoing charges from
Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush that U.S. military
readiness is slipping, the nation's top military officers told
Congress Wednesday that preparedness to fight has eroded to the
point that the Pentagon's main strategy of being able to win two
wars at once now carries high risk. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Washington) _ A top Energy Department official says
that home heating oil prices will stabilize over the next several
months but that they likely will remain ``substantially'' higher
than last year. However, Robert S. Kripowicz, acting assistant
secretary for fossil energy, warned that President Clinton's
decision last week to release 30 million barrels of oil from the
nation's emergency reserve can't prevent price spikes caused by any
unusually cold winter or shipping disruptions. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP _ Vice President Al Gore stumped in Iowa for
his Medicare prescription drug plan while Texas Gov. George W. Bush
visited a Catholic school in South-Central Los Angeles, which he
called a ``beacon of hope.'' Meanwhile, Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va.,
chair of the National Republican Congressional Committee, said
Republican chances of keeping control of the House were good,
regardless of whether Gore or Bush wins on Nov. 7. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ Presidents traditionally revere
their mothers and rarely praise their fathers or even speak of
them. That may not be true in the future when so many modern
fathers are involved in hands-on parenting. But the stronger,
sometimes domineering, influence of mothers on sons who wound up in
the White House cannot be denied. We know every little boy can grow
up to be president, but it helps to have a wise mother on his side.
By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ As we head into the final month
of the presidential campaign, the race between Al Gore and George
W. Bush is very close and very confrontational. But the two
candidates lack the vision and the idealism that generate great
expectations within the electorate, especially among young
Americans. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (For release Sunday, Oct. 1.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PROFILE-FLYNN-ART-2ND     09-27 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-FLYNN-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... sold newspapers.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His rise was gritty. South Boston sports star, then basketball
fame at Providence College.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, he nosed into politics, ran for state representative
in 1970, and won.
</P>
<P>
   When the buses rolled into South Boston in 1973 with black
children on them, young Ray Flynn flared his nostrils. He wanted to
stop the buses. He wanted the white children to stay out of school.
Ray Flynn and Billy Bulger and James Kelly: the three anti-busing
horsemen of South Boston. ``I saw it as pitting poor against
poor,'' Flynn said. Many outside of Boston saw it as denying black
schoolchildren equal education. The city became an emblem. It
wasn't pretty. ``But even during busing,'' he said, ``I used to
play basketball every Sunday morning at the Roxbury Boys Club.''
</P>
<P>
   He got elected to the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Men change. Minds bend.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was pulling different coins from his pockets. He wanted
to heal, not divide. He pulled a black man from a mob on Boston
Common. He stopped railing against busing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 he got elected to City Hall. Mayor Ray Flynn. Silky
Kevin White went off to do other things.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor, Flynn would show up at fires. He'd hustle to food
kitchens to help. He prayed in black churches. You could have
called him Ray Fiorello LaGuardia James Michael Curley Richard
Daley Flynn. He had a hammer. And he had a feather. And suddenly,
he opened his eyes and had a city to behold, a city that believed
in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being mayor of a city is a spiritual thing. It's about
personal relationships with the people. It's whether or not you can
make them better people _ or help make them better people. It's not
about issues. It's not about the economy. It's not about bond
ratings. It's about what's important to people. And what's
important to people is being treated with dignity, and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a plunk from the Tobin Bridge on a cold January
morning in 1990. And with that, it looked as if Ray Flynn were
going to meet his Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three months earlier, in October, a man, white, said
another man, black, had shot and killed his pregnant wife. A black
man, William Bennett, became the ``prime'' suspect. Flynn had
demanded that police find the killer. The criminal justice system
and the media became embroiled in a terrifying whodunit that let
loose racial fears and political fingerpointing.
</P>
<P>
   After Charles Stuart apparently committed suicide with
prosecutors closing in on his deception, blacks were angry. Ray
Flynn walked the streets of Boston. There were those who wondered
anew where his heart and mind lay. They remembered busing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember somebody gave me advice, I think Mike Haynes,''
recalled Flynn of the minister of Twelfth Baptist Church. ``He
said, `Ray, you have credibility. Get out there and go to as many
meetings as you can. Get up there and explain how you feel. Don't
try to be cute. Listen to the people and answer their questions as
directly as you can.' In all the years in politics, that's the best
advice I'd ever been given.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to a community meeting in Mattapan. The people were
there. Waiting. Women with questions. Men with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm not going to make a political statement. When you
want me to speak, I will. I will stay and answer every question.'
Some of the people in City Hall were telling me to forget the
meeting, let it all blow over. Toward the end, this woman, very
sophisticated, very polished, said, `Mr. Flynn I'm tired of the way
you've treated me, my family and the community.' She concluded her
speech by saying, `You have been doing this for 200 years.' I
thought there would be a thunderous reception, but there was dead
silence. She says, `Mr. Flynn, the reason why I'm saying this to
you is you're the only white politician who came into my community
and not only listened to us, but have spoken for us.' And with
that, the whole place erupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn walked tall again across his neighborhoods. It was still
his city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get comfort,'' he said, ``that even my harshest critics
who have never given me credit for anything have given me credit
for being a racial healer. That's the most important thing. Without
that, nothing works.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Flynn added, the Stuart saga has never let him
go. ``This guy was one of the most devious men you'd ever want to
meet,'' Flynn said of Stuart. ``I've retraced his whole life. He
was following the homicide rates in Mission Hill. I've spoken to
people he talked to. He knew crime statistics. He knew where there
had been drive-by shootings. . . . He knew the names of local
gangs. This, a guy from Reading! This, a guy who worked in a
prestigious fur store with a Newbury Street address! And this guy
is interested in gang stuff? Why? He figured he could get away with
murder. And almost did. I never talked about it till now. That's a
story the people deserve to know. This guy wasn't following the
stock exchange, mind you; he was following crime statistics in
Roxbury. He wanted people to believe this Camelot storybook
situation with his wife making a wrong turn in Roxbury. That the
best of their world had been in front of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn seems genuinely seized by his Stuart investigation. ``I'm
working like hell on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But politics is a complex business, and rarely a deathless one.
The Stuart imbroglio took a toll on Flynn, even if, at the time,
you couldn't quite see it in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In time, there were rumors that Ray Flynn wanted to go to
Washington if a Democrat won the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And the victorious Bill Clinton appointed him ambassador to the
Vatican. The job seemed tailor-made for an Irish Catholic from
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He warned Clinton: He was going to travel the world as
ambassador. And he did, hopping to India and Somalia from Rome,
feeding the hungry, hugging the desperate in refugee camps, looking
at bodies buried in the rubble of earthquakes. He had the power to
call in Black Hawk helicopters, and did. He loved it. Not the desk
work, but the sloshing through the mud, setting food before the
eyes of the hungry in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not such a big world'' after all, he said he felt at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   He moved things by the sweat of his brow. As he had done in
Boston. But the world wasn't Boston. Other diplomats were aghast at
his style. Meetings were missed. Cables went unwritten. There were
reports he was not handling all of his duties as ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't interested in being the pomp-and-circumstance kind of
ambassador, going to lavish cocktail receptions,'' he sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   The Accidental Diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Early into Clinton's second term, Ray Flynn bowed out. He
returned to Boston and announced a run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   His candidacy, however, could not get traction, particularly
after reports in the Globe giving harsh details of social drinking
while in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   So, unable to raise money fast enough, he dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Five years abroad, and he was like a stranger in his own town.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, though, he announced a run for Congress when
Joseph Kennedy declined to run again in the 8th District.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to many as if Ray Flynn were trying to put the sand
back in the hourglass.
</P>
<P>
   But where there had been populist magic before, now there were
wary voters. In the primary he came in a distant second in a field
of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Capuano: 19,446 votes; Flynn: 14,839 votes.
</P>
<P>
   He lost in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different area,'' he said. ``I did well in Roxbury. I
lost in Cambridge, Somerville, Belmont, areas I didn't know as
well. I did the best I could. I took a strong pro-life position. It
was different politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got hurt,'' he said of the Globe's reporting about
his drinking. ``And the people got hurt. I don't think anybody came
out of this thing looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he says he can't envision ever running for political office
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfair to the family,'' he said of political life.
``They didn't ask to be in the limelight. My wife was never
interested in fame or notoriety. She's a wonderful wife, mother,
grandmother. Having said that, she was very supportive of what I
wanted to do. I was a fierce competitive athlete who drove myself
to become an All-American. I also had a fierce commitment to help
eradicate injustice and poverty. I'm not apologizing for that.
That's who I am. That's how I felt. If I just decided the political
world was going to be too mean and nasty for me, well, that's not
who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Flynn was once in New Jersey, hooping with Bill Bradley.
``We both said there's no experience like competitive sports. You
practice, sweat, there's pain. You go out on the court and lose.
And you pick yourself up. You look for the next game. You don't
dwell on the losses. You move forward. I think being an athlete was
the greatest preparation to being an important political figure. I
mean, you get hit in the nose with an elbow, you take the towel,
wipe away the blood, and get back out in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the books and TV show ``take off,'' a larger
limelight could emerge for him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1983,'' said Flynn, talking of the year of his rise, ``if
you were sitting in this house _ my wife, six children, no summer
home, no property anywhere else _ well, I'm trying to say I didn't
get into politics to make money or serve my own financial
interests. So it's clear why I served the people. I wanted
desperately for them to believe in me. We all need to believe in
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
