<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GREEN-BOS &LR;      09-27 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GREEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY VOICES SPOIL THIS WRITER'S TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PRAGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
The Green Suit 
By Dwight Allen 
Algonquin Press of North Carolina, 274 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Literature is littered with lovable losers, but Peter Sackrider
is not one of them. He's not hateable, either; he's just weak,
feckless, and going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   At once, he is the best feature of ``The Green Suit,'' Dwight
Allen's first book, and a symbol of its shortcomings: He and other
Allen creations are well-drawn, but there's hardly a likable (let
alone admirable) soul in the lot.
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Alex, is no fun, but at least she has the excuse of
being a depressive. His girlfriend, Rachel (after he'd left his
wife, abruptly, for some other woman), is dismissive. His mentor,
Harvey, talks at him, but doesn't see him.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion has to begin with Sackrider, a writer from
Kentucky who would now be 49 if he were real. ``The Green Suit'' is
a collection of stories spanning roughly 25 years, beginning in the
mid-1970s, when he's 23. His essential weakness is expressed in
myriad ways, but it's the day he's on the tennis court with Hal,
the boyhood friend who married Peter's girl, that the
characterization is clinched: Peter has won the first set easily,
and is up 3-0 in the second, when Hal says, ``This it it, Pedro.
This is your stop.'' Hal's play doesn't change, but on cue, Peter's
does. He starts hitting into the net or outside the lines, and he
leaves the loser.
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes in the fourth chapter, one of the opening
quintet in which Sackrider is narrator. Who's talking in ``The
Green Suit'' doesn't become an issue until Chapter 6, when Willie,
the stout black woman who kept house for the Sackriders for
decades, takes over, without warning. Three other women from
Sackrider's life each take a chapter before an unknown narrates
Chapter 10, and Sackrider returns for the finale.
</P>
<P>
   As a device, it falters. First, there is the confusion that
comes from beginning the voice-swapping after 134 pages, or about
half the book. The subsequent switches are less jarring, though
they require awkward little references to establish the narrator's
identity (as in the next chapter, when Claire, Peter's wife, whom
we're well familiar with, has to introduce him as her husband).
</P>
<P>
   The execution is faulty, too. Peter's voice in the first five
chapters is comfortable, which stands to reason because Allen is
also a white Kentuckian of middle age. But Willie's voice is
foreign, and when Sackrider's mother gets her turn, it seems off by
a quarter-turn, such as when she comments: ``There's light left in
the day, even if it's all squirrelly, flickering in the crowns of
the trees.'' She's suddenly wiser, cleverer, and more poetic than
we've been told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not Renata,'' the third chapter in the women's sequence,
offers the best of what the technique has to offer: Allen gets to
explore a memory of Sackrider's, mentioned secondarily in a
previous chapter, from the other character's perspective. But the
approach to it seems like an inside joke: She's ``not Renata''
because Sackrider, when he fictionalized their break-up, changed
her name from Nora Sue. She read the story, and now gets to
respond. It suggests that Allen is writing about writing about a
break-up.
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant commonality of these stories, most of which have been
published individually in journals, is their richness of nature.
Allen clearly knows his flora, and he may have a thing for snakes,
which slither in on three separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
   In his choices of words, Allen is generally successful. There's
a charming folksiness that's becoming to a story that springs from
the South, such as when a boy's feet are ``as white as eggs under
refrigerator light.'' And he captures an essence when Sackrider
opens the room of a friend's brother who's away in Vietnam: ``The
air felt ancient, as if it were being preserved for Harry to
breathe when he came back.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he likens a house of cards to a ziggurat, he's hardly
helping, and when he writes, ``Alex gave Bernardo a long look, like
what a child might give a comedian who is perhaps not a comedian,''
he's not helping at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
