<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING EYEBROWS IS HER JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much thought do you give your eyebrows?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in my case, is not much, and nowhere near enough by
Robyn Cosio's standards. Cosio is perhaps the premier eyebrow
stylist working today. I say ``perhaps'' because there are many
other acclaimed eyebrow stylists in cities across the land. So far,
though, Cosio is the only one to have produced a book, a handsomely
illustrated coffee-table number titled, simply, ``The Eyebrow''
(HarperCollins, $30).
</P>
<P>
   We are living in a New Golden Age of the Eyebrow, according to
Cosio, and she should know. She has a long list of celebrity
clients in New York and Los Angeles, and her services are coveted
by ordinary mortals willing to pay $65 for a five-minute eyebrow
tuneup. (By contrast, Tammy Giuoag, of Perfect Nail, named Boston's
best eyebrow artist by Boston Magazine, charges a mere $10 for 20
minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eyebrow,'' written with the help of Cynthia Robins, traces
the eyebrow's march through history, from ancient Egypt to the
present. Eyebrows, Cosio observes, are ``iconic.'' I assume she
means iconic in the profane sense, not the sacred. But perhaps not,
considering her reverential tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each period,'' she writes, ``the eyebrow, the chief
indicator of emotion and expression on the face, has spoken louder
than any word that has issued from the lips.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess it must be true, if Cosio says so. Although I confess
the importance of the eyebrow came as a surprise, until I recalled
something Virginia Kelley, late mother of President Clinton, wrote
in her autobiography, ``Leading With My Heart'': ``Do you know how
bald you look from your chin to your hairline if you don't have
eyebrows? They're put there for a reason, to hold your face
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Nature shortchanged Kelley in the eyebrow department, and she
lamented the time lost in a lifetime of drawing on eyebrows. ``No
telling what I could have accomplished in this world if I had been
born with eyebrows,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She was being a little hard on herself. After all, most of us
born with eyebrows to spare won't manage to rear a future US
president. But I understand what she was getting at because
sometimes I think I might have done more with my life if I hadn't
wasted so much time worrying about hair, weight, skin, teeth, and
all the other areas of concern that make self-maintenance
practically a full-time job. And just when you think you have
things more or less in perspective, up pops something like Cosio's
book to remind you that there's another area you've neglected.
</P>
<P>
   Before I added ``eyebrow job'' to the ever-lengthening list of
things-I'll-never-get-around-to I turned to the do-it- yourself
section and Cosio's instructions for creating what she calls ``your
perfect fantasy brow.'' How hard could it be?
</P>
<P>
   Step 1. I stared into a hand mirror while asking a long series
of penetrating eyebrow-related questions: Do my eyes look too close
together? Is one eyebrow thicker than the other? Do they march
across my nose? etc.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2. I took a pencil and, following Cosio's instructions,
held the lower end to the side of my nose, and moved the upper end
across my eyebrow trying, and failing, to locate the elusive
``perfect arch.''
</P>
<P>
   Three pages of detailed instructions later my perfect fantasy
brow remained a fantasy and $65 for five minutes of eyebrow
trimming was beginning to look like a bargain. Maybe that was
Cosio's plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
