<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-SOCIETY-MIXING-BOS &LR;      09-27 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIETY-MIXING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD BONDS BETWEEN BLACK, ASIANS REEMERGE IN POP CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say write what you know, and that's exactly what Chi Muoi
Lo (CHEE MOY LOW) did when he scribbled out the screenplay for his
new movie, ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by and starring Lo, tells the story of two
Vietnamese orphans adopted by an African-American family. OK, so Lo
wasn't adopted, but when his parents and 12 siblings immigrated to
the United States from Vietnam in 1975, the US government plopped
the family down in a predominantly African-American neighborhood in
West Philadelphia. ``I grew up with all African-American friends,
girlfriends, and surrogate mothers,'' remembers Lo, 31, speaking
from his Los Angeles office.
</P>
<P>
   He recreates that world, perched at the intersection of Asian
and African culture, in ``Catfish.'' This cross-cultural
intermingling is increasingly being explored not only in films, but
in music, and is also reflected in general lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Catfish'' and the upcoming ``Brother'' _ the
first American movie by Japanese star Takeshi ``Beat'' Kitano that
features African-American actor Omar Epps _ movie audiences have
watched Forest Whitaker zen out in ``Ghost Dog,'' Aaliyah and Jet
Li make like in ``Romeo Must Die,'' and Chris Tucker and Jackie
Chan goof off in ``Rush Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as musical acts the Wu-Tang Clan and Sisqo incorporate
Chinese culture into their imagery, a growing number of
Asian-American musicians are mixing Korean music with hip-hop or
rapping about the forced relocation of Japanese-Americans during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Pro basketball players Allen Iverson and Marcus Camby even go so
far as to etch Chinese symbols onto their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may dismiss this trend as shallow, ephemeral
pop-cultural sampling. But the current intermixing scratches the
surface of a shared history that blossomed at least 500 years ago,
when Chinese and East Africans began trading goods with each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Building bonds
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an age-old story,'' says Lisa Yun, a professor at SUNY
Binghamton, who wrote about this subject in a recent issue of Black
Issues Book Review magazine. ``It's just that we have nationally
tried to erase it from the history books.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the strong bonds exist, she says. ``You have these
communities in New Orleans, Filipino Creoles who have been there
for generations. You have Afro-Chinese from Jamaica, black Chinese
from Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   And today's mixed-race generation is increasingly getting face
time in the media. Every time Tiger Woods swats a golf ball, we see
the scion of a black father and Thai mother. Hip-hop mogul Russell
Simmons makes the social rounds with his model-wife Kimora Lee,
who's a mix of Korean/Japanese and African-American ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   So what's inspiring this cultural and emotional interaction?
``We're people that have a lot more similarities than
differences,'' Lo explains, mentioning among the former the
importance of strong family ties and the common experience of being
an oppressed group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both warriors,'' notes Tracii McGregor, editorial
director of the Source Publications, which publishes hip-hop
magazine the Source. ``Our history is very similar.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chinese immigrants first came to California in the 1800s,
Yun explains, they experienced segregation and were not allowed to
vote. ``All the laws that applied to blacks at that time were
applied to the first Asians who were coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish'' stands out from many films featuring black and Asian
casts by showing realistic emotional exchanges between the two
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Lo's character, Dwayne, frets over a loving, though troubled,
relationship with his African-American girlfriend (Sanaa Lathan).
Audiences see genuine affection between Dwayne and his
African-American parents (Mary Alice and Paul Winfield), something
that didn't happen in the Asian/African-American twist on Romeo and
Juliet, ``Romeo Must Die.'' That film transformed the star-crossed
lovers into the daughter of a mob boss and a quick-kicking son of a
Chinese mafia leader. By focusing on crime and kung-fu, Lo says,
the movie ``basically uses the two major stereotypes of our
culture, combines it together, and says, `OK, we can accept you
guys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's attitudes like this that makes Yun disdainfully call some
of these exchanges ``trendy fetishizing of interracial
relationships.'' But in another breath she speaks with wonderment
of the trend's effect: ``More people are talking to each other and
asking the question, `What are the possibilities if we actually
spoke to one another beyond cultural sampling?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Answers are appearing with more and more frequency. An
exhibition at New York City's Caribbean Cultural Center next year
will explore Asian contributions to Caribbean culture in the areas
of film, music, and the visual arts. Meanwhile, at Columbia
University, a conference in November will feature black and Asian
scholars discussing their common bonds in education, music, sports,
and religion. In Washington, D.C., Bill Lan Lee works as acting
assistant attorney general for civil rights, a position long
associated with African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lingering tensions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such rapproachements don't mean there aren't tensions between
the groups. Relations hit a low point during the Los Angeles riots,
when African-Americans targeted Korean-owned grocery stores. In one
``Catfish'' scene, Dwayne's birth mother expresses mute shock when
she discovers her children's adopted parents are black.
</P>
<P>
   With that look, Lo wanted to address the racism sometimes
exhibited by immigrant Asians when they come to the United States.
It was a controversial choice within the Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people coming to me, usually the younger
generation, glad that I had pointed that out,'' says Lo, whose film
has already been released in Chicago, New York, and Los Angeles.
``The older generation resents that I pointed it out. The fact is .
. . we don't talk about Asian prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yun blames the intolerance on both sides on what she calls
``identity politicians'' who sow seeds of discord by stressing
cultural differences that often devolve into stereotypes. They
paint Asians as the ``model minorities'' and African-Americans as
the troublemaking upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mixing it up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Protesters of Asian and African descent tried to overcome those
divisions in the 1960s and 1970s, says Yun, when political
movements attracted people from a variety of cultural backgrounds.
It was Japanese-American activist Yuri Kochiyama who cradled
Malcolm X as he lay dying in the Audubon Ballroom. Yun credits the
nostalgia for that period with jump-starting the current
cross-cultural intermixing.
</P>
<P>
   New York Knicks player Marcus Camby developed his love of
Chinese culture the way many African-Americans do: by watching
kung-fu movies. Now he has Chinese characters tattooed on his right
arm, while pop singer Sisqo uses a dragon as his personal insignia.
Some members of the Wu-Tang Clan even study martial arts under a
Shaolin monk.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing number of Asian-Americans are dipping into
African-American culture by way of hip-hop, gospel, and jazz. The
New York group Jamez mixes a musical cauldron of traditional Korean
music and hip-hop, San Francisco recently hosted its 19th
Asian-American jazz festival, and a church in Harlem teaches a
growing number of Japanese how to sing gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this ethnic intermingling can go to one's head.
Lo's multicultural upbringing led him straight to an identity
crisis by the time he was a teenager. Since then, he's fashioned an
easy truce between those influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about being myself is I am able to take all the
good things about different cultures,'' says Lo.
</P>
<P>
   That ability shows as he melds African and Asian-American
culture in ``Catfish and Black Bean Sauce.'' After all, it's what
Lo knows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
