Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TRACK-SIDE1 _ SYDNEY _ Track sidebar, probably on Gail
Devers. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-JONES _ SYDNEY _ Marion's big night. Marion Jones runs in
second round of 200 meters, compets in long jump qualifying.
(Rosen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-MARION _ SYDNEY _ Palm Beach Post columnist Dave George
writes about Marion Jones' longest day. (George, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-NIGERIA _ SYDNEY _ Feature on the Nigerian hurdler whose
husband was killed by a car while walking in Sydney before the
Games. (Tierney, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ARCH-ALOYZIE _ SYDNEY _ Tom Archdeacon column on Hurdler
Glorie Aloyzie of Nigeria who won the silver medal in the women's
100-meter hurdles despite tragedy. Her fiance was killed here a day
before the Games began when he stepped in front of a bus. They were
to be married as soon as the Games were over. Aloyzie has been a
mess since her fiance was killed. She wanted to go back home and
take his body with her but her teammates talked her into staying in
Sydney. She since has refused to eat and has lost 15 pounds from
her 115-pound frame. Her coach has been spoonfeeding her. One of
her teammates has to literally rock her to sleep each night. But
she somehow managed to pull it together and breeze past the favored
runners and nearly became the first Nigerian sprinter to win a gold
medal. (Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASE _ SYDNEY _ Coverage of gold-medal baseball game, U.S.
vs. Cuba. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ARCH-BASEBALL _ SYDNEY _ The United States finally beat the
two-time defending champ Cuba in baseball shutting out the favorite
4-0 this morning. (Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOCC _ SYDNEY _ Women's gold medal soccer advance. (Parker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CYCLE_ SYDNEY _ Follow on Lance Armstrong in road cycling.
(Maher, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISSUE-ADS _ Playing good cop/bad cop, the national political
parties this season are churning out negative advertisements, while
the candidates are largely sticking to positive messages. The
strategy is allowing candidates such as Gore and Bush to claim the
high road, while the parties do the dirty work. Analysts predict
the diet of negative party advertising to increase sharply between
now and election day, mirroring trends established in 1998.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ A look at the dynamics of the vice presidential
contest. (Baxter, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-MATH _ WASHINGTON _ The nation should spend more than $5
billion a year raising the ``unacceptable'' performance of the
nation's ``scandalously underpaid'' math and science teachers to
world-class standards, the National Commission on the Teaching of
Science and Math reported Wednesday. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-DATA _ Test results and questions for parents to ask.
(Mollison, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Education
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-KIDS _ WASHINGTON _ Opening Scene: Eight movie
moguls sit at witness table facing a committee of skeptical
senators on the very day it was revealed their studios used
children as young as 9 to screen R-rated films. It's a classic
confrontation of East Coast vs. West Coast. ``Filled with
loopholes,'' proclaims the committee chairman, Sen. John McCain,
R-Az., a former war hero with a reputation for independence. (Dart,
Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S.
Government.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES _ WASHINGTON _ A major crackdown on substandard
nursing homes has a long way to go to bring care up to federal
standards, says a General Accounting Office report that will be
released Thursday. The GAO found numerous shortcomings two years
after President Clinton announced the effort, which will be
reviewed by a Senate Special Committee on Aging hearing Thursday.
(Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Social
Issues
</P>
<P>
   HOLYFIELD _TENTATIVE _ Checking tip that Evander Holyfield was
evicted from his Sandy Springs restaurant on Wednesday for not
paying bills. (Saunders, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU _ JERUSALEM _ Clearing the way for his expected
return to the top echelons of politics, Israeli papers reported
Wednesday that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will not be
charged in an investigation into corruption allegations. His famous
``time out'' from politics, which he announced after losing in the
1999 election to Ehud Barak, will likely end soon. Netanyahu, the
man Israelis either love or love to hate, was in the United States,
but he is expected to return and start trying to knock off those
that stand in his way _ first Likud Party icon Ariel Sharon and
then, in expected early elections, Barak. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other. Expected to move by 5:30 p.m. ET on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   FALUN-GONG In the three weeks that Xiaohua Du has been under
house arrest in China for carrying banned religious materials into
the country, friends and supporters of the Atlanta engineer have
worked tirelessly to press for her return to the United States -
but with little success. (Ahmed, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REUNITE _Next week Germans will celebrate the 10th anniversary
of the re-unification of their country. But the euphoria of
re-unification has long since faded. Tearing down the wall that
divided the two Germanys was easy. Creating a truly unified nation
has proven more difficult. Fresh from a visit to his country,
Germany's Atlanta-based consul general assesses the situation.
(Graham, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
