<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   PAAVO-JARVI _ ATLANTA _ A preview of tonight's ASO concert,led
by Paavo Jarvi, the new conductor of the Cincinnati Orchestra, a
comparable ensemble to the ASO. Unusually, Jarvi is from a
conducting dynasty: his father has held many distinguished posts,
his brother is also a fast-rising conductor. With the ASO he'll
perform unfamiliar music by a fellow Latvian, Tuur's ``Flux.''
(Ruhe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GOULD _ Review of ``Joe Gould's Secret.'' Grade: B+
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEXT _ Coming soon: ``U-571,'' ``Snow Day,'' ``Bossa
Nova.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RINGEL _ As the Olympics wind down, Eleanor Ringel
Gillespie looks at some of the best Australian movies.(Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-GOSPEL _ Lede review of both the legendary Shirley
Caesar's ``You Can Make It'' and Yolanda Adams' No. 1 gospel CD
``Mountain High. . . Valley Low.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE _ The big news this week is the World
Wrestling Federation's move to The Nashville Network. Monday
night's ``Raw is War'' made its debut on TNN and the television
ratings did not waver much. (Allen, Cox News Service) MOVED.
(CoxNet: the first week of each month this will be accompanied by a
wrestling page.)
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. This week: Light
is like any other valuable; the less there is of it, the more it's
worth. Trying to enjoy every particle as days grow shorter, I want
light to wash over me, cleanse me of sticky summer, show me fresh
views of the garden. So, on some days I become my father when he
was an old man, going to bed with nightfall, rising early, getting
to the garden as often as I can, staying as long as light lasts _
and beyond. How ironic that there's less light just when lower
temperatures make being outside more bearable. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STORM-DAMAGE _If your house and yard sustained minor damage
during last week's storms, you may be able to handle most of the
repairs yourself without calling in the professionals. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
