<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: THE DOG ATE MY DRUG TEST RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Regarding that form of drug known as
``performance enhancing,'' there is only one claim I would
definitely believe from any athlete:
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, Chief, I slurp 'em up like corn flakes. I can't
wait to finish talking to you so I can go get me some more.''
</P>
<P>
   That person I would believe.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it's better to not say anything. If you haven't
touched off the alarms, like some hapless tourist trying to enter
Olympic Park with a manhole-sized 50-cent coin in your pocket, just
keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   If they haven't busted you, don't make rash statements. Don't
hold news conferences. Don't release your latest urinalysis
printouts. I don't want to know. Just keep running or jumping or
flinging heavy weights into the atmosphere, whatever your redeeming
social value may be.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if this is your thing, keep jogging around the premises with
your burly significant other strapped onto your back. This
brand-new Olympic event is currently being performed by Marion
Jones, the latest ``Perils of Pauline'' heroine to capture the
imagination, the sympathy, of the world during these Final Days
(how biblical) of these Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   First Cathy Freeman survived her frigid dousing from the
artificial Olympic rain forest during the opening ceremony, and won
a gold medal. Then Marie-Jose Perec did not survive the goblins,
external or internal, that pursued her, and she got outta town. Now
it is Marion Jones' soap opera, and welcome to it.
</P>
<P>
   Jones became a candidate for Oprah, or maybe even Springer, on
Monday when it was announced that her husband, C.J. Hunter, had
been busted for testing positive. He's a very large person who
throws the shot. He says the stuff probably got into his system
through some nutritional supplement he was taking. I say,
yeah-yeah-yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal about Hunter, but because I suspect many
athletes are ingesting or inoculating all kinds of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Just Wednesday we witnessed the weird spectacle of a former
world-record holder, Mihaela Melinte of Romania, being escorted off
the infield moments before she was to commence throwing the hammer.
Melinte has been suspended for testing positive for nandrolone _
the very same substance that was found in Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt she has her explanation, but Hunter surely did not get
much sympathy from the members of the International Olympic
Committee, who are becoming world-class skeptics. There is plenty
to be skeptical about.
</P>
<P>
   There was a story in the paper the other day that workers in the
Athletes' Village were concerned after finding syringes in the
bedsheets and towels and general detritus of the residents. At
least one worker was pricked, a scary prospect in this day and age.
It is doubtful there are that many diabetics in the village, and
besides, people with real medical needs tend to be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the athletes only mirror the rest of us, a world
full of chemical junkies, gobbling one thing or another for the
sniffles or the pips or the blues or the skinny biceps or whatever
it is we think ails us.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes can only hope their chemists are on top of their game,
unlike the blithering idiot of a doctor who apparently or allegedly
gave cold medicine to the 16-year-old gymnastics gold medalist from
Romania, Andreea Raducan.
</P>
<P>
   The kid had to cough up her gold medal because we're all on the
lookout for drug cheats. It's all so sad, but what are you going to
do? When they wake us up in the middle of the night in Seoul or
Sydney and say, hey, they just busted Ben Johnson, or Marion Jones'
husband, the whole world goes on drug alert. What a bore.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has no known history of dabbling with forbidden
fruit, had to pursue her dream of five gold medals while dealing
with the busting of her husband. Goodness only knows whether she
was aware of it. Husbands don't necessarily tell their wives
everything they do.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Jones stood by her man at a news conference.
Wednesday she had to qualify in two more events, a long day at the
Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 11 a.m., she ran the first heat of the women's
200-meter qualifier, finishing in 22.75 seconds, not exactly
gold-medal-final pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along this would be my hardest day at the
Olympics,'' Jones said. ``The heats and the long jump. I took it
easy in my race, and now I'll try to stay off my feet for a few
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   She came back in the evening and qualified for the finals. Then
she qualified for the long-jump final round in her first qualifying
jump and got off her feet again. She's carrying a lot of weight
around these days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-WRESTLING-ART-NYT     09-27 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDNER OF U.S. STARTLES WRESTLING WORLD WITH GOLD MEDAL VICTORY
OVER KARELIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia, Wyo.)  (ART ADV: Photos OLY 2,3,4,5,7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The wrestling behemoths stood side-by-side
during introductions, diplaying two distinct versions of 286-pound
physiques. On the left was the lean and sculpted Siberian tax
officer complete with snarl. On the right, with his hands clasped
before him, was a bulky slab of prime Wyoming beef who looked like
a shy kid with too much baby fat.
</P>
<P>
   Rulon Gardner knows how his roundish 29-year-old frame appears.
``Yeah, people make fun of me, like I ate a little kid and he's in
my chest,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it, but that enormous 54-inch chest guards a
pair of lungs harnessing a deep reservoir of aerobic strength that
would be his weapon of endurance against his opponent, Alexander
Karelin, the emperor of Greco-Roman wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of the most startling upsets in Olympic wrestling
history, Gardner defeated Karelin, 1-0, in overtime of the
130-kilogram (286-pound) final, blocking Karelin's attempted march
to a fourth consecutive Olympic gold medal. It was at least the
most surprising since Andrej Wronski of Poland won the Greco-Roman
heavyweight title in 1988 with no previous international titles.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin had never lost in international competition, and had not
lost at all since 1987. That loss was to a Soviet wrestler, back
when there was a Soviet Union, a still-standing Berlin Wall and a
cold war. For sheer surprise, Gardner's victory over such an
overwhelming favorite may rival the U.S. hockey team's upset of the
Soviet team at the 1980 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was a first-time Olympian, but he said he felt unusually
calm as he faced Karelin, an ease of mind doubtlessly unlike many
of Karelin's victims since 1987. When Karelin was starting his
13-year unbeaten streak, Gardner was milking cows, baling hay and
shoving rocks on his family's struggling dairy farm in tiny Afton,
Wyo., completely unaware of the terror of Karelin's signature
reverse body lift. It wasn't until 1992 that Gardner said he'd even
heard of a mighty Russian wrestler with Herculean strength but
didn't know his name. By 1995, Gardner knew who he was. By then,
Karelin had won gold in Seoul and Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a single, unbroken path to wrestling for Gardner.
At the University of Nebraska, he was the lineman who got away from
then coach Tom Osborne. Had Osborne matched the size of his
wrestling scholarship, Gardner might be fending off Jevon Kearse,
not grappling with Karelin.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were on a stage in Australia, in an exposition hall
packed with fans including Henry Kissinger and Juan Antonio
Samaranch, the president of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And Karelin was expected to fling Gardner, best known for
winning two Pan American championships, about the yellow and red
mat and return to Novosibirsk in Siberia with his fourth gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   But nine minutes later, there was Gardner exulting with a
somersault and a cartwheel. He had beaten Karelin by never letting
the Siberian toss him, turn him, take him down or flip him on his
head. Karelin was incapable of getting a firm or lasting grip on
the elusive Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   They pushed and poked each other relentlessly but Karelin failed
to gain an advantage even when grabbing Gardner's shaved head in
his big mitts. Nothing worked. Karelin lifted Gardner twice, but
Gardner's bulkiness, that huge chest, that center of gravity, kept
him grounded. In Greco-Roman wrestling, holds are not permitted
below the waist.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Big Man made a mistake. In a clinch with Gardner
for a minute to start the second three-minute round, he released
his lock. Gardner's coaches roared to the referee that he had
earned a point. The clock stopped, the three officials conferred
and gave Gardner the only point he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on that almost every day in practice,'' Gardner said.
``In the semis, I lost a point in a clinch. I have no idea why he
broke the clinch. I knew he broke it, but I thought he was going to
throw me and I thought: `Oh, no. What if the tape doesn't show he
broke the clinch?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner compared battling Karelin to moving a reluctant horse
where it doesn't want to go. But no, he amended the thought. A cow,
not a horse. ``If you get a chance,'' he said, ``go up against a
cow and push it. Just experience pushing a cow, to get her to move
where you need her, and that's what he's like. Only he's a bit
quicker. No, a lot quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe Karelin was tired after two matches Wednesday. Even
Goliath's knees start creaking. A Russian journalist joked that
Karelin may have been distracted by his duties in the lower house
of the Duma, the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin took his loss with class, placing his right hand on his
heart to acknowledge the fans simultaneously roaring in amazement
that he had lost while saluting his former invincibility. Then he
disappeared without a word.
</P>
<P>
   For Gardner, there was plenty to say, though, and plenty of
support. His parents, Reed and Virginia, four sisters and three
brothers were there. They and seven more members of the Gardner
family had scraped together the money to stand by Rulon.
</P>
<P>
   As his son cheerfully and skillfully talked with a horde of
reporters almost as large as Afton's population, Reed stood apart,
an American flag draped from his left shoulder down to his waist.
He held it in place with his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Gardner talked about hard times on the farm, of living
year-to-year, ``struggling to stay alive and hope next year will be
better.'' All the kids have left the farm, save Rulon, who runs it
now while his father helps out.
</P>
<P>
   His father remembered when Rulon, the youngest of his nine
children was chubby and quiet and easy for other boys to tease
</P>
<P>
   Reed Gardner said that his son's one defeat by Karelin three
years ago was a whupping to build on, an indelible memory of
frightening strength. Certainly, Karelin was not an abiding
obsession, as he was to Matt Ghaffari, the effusive Iranian-born
U.S. wrestler who lost the Olympic gold medal match to Karelin in
1996. ``As far as Alexander Karelin intimidating Rulon,'' Reed
Gardner said, ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was asked if he had sensed Karelin backing off,
surrendering, in the waning moments? Yes, he said, but added that
he had to be ready ``for one last explosion.'' But somewhere in
those final seconds, he said, Karelin mumbled something in Russian.
``I think,'' Rulon Gardner said, ``it was basically, `I give up.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
