<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS AND FORMER RUSSIANS SHINE IN BOXING; 3 U.S. FIGHTERS MOVE
ON 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ They come from Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan,
Uzbekistan, Ukraine and Russia, burly men who fight with a
relentless, intractable boxing style. On the 12th day of the 2000
Olympic boxing tournament, in a headstrong march through the
quarterfinals, it was the fighters from the countries formed by the
breakup of the Soviet Union that imposed a new pecking order on the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The once invincible Cuban boxers lost four consecutive
quarterfinal bouts and the Americans got back in the medal hunt
with three fighters _ Ricardo Juarez, Ricardo Williams Jr. and
Jermain Taylor _ advancing. But when the day ended, with the
semifinals set in 12 weight classes, the talk was no longer of the
rivalry between the United States and Cuba, it was about the
widespread improvement in fighters from nations that had once
fought under one federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you had one guy from the Soviet Union to get
past in each division,'' Tom Mustin, the U.S. boxing coach, said.
``Now, realistically, there's four or five of them from what used
to be the Soviet Union. And they're all good. Real good.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, fighters from Russia, Ukraine and
Kazakhstan won one gold medal each. Cuba won four gold medals and
three silver. The United States won one gold medal and four bronze
medals.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sydney Games, Russia has placed seven fighters in the
semifinals, more than any other country. Five fighters from Ukraine
have advanced to the medal round as well, four from Kazakhstan,
three from Uzbekistan and one each from Georgia and Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has six semifinalists and the United States has four,
including bantamweight Clarence Vinson, who will face Cuba's
Guillermo Rigondeaux Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Since both losing fighters in the semifinals receive bronze
medals that means the countries from the former Soviet Union are
assured of winning 21 boxing medals at this year's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are brawlers and they're extra strong,'' Mustin
said. ``They probably do a lot of weight lifting and neck exercises
because punches don't seem to affect them. They walk through them
and keep hitting you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mustin plans to get some head-to-head competition with Russia or
Kazakhstan in the coming non-Olympic years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring those guys in for some dual meets,'' he said.
``They are also fighting rougher _ more pushing and shoving and
pulling a guy's head down. And we've got to get used to that, learn
some of that. In U.S. amateur boxing, we fight relatively clean.
But you can see in these fights, they're letting more of that go.
We've got to adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good day for Mustin's team, something the U.S. fighters
needed after their team captain, Michael Bennett, was eliminated by
Cuba's heavyweight, Felix Savon, on Tuesday. Middleweight Jeff Lacy
was also soundly beaten on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest U.S. victory Wednesday came from Juarez, a
featherweight who defeated Somluck Kamsing of Thailand, a gold
medalist in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez, a reigning world champion, was behind on points, 11-9,
midway through the third round. But Juarez unleashed a 10-second
flurry of punches, chasing Kamsing from the center of the ring to
the ropes and keeping him there where he landed eight unanswered
punches. The fight was stopped in the fourth round because Juarez
was ahead by 15 points, 31-16. In the Olympics, fights are stopped
if one boxer is behind by 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Kamsing was 6 inches taller than the 5-foot-3-inch, 125-pound
Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough situation,'' Juarez said. ``But I'm pretty
tough, too. I don't worry about taller opponents, at my height,
everyone is taller.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, meanwhile, predicted he would win the middleweight
division after his convincing 19-14 victory over Germany's Adnan
Catic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going all the way,'' Taylor said. ``I'm going to win the
gold medal, I feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was expected to have to face Cuba's Juan Hernandez in the
next round. But Hernandez, a world champion who had several
commanding victories in the last two weeks, lost to Yermakhan
Ibraimov of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will face Cuba's Diogenes Luna in the welterweight
semifinals. Luna won his quarterfinal Wednesday with a knockout,
which is unusual in amateur boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can hit, but he also can be hit,'' Williams said of Luna.
``He takes a lot of punches and I'm going to feed him a lot of
leather.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was involved in a close fight with Russia's Leonov
Alexandre when he outpointed Alexandre, 7-1, in the third round.
Mustin calls Williams the U.S. team's most talented fighter because
of his great footwork and quick hands. Williams, 19, may need that
quickness against Luna, a seasoned 23-year-old who has barreled
through all of his opponents here.
</P>
<P>
   Luna was the lone Cuban fighter to win his bout Wednesday.
Tuesday, Cuban fighters were undefeated in five fights. Besides
Hernandez, Alexis Rubalcaba, Manuel Mantilla and Yosvany Aguilera
also lost.
</P>
<P>
   Flyweight Jose Navarro was the lone American to lose Wednesday
when he was defeated by France's Thomas Jerome on points, 23-12.
Navarro fell behind in the third round, and desperate for a
comeback, left himself open for even more punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried, but he was scoring more and more,'' Navarro said.
``I'm going to try to mature from this. I did the best I could.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
