<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-AUSSIE-TOWN-ART-9     09-27 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AUSSIE-TOWN-ART-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVE REVIEWS 90 MILES FROM SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo OLY 25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITHGOW, Australia _ The teacups clinked daintily as the ladies
of the Lithgow Valley Lawn Bowling Club sat down to lunch. But the
talk was of male Olympic swimmers and their rippling muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Lenny Krayzelburg,'' said Beryl Hammonds, clutching her
heart in a mock swoon as she referred to the American backstroker
who won three gold medals. ``There's nothing wrong with him that I
can see.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kirkland and Ruth Harries nodded vigorously as they
recalled their own long nights in front of the television. The
women cooked 15 dinners before the Games started, so they would not
miss a minute of the coverage. They watch at home so they can toast
every medalist, no matter the nationality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get nice and drunk because all we have to do is fall into
bed at the end of the night,'' Harries said with a titter.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow, population 15,000, lies at the end of the electrified
railroad line 90 miles west of Sydney, on the slopes of the Blue
Mountains. It is not the sort of place the writer Donald Horne was
thinking of when he famously described Australia as ``the lucky
country'' four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Remote, economically depressed and cursed with depressing
weather, Lithgow is worlds away from the designer skyscrapers and
sun-splashed beaches of Sydney. A few cars rattled along Main
Street, barely outracing the fog that scudded down from the nearby
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all its hard-luck veneer, Lithgow is as proud, as
captivated and as unabashedly excited about the Olympics as is
Sydney. At a time when its factories are shutting down and its
young people are fleeing for better opportunities elsewhere, the
Games have given Lithgow's residents _ coal miners, train engineers
and prison guards _ something to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of towns like Lithgow speckled across the
Australian hinterland. Left out of the economic boom that has
transformed Australia, and neglected by politicians who live on the
coast, these towns are nevertheless rejoicing in the success of the
Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've shown that for a small country, we can put on a
great show,'' said Don Green, a driver for the state roads and
traffic authority. ``That's what has made a lot of Australians very
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who was nursing a pint at the Grand Central pub, noted
that Lithgow had a distinguished Olympic tradition. Marjorie
Jackson, a runner who won two gold medals at the Helsinki Games in
1952, came from here. Last month, the Lithgow Flash, as Jackson is
called, returned to her hometown to carry the Olympic torch when it
passed through on its way to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played net ball against Marjorie Jackson in school,''
Kirkland said at the lawn bowling lunch. And Barbara Bryce chimed
in, ``I lived next door to her.'' Everybody had a Marjorie Jackson
story.
</P>
<P>
   Only slightly less exalted is John Doyle, a local comedian who
under the stage name Roy Slevin is the co-host of the ``Dream,'' a
wildly popular late-night show that follows the Olympics on
Australia's Seven network.
</P>
<P>
   Slevin and his partner, H.G. Nelson, take gleeful jabs at
everything from New Zealand to the grandees of the International
Olympic Committee. And Slevin draws heavily, if not altogether
factually, from his childhood here.
</P>
<P>
   A drive through Lithgow explains why the Olympics have lifted
this place in a way, perhaps, that it would not lift an Appalachian
mining town. Beyond Main Street, and the stony ruins of a
19th-century steel mill that gave the town its start, lie verdant
playing fields and sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   For a town with few resources, Lithgow has spent a fortune on
sports. It has a heated Olympic swimming pool, a new basketball
stadium, a running track, tennis courts, cricket grounds and hockey
fields that Len Ashworth, the editor of the local paper, says cost
the taxpayers here nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sports is how Lithgow has coped with being on the short end of
one economic cycle after the other. First the steel mill closed,
then the coal mines cut back. The small-arms factory that makes
machine guns was downsized after the Australian army began
importing them from overseas. And, in the most recent setback, a
bra factory shifted its operations to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people get laid off around here, they take up another
sport; it's better than moping at home,'' said Annette Geddes, who
works at the Lithgow Workmens Club, where the members play
competitive snooker.
</P>
<P>
   Some people take a more cynical view of Lithgow's jock culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else is there to do?'' asked Paul Nichols, a barber, as
he lounged in his shop, watching a field hockey match on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow's addiction to sports does not mean it has escaped the
more normal addictions of a town in tough times. Drug abuse is a
problem and the town's seven pubs _ or hotels, as they are called
in Australia _ fill up each day with locals who come to drink their
lunches and dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If beer drinking were an Olympic sport, we'd represent all of
Australia,'' said Nichols, 24, whose hair is dyed white.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do people here have any illusions about whether the Olympics
will help them. The Australian government forecast is that the
Games will attract 1.5 million more tourists to the country than
usual between 1998 and 2002. But with few attractions aside from
the rugged Blue Mountains, most will not make it this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest, Sydney is going to get all the benefits,''
said Robin Clark, a laborer who has been unemployed since he hurt
his shoulder a year ago. ``It's going to help Australia, but not
all of Australia.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clark spends his days hunkered over a snooker table at the
Workmens Club. He thinks Lithgow's future depends on attracting new
industries. A silicon manufacturer and a fireworks maker recently
set up shop here, while a consortium of companies has talked about
building a vast aluminum smelting plant. That would create 1,000
jobs and could transform Lithgow's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has got to happen soon, because a lot of people have
been laid off,'' Clark said, his voice briefly rising above a
monotone.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the unemployed wind up at the local off-track betting
parlor, where a bank of televisions was showing the field hockey
match and a harness race. Betting on the Games is not allowed in
the province of New South Wales, so the few wagerers ignored the
hockey to focus on the ponies.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Campbell, who runs the parlor, said business had fallen by
10 percent to 20 percent since the Games started. Even the
hard-core gamblers, she said, seemed to be taking a rest to watch
the Olympics on television. The traffic was equally thin next door,
at the Bracey department store.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their personal struggles, people here have set them
aside for two weeks to savor Australia's moment in the sun. Green,
of the roads and traffic authority, chalked it up to the Australian
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had droughts and fires and downturns in this town, but
it doesn't break our spirit,'' he said as his mates ordered another
round and settled in for another evening of Olympic enjoyment. ``We
just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
