<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     09-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THIS CAMPAIGN LACKS RHYME AND RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As we head into the final month of the presidential
campaign, the race between Al Gore and George W. Bush is very close
and very confrontational. But the words spoken by the two
candidates lack the vision and the idealism that generate great
expectations, especially among young voters.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' last week, former Gov.
Mario Cuomo of New York declared: ``You campaign on poetry; you
govern on prose.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems not to have infiltrated the political psyches of Gore
and Bush, who rarely venture beyond pedantic prose. Damning the
opposition candidate can solve a vital political need _ votes. But
poetry and idealism are required to lift the spirits of Americans
and make the young understand that they live in a great country
with a great future.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate obviously wants to know where the candidates
stand on such issues as Social Security, Medicare, the cost of
prescription drugs, education and, of course, a national energy
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Many crave a menu of old-fashioned beef and potatoes _ a repast
of the sturdy victuals that sustain life and good health. But they
also desire an ample serving of frothy dessert complemented by an
effervescent glass of Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan and John Kennedy were masters at using language to
inspire as well as to inform. They understood the art of generating
enthusiasm for the opportunities that lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After denouncing big government, high taxes and lavish spending,
Reagan would paint a glowing word picture of the ``shining city on
the hill,'' an idealized vision of America as it was and as it
could be. In doing so, he nourished the hopes and dreams of the
people and won great victories at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   As he traversed the country in 1960, Kennedy repeatedly sounded
a basic theme that dwelt upon the vast opportunities that lay ahead
if he were permitted to ``get America moving'' again. In his
inaugural address in 1961, Kennedy electrified America when he
declared: ``Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you
can do for your country.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, the new president lifted the human spirit far
above the Cold War problems that faced America on that frigid day.
</P>
<P>
   For one glowing moment, people everywhere applauded the concept
of putting their country ahead of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Humphrey had a similar effect on many Americans in 1948,
when he was seeking his first term in the Senate. Appearing before
a Democratic National Convention that was deeply divided over civil
rights, he proclaimed: ``The time has arrived for the Democratic
Party to get out of the shadow of states' rights and walk
forthrightly into the bright sunshine of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Humphrey's words and the civil rights plank adopted by
the convention led to a walkout of some Southern delegates, they
placed the national Democratic Party foursquare behind full
constitutional rights for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment forward, black Americans knew they had staunch
friends in one of the republic's major political parties. The road
ahead was littered with violence and bloodshed as courageous civil
rights advocates battled the defenders of racial segregation and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, President Lyndon Johnson, a son of the old Confederacy,
signed into law legislation that outlawed segregation in employment
and in public accommodations. It also authorized the attorney
general to initiate desegregation suits.
</P>
<P>
   That law and others that followed broke the back of racial
segregation in the South and, to the surprise of many Southerners,
opened the door for economic boom in that section of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt and Woodrow Wilson both stirred the latent
idealism in the people and greatly enriched the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Adlai Stevenson twice was defeated for president, his
majestic rhetoric raised politics to a new level. He, like Kennedy,
instilled in millions of young Americans a belief that public
service is a noble calling.
</P>
<P>
   Young Americans, witnessing Gore and Bush's constant scrimmaging
over Social Security, Medicare, prescription drugs and other issues
dear to the hearts of senior citizens, must wonder why they should
vote.
</P>
<P>
   These young people need an eloquent dose of the kind of vision
and determination that Franklin Roosevelt used to assure the
American people that the sun would shine through the dark clouds of
the Great Depression. Their votes and their participation are
needed in our future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
