<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3563 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ADDICTION-METALS-NYTS     09-27 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADDICTION-METALS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME METALS MAY HEIGHTEN RISK OF DRUG ADDICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See ``What To Do'' sidebar below)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY RANDY DOTINGA  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Exposure to certain metals may do more harm than previously
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Lead and cadmium appear to make people more susceptible to
alcohol and drug addiction, says Jack Nation, a psychologist at
Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an unhappy situation where our chemical environment
may be altering patterns of drug use and abuse,'' says Nation, who
has spent 15 years studying the effects of environmental
contaminants on drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Cadmium, a component of cigarettes, enters the body when someone
smokes, and it stays for decades, Nation says. It also enters
fetuses when mothers smoke during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   A common exposure to lead comes via old paint, making children
in poor neighborhoods especially vulnerable. A 1999 study warned
that 70 percent of children in major metropolitan areas might be at
risk of dangerous exposure to lead.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings in the latest study stem from the researchers'
tests on rats.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to lead changed how the rats in the study reacted to
the effects of cocaine, Nation says.
</P>
<P>
   The processes that cause drug addiction in rats appear similar
to those in people, Nation says. And, unlike other drugs, he says,
cocaine packs a bigger punch as people use it more often, which
makes it especially addicting.
</P>
<P>
   The rats were allowed to self-administer cocaine by pressing a
lever that sent the drug into their jugular vein, he says. While
initial doses of cocaine didn't do much for the lead-exposed rats,
the animals actually became ``supersensitive'' to later doses, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to cadmium, on the other hand, made the rats more
tolerant of the effects of alcohol and drugs, the study says.
Results appear in the October issue of the journal
Neuropsychopharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   In some people, higher tolerance to drugs and alcohol could keep
them away from addiction because they won't get much of a kick from
their first doses, Nation says. But others might face greater
danger because they'll need to take more drugs to get their desired
high, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're talking about are cases where you have people who
are going to use drugs because of their life circumstances,'' he
says. ``They're going to have to opt for a higher dose.''
</P>
<P>
   And those higher doses will pose greater harm to their bodies,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The two metals _ lead and cadmium _ appear to change the way the
chemical dopamine works in the brain, Nation says. Scientists
suspect dopamine is a major player in addiction because it
regulates positive feelings, like euphoria, that can accompany a
drug-induced high.
</P>
<P>
   However, not everyone is convinced that a definite link exists
between lead, cadmium and increased drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kuczenski, a psychiatry professor at the University of
California, San Diego, says it's clear that lead affects the way
dopamine functions in the brain. But, while lead exposure changes
the way a body adjusts to drug use, that doesn't automatically
translate into greater likelihood of addiction, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And it's far from clear whether greater tolerance for a drug
will make someone more likely to become an addict, Kuczenski says.
</P>
<P>
   As for nicotine, he says, researchers still need to investigate
what the combination of smoking and hard drugs does to the body.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO
</P>
<P>
   Whether lead exposure does or does not make drug addiction more
likely, lead remains a hazardous substance. If you live in an older
building, learn about lead and how to protect yourself and your
family.
</P>
<P>
   For information about lead poisoning and how to avoid it, take a
look at information offered by the Alliance to End Childhood Lead
Poisoning (www.aeclp.org/2/index.html).
</P>
<P>
   To read more about cadmium and its effects on the body, check
out information from the environmental group Eco-USA
(www.eco-usa.net/toxics/cadmium.html).
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3566 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-STROKE-WHOLE-GRAIN-ME     09-27 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-WHOLE-GRAIN-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOLE-GRAIN DIET CAN WARD OFF STROKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See``What To Do'' sidebar below)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY ED EDELSON  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   A single slice of whole wheat bread a day can be a lifesaver,
says a report on a long-term study showing that a higher intake of
whole grain foods reduces the risk of stroke by more than 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is so striking that ``replacing refined grains with
whole grains by even one serving a day may have significant
benefits in reducing the risk of ischemic stroke,'' a group led by
Dr. Simin Liu of Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston writes in
the latest Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Ischemic stroke, in which part of the brain dies when its blood
flow is blocked, accounts for 70 percent of the 600,000 strokes in
the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   One serving of bread is a single slice, says Diane Quigliani, a
registered dietitian and spokeswoman for the American Dietetic
Association. So switching from white bread to whole wheat bread at
the breakfast table can make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   The finding comes from the Nurses' Health Study, which has
followed 75,521 women since 1984. Liu and his colleagues compared
the incidence of stroke with the participants' reports of their
eating habits. They focused on refined grain foods _ sweet rolls,
cakes, white bread, English muffins, pancakes, waffles and the like
_ versus whole grain foods including cooked oatmeal, brown rice,
wheat germ, popcorn, and whole grain breakfast cereals.
</P>
<P>
   THE MORE GRAINS, THE BETTER
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of ischemic strokes among the 20 percent of women
who reported the highest intake of whole grain foods, 2.7 servings
a day, was 43 percent lower than in those reporting the lowest
intake, an average of only one-eighth of a serving a day, the
researchers found. In between those two extremes, there was pretty
much a direct relationship between whole grain intake and lower
ischemic stroke risk. There were not enough hemorrhagic strokes, in
which a blood vessel bursts, to give statistically significant
results.
</P>
<P>
   The protective effect remained constant when other major risk
factors for stroke, such as smoking, exercise, dietary fatty acids
and hormone therapy for menopause were examined, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   There are several possible reasons why whole grain foods are
better for health than refined products, says Liu, of the division
of preventive medicine at Brigham and Women's Hospital. Whole
grains contain an abundance of antioxidants, minerals and fiber,
all of which are removed by processing. They also contain folate,
magnesium, vitamin E and potassium, all of which have been linked
by different biological mechanisms to reduction of the hardening of
the arteries that leads to heart attack and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis found that the presence of all those components
did not explain the protective effect completely, ``indicating that
other constituents may contribute to additional protection,'' Liu
says.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers note that the 2.71 daily servings of the
women with the highest intake still falls short of the three
servings a day recommended by the American Dietetic Association and
other medical and nutritional authorities. Overall, the average
intake of the nurses was one serving a day _ and that is much
better than the intake of Americans in general, who average
one-half of a serving daily.
</P>
<P>
   Whole grain foods range from the prosaic, like ordinary
breakfast cereals, to the more exotic, including bulgur (a form of
whole wheat found in the Middle East), couscous and quinoa. One
ounce of a whole grain cereal, a half cup of brown rice and that
one slice of whole wheat bread will provide the three recommended
daily servings, she says: ``These are not huge amounts.''
</P>
<P>
   And the benefits go beyond stroke prevention, Quigliani adds.
``The Food and Drug Administration has approved a health plan
saying that diets rich in whole grain food and lower in total fats
and cholesterol can reduce the risk of heart disease and certain
cancers.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to identify whole grain foods, says dietician Diane
Quigliani: Read the ingredient label. ``Look for the ones that have
whole grains as the first ingredient,'' she says. ``Whole wheat,
whole oats, whole barley, cornmeal, cracked wheat, graham flour,
brown rice. If you see one of these as the first ingredient, it's a
good choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Read the labels to pick out the whole grain products, add fruits
and vegetables and other fiber-rich foods and protect your heart
and brain. You don't help yourself very much if you eat whole wheat
bread only to constantly put junk between the slices.
</P>
<P>
   Also keep in mind that this is a study of nurses, who tend to
lead healthier lifestyles than do most people.
</P>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association (www.eatright.org/nfs/) can
get you started eating right, and the the American Medical
Association (www.ama-assn.org/insight/spec_con/stroke/stroke.htm)
has more information about strokes.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
