<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3575 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     09-27 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV15-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 15, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I bought a new set of top quality drill bits for my electric
drill to make holes in metal.
 &HT;    However, I find that whenever I want to drill a hole through a
smooth metal surface, the tip of the bit ``wanders'' or skitters
around before it gets started, making it very difficult to form the
hole exactly where I want to.
 &HT;    What do you think I am doing wrong?
 &HT;    A: A drill bit ``wandering'' before it gets started is not an
unusual problem.
 &HT;    To prevent this use a variable speed drill running at a low
speed and start by first using a center punch to make a slight
dimple in the metal where you want the bit to start.
 &HT;    Then build a small ``dam'' around this dimple, using a ring of
putty or glazing compound, and fill this with a small amount of
kerosene or light lubricating oil before starting to drill.
 &HT;    The lubricant will help the bit cut faster and cooler.
 &HT;    Another tip: Before using a bit larger than 1/4'' start by first
drilling a smaller hole, then finish with the larger bit.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My fireplace hearth is made of marble and I have been told
that this stains easily.
 &HT;    Is there a sealer you can suggest that can protect the marble
against such staining?
 &HT;    A: The coating most frequently used on marble is a good grade of
white or clear paste wax which is rubbed on, then buffed vigorously
to produce a shine.
 &HT;    There is also a variety of stone sealers for use on marble,
usually sold in home centers and by local marble or stone dealers.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our kitchen sink has a garbage disposal unit under it, and
there is a foul odor coming from this drain.
 &HT;    Short of replacing the disposal unit, what can I do to get rid
of this smell?
 &HT;    A. Many markets and hardware stores sell special cleaners and
deodorants for use in garbage disposals.
 &HT;    Another household remedy that often works is to pour vinegar
into the drain and let it sit for about 30 minutes before flushing
it down with running water.
 &HT;    A cupful of household bleach mixed half and half with water
poured into the disposal also is claimed to work, but flush this
away with water after about 10 minutes.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our old bedroom furniture is finished with mahogany veneer
and this thin veneer has a blister on the top. Can it be repaired
without completely refinishing the dresser?
 &HT;    A: Slice through the blister with a razor blade, then press one
side of the blister down and slide the tip of a thin knife blade
under the raised half.
 &HT;    Use the tip of the blade to scrape out as much of the old dried
glue as you can, then press this half of the blister down and do
the same under the other half.
 &HT;    When finished, use a toothpick or thin blade to spread a small
amount of white carpenter's glue under each raised half of the
blister.
 &HT;    Press down firmly on the whole blister and wipe off any excess
glue that oozes out.
 &HT;    Cover the area with waxed paper, then pile some books or
magazines on top to hold the veneer down until the glue has dried.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``DRILLING A HOLE IN SHEET METAL'' goes
with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Center punch is used to create dimple in metal, and dam
of putty holds pool of lubricating oil to help drill bit cut
precisely and faster.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
