<SLUG> BC-DIVA-OMARA-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVA VISTA
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN- Social Club's Portuondo to grace UCLA's Royce Hall 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. ``TONIGHT'' refers to Fri., Sept. 29, 2000.) 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
When Celia Cruz sailed the Florida Straits to find fame and fortune
in the U.S., Omara Portuondo remained in Havana as Cuba's premier
diva for 50 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sole female member of Buena Vista Social Club, Portuondo's
seductive, velvety vocals could, it's been said, make the dead
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Lately she's been making audiences rise instead, wherever she
and other members of Buena Vista Social Club appear.
</P>
<P>
   While she's been a huge star at home for decades, she made her
U.S. solo concert debut just three years ago when Buena Vista
Social Club performed at Carnegie Hall. That event was filmed by
Wim Wenders for his Oscar-nominated documentary, ``Buena Vista
Social Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Portuondo has toured extensively with the Social
Club's Ibrahim Ferrer and Ruben Gonzalez (who was her pianist in
the '40s), released an acclaimed self-titled album, and embarked on
a headlining trek that brings her to Royce Hall tonight, Saturday
at Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts and Oct. 7 at the
Hollywood Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's music people understand,'' Portuondo, 70, said in Spanish
through a translator. ``I think it has an element that's fresh. It
has melody and harmony that's very attractive to the ear, even to
people who never understood our culture. So they think they're
hearing something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Often compared to the likes of Edith Piaf and Billie Holiday,
Portuondo began her musical career in the '50s when she and her
sister sang American jazz standards and later formed a female vocal
quartet. In 1959 she issued her first album, a collection of
American jazz and Cuban favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nat King Cole, like Tony Bennett, Sarah Vaughan and Piaf, were
presented in Cuba for special events,'' Portuondo recalled. ``It
was the surprise of my life when I saw Piaf. She was dressed in
black. She didn't move or anything. She was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Portuondo met Buena Vista Social Club producer Ry Cooder by
accident. She happened to be at a Havana studio at the same time as
the guitarist, who was putting together a collection of golden-age
Cuban songs played and sung by the surviving musicians of the era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew it was going to get a Grammy,'' she said of the
resulting album. ``I went to record with friends who knew the
music. But we didn't know anything would happen around the world
because of it. It's a good album. That's all we knew. In reality,
an artist never knows what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do it with lots of love and dedication. I couldn't predict
it was going to be such a huge hit because, in reality, there are
other records that aren't hits. So, it was a beautiful surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Portuondo lives in a high-rise Havana apartment with
views of the sea and remains a flamboyant fixture on the local
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I spend so little time in Cuba,'' she said. ``I
travel all over the world, in Europe and South America, especially
after the Buena Vista Social Club. In all parts of the world,
people know the film and the album and they're in love with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, they're in love with all of us. This is a work
that unites lots of elements. It comes from a great love.'' &QL; 
---OMARA PORTUONDO &QL; 
Where: Royce Hall, UCLA campus, Westwood. When: 8 tonight (plus
Saturday at Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts and Oct. 7 at
the Hollywood Bowl). Tickets: $20 to $45. Information: (213)
480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
