<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenpeace lobbies for execution stay for moths
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Save the bogong moths! That's the cry from Greenpeace, which is
protesting plans to exterminate the moths that are swarming around
Olympic Park. The stadium lights attract the moths, and official
have considered spraying pesticides to get rid of them. The moths
are harmless, but annoying.
</P>
<P>
   First a medal, now a watch
</P>
<P>
   Gold medal winner Cathy Freeman was spotted at the Watches of
Switzerland store downtown, where her husband, Sandy Bodecker,
bought her a Cartier watch. The store would not say which watch she
chose, but the styles she looked at cost between $19,000 and
$64,000, depending on the number of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Really pulling for Freeman
</P>
<P>
   More than 8 million Australians watched Freeman win the
400-meter race, making it the most-watched sports event in Aussie
history. More than 90 percent of all televisions in Sydney that
were on at that time were watching the race.
</P>
<P>
   Tattoo mania
</P>
<P>
   Sydney stores are running out of the stick-on flag tattoos that
Aussie fans like to wear on their faces. The tattoo, which costs
$2-$3, is one of the hottest selling items at the Games. More
supplies are on the way _ but they may not get in stores until
after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
