<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CYCLE0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour de France winner triumphs, but it's not Armstrong
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - A Tour de France winner captured the gold at the
Olympic men's road race here, but it was not Lance Armstrong.
German Jan Ullrich, the 1997 Tour de France winner and runner-up to
Armstrong this year, powered away from two other riders on the last
lap and then raised his hands in triumph after just under five and
one-half hours of cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandre Vinokourov of Kazakhstan took the silver with
Ullrich's German teammate Andreas Kloeden taking the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   George Hincapie was the top U.S. finisher at eighth. Armstrong,
the current Tour de France champion and a cancer survivor, was
13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a road race and things didn't roll our way,'' Armstrong
said. ``We had a plan, but unfortunately those three guys got out
and rode away.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said that the plan was for someone to go out early
then have Hincapie ride with the leaders and for him to then take
over near the end. He said he reached Hincapie, who assured him
there was no one out on a breakaway. Armstrong saw a monitor and
said, ``George, who's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie was more stunned than Armstrong that other riders had
gotten away.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong still has the individual time trials coming up on
Saturday and is considered one of the favorites, along with
Ullrich, in that event.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a super talent,'' Armstrong said. ``He'll be hard to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming in Armstrong thought that in this one-day road race over
relatively flat terrain there could be a number of possible
winners. He named Ullrich, but also included some of his U.S.
teammates. None, however, threatened to win a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the race was literallly a ride in the park.
The 148.5-mile course consisted of 14 laps in and around Moore
Park. For the first seven of those laps Armstrong and cycling's
bigger names and countries were content to watch a quartet of
riders stage a small breakaway. After seven laps Orlando Rodrigues
of Portugal, Remigijus Lupeikis of Lithuania, Evgeny Wacker of
Kyrgyzstan and Piotr Wadecki of Poland had a lead of just under
three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By the eighth lap, however, they'd been reeled with Frenchmen
Laurent Jalabert and Laurent Brochard among the leaders as well as
Armstrong's teammate Tyler Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   This road race was Armstrong's third Olympic effort in that
event. In 1992 in Barcelona he finished 14th and in the 1996 Games
in Atlanta, he finished 12th. ``I didn't think about that. I was
riding for today,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
