<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTES0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A recap of other events Wednesday
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basketball
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie sparked a 58-43 victory over Slovakia, moving the
U.S. into the semifinals. The Americans will face South Korea,
which gave them fits in the first game of the preliminary round. In
the other quarterfinals, Brazil got by Russia 68-67, and Australia
routed Poland 76-48.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing
</P>
<P>
   Featherweight Rocky Juarez outclassed 1996 Olympic champion
Somluck Kamsing of Thailand to reach the boxing semifinals. Ricardo
Williams Jr. was assured of at least a bronze with a 17-12 win over
Russia's Alexandre Leonov in the 139-pound semifinals. Williams
will face Diogenes Luna of Cuba on Friday. Teammate Clarence Vinson
is in the 119-pound semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Canoe-Kayak
</P>
<P>
   Martin Doktor of the Czechs Republic, the 1996 winner in both
the canoe 500- and 1,000-meter events, was disqualified from the
men's C-1 500 for drifting too close to a competitor. Germany had
filed a protest against him. The rule is designed to prevent boats
from riding in another's wake.
</P>
<P>
   Diving
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Keim and Michelle Davison of the U.S. qualified for the
women's springboard diving final. China's Fu Mingxia, the defending
champion, was seeded first after the semifinals. She is trying to
become the third diver to win four gold medals. Guo Jingjing of
China was seeded second and Russia's Yulia Pakhalina third. Keim
was seeded eighth and Davison 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Equestrian
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight Games, Germany, the Netherlands and the
U.S. finished 1-2-3 in team dressage. Germany won its seventh gold
medal since 1964. Christine Traurig, riding aboard Etienne, secured
the bronze for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Field hockey
</P>
<P>
   India, an eight-time gold medalist, was eliminated from men's
competition after it drew 1-1 with Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Track and field
</P>
<P>
   World champion Mihaela Melinte of Romania failed a pre-Games
drug test and was not allowed to compete in the women's hammer
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis
</P>
<P>
   Sebastien Lareau and Daniel Nestor of Canada took the gold in
double's tennis Wednesday, beating Todd Woodbridge and Mark
Woodforde of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Volleyball
</P>
<P>
   Russia edged Cuba to reach the men's semifinals. Favorite Italy
lost a set before coming back to beat Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Water polo
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men's team defeated Greece to reach the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
