<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SALLYFIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ``BEAUTIFUL'' EXPERIENCE FOR SALLY FIELD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
TORONTO _ After 35 years in show business, Sally Field knows all
about the limitations and expectations placed on women. For much of
her career, Field traded on being cute and perky; when that ran its
course, she went for sexy in such movies as ``Stay Hungry'' and
``Smokey and the Bandit.'' She even posed for the cover of Playboy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not until ``Norma Rae'' in 1980 did Hollywood begin to take her
seriously as an actress, but even then she didn't feel secure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, when she won her second best-actress Oscar (for
``Places in the Heart''), winning the industry's approval still was
a paramount concern, as shown by the way she famously trilled ``you
like me! You really like me!'' in her acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   So it's interesting to hear her say that what attracted her to
``Beautiful,'' the new Minnie Driver comedy that Field chose as her
feature directing debut, was that the female lead character isn't
very likable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What appealed to me was the character,'' Field said recently
in Toronto, where ``Beautiful'' was screened as part of the Toronto
International Film Festival. ``It is what made me interested in the
first place and kept me interested all the way, even though we
really developed the piece for about a year and a half to get the
story as close to right as we could get it. But it was the
character that I loved, this larger-than-life, hopefully funny
female, who was very flawed and complicated and who really walks a
fine line between being likable and not likable.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the serious Field talking. Post-cute. Post-Playboy sexy.
She's still trim and pixyish. She still has that familiar girlish
voice. But you don't think Gidget. You don't think the Flying Nun.
The confident, middle-aged woman sitting ramrod-straight in a chair
near the window in this nondescript hotel suite isn't straining to
amuse. This woman is a movie director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most female characters come on screen and they're asking to be
liked, constantly, nowadays especially,'' she continued. ``And Mona
(the character Driver plays) never does that. Ultimately, if you
don't end up liking her _ which you may not _ you end up caring
about her. You want to see her survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mona has had one goal her whole life _ to be crowned Miss
American Miss.
</P>
<P>
   One irony of the film is that, while winning the title might be
seen as the ultimate in societal approval, Mona is so singleminded
in her pursuit of it that she alienates almost everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby, her friend from childhood (played by Joey Lauren Adams),
is the only person who can stand her.
</P>
<P>
   Mona is the kind of woman who would wear a pageant crown to a
diner and think people were staring because she's beautiful. When a
pregnant woman goes into labor in the supermarket, Mona springs
into action _ not because she cares about the woman and child, but
because the publicity will do her good.
</P>
<P>
   And when she gets pregnant as a teen-ager, she avoids
disqualification as a beauty queen by giving the child (Hallie Kate
Eisenberg) to Ruby to raise as her own.
</P>
<P>
   The child doesn't know, and no one else acknowledges, that Mona
is the mother.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tricky movie that tries to work on several levels, to
make big statements about societal and personal values while also
keeping audiences entertained.
</P>
<P>
   Field previously directed and co-wrote a made-for-television
movie, ``A Woman of Independent Means,'' and she directed an
episode of Tom Hanks' HBO series, ``From the Earth to the Moon,''
but those projects didn't fully prepare her for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bigger story to tell,'' she said of ``Beautiful.''
``There's a lot going on. We have children and beauty queens and
singing and dancing and musical numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   To juggle all of this in a small-budget movie that is both a
comedy and a character study wasn't easy. And Field acknowledges
that she isn't yet the director she hopes to become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing it (directing) slowly so that I could both
figure out if I really wanted to be in this arena, No. 1, and No.
2, if I should be in it at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She's made up her mind that she wants to keep directing,
although she doesn't yet have another movie lined up. And she
doubts that she'll be directing herself in a movie anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, directing is such a difficult task I don't want to
give myself any other ball to keep in the air while I'm doing it,
other than just trying to learn as fast as I can,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to do both. I'd like to be able to have
the opportunity to learn, to be better at directing. I'm a much
better actor than I am a director. I'd like to get better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll be seen this season in six episodes of ER, playing the
mother of one of the regular characters, Maura Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   Stars nowadays, as a group, wield more power in Hollywood than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Field was among the first of the current crop of actresses to
open her own production company to find and develop movies. It was
a way of manufacturing good roles in an industry that often
shortchanges women.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get out there and do what you can to find the
product that you would like to be part of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sit back and shake your fist. That's a good first
step, but not much gets done when you sit back and shake your
fist.''
</P>
<P>
   A solid strain of feminism runs through Field's work, especially
in her movies about strong women persevering against all odds. She
downplays the feminism of ``Beautiful,'' though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parenting issues and the single-mother issues and all that
are there,'' she said, ``but at the bottom of all of it is this
character who has this pain and damage from childhood that she
carries around with her, and to grow up and be a productive,
worthwhile adult, she has to let them go and move on to another
part of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the biggest and most difficult thing for a
human to do _ to not cling on to those things from the past, to
find who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   But, while she prefers talking about ``the human dilemma'' Mona
faces, Field acknowledges that there is much in the movie that she
can relate to as a woman in the show-business world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pressures of those parameters that are set up for
women to be like, to cram yourself into some little box,'' she
said. ``Whether it's society, the advertising industry, the motion
picture business or whoever sets this up, if you don't fit into
that box, you're not female, you're not attractive, you're not
productive, somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides the physical things you have to fit into, so many
of the things that are precious to human beings _ whether it's
ambition, drive, passion, anger, cleverness or desire _ all of
those things in a woman can be considered negative, and really
they're just glorious.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about how this relates to the movie, Field laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mona's case, sometimes they're a little more ... colorful
than one would like,'' she said. ``But that's what I love about her
_ she makes big, big ol' ugly mistakes, and she's not a perfect
person. I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
