<SLUG> BC-YUGO-SCENE-720&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK OF END OF MILOSEVIC ERA FILLS BELGRADE'S STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ In the crumbling streets of a faded
Belgrade, tired and worn from 10 years of international sanctions
and isolation, most people have simply had enough of the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not sure he is going to go quietly after his
apparent defeat in Sunday's elections here. And they are nervous
about a police crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Serbia, so why should anything be easy?'' said Sasha,
drinking an espresso at the Ipanema cafe. ``Everything is clear.
It's not finished, but it's clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gojko Komazec, a waiter with a long ponytail, said that few
believe the preliminary vote totals that state television suddenly
announced Tuesday night, showing Milosevic trailing his main
challenger, Vojislav Kostunica, but denying Kostunica an outright
victory in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica immediately accused the government of vote fraud,
challenged the Federal Election Commission to verify its results,
and said he would not participate in a second round on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Is Milosevic finished? ``I hope so,'' Komazec said. ``This is
the first time I can remember that I'm not worried about our
future. But I am very worried about the next few days,'' when the
opposition, which says Kostunica has won outright, holds rallies to
support him.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, people were snapping up independent daily
newspapers like Blic, Danas and Glas Javnosti to get the news, and
there were angry conversations about Milosevic's effort to buy time
and hang on to power. Overhead, campaign posters for Milosevic's
Socialist Party are beginning to fade.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the bomb damage from last year's NATO airstrikes
has been fixed in Belgrade, including repairs to the Foreign
Ministry and the Serbian Parliament buildings, other structures,
like the headquarters of the Yugoslav army and the Serbian and
federal Interior Ministry buildings, are untouched, blasted and
sooty.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even the Brankov Bridge over the Sava River to New Belgrade is
only half-painted, with one set of guardrails an already fading
blue, while the other side was never repainted at all.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the markets are full of fruits and vegetables, even if there
is grumbling over the prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be better for all of us if he just goes, and takes
his family, too,'' said Pero Drvenica, pushing his three-year-old
daughter, Milica, through the Kalenic market, full of bright red
peppers and orange squashes. ``He's finished, and he has to know
it. It's obvious he lost and he's in a panic, and nobody believes
this children's story of a second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Drvenica said he would come to any rally the opposition called
and bring Milica, too. ``It's her future,'' he said. ``This guy, if
he's clever, could finish this very easily and just accept the vote
of the people. In a second round he'll be humiliated even more.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Darko, who asked that his last name not be used, said that he
had been pressured in his company to sign a petition for
Milosevic's candidacy. In the end, he said, he signed twice, for
two different bosses. He voted for Kostunica anyway, in part
because of his anti-communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has got to go,'' Darko said. ``I'm so happy, but
mostly for my father,'' whose property had been confiscated after
World War II by the victorious communists. He said he had convinced
his sister, a Milosevic supporter, to vote for Kostunica, too. ``I
told her, `Don't vote for yourself. Vote for your kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dragana Kreca, 31, works as a waitress, complaining that jobs in
state companies are mostly reserved for members of the ruling
parties of Milosevic and his wife, Mirjana Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is over,'' she said. ``Maybe not today, but sometime
soon. Serbia voted for Kostunica and a different future _ it's
enough of this life of cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Curcic, 48, was selling huge sacks of peppers and
cucumbers from his truck. ``I don't know how Milosevic will give up
technically and how he'll accept his loss, but he's gone,'' Curcic
said. ``America punished all of us because of this guy, who was
your ally at one moment, and you didn't do much to help us get rid
of him,'' he said. ``Now he can go to China or India, it doesn't
matter, but he has to go.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Curcic, Milosevic's campaign was offensive. ``These are
stupidities they sell to old people,'' he said. ``We all know our
kids aren't terrorists, and it's crazy to call anyone who thinks
different an enemy of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, by contrast, said Nenad Piljak, is ``a normal man.''
Piljak sells fruit in the morning and studies to be a
physiotherapist in the afternoon, and he likes Kostunica's defense
of Serb interests. ``I believe it is an honest and fair patriotism
that he represents,'' Piljak said. ``I think it's fine that he has
this distance from America. Serbia belongs in Europe. The Americans
bombed this country and committed a big crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't European countries in NATO bomb, too? ``Yes, they
participated,'' he said. ``But everyone knows who the big boss
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs also committed crimes in Kosovo, Piljak said,
especially with the expulsion of so many Albanians. ``But Serbia
was also defending what belongs to her,'' he said. Kostunica
strikes the right balance, Piljak said, adding that he found the
Milosevic campaign offputting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest crime is to divide your own people into patriots
and traitors because of their political beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These elections ``are the beginning of the end of Milosevic,''
Piljak said. ``He needs to lose the Serbian elections before he
finally goes.''
</P>
<P>
   As for himself, Piljak has no plans to study this week. ``I'm
going to go to the rallies and greet my new president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Brankovic, a civil engineer, will go, too. But he's
anxious. ``I hope Milosevic is finished, but I'm not sure,'' he
said. ``He still has the police and the army. I'm too old _ I'm 51
_ and I'm a little bit afraid of what will happen, but really I'm
afraid for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Stankovic, 32, says he voted for the first time in 10
years, and he thinks Kostunica is right to reject a second round.
``In the evening, I'll come out with my brother and my friends to
the rallies, and if we have to fight, we'll fight,'' he said. ``But
I don't think the police and army will fight with us. I really do
expect them to accept the will of the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
