<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BLUEDOGS-TEX     09-27 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUEDOGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE RODRIGUE'S POP-ART POOCH IS HOTTER THAN EVER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may well go down as the most profitable bedtime story ever
told. When George Rodrigue was just a tyke growing up in the
southern Louisiana town of New Iberia, he was spellbound by his
mama's French-Cajun tale of the werewolf, or ``loup-garou.'' This
snarling creature would prowl the nearby sugar-cane fields, his
mamma said, snatching up misbehaving youngsters and devouring them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when Rodrigue, 56, had grown into a moderately
successful Louisiana-based painter, he was working on illustrations
for a book on Louisiana ghost stories like the ones his mother
recounted. Drawing from memory and some mysterious inspiration,
Rodrigue began painting a dog-wolf creature bathed in the blue glow
of a bayou moon. Rodrigue's friends and hangers-on soon dubbed the
result ``the Blue Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, ``cash cow'' might be a better name for Rodrigue's bit of
brushwork. Rodrigue's Blue Dog has become one of the most
recognized and marketed artistic icons ever conjured up. Not since
Andy Warhol's Campbell's soup can, Peter Max's Froot Loop-colored
posters or Keith Haring's radiant dog series has one artist plugged
in so completely to the mercurial pop-art market.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue's azure doggy is reaping all the rewards that
commercial pop art can offer. From that memorable week in 1990 when
20 of the artist's Blue Dog works all but flew out of his New
Orleans gallery, Rodrigue now enjoys $8 million in annual sales of
Blue Dog art at his four galleries in New Orleans; Carmel, Calif.;
Munich; and Tokyo. At one time, a Blue Dog oil painting could be
had for $400 to $600. Today, they can't be fetched for under
$15,000, with ones measuring 8 feet by 12 feet commanding close to
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first painted the Blue Dog, it was what I wanted, and
then all of a sudden it was what everyone wanted,'' Rodrigue
sheepishly admits.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue's most recent book, ``Blue Dog Man'' (Stewart, Tabori &AMP;
Chang, $50), has sold briskly, and the Blue Dog Cafe opened in June
of last year in Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Blue Dog's A-list of patrons, beginning
with Bill and Hillary Clinton. Jane Fonda also owns Blue Dog art.
Whoopi Goldberg has six of the cerulean creatures and wants to base
a TV series on the mysterious canine. Stroll through the homes of
TV anchorman Tom Brokaw or jazz entertainer Harry Connick Jr., and
several Blue Dog works will all but bark at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Dog is a character, not a cartoon like Snoopy,''
Rodrigue cautions. ``It's a pure pop art image that, unlike Andy
Warhol's art, which was made from established labels, I've created
on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, yet no pop image can officially take its place
alongside such famously faddish logos as the yellow smiley face
until a corporation makes it part of an ad campaign. For Rodrigue,
that happened when the Xerox corporation created a $200 million,
five-year campaign requiring 30 renditions of the Blue Dog for the
corporation's print and TV ads. NBC's current Olympics broadcast
features one spot in which the Blue Dog pitches Xerox's latest
``new breed'' of color printer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These commercials are just another type of painting for me, a
way to get the image to people for free,'' says Rodrigue, who
allows only that he will ``get a lot'' financially in the Xerox
deal.
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, Rodrigue's Blue Dog fame brought him to North
Texas, as Neiman Marcus invited him to be its guest at the annual
Cattle Baron's Ball. There, Rodrigue presided over the charity
auctioning of one of the three painted cows he made for Chicago's
``cows on parade'' street exhibit. One of the cows, covered in his
Blue Dog motif, reaped $25,000 at the ball's auction.
</P>
<P>
   The object of all this feverish spending is a disarming little
creature with a cobalt-blue coat and a downy white snout. The
sources of its mass appeal must be in its completely placid pose,
and its yellow eyes that seem to hypnotize a viewer even as they
project a Buddhalike empathy. It seems to be a furry oracle, a
feral fount of life's answers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one, starting with its creator, really understands the
root of its overwhelming success. ``I painted the dog as if it was
a person and a spirit,''
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue says. ``He is looking on behalf of mankind. I mean,
I've seen people cry in front of it, love it, cherish it and just
connect with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding the wave of his current commercial appeal, Rodrigue
doesn't seem defensive about the possible co-opting of his artistic
creativity by the bottom-line world of corporate marketing. ``In
pop art, there is no longer a real hard line between art and
promotion or advertising,'' Rodrigue says. ``The public already
interacts every day with pop art images from Exxon or Coca-Cola, so
really, it is just about how you reach the public with your
product, and art is my product.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, for all Rodrigue's acceptance of the commercial
requirements of being a pop artist, he holds on tightly to the
creative reins of his Blue Dog creation. Indeed, before Xerox
approached Rodrigue, he had turned down dozens of other
corporations because he would have lost creative control of his
Blue Dog image. He has also rejected those who want his dog to
decorate T-shirts and key rings, although he will produce, at least
according to his own Web site, Blue Dog notecards and a desk
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to sell my Blue Dog in some open-ended deal the
way Snoopy was sold to Met Life,'' Rodrigue says.
</P>
<P>
   Just how closely Rodrigue plans on clutching his Blue Dog idea
will be seen in next year's Xerox print ads, in which Rodrigue
tentatively plans to paint all the elements (images of the Xerox
printers, the ad text) along with his signature Blue Dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Dog is of today, and whether it lasts or not, history
will tell us,'' Rodrigue says. ``The first test, though, was to
break away and get out of the pack. The public already made that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
amarton(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
