<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BELGIAN-RECIPES2     09-27 4163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BELGIAN-RECIPES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A feast for eyes, nose and mouth
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth Van Waerebeek puts the Belgian love of food like this: ``We
are a country of 10 million people and 5 million cafes.'' At those
cafes (and in their home kitchens), Belgians love to feast on
mussels and fries, divine chocolate and specialty beers.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian native Philippe Haddad, chef/owner of Philippe's a
Bistro in Peachtree Hills, remembers his parents' dinner parties
featuring exquisite charcuterie, sauerkraut made with champagne and
cabbage pickled at home. ``It was a feast for your eyes and your
nose and then your mouth,'' said Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we offer a few representative dishes that are easy to
prepare and guaranteed to open the door on a whole new cuisine that
many of us have not experienced in depth before.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, start with the mussels, which have become far
easier to find in grocery stores (though to be sure you still may
want to order ahead). Keep in mind that mussels are still alive
when you purchase them. So don't keep them in an airtight bag. Do
keep them in chilled ice water until ready to cook. Add a pinch or
two of cornmeal to the water to aid in cleaning. Use a sharp knife
to scrape off the beards. If a mussel opens during cleaning, tap it
lightly; it should close again. If it doesn't, it's dead and should
be discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking mussels couldn't be easier. Those of you with home deep
fryers will have no excuse for not trying the traditional frites.
(Fried potato lovers may want to invest in a fryer.) The beef and
beer stew is simple and absolutely ideal for the cool weather
ahead. And chocoholics won't want to miss the Belgian ganache tart.
Be sure to pick up some Belgian beers to enjoy with this cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Steamed Mussels With Beer and Curry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, mussels are often served family style; the steaming
pot is brought to the table along with a big empty bowl (or the lid
of the pot) for discarded shells. This version gets its sunny
yellow sauce from the curry. Be sure to have plenty of bread on
hand for dipping. The sauce is divine.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 finely minced garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds mussels, thoroughly cleaned and bearded
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Hoegaarden, Leffe Blonde or other blond beer
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely minced chives
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a pot large enough to hold all the mussels. A
large stock/soup pot will work; so will a large saute pan. You'll
need a lid. Add the shallots, garlic and curry powder and saute for
about 3 minutes. Add the mussels and sprinkle with a generous
grinding of black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the beer and the cream over the mussels and cover the pot
tightly. Steam the mussels over high heat for 3 to 4 minutes, until
they open. Take pot off heat and shake vigorously to toss the
mussels with the buttery shallots and garlic. Garnish with parsley
and chives. Serve at once. _ From: Ruth Van Waerebeek, Cook's
Warehouse class.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 320 calories, 12 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 77), 7 grams carbohydrates, 112
milligrams cholesterol, 308 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Philippe's Belgian-Style Mussels
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-course servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 13-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic Belgian-style mussel dish that Philippe Haddad
serves at his bistro in Peachtree Hills. If you want to serve it as
an appetizer, simply steam fewer mussels, but you'll probably want
to keep the amounts the same for the rest of the recipe. That way,
you'll have plenty of sauce for dipping bread into. Serve with
fries and Belgian beer for a complete and classic Belgian meal.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mussels, bearded and cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Hoegaarden or other blond beer
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced herbs (such as parsley, tarragon, chervil)
</P>
<P>
   2 Roma tomatoes, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium Dutch oven over medium-high heat, melt the butter.
When hot, add the celery, shallots and garlic and stir briefly.
Cover and cook, stirring frequently, until vegetables are
translucent, about 5 minutes. Add the mussels to the pot, cover
again and cook for 5 to 6 minutes. Add the beer, cream (if using)
and minced herbs. Shake the pot to evenly distribute the mussels,
liquid and herbs. Cook for a few more minutes, until all the
mussels have opened. Transfer to deep serving bowls; sprinkle with
the tomatoes, chives, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with cream): 272 calories, 20 grams protein, 15
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 50),14 grams carbohydrates,
80 milligrams cholesterol, 481 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pommes Frites
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: 15 minutes to overnight
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Resting time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 6-8 minutes per batch (total)
</P>
<P>
   Shaun Doty, chef at Mumbo Jumbo, and his assistant Jeremy Fox
have both trained in Belgian restaurants and mastered the art of
pommes frites. The key is to fry the potatoes twice (russet
potatoes work best). Use a home deep fryer rather than a pot, which
can be dangerous (grease pops out) and difficult to get even heat
in. And work in small batches; too many fries at once will bring
down the temperature of the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a step-by-step recipe. Master it and you'll understand
why the Belgians love to have frites with just about everything.
Serve with homemade mayonnaise for the authentic experience. They
are unbelievable with bearnaise sauce. And, of course, the American
standby, ketchup, is also good.
</P>
<P>
   6 large russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Peanut oil or canola oil, enough to fill a home fryer to
manufacturer's specifications (some call for as much as 2 quarts
oil)
</P>
<P>
   Salt (and pepper or other seasonings, if desired)
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut them in half lengthwise. Put the flat
side of each potato half on a cutting board and cut lengthwise into
1/4- to 1/2-inch wedges. Soak the cut potatoes in a bowl of water
for 15 minutes to overnight (this rinses off the exterior starches
so the fries won't stick to each other).
</P>
<P>
   Add oil to the deep fryer and heat to 300 degrees. Remove the
fries from the water and thoroughly pat dry with a kitchen towel.
In small batches, fry the potatoes for about 3-4 minutes. The fries
should still be fairly white and al dente (soft on the outside but
still firm in the center). Drain and place in single layers on dry
kitchen towels. Allow to rest for at least 15 minutes. (You can do
this step in the morning, cover and allow to rest until evening if
desired.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in the deep fryer to 375 degrees. Again in small
batches, fry the potatoes for another 3-4 minutes, until the fries
are golden brown. Remove and season immediately with salt and other
preferred seasonings such as pepper, paprika, cayenne, garlic salt
and chopped parsley. Serve with dipping sauces (mayonnaise is the
classic Belgian choice).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 241 calories, 3 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 34 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 7 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Salad With Roquefort Toast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1-2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for apple season, this salad is simple and elegant
_ a fine example of Belgian cuisine. The bitter endive is mellowed
by the sweet vinaigrette. The salty cheese toast pairs nicely with
the apple wedges. To toast walnuts, spread in a single layer on a
baking sheet and bake in a 400-degree oven until they begin to
brown, 7-9 minutes. You'll have plenty of vinaigrette left over;
store tightly covered in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   For the vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup walnut oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup corn oil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raspberry or cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   For the Roquefort Toast:
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Roquefort or other blue cheese, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter, room
</P>
<P>
   temperature
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 slices firm white bread, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   (optional)
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups Boston lettuce, red-leaf lettuce, radicchio and/or
watercress leaves, rinsed, dried and torn into bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 Belgian endives, cored and leaves separated
</P>
<P>
   1 tart green or red apple, unpeeled, halved, cored and thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup walnuts, lightly toasted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. To make the vinaigrette, whisk together the
walnut oil, corn oil, vinegar, salt and pepper and set aside. Next,
cream together the cheese and the butter with a fork or on the low
setting of a mixer. Spread the mixture on the toasted bread and
broil until the cheese has completely melted and becomes bubbly,
1-2 minutes. Sprinkle with the chives, if using. Cut each toast
diagonally into 4 triangles.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad, spread the mixed leaves on a big platter. Arrange
the endive leaves, alternating with the apple slices, on top of the
lettuce leaves. Sprinkle with walnuts and shallot. Just before
serving, drizzle 1-2 tablespoons of the vinaigrette over the salad.
Arrange the warm Roquefort Toast triangles on the salad. Serve
remaining vinaigrette on the side (and refrigerate leftover
vinaigrette in a tightly closed container for up to 1 week). _
From:
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Eats Well in Belgium Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with 1 tablespoon vinaigrette): 330 calories, 7
grams protein, 27 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 74), 17
grams carbohydrates, 34 milligrams cholesterol, 375 milligrams
sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Breast With Brussels
</P>
<P>
   Sprouts-Potato Ragout
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Brussels sprouts are one of those vegetables that divide _
either folks love them or hate them. I used to be in the ``hate
them'' camp until I began to experience them fresh and lightly
cooked. Philippe Haddad serves grilled chicken over the sprouts and
potatoes in this hearty dish that's popular at his bistro _ it
makes for an ideal fall meal. The bacon really adds extra flavor.
Applewood bacon can be found at eatZi's in Buckhead. You can
substitute another smoked bacon if you prefer. Haddad uses a
bone-in breast; we adapted the recipe to boneless chicken breast.
If you prefer bone-in, increase cooking time to ensure the chicken
is thoroughly cooked.
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves, free range
preferred, about 6 to 8 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh thyme leaves, chopped, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh rosemary leaves
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 slices applewood-smoked bacon, sliced
</P>
<P>
   crosswise into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 Idaho potatoes (about 1 1/2 pounds total), peeled, cut into
3/4-inch dice, blanched
</P>
<P>
   for 3 to 4 minutes, and drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brussels sprouts (about 8 to 10 medium), blanched for 2 to
3 minutes, drained well, and halved
</P>
<P>
   Pinch freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark Belgian beer
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Trim all excess fat from chicken breasts, brush with 1
tablespoon of the olive oil, sprinkle with 1 tablespoon of the
thyme, the rosemary and black pepper to taste. Heat a large cast
iron skillet or grill pan over medium-high heat and brush with a
little of the olive oil. Place the chicken breasts in the pan, skin
side down, and cook for 5 to 6 minutes or until golden on that
side. Turn and continue cooking until just cooked through and
browned on the second side. (You can use a charcoal or gas grill if
preferred.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat.
Add the remaining olive oil, the bacon strips and shallots. Cook,
stirring constantly, until browned, about 5 minutes. Add the
potatoes and cook, stirring frequently, for 2 to 3 minutes. Add the
brussels sprouts and nutmeg, and continue to cook until browned.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When chicken is done, remove to a plate and set aside. Add the
beer to the pan you cooked the chicken in to deglaze it. Boil
briefly, adding the remaining thyme, and season with salt and
pepper to taste. Slice the breasts on the diagonal, and serve at
once on top of a mound of the potato-brussels sprout mixture. Pour
a little of the sauce on top of each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 491 calories, 43 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 31 grams carbohydrates, 110
milligrams cholesterol, 279 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Leeks Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 20-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Leeks are hugely popular in Belgium and are prepared a number of
ways _ braised, steamed and broiled. It's quite lovely. This recipe
comes from ``Belgo Cookbook'' by Denis Blais and Andre Plisnier
(Clarkson Potter, $25). Belgo is a trendy restaurant in London and
New York that features Belgian cuisine and waiters dressed as monks
(paying homage to the beer-brewing tradition of Belgian monks).
</P>
<P>
   Try to find slender leeks if possible; if not, split thicker
ones lengthwise for a nicer presentation. Look for leeks that have
a longer white section compared to the green. That will make them
easier to wash well and still be able to cook whole.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds leeks, about 8 medium
</P>
<P>
   Water for cooking leeks
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon finely chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   Good pinch fresh thyme leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Peel off the outer leaves of the leeks, and trim the root ends
and green tops so that they are all the same size. Wash them well.
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large skillet or saute pan with water, add 1 teaspoon
salt and bring to a boil over high heat. Add the leeks and cook
until they are tender right through when tested with the point of a
knife _ this will take about 20 minutes, depending on size. (Twenty
minutes was about right for leeks that were about 3/4 inch in
diameter.) Remove the leeks from the pan, refresh under cold
running water, then gently squeeze them dry. Place in the
refrigerator and chill until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare the vinaigrette: In a small mixing bowl,
combine the mustard, garlic, shallots, thyme, vinegar, salt and
pepper. Slowly add the oils, whisking constantly. When ready to
serve, remove the leeks from the refrigerator, pour the vinaigrette
over them and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 209 calories, 3 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 24 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 41 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Carbonades Flamandes
</P>
<P>
   (Flemish Beef Stew)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 hours, 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Put this on the menu for fall and winter. It's easy and robust.
This stew has long been a part of the culinary heritage of Belgium,
and every cook has his version of it, passing along the secrets to
the next generation. This is best made a day ahead, and the success
depends on the quality of beer. Look for a rich, dark and slightly
bitter beer, like Rodenbach, a dark Abbey beer or Leffe Dark. This
is another dish that Belgians eat with fries.
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds boneless stew meat (beef), such as chuck, cut into
2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions (about 2 pounds), thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 bottles (12 ounces each) of dark beer,
</P>
<P>
   preferably Belgian
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 sprigs fresh thyme or 1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons red currant jelly (or brown sugar)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cider or red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Season the beef cubes with the salt and pepper and dredge with
the flour. Shake off any excess. Melt 2 tablespoons of the butter
in a large heavy skillet over high heat until hot but not smoking.
Add the beef cubes and saute until nicely browned on all sides.
Work in batches so as not to crowd the beef cubes or they will
steam instead of saute. Add 1 tablespoon of butter, if necessary.
Transfer the beef cubes to a heavy Dutch oven.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 1 tablespoon butter to the skillet and melt
over medium heat. Add the onions and cook, stirring occasionally,
until browned, about 15 minutes. If necessary, raise the heat
toward the end of the cooking time. It is important to brown the
meat and the onions evenly to give the stew its deep brown color.
Stir the onions just enough to avoid burning them but not so often
as to interrupt the browning. Put the onions in the Dutch oven with
the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the beer into the skillet and deglaze, scraping with a
wooden spoon to loosen any brown bits and bring to a boil. Pour the
beer over the meat. Add the thyme and bay leaves. Simmer, covered,
over low heat until the meat is very tender, 1 1/2 to 2 hours. Just
before serving, stir in the red currant jelly or brown sugar and
the vinegar; simmer for 5 minutes. (Do not skip this step. It gives
the stew great depth of flavor.) Taste, adjust seasonings and serve
(or allow to come to room temperature, and then store in an
airtight container in the refrigerator for a day, reheat and
serve.) _ From: ``Everybody Eats Well in Belgium Cookbook'' by Ruth
Van Waerebeek (Workman, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 572 calories, 67 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 14 grams carbohydrates, 221
milligrams cholesterol, 485 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Chocolate Ganache Tart
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 27-33 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes for crust
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 4 1/2 hours or more, divided
</P>
<P>
   This is a serious tart for chocolate lovers, ideal when made
with a Belgian chocolate such as Callebaut. But Callebaut can be
hard to find in Atlanta. We did find some online sources _
www.chocolatesource.com and www
</P>
<P>
   .gourmetmarket.com. If you don't want to order the chocolate,
choose another high-quality chocolate such as Valrhona or Scharffen
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe Basic Flemish Pie Crust (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces best-quality bittersweet chocolate, chopped into small
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon espresso powder (or 2 tablespoons instant regular
coffee)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup confectioners' sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk, mixed with 1 tablespoon water for egg wash
</P>
<P>
   Unsweetened cocoa powder for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream, whipped to soft peaks for serving, optional
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter a 9-inch tart pan with a removable bottom.
Roll out the pie crust dough on a lightly floured surface into a
circle slightly less than 1/4 inch thick. Line the tart pan with
the dough, trim the edges and prick the bottom evenly with a fork.
Refrigerate for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line the bottom of the tart pan
with aluminum foil. Fill 2/3 full with dry rice or beans or pie
weights. Place in the oven and bake 10 minutes. Reduce heat to 375
degrees and continue baking until the pastry is lightly browned,
another 5 to 8 minutes. Remove the foil and pie weights and let the
crust cool completely on a wire rack. Leave the oven on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare the chocolate filling: Place the chocolate
pieces in a mixing bowl. In a medium saucepan over medium-high
heat, combine the cream, espresso powder and confectioners' sugar.
Bring to a rolling boil. Immediately pour this hot cream mixture
over the chopped chocolate and stir with a wooden spoon until the
chocolate is melted and smooth. Beat in the eggs and egg yolks, one
at a time, until thoroughly combined.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the bottom and sides of the pastry with the egg wash. Pour
in the chocolate ganache and bake in the preheated 375 degree oven
until set, about 12 to 15 minutes. Transfer to a wire rack to cool.
When cool enough to handle, remove the side of the pan and let cool
completely. Chill in the refrigerator for 4 or more hours before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Use a fine sieve to sprinkle the cocoa powder evenly
over the surface of the tart, place a doily on top of the cocoa,
and sift a layer of confectioners' sugar on top. Very carefully
remove the doily. You will have a very pretty decorative pattern.
Or simply serve the tart cold with a bowl of freshly whipped cream.
_ From: ``Everybody Eats Well in Belgium Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 497 calories, 8 grams protein, 36 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 65), 37 grams carbohydrates, 210
milligrams cholesterol, 156 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Basic Flemish Pie Crust
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 crust
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: at least 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 to 18 minutes (for unfilled crust)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, chilled and cut into small
cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup ice-cold water
</P>
<P>
   Measure the flour into the bowl of a food processor and pulse on
and off for a few seconds. Add the butter, egg and salt and pulse
the machine on and off a few times until the mixture has a very
coarse texture and the pieces of butter are about the size of small
peas. With the motor running, add the water through the feed tube a
little at a time, until the dough just begins to hold together. Do
not let the dough form into a ball or it will be overworked and
tough. Stop immediately. Scrape the dough from the processor and
shape into a thick disk. Wrap in plastic wrap and refrigerate at
least 1 hour before using. Roll out and use as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 177 calories, 3 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 18 grams carbohydrates, 46
milligrams cholesterol, 124 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Waffles
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10-12 waffles
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Resting time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3 to 5 minutes per waffle
</P>
<P>
   Waffles are usually the first thing that comes to mind with the
prompt ``Belgian food.'' Yeast is what sets Belgian waffles apart.
The waffles are light, buttery and have just the right amount of
sweetness. They would be great topped with ice cream and chocolate
sauce for dessert. You do need a Belgian waffle iron, with the deep
holes and extra height, to make these work.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe calls for leaving the batter on the countertop
overnight. While most food and bread experts say the ages-old
practice is safe because the batter will be fully cooked and any
harmful bacteria destroyed, federal food safety advice is to
refrigerate it. If you are concerned about any health risk,
refrigerate after two hours' fermentation.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the flour, sugar, salt and yeast and
blend well. Melt the butter and mix with milk. Using a whisk,
combine the milk mixture with the dry ingredients. Cover the bowl
with plastic wrap and let sit on the kitchen counter overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning lightly spray the waffle iron to prevent
sticking and preheat it. While the waffle iron is preheating,
separate the eggs and whisk the yolks into the batter. Put the egg
whites in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with a wire whisk.
Beat egg whites until they form soft peaks. Using a rubber spatula,
gently fold the egg whites into the batter. Do not overmix. The
batter might have streaks or be slightly lumpy. Pour 1/2 cup of
batter into each square section of the waffle iron, spread evenly.
Cook for 3 minutes or until golden brown (times may vary by waffle
iron). Repeat with remaining batter.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Lightly dust with confectioners' sugar. Top with fresh
berries, syrup, chocolate sauce or jam. _ From: Cuisine magazine
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 191 calories, 5 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 20 grams carbohydrates, 73
milligrams cholesterol, 257 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
