<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BELGIAN28-COX     09-27 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BELGIAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Belgian Way: At last, small country's cuisine is beginning
to make big inroads in America _ and the robust dishes go way
beyond waffles
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, a friend in New York nudged me toward a
restaurant in her Greenwich Village neighborhood. ``Belgian food,''
she said. ``Cafe de Bruxelles. You'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Waffles for dinner won't do, I protested. And I don't want
brussels sprouts, either, exhausting my knowledge of Belgian
cuisine in half a breath.
</P>
<P>
   She pushed me through the door into the cramped and casual cafe.
We sat down at a table topped with white butcher paper and cracked
open the menu.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't believe my eyes. A recent convert to mussels, I was
astounded at the choices. There were mussels in cream and herbs.
Mussels with tomatoes and garlic. Mussels with wine and shallots.
Mussels steamed in beer. Mussels at least a dozen different ways.
There was the promise of plenty of bread to sop with, and (here's
where I really fell in love) there were the traditional pommes
frites on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The uninformed (as I was) would refer to pommes frites as french
fries. The Belgians will hear nothing of it. So what if France,
Spain and England all lay claim to frites; Belgians believe they
are the original potato-frying nation. To back this claim, they've
perfected the twice-fried-to-a-crisp technique and serve them in
paper cones or cups with an array of sauces for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the only proper partner for the classic Belgian
bistro fare of mussels and fries is Belgian beer, which is taken as
seriously as wine is in France.
</P>
<P>
   If your knowledge of Belgian cuisine is as limited as mine was,
don't fret. The Belgians are coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, Cafe de Bruxelles has been joined by
nearly a dozen Belgian restaurants in New York, from trendy
chain-concept Belgo to farmhouselike Le Pain Quotidien. Why, right
there at Times Square is B. Frites, a fast-food outlet that often
has a line out the door. It serves only Belgian fries and dipping
sauces (the classic is homemade mayo).
</P>
<P>
   And, this month, the city so hard to impress practically gushed
over Belgium's Crown Prince Philippe and Princess Mathilde when
they visited the Big Apple. The New York Times referred to the
couple as ``the fabulously cool new royals'' (compared to the
stodgy old British ones) and noted the ``effusion of Belgianoph
eateries'' and the ``explosion of interest in Belgian beers,
chocolates and double-fried potatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Atlanta, Belgian-born chef Philippe Haddad opened a
bistro in Peachtree Hills this year featuring many classic Belgian
dishes such as braised rabbit and waterzooi (a seafood stew).
Belgian-trained Shaun Doty, chef at Mumbo Jumbo, includes some
classic Belgian bistro cuisine on his menu, including pommes
frites. Belgian beers like Hoegaarden and Stella Artois are flowing
more than ever from bars around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belgian cuisine is one of the last of the Western European
cuisines to make a presence in the U.S.,'' said Milford Pruitt, a
writer for Nation's Restaurant News who has tracked the trend.
</P>
<P>
   While New York has been the epicenter, Belgian eateries are
popping up in other cities such as Washington and Philadelphia. And
Belgo, which began in London, is eyeing expansion to other U.S.
cities beyond New York.
</P>
<P>
   Better not to wait for a Belgian bistro to pop up on your
corner, though.
</P>
<P>
   This food, which Haddad described as ``close to French, but not
as artsy,'' is easy to make at home and worth the (fairly minimal)
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use just a few ingredients, but we do everything right,''
said Ruth Van Waerebeek, author of ``Everybody Eats Well in Belgium
Cookbook'' (Workman, $15.95), who recently taught a cooking class
on Belgian cuisine at Cook's Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Waerebeek explained that Belgians rely on heirloom recipes that
seek to balance bitter and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The native Belgian endive, for example, is often braised and
then finished with a powdering of confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet scallops might be splashed with a spicy and bitter aged
beer. Carbonades Flamandes, or beef stewed in (what else?) beer, is
given a splash of vinegar after a couple of hours of slow cooking.
</P>
<P>
   We offer a primer on Belgian classics, including one of Haddad's
mussel recipes, Doty's step-by-step pommes frites, Waerebeeks' beef
stew and a Belgian chocolate ganache tart that begs for pairing
with a little Kriek, the Belgian cherry-flavored ale that's often
served as an after-dinner drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most amazing food,'' said Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   ``So simple and so tasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
