<HEADER>
A3666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE28-COX     09-27 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the mountains, nature stages its own light show
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Light is like any other valuable; the less
there is of it, the more it's worth. Trying to enjoy every particle
as days grow shorter, I want light to wash over me, cleanse me of
sticky summer, show me fresh views of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   So, on some days I become my father when he was an old man,
going to bed with nightfall, rising early, getting to the garden as
often as I can, staying as long as light lasts _ and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic that there's less light just when lower temperatures
make being outside more bearable. Here on my ridge, light arrives
like a slow-moving train; it is not until 9 or 10 o'clock that we
see and feel it fully, hours after it shows itself from afar,
lighting up the top of the ridge across Fightingtown Creek.
</P>
<P>
   While light here still is relatively free of man-made haze, some
mornings do block it with rolling fog, lending a lovely surreality
to the landscape, showing trees and shrubs through a lens dimly
lit.
</P>
<P>
   But like so much of nature here, light operates in extremes.
Foggy early, yes, but later it rises above the thick forests of
pines, oaks, maples and shines, bright, hard-edged, on autumn's
garden, that space combining seasonal renewal and decline. This
light is unforgiving and uncompromising, exposing every crevice and
crinkle. At midday, it can be white hot, even in autumn. At the
same time, light is a garden feature in itself, fashioning plant
shadows into intriguing images. (Look over there _ a cloud-pruned
Japanese black pine that becomes a stick figure lying on the
ground.) And it provides as illuminating a look at individual
plants as you'll ever get.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I saw a treeful of deep-green magnolia leaves
glistening, shimmering in the light breeze, surrounding five white
blossoms still waiting to open. The light turned their thin petals
to satin. Satin, too, were the pink blooms of the hardy begonia,
complementing the hanging seed pods _ little brown lanterns lit by
the afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   At last, I have grown zinnias from seed, seed donated by several
zinnia gardeners who knew of my past failures. This year, those
pretty-petaled plants stand tall, glowing in the sunshine like
fringed balloons of many colors.
</P>
<P>
   Fuzzy mullein has to be touched, explored. How else can you know
how fine that hairy surface feels when sun streams across it?
</P>
<P>
   Mullein and other grays and whites _ and yellows _ always light
dark corners of the garden, but this time of year they seem to glow
brighter than ever. Leaves of dusty miller, blooms of lantana,
goldenrod absorb the light and give it back, magnified and
magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   Standing near each another, the purple-blooming rosemary and the
bloomed-out lavender compete for best of show in the gray-green
category. In lighting up their part of the garden, they give extra;
brushing and enjoying their fragrant leaves during a walk down the
path would be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The darker fennel shines too as light streaks through its lacy
form, turning that sweet plant into an elaborate spider web,
catching attention and admiration for hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   As always, there is decay in the garden, even amid light, which
is life itself.
</P>
<P>
   When you get real close to joe-pye weed this time of year, you
notice that its pinkish-purplish flowers have started to come
undone, showing fuzzy white at their unraveling tips. And the last
cherry tomatoes glow lonely, looking so much like the Jerusalem
cherry fruit soon to shrivel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the leaves of gold and red and yellow, drifting
through autumn light, represent decay too, but what glorious decay.
Divine decadence, really. Remnants from lives of spring and summer.
Remnants of lives lived well.
</P>
<P>
   How satisfying that they, and we, see the light.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
