<HEADER>
A3667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     09-27 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shopping Destination: Cashiers, N.C.
 &HT;    A country crossroads that brims with flavor
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cashiers, N.C. _ Maybe it was the gray of the day, but somehow
cut flowers never looked more colorful and home-grown tomatoes
never redder than they did on a recent rainy Sunday morning at the
Cashiers Farmers Market.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drizzle, a steady stream of folks stopped in to
trade with owners Robin and Tom Crawford, who welcome regulars and
first-timers alike with small-town friendliness. The place is
packed with the region's bounty: fresh-from-the-farm produce,
apples from Hendersonville, breads from Annie's Naturally in Sylva,
sourwood honey from Cashiers, Morgan Mill grits and flour from
Brevard, coffee from Smoky Mountain Roasters in Clyde and the
market's private-label jams, jellies and relishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bit of European shopping,'' says Paul Sanger,
holding a plastic bag filled with ripe tomatoes. The landscape
contractor owns homes in Atlanta and Cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   Sanger says a trio of businesses are his favorite places in
Cashiers: the Farmers Market; the Chopping Block, where he buys
meat and seafood; and the Chattooga Nursery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the atmosphere that makes it special,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The Farmers Market is one of the few businesses open on Sunday,
but on Saturday the town at the intersection of U.S. 64 and N.C.
107 _ they call it the ``Crossroads'' _ is full of browsers and
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shop-lined ``downtown'' in Cashiers. Instead, most
of the businesses are clustered in mini-shopping centers such as
Cashiers Commons, Chestnut Square and Village Walk Fine Shops.
Antique shops are scattered around the area. Less than a half-mile
from the Crossroads on N.C. 107 is where you'll find Basketworks,
Rusticks and Vivianne Metzer Antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cashiers shops are outposts of stores in nearby Highlands.
One is Southern Hands, which carries fine crafts from North
Carolina artists, such as woodturner Donald Krebs of Scaly Mountain
and Lee Davis of Brasstown, as well as other Southern artists. But
the store also has an area exclusive on handmade hardwood
reproduction Shaker furniture by Douglas Dines of Pennsylvania.
Another sister store is Bird Barn, which has everything for birds
and bird lovers, gardens and gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   Cottage Walk, one of the few shops open Sundays, is a treasure
chest of antique and reproduction furniture, lamps and interesting
accessories. Of particular interest are trunklike Austrian wedding
boxes from the 1880s used to hold a bride's dowry. ``Some have the
original locks and paints, and all have lots of history,'' says
employee Dan Allen. Prices range from $500 to $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to drive on N.C. 107 south to check out Basketworks,
where the eclectic array of merchandise displayed in room vignettes
includes some rare 17th- and 18th-century Chinese figures. Nearby
is Rusticks, which has everything to decorate a mountain home in a
style that blends rustic with elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Before you set out for the stores, pick up a shopping guide at
the Cashiers Area Chamber of Commerce on N.C. 107 north, next to
the Laurelwood Mountain Inn. Think of it as a road map to retail
nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   The map also shows the Cashiers Walking Trail, which loops
through the main shopping area.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be surprised if you run into someone you know. As Bird
Barn employee Janice Bryson says: ``Most of Atlanta is up here.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From downtown Atlanta, take I-85 to I-985 and
stay on Ga. 365/U.S. 23 to U.S. 441 at Cornelia. North of Dillard
look for signs for Highlands and follow N.C. 106. In Highlands, go
west on U.S. 64 to Cashiers, which is at the intersection of N.C.
107.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays; a
few shops are open Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Spaces are provided outside businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: At the Cashiers Area Chamber of Commerce, N.C. 107
south (at the Crossroads). Also, restaurants and the Exxon station
offer facilities for customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Some steps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 828-743-5191 (Chamber of Commerce).
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wild Thyme Gourmet Continental Cafe: If the urge to get a bite
strikes while you're browsing the shops of Village Walk, head
straight to Wild Thyme for sandwiches, soup, salads and
from-scratch baked goods. Two excellent choices are Curry Chicken
Salad ($6.95) and the Turkey, Brie and Avocado Wrap ($7.50). N.C.
107 south. 11:30 a.m.-3 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays. 828-743-1065.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cornucopia: Near Basketworks, the Book &AMP; Specialty Shop and
Rusticks, this wonderful little restaurant is housed in the
second-oldest building in Cashiers Valley, built in 1892. Lunch
entrees include the Fifth Generation Meatless Sandwich, with
spinach, cream Havarti and avocado ($6.95); Chicken Mandarin
Spinach Salad ($7.95); Bengal Curry Chicken Salad ($8.49, served in
a melon half); and Crab Cakes ($10.95). Leave room for homemade
desserts _ we went for the vanilla buttermilk pie ($3) and the
fresh blackberry cobbler a la mode ($3.50). 11 a.m.-2:30 p.m.
daily; 6-9 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays. N.C. 107 south. 828-743-3750.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Laurelwood Mountain Inn: You can't beat the location of this
rustic mom-and-pop-style motel and log cabin suites. It's a half
block north of the Crossroads and walking distance from most shops
and restaurants. There's a large deck with rockers, and the wooded
grounds are beautifully groomed. On the 1 1/2 acres are a
children's playground, gazebo, picnic table and grill. Owners Bob
and Lise Dewes live on site and can help you plan tennis and golf
outings, skiing, horseback riding, drives to the area's many scenic
waterfalls _ or whatever you want to do.
</P>
<P>
   $67-$135. 1-800-346-6846; www.laurelmountaininn.com
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   At least nine waterfalls _ including Whitewater Falls, which at
411 feet is the highest falls in Eastern America _ are within a
30-miles radius of Cashiers. For more information, see the Jackson
County Chamber of Commerce tourism site at www.nc-mountains.com and
click on waterfalls. Or call 1-800-962-1911. Also, see
www.franklin-chamber.com/waterfal.html.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
