<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find itemsBy Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and a daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please advise where I can find Andrea's Eye Q's Undereye
Circle Complex. I have searched in pharmacies in my area and could
not find it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dorothy Aenlle, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another Andrea query: For years I've used Andrea's Eye
Makeup Remover Pads, but recently I have not been able to find
them. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Miller, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: The eyes have it. Andrea's Eye Q's Undereye Circle Complex
($6.49 for a .5-ounce tube) is available at most Ulta stores. We
found ours at the 2059 Scenic Highway location in Snellville
(770-979-7151). The manufacturer says this treatment, which
contains vitamin K, diminishes undereye circles. The other Andrea
item, Eye Make-Up Remover Pads Original Formula, is available at
Eckerd Drugs, 2325 Pleasant Hill Road, Duluth (770-497-4425). A jar
of 65 pads is $4.49. These pads condition the eye area while gently
removing all traces of shadow color, liner pencil and mascara.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At an auction, I purchased an item containing a gift
certificate for a pound of See's Candies. I've never seen one of
their stores here. I'm originally from out West and consider See's
Candies a rare treat. Can you help me locate a store where I can
redeem the certificate?
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Mascheck, Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: See what we found for you. Since 1921, the California-based
See's Candies has been making yummy confections. Today, See's, now
owned by Berkshire Hathaway, makes more than 100 varieties of
candies including chocolates, toffee, peanut brittle and lollipops.
The company does not have any shops in Georgia; however, for the
holiday season, it will open four gift centers that will sell
prepackaged candies and that will accept your gift certificate. The
openings and locations are: Nov. 11, Perimeter Mall and Mall of
Georgia; Nov. 16, North Point Mall in Alpharetta and Town Center at
Cobb. Shops will close Dec. 29. You can also order See's Candies at
www.sees.com or by calling 1-800-347-7337.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For years, I have been trying to locate ``Lindsay's Tea _
Royal Fireside.'' The container claims that the ``tea is full of
excitement.'' It also says to ``live dangerously and invite someone
you'd like to know better to tea.'' Please help me locate this
wildly delicious ambrosia!
</P>
<P>
   _ Midge Kennedy, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another tea request: I am trying to find TenRen Hibiscus
Spice Tea, which I bought in a Chinese restaurant in Los Angeles.
Once brewed, the color is red. I would love to buy more of this
wonderful tea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robin Patterson, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's tea for the two of you. Both San Francisco-based
companies offer a variety of teas steeped in tradition. Lindsay's
Teas has been family-owned for four generations by Mountanos Bros.
Coffee. The teas, which come from tea gardens around the world,
include black, green, oolong and white, as well as specialty teas.
Royal Fireside is a blend of China black tea, elderberries, orange
flowers and red sandalwood. A 4-ounce canister of loose tea is $9;
25 tea bags are $6.50. To order: 1-800-624-7031.
</P>
<P>
   TenRen has been a tea manufacturer in the Far East for more than
40 years. It exports a wide variety of teas including herbal,
green, black, white, oolong and King's tea, a blend of oolong and
ginseng. The tea is sold in California, Hawaii, Washington state,
Illinois, Texas, Maryland and New York. You can order Hibiscus
Spice, a blend of black tea and dried hibiscus flowers, through the
Internet (www.tenren.com) or by calling 1-877-898-0858. A box of 20
bags is $2.35; a box of 50 bags is $5.60.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been looking in every store for ``correction tabs'' to
be used on typing errors. You slip one into the typewriter, hit the
key where your error is, then retype with the correct letter or
number. The older I get, the more I need them. Help, please!
</P>
<P>
   _ Edna Ellingsen, Powder Springs, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: No more typos for you. We traced your item, officially called
Re-type Correction Film Tabs, to Artlite Office Supplies &AMP; Pens,
1851 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-875-7271). A box of 30 is $1.59.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to replace my 30-year-old Kik-Step kitchen stool by
Cramer. You kick the stool, and it rolls on casters. There's no
bending or lifting for hard-to-reach items. So far, I can't locate
a store that carries this item.
</P>
<P>
   _ William J. Johns, Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We got a kick out of your request. The Kik-Step kitchen stool
was invented by Roy Cramer in the '50s and is still rolling right
along. Kick the 14-inch stool and it rolls on casters. Step on it
and it locks. Nonskid treads prevent slipping. With its wraparound
bumper, your walls and furniture are protected. The Kik-Step
($49.95) comes in a variety of colors. It's available on the
Internat (www.kikstep.com) or by calling 1-888-670-5049. You can
also order it through a Crate &AMP; Barrel catalog for $59.95:
1-800-323-5461.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
