<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Cities are nice, but livin's
easier in a small town
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was in Boston and New York City this past
week. I do love the big towns.
</P>
<P>
   Just being there seems to make me breathe easier. I think it's
anonymity, knowing that if I happen to stub my toe trying to step
up on a curb and pronounce a bad word, the incident will not be
reported later that day in the coffee shops.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's one of the good things about life in a small
town. It keeps you on your toes.
</P>
<P>
   This was a personal trip. My wife and I were visiting our middle
daughter Erin, her husband Jessie and our baby grandson Wesley who
live near Boston, in Worcester, where our son-in-law is a
geophysicist.
</P>
<P>
   (Try saying ``geophysicist'' three times fast. You'll sound like
a spitting cat.)
</P>
<P>
   Among his various titles, my favorite is Visiting Scientist at
M.I.T. If I were him, I'd put it on the side of my car.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember when the side of his car said Pizza Delivery.
That was when he was working his way through school toward a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   He also toiled as a roofer, which hereabouts is often considered
a more productive profession than Ph.D., assuming that doesn't
stand for Post Hole Digger.
</P>
<P>
   Please note, lest the above might indicate otherwise, my
son-in-law is no Yankee boy. He grew up right here in Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to guess, I'd say he is most likely the only Visiting
Scientist at M.I.T. with a portrait of Robert E. Lee hanging in his
den.
</P>
<P>
   Too, if my daughter would allow it, he'd fly the Confederate
battle flag from the front of the house just to shake up the
neighborhood. Geophysicists are that way.
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, I suggested he display the proud flag of the
Lone Star State of Texas. After all, we won our war.
</P>
<P>
   People in Massachusetts will tell you the same about their
set-to with the Redcoats. The Revolutionary War seems much on their
mind, the Shot Heard 'Round the World still ringing in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   We visited Lexington and Concord, beautiful towns in a wondrous
countryside. Amazing that they have all those woods and no log
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   I made it a point to pay my respects at the graves of Nathaniel
Hawthorne, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau and Louisa May
Alcott, all buried on Authors Ridge in the Concord cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped by Walden's Pond as well where Thoreau retreated to
nature to write and meditate and live alone in a cabin. Never mind
that his mother brought him a hot lunch every day.
</P>
<P>
   My son-in-law, genius that he is, drove us into New York City
and never missed a turn. We all stayed at the Plaza Hotel, my first
time there.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be embarrassed to tell you what the rooms cost. Suffice it
to say a bottle of Coca-Cola from the mini-bar was $5. And I'm
talking about a little Coke.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, I guess I do breathe easier in my own
hometown where four-bits will buy you the coldest Coke in town, and
that's the big bottle.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; web site, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
