<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUD     09-27 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Thursday, Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-FUNDS-BRITAIN (London) _ As London is seeing the greatest
cultural expansion in its history _ a $600 million millennium
effort funded in part by England's National Lottery and in part by
private donations _ a list of many of the largest donors reads like
a who's who of American philanthropists. New galleries and
courtyards, libraries, reading rooms and additions are being
christened with names like Annenberg and Sackler. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICS-NAUGHTY-WORDS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The publisher of the
Loeb Classical Library, the very proper series of Greek and Roman
literature for English-speaking readers, has been gradually putting
back the naughty bits it had been editing out of the books. By
Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Gore Vidal's ``The Golden Age,''
reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TALK (New York) _ Of the various newfangled epiphanies that
has smote book publishing lately, the most interesting is not the
future of the e-book or print-on-demand or on-line publishing.
Rather, it is that there is a large, and growing, citizenry of
black people who buy books and are greedy for reading material
relevant to them. By Martin Arnold.
</P>
