<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      09-27 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRESIDENTS ARE MAMAS' BOYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Any reporter who covers the White House soon learns
that presidents revere their mothers and rarely praise their
fathers or even speak of them.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be true in the future when so many modern fathers
are involved in hands-on parenting. But the stronger, sometimes
domineering, influence of mothers on sons who wound up in the White
House cannot be denied.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book ``First Mothers,'' veteran Time magazine
correspondent Bonnie Angelo tells the stories of the women who
shaped the lives of presidents, dating back to Franklin D.
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   The fathers of these men who rose to the pinnacle of political
power were often distant. They were formidable to their offspring
and too busy making a living for their usually large families to
mold their boys, Angelo explained.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these fathers were losers, and their famous sons _ such
as Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan _ were ashamed of them.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's depicted his father as a failure, both in business and
as a California citrus fruit grower. Reagan's dad was an alcoholic
who left an indelible memory on his son when he came home drunk on
Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   But their mothers stepped into the breach. Who can forget
Nixon's anguished cry, ``My mother was a saint,'' as he announced
his resignation from the presidency on Aug.9, 1974?
</P>
<P>
   No one doubted the firm hand of Sara Delano Roosevelt in guiding
_ or interfering in _ her son's life. She was the aristocratic
grand dame who said she had only wanted her son to grow up to be
``straight, honorable, just and kind, an outstanding American.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelo shows that the caring mothers were not just comforting to
their sons, they were also strong disciplinarians and tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Harry S Truman's mother, Martha, taught her son to be a
voracious reader of stories of heroic men and great events. Truman
said that by the time he was 14 years old he had read all the books
in the Independence (Mo.) public library ``and our big old Bible
three times through.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman knew his history and loved it. His historical knowledge
served him well in the presidency when he had to make the daring
decision to drop the atomic bomb on Hiroshima. He had been in World
War I and understood the value of rebuilding Europe in the
aftermath of World War II to stop the spread of communism.
</P>
<P>
   Truman and his mother were very close and she spent months at a
time in residence at the White House. Her devoted Harry went back
to Independence and stayed in the family home when his mother, then
in her 90s, was dying. When his top aides questioned his long stay
away from Washington, he said his mother had cared for him when he
was growing up and he wanted to do the same for her in her final
days. She died on July 26, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight D. Eisenhower's mother, Ida, came from the same stalwart
midwestern stock. She had six sons and ``Ike'' was the most
troublesome. Although orphaned and poor, she managed to go to
college and formed a strong personal commitment to education. She
provided the spark that ``inspired her sons to make something of
themselves,'' Angelo said.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, Eisenhower wrote that his mother ``was by far
the strongest influence on our lives.'' When his father died,
Eisenhower was commanding the allied troops in Europe in World War
II and couldn't go home for the funeral. He could only send a
telegram. Ike later said, ``My only regret is that it was always so
difficult to let him know the great depth of my affection for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Kennedy family, it has always been assumed that Joe
Kennedy, patriarch of the clan, ruled the roost and pushed his sons
into politics. He did that but Rose Kennedy was ``the one who was
there,'' Angelo wrote. President Kennedy said, ``Mother deserves
more credit than she gets. She read to us. She took us to Plymouth
Rock and Old North Church and other historic places. She gave me my
interest in history.'' Kennedy said his dad ``was not around
much.'' At the same time, Angelo said ``in all fairness, Joe did
his share of imparting the realities of life and politics to his
children.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rose Kennedy's maid told her: ``You've had the best of
everything, haven't you, Mrs. Kennedy?'' Angelo writes that Mrs.
Kennedy looked into the distance and replied softly, ``I've had the
best of everything and the worst of everythingthe agony and the
ecstasy, that's what my life's been like.''
</P>
<P>
   She had lost two sons by assassination and a son and daughter in
plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon B. Johnson used to tell us that his mother, Rebekah
Baines Johson, would shake his toes at dawn to wake him up and
would chide him that the other boys on the block had already been
up for an hour. She was a political liberal and believed that the
strong must take care of the weak. Her philosophy ``was the core of
the Great Society programs,'' Angelo said.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush also put his mother, Dorothy, on a
pedestal. Her philosophy was ``give the other guy credit. Don't
whine and complain. Count your blessings. Honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   On his first day in the Oval Office, Bush invited his mother to
sit next to him in the armchair, usually reserved for visiting
heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter's mother, ``Miss Lillian,'' and President
Clinton's mother, Virginia Kelley, were fun loving and irreverent.
They both lived to see their sons become president.
</P>
<P>
   We know every little boy _ and girl _ can grow up to be
president, but it helps to have a wise mother on his or her side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
