<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GLENN-MATH28-COX     09-27 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-MATH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANEL TELLS HOW TO IMPROVE MATH AND SCIENCE TEACHING
 &HT;    570&AMP;add. With GLENN-DATA.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation should spend more than $5 billion a year
to raise the ``unacceptable'' performance of the nation's
``scandalously underpaid'' math and science teachers to world
standards, a national commission reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to act now, before it's too late,'' said former Sen.
John Glenn, the ex-astronaut who chairs the National Commission on
the Teaching of Science and Math in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of the teaching force will turn over in the next 10
years,'' he said. ``That's frightening, but maybe we can look at it
also as an opportunity. If we can galvanize people into better
standards, into expecting more out of teachers, then the (higher)
pay will be looked at as fully deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel of business, education and government officials and
outstanding math and science teachers released its report, ``Before
It's Too Late,'' at the National Air and Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Patting the heat shield of Friendship 7, the 2,900-pound
spacecraft that carried him into orbit around the Earth 38 years
ago, Glenn said, ``I am glad that the math and science that went
into that were first-class stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, too few students learn as much about math and science
as is necessary to protect the nation's prestige, good jobs,
military security and competitive position in a global, networked
economy, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   It cited often-used statistics from the mid-1990s that show most
Americans emerge from high school with less knowledge of math and
science than most students their age in other nations, and
suggested widespread use of several remedies that have been tried
only on a limited scale.
</P>
<P>
   More recent statistics showed that many students in middle and
high schools, especially in big cities, study math or science under
teachers who neither majored in nor were certified to teach those
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Cures endorsed in the report included increasing paid,
on-the-job time for training and professional development during
the school year and summer for math and science teachers. It said
they also need more administrative support and better classroom
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To recruit and prepare new teachers, the commission called for
the creation of 15 new university-based math and science academies
offering one-year $30,000 stipends to 3,000 potential teachers, and
a Web site that would serve as a national portal to research-backed
tips on teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
   It said the federal government should expand programs that
forgive the student loans of math and science teachers who go to
underserved schools. Anticipating the report, the House hurriedly
passed such a measure Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations would cost $5 billion a year, the commission
said.
</P>
<P>
   About $4.5 billion of that would be split between the federal
government, which would pay two-thirds, and state and local
governments. That is a far cry from the current ratio, in which the
federal government pays only about seven cents out of every dollar
spent on kindergarten through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   The other $500 million would consist of rewards and incentives
by businesses to teachers and schools whose teachers excel in math
and science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the children's fault that they're deficient when they
come out of high school. It's the system that's broken and must be
fixed,'' said commission member Craig Barrett, president and CEO of
Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He and Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming, who were among the most
active members during the commission's year-long study, also
emphasized that the report linked rewards for teachers to
assessments of how much their students are learning.
</P>
<P>
   The report said, ``Schools with exemplary professional
development systems, and those that, most importantly, show
improvement on rigorous assessments of student achievement in
mathematics and science, must be recognized with monetary rewards
for their teachers and other staff, and through well-publicized,
showcase events.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of pay raises for teachers was not included in the
estimates. But the commission warned that many math and science
teachers are hired away by private firms that offer higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   The commission plans to mail copies to the estimated 135,000
school board members in the nation's more than 15,000 districts.
``We have lists with almost all of their addresses,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of reaching school board members too busy to read
beyond the three-page ``executive summary'' near the front of the
47-page report, the commission will also mail videotapes created
and donated by the Disney organization.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the report from the commission he created in July
1999, Education Secretary Richard Riley said that approval of
President Clinton's education budget by Congress ``would be a
strong down payment on the kind of investment called for by this
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a Democrat, and Geringer, a Republican, later said that
they thought the nonpartisan report provides the presidential
candidates with a framework for intelligent debate on math and
science teaching, rather than ammunition for either side.
</P>
<P>
   The free report is available by a toll-free call to
1-877-ED-PUBS or online at www.ed.gov/americacounts/glenn
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
