<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-TRACK-ART-2TA     09-27 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-TRACK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERCOMING FEAR OF LANE 1, TAYLOR HURDLES TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos OLY 8,9,10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ According to former Olympic track coach Mel
Rosen, there is only one good place to run a long sprint from lane
1 _ the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Earthbound athletes have to contend with tight curves and
centrifugal force and staggered starts. It is difficult even to see
all the runners in the seven outer lanes, much less to catch them.
When Angelo Taylor drew lane 1 for Wednesday night's 400-meter
hurdles race, he whistled to himself and wondered whether he had
any chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a spotty night for the Americans. Marion Jones
cruised through the second round of the 200 meters in 22.50 seconds
and qualified efficiently for Friday's long jump final, leaping 22
feet 3 inches on her only attempt. Chris Huffins also led the
decathlon after five events. But Gail Devers stopped during the
100-meter hurdle race, saying she had aggravated a hamstring
injury. And until the very last stride, it appeared that Taylor,
too, would find unfulfillment in the 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   He ran a smooth, patient race, though, making a ferocious charge
over the final three hurdles. At the tape he made a desperate lean
and won the gold medal in 47.50 seconds in a photo finish over Hadi
Souan Somayli of Saudi Arabia, who took second in 47.53 for his
country's first Olympic medal. Somayli had the lead out of the
final turn, but he leaned backward over the 10th hurdle and lost
some slight momentum, which was the difference between gold and
silver.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Taylor finish first in the dreaded lane 1, he set a
personal best. It was the fastest race ever won from the inner
lane. Still, the outcome was so close that Taylor did not realize
he had won. He dropped to his knees to pray, and it was only when
he heard his name declaring him the winner did he learn that he was
an Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be a tough race and I didn't know if
I was going to be able to do it,'' said Taylor, who is 21 and was
just out of high school in suburban Atlanta during the 1996 Summer
Games. ``This let me know I could run from any lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning from lane 1 would not be an obstacle, his friend,
Terrence Trammell, convinced Taylor before the race. They had been
high school teammates in Decatur, Ga., and Trammell had won a
silver medal in the 110-meter hurdles Monday night. ``Shock the
world from lane 1,'' Trammell shouted to Taylor by cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   It was not unprecedented to win a gold medal in the 400-meter
hurdles from the inside lane. At the 1972 Summer Games in Munich,
Germany, John Akii-Bua of Uganda set a world record in 47.82
seconds. Before Wednesday night's race, Taylor convinced himself
that there would be one huge advantage on the inside. He was the
fastest sprinter among the hurdlers, with a personal best of 44.89
seconds in the open 400. The others would not be able to see him
coming. When he accelerated out of the final curve, they would have
to begin chasing him just as their legs grew heavy with fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told myself to stay relaxed,'' Taylor said. ``Those
guys know I have the best speed. There was more pressure on them
than me.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   At DeKalb High School in suburban Atlanta, Taylor had learned to
run on a cement track. He tried to pattern himself after the
two-time Olympic champion Edwin Moses, who attended Morehouse
University in Atlanta. And when he attended one day of the Atlanta
Olympics, it was to watch Derrick Adkins win the 400-meter hurdles.
They later became training partners.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Taylor ran patiently on the tight curves,
measuring his speed to jump fluidly over each hurdle, taking 13
steps between the first eight hurdles, and 14 between the final two
as he made his charge, seeing Somayli out of the corner of his eye,
chasing him down with a final lean, winning by the thickness of his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always watched the Olympics and thought, ``That could be me
one day,'' Taylor said. ``My day is here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   If there was a more impressive performance, it came in the
women's 400-meter hurdles. Irina Privalova of Russia established
herself as one of the most versatile Olympians of all time, winning
in a personal best of 53.02 seconds, eight years after winning a
silver medal in the 100 meters at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would get a good result, but I never thought I
would win a gold medal,'' said the 31-year-old Privalova, who
defeated the 1996 champion Deon Hemmings of Jamaica. ``This medal
means more. I was younger and healthier before. This one took a lot
more effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also demonstrated her versatility as she continued her
quest to become the first female track and field athlete to win
five gold medals in one Olympics. Her attempt has been complicated
by the disclosure that her husband, the shot putter C.J. Hunter,
had tested positive for the steroid nandrolone. The track is her
one refuge from the turmoil and the suspicion that now attends her
own performances.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Jones took a sizeable lead then downshifted
across the finish line of the 200 heats. Then she needed only one
attempt in her most uncertain event to qualify for Friday's final
of the long jump. Only Heike Drechsler of Germany, the 1992 Olympic
champion, had a longer jump Wednesday night at 22-5 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, the last couple days have been really
difficult,'' Jones said. ``Right now, I have gold medals to win.''
She added: ``Once I stepped on the track, everything that had
happened the last couple days was in the back of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' chances of winning five gold medals seemed to grow more
precarious, however, when Devers pulled up in the 100-meter
hurdles. Devers is a two-time Olympic champion in the open 100
meters and was scheduled to run a leg of the 400-meter relay on
Saturday. Her status is now uncertain. Inger Miller has decided to
run the relay, her coach John Smith said, but she will not be fully
recovered from a hamstring injury that kept her out of the 100 and
200 sprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a challenge,'' Smith said of the American
relay. ``The Bahamas has four healthy girls. Jamaica has four
healthy girls. We don't. That's a problem. Four healthy girls will
outrun one.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in her Olympic career, Devers experienced a
bizarre conclusion to the 100 hurdles. At the 1992 Summer Games in
Barcelona, Spain, she led after nine hurdles, only to clip the
final hurdle with her lead foot. She stumbled across the finish
line, but four other hurdlers beat her to the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, she seemed to run smoothly over the first four
hurdles, only to stop before reaching the fifth hurdle. Devers has
suffered from chronic hamstring problems throughout her career,
complicated now by a bout of sciatica. The hamstring began to
tighten on her during the rounds of the hurdles, she said, adding
that she thought during the final she would ``go all out until the
leg fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hamstring began to clench, and would not loosen, and she
could not go on, she said. She dismissed any suggestion that she
felt jinxed in the 100 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think luck is involved in track,'' Devers said. ``It's
skills. This day, my skills were not enough to get me through this,
mentally or physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Had her leg not restricted her, Devers should have easily won
the race. Olga Shishigina of Kazakstan took the gold in 12.65
seconds. Devers has run eight races faster than that this season,
including 12.61 in the first round of the Olympics. Second place
went to Glory Alozie of Nigeria, who finished the Games in poignant
triumph after beginning it with the death of her fiance, Hyginus
Anugo, a sprinter who was hit and killed here by a bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would go home, but I was encouraged by my coach,''
Alozie said. ``I still feel what happened, but my friends, my coach
and my family helped make me feel happy again.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   Devers was not the only favorite to experience frustration
Wednesday night. Wilson Kipketer, the Kenyan who has become a
world-record holder as a Danish citizen, let the 800 meters unfold
too slowly and could not take the lead with his urgent kick at the
finish. Nils Schumann of Germany won in 1:45.08, while Kipketer was
second in 1:45.14, four seconds off his world record. It was the
slowest winning time in the 800 since the 1980 Moscow Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Dvorak of the Czech Republic, the world-record holder in
the decathlon, slumped to seventh after five events. Huffins stood
first with 4,554 points, although he struggles with the javelin and
1,500 meters on the second day. Sergei Bubka, the world-record
holder in the pole vault, continued his Olympic frustration in a
career that has been diminished by injury. He missed all three
attempts at 18-8 1/2 in Wednesday night's qualifying round. After
winning a gold medal in 1988, Bubka has reached the final only once
in the past three Games, failing on that occasion to clear any
height.
</P>
<P>
   Another drug scandal hit track and field Wednesday when Mihaela
Melinte of Romania, the gold-medal favorite in the women's hammer
throw, was told on the track before the qualifying round that she
had tested positive for nandrolone. Victories were also tempered by
the knowledge that Shishigina in the 100 hurdles and Elina Zvereva
of Belarus in the discus had previously served drug suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the suspicion in track and field that Devers was asked
whether she withdrew to avoid having to take a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't infer one thing from the next, and one person to the
next,'' Devers said. ``It's not fair. Me pulling up is an injury.
That wouldn't be a thought that would cross my mind. If people are
going to speculate, they are going to speculate. If that was my
concern, I wouldn't have started this Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
