<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY MEMORIES REMAIN OF FIERCE U.S.-RUSSIA BASKETBALL COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The game was over, and the aging Russian man
quickly made his way through the emptying stands and down to the
floor until he finally reached his old friend at courtside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Doug,'' Aleksandr Gomelsky said in charming, if
halting, English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Coach,'' Doug Collins replied, sounding like someone
whose high school teacher had caught up with him as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice to see you. How've you been?'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, OK. We talk later, yes?'' Gomelsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins and Gomelsky are links to a different era of U.S.-Russia
basketball, when meetings between the two countries meant so much
more than sports. On Thursday night, they will meet in an Olympic
quarterfinal, a game almost anyone can find a ticket to in Sydney
proper. Collins and Gomelsky, employed as television commentators
for their respective countries, agree that the Americans are simply
too skilled and strong for the Russians to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not like the old days,'' Gomelsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Not like 1988, when Gomelsky coached what would be the last
Olympic team from the Soviet Union to a gold medal in Seoul, South
Korea, defusing the press of John Thompson's American college
players, stunning the United States and doing his part to usher in
a new, potent era in international basketball: The U.S. of NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And not like 1972, when Collins, a stringy-haired collegian,
stepped to the foul line in the final seconds while Gomelsky, an
exiled national coach, watched from home. The Soviets won a
disputed 1-point victory over the United States in Munich after the
final three seconds were replayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night at halftime, they showed '72 up on the arena
screen,'' said Collins, the NBC analyst who hit two clutch free
throws for the United States and, along with his teammates, refused
the silver medal as a protest to the controversial ending. ``You're
always going to feel it at Olympic time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time I'll feel it most is when they hand out the medals.
And when the United States gets the gold and they play the national
anthem _ the thought of being up there with your teammates and
having that experience ... you know, something we should have had
was taken away from us. That's what gets me more than anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomelsky, whose visa and job were revoked for losing a
competition to Yugoslavia the previous year, did not attend the
Munich Games. But he watched with pride as the Soviets, employing
his system of screens and movement, finally stayed on the same
court with the great American athletes. He is astounded at how
wronged many Americans still feel over Munich.
</P>
<P>
   ``American people say it is not the right competition because
American boys don't take home a gold medal,'' he said. ``But
history is not always fair. I won the world championship in 1959 in
Chile. But my team got a disqualification because we didn't play
against Formosa. I won every game in Chile, two times United States
and two times Brazil. But history's champion is Brazil. Same in
Munich with the United States. See, history is not always fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, they call Gomelsky the Silver Fox. Whether the
nickname pertains to Gomelsky's personal or professional life is up
for conjecture. He turned 72 this year. Yet Gomelsky's fourth son _
his oldest is 46 _ turns 3 years old in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is 33 now,'' he said. Second wife? ``No, No. 3. Every
20 years, I change women.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomelsky, who lived in San Diego for a time in the 1990s, is now
president of Central Army, the Moscow basketball club that
routinely wins the Russian championship. His brother, Yevgeny,
coaches the Russian women's team. Gomelsky has attended 10
Olympics, beginning as an assistant with the Russian team in
Melbourne in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the '56 team,'' he said. ``Much better than this
team. Bill Russell. K.C. Jones. Great, great players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want my opinion on this United States team?'' Gomelsky
asked, unsolicited. ``In my opinion, the first Dream Team and the
second Dream Team were much better than this team. Because not only
were they great names and great people, but all the players on
Dream Team No. 1 were together _ with Larry Bird, Magic Johnson and
Jordan. Fantastic players. These are good players, but not great.
Regular players. But for this competition, there is not much
interest (for the game) in your team. Because your team is much
better. Your team will win, but not by a big score.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomelsky's old team is spread among several former Soviet states
today; the Eastern European threat to U.S. supremacy faded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he plans to catch up with Gomelsky. They rarely
talk about Munich. ``But when we do, he's always been very kind to
me about stepping up and making the free throws,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is truly a legendary figure in the game,'' he added.
Collins said that Gomelsky was one of the first international
coaches to use American methods ``to teach the Russian players the
fundamentals, the basic skills of the game, and to get the pro
offenses and the college offenses the United States were using.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomelsky had already gone when Collins was finished talking. He
was off looking for another former U.S. Olympic player with a
wealth of basketball knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Brown, he is a very, very good friend,'' Gomelsky said
of the U.S. assistant coach. ``I must talk to him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years after Munich, 12 years after Seoul, the
Silver Fox is still at work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1556EDT &QL; 
