u a BC-CIR-MTV-NYT &LR;      09-27 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MTV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THIS MTV SHOW, VIEWERS DIRECT FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHEL MARRIOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first glance, the scene at MTV's Times Square
studio on a recent Monday afternoon was familiar to anyone who has
ever watched even a few minutes of the channel. There were music,
dancers, DJs, guest appearances and, of course, music videos. But
this show, called Direct Effect, may be anything but typical. Its
producers say that it offers a glimpse into the near future of
television for all viewers, even those who can't hold a beat in a
basket.
</P>
<P>
   Direct Effect's primary distinction from regular television fare
is that it offers viewers to not only watch it on cable television,
but to help direct it through computers wired to MTV.com. Well, at
least, they can help select _ interacting in real time _ what music
videos will be featured on the live hourlong hip-hop music show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect for our audience,'' said Sara R. Cohen, vice
president of programming for MTV.com. She described MTV's young
core audience as being ``convergent people,'' as comfortable with
their computers and cell phones as they are with their televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Once logged on to MTV.com, viewers can follow a link to Direct
Effect, where they will find three thumbnail pictures and
descriptions of the artists and videos. To vote for the next video
to be played on Direct Effect, viewers click once on a spot under
the description of the video. The vote is sent to the network's
control room in New York, where it is rapidly tabulated with
others. A running tally of the vote is posted on the live
television screen almost up to the last minute before the next
video is shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the presence of this sort of show is really
reassuring,'' said Todd Boyd, a professor at the University of
Southern California's School of Cinema and Television and an expert
on hip-hop culture, ``especially when you hear so much about the
`digital divide' and large numbers of black people and minorities
being left out of the digital revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, when one considers how increasingly comfortable
young people, all kinds of young people, are with cutting edge,
computer-based technologies like computer games and digital music,
``it's not surprising that we have reached a point where the
connection of television and the Internet is so direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without a computer, what viewers see on their television
screens is a blend of old-fashioned television dating back to the
days of American Bandstand and Soul Train and Web-inspired multiple
screens and banner text. In some instances as many as five screens
may compete for the viewer's attention at once.
</P>
<P>
   MTV producers and executives said that they are encouraged by
their own studies of their audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience demonstrates that it is very willing to
participate in multi-screen programs here and now,'' said Nicholas
Butterworth, president and chief executive of MTVi, the interactive
arm of MTV Networks.
</P>
<P>
   As high-speed, broadband Internet service is slowly
proliferating the United States, television and Internet executives
are increasingly promising that PC-smart, set-top boxes will one
day soon start transforming television, making much of it
interactive. Brian Graden, president of programming for MTV, said
his viewers were not willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience is probably not like any other,'' added Brian
Graden, president of programming for MTV. ``About 70 percent of
them have computers and TV in the same room and use them at the
same time. They have come up with a crude two-box solution to
interactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTV Networks/Viacom Study of Media, Entertainment and
Leisure Time found last summer that there has been a significant
swell in the numbers of people owning and using personal computers
in their homes. But the study also showed that television is not
losing its audience to the Internet. Instead, the two media are
co-existing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than making trade-offs between different media options,
Americans are finding ways to incorporate new forms of media into
their lives without sacrificing the things they already love,''
said Betsy Frank, executive vice president for research and
planning at MTV Networks.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she said, many people are multitasking, reflecting
something she calls ``behavioral convergence,'' which she defines
as ``people acting as if their media platforms have already
converged even though the technology isn't there yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3698 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-D2-GAME-NYT &LR;      09-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-D2-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIDEOGAME WITH CINEMATIC ASPIRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
 By CHARLES HEROLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could happen to any developer. You spend years working on a
game, creating an elaborate story, detailed characters and
beautiful snow scenes carefully lighted to reflect the time of day.
Then, just as you think you're finished, you realize that you have
completely forgotten one thing: giving people something they can
actually play. With no time left, you quickly toss in a little
mindless action and release the game.
</P>
<P>
   That is not necessarily what happened with D2, Warp's
action-adventure game, but it feels that way. D2 is a game that is
good at all the extraneous elements of a videogame but bad at the
one central necessity _ that it be entertaining to play.
</P>
<P>
   The game begins with terrorists ranting about an entity called
``Shadow, the Final Destroyer'' as they cause a plane to crash over
Canada. Laura, a passenger, awakes in a cabin she has been carried
to by a fellow passenger, Kimberly, who found her eight days after
the crash. How Laura survived for those eight days is one of the
central mysteries of D2. Even more mysterious is why one of the
terrorists arrives, pulls a gun on the two women and then turns
into a savage plant.
</P>
<P>
   After Laura shoots the plant, the game begins. D2 has an
unusually lengthy introduction, 20 minutes long. Games often have
``cut scenes,'' which interrupt the game with short animations that
move the story forward, but it soon becomes clear that D2 has
enough footage for a full-length feature film. It's an excellent
film _ the cut scenes are as good as you'll find in any game. The
problem is what happens between them.
</P>
<P>
   The first indication of a problem comes when that terrorist
``blossoms,'' which is D2's poetic way of referring to the plant
transformation. Until then, the look of the game is elegant and
crisp, but the monster plant has the look of something out of a
Roger Corman horror film: awkward, ugly and downright silly.
</P>
<P>
   Once Laura heads out into the snowy Canadian wilderness, she
discovers that these plant monsters are everywhere. The game
suggests that they may all be mutated passengers of the crashed
plane, but if so, there must have been several thousand people
aboard because you never run out of monsters.
</P>
<P>
   When attacked, you go into battle mode, which involves shooting
at monsters until they're all dead. As you kill things, their green
blood splatters on the screen. At times you can barely see what
you're shooting at. When everything is dead, you start walking
again.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen over and over again, with little variation.
There are only a handful of different monster types, and there is
not much strategy needed to kill any of them. Most action games
position monsters for maximum effect, giving you a feeling of dread
as you turn a corner because you know you're about to be inundated
by zombies or aliens. But D2's monsters simply show up every time
you have walked a dozen steps or so. All through the game it's the
same thing: Walk, kill, walk, kill, walk, kill.
</P>
<P>
   There is no terror, no surprise. Instead of feeling that you are
trapped in a nightmare world where you are battling for your life,
you feel as though you are being repeatedly asked to take out the
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   You will also need to use your rifle to hunt for food, which can
be used to replenish your health. That is rather tedious, but at
least the bunnies don't look like horror movie rejects. The
adventure component consists simply of going from place to place
and picking up everything you find. D2 is an adventure game without
puzzles, an action game without excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Failing miserably as a game, D2 succeeds remarkably well as a
movie. A boy is forced to practice piano until he goes mad, a
scientist puts his wife's mind into a computer, a mutating woman's
eye falls out, and a butterfly emerges from the socket. The best
thing Warp could do for D2 would be to string the cut scenes
together and release it into theaters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most notable oddities in D2 is that the character you
lead through the snow to kill plant-people is less interesting than
everyone she meets. Laura doesn't speak a word until the game is
almost over. She generally expresses herself with thoughtful,
empathic looks and a variety of sighs, grunts and screams,
depending on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The real star of D2 is Kimberly, a depressed drug-addicted poet
who saves and befriends Laura and keeps telling her how wonderful
she is. (That is almost a running joke of the game; Laura wins
friendship, love and devotion while evincing absolutely no
personality.)
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly is a fascinating character. In the real world a
garrulous, self-involved poet would be annoying, but within the
game her melancholic musings and sudden bursts of anger are
fascinating. There is something truly remarkable about an action
game in which a woman sits down and explains her poetry. At length.
</P>
<P>
   The imagination that informs the story contributes to the few
successful action moments in the game, when you must battle the
particularly strong ``boss'' monsters.
</P>
<P>
   These monsters are the least plantlike because they have
retained vestiges of their humanity and talk to you while you are
killing them. It is chilling to shoot a plant-man as he's reliving
a conversation with his granddaughter or to fire repeatedly at a
plant-woman as she says, ``I thought we were friends.'' If D2 had
fewer monsters with more personality, its humdrum pedestrian action
would be more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   The last section of the game turns the tedious gameplay on full,
as Laura runs a gantlet of monsters before facing the last boss.
There is no secret to killing your final foe _ you just have to
keep shooting and replenishing your health until the enemy dies. If
you haven't stored up enough first-aid kits and killed enough
bunnies to outlast the monster, you'll never make it to the end.
It's the ignominious finish to the game's lackluster play.
</P>
<P>
   After the final lengthy cut scene, the game ends with a list of
statistics involving pollution, starvation, AIDS and other horrors.
The implication is that the story has something to do with the
evils of war and disease, although it is impossible to see how that
was meant to be conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a puzzling finale for a puzzling game. The game's central
mystery is not how Laura survived for eight days, or why people are
turning into plants, but how D2's makers believed that they could
get away with such anemic gameplay. As Laura would so eloquently
put it, ``Hmmmm?''
</P>
<P>
   D2, developed by Warp and published by Sega of America for
Dreamcast; $49.95; for 17 and older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
