<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETING-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Entertainment industry
representatives, stung by federal criticism that too much
advertising is aimed at minors, offer a 12-point proposal to stop
marketing movies deemed inappropriate for underage audiences. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-READINESS (Washington) _ Echoing charges from
Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush that U.S. military
readiness is slipping, the nation's top military officers told
Congress Wednesday that preparedness to fight has eroded to the
point that the Pentagon's main strategy of being able to win two
wars at once now carries high risk. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Washington) _ A top Energy Department official says
that home heating oil prices will stabilize over the next several
months but that they likely will remain ``substantially'' higher
than last year. However, Robert S. Kripowicz, acting assistant
secretary for fossil energy, warned that President Clinton's
decision last week to release 30 million barrels of oil from the
nation's emergency reserve can't prevent price spikes caused by any
unusually cold winter or shipping disruptions. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton has pulled
further ahead of Republican Rep. Rick Lazio in the New York Senate
race and has reached the 50 percent support level for the first
time, according to a new poll. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MEDICARE (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Vice President Al Gore
stresses his plan to cover the cost of prescription drugs through
Medicare. By PATTY REINERT
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION (Los Angeles) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush makes a
foray into a state where he trails Democrat Al Gore, addressing an
audience on the subject of school discipline. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SECRET (Pasadena, Texas) _ In 1953, a Pasadena man
working as a lab technician at a fertilizer plant died suddenly.
His death has been a mystery to his family for nearly half a
century. Now his daughter, Chloe Lewis, believes that he may have
died of radiation poisoning because the room where he spent most of
his day had been part of a secret federal project to test the
feasibility of extracting uranium from the phosphate ore that was
used to make phosphate fertilizer. BY JANETTE RODRIGUES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ Presidents traditionally revere
their mothers and rarely praise their fathers or even speak of
them. That may not be true in the future when so many modern
fathers are involved in hands-on parenting. But the stronger,
sometimes domineering, influence of mothers on sons who wound up in
the White House cannot be denied. We know every little boy can grow
up to be president, but it helps to have a wise mother on his side.
By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ As we head into the final month
of the presidential campaign, the race between Al Gore and George
W. Bush is very close and very confrontational. But the two
candidates lack the vision and the idealism that generate great
expectations within the electorate, especially among young
Americans. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed; for release
Sunday, Oct. 1.)
</P>
