<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PORTRAIT OF ORSON WELLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
(Eds: Jonathan Mandell reviews theater for Broadway.com and is the
managing editor of GothamGazette.com, a Web site about New York
City politics and policy.) 
 By JONATHAN MANDELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just before Orson Welles died, as the scene is
presented in ``War of the Worlds,'' a new biographical drama that
opens the Next Wave festival on Wednesday in the Harvey Theater at
the Brooklyn Academy of Music, he uttered a last word that could be
taken as the key to his whole personality. The word was ``Thorne,''
the name of a room he often visited at the Art Institute of Chicago
when he was young. ``It was a place of magic for him,'' said Naomi
Iizuka, who wrote the script in collaboration with Anne Bogart, the
artistic director of the SITI Co. which helped create the play and
will perform it at the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Could Welles' last word actually have been ``Thorne''? Could
there be such a startling parallel between the life of this actor,
director and bon vivant and the plot of the film ``Citizen Kane,''
Welles' masterpiece in which the title character, the newspaper
magnate Charles Foster Kane, speaks a similarly evocative name,
``Rosebud,'' just before he dies?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's speculative,'' Iizuka conceded. ``Anne and SITI and I
are speculating about that, in the same fashion that Welles
speculated about Rosebud.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not exactly in the same fashion. When Welles made
``Rosebud'' the last word of Kane, he was probably having sly fun
with William Randolph Hearst, the real-life figure on whom Kane is
often thought to have been based. Hearst did have a Rosebud who was
dear to him. It was not his childhood sled, as in the movie, but
rather his adult mistress, Marion Davies, whom he had given the pet
name Rosebud. More to the point, when ``Citizen Kane'' came out in
1941, Hearst had not actually uttered any last words; he was still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   To the creators of ``War of the Worlds,'' part of a surge of new
works about Welles, fact is not relevant. ``Welles was very
interested in fiction, often including fictions he told about
himself,'' said Bogart, who conceived and directed this latest in a
number of avant-garde biographical dramas dealing with what she
calls ``big people.'' Previous subjects: Andy Warhol, Robert
Wilson, Marshall McLuhan; present or future subjects: Virginia
Woolf, Robert Rauschenberg, Leonard Bernstein. ``The people who
know my work will be surprised at how linear this one is,'' Bogart
said.
</P>
<P>
   As in most of her productions, she said, she started with a
question. This time it was, ``When did news become entertainment?''
</P>
<P>
   She thought the answer was ``The War of the Worlds,'' the 1938
radio play that made the 23-year-old Orson Welles a star. He turned
the H.G. Wells tale about a Martian invasion of Earth into a
simulated news broadcast that was so convincing it panicked
listeners across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I changed the question,'' Bogart recalled. ``It
became, `How do you ever know a person?'''
</P>
<P>
   ```War of the Worlds' is not a documentary,'' she added. ``We
use the poetic language of the stage.'' Many characters are
composites or invented outright. ``It tells his story,'' she said,
``but I can't say it's his life.''
</P>
<P>
   If not his life, it is, in a way, his movie. ``War of the
Worlds,'' which also has been presented at the Humana Theater
Festival in Louisville, Ky., and the Edinburgh Festival in
Scotland, is named for the radio broadcast. It is ``Citizen Kane,''
though, that is the more direct inspiration for ``War of the
Worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, Welles is given the Kane treatment, the story of
his life and work explored as if it were a mystery. The play
appropriates the film's structure and even some of its scenes and
techniques. (Hence the Thorne speculation.)
</P>
<P>
   Along with all this invention and meditation, there are some
facts in the play, and they too are surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a tragic character,'' said Bogart about Welles. ``He
had a fantastic life, full of traveling and people and love and
great restaurants. I think audiences will be surprised by the
breadth of his work, and just the quantity of it, if not the
quality. At the end of the play, we list the films he was involved
in; there must be 100, and that's not even a complete list.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogart and her company are far from the only artists who have
become taken with the man and his work. Fifteen years after his
death, Orson Welles _ boy genius turned portly outcast, film
pioneer, theatrical innovator _ is experiencing a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com lists 45 different titles about him. (It lists 34
about William Randolph Hearst.) The respected Welles biographer
Simon Callow is soon to come out with his second and last volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``RKO 281,'' a movie shown last November on HBO and now out on
video, tells the story of the making of ``Citizen Kane'' (``RKO
281'' was the way RKO, the studio that financed ``Citizen Kane,''
referred to Welles' project before its release). It is based on the
1997 documentary ``The Battle Over `Citizen Kane,''' which was
nominated for an Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   A month later came the theatrical release of Tim Robbins' film
``Cradle Will Rock,'' which tells several true stories from the
1930s, including that of Welles' defiant staging of Marc
Blitzstein's pro-union musical ``The Cradle Will Rock'' over
government objections. (The Jean Cocteau Repertory Co. is currently
staging a revival of Blitzstein's musical at the Bouwerie Lane
Theater.) In an irony that Welles fans note with some bitterness, a
year before his death, Welles wrote his own screenplay about this
episode from his past, with the title ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' but
he could not get the financing to make it into a film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of artistic necrophilia,'' Henry Jaglom, a filmmaker
and one-time Welles collaborator, told The Hollywood Reporter.
``There is all this interest in him and his work, but when he was
alive he was cast aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, William Hurt starred in ``The Big Brass Ring,''
a film about a gubernatorial candidate threatened by a scandalous
past, which was adapted directly from another screenplay that
Welles wrote, in 1982, and could not get produced.
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. Postal Service has gotten into the act, last year
issuing an ``Orson Welles' `Citizen Kane''' postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with Welles is continuing this year on the
stage. ``Orson's Shadow,'' written by Austin Pendleton and produced
by the Steppenwolf Theater Company in Chicago, tells the story of
Welles' production of Ionesco's ``Rhinoceros'' at the Royal Court
Theater in London. At the urging of the theater critic Kenneth
Tynan, he directed Laurence Olivier and Olivier's new love, Joan
Plowright.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystery to me why he's in the zeitgeist,'' said Bogart.
``I was disappointed that this person that I spent years
researching is suddenly everywhere. I thought, `This was mine!'''
</P>
<P>
   For Bogart, doing a play about Welles offered her a chance to
translate close-ups, panning and point-of-view techniques to the
stage: ``So much of my work as a director is deeply affected by
cinematic technique. Too much of our theater is stuck in the 19th
century, with box sets and living rooms.'' Still, she said: ``I
will never make a film. I'm interested in being in the same room
with people, breathing common air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
