<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3713 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-27 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER COLUMN: THIS NET IS JUST FOR GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a lovely September afternoon and I was doing what many
like-minded souls do on weekends in autumn: playing football with
friends. But instead of running around and possibly damaging
valuable body parts, I was sitting in a comfortable chair at my
friend Jenn Sturm's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   I held the video game controller while Jenn typed taunts at our
opponent (who was in Michigan) on a keyboard attached to a Sega
Dreamcast video game console. We were playing Sega's new
``SegaSports NFL 2K1'' football game, the first Dreamcast title
that has built-in connectivity to Sega's brand-new gaming network,
SegaNet.
</P>
<P>
   SegaNet, which opened its servers to gamers all over the country
on Sept. 7, is a combination Internet service provider and
high-speed private network. It was designed and built especially
for people who like to play video games against opponents online,
either from a PC or a Dreamcast console, which has a convenient 56K
modem inside.
</P>
<P>
   People who sign up to use the network pay $21.95 per month and
can also browse the Web from the Dreamcast. Customers also get a
personal sega.net e-mail address, and to sweeten the pot, Sega is
offering a $150 rebate check (which is about the price of the
console these days) and a Dreamcast keyboard to customers who sign
up for 18 months of SegaNet service.
</P>
<P>
   Playing games against other people over the Internet is nothing
new. On the low-tech side, people have been e-mailing chess moves
to opponents for years. More recently, battle games like ``Quake''
and ``StarCraft'' have drawn legions of faithful players into
real-time online competitions to blast bad guys off the screen.
``Ultima Online,'' a Web-based role-playing game cast in a medieval
setting, has drawn players from more than 114 countries. ``Ultima
Online'' players have even gotten married in real life, thus
merging virtual and real community.
</P>
<P>
   And the concept of community is a big part of gaming,
particularly with console games. I always found the old Atari 2600
to be most fun when I could whomp my sister in a game of
``Warlords'' after school. It was much better than playing
``Pac-Man'' by myself at the mall, because there was a human
element there (not to mention sibling rivalry). The
unpredictability and competitiveness of the game environment is a
big part of the appeal for many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaming has always been, certainly from our perspective, a
societal undertaking,'' said Peter Moore, the president and chief
operating officer of Sega of America Dreamcast. ``It's often been
perceived as this lonely guy in his bedroom playing video games all
night long on his own, but as our research tells us, when
multiplayer games became popular, it became a way of kids getting
together and playing against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed and response to the things happening on screen are vital
for surviving in a video game. And on those days when the Internet
just crawls, playing a game is darn near impossible due to the
agonizingly slow response on the screen to player input.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the problem, Sega.com, the online-entertainment
company founded by Sega Enterprises Ltd. in Japan, created SegaNet
just for the dial-up-modem game-playing environment. SegaNet
engineers created regional hubs and reduced the number of hops (all
the different computers a particular packet of data bounces to on
its way to its destination) for the connection to increase the
network's speed. The network was created to work with 56K modems,
although broadband options will be available later.
</P>
<P>
   I figured if I was going to try SegaNet, I should play with a
professional. Jenn, in addition to being a whiz who regularly
fillets me in the Dreamcast fighting game ``Soul Calibur,'' is also
the director of systems for Flooz.com, an online gift currency
site. We popped in the ``NFL 2K1'' game disk, connected a telephone
cord to the modem jack and attached the Dreamcast keyboard to the
game console. It didn't take us too long to find the option to
connect to the network, since it's right there on the game's main
screen. (People who buy the football game get 50 free hours to try
out SegaNet, and gamers can also sign up at www.sega.net.)
</P>
<P>
   The instructions on the screen walked us through setting up a
user name and a password for SegaNet, as well as a local access
number. We connected to the network at 28.8 kilobits per second. We
soon landed in the lobby, where we could see how many people were
connected to the network at any given time and where they were
from, based on the information from the SegaNet user account. To
strike fear into the hearts of our opponents, we chose the online
name TruckerMan for our first SegaNet experience.
</P>
<P>
   The game includes a chat program so that you can type comments
on the keyboard before and during the game, and we soon found
ourselves in a match with someone from Michigan. The ``NFL 2K1''
game itself is hyper-realistic, with beautifully rendered players
and all the trappings of a televised game, like multiple camera
angles, instant replay and announcers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our connection at half the potential speed of the modem,
Jenn thought the game's response times were pretty good. There were
also only about 50 or 60 people connected to the network at the
time, which might have had something to do with it. We traded moves
with the person in Michigan smoothly enough to make it seem as if
he were right there in Brooklyn with us.
</P>
<P>
   Jenn went back on the network one weeknight a few days later and
noticed some slow response times in the chat function, as well as
in the game's team selection and setup; it might have been because
three times as many people logged on, compared with our first time.
</P>
<P>
   Sega representatives said voice-chat capabilities were in
development for future games, which is good, because it was rather
hard to type in the chat window on the keyboard while playing. So I
handled the actual gameplay _ and promptly got our quarterback
sacked three plays in a row. (TruckerMan turned out to be one of
those ``all talk and no action'' kind of guys.)
</P>
<P>
   The Sega Dreamcast platform has a lot of competition coming up.
Microsoft has announced plans for a game console called the X-Box,
and Nintendo is working on its new GameCube device. And then
there's Sony's much-anticipated PlayStation2, which is set to
appear in the United States in late October.
</P>
<P>
   With CD, DVD and online capabilities, PlayStation2 looks like it
wants to be an all-purpose entertainment center, so Sega's decision
to concentrate on pure, hard-core gaming over the phone lines sort
of sets it apart. The company plans to steadily release game titles
with the built-in network functions for SegaNet, including a scion
of online game royalty, Quake III Arena, in October.
</P>
<P>
   Gamers are a fussy lot, so whether SegaNet takes off depends on
whether it can keep up with the whims and demands of its target
audience. For a network that has just come to life, it's off to a
pretty good start as a network and a community.
</P>
<P>
   And TruckerMan is really looking forward to ``Quake III Arena''
on the Dreamcast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
