<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-ARCH-ALOYZIE0928-     09-27 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-ALOYZIE0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiny Nigerian fight's through pain of fiance's death, wins
silver medal
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ She will head back to Nigeria with a silver medal and
the body of her fiance'.
</P>
<P>
   No athlete at the Sydney Olympic Games has gone through anything
quite like Glory Alozie. She has experienced crushing loss,
spectacular triumph and, Wednesday night, the embrace of an Olympic
Stadium crowd that knew some of what the tiny athlete has endured
in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Alozie is a hurdler and hers is the ultimate story about getting
over hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   It's about trying to somehow force yourself forward after you've
been too shell-shocked to march in the Opening Ceremonies, or even
leave your room in the Olympic Village.
</P>
<P>
   It 's about being so numb in the days before your race, that
your coach _ seeing you'd lost some 13 pounds in two weeks _ had to
all but force his way into your room and feed you with a spoon, so
you'd finally eat. It's being so frightened of being alone at night
that your teammates and close friend, Joan Ekah, must crawl into
bed with you and hold you until your eyes finally close.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as the 2000 Olympic Games approached, the
22-year-old Alozie could not have been happier. Even though she now
lived and trained in Valencia, Spain, she was a national heroine in
Nigeria. She was the second-best 100-meter sprinter in the world, a
5-foot-1 sprite who always was on the back heel of popular American
runner Gail Devers.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, her beloved boyfriend, Hyginus Anayo Anugo _ the
guy who loved to give her flowers and gifts and playful kisses, the
Bible-carrying Christian who would pray daily with her _ had
proposed to her. They planned to marry four months after the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Like Alozie, Anugo was trying to make the Nigerian Olympic team.
He had been one of the sprinters in the mix for the Nigerian 4 X
400-meter relay team. But by the end of August, the
financially-strapped Nigerians decided to send just six relay
sprinters, not eight, to Sydney. Anugo didn't make the cut
</P>
<P>
   That's when Alozie stepped in and pleaded with officials to
bring Anugo to the Games. She ran better when he was around.
</P>
<P>
   No Nigerian woman had ever won an Olympic gold medal and Alozie
stood a chance. That's why she had left her isolated town in
Nigeria and moved to Spain three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing near her village,'' said her manager, Julia
Garcia. ``To train on a decent track, she had to ride a bus 18
hours. It was impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   She took silver at the World Championships in Seville last year
and this season had run strongly in Europe. Her last Olympics'
tune-up was to be a race in Japan. Anugo, meanwhile, headed to
Sydney to train with the other sprinters and await Alozie's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, one of the first nights he was here, Anugo left the
apartment he shared with the Nigerian coaches in a southwest suburb
of Sydney and ran to a nearby convenience store to get food. On his
way back, he ran in front of an idling bus, smiled, waved at the
driver, and...stepped into the path of a speeding car.
</P>
<P>
   Hyginus Anayo Anugo was dead at 22.
</P>
<P>
   When Alozie was told the news, she pulled out of the Japanese
meet and planned to do the same in Sydney. She couldn't fathom
running. Her thinking convoluted by shock and grief, she blamed
herself for Anugo's death. If she hadn't insisted he be at her
side, he would not even have been in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   She came to Sydney only because this was where Anugo's body was.
While she reported to the Athletes Village, she could not bring
herself to train.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the accident happened, I thought there would be no way
Glory would be in shape to run,'' Garcia admitted.
</P>
<P>
   She told how it took Alozie's coach, Rafael Blanquer, five or
six days to finally coax Alozie to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread through the Village and soon other athletes from
other nations were visiting Alozie, encouraging her, looking out
for her as she began to venture from her room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got phone calls and letters and E-mails from people I did
not know,'' Alozie said. ``I began to think God was helping me. He
was showing me the way.''
</P>
<P>
   If she competed, she figured she would be doing what Anugo had
wanted her to do. That is why he'd come here. He'd always loved to
see her run.
</P>
<P>
   So she worked her way through the 100-meter hurdle prelims and
then won her semifinal heat. In the other semifinal, Devers, the
gold medal favorite, pulled up lame and that set the stage for the
final.
</P>
<P>
   When she was announced, Alozie kissed her fingertips and shyly
flung the kiss skyward. With the gun, she got a good start and led
the rest of the field through nine hurdles. But Kazakhstan's Olga
Shishigina caught her at the 10th hurdle and managed to lean into
the tape before her. Shishigina finished at 12.65. Glory was second
at 12.68 and American Melissa Morrison won bronze with a 12.76.
</P>
<P>
   A half dozen strides past the finish, Alozie collapsed to her
knees in prayer. From the crowd, a teammate called to her and held
out the green and white Nigerian flag. Alozie wrapped it around her
shoulders, then stood and watched a replay on the stadium's
overhead screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she has done tonight is spectacular,'' Garcia said. ``She
is so little and she stood so big.'' One by one, most of the other
women in the race came over and hugged her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glory is a very strong lady,'' Morrison said. ``We all wanted
her to know how we felt about what she'd done.''
</P>
<P>
   With some coaxing, Alozie took a slow victory lap. She held the
flag over her head, then draped it back on her shoulders. She ran,
she walked, she stood and then started again. Many in the crowd
stood and applauded. The two other medalists had completed their
circuits and she still had a third of the stadium to go. She was in
no hurry to finish. No hurry to leave the track and face what was
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said she would wait until morning to talk to Alozie about
working out funeral details. The Nigerian officials here haven't
yet said they have funds to handle the arrangements of taking
Anugo's body back home. ``We have many things to decide, but that
will wait,'' Garcia said. ``Right now, this should be a good moment
for Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   On the awards podium, Glory held her silver medal in her hand
for a long time and finally bent down and kissed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I though of Hyginus,'' she said later. ``I thought of
what had happened and how difficult the past weeks have been. I
thought about where I was now. This medal is the most important one
of my life. It is Hyginus' medal.''
</P>
<P>
   After talking briefly with the media, Alozie slipped down a
hallway and was met by Ekha, who cradled the little hurdler's face
in her hands, then kissed her on the cheek. Slowly, the two made
their way into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``God will help me through this,'' Alozie said. ``I don't know
why this happened or what it's all about, but God must have a good
plan for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her voiced trailed off ...
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to. He wouldn't leave me all alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
