<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASE0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong pitching, timely hitting lead U.S. over Cuba
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - Behind his back, we laughed at Tommy Lasorda. He's so
brazen sometimes, many times, that his expressions border on the
outrageous. Well, not this time.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Games, the former Los Angeles Dodgers manager all but
assured an American gold medal in baseball, even though TeamUSA had
to get through prohibitive favorite and international powerhouse
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come 10,000 miles to lose,'' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't. In a stunning performance, Wednesday the United
States thrashed two-time defending Olympic champion Cuba 4-0 to
capture the gold medal _ and make Lasorda a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ben Sheets of the Milwaukee Brewers' organization shut
down the explosive Cuban bats, giving up just three singles in
going the distance. And the U.S. bats, which at times have been
quiet, brought more noise than anyone expected against the dominant
Cuban pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Neill started things in the first inning with a home run,
and the United States never looked back in earning its first
baseball gold medal. The win avenged a dominant Cuban 6-1 victory
over America last week.
</P>
<P>
   The United States probably stunned itself with Neill's
opposite-field home run to left. Cuba manager Servio Borges clearly
recognized the significance of the game, removing starter Pedro
Luis Lazo after just one inning.
</P>
<P>
   In came Jose Ibar, who had not given up a run in the Games. And
true to form, Ibar was brilliant, not allowing a ball out of the
infield for three innings. Then, even he became hittable.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Catcher Pat Borders lined a double to the
wall in right-centerfield to drive in Doug Mientkiewicz, who had
walked. It was 2-0, U.S., and chants of ``U.S.A., U.S.A.'' began.
</P>
<P>
   Ibar was replaced by Maels Rodriguez, with runners on first and
third and one out. He walked Brad Wilkerson, struck out Neill, but
allowed a two-run single up the middle to rightfielder Ernie Young,
giving America a commanding 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly imposing advantage because Sheets was on
his game. Cuba never had a runner reach second base, as Sheets had
full command of his arsenal. He was throwing in the low 90s in the
eighth inning, a display of power. But his offspeed stuff kept Cuba
guessing _ and guessing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   When Sheets recorded the final out, Team USA mobbed him on the
field, a wild celebration many did not believe would occur _ except
Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
