<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COOPER-HEWITT-APPOINT     09-27 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOPER-HEWITT-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGES FOR THE NEW CURATOR AT THE COOPER-HEWITT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Britain)   By JULIE V. IOVINE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As an Englishman about to move to New York, Paul W.
Thompson has a lot to think about. Where should he and his family
live? Is it too late for his daughters to get into Spence? Oh, and
what's to be done about reinventing the Cooper-Hewitt National
Design Museum?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Thompson was appointed the new director of the
Cooper- Hewitt, a cultural organization housed in a flamboyant
Fifth Avenue mansion at 2 East 91st St. The Cooper-Hewitt is
national design museum and archive, historic collection and
graduate study program. Its exhibitions over the years have ranged
from the hardly spine-tingling 1991 airing of ``The Cooper-Hewitt
Collections: A Design Resource'' to the raucously interactive 1998
exhibition ``Unlimited by Design,'' an unprecedented review of
universal design products.
</P>
<P>
   It is an institution that bears the awkward responsibility of
tending vast, idiosyncratic holdings that include matchbooks,
Soviet porcelain, shopping bags and the Tibor Kalman papers, while
simultaneously trying to accommodate the demands of today's
hyperactive design community longing for a mecca to call its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's the whole name thing,'' Thompson said in a
telephone interview from London as he pondered what awaits him at
the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum when he starts early next
year. ``It's such a long name, maybe it needs shortening.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a new leaf _ if not a whole new life _ for the
41-year-old who will be leaving his post as director of the Design
Museum in London, where he made a name for himself by paying off a
nearly $2.2 million debt and keeping Sir Terence Conran, the
museum's expansive founder, somewhat at bay. Chronically short of
money, the Design Museum has relied heavily on importing
exhibitions that originated elsewhere, including ``The Work of
Charles and Ray Eames'' (which was initiated by the Library of
Congress in partnership with the Vitra Design Museum and traveled
to the Cooper-Hewitt) and ``The Life and Work of Buckminster
Fuller'' (which came from Zurich). At the time of the museum's 10th
anniversary last fall, Rowan Moore of The Evening Standard in
London gave the museum three cheers, but then noted that ``it still
doesn't quite fizz.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was the first curator of one of the most popular
permanent installations, called ``Review,'' a continuing display of
the latest work coming out of London's design studios. His most
ambitious recent offering was an exhibition this year on the
Bauhaus that took advantage of materials that had only recently
resurfaced in post-Cold War Germany, including Walter Gropius' own
office desk from Dessau.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing Thompson's eight years at the helm of the Design
Museum, Conran said, ``He's not a visionary but he will bring a
professionalism that frankly the Cooper-Hewitt has lacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cooper-Hewitt has also had to combine original exhibitions
with more standardized fare. But it strove to be a pacesetter with
increasing success in such shows as the intensely colorful
``Alexander Girard'' retrospective that opened this month and the
recent ``Design Culture Now,'' a triennial presentation of
breakthrough designs in architecture, graphics, fashion, landscape,
new media and theater.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, whose London friends describe him as consummately
British _ dry humor, loud ties and all _ seemed less concerned
about the next really big show than about the museum's identity.
``I need to work on it as a brand,'' he said, hesitating only
briefly before lunging into full-throated marketing lingo. ``It
needs to be contemporized _ what a horrible word,'' he said. ``Not
enough people know about it. I have to concentrate on getting its
brand really established.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of the naming of Thompson spread, the design community
in New York offered their thoughts and ideas, both pragmatic and
wistful, about the future of a museum that had been tended with
missionary zeal by Dianne H. Pilgrim, who retired in January after
being the museum's director for 12 years. Pilgrim happily allowed
her curators to hammer home their themes when more subtle means
would have sufficed.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York needs a museum that perpetually shows contemporary
work,'' said Karim Rashid, the designer who aims for high design at
cheap prices. ``The Cooper-Hewitt is relatively steeped in the
past, when it could be the epicenter of what's new. Let the Met do
the old stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cooper-Hewitt's core collection is more than 100 years old,
started by the three Hewitt sisters, granddaughters of the
industrialist Peter Hewitt. That collection includes 19th-century
textiles, drawings, prints and other collectibles befitting a
Victorian stash. ``It's really two museums in one building,'' said
Constantin Boym, who is known for using recycled and found objects
to make household wares. He added that the new director must face
the challenge of finding a connection between the applied arts of
the 19th century and the problems of design as a cultural
phenomenon now. ``The importance of the institution is growing at
the same rate as design is becoming important in the economy and in
the culture at large,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing more than a few other New Yorkers, Boym said he dreamed
of a Cooper-Hewitt that would be as actively involved as museums
used to be in the 1920s and '30s, not only organizing exhibitions
but also design competitions, housing studies and design awards.
``I want to see shows that aren't just reflections of what's
happening, but catalysts to help things happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the 1899 Cooper-Hewitt building itself, built by
Andrew Carnegie and taken over by the museum in 1976, that comes
under the most frequent fire as an almost impossible venue for
staging exhibitions on modern design. It was a problem easily
appreciated by visitors to the Eames show as they were forced to
make out the couple's radical experimental films projected in
darkly paneled rooms, something like showing newsreels in a black
hole.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few bystanders are suggesting, why not divide the
old from the new and move the more contemporary spirited
exhibitions to a more flexible, dare we say hipper, location.
``It's a really heroic institution in a tough building,'' said
Paola Antonelli, a design curator at the Museum of Modern Art, who
said that early on in the process she turned down the chance to be
considered for the director's job. Bifurcation, she worried, would
impoverish an audience that needs to see design as it has evolved
within its entire context.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who now lives in a turn-of-the-century terrace house
in West London (which he noted was ``like living in Brooklyn'') but
works in a white cube on the south bank of the Thames designed by
Conran Roche, seemed to have few qualms about the Cooper-Hewitt's
present home. He soundly rejected any suggestion that he might be
thinking of a move, or that he might be susceptible to the
expansionitis infecting so many other museum directors. He did,
however, allow that the garden at the Cooper-Hewitt looked very
attractive. The land under it, that is.
</P>
