<HEADER>
A3747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     09-27 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Sept. 28. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Ned Kilkelly; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: nekilk(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A vast crowd of at least
200,000 converged on central Belgrade Wednesday for a rally to show
support for opposition candidate Vojislav Kostunica. (Summary from
wires.) By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-SCENE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ In the crumbling streets of
a faded Belgrade, tired and worn from 10 years of international
sanctions and isolation, most people have simply had enough of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. But they are not sure he is
going to go quietly after his apparent defeat in Sunday's elections
here. And they are nervous about a police crackdown. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ After deliberating for six
months, Israel's attorney general has found insufficient evidence
to prosecute former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on corruption
charges, clearing the way for a possible political comeback by the
charismatic rightist leader. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-GAS (Jerusalem) _ Traveling with a boatload of aides to
a drilling rig 19 miles off the Gaza coast, Yasser Arafat
celebrated the multibillion-dollar discovery of what industry
officials confirmed Wednesday is a major natural gas deposit in
waters controlled by Arafat's Palestinian Authority. The gas find,
considered more than enough to meet Palestinian needs for a decade
or more, will provide ``a strong foundation for a Palestinian
state,'' Arafat said. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, Netherlands) _ In an atmosphere so
hostile that the witness's fear could be heard even in the voices
of his translators, the testimony of the most important witness in
the Lockerbie trial was systematically torn to pieces on Wednesday.
Two defense lawyers spent the day decimating every important point
made on Tuesday by Abdul Majid Giaka, a Libyan double-agent who has
been in a federal witness protection program for the last decade.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-MEDIA (Washington) _ A top entertainment executive told
the Senate Wednesday that it was a ``judgment lapse'' for his movie
company to try to advertise a film with violent scenes on a
children's television network. The executive, Mel Harris, president
and chief operating officer of Sony Pictures Entertainment,
defended his company in another instance when children aged 9 to 11
were interviewed as part of the test marketing of a violent R-rated
movie. Harris was one of eight executives from the country's
largest movie studios who testified Wednesday before the Senate
commerce committee about the marketing of violent movies to
children. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURE-POOR-KIDS (Undated) _ Three years ago, Congress provided
$4.2 billion to the states to provide health insurance for the
millions of children whose parents were too poor to afford
commercial plans, but who made too much to qualify for Medicaid.
But a majority of the states are in danger of forfeiting their
share of the federal money, because they have not been able to get
their versions of the program, The Children's Health Insurance
Program, up and running. What separates those states that have
managed to enroll children into health insurance programs from
those that did not defies convenient leaps of logic and, in many
cases, the expectations of experts of the program. By Jennifer
Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-ABORTION-PILL (Undated) _ In a major victory for supporters
of abortion rights, the Food and Drug Administration ended an
18-year standoff Wednesday and announced it had approved the
marketing of an abortion-inducing pill, the first alternative to
surgical abortion approved in the United States. By Gina Kolata and
Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASEBALL (Sydney, Australia) _ In a shocking upset, a U.S.
team made up of top prospects, lower-level minor-leaguers and a
former major-leaguer or two shut out Cuba, 4-0, to win the gold
medal. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT-OLY 6.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLING (Sydney, Australia) _ In perhaps the greatest
Olympic wrestling upset ever, Rulon Gardner of the United States, a
first-time Olympian, beat Russia's heavyweight, Alexander Karelin,
ending the Russian's string of three straight gold medals. By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT-OLY 2,3,4,5,7.
</P>
</TEXT>
