<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-GOSPEL28-COX     09-27 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-GOSPEL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gospel divas stay in the spirit
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley Caesar doesn't give you time to wonder whether or not
you want to sing the Lord's praises. At the start of the gospel
pioneer's 35th album in her 33-year career, the New Direction Choir
announces:``This is the day that the Lord has made, rejoice!'' A
rhythm guitarist punctuates the statement with an excited strum.
Trumpets blast. And the muscular, husky blare _ that is, Caesar's
voice _ snatches you by the spirit and pulls you in.
</P>
<P>
   Then she puts on her ``breastplate of righteousness'' for the
bluesy call-and-response ``Armor of God,'' rounding it off with a
sung sermon that reaffirms she is an equally gifted pastor. It's a
moment of improvisation that's too rare here.
</P>
<P>
   For a more R&AMP;B-sounding CD that is a little less direct about
its subject, there's Yolanda Adams' ``Mountain High... Valley
Low.'' Smoother and sharper vocally than Caesar, the Grammy winner
glides capably from the big orchestrations of the conventional
``That Name'' to ``Time to Change,'' which opens with turntable
scratches. But she really wins when she combines the two schools of
gospel on ``Open My Heart,'' employing Janet Jackson's producers
Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis to come up with a song simple and earnest
enough for those of Caesar's generation to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Can Make It''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Caesar. Word/Epic. 10 tracks. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain High ... Valley Low''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Adams. Elektra. 11 tracks. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Shirley Caesar: www.myrrh.com,
www.shirleycaesar.com.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Yolanda Adams: www.elektra.com,
www.yolandaadams.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
