<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-GOULD28-COX     09-27 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GOULD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Share in charming eccentricity of `Secret'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Gould (Ian Holm, right) was a colorful eccentric who roamed
the streets in the '40s, dividing his time between flophouses and
an in-circuit of celebrity parties, all the while going on about
his great work. Gould became ``famous'' when he was profiled by
genteel New Yorker essayist Joe Mitchell (Stanley Tucci, who also
directed). The overall impression is a kind of New Yorker sketch of
a movie. Spare, mystifying, yet with a lingering impact.
</P>
<P>
   `Joe Gould's Secret'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For the official site:
www.joegouldsecret.com
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Final Destination'' (R) _ Sole survivors of a jet explosion,
Devon Sawa and six other high schoolers realize the Grim Reaper,
feeling cheated, is stalking them one by one. Not exactly a
classic, this teen horror flick still boasts some intelligence and
frisky wit.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Black and White'' (R) _ The latest from writer-director
James Toback is a largely improvisational look at interactions
between white and black culture in New York. It's not a very good
or intelligent movie, but it's a topical powderkeg likely to launch
arguments and discussions more complex and sophisticated than the
film itself. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' (PG) _
Yabba-dabba-don't. A new, needless, live-action ``Flintstones,''
with Mark Addy as Fred, Stephen Baldwin as Barney and the courtship
of Wilma and Betty as the plot. Inoffensive and mildly amusing in
spots, but hardly worth it. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Stephen Whitty, Newhouse News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Where the Heart Is'' (PG-13) _ A corn pone comedy-drama
about a single mom, made with enough polish to be a guilty
pleasure. Natalie Portman plays the pregnant teen who heads for
California and winds up becoming the Wal-Mart Mom in Oklahoma. She
gets good support from Stockard Channing, Ashley Judd and Sally
Field. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cup'' (G) _ If the Jamaicans can field a bobsled team to
the Olympics, why shouldn't some Tibetan monks-in-exile succumb to
soccer fever? That's the premise of this slight, sly charmer set in
Bhutan (a tiny country in the foothills of the Himalayas), directed
by a lama and starring real Buddhist monks. A soccer-mad
14-year-old monk-in-training is determined to see the finals of the
1998 World Cup. It is a refreshingly candid and gently humorous
film. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Waking the Dead'' (R) _ A haunting romance in which an
aspiring politician (Billy Crudup) in the early '80s thinks his
radical beloved (Jennifer Connelly), killed in a car bombing in the
'70s, may be back from the dead. Crudup is superb, and Connelly is
effective in a more limited role. The movie is a little too
earnest, a little slow, but it's more than recommended to those who
love fine acting. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Last September'' (R) _ Set in rural Ireland in 1920,
four years after the Easter Uprising, the movie comes off as a kind
of minor-league ``Heartbreak House'' in which the fates of assorted
characters gathered in and around a once grand manor mirror the
political tensions between the Irish rebels and their English
rulers. Oh, it's well-crafted and elegantly acted, but a mess
nonetheless. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
