<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL-COX     09-27 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    bobl -- 5430
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PLEASE USE ELEANOR RINGEL GILLESPIE PHOTO SIG
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Aussie theme aids Olympic overindulgence
 &HT;    For Olympic respite, try Aussie classic
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling a little overdosed on the Olympics? Nobody should
stomach a steady diet of competition, interviews with medalists,
cooking demonstrations, Katie Couric with a kangaroo, etc. Time, I
say, to watch a movie. Maybe something from, well, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad Max,'' ``Crocodile Dundee'' and Russell Crowe are some of
the more familiar wonders from Down Under. Here are some worthy
titles you may not have seen:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Man From Snowy River'' (1982): If you were wondering
what all those cowboys in the Sergio Leone dusters were doing at
the Opening Ceremonies, here's one possible source of inspiration.
This full-gallop film is a great family choice. Think David Lean
directing ``My Friend Flicka.'' Handsome Tom Burlinson is the
titular ``Man From ...,'' an Outback nobody who must prove his
worth _ to himself, to a haughty, horse-loving rancher (Kirk
Douglas, who also plays his twin, a guy with a wooden leg) and to
the rancher's spunky daughter. The boy-to-man challenge _ to
capture a wild stallion that's made off with Douglas' prized
racehorse _ is shown as a death-defying round-up, near mythic in
its raw, surging power. Incidentally, the movie is based on
Australia's national poem (of the same name) which was written by
Banjo Paterson, who also wrote the ubiquitous ``Waltzing Matilda.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gallipoli'' (1981): Before he became famous in America for
such movies as ``Witness'' and ``Dead Poet's Society,'' director
Peter Weir was one of Australia's most successful directors. And
before he became famous as Mad Max, the Road Warrior, Mel Gibson
made movies like this magnificent anti-war picture about two Aussie
sprinters who join ``the greatest game of all'' (i.e., World War I)
and meet their destinies on the blood-soaked beaches of Gallipoli.
The picture blends the boisterousness and bluff naivete of a boys'
adventure book with a twinge of after-the-fact sorrowing cynicism.
Like some Australian John Ford, Weir turns the predictable into
poetry. And while the opening sequence of ``Saving Private Ryan''
may pack more special-effects power, you're not likely to forget
this film's brave, doomed beachfront assault. Gibson, as a harmless
rascal, and Mark Lee, as a sunshine boy sprung full-blown from a
Siegfried Sassoon poem, are both excellent as the two mates who
learn all too well where the paths of glory lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Last Wave'' (1977): Weir again, this time in a more
mystical mood. Richard Chamberlain, a.k.a. the once and forever Dr.
Kildare, looks like the whitest white man in the Southern
Hemisphere as a big-city lawyer who becomes involved in ancient
Aboriginal mysteries. While black rain and frogs fall on Sydney
(hmm, wonder if Paul Thomas Anderson watched this before writing
``Magnolia''), Chamberlain tries to sort out his strange dreams
which seem tied to an Aborigine prophecy about the world being
destroyed by a flood. And if you thought the wave at the end of
``The Perfect Storm'' was something, consider this movie's final
image.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Walkabout'' (1971): A sort of back-to-nature warm-up for
such suggestively image-laden films as ``Don't Look Now'' and ``The
Man Who Fell to Earth,'' Nicolas Roeg's first solo effort as a
director takes its power from the primal beauty of the Australian
wilderness and its multitude of inhabitants. Two well-off English
children _ young Lucien John (Roeg's son) and Jenny Agutter,
embodying the essence of an adolescent English Rose _ are suddenly
on their own in the Outback when their father commits suicide.
They're rescued by a young Aborigine (David Gulpilil, who's also in
``The Last Wave'') who imparts a few life lessons as he returns
them to safety. The story is pretty simple, but Roeg, a former
cinematographer, turns authenticity _ the film was shot on
location, a huge deal 30 years ago _ into artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
