<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILITARY-READINESS-HN     09-27 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-READINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILITARY CHIEFS SAY U.S. READINESS IS IN DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Echoing charges from Republican presidential
nominee George W. Bush that U.S. military readiness is slipping,
the nation's top uniformed officers told Congress Wednesday that
fighting preparedness has eroded to the point that the Pentagon's
strategy of being able to win two wars at once carries a risk of
higher casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy that has guided the military since the fall of the
Berlin Wall in 1989 has been to train for a worst-case scenario of
fighting two major wars at the same time. Simultaneous wars against
Iraq and North Korea are the most commonly cited hypothetical
example.
</P>
<P>
   But Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs, said
that a combination of factors has undermined U.S. military
readiness. He cited declines in defense budgets and overall force
levels over the last decade coupled with aging military equipment
and frequent deployments abroad on peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Shelton said, the U.S. armed forces likely would
prevail if war broke put in two different parts of the world _ but
the wars would last longer and U.S. casualties would be higher than
if readiness were not declining.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does mean is that it would take us longer to respond
to hostilities. In turn, that can mean territory lost and the
potential for a longer fight with increased casualties,'' Shelton
told the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assess the risk factors for fighting and winning the first
major theater war as moderate,'' Shelton said. But low readiness
rates for certain military units combined with problems in ferrying
weapons to the second war zone would result in a ``higher risk''
for the second theoretical conflict, he said, referring to higher
casualties and a lengthier conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The other service chiefs from the Army, Navy, Air Force and
Marine Corps agreed with Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Vern Clark, chief of naval operations, added that fighting
a second war at the same time ``will be a difficult task.'' Air
Force Chief of Staff Gen. Michael Ryan said that while the United
States at present could prevail in two wars, ``It's the future I
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The readiness of the U.S. military has become a campaign issue,
with Texas Gov. Bush and Dick Cheney, the vice presidential nominee
and a former defense secretary, contending that the armed forces
are in disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have accused the Clinton administration of
eroding military readiness by sending the armed forces abroad too
often on peacekeeping missions, by cutting defense spending and by
not replacing older weaponry. As a result, the GOP ticket argues on
the stump, the military has low moral, insufficient training and
outdated equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech, Bush said that the armed forces have been
``undermined by back-to-back deployments, poor pay, shortages of
spare parts and equipment, and rapidly declining readiness.'' Bush
has referred to the U.S. armed forces as ``a military in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration and Vice President Al Gore, Bush's Democratic
opponent, have conceded the military needs improvements,
particularly in pay and benefits, but that readiness is not
faltering. In fact, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart says the
Army, Marines and Air Force are more ready for battle today than in
1993, when Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, ranking Democrat on the committee,
countered Bush's charges Wednesday, saying that military readiness
had not slipped since 1993 when President Clinton took office.
Levin said, ``the quality of today's force is excellent by any
measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, who was appointed by Clinton, took pains not to endorse
Gov. Bush's readiness views. He said that the ``first to fight''
units _ those troops sent to police Kosovo and Bosnia and the
pilots enforcing no-fly zones over Iraq and Navy aircraft carriers
at sea, for example _ ``are trained and ready.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This readiness capability has repeatedly been demonstrated
during the past year in the Balkans, in Southwest Asia in East
Timor, and in other operations and exercises around the world,''
Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   But readiness is in decline among key support units, he said,
including intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance units,
combat support units, airlift aircraft and airborne tankers for
mid-air refueling.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving a specific dollar figure, the military chiefs
said that the services need more money to replace aging equipment
with new weapons that are less costly to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   For example, operations and maintenance costs in the Army ``have
increased by 30 percent over the last three years because it costs
more to maintain aging equipment,'' said Army chief of staff Gen.
Eric Shinseki.
</P>
<P>
   In the Air Force, the average age of planes is 22 years ``and we
are buying about one-third of the aircraft we need'' to replace the
aging force, said Ryan. ``We have never dealt with a force this
old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy, meanwhile, needs to buy between 160 and 180 planes
annually to replace existing planes for its aircraft carrier fleet
but has money for only 128 per year, said Clark. The Navy also
needs nine ships annually to sustain its current force level of 318
ships. But is purchasing about three less than required.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goure, a military analyst with the non-partisan Center
for Strategic and International Studies, said the testimony from
the chiefs underscored that the next president will need to commit
additional funds for national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without massive increases in funding, the U.S. military will
decline to a shadow of the force that won the Gulf and Kosovo
wars.'' Goure said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush have pledged more money for the military.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report, the Congressional Budget Office says it will
take an additional $51 billion a year over the next 15 years to
keep the U.S. military at its current strength. The CBO said that
the government should be spending about $340 billion annually to
sustain military levels and keep readiness constant. This year's
budget calls for $289 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
