<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LIZSMITH-MEMOIR-TEX     09-27 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIZSMITH-MEMOIR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP: CAN'T GET ENOUGH OF LIZ, AND GOSSIP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I first fell in love with Liz Smith as a boy growing up in New
York in the 1980s, when I was hopelessly addicted to the NBC
affiliate's daily news program, ``Live at Five.'' An odd mixture of
news, celebrity interviews and goofy banter, ``Live at Five''
employed Liz as its gossip reporter. She'd pop in three or four
times a week, muse in her relaxed Texas drawl about whichever stars
happened to be in the news that day, and then, after two or three
minutes of her shtick, shuffle off _ presumably to some fabulous
party or neon-lit Broadway opening.
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year-old, I probably should have been terrified by this
odd bird _ a preternaturally leathery old lady dressed in the sort
of unflattering '70s-era pantsuits that even my dotty old
grandmother knew enough to avoid. Instead, I was deeply intrigued.
As Liz yakked on and on about complete and utter nonsense (I seem
to remember Madonna and Sean Penn's marriage being one of her
favorite subjects), all I could think was: When I grow up, I want
this woman's job.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I decided to pursue a (slightly) more legitimate
path as a film critic, but Liz taught me some lessons. After all,
here was a woman who made a lot of money doing exactly what I loved
to do most as a kid _ namely, obsess about popular culture. She
helped me to understand that if you treat your passions seriously,
no matter what they are, people will treat you seriously for them.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is by way of saying that Liz's long-awaited memoir,
``Natural Blonde,'' has landed on my desk _ and it makes me happy
just to look at the cover. Liz beckons in all her blond-coiffed,
pantsuited glory before a bright yellow background. Unsurprisingly,
she's smiling. She's always smiling. Which is another reason I love
Liz. That smile is completely infectious. Perhaps it's her dowdy,
dorky manner, or perhaps it's her Southern-girl-done-good charm
(she was born, in fact, in Fort Worth) _ but whatever the case, she
makes us think that we can be just as fabulous, just as successful,
just as unabashedly frivolous as she is.
</P>
<P>
   What does one say about a book like ``Natural Blonde?'' It reads
like, well, a 445-page Liz Smith column. She drops names with the
fury of God sending down a plague of locusts. She precedes
virtually every one of these names with one of the following
phrases: ``my great friend ...,'' ``the brilliant ...'' or (my
personal favorite) ``that adorable rat fink.'' She writes things so
senseless _ ``Sometimes I say under my breath, `To be or not to be,
but to be in Vanity Fair.' '' _ that they almost sound profound.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite part of the book (and her column) is when she
shamelessly effuses over various celebrities. She likes to imagine
her favorites _ like Elizabeth Taylor or Madonna _ as some sort of
cosmic combinations of Laurence Olivier, Gandhi and Lady Godiva. In
Liz's world, the greatest virtues are talent, charitable largess
and physical beauty that's been tempered by sordid scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my single favorite moment of the book occurs when she
has drinks with Frank Sinatra, not long after having criticized
some of his loutish public behavior in her column. Her
so-purple-it's-bruised prose sums up a lifetime spent blissfully in
thrall of the stars: ``As his chauffeured car drove away, I
realized I had thrown all judgment to the wind. I was Sinatra's
slave. Co-opted by a couple of gin and tonics. I was his for the
rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   I know, it all sounds so lightweight, so empty-headed, so
relentlessly sycophantic _ so why can't I get enough of it?
</P>
<P>
   Because, quite simply, I love celebrity gossip. I'm a junkie.
Sure, there's a pernicious side to turning private lives public and
shaping human tragedy and trauma into easily digestible pop
entertainment. But I prefer to look on the brighter side, which is
that gossip also helps to fuel our most outlandish _ and, in this
celebrity-soaked age, sometimes necessary _ pipe dreams: that we
can mingle with the rich and famous; that we're on a first-name
basis with Julia and Tom and Mel; that we can perhaps even BE one
of the rich and famous; above all, that we can pursue our quixotic
dreams and someone might even be foolish enough to reward us for
them.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of ``Natural Blonde,'' Liz rhetorically asks what she
wanted from her life. She writes: ``I wanted to win friends and
influence people. It happened. I wanted a voice. I got one six days
a week and in syndication for almost 30 years. ... I wanted to work
hard and be so absorbed that sleep would fall on me nightly like a
blessing. It does.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossip may be a trifling, meaningless pursuit. But this book
isn't _ because it shows us that a life lived to its fullest is the
happiest life of all. Keep smiling, Liz. You've earned it.
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Kelly is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7032, or e-mail:
cmkelly(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
