<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-DINING-LASVEGAS-900(2     09-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINING-LASVEGAS-900(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE DINING IN LAS VEGAS? YOU CAN BET ON IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The men and women who love business are beginning to
love men and women who cook.
</P>
<P>
   The businesspeople who built up this gambling oasis were more
concerned with house profits than house wines. But in recent years,
they've found that paying attention to the culinary side of the
house adds up on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 72 restaurants opened in Las Vegas, and many had
marquee names on the menu. One of the first big names to take his
show to Las Vegas was Mark Miller, owner and executive chef of the
Coyote Cafe in Santa Fe and Red Sage in Washington, D.C. Miller
opened his Las Vegas location in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Las Vegas, restaurants get tourist business on the weekend
and convention business during the week,'' Miller says. This
around-the-clock dining generates big cash. It also keeps hotel
guests in the hotel, the better to part the guest from his money at
the gaming tables. More big cash.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Vegas served the culinary equivalent of the lowest
common denominator. Buffets, hidden in the bowels of casinos behind
mazes of slot machines and keno parlors, were a big draw for their
prices, not their presentation. Shrimp cocktail, the celebration
food of the 1950s, was often as high up on the food chain as
restaurants swam.
</P>
<P>
   But since the early 1980s, eatertainment has become an American
avocation. Chefs have become celebrities, and dropping dish names
at dinner parties has become a parlor game. Now, avid diners can go
to Las Vegas and sample the food of the restaurant world's biggest
names.
</P>
<P>
   Can't make it to Boston to sample Todd English's food at Olives?
Don't have plans to jet into the Big Apple to check out Le Cirque?
Not to worry; you can go to branches of both restaurants in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware, though, that with the huge leap in quality, these
Vegas restaurants come with far higher tabs than the trenchermen
buffets. And if you lose most of your money at the gaming tables,
the buffets at Circus Circus feed 10,000 diners on an average day.
</P>
<P>
   AUREOLE, MANDALAY BAY HOTEL, (702) 632-7401:
</P>
<P>
   Despite its ``Mission: Impossible''-style 42-foot-tall wine
cellar _ servers are hoisted by a rope to grab one of the 10,000
bottles _ Charlie Palmer's restaurant doesn't disappoint in the
substance department.
</P>
<P>
   A slick hardscape of wood, water and metal results in a room
that is far more welcoming than it would seem. Some of that warmth
can be credited to a professional, egalitarian waiter who ushered a
lone woman to a banquet instead of the dining equivalent of Elba.
</P>
<P>
   The food is just as thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Aureole's fixed-price menu ($55) is three courses with as many
as 10 options each. The spiced lobster chowder, dolled up with
ambrosial mascarpone dumplings, made an impression that lasted for
days _ through many other solid meals. Spiced tuna tartare was the
only misstep _ the minced tuna was sided with sesame flatbread in
the shape of chopsticks. (Perhaps I was expected to eat the fish
Chinese-style?)
</P>
<P>
   But no matter. A superb blueberry Meyer lemon cheesecake was the
perfect meal ender _ a touch of citrus that left things on a light
note despite an hourlong meal.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner for two will run about $200.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER GRILL, MANDALAY BAY HOTEL, (702) 632-7403:
</P>
<P>
   The Mandalay Bay is a prime example of how Las Vegas hotels are
mixing up their offerings so guests won't get bored and stray. The
Food Network's Two Hot Tamales, Mary Sue Milliken and Susan
Feniger, offer up food that is fun and festive without being
stuffy.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's cantina opens at 11:30 a.m., offering lamb
tacos ($7), guacamole and chips ($7.50) and poblano quesadilla
($8.50). Remember, we said this food would cost you.
</P>
<P>
   COYOTE CAFE, MGM GRAND HOTEL, (702) 891-7349:
</P>
<P>
   Coyote Cafe is one of the old dogs on the Vegas scene, but don't
let that stop you from checking it out. Just down the way from the
wildly popular Emeril's New Orleans Fish House in the MGM, this
restaurant seems comfortable in its skin.
</P>
<P>
   This was the only restaurant where I had a waiter who was
middle-aged, a comforting sign. I approved when he tried to talk a
customer out of ordering a frozen margarita, saying the ice covered
the flavors. And I loved it when he brought my chile grilled ahi
tuna just as requested _ seared outside and cool in the middle. And
it didn't hurt that the fish was sided with tempura-fried fennel
and wonderful blue potato hash. Heaven. Age definitely has its
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   NOBU, HARD ROCK HOTEL, (702) 693-5090:
</P>
<P>
   Nobu rocks _ and not just in its location.
</P>
<P>
   This Japanese restaurant, co-funded by Robert De Niro, offers a
rollicking good time to well-heeled diners throwing back sake and
tucking into artful plates of sashimi. Howard Stern may be this
restaurant's biggest fan, but the clientele would not appear to be
his audience _ all were using their napkins and sitting upright in
their chairs.
</P>
<P>
   For a blowout meat, a multicourse meal at the chef's discretion
is $70 a person and up. A dinner entree runs around $25 per person.
</P>
<P>
   But half the fun with sushi and sashimi is the point-and-pick
element. The yellowtail ($7 for two pieces) was excellent, as was
the toro (tuna belly) at $10 each. I told you this food would cost
you.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner for two, depending on the gluttony factor, is around
$150.
</P>
<P>
   PICASSO, BELLAGIO HOTEL, (702) 693-7223:
</P>
<P>
   Picasso is one of the restaurants in Steve Wynn's Bellagio, a
complex built as a tribute to his art collection. Wynn's ego isn't
the only thing on display _ the folks in the restaurant are mighty
proud of themselves, too.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because it was named Best Restaurant of the Year in
``Esquire'' magazine, it's the most difficult room in town in which
to get a table. I made a reservation in June for an August meal. Is
it worth the price ($325 for two) and the advance planning? I don't
think so.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are lovely, with subtle touches of the painter's
southern France tucked into inconspicuous places. Beyond the
curtained window are energetic spouting fountains, in sort of a
Versailles _ or is it Kansas City? _ homage.
</P>
<P>
   Diners can go two ways with the menu _ an $85 five-course
``degustation'' menu or a $75 four-course dinner. To simplify the
wine process, a sommelier's wine pairing for each course is $48 for
the degustation, $38 for the prix fixe.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Julian Serrano is a former Alain Ducasse (he of the six
Michelin stars) protege, and the influence shows. The food is
beautifully presented _ a perfectly folded white napkin nestled
shells holding oysters in a Vermouth sauce. Andalusian gazpacho was
tarted up with lovely bits of Peekytoe crab.
</P>
<P>
   But as the meal progressed, dishes lost their focus. Medallions
of fallow deer were well-done _ but there were so many bits and
bites of vegetables that the meal became confusing. And irritating.
The waiter appeared to be a transplanted New Yorker. Overhearing a
comment about a $25 margarita, he seemed to assume that our table
might not be good for the bill. The rest of the meal featured
sarcastic responses and perfunctory service.
</P>
<P>
   TAQUERIA CANONITA, THE VENETIAN HOTEL, (702) 414-3773:
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Pyles' newest concept is Star Canyon lite _ smaller,
slightly less-expensive variations of the food he serves at his Oak
Lawn restaurant in Dallas. Difference is, here the food is served
next to the canal _ yes, that's right _ complete with gondolas,
that runs through the second floor _ yes, again _ of the Venetian
Hotel. (The Vegas edition of Star Canyon is on the first floor of
the same hotel.)
</P>
<P>
   Small plates are in the $6 range and are, indeed, small portions
of gorditas, tamales, tacos and the like. For more filling fare,
order chicken tampiqueno ($11) or grilled shrimp with toasted
cumin-lime crema. This food and experience don't touch the
experience of eating at Star Canyon, but for a quick bite, it's
fine. And comforting. It's good to know that Southwestern cuisine
has the legs to make inroads into a dining category that doesn't
require valet parking. And look for Taqueria Canonita to pop up all
over. The first Metroplex location has now opened in Plano.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
