<HEADER>
A3778 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     09-27 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE PIES ARE WORTH THE DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you haven't placed your Thanksgiving or Christmas pie order
with Auddrena Smith of Albany, Texas, you're just about too late.
</P>
<P>
   The banana cream pies, the coconut creams; all those pies with
the mountainous meringue toppings will be going to the early birds
_ the folks who live in the West Texas town near Abilene, or read
about Smith's pies in the local press.
</P>
<P>
   The Abilene newspaper recently ran a story about Smith's pies.
It came out on her 77th birthday; she got calls of congratulations,
but she also got a lot of holiday pie orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this thing has gone this far,'' she said,
laughing. ``My pies aren't really a business. It's just something
to do. I'm retired, and a lot of times there isn't much to watch on
television, and I get tired of reading. So I make pies.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a business aspect to her pies. The Fort Griffin
General Merchandise restaurant and the Terra Cotta tearoom in
Albany feature her pies.
</P>
<P>
   Smith makes deliveries to both each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how it started,'' she said. ``I asked to bring some
pies for dessert to a Lioness club meeting. We were meeting at the
Fort Griffin restaurant and I told Ali and Nariman Esfandiary, the
owners, that I would bring my own plates and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, they came to me and asked me if I would come to the
office,'' she remembered. ``I thought, `Oh, what is this about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the restaurant owners were looking for someone
to make pies, and once they tasted Smith's, they knew they had
found the right person.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 77 years old and have been cooking all my life,'' she
said. ``But I didn't ever think about selling anything. I wouldn't
be selling them now if it wasn't for that meeting. I just made them
for church dinners, or when neighbors got sick or were in the
hospital. Whenever the church had an event, I would get the
desserts. I usually take a pie. I keep the crust dough made up in
my freezer.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that she isn't getting rich making the pies, but that
it does give her something to do, and the money adds up. ``I'm
going to Branson, Missouri, in October,'' she said, ``and I don't
have to pay for the trip out of my living expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith can't divulge her recipes, she said, because the
restaurant owners are afraid that if everyone knows how to make the
pies, they'll stop coming to Albany to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Smith doubts that will happen, though. Making pies her way takes
a lot of time and care. The recipes were her mother's, and she has
never seen them in a cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I make my pie filling, I use a water bath, or
bain-marie,'' she said. ``When I make the cream filling, I put in
my sugar and cornstarch, then mix a little bit of milk with that to
form a base. Then I add egg yolks, and finish by adding the rest of
the milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I cook the filling in a pan over hot water. I put my
butter in it, then flavoring. If I'm making a fruit pie, I put in a
little more cornstarch so it will plate out, and I drain the fruit
really well, or it will be a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's most-requested pies are cherry, lemon meringue, lemon
chess, chocolate cream and coconut cream.
</P>
<P>
   For the crust, Smith said, she uses only Gold Medal flour and
Crisco shortening. The basic proportions for a batch of Smith's pie
crusts include 4 cups of flour, 2 cups of Crisco, a teaspoon of
salt and 1 cup of ``real cold'' sweet milk. It's enough for about
six pies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just work all that into a dough, cover it and refrigerate
overnight,'' she said. ``If you have to, you can make it early in
the morning and use it later that afternoon, but it won't be as
good as if you left it overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith rolls out the dough, places it in pie pans and stacks them
in the freezer. When it's time to use them, she lines them with wax
paper and weights them with dried beans or rice. They are baked in
a 400-degree oven for about 20 minutes, the weights and wax paper
are removed and the crusts are returned to the oven, under a
watchful eye, for an additional 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The meringue, something of a Smith signature, is made with six
egg whites. She beats the eggs until they are stiff, then adds a
mixture of sugar, cornstarch and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always mix your cornstarch with cold water,'' she said. ``Then
add the sugar and heat until the sugar is dissolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith works the hot liquid into the beaten egg whites, then
flavors the meringue mixture with a little vanilla, pineapple or
banana extract _ depending on which kind of pie she's making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to do more than give it just a little taste,''
she said of the extracts. ``I want just enough to flavor the egg
whites. It doesn't take much. I don't measure that. I just know
about what kind of little hole it's going to make and when that
little hole is filled, that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith warns emphatically, though, not to use lemon extract, and
``don't ever try lemon juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Both will quickly flatten the egg whites, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
