<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3789 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-`GIRLFRIEND'-TEX     09-27 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`GIRLFRIEND'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS NATIVE LIKES RUNNING WITH `GIRLFRIENDS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas native Jill Marie Jones has a great new job in LA for
which she gets to wear fabulous designer outfits, deliver witty
dialogue and nearly freeze to death on a Hollywood sound stage for
14 hours a day. Sound like fun?
</P>
<P>
   It is for this Girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, one of the stars of ``Girlfriends,'' UPN's new Monday
night sitcom about four African-American women (Tracee Ellis-Ross,
Golden Brooks, Persia White and Jones) with different dysfunctions,
opened to mixed reviews last month, with some critics calling the
show the black ``Sex and the City.'' But Jones is too busy having
the time of her life to get caught up in what other people think.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the most amazing feeling ever,'' says Jones, who
plays Toni, a shamelessly materialistic and manipulative real
estate agent in search of a man with the three P's _ Porsche,
portfolio and a closet full of Prada suits. ``To be in LA for only
1 1/2 years and to have my first real acting job on a prime-time
show, it's like an incredible thing. Toni is so much fun to play
because she's so unlike me. She's very `me' oriented, and I'm very
Southern and family-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' journey from Duncanville High School to Hollywood's
Paramount lot has been a surprisingly easy one considering that
there are so few quality parts for women _ particularly
African-American women _ in Tinseltown. She credits her good
fortune to determination and divine will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I wanted to be in entertainment,'' says Jones, a
former Dallas Cowboys cheerleader and Dallas Mavericks dancer whose
previous acting credits include the HBO movie ``America's Dream''
and NBC's Saturday morning series ``City Guys.'' ``I've been
modeling for a while, but I really wanted to be a soap opera
actress. I've been watching soaps since I was a little girl, and I
still do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't always been easy, but I'm blessed. Thank God. I have
friends who have been out here for years, and they're like still
knocking on doors. I didn't think it was going to happen this
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jones thinks LA is ``cool,'' she also says she ``would not
be here if it weren't for the business.'' And she books flights
back to Texas every chance she gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for me to be around family,'' says Jones,
who spends most of her time watching her soaps and Blockbuster
movies with her mom when she's in Dallas. ``I miss a lot about
Texas. Dallas represents more than home for me. It's a beautiful
place, and I love it. Hopefully, one day I'll be able to return.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in LA, Jones rarely has time to do anything outside work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what life is like outside of Paramount Studios,''
Jones says. ``We've been working so much. Sometimes we all hang out
together and do dinner or something. When we go dancing together,
something scary happens on the dance floor. It's out-of-body!
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing has really changed for me. All of this is still
somewhat surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
