<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3791 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-GIRL-FIGHT     09-27 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-FIGHT-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIGHT OF THEIR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
bc-GIRL-FIGHT (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily Newscc,78p3  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been hundreds of boxing movies. In recent years, as
female prizefighting has become more of a reality, a few quick-hit
films on that particular subject have slipped in and out of the
marketplace with about as much notice as a bleeder who never makes
it past the first round.
</P>
<P>
   So what makes ``Girlfight'' feel like a contender? For one
thing, its writer-director, Karyn Kusama, has been sparring for
seven years, and her experiential knowledge of gyms and the
characters she met there brings bracing life to what, in most other
boxing movies, are rote cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the film's star, first-time actress Michelle
Rodriguez. A young woman of fierce presence and smoldering
intensity, the uninhibited 22-year-old is frighteningly convincing
as a belligerent Brooklyn projects teen who discovers
self-discipline -- and, for the first time, the possibility of both
hope and love -- when she enters the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Although it took many years for Kusama, a longtime assistant to
indie film icon John Sayles, to gather the financing for her
low-budget featuremaking debut, and Rodriguez had to undergo a
grueling, 4 1/2-month training regimen before the project began,
the effort, so far, seems to have been worth it. ``Girlfight'' won
the best directing award and shared the grand jury prize at the
Sundance Film Festival in January and was a popular favorite at the
prestigious Cannes festival in May.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of this highly personal but potential-laden
labor of love's commercial release, its principle girls are girding
for the fight of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard to make a movie, but now I'm realizing that
there's a whole other, second process of getting the movie out
there and seen,'' notes Kusama, a 32-year-old New York University
film school graduate who's wanted to direct since she fell in love
with mvies during her St. Louis childhood. ``I hope people will
respond. I have a good sense that it's a somewhat likable film. I
don't want to say it's commercial, but it is an emotionally
accessible film. And people always like a good story, for the most
part.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kusama sounds a bit tentative at this advanced stage of the
game, imagine the creatively volatile combination of instinctual
aesthetics and uncertainty that's gone into ``Girlfight'' from its
very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, what's a suburban woman of Japanese-Midwestern
parentage doing making a story about inner-city Latinos? And then
giving the starring role to a snarly Jersey girl -- after passing
on some 350 other applicants, many of them professional actresses
-- who just got fired from her Toys 'R' Us job?
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was always that one about a woman making a
film about an extremely masculine-identified sport. But it's clear
that Kusama was better prepared for that part of the task than most
men who've aimed cameras at the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised, to be honest, by how many boxing movies I see
that don't have much understanding of boxing,'' Kusama notes. ``I
think what has informed films' interest in the boxing world for so
long was that world outside of the ring, because it was so colorful
and filled with drama. Of course, I wanted to represent that
beautiful, rich culture, but I wanted to have something going on in
the ring that felt as substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something that we forget about boxing is that it is a sport
and it requires strategy and a kind of mental skill and toughness,
not just brawn. I wanted to create a story around a character
learning a craft.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Rodriguez fit in. Beautifully. Despite her complete
lack of boxing knowledge and minimal movie experience (she'd been
an extra in ``Summer of Sam,'' ``For Love of the Game'' and
``Cradle Will Rock''; hated it, too), she came to the cattle-call
audition -- her first -- with what the director calls ``presence
that just stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   The refreshingly upfront Rodriguez describes her appeal more
bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was PMS; PMS and pessimism,'' says the actress, a
onetime military brat who's been brought up, alternately, by a
Dominican mother and Puerto Rican father. ``That's the combination.
I'm such an extremist, sometimes, and could probably be an
extremely crazy broad. Karyn is so, like, together; we're total
opposites. I'm this weirdo who always gets there late while she's
so on-point and knows what she wants. But she saw something in me
that I didn't know was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, getting Rodriguez reliably to ``Girlfight's'' sets
entailed moving her into the home of one of the film's producers
during production. On the other hand, the novice actress displayed
an incredible dedication to physical training for months before
production started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picture this: You get up, five days a week, and travel two
hours on trains from Jersey City all the way to Brooklyn,''
Rodriguez explains. ``Once you get there, you change and run for a
half hour, usually about two miles. Then you jump rope for 15 to 20
minutes, which is pretty painstaking. And that's just the warmup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, you move strategically in the ring for 15 minutes,
throwing punches. Then you go hit the speedbag; getting my timing
precise for that was the hardest thing of all. After that, you
spar, maybe, twice out of the five-day week. You're dodging punches
and getting frustrated because you are not as trained as the person
you're fighting or getting punched in the gut because you are more
trained than the person you're fighting, and he's 20 pounds heavier
and a guy and angry because you whacked him. Then you go to
calisthenics and get 20-pound sandbags thrown on your stomach.
...''
</P>
<P>
   OK. We're exhausted just hearing about it. And remember, there
were a few required acting classes, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a whole mental experience of preparing for this
role, too,'' Rodriguez acknowledges. ``I'm much more rambunctious
than the character in this movie, much more talkative. I took about
a month's worth of training with an acting coach in the Village,
and his focus was to teach me to internalize my emotions. Karyn
really wanted me to get to that internal core, and what I had to do
was just suck it all in.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama, who refers to Rodriguez as ``The Hurricane,'' admits
that she took a big gamble on the untried girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle's instincts were great, and she just had a great, raw
talent as both an athlete and actor,'' Kusama notes. ``But it was a
big risk to cast such an untested property. Everybody you work with
has that to some degree; I just presumed it would be more volatile
with her. To some degree it was, but you know, she showed up and
was a total pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Although new to the movie and boxing games, Rodriguez was in a
position to judge Kusama's ability in a key area, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Karyn's depiction of Latin families and Latinos was
incredibly well-done,'' the actress says. ``I think that had to do
with hanging around the gym for seven years, getting to know the
coaches and going to the parties at their homes. There's a very
big, intense, crazy love of life within Latin minority groups, and
acceptance of situations that you're in. That's a beautiful thing
that I think she was able to capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama, though always reluctant to acknowledge getting anything
right, traces whatever works in the movie to her love of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really responded to the routine, the repetitiveness and
the aggressiveness of boxing,'' notes the director, who was turned
on to fighting by a female co-worker at a New York film exchange.
``Figuring out ways to find what power you have, and then control
it, was exhilarating, and I believe it's a theme in a lot of our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought the sport was great. But more than that, I
loved the workout, and I loved the people, who I felt that, over
time, accepted me. The gym was a place unlike any other for me, in
terms of how lively it was and how mixed it was, with so much
interaction between all different kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what a lot of storytelling is is trying to find
what you connect to in a foreign world,'' Kusama concludes. ``That
foreign world, to some degree, can be your imagination. I was
definitely concerned, while I was making this film, about creating
an authenticity to the world, the characters, to their struggle; I
can't be sure, obviously, that I succeeded, but I wanted to find
the emotional honesty there. I think that's the big struggle: You
can get the facts and do the research, which is the stuff that's
just my obligation as a storyteller. But then, to find what's real,
that's more the role of the artist.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
