<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ENTERTAINMENT-KIDS28-     09-27 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-KIDS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS DUBIOUS OF FILM INDUSTRY'S MARKETING PROMISES
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opening Scene: Eight movie moguls sit at witness
table facing a committee of skeptical senators, only hours after
revelations that major studios used children as young as 9 to
screen R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   These are Hollywood's top honchos, star-makers and star-breakers
powerful enough to green-light a $50 million movie from their car
phones. But now they're pitching a proposal of their own: the
studios will voluntarily restrict marketing of violent and raunchy
movies to underage audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It's classic East Coast vs. West Coast, political polls vs. box
office. Elections are only weeks away, and some of the senators
have actually read the movie-makers' proposed guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filled with loopholes,'' proclaims the committee chairman,
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   There is stirring in the ornate Capitol Hill hearing room jammed
with lobbyists and journalists and activist moms and PR types and
TV crews and aspiring screenwriters hoping to slip a script to a
Hollywood executive. Conflict in the opening scene has grabbed this
audience.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called Wednesday's hearing of the Senate Commerce
Committee after the studio chiefs snubbed an earlier session to
review a Federal Trade Commission report that the entertainment
industry was targeting underage children with advertising for
R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday, The New York Times reported that major
studios routinely recruited underage teenagers and children as
young as 9 for audiences test-screening rough cuts of violent films
and trailers for R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Under committee questioning, some studio executives admitted
peddling inappropriate movies to underage audiences in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Harris, president of Sony, parent company of Columbia
Pictures, conceded that it was ``judgment lapse'' to try to
advertise ``The Fifth Element,'' a violent PG-13 science fiction
film starring Bruce Willis, on the children's network Nickelodeon.
The network refused the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said their new guidelines would end such
inappropriate marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he was ``concerned about the language'' in the
proposals. One pledge, for instance, is that ``each company will
review its marketing and advertising practices in order to further
the goal of not inappropriately specifically targeting children in
its advertising of films rated 'R' for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not simply say 'we will not market R-rated movies to
children under 17, period'?'' asked McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Because some R-rated movies _ like ``Saving Private Ryan,'' for
instance _ are appropriate for some teens under 17, replied Stacy
Snider, chairman of Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Such responses displeased some committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, noted that the government
has stepped in to prevent kids from being targeted by tobacco and
alcohol ads. If the entertainment industry doesn't stop on its own,
she warned, ``you're going to see some kind of legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the studio heads warned that such legislation might violate
constitutional guarantees of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition its action on R-rated films, the industry should
stop peddling PG-13 movies to pre-teens during commercials for
cartoons and other children's programs, senators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to review the appropriateness of all
advertising,'' promised Rob Friedman, vice chairman of Paramount's
Motion Picture Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America announced 12 new
guidelines for its marketing practices the day before the hearing.
Committee members called the proposals a promising first step, but
pressed for more concrete pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., asked if the studios would promise
flatly to stop advertising R-rated movies on Internet sites
primarily visited by teenagers. Several of the executives refused,
insisting that such decisions must be made on a film-by-film basis.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, some executives declined to forswear airing any
commercials for R-rated movies on TV networks before 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   However, the studios did unanimously promise not to
``knowingly'' allow children under the age of 17 into research
screenings for films rated R for violence unless they are
accompanied by a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman believes the entertainment industry needs to
work more on the conclusion of this saga.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines represent ``significant progress,'' McCain
concedes. But ``the language is not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And even beyond cleaning up its marketing practices, he says,
the entertainment industry should consider a ``universal system''
to rate everything from movies to TV shows to video games.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.mpaa.org and www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
