<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUTS ABOUT ENGLISH TOFFEE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeannie Wright was one of several readers who sent in the
requested recipe for English toffee. In fact, the recipe she sent
looks as if it was clipped from an electric company newsletter. And
Doris Bettis of Trophy Club sent her version of the recipe, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH TOFFEE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 25 squares
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce package chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped almonds or pecans
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and water in saucepan. Add butter and heat slowly
until completely melted. Add salt and corn syrup. Cook to 260
degrees or soft-crack stage. Add vanilla; pour into 8-inch-square
pan and allow to cool. Melt chocolate and spread on toffee.
Sprinkle with nuts. Cool and cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per square: 148 calories, 10 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 20 milligrams cholesterol, 101
milligrams sodium, 64 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND TOFFEE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter (no substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped almonds, toasted, see Note
</P>
<P>
   4-ounce bar milk chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 3/4 cup finely chopped almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Note: Pecans, walnuts or almonds can be used in this recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter 15 1/2-by-10 1/2-by-1-inch jellyroll pan.
</P>
<P>
   In heavy pan over medium high heat, cook butter, sugar, salt,
water and corn syrup to hard crack stage (290 degrees), stirring
constantly with a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately remove from heat and stir in coarsely chopped
almonds. Pour into prepared pan and spread mixture to edges. Cool
for a few minutes. When cool enough to touch, remove from pan and
place on a sheet of waxed paper. Microwave chocolate bar until
melted. Spread over top of toffee and sprinkle with finely chopped
almonds. Chill for 1 hour. Break into pieces and store in air-tight
container.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of toffee may be coated with chocolate, requiring an
additional chocolate bar and 1/2 cup finely chopped nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per ounce: 118 calories, 9 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 13 milligrams cholesterol, 54
milligrams sodium, 65 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   Bennie Wise sent the following e-mail: ``I was born and raised
in Shreveport, La. My deceased mother made the best chicken (or
turkey) and dressing I've ever eaten. Problem _ she never measured
anything, so she couldn't tell you how much of an ingredient. She
used homemade corn bread, onions, celery, eggs, salt, pepper, broth
(didn't like canned broth _ said the taste of the real thing was
better). She very gently toasted white bread in the oven until it
was totally dried out and lightly brown. She never used poultry
seasoning or sage. Can anyone give me a similar recipe?''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
