<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REQUIEM-WEBSITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIND TRIP 
`DREAM' SITE MIGHT BE A NIGHTMARE
</HEADLINE>
bc-REQUIEM-WEB (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily Newscc,78p3  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a trip to www.requiemforadream.com and you'll find yourself
wondering if you have taken the wrong potion in Wonderland. This is
not your usual movie promotional Web site, but then ``Requiem for a
Dream'' is not from your usual filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Aronofsky, whose first film, ``Pi,'' dealt with an
obsessed math genius, turns his attention to Hubert Selby Jr.'s
novel of drug-fueled delusion and isolation in the Coney Island
district of New York. ``Requiem,'' which stars Ellen Burstyn, Jared
Leto, Jennifer Connelly and Marlon Wayans, is set for release Oct.
20 from Artisan. Though the film is currently unrated (it was
originally rated NC-17, but the filmmakers withdrew their
application), there is little as far as we can tell that is overtly
sexual, violent or advocates drugs.
</P>
<P>
   What you find when you first encounter the site which uses movie
scenes, excerpts from the book and sound bytes is an upbeat,
somewhat confusing scene. Soon, though, as you try to interact,
colors begin to fade, error messages occur, and you're directed
into weird places. If you don't know any better, you'll think there
is something wrong with your computer and you're no longer in
control. The site, according to Artisan, is meant to be an extended
mind trip that mirrors the characters' quest for happiness and
their ultimate disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   You be the judge as to whether this Web site works or not, but
it's clear that you'll be seeing more of these kinds of adventurous
sites as studios seek new ways to promote their films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
