<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jew vs. Jew'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Samuel G. Freedman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the most horrible people that God put breath in,'' a
woman says about the strictly observant Hasidic Jews of Kiryas
Joel, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A member of some anti-Semitic fringe group? No, the naysayer is
Jewish, and the conflict embodied in that situation is the essence
of Samuel G. Freedman's informative ``Jew vs. Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the suburban streets of Great Neck to the foot of the
Western Wall, I have witnessed the struggle for the soul of
American Jewry,'' the Columbia University professor writes, saying
that the central questions are: How is Jewish identity defined? Who
decides what true Judaism is? What is the Jewish compact with
America?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jew vs. Jew'' divides itself into six major sections, pairing
an introductory essay with an illustrative episode. For instance,
``Unity vs. Pluralism: Visions of Jewish Community'' embodies
itself in an unsuccessful Modern Orthodox push for a
synagogue-school campus that bitterly divides an Ohio town _ a
community that is more than 80 percent Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman's book is fairly lengthy (about 350 pages) but quite
readable, and it provides a picture of religious and cultural
conflict that has undoubtedly evaded the radar of many readers. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesus Mysteries: Was the `Original Jesus' a Pagan God?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Freke and Peter Gandy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harmony Books, $24.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether you conclude that this book is the most alarming heresy
of the millennium, or the mother of all revelations, ``The Jesus
Mysteries'' deserves to be read.
</P>
<P>
   Its premise is that Jesus Christ was not a historical figure,
but a Jewish adaptation of the pagan ``god man'' myth. The authors
insist that their research points to a Christianity that is even
older than 2,000 years. Today's Christians, in their myriad
denominations, are painted as the descendants of the Gnostics.
</P>
<P>
   Event by event _ starting with the virgin birth in a cowshed,
all the way to the martyred death and miraculous resurrection _
parallels are found for The Greatest Story Ever Told in the
mythology of ancient Egypt, Greece and Persia. Each example is
weighted with notes and sources.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, the systematic deconstruction of Christian
mythology becomes a little tedious. But just when you want to shut
the book, along comes a provocative summary or analysis that tempts
you to read on. At the end, you are left with a reaffirmation of
Christian antiquity _ and a better understanding of paganism, to
boot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Amrita Shlachter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
