<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TV-WRIGHT-NYT &LR;      09-27 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-WRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC CHIEF LAUDS NETWORK'S PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Wright, the president of NBC, has heard all the criticism of
the network's coverage of the Sydney Olympics and has seen the
ratings fall below NBC's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains steadfastly upbeat. ``I feel terrific about the
coverage,'' he said by phone from Sydney. ``I'm finding the whole
experience very exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   He is referring in part to the experience of being in Sydney
itself, traveling to the event sites, which he described as
spectacularly beautiful. But Wright emphasized that NBC is making
no apologies either for its coverage or for its ratings
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings may have fallen short of NBC's promises to
advertisers, but, he said, ``We're reaching 23, 24, 25 million
viewers a night.'' That has been good enough on most nights to beat
all of NBC's network competition combined, validating, by NBC's
definition, the status of the Olympics as one of television's
signature big events.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era of fractionalizing audiences,'' Wright said, ``the
ability of the Olympics to gather audiences of that size will only
get more valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he was encouraged that the ratings began to
increase during the second week of broadcasts, something that
usually does not happen. But that upward trend did not hold up
through Tuesday night, when NBC suffered a steep drop-off, scoring
just a 12.4 rating, one of the lowest for any night of an Olympics
in history.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives said Wednesday that they expected a weaker
performance because the second Tuesday, with gymnastics over and no
main track-and-field events scheduled, always brings a lull in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   NBC filled with cycling, volleyball and a heavy dose of weight
lifting. Audiences fell away. From 8 p.m. to 9 p.m., the Olympics
came close to being beaten by a rerun of a celebrity edition of the
ABC game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, while praising the production work in Sydney under Dick
Ebersol, said he agreed with some of the reasons being cited for
NBC's struggle with the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That time difference is really tough,'' Wright said. ``I don't
really know what Dick could have done about that.'' Certainly NBC
made its ratings situation more difficult by extending its
prime-time hours from 7 p.m. to midnight, up from the traditional 8
to 11. ``That set up some rather nasty comparisons with past
Olympics,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   But like many other NBC executives, Wright totally disparaged
the comparison to the live telecasts of events being carried by
Canadian television, noting that NBC could hardly pay $705 million
for rights to the Games and then run them live from 3 a.m. to 8
a.m, as the CBC is doing. ``That isn't even working for Canada,''
Wright said, noting that ratings there are ``minuscule.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the rating patterns in the United States have
taken an odd turn, with the Olympics playing best in cities where
they are the most delayed. Among the top 20 cities, the highest
ratings are from West Coast markets like Seattle, San Francisco and
Los Angeles, while only one city in the Eastern time zone,
Philadelphia, is among the top 20. To NBC executives this suggests
that the time delay is not completely the problem, though it may
have something to do with the media concentration in the East,
where the results seem inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Wright pointed out that the ratings news has been good for NBC
elsewhere than in network prime time. The ``Today'' show is at
near-record rating levels, and NBC's cable channels, MSNBC and
CNBC, are up by two and three times more than their normal ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Wright recalled that eight years ago in Barcelona, Spain, NBC
tried the infamous ``Triplecast,'' pay-per-view supplementary
coverage of the Games on cable channels in partnership with
Cablevision. ``We each ended up losing $50 million,'' he said.
``This year we have the true Triplecast. Baseball and softball and
boxing are totally available on cable, and they're doing very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, without citing specific figures, Wright said,
``Financially, we're going to be fine.'' Before the Games he had
predicted that NBC would make a very small profit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, everything that is happening to NBC at Sydney, good and
bad, is relevant to the network's financial future, because NBC has
committed more than $3 billion in rights to the next five Olympics.
Wright stressed that NBC remains enthusiastic about holding those
rights, though he conceded that it is incumbent on NBC to improve
on ways it can keep viewers informed about Olympic athletes between
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true with young viewers, he said, many of
whom don't follow Olympic sports at all. ``The Internet will be a
big part of that challenge,'' he said. NBC will try to use the
Internet to keep interest in Olympic athletes high.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping advertisers excited about supporting the Games may be
the biggest challenge. Wright conceded that with the Salt Lake City
Winter Games coming up in just 16 months, there is a risk of
Olympic oversaturation. But he said that he would certainly not
favor a return to the days when both winter and summer Olympics
were held in the same year. ``If I'm an advertiser, that doesn't
work for me,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, ``Salt Lake City is a domestic Olympics. That
will take care of itself.'' He said NBC has already sold about 60
percent of the advertising time for Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But the Summer Games in Athens will follow only another 17
months after Salt Lake City. The figure for advertising sold for
that production is at 20 percent. ``Athens is the next challenge,''
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-OIL-PRICES-HNS &LR;      09-27 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. ENERGY OFFICIAL SAYS HEATING OIL PRICES WILL STABILIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the help of President Clinton's decision to
release 30 million barrels of oil, home heating oil prices will
stabilize over the next several months, a top Energy Department
official predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the winter months, consumers should see prices holding
steady,'' Robert S. Kripowicz, acting assistant secretary for
fossil energy, told the Joint Economic Committee of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned that prices will remain ``substantially'' higher
than last year and that the decision to release the oil over the
next 30 days from the nation's emergency reserve can't prevent
price spikes caused by an unusually cold winter or shipping
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people should understand that this policy is not
an iron-clad guarantee and that they could see some kind of
temporary price increases because of a number of reasons,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kripowicz also rejected claims that the administration's release
of 30 million barrels _ which equals about 1-and-1/2 days worth of
oil used in the United States _ would have little impact on prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to remember that the current price jump was caused
by the reduction of only about one or two million barrels a day,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kripowicz said that replenishing a million barrels a day to the
market should cause prices to level off.
</P>
<P>
   World production of crude oil is between 75 million and 76
million barrels a day, with the United States consuming about 19
million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of home heating oil have fallen in the wake of the
Clinton administration's decision but they remain near 10-year
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have predicted that consumers will pay close to $2 a
gallon to fill their home heating oil tanks this winter. The East
Coast retail price averaged $1.4635 a gallon last winter, with a
high of $1.9470 in the first week of February, according to the
Energy Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal winter, a typical house uses 680 gallons of home
heating oil, according to the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Kripowicz said that increased production from OPEC members also
should cause oil prices to begin to fall sometime next spring or
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that neither the release of the strategic
reserve oil nor OPEC's promised increase in output this winter will
help increase inventories of home heating oil, which reached a
24-year low in August.
</P>
<P>
   Home heating oil inventories, according to the Energy
Department, are at 48.1 billion barrels, down from 72.4 billion a
year ago. On the East Coast, heating oil inventories are 24.4
billion barrels, down from 48.5 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 800,000 barrels a day in increased production that OPEC
promised earlier this month will not start flowing until Oct. 1,
and it takes about six weeks to arrive at refineries in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The crude oil from the reserve is not expected to show up as
home heating oil at the retail level until the end of November or
December.
</P>
<P>
   Kripowicz said the low inventories and rising prices were caused
by low oil prices in the mid-1990s _ which pushed both foreign and
domestic producers to cut back or shut down _ and a sharp increase
in demand for oil resulting from the economic boom in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Vice Chairman Jim Saxton, R-N.J., said the release of
the strategic reserve oil should be a temporary solution to
``America's dependence'' on foreign oil. He said the government
needed to develop a policy to promote more domestic oil exploration
and to use U.S. influence to stop OPEC members from ``exploiting''
U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States must do everything in its power to undermine
the OPEC cartel and its monopoly power over supply and prices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States imports 57 percent of the crude oil it
consumes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
