<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASEBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONSTARS ALL, U.S. DETHRONES CUBA IN BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo OLY 6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ As the United States closed in on a
remarkable victory over Cuba Wednesday night, Bob Watson, the man
who helped put the team together, rose from his seat behind home
plate and began to accept congratulations. When Mike Neill made a
sliding catch of Yasser Gomez's fly ball to left to seal Ben
Sheets' three-hit shutout, the emotion that had been building since
the middle of the third inning exploded in chants and cheers.
Watson and his wife, Carol, were right there in the middle of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   The United States upset Cuba, 4-0, to win its first Olympic gold
medal in baseball. The victory was not met with the cascades of
emotion that Cathy Freeman of Australia received on Tuesday _
nothing the United States will do here will equal those _ but it
came close.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. baseball team had done the impossible. Four days after
being vanquished by mighty Cuba, ruler of international baseball
for decades, a U.S. team mixed with minor leaguers past their prime
and young players still short of theirs snapped Cuba's domination.
This team won the U.S. first official Olympic gold medal in the
sport known as the American pastime.
</P>
<P>
   True, the United States won the gold at the 1988 Seoul Olympics,
but baseball was a demonstration sport that year and _ more
important _ Cuba boycotted those Games. But Cuba, the two-time
defending gold medalist, had been front and center in international
baseball for a long time, and Cuban scouts said this team was one
of their country's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys pitching for the Cubans can go right into the
majors,'' said Tommy Lasorda, the U.S. manager. ``But it's not
always the best team that wins or the strongest man who wins the
fight. In most cases, it's who wants it more than the other. We
wanted it more than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States jumped on Cuba immediately. Neill's solo home
run in the first inning set the tone; three runs in the fifth
sealed Cuba's fate. With a 4-0 lead, Sheets, 22, was untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   After Cuba won the gold in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992 and
repeated at Atlanta in 1996, Watson, the former major league player
and general manager, was part of a delegation to put together a
team of professional players who would stand up to the Cubans. This
eclectic group of players rose to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday night's game, Lasorda gushed _ as only he can _
that this was larger than winning a World Series ring, that he felt
more excited about Neill's home run than he did about Kirk Gibson's
famous pinch-hit homer in the 1988 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other one was for a team,'' Lasorda said. ``This is bigger
than the World Series; I managed in four World Series _ it's
bigger. When the Dodgers win a championship, the Dodger fans were
happy. Today, the United States of America is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   This victory did not have the suddenness of the Miracle On Ice
in 1980 at Lake Placid, when a young American hockey team upset the
powerful, unbeaten Russians. This was closer to an extended rescue
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The national pastime had been appropriated by Cuba, which has
dominated not only the U.S. team but all others in international
baseball for decades. The Cubans were 64-1 in international
tournaments between 1986 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The perplexing question for the United States was twofold:
</P>
<P>
   How could the nation that invented the game, a nation in which
baseball's mythology is so much a part of its character, a nation
whose lore and spirit is wrapped up in the game, be so thoroughly
dominated by an island nation a fraction of its size?
</P>
<P>
   The other question, expressed as a doubt, was: Could this team
break down a teamful of stars?
</P>
<P>
   ``When this team was picked,'' said Doug Mientkiewicz, the U.S.
first baseman, ``a lot of people looked at the names on the list
and asked: `Who are these guys? Who are they sending over?' That
was the motivating factor for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Cuba's manager, Servio Borges, whether his team's
loss to the United States signaled the end of an era for Cuba, too.
He said no, quite the contrary. ``A new era is just beginning,'' he
said. ``This is the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Cuba Wednesday night became the victim of its own
success in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans forced the United States to get better, to drop
college players from its team and enlist toughened professionals to
uphold the nation's baseball image.
</P>
<P>
   For Cuba, the question is: Now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to work harder,'' Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart and soul of this U.S. team were three players whose
best days as major-leaguers were behind them. The grit came from
them. Ernie Young, the 31-year-old right fielder who now plays in
the Pacific Coast League in the St. Louis Cardinals organization,
broke the game open with a bases-loaded single. Pat Borders, the
37-year-old catcher who plays with Class AAA Durham for the Tampa
Bay Devils Rays, delivered an RBI double. And Neill, 30, who is
with Class AAA Tacoma in the Seattle Mariners' system, had the
early home run.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the U.S. team rests with a pitcher like Sheets,
who is just beginning his career in the Milwaukee Brewers' system.
Sheets, who signed the highest bonus in Brewers history, played at
Class A Huntsville and Class AAA Indianapolis this season. He
should move into the major league rotation next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first got here I predicted that when this is all over,
everybody in the world is going to know about these players.''
Lasorda said. ``By golly, they know now that these guys are
outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
