<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM EXECUTIVE ADMITS `JUDGMENT LAPSE' IN TRYING TO ADVERTISE TO
KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A top entertainment executive told the Senate
Commerce Committee on Wednesday that it was a ``judgment lapse''
for his movie company to try to advertise a film with violent
scenes on a children's television network.
</P>
<P>
   The executive, Mel Harris, president and chief operating officer
of Sony Pictures Entertainment, defended his company in another
instance when children aged 9 to 11 were interviewed as part of the
test marketing of a violent R-rated movie. But Harris said Columbia
Pictures, a subsidiary of Sony, would no longer use under-age
children in focus groups unless they were accompanied by their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was one of eight executives from the country's largest
movie studios who testified Wednesday before the Senate commerce
committee about the marketing of violent movies to children.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the eight (not including Harris) promised they will stop
appealing to children younger than 17 in their marketing of R-rated
films. But the other four said they could not make such a promise
because it was appropriate for some children under 17 to see some
R-rated movies, like ``Saving Private Ryan'' or ``Amistad,'' with
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Motion Picture Association of America announced
new voluntary steps to limit the marketing of adult-rated movies to
children. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who heads the Commerce
Committee, was critical of the new policy. ``I don't understand
this language,'' McCain said. ``It is filled with loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson, R-Texas, said Wednesday that if the
industry does not take steps to keep violent films away from young
children ``you're going to see some kind of legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   At another hearing on the other side of the Capitol, an awkward
moment occurred when a congressman asked Gerald Levin of Time
Warner whether the media promoted violence. Levin, whose son was
killed, responded that the congressman had not experienced violence
as a personal tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
