<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBBETS-FIELD-RELICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EBBETS LIGHTS ARE DIMMED AGAIN, A LINK TO DODGERS NEEDS A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Mass., Ill.)   By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lights of Ebbets Field, which gazed down on a
golden past of Robinsons and Reeses and Walkers and Furillos, found
a home in Downing Stadium when the wrecking ball tore into the home
of the Dodgers and stilled the heart of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Now dem lights _ or whatever may be left of them _ are about to
go homeless again.
</P>
<P>
   Downing Stadium faces demolition this fall as part of a $200
million renovation of Randalls Island, its home near the Triborough
Bridge and at the conjuncture of Manhattan, Queens and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The Randalls Island Sports Foundation, a public-private
partnership with the Parks Department that is developing the park,
plans to hand over the stadium, emptied of anything of value, to
the demolition contractor on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is worth saving, if it means something to
someone,'' said Parks Commissioner Henry J. Stern. ``If these are
the lights from Ebbets Field, they have to be preserved. You'd have
to be a philistine to destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklynites still call Walter O'Malley far worse than a
philistine for moving their beloved Bums to Los Angeles after the
1957 season. Indeed, the lights are a reminder of the power of one
of America's great nostalgia machines: baseball. The Dodgers are
still such a powerful presence in Brooklyn that the design for the
proposed New York Mets stadium consciously evokes Ebbets Field, and
a Dodger flag flies over Brooklyn Borough Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But the lights are not the only holy relic from New York's
baseball past.
</P>
<P>
   Another stadium, the Polo Grounds of the New York Giants, was
done in four years after the same wrecking ball demolished Ebbets
Field in 1960. (The ball was painted white, like a baseball, in a
whimsy of the time that now seems cruelly mocking.)
</P>
<P>
   At the former stadium sites, the only remnants are plaques and
the names, which are attached to housing projects. But in spots
around the city, in museums and in private homes, bits and pieces
of New York stadium history abound.
</P>
<P>
   Over on Utica Avenue in East Flatbush, in front of Canarsie
Casket Co., stands the center field flagpole from Ebbets Field. It
was erected there by Marvin Kratter, a developer who owned the
stadium in its final years and who built the housing project,
according to a plaque.
</P>
<P>
   The pole is a source of pride for Samuel M. Romano, an owner of
the casket company, who worked as a maintenance man at Ebbets Field
and still loves his old team. ``We're Mets fans, but really Dodgers
fans,'' he said. That's the Brooklyn Dodgers, please understand.
</P>
<P>
   Kratter also donated about 2,200 Ebbets seats to a ball field
for inmates at the old workhouse on Hart Island. After years
exposed to the elements, they fell into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   Some were salvaged and presented by the Brooklyn Dodger Hall of
Fame to former Dodger players. A few iron frames were passed on to
the office of the New York City correction commissioner, said
Thomas C. McCarthy, a correction spokesman. One was given as a gift
to honor the long service of a correction officer who worked on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Old Ebbets Field seats, in fact, are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Donald N. Thompson, a Dodger outfielder in 1951-54 now living in
Asheville, N.C., has several. A client of his real estate business
gave them to him several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still got them,'' Thompson said. ``They work perfectly, No.
23 and 24. They fold up in back, in that old Dodger blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum in Cooperstown has
one, plus two benches from a grandstand, the cornerstone and home
plate. Four seats reside at the Brooklyn Historical Society, along
with another home plate, a base, a section sign, a brick and the
1955 World Series pennant.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Gladstone, a collector and the owner of the Class A
minor-league team in Pittsfield, Mass., owns a bronze plaque that
hung in the Ebbets Field rotunda and lists the team's ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The Polo Grounds has a lower profile in the nostalgia gallery,
but its ghosts also linger.
</P>
<P>
   Up in Manhattan and a mile or so north of Downing Stadium stands
a decrepit concrete staircase. Clothes litter the steps. Most of
its railing is gone. A chain link fence blocks the top entrance, at
Edgecombe Avenue and 158th Street. But large bronze letters on the
middle landing declare: ``The John T. Brush Stairway presented by
the New York Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Named after a Giants owner, the stairway descends part of
Coogan's Bluff, down to a road that runs into Harlem River Drive
and just a few hundred feet from where the Polo Grounds stood.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mandt, director of operations at Shea Stadium, says he
has a little piece of the roof from a Polo Grounds dugout, courtesy
of a former Shea employee whose father, a rabid fan of the Giants,
salvaged it during the demolition, just as many fans scooped up
earth and bits of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame in Cooperstown holds other remnants of the Polo
Grounds: the seat used by the wife of John McGraw, the Giants
legendary manager; a concession stand; a souvenir board; a
megaphone used for announcements before a public address system was
in place; a turnstile; several seats; iron figures from an aisle
shaped with the letters NYG; and a gong used to signal the start of
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Less well-known stadiums have left remains. Near the Gowanus
Canal in Brooklyn, a brick wall on Third Avenue between First and
Third streets forms part of a Consolidated Edison warehouse. Con Ed
and baseball historians say the wall came from Washington Park,
home of the Brooklyn Dodgers for 14 years before the team moved to
Ebbets Field in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Stengel played his first game at Washington Park, and Cy
Young his last.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the story of a relic is even better than the real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ebbets Field clock was long believed to have rested atop the
minor-league park in Asheville, N.C., home of the Asheville
Tourists. Not so, said the team's assistant general manager, Chris
J. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a scam,'' he said. ``Someone drove through the state
with a van full of Ebbets Field clocks, selling them to
minor-league stadiums.''
</P>
<P>
   Must have been a New Yorker, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The market for stadium memorabilia truly began with the
restoration of Yankee Stadium in the early 1970s, said Bert Sugar,
the boxing writer and baseball author and a collector.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors swept away old seats, metal plaques from box-seat
railings, bricks, even Stadium Club matchbooks, Sugar said. A
Japanese department store bought the flagpoles that bore pennants,
uniforms, even grounds-crew overalls.
</P>
<P>
   When the Boston Red Sox refurbished the famous wall in left
field in 1975-76, the team sold chunks for charity, Sugar points
out. The Chicago White Sox did the same with bricks and chairs from
the old Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
