<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERACTIVE-TV28-COX     09-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-TV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS CRITICIZE AGENCIES REVIEWING AOL MERGER
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House hearing Wednesday to examine interactive
television was dominated instead by lawmakers blasting the federal
regulators and antitrust officials reviewing the proposed merger of
Time Warner Inc. and America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the process stinks,'' said Rep. Billy Tauzin, chairman
of the House Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced Jan. 10, both the Federal Trade
Commission (FTC) and Federal Communications Commission (FCC) have
been studying it to determine whether the combination of AOL, the
world's No. 1 Internet company, and Time Warner, one of the world's
biggest cable and media companies, would force cable customers to
buy the new company's services and content.
</P>
<P>
   Because the review process often involves private negotiations
with corporate executives, the federal regulator has become ``the
master in a dark room,'' Tauzin told reporters after the hearing.
He said he will push legislation next year to bring ``sunshine'' to
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have been particularly concerned about interactive
television, a new technology that allows consumers to use their TV
sets to surf the Internet, send e-mail and exchange instant
messages while continuing to watch their favorite programs.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that consumers have many options for receiving this
and other Internet-related services, regulators are negotiating
with the companies. They appear poised to force the merger partners
to accept certain conditions to win approval of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Washington Post has reported that the FTC may
ask AOL to sell its $1.5 billion stake in General Motors Corp.'s
Hughes Electronics unit, a maker of satellites and a potential
competitor for Time Warner cable lines. And the Wall Street Journal
has reported that regulators might restrict AOL Time Warner's
relationship with AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, AOL Chief Executive Steve Case and Time
Warner Chief Executive Gerald Levin said their cable lines, instant
messaging services and interactive television will be open to
rivals, though they do not want to be bound by a legal requirement
for ``open access.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition from digital subscriber lines, wireless devices and
satellites will force them to provide customers with plenty of
choices, so there is no need for regulations, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, the executives sidestepped questions about their
merger on the grounds they were in negotiations with the FTC and
FCC.
</P>
<P>
   While Tauzin was criticizing regulators in his hearing, House
Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., was issuing a letter
to FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky saying his agency should not force
AOL Time Warner to open its cable lines to competitors, on the
grounds that the FTC lacks the expertise to dictate such a
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators should hold off on ``open access'' issues until a
national policy has been established and applied to all companies,
Bliley said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Case said the closed-door merger review process
was not the right place to create and impose a new policy for the
nation's cable system. ``There are some significant policy issues
that are best dealt with in the proper policy forum,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While Republican lawmakers were complaining about regulators,
Democrats were sharply criticizing Tauzin's decision to call only
Case and Levin to testify. Several Democratic subcommittee members
said corporate competitors and consumer groups also should get a
turn to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those groups have testified at other hearings, both in
Congress and before the FCC. ``I think this merger has been the
most scrutinized merger in history,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tauzin said he would hold a second hearing for merger
opponents, most likely on Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of both companies already have approved the deal.
The companies say they expect to win regulatory approval later this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission, www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission, www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   AOL, www.corp.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, www.timewarner.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
