<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EBBETS-FIELD-RELICS-2     09-27 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBBETS-FIELD-RELICS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Comiskey Park.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Downing Stadium is unlikely to attract the same sort of
veneration, though it has its own rich memories. There, Jesse Owens
qualified for the 1936 Olympics, Pele played his first game for the
New York Cosmos and the Black Yankees of the old Negro National
League played a season, in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Now, cracks ripple through the foundation, and reinforcing metal
rods are laid bare and rusty from crumbling concrete. There are no
concession stands, hot water in the locker room showers or even
seats at the stadium, which has a capacity of 21,000.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials promise to preserve what is worth saving,
including stylish bathroom tiles, old wooden refrigerators and
exterior murals painted by the students at New Dorp High School of
Staten Island, which said it was willing to take them back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow, history seems to still shimmer in the air above.
The lights of Ebbets Field, after all, shone on the first black man
to play major-league baseball in the 20th century. They lighted up
one of the game's great moments: the second consecutive no-hitter
by Johnny Vander Meer of the Cincinnati Reds, on June 15, 1938. It
was the first night game at Ebbets Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe right then and there, those lights became magic,'' said
Michael Benson, a baseball historian and the author of ``Ballparks
of North America.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Downing lights were offered for the new
minor-league stadium being built in Coney Island, which would have
been an all-too-perfect fate, but city officials said they were too
expensive to adapt. Officials of the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown
said they would come down to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   Stern had a few spur-of-the-moment ideas: hang them at park
headquarters or a historic house, or maybe a museum wants them.
</P>
<P>
   But after a closer look, it turns out there is not much Brooklyn
left in the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Department records show that after the destruction of
Ebbets Field, the lights were sent to Downing Stadium and plans
were drawn up in 1962 to have them installed on new poles and
frames. Over the years, many of the individual lamp fixtures were
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how many of the original are left above the
stadium or in storage space filled with fixtures, which seem mostly
newer but with a sprinkling of heavy cast-iron and glass models
that parks electricians say are originals.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Downing Stadium or the Parks Department seems to know
what happened to the rest of the original lights.
</P>
<P>
   That does not matter much to one former Dodger, Ralph Branca,
who perhaps more than anyone else unites the Polo Grounds and
Ebbets Field. Branca threw the pitch that Bobby Thomson hit over
the fence at the Polo Grounds and became the ``shot heard 'round
the world'' to give the Giants the 1951 pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Branca said the Ebbets lights prompted ``no feelings, to tell
the truth,'' and he could think of little use for them now _
``unless you got some collector who's got a big back yard who wants
to light it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
