<HEADLINE>
US RELAY TEAMS TRY TO GET THEIR ACT TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ While it might not be fair to say the US relay teams
are in their typical disarry, neither are they exactly in array.
</P>
<P>
   A traditional hotbed of controversy (remember the 1996 should or
shouldn't Carl Lewis run saga?) spiced with a dropped baton or two,
the 4 x 100 men's relay this time around is a big favorite to win
gold, given the woes of rival Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there are no . . . issues.
</P>
<P>
   US coach John Chaplin earlier this week announced he plans to
run Jon Drummond, Tim Montgomery, Bernard Williams, and Maurice
Greene in all rounds of the 4 x 100, assuming Greene, who would
anchor, has recovered enough from his 100-meter victory to run the
first round Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greene is a little sore,'' Chaplin said.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been talking about his attitude, because Greene is
reportedly annoyed that Montgomery has been named a starter instead
of Greene's Hudson-Smith International teammate Curtis Johnson, who
is not even in the final pool of six that includes Brian Lewis and
Ken Brokenburr. Last month, a relay team with Johnson instead of
Montgomery ran 37.65 seconds in Berlin, fifth-fastest of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Chaplin basically said at the (US) trials that he had
never heard of Curtis Johnson,'' said Emanuel Hudson of HSI, the
training group to which Greene, Williams, Drummond, and Johnson
belong. According to Hudson, Chaplin told everyone after the trials
they had to prove themselves, so the HSI athletes did.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Greene was so unhappy over the snub he would refuse
to run are untrue, said Hudson. ``Since Maurice Greene trains with
Curtis Johnson every day of the year, I'm sure you can understand
not being happy,'' he said. ``(But) Maurice is running because this
is so big, and he feels the United States is looking for him
despite the fact that the coaches are making decisions they may or
may not be able to live up to.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's 4 x 400 squad has not yet been named, but with
400-meter gold medalist Michael Johnson anchoring and 400-meter
hurdles gold medalist Angelo Taylor _ a Johnson favorite _ likely
to form half the team, there should be more talk about world
records than any internal squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   The women's relays face a different set of problems. In the 4 x
100, the good news is Inger Miller, who missed the 100 and 200
meters with a hamstring injury, is expected to be back for the
relay. The bad news is no sooner was Miller looking promising than
Gail Devers aggravated a hamstring strain in the semifinal of the
100-meter hurdles Wednesday night, failing to finish the race. Her
status is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Without Miller and Devers at full strength, Marion Jones's plan
for five gold medals could end right there, assuming she's still in
the hunt after the 200 and long jump finals. Chryste Gaines,
Carlette Guidry, Nanceen Perry, and Torri Edwards round out the
pool, but would be no match for a tough Bahamas squad that includes
Jones's training partner Chandra Sturrup, Sevatheda Fynes, Pauline
Davis-Thompson, and Debbie Ferguson. That's the same squad that won
the world championships last summer, leaving a Jones-less US team
to finish fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the women's 4 x 100 doesn't falter, the 4 x 400 might.
No US woman advanced to the final of the 400 here, and an ill Jearl
Miles-Clark failed to get to the final of the 800. The fastest
400-meter runner on the team is Jones, despite having run only one
race all season solely to make her case for being named to this
squad. Russia, meanwhile, has a deep team led by 400-meter hurdles
gold medalist Irina Privalova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware that there are a bit of problems,'' said Jones after
winning the 100-meter gold medal. ``But I'm confident that when it
comes time to put the fastest four legs out there in the 4 x 1 and
the 4 x 4, that we'll be prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
