<HEADLINE>
CHANGE MARKS YEAR FOR US WOMEN'S SOCCER TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ ``Did we ever look like that?'' Michelle Akers asked.
One of her shoulders was in a sling, and now she was doing
something new. She was observing the US women's soccer team rather
than playing for it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most familiar things appear to be different when you
trade in subjectivity for objectivity, so the injured Akers's
question Sunday was fair: Have the Americans ever played as if they
had message necklaces (Need First Cup of Coffee) draped around
their necks? Did they ever look so sluggish in 1999, when she was
with them and even nonfans knew their names?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Given that answer, Akers smiled. She knew even the great World
Cup team of 1999 had halves and entire games like Sunday's, a 1-0
win over Brazil. It was the kind of unremarkable win that sends
spectators to Before and After photos and This Year/Last Year
comparisons, reaching for better days. But after a year like '99,
the tendency is to romanticize yesterday while poking at today's
weaknesses _ which are perceived to be new.
</P>
<P>
   It's post-magical season syndrome. It happens in all sports.
There is always the mirage of a current crisis, even when final
results are favorable to those of the past. The women knew this was
coming. They won the World Cup last year at home, topping China in
a shootout. This year, they are in another country, preparing for
Thursday night's gold-medal game against Norway at Sydney Football
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Last season: The women played before a mostly loving Rose Bowl
crowd of 90,000-plus on the Fourth of July. They were on talk
shows. They were on editorial pages. Mia Hamm was doing commercials
with Michael Jordan and Brandi Chastain was on the tube with Kevin
Garnett. The defender took her shirt off for an ABC audience,
removed the rest of her clothes for a Gear magazine audience, and,
suddenly, the US women had buzz in all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   This Season: The women played their last game before a mostly
angry Bruce Stadium crowd of 11,000-plus. ``We're playing in front
of family and friends now,'' Chastain said. Some of them were
supporters Sunday. Most of the pro-Brazil fans booed the winners
off the pitch in Canberra, Australia. The only buzz came from
conversation, which generally ended with, ``Brazil outplayed them.
The Americans are washed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Both seasons: The women are involved in the match that will
determine the world's champion.
</P>
<P>
   Problem? What problem?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are differences. The reliable Akers, 34, is
gone from midfield. Her replacement is Lorrie Fair, 22, who
returned to school (North Carolina) after the '99 Cup and won
another championship there. Akers said Fair keeps in touch via
e-mail, and the recent graduate reports that people are always
asking if the midfielder of the past and present dislike each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great kid,'' Akers said, laughing at the alleged rift.
Fair is a very good player, too. She helped change Sunday's game,
simply by making eye contact with Chastain. The defender had a free
kick. Her eyes met Fair's and ``sometimes you just know what
someone is thinking with the way they look,'' Chastain explained.
``She wanted the ball.'' Chastain got it to her, and Fair got it
toward the area where Hamm placed it in the net.
</P>
<P>
   The goalkeepers have changed. Where there was once a Bri, there
is now a Siri. Briana Scurry still is on the team, but Siri
Mullinix has been the regular keeper. Scurry, a UMass graduate, was
bothered by severe shin splints in the spring. She is healthy now;
she simply lost her job to Mullinix. Her replacement, nicknamed
SeerDog, played with Fair at North Carolina. She made a save Sunday
that was a classic from the Scurry archives, a full-body extension
and then a smother of the ball. If a less qualified keeper had been
playing, this would be a Brazil vs. Norway conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The team's collective wit and approachability have not changed.
This still is one of the most fun groups to be around in sports.
Chastain, who defends as well as she did last season, was recently
asked about Hamm. A reporter began to say that soccer could not
have a Jordan, but Chastain interrupted, ``I don't know. I think
Diego Maradonna did a damn good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team continues to receive loads of e-mail; young men and
women continue to come to the sport because they are intrigued by
the Americans' style.
</P>
<P>
   The coach has changed. The winning margins (closer) have
changed. The media requests have decreased. The crowds are smaller.
But when you compete in any sport, the essence of your happiness is
directly tied to what happens when you play. There will be a game
Thursday night involving the US women. They won the top prize last
year in Los Angeles. If they win it this year in Sydney, so be it.
That would be a change of scenery, and there's nothing wrong with
that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
