<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-U.S.-DONOR-BRITAIN-2T     09-27 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-DONOR-BRITAIN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH ARTS INSTITUTIONS FIND THEIR DONOR WALLS REINFORCED BY
AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago J. Paul Getty II gave the National Gallery in
London a $62.5 million grant, the largest since its founding in
1824. That any individual, let alone an American, would give so
generously to a British museum was unheard of. In those years, few
rich Britons ever wrote a substantial check to a cultural
institution. They didn't have to; the government provided ample
support. Besides, for British citizens, giving never had the tax
advantages that it does in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Getty, an Anglophile whose father was the founder of the Getty
oil fortune and the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, lives in
England. His donation did not go unnoticed; in 1986 he received an
honorary knighthood from Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Sir Paul, who has since become a British citizen,
could be considered something of a pioneer. Today, as London is
seeing the greatest cultural expansion in its history _ a $600
million millennium effort financed partly by England's national
lottery and partly by private donations _ a list of many of the
largest donors reads like a Who's Who of American philanthropy. New
galleries, courtyards, libraries, reading rooms and additions are
being christened with names like Annenberg and Sackler.
</P>
<P>
   And though few American donors are likely to receive honorary
knighthoods, there are other perquisites. It costs far less to make
a splash in London than in New York, where a $15 million check
won't necessarily extract an invitation to join a board. And, of
course, there's always the possibility of hobnobbing with titled
folk and royals.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known Americans who have written big checks include
Maria-Theresa Heinz, the widow of Sen. John Heinz III; Jayne
Wrightsman, one of the New York Metropolitan Museum's most generous
trustees; Cynthia Polsky, another Met trustee; Jonathan H. Kagan, a
managing director of Lazard Freres; and Raymond Sackler, the
psychiatrist and collector. Each has given support to places like
the National Portrait Gallery, the Royal Academy, the British
Museum and Somerset House.
</P>
<P>
   American money accounted for nearly 30 percent of all the
individual financing for the $214 million Tate Modern in London,
the first new national museum in Britain in 100 years and its first
devoted solely to modern art. The donors' wall includes the names
of some of America's best-known contemporary art collectors _
Donald Fisher, founder of the Gap; Charles Schwab, the investment
magnate; Donald L. Bryant, the St. Louis collector; Mortimer and
Theresa Sackler.
</P>
<P>
   American corporations, too, have been generous. Bloomberg News,
whose founder, Michael R. Bloomberg, is a trustee of the Met, gave
the Tate Modern more than $1.5 million for a series of reading
rooms and for three audio guides.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on how the donations to British institutions are
made, they can be tax-deductible in the United States..
</P>
<P>
   ``We see ourselves as the 51st state in the union,'' said Colin
Tweedy, chief executive of Art and Business, a nonprofit
organization in England that promotes business investments in the
arts. ``The American government is effectively paying for many
projects here.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the phenomenon, Tweedy added, is simply that
``Americans understand how to give, what to give and how to get
something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Christensen III, a New York lawyer who is a trustee of the
American Fund for the Tate, has noticed that ``the idea of U.S.
fund-raising for foreign charities is more and more au courant.''
</P>
<P>
   One important factor has been the formation by British art
institutions of American fund-raising arms that have tax-exempt
status in the United States. Based in New York, these ``friends''
groups are independent charitable organizations with boards of
directors that decide how to spend the money. An American donor can
write a check to one of these groups and take the same tax
deduction that writing a check to the Met or the Modern brings.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just tax benefits that prompt Americans to support
English institutions. A small check in London goes a lot further
than in New York or Los Angeles and generally gets the donor's name
on the right party lists.
</P>
<P>
   Some donors are simply Anglophiles who enjoy the cachet that
comes with supporting a London arts group; others, like the scores
of American investment bankers who have been transferred to London
and have been living there for several years now, consider England
a second home. And for serious collectors who give, there is
instant access to some of the world's leading scholars and curators
as well as weekend excursions featuring tours given by experts
through some of Europe's greatest private art collections and
parties organized by the British museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``These institutions sort of belong to the world; they're
global,'' said Jill Sackler. She and her late husband, Arthur, were
the principal donors of a wing named after them at the Royal
Academy. Mrs. Sackler recalled that as the international chairwoman
of the Edinburgh Festival in the 1980s she met Sir Hugh Casson, who
was then president of the Royal Academy. Casson, who died last
year, invited the Sacklers for a tour of the academy, and a long
relationship was born.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Cramer, a television and theatrical producer who has
given not only money but also artworks to the Tate Modern, said
that Anglophilia was the main reason for his generosity. But he
added: ``When I first went to London, the Tate was the one place I
would go to see exhibitions. The other museums seemed so
excessively stuffy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Cramer moved from Los Angeles to New York and sold
or gave away much of an art collection that belonged in part to him
and in part to a foundation he established, he asked some of the
artists whose work he planned to donate where they wanted it to go
to. ``Roy and Dorothy Lichtenstein wanted an interior painting of
Roy's to go to the Tate because the Modern already had a comparable
one,'' he said. ``The Modern already had an early Richard Serra
which was similar to one I also gave the Tate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer recalled that during the years the museum was under
construction, ``there wasn't a collector who cared who didn't get a
personal tour.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt a part of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling has been carefully nurtured by the museum. Jacob
Rothschild, a philanthropist and the former chairman of the lottery
fund, said that clever marketing was one reason for the Tate
Modern's success. ``The Tate has projected itself as a very
non-British institution but a totally international one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Serota, the director, said he had been getting a lot of
American gifts, ranging from $750,000 to $2 million. ``Major
collectors of 1980s and '90s art come here to see shows,'' he said.
``For someone who's used to giving $5 million to their local
museum, to give $1 million to the Tate isn't that much, and it
gives them a foothold in Europe. They enjoy being here, and
relatively small sums make a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the families of American artists want to be included in the
Tate Modern. Candida and Rebecca Smith, the daughters of the
American sculptor David Smith, sold ``Wagon 2,'' one of their
father's works, to the American Fund for the Tate, which gave it to
the new museum.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing has become important to all of London's arts
institutions, since government financing has become scarcer and
lottery money often has to be matched by private donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans invented fund-raising, and we're running to catch
up,'' said Sukie Hemming, director of the British Museum
Development Trust. ``For so long, old money has been cash-light
because it is all tied up in land. Giving has never come from the
aristocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Hemming said, has a lot to do with what she calls ``the
English mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't grow up in the U.K. understanding ambition,'' she
said. ``We find it unsettling, whereas in the States it's endemic.
To have ambition and make money in America is applauded, and part
of establishing wealth is giving it away. That's changing here. The
dot-coms have helped. But it's slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Devine, director of the British Museum's six-year-old
American Friends office in New York, said that the museum's
world-class collections were her best sales tool. ``Our focus is
educational,'' she said. ``Collectors can use our curators and have
great access to them. We're a storehouse of information and
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Each institution has its own friends office, and each has a
sales pitch tailored to the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end there has to be something for Americans in it,''
said Danny Khosrovani, president of the American Friends of the
Royal Court Theater, which reopened in March after a $42 million
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money that Khosrovani has raised _ upwards of
$250,000 _ has gone into supporting American playwrights who have
had difficulty getting their plays produced in the United States.
Last year alone, seven Royal Court productions could be seen either
on or off Broadway. ``We help American voices in the theater,'' she
said. Playwrights like Rebecca Gilman, whose play ``Spinning Into
Butter'' closed at Lincoln Center last week, got her start at the
Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Academy of Art was the first London art institution to
set up an American office. That was in 1983, and over the years it
has received gifts and pledges for about $30 million. When Paul
Mellon, the Washington philanthropist, died last year, he
bequeathed the academy $5 million. Unlike the British Museum or the
Tate, the Royal Academy gets no government subsidy. Nor is it a
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were set up in 1768 by artists to be the first professional
association of artists,'' said John Nickson, director of the Royal
Academy Trust. ``Our links to the United States are strong; they go
back to the 18th century and have continued.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the founding members was the American painter
Benjamin West, who became the academy's second president. The
institution is in the final phase of the renovation of Burlington
House, its home on Piccadilly. The American associates expect to
raise about a third of the $30 million cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our donors are Anglophiles who are sophisticated enough to see
the art world as global,'' said Kathrine Ockenden, president and
executive director of the American Associates of the Royal Academy
Trust. ``Since we don't get government help, we run the ship
ourselves, which is something Americans admire and understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy organizes many symposiums and other events that
bring Americans to London. And sometimes it has organized
exhibitions that come to American museums, like ``Sensation: Young
British Artists from the Saatchi Collection,'' the controversial
show that opened at the Brooklyn Museum of Art last fall. Others
include ``1900: Art at the Crossroads,'' which was at the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum earlier this month; ``Chardin,'' which was at
the Met recently; and ``Art in the Age of Queen Victoria,'' which
ended a five-city American tour this week at the Cincinnati Art
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller London institutions, too, like the National Portrait
Gallery and the Dulwich Picture Gallery, rely heavily on American
support. ``The roll call of British patrons could be counted on
less than one hand,'' said Desmond Shore-Taylor, director of the
Dulwich. ``It's in the American mind-set that rich people support
the arts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
