<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD QUICK TO POINT DOPING FINGER AT YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ It didn't have to be C.J. Hunter. It could have been a
swimmer, a rower, even a judoka. As long as it was an American. The
Lords of the Rings have been waiting to have just one US athlete
send the doping needle off the dial to turn the accusing finger
back on the Yanks and haul them up as hypocrites before the world.
</P>
<P>
   Having it be Mr. Marion Jones merely made the reversal more
delicious, especially when Hunter claimed it must have been those
nasty iron supplements he'd been swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the usual thing,'' cackled Dick Pound, the
International Olympic Committee member from Canada who has had
Americans up to here after having to play Dick Tracy during the
Salt Lake City bidding scandal. ``Athletes always say, `It's not
possible,' followed by, `There must be some mistake in the sample,'
followed by, `I must have got it from the toilet seat,' followed
by, `Here's a writ for $12 million from my lawyer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnnie Cochran gets Hunter off the hook (``If it's
something he ate, you must reinstate''). But for now, Hunter is
sitting in the stocks in the town square and the Lords are letting
fly with the tomatoes. It's all about payback.
</P>
<P>
   How far back do you want to go? Two years? Ten? Twenty? More?
Jimmy Carter leading the boycott that ravaged the 1980 Games in
Moscow. The US soiling Lillehammer's winter wonderland with its
sordid Nancy-Tonya soap opera. Atlanta turning the 1996 Games into
a street corner flea circus with a mad bomber (and Pound's wife
getting arrested amid a jaywalking beef).
</P>
<P>
   Then Salt Lake, whose sleazy story of scholarships and ski
vacations created the worst scandal in Olympic history and exposed
one-fifth of the Lords as shameless junketeers on the grab.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the scandal, which IOC insiders knew was
possible given the host-city derby. It was how the Americans
climbed up into their moral pulpit and began finger-wagging,
howling for expulsions and reform.
</P>
<P>
   It was the FBI rummaging through boxes of records filled with
embarrassing personal dossiers on IOC members (does the Venezuelan
lady really like younger guys?). It was John Hancock pulling the
Olympic rings off its letterhead. It was the American congressmen,
who'd been slopping at the soft-money trough for years, making Juan
Antonio Samaranch raise his right hand, so help him God. ``What did
you know and when did you know it?'' Mr. Upton from Michigan
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw was the doping issue, which the IOC has been
wrestling with (and, it admits, losing) for three decades and more.
The athletes are always a quadrennium ahead of the labs. The
international federations can't agree on penalties. The national
Olympic committees cover up for their athletes.
</P>
<P>
   So when the IOC decided last year that it should create a global
anti-doping agency (and put Pound in charge), it was the Americans
who led the catcall chorus, saying the Lords have no credibility on
drugs. The same Americans who do all their own testing and always
seem to come up clean. And who's their point man? Bill Clinton's
guy. The Americans should put their own house in order before
playing prosecutor, IOC drug chief Prince Alexandre de Merode said
tartly.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the Americans weren't right. The new World
Anti-Doping Agency should be free of IOC influence if it's to have
global credibility. And didn't the IOC end up adopting most of the
reforms the Mitchell Commission recommended?
</P>
<P>
   The US Olympic Committee, which was also tarred by the Salt Lake
scandal, had its own shake-up and started an independent
anti-doping agency, which takes effect right after these Games.
</P>
<P>
   That's what irks the rest of the Olympic family. Now that the
Americans finally got religion, they're coming on like Elmer
Gantry. But why not, Gantry says? Who fills up the IOC's collection
plate, after all? Virtually all of the global Olympic sponsors,
like Hancock and Kodak and Xerox, are US companies.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy a T-shirt in Olympic Park, you pay with a Visa card.
If you buy a soda, Coke makes it. If you eat fast food in the
athletes' village, it's Mickey D's. NBC paid $3.5 billion for the
rights to the Games through 2008. Sydney is getting $700 million in
TV cash from the US alone, twice as much as all of Europe is
paying.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics run on the Yankee dollar, so if the Yankees want to
be evangelical about it, that's their privilege: You take our
money, you listen to our sermon. If you stand in the soup line with
your hand out, you sit through the salvation speech.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the IOC has to like it. The US may pay for these Games
and they may top the medal table by a mile. But, as Norwegian
speedskating deity (and IOC member) Johann Olav Koss said this
week, there shouldn't be one rule for the world and another for the
US.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC is going to take a gold medal away from a Romanian
pixie for taking a couple of cold tablets, it's not going to wink
at an American shot putter. So when word came out this week that
Hunter tested positive for nandrolone on four different occasions
this summer, the IOC and the international track federation put
Elmer Gantry on the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   Five Americans, de Merode said, competed in Seoul in 1988
despite failing tests before the Games. And 15 others, the IAAF
claimed, tested positive before Sydney. Mr. Marion Jones may yet
slip off the hook, but he's already been spattered with foreign
tomatoes. Payback has many forms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
