<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of the nation will be rather tranquil Thursday as a large
high-pressure system moves into the eastern two-thirds of the
country. In the Northeast, some patches of clouds will linger along
the New England coast as moist breezes from the northeast combine
with a jet-stream disturbance to produce a band of clouds. Farther
inland, sunny skies will be dotted with many cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening jet-stream disturbance will pass over a nearly
stationary front in Florida, promoting scattered showers and
thunderstorms. Some of these showers will contain locally heavy
rain. Meanwhile, the interior Southeast will be seasonably warm.
</P>
<P>
   A broken area of clouds and showers will move from the Southwest
into Wyoming and eastern Utah. Clouds will also arrive ahead of a
weak cold front in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HELPFUL HURRICANES
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Isaac, churning through the eastern Atlantic, is
expected to move north and eventually dissipate without threatening
land. But this storm, like most tropical storms and hurricanes is
performing the important task of moving heat from the tropics
toward the middle latitudes. In the cold season, powerful winter
storms transport frigid air toward the equator while drawing warmer
air toward the poles, helping to erase the natural global energy
imbalance. In the warm season, when midlatitude storms are weak,
tropical storms, both benign and destructive, help balance the
weather budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
