<SLUG> BC-OLY-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S TOP GIANT IS NOW AN AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ For 13 years, the mammoth men with sequoia thighs and
refrigerator chests who populate the 130-kilogram class of
Greco-Roman wrestling have had two-tier competitions in which they
all compete for what's left over after the same truly legendary
figure takes home the gold.
</P>
<P>
   In towns you've heard of (Stockholm, Copenhagen, Seoul,
Barcelona) and towns you haven't (Kolbotn, Poznan, Tampere,
Gaevle), they have entered international competitions in their
weight class resigned to silvers, bronzes, and lesser numerical
placements. There has never been any question who would win.
Alexander Karelin, the sculpted 286-pound pride of Novosibirsk,
Siberia, last lost a match to (itals)anybody(unitals) in 1987, and
had come to Sydney undefeated in an estimated 300 international
matches during the last 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night, the three-time gold-medal winner and
nine-time world champion finally heard a new tune at the end of his
gold-medal match. It's called ``The Star-Spangled Banner.'' The new
King of Gigantic People is an American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm numb to beat that guy,'' said 29-year-old Rulon Gardner.
``He's the best wrestler in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Karelin is actually the best wrestler of all time, but on
Wednesday he was beaten, fair and square, by a massive man from
Afton, Wyo., and the University of Nebraska who has never before
brought home a medal in major international competition. Now he's
got America's first nonboycott gold in this sport, and the
reverberations are sure to be felt around the entire Olympic
communuity, where the noble Russian is more commonly regarded as a
celestial envoy than as a mere human being.
</P>
<P>
   It was pretty much assumed that Karelin would never again lose.
Surely, no Russian ever thought the man who would end the winning
streak would be an (itals)American(unitals) who admits he had never
even heard of Karelin until the legend had already won two gold
medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard there was some great Russian back around '92,'' said
Gardner, ``but I really didn't know exactly who it was until around
'95.''
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate that when the great man was finally brought down
after 13 long years it was by someone who could easily relate to
Karelin's own rural roots. Gardner, youngest of nine, was raised on
a dairy farm in Wyoming. Karelin is said to have trained by hauling
logs. Gardner spent many hard years doing every imaginable
distasteful farm chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I start?'' said Gardner, whose 1-0 victory will be
required study material for all those wrestlers who have tried and
failed to depose the Great Karelin. ``It's been a hard life. But
one thing I've always said to myself is not to quit. Just don't
ever quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Will is one thing, but mere will could not defeat Karelin, who
has always been able to overpower people. ``Go out on a dairy
farm,'' suggested Gardner. ``Get up against a cow and try to move
it. The only problem is Alexander is a little quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Karelin wasn't able to move the superbly conditioned
Gardner, who has a 54-inch chest. In their only previous meeting
three years ago, Gardner was thrown during a 5-0 overtime loss. But
this time, he was the more manly man. Karelin actually got tired
trying to shove Gardner around.
</P>
<P>
   The only point was the Greco-Roman equivalent of an unearned
run, and it came 30 seconds into the second three-minute period.
The wrestlers were placed in a standing clinch to start the period,
and Gardner received a point when Karelin broke his hold before a
full minute had elapsed. It took a sideline conference to decide
the matter, but the point was awarded, and it held up for the
remainder of the period and all through a three-minute overtime
session. (If neither man has 3 points after two periods, an
overtime follows. If someone is ahead after the additional three
minutes, he wins the match.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrestled a perfect match,'' shouted deliriously happy US
coach Dan Chandler. ``The idea was not to get turned and get
(Karelin) tired on his feet. I knew Rulon would wrestle him well,
but you don't know if he could win the match against the greatest
wrestler of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Karelin was thought to be vulnerable four years ago when he
arrived in Atlanta with a bad shoulder. He needed all his wiles to
win gold medal No. 3, defeating American Matt Ghafari in the
finals. But a lot has happened in the ensuing four years. For one
thing, he was elected to the Duma, the lower chamber of Russia's
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting older,'' conceded Chandler, ``and he's heavy into
politics. You wonder when he finds time to train. You could see him
losing a little during the last four years. He was beatable.
Fortunately, it happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, he wasn't the wrestling machine who treated his six
Barcelona opponents, as we're told in David Wallechinsky's ``The
Complete Book of the Summer Olympics,'' like ``inanimate objects.''
But he was good enough to wrestle his way into a fourth Olympic
final, and he always carries with him a mystique. Going undefeated
for 13 years does give you an aura.
</P>
<P>
   But when he got to this match, he found himself involved with a
massive, determined, and intelligent opponent who simply wasn't
afraid. ``With him, I just had a certain type of calm,'' Gardner
explained. ``It was weird.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the requisite number of Americans waving their flags
and chanting their ``USAs!'' but the rest of the crowd was in the
big man's corner, and they were confident he would come through _
as always. But nothing the champ did worked against this wide-body
American who surely looks like one Tom Osborne let get away.
</P>
<P>
   With four seconds left, the champion knew it was over. He simply
stood up to accept his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to see him lose,'' said Chandler. ``I love him. He's
not just a great wrestler and one of the greatest Olympians of all
time, but he's also a great man. He's one of the greatest men of
the generation. And he reacted the way you knew he would. He came
over, shook my hand, and said, `Yeah, he did well.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something to me in Russian, right at the end,''
confided Gardner. ``I don't know what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been: ``How can I get a chest like yours?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
