<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WVBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN VOLLEYBALLERS DIGGING IN FOR A WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ They weren't supposed to be this far into their
Australian athletic vacation.
</P>
<P>
   America's female volleyballers, ranked 10th in the world headed
into the Olympics, were expected to make a polite showing here,
maintain their international integrity, and head home long before
things became serious, with suitcases loaded with little more than
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, they've got one foot up on the medal stand and they're
dreaming of winning their first gold medal in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible,'' said Stacy Sykora, the former Texas
A&AMP;M standout who fills the newly created ``libero'' position,
making her the club's key defensive force. ``When I woke up
(Wednesday) morning, I was still in awe over the whole thing. I
mean everything _ the fact that we're 5-1, the fact that we beat
Korea (Tuesday) in a five-set nailbiter. It's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Yanks, seeded ninth, have beaten higher seeds
Croatia (8), China (4), and Korea (5) to get to the semifinals
against the Russians. Their only loss was to the mighty Brazilians,
the court queens who face archenemy Cuba in Thursday's other
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians' strength is in their size and offensive attack.
They have seven women who are 6 feet 3 inches or taller, topping
out with Ekaterina Gamova (6-7) and Olga Potachova (6-8). The
Russian Rockettes are now 6-0, following a 3-0 win over China, and
the Yanks figure they'll attack the way they always do, with a
strong, aggressive offensive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just huge,'' said the peppery Sykora, the most
animated of all the Americans, constantly chattering on the floor
and interacting with her teammates. ``The difference is, we're a
blocking and defensive team, and they are attack _ and attack some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   By definition _ the ``libero'' position literally written on the
back of her jersey _ the 5-foot-10-inch Sykora is center of the US
defense. The position was introduced to the sport only two years
ago, and this is its debut in the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The libero can't attack, can't block, can't serve. In fact, the
libero isn't allowed to set the ball with two hands unless she is
in the far backcourt. She is allowed to punch set the ball with her
two forearms when in the forecourt, but for the most part, liberos
are ``free'' only to dive and dig, do all the dirty work _
honorably, of course _ to keep the ball alive on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an offensive player in college,'' said Sykora. ``But I
always loved playing defense, too. And when the libero position
came around, my college coach (Laurie Corbelli) figured it would be
good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbelli, a member of the US silver-medal team in Los Angeles in
'84, knew it was Sykora's dream to play for the Americans. She also
knew the team would have enough big hitters. If Sykora could find a
niche on the national squad, it had to be in charge of putting some
bite in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be my senior year when she told me about it,''
Sykora said. ``And I figured right then, `That's for me.' I just
knew I'd do anything to be part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after college, Sykora had a two-day audition for the job,
won a sixth-month tryout, and now she's here with a chance to
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have just been coming together for us at the right
time,'' said Sykora, whose teammates, none bigger than 6-3
(Danielle Scott and Heather Brown), can match the Russians' jumping
power at the net. ``Now we've got to keep that going, and that will
mean getting a good defensive blocking game out there against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   From here, the 23-year-old Sykora will be headed to Europe,
where she will begin a pro career with Ravenna, in northern Italy.
Libero is Italian for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be known as one of the best passers in the world,''
Sykora has said. ``Or at least among the top three passers in the
world, and (best) defensive players . . . I want people to talk
about the girl from the USA who can really pass. I want to make a
name for myself. I want to be somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking down the Russian Federation would be a giant step toward
making a name, not just for Sykora but for all the Americans.
Getting a shot at the powerful Cubans or Brazilians (provided one
is left standing after their semifinal) would guarantee it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us right now are trying not to think about what all
this means for the program,'' she said. ``We know it's great, and
we honestly believe we can beat anyone, but it's like, oh my gosh,
this is so great, let's just focus on each game and not think about
the rest. I mean, USA volleyball wasn't still supposed to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But they're still around, looking for medals instead of
mementos.
</P>
</TEXT>
