u f BC-HEWLETT-FIORINA-BOS &LR;      09-27 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-FIORINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HP CHIEF DEFENDS PRICE PAID FOR TECHNOLOGY CONSULTANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hewlett-Packard's chief executive, Carly Fiorina,
Wednesday defended the $18 billion offer her company has made for
the technology consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, calling it
``a fair price for everybody involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Boston College's Chief Executives Club, Fiorina said
she is optimistic the two companies will reach a merger agreement
in four to six weeks. If so, the world's second-largest computer
maker will be in the unique situation of absorbing 30,000
consultants into its 86,000-employee work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it would be a challenge,'' Fiorina said when asked
about combining firms from different industries with such varied
corporate cultures. ``But we are already alligned (with PwC) when
it comes to strategy and our view of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard first confirmed two weeks ago that it was in
merger talks with the consulting giant. The idea, Fiorina said, is
to create a single entity that can identify problems for companies
through its consulting unit and then solve them through its
products and services divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts have questioned the widsom of such a corporate
marriage, citing Cisco Systems' recent $1 billion investment in
KPMG Consulting as a sign of things to come. Sun Microsystems, a
Hewlett-Packard competitor, also has its own consulting arm.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag has come under fire in some quarters, though. In
the week after the merger talks became public knowledge,
Hewlett-Packard shares lost $18, or almost 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consulting division will have about $8 billion in revenues
in fiscal year 2001,'' Fiorina said. ``A multiple 2.2 to 2.3 times
that is certainly in the normal range for this type of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the deal happens or not, Hewlett-Packard is in the
process of building its own technology-consulting business. It
hired 600 consultants in the latest quarter, boosting its total to
about 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting revenues grew 46 percent in the past year, helping
Hewlett-Packard boost overall revenues 15 percent. Wednesday,
Fiorina said the company will again report revenue gains of that
magnitude for the third quarter, which ends this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
