<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-HOMES28-COX     09-27 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NURSING HOME QUALITY MAY BE GOING BACKWARDS
 &HT;    540&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after President Clinton launched a
crackdown on problem nursing homes, congressional investigators say
the nation may be losing ground in the battle against neglect and
abuse in its 17,000 nursing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 percent of those homes have been cited for harming
their residents or for putting them in immediate jeopardy, the U.S.
General Accounting Office said in a report to be issued
Thursday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   That figure marked an increase over the nearly 28 percent of
homes with serious deficiencies before the enforcement effort
began.
</P>
<P>
   The increase ``could be the result of better detection'' of
deficiencies, said the GAO, the non-partisan investigative arm of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, recent nursing personnel shortages ``raise concerns
that the actual proportion of homes with deficiencies may have
increased,'' the report warned.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, requested the study to review
progress of the nursing home initiative, which Clinton announced
two years ago in response to a scathing report on nursing care for
the 1.6 million Americans in long-term facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you that there's dramatic improvement, but
I can't,'' said Grassley, whose Special Committee on Aging will
hold a follow-up hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Grassley said, ``we had 30 percent of people in
California nursing homes that are in life-threatening situations. I
think it would be wrong for me to conclude that it's different
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley credited the Health Care Finance Administration (HCFA),
which oversees most nursing homes, with giving ``more attention''
to the nursing home standards that were passed by Congress in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving the bureaucracy, but it's kind of like towing a
house,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana, the
ranking Democrat on Grassley's panel. ``This nursing home
initiative began more than two years ago, and while we've made some
improvements, it still seems in many ways we've been stuck in the
same position since day one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA administrator Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, responding to the GAO
report, acknowledged that ``it is still too early to draw
definitive conclusions about the impact of various (1998 nursing
home initiative) provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings of the GAO study:
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite more weekend and off-hours inspections ordered by the
Clinton administration, inspections in some states ``continue to be
predictable, allowing facilities to mask certain deficiencies if
they chose to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Much of the federal government's stepped-up enforcement
program won't be ready to implement for two or three more years and
would require ``sustained'' efforts to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Clinton administration directive that states focus on their
worst nursing homes brought increased monitoring of 60 facilities
nationwide. Of these, a dozen dropped out of federal financing
programs. About half were fined, and 28 of the homes are now ``in
substantial compliance'' with federal standards, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office said the number of homes was too small to
have a significant impact nationwide and cited California's state
effort, which two years ago began to scrutinize 36 of its worst
homes.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also criticized federal regulators at HCFA for failing
to catch problems in Oklahoma, where the head of the agency that
inspects nursing homes was indicted for bribery last May.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA could have spotted irregularities by a simple review of
Oklahoma's inspection results, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Oklahoma's own reporting showed an exceptionally
high percentage (22 percent versus 16 percent nationwide) of homes
with no deficiencies. At the same time, the state failed to enter
some inspection results into the HCFA data system for two years.
</P>
<P>
   When federal officials conducted surveys of 16 Oklahoma homes
suspected of bribing the top inspector, they found that half the
homes had at least 20 deficiencies more than the state found. One
home had 37 health citations in the federal survey, whereas state
officials had found only one deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In the GAO study, about 18 percent of Georgia's nursing homes
were cited for actual harm to residents or for putting them in
immediate jeopardy in the 1997-98 period before Clinton announced
his initiative. From 1999 through last July, the percentage jumped
to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The figures for other states include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida: 36 percent before the initiative, and just under 22
percent afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas: 22 percent before the initiative, and 25 percent
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ohio: 31 percent before the initiative, and just under 29
percent afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Colorado: 11 percent before the initiative, and just under 17
percent afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   _ North Carolina: 31 percent before the initiative, and 42
percent afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Special Committee on Aging, aging.senate.gov
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Financing Administration, www.hcfa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
