u l BC-KITCHEN-REMODEL-ART-2     09-27 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-REMODEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN URBAN FAIRYTALE: A $20,000 KITCHEN MAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: the 2nd take consists of three kitchens designed at the
request of editors of House and Home.) 
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In New York City, remodeling an entire kitchen for
less than $20,000 _ with new appliances in better locations, new
countertops, cabinets, floor and labor _ is the equivalent of
finding a two-bedroom apartment for $1,000 a month. It's possible,
but not very likely.
</P>
<P>
   To Michael McDonough, a New York architect, the $20,000
remodeled kitchen is an urban fairy tale. ``It's `the
brother-in-law kitchen,''' he said, meaning that it can be achieved
only if your brother-in-law is a licensed plumber, electrician and
general contractor, and utterly devoted to you.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen and bath are the most expensive rooms to redo
because they require appliances, cabinetry, countertops,
electricity, water and gas lines, plus the labor to install them.
Remodeling magazine pegs a minor American kitchen makeover (new
paint, new cabinet fronts, perhaps a new floor) for this year at
$8,655, and a major remodeling (the works) at an average of
$31,090. The appliances and materials are one-third of the cost;
the rest is labor. In New York, labor runs high.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the trades have to be involved,'' said Paul Deffenbaugh,
Remodeling's editor in chief. ``You'll do it once or twice in your
lifetime, kind of like getting married, and you'll want to do it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the $20,000 makeover is possible, especially if no
walls or fixtures have to be moved. Here are four kitchens to prove
it, from a modest $5,000 redo to a makeover that slightly topped
the budget because a wall was demolished. In addition, House &AMP; Home
asked three Manhattan design firms for budget ``concept'' kitchens.
Ikea cabinets, those affordable chameleons, turned up in kitchens
traditional and modern (with finishes from aluminum to laminate to
cherry).
</P>
<P>
   In realizing her vision, Helene Verin sacrificed custom
cabinetry _ but not style _ for Ikea's frosted-glass cabinets,
lighted from within to glow softly. The savings let her splurge on
walnut counters. Each kitchen, real or theoretical, offers
uncluttered counter space and invites a person to get busy and
cook.
</P>
<P>
   WHIMSICAL FEMINISM
</P>
<P>
   Verin is a designer of interiors, furniture and wallpaper who
lives in the Flatiron district, and her kitchen is a
tongue-in-cheek statement of feminism (she just got divorced and
she's happy). The pass-through from the kitchen to the dining room
is cut in the shape of an egg. The thick glowing curved walnut
counter for the pass-through? ``It's the shadow of the egg,'' Verin
said. Three ceiling lamps in the shape of milk bottles, designed by
Droog, complete the feminist symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Verin knew how to prioritize artfully. She loved the
voluptuousness of custom-cut solid walnut, made for the
pass-through and around the sink. It was a nod to the late George
Nakashima, one of America's foremost furniture craftsmen. She then
economized by using walnut veneer for below-the-counter cabinetry
and the front of the refrigerator. For a backsplash, she had glass
cut to fit, but she frosted it herself using a $4 tube of spray
frost, called Krylon Glass Interior Frosting Spray. The Magic Chef
stove, Bosch dishwasher and Franke sink are new; their chrome or
stainless steel finishes resemble those of higher-end appliances.
But she kept the old refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is 10 feet by 7 feet 3 inches, but ``the advantage
of this place is that the ceiling is 12 feet high,'' she said. So
she raised the height of the cut-out entrance to the kitchen from
7{ feet to its full 12 feet, and suddenly a small kitchen soared.
Total cost: $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   THE ENDLESS COUNTER
</P>
<P>
   Suzie Jackson wanted a kitchen with more than enough counter
space. Jackson is a food stylist who until last month lived with
her husband, James, and daughter, Edwina, in a TriBeCa loft. (They
have since moved to Australia.) Brad Zizmor, who designed the loft
with Dag Folger, his partner at A&AMP;I Design in Manhattan, obliged.
The kitchen is 18 feet long by 12 feet 9 inches wide; the counters,
one on each side, run the entire length.
</P>
<P>
   The efficient room is an austere homage to the loft's industrial
heritage, warmed with wood. The countertops are Fireslate, a
synthetic heat-resistant, laboratory countertop material
(800-523-5902), so Jackson could put hot pots directly on it.
Although Fireslate is only half an inch thick, the architects
attached it to the sides, so the counters appear to be ``big and
bulky and permanent,'' Folger said. They designed a storage system
of birch plywood shelves, drawers and cabinetry, framed with
Speed-Rail, a cast aluminum tubing system intended for scaffolding
or industrial handrails. The floor is trompe l'oeil: What appears
to be concrete is 4-by-4-foot squares of Ply-cem, half-inch thick
panels of concrete impregnated with wood fibers. ``It's used for
industrial roofing,'' Zizmor said, ``but it's lighter and more
stable than plain concrete, which can also crack.'' Total cost:
$17,450.
</P>
<P>
   MIDCENTURY MODERN FOR LESS
</P>
<P>
   David Colman's clutter-free, cozy (that's another word for
``small'') midcentury-modern kitchen cost only $5,000. ``I wanted a
nice, clean, white and green kitchen,'' said Colman, a freelance
writer who lives in the Wall Street district. ``The kitchen had an
awful ivory and wood laminate-accented cabinet with a hideous tile
floor and fluorescent light.''
</P>
<P>
   Out went everything except the refrigerator and stove.
</P>
<P>
   He installed an antique porcelain sink, a new pine floor,
butcher-block counters and those glass-fronted cabinets from Ikea
(to hold his red and white 1950s Paul McCobb dishes, found on
eBay). To economize, he gave up on the idea of $50 crystal knobs
and bought chrome ones at P.Guerin, a custom hardware house in
Greenwich Village, for $5 each, and painted the walls himself. ``My
knobs have pedigree,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MINIMALIST, BARRIER-FREE, ZEN
</P>
<P>
   At age 89, Will Machado, an interior designer gave himself an
inspiring present: a minimalist Zen kitchen that is warm, serene
and efficient. He wanted a kitchen that was easy to walk around,
and he demolished a wall separating the kitchen from the living
room. ``I wanted to simplify my life,'' he said, but even with a
$30,000 budget (including demolition) he had to make trade-offs. He
loves wood for its warmth and tactility, and he hired Stephen Iino,
a cabinetmaker, to execute his design in ash and maple. (The old
appliances stayed _ Machado cooks some meals at home, or goes out
to Nick &AMP; Toni's Cafe a block away.) Machado eliminated the thing
that annoyed him most: overhead doors that swung out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why open doors and bang your head?'' Machado asked. ``All the
doors slide, the pulls are holes and drawers slide out.'' He pulled
out a drawer, and shut it with a bump of his hip. The cabinetry was
$20,000. The demolition, rubber floor, and other work cost an
additional $10,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
