<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-REMODEL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: additional $10,000.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THREE KITCHEN SCHEMES
</P>
<P>
   House &AMP; Home asked three design firms to take an 8-by-10 foot
Manhattan galley kitchen and create a replacement kitchen for
$20,000, labor included. Their recipes included a mix of things
expensive (custom-cut walnut, a Garland stove) and modest (those
Ikea glass-fronted cabinets, or the fireproof composite Fireslate
for counters).
</P>
<P>
   PLAN I: PRET-A-PORTER
</P>
<P>
   ``We used off-the-shelf pieces that would require a minimum
amount of craft,'' said Robert Young, who did the design with his
partner, Shea Murdoch, in Murdoch Young Architects. . They were
inspired by industrial kitchens to use two under-the-counter
refrigerators and a freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it open to seem larger, and banished any big vertical
space hog, like a full-size refrigerator,'' he said. ``You reach
down and grab what you need,'' just as chefs do, he said. They used
only one closed cabinet. ``You have to be able to deal with putting
things in nice containers. But it's not for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The custom stainless steel counter has a built-in sink and
backsplash; stainless steel shelves are bolted onto painted plywood
panels. The planned appliances, like the Jenn-Air gas range and
dishwasher, Braun hood, Marvel refrigerators and freezer, are also
stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   Closed storage includes, yes, one Ikea glass-fronted cabinet
($148), but also Antonio Citterio's, cobalt blue plastic rolling
carts from Kartell ($800 each), custom-fitted with butcher block
tops.
</P>
<P>
   The rubber tile floor is from Flexco. ``It's easier on your feet
than a ceramic tile floor,'' Young said. Total cost: $19,586.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN II: SEE THROUGH
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Gans and Matt Jelacic, of Gans &AMP; Jelacic Architecture,
designed a glowing kitchen with sliding glass cabinet doors and
glass shelves. ``We wanted the transparency,'' Gans said, ``because
part of making the shoe box kitchen a great space is the quality of
the light, and the cleanliness of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   The architects proposed industrial-grade steel brackets and
standards, and laminated glass doors made of two pieces of glass
with plastic film in between. ``You can go from opaque white to
clear just by choosing a different kind of film,'' Gans said. The
sliding doors are hung on a heavy-duty track. Cereal boxes can go
behind opaque doors, and Champagne flutes behind clear.
</P>
<P>
   An open shelf holds the computer, perhaps the kitchen tool of
the 21st century. They also proposed a poetic sheet of glass along
one wall, etched with measurement equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   The stainless steel counters have two holes cut into the top,
for nonrecyclable and recyclable garbage. Elsewhere, inexpensive
($146 each) wire cabinet-carts will roll out on wheels; they have
plywood fronts sprayed with durable auto body paint. ``You can get
a slick, personalized, color-coordinated finish,'' said Gans, who
likes the brilliant color palette of the Volkswagen Bug available
from Heavenly Bodyworks in Chelsea (212-691-1092). The walls and
floor are equally slick, and are made of Pergo, a washable
composite laminate that resembles wood. Total cost: $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN III: OPTICAL TRICKS
</P>
<P>
   Like Gans and Jelacic, Ronald Bricke, an interior designer,
created a kitchen with glass-fronted cabinets (Ikea again) and an
open shelf for appliances. His design differs, however, in his use
of tiles for texture and scale. For the counters and floor, he used
dusty green glass ceramic tiles 12 inches square, from Trans
Ceramica Ltd. in Pennsauken, N.J. They're ``the color of a dried
bay leaf,'' said Bricke, a great amateur cook. Total cost: $18,031.
</P>
<P>
   The tiles for the backsplash and the back half of the counters
are polished, and the ones in front of the counter are unpolished
to keep water from flowing freely over the edge. On the floor, he
alternated double rows of polished tile with double rows of
unpolished ones, for aesthetic and functional reasons. ``The
stripes give an impression of widening the room,'' Bricke said,
``and although it would be safest if you kept the whole floor
unpolished, the staggered pattern of polished and unpolished is
fairly safe.'' He's tried it on a client, who in three years has
never slipped, ``and still has all her teeth,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
