<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CARE WORKING WITH STONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Working with natural stone can be a rewarding experience because
a project finished in stone has a rustic charm that is unmatched in
any other building material. Stone is easy to work with because it
requires minimal dressing and shaping, although gathering and
positioning stones calls for a lot of muscle and sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The novice stone builder can acquire the necessary skills for
stone construction by tackling a relatively simple project like
building stone steps up the side of a low hill. Such a project not
only enhances the landscape but it also can be functional if you
have property on two levels.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the first step is to acquire the stone. Where can you
get natural stone? If you have a large piece of property, you may
find that you have enough rocks in your own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Construction sites are another source of free stone. Builders
often collect rocks when they excavate the ground for a foundation.
If you ask the builder, he may give you the stones if you offer to
haul them away.
</P>
<P>
   You can also find stones and rocks in fields and woodlands
around your home. Do not, however, assume that stones are free for
the taking simply because they are lying in a vacant field. The
land belongs to somebody and so do the stones. Always ask
permission before attempting to gather stones from anyone's
property.
</P>
<P>
   Stones are heavy and even a small load can weigh enough to tax
the suspension system of a car; if possible rent a pickup . Before
loading the stones, lay down a sheet of plywood on the truck bed to
protect it from dents and abrasion.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good idea to carry along a pry bar and a shovel to help
you dislodge and uncover stones embedded in the dirt. And, if
possible, bring a wheelbarrow to help you move heavy rocks to the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few hazards involved in gathering stone in the wild.
Be wary when pulling any stone from a hill or a cliff. This could
start a landslide. Be sure of your footing as you move over rugged
terrain so you do not slip or fall. In addition to looking for
rocks, keep a sharp eye out for snakes, wasps and poison ivy.
Finally, enlist the aid of a helper. In addition to helping you
move heavy rocks, he can help you in the event of an accident or
injury.
</P>
<P>
   You can also purchase stone at a commercial stoneyard. Obviously
this costs more than gathering your own pieces, but it's a lot
easier because the dealer does all the heavy work, including
delivery. Even if you can get the bulk of your rocks from a free
source, it is well worth visiting a stone yard to find interesting
and colorful rocks that can highlight your project as a supplement
to those available in local fields.
</P>
<P>
   Once the stone is on site, you can begin construction. Use flat
stones that are at least 24-inches wide for the steps. You can use
two stones together to make the tread, but avoid, if possible,
using three or more stones for one step. This combination can make
the steps uneven and unsteady.
</P>
<P>
   Stone steps need more tread (the measure from the front lip to
the back of the step) than normal steps. Normal steps can have a
9-inch tread, but stone steps should be at least 12 inches from
front to back; 16 inches is even better.
</P>
<P>
   If the stones are too big or if their surfaces are too
irregular, you can dress them with a hammer and chisel. Place the
stone on soft ground and use a cold chisel and hammer _ either a
ball pein (also called a machinist's hammer) or a drilling hammer
(also called a hand sledge) _ to chip away at the lumps and high
spots on the rock surface. Work carefully because natural stone has
veins and cracks that could easily open up and split the rock when
struck with a hammer and chisel.
</P>
<P>
   Start at the bottom of the hill and dig out enough dirt to fit
the first step plus an additional six inches for a gravel bed. The
gravel bed is not essential, but it will provide a solid base for
the stone and a drainage path for ground water. Place the stone so
the front edge is slightly lower than the back. This incline will
allow rainwater to run off the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bottom step is in place, excavate above it for the next
step and gravel bed. This step should overlap the lower one to keep
ground water from under cutting the stones. Use the same technique
to dig back into the slope for the remaining steps. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
