 PERSONALS: Guys Just Want to Have Fun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In Hove, England, the administration of the Pussycats Club has
complained to local authorities that a licensing regulation
forbidding the touching of lap dancers discriminates against the
blind.
</P>
<P>
   Club director  &UR; Kenneth McGrath &LR;  told the London Telegraph that
when two blind men visited the club as part of a stag party, they
``said they very much enjoyed the dances and sensed highly the
proximity of the dancers and, in particular, enjoyed the smell of
their perfume. Given their disability, they felt controlled
touching ought to be permitted for registered blind persons only
and with the dancers' consent.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said 11 out of his 15 dancers said they would not mind
being touched, under regulated circumstances. A city council member
said the license variation request will be taken under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DECONSTRUCTING DADA, BADA-BOOM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Art historian  &UR; Rhonda Roland Shearer &LR;  contends that some of the
items presented as ready-made by  &UR; Marcel Duchamp &LR;  _ a hat rack, for
example, or a reproduction of the Mona Lisa with mustache and beard
drawn on _ are actually items created especially for the art.
</P>
<P>
   This is a controversial contention to art historians, reports
Lingua Franca, which sent reporter  &UR; Daniel Berchenko &LR;  to Shearer's
laboratory to check out her research.
</P>
<P>
   She owns ``one of the world's largest collections of Duchampian
art and ephemera,'' says the magazine, including works she made
herself, such as ``a replica of Duchamp's urinal constructed
entirely out of Fruit Roll-Ups.''
</P>
<P>
   The day Berchenko visited the lab, Shearer and nearly a dozen
researchers ``donned austere white lab coats, huddled around 3-D
models and scrawled equations on chalkboards in an absurdist
performance for this reporter's benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchamp would have loved being there . . . or maybe he was.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LOOKING GOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Highlights from Fashion Week in New York, as per the New York
Observer:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Imitation of Christ line was shown at a funeral parlor,
where models portrayed a stream of mourners. Actress  &UR; Chloe &LR; 
 &UR; Sevigny &LR;  is billed as the line's creative director.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Andres Serrano &LR;  photographed the fall Gucci collection, for
Flaunt magazine, ``as modeled by a swarthy, surly-looking dwarf. .
. . Despite the massive, and predictable, bunching on the trousers
and sleeves, Mr. Serrano's concept actually works.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marc Jacobs &LR;  showed a line that included this item, described
in his show handout: ``No. 42. Chris: wool jacket-stinky rat
T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CRUNCHY DELIGHTS? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Readers who find wine tastings confusing may be intrigued by a
class offered in the latest edition of the Cook's Journal: ``Reidel
Glass Tasting Exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The glass you sip from can greatly affect the degree of
enjoyment you experience,'' says the catalog listing. The class
will include ``a series of tastings as we learn the importance of
shape and design of a glass.'' Reidel is the name of a glass
manufacturing company; participants get four glasses to take home
``for continued enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WORDS THAT WERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Commenting in an Aug. 31 press release about charges of racial
quotas within the Secret Service, Rep.  &UR; Cynthia McKinney &LR; , D-Ga.,
said, `` &UR; Al Gore &LR; 's `Negro Tolerance Level' has never been too
high. I've never known him to have more than one black person
around him at any given time. I'm not shocked, but I am certainly
saddened by this revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, her office rescinded the statement, says
Roll Call, saying that the remarks were in a ``draft press release
that was in the editing process and (was) never intended for public
distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   But as of Wednesday, Sept. 27, the comment was still at
 &LR; www.house.gov/mckinney/news/ &LR;   &LR; pr83100.htm &LR; .
</P>
