<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     09-27 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GOLDEN AGE': THE WASHINGTON CROWD, GRAYING NOW, IS REVISITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-three years after he began his series of interlocking
historical novels with ``Washington, D.C.,'' Gore Vidal has done
something curious: revisited the characters and events of that
first installment with a perspective now altered by age and time.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Golden Age,'' the seventh and concluding installment
(the others are ``Burr,'' ``Lincoln,'' ``1976,'' ``Empire'' and
``Hollywood''), Vidal returns to World War II and the McCarthy era.
He reimagines the ambitions and schemes of the same fictitious
people. And he veers so close to the narrative of ``Washington,
D.C.'' that both books even conclude with the same valedictory
passage, one that equates the fall of a republic or the rise of an
empire with the activities of bacteria on a microscope's slide.
</P>
<P>
   That's nice, but Vidal isn't actually one for false modesty,
national or otherwise. In a postscript, he maintains that he was
right about Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemings in ``Burr'' and that
he's right about Franklin D. Roosevelt's complicity in the Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The latter, along with the advent of the nuclear age, the Truman
Doctrine, the military-industrial complex, rampant anti-communism
and the Korean War, is one of the main historical matters to be
dissected _ and gossiped and speculated about _ here.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal's emphasis has changed, to the point where the fictional
characters who made a sharp-clawed story out of ``Washington,
D.C.'' have receded to the background. After all, they're older
now, and the author has already put most of them through the
wringer. Unfortunately, a forest of loose ends still dangle from
their past histories, and the most recent book, ``Hollywood'' (set
in the 1920s), is 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   So there is much page-clogging explaining to be done, along the
order of ``While Frederika dozed, Blaise went into the men's
section of the pool house, where Peter had observed his sister,
Enid, being made love to by Clay Overbury, now her husband, as well
as aide to Senator James Burden Day, whose daughter, Diana, was
becoming, more and more, the center of Peter's daydreams.''
</P>
<P>
   As Burr himself might have said to Jefferson (in a series where
ascribing made-up dialogue to real historical figures is standard
practice), ``Whew.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vidal's interest this time is less concentrated on his
characters' private vicissitudes. Like Orson Welles, who of course
turns up in a heavily name-dropping story that begins in 1939, he
is interested in deep focus.
</P>
<P>
   So the series' familiar figures, like the aging former actress,
newspaper publisher and illegitimate Burr descendant Caroline
Sanford Sanford (see a previous volume to learn why she married her
cousin), are integrated into an ambitious historical tableau.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, that means that Caroline is a house guest at
the White House while Franklin D. Roosevelt charts his course
around America's isolationists, and that another character is on
hand to watch H.L. Mencken, Walter Lippman, Joseph Alsop, Drew
Pearson and Walter Winchell cover the 1940 Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee, Wendell Willkie, is also acquainted with Vidal's
fictitious characters and is enthusiastically analyzed by one and
all.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, ``The Golden Age'' spans the same period
(1939-54) that is captured far more zestily by another current
cameo-filled novel, Michael Chabon's ``Amazing Adventures of
Kavalier &AMP; Clay.''
</P>
<P>
   Both authors bring on assorted famous faces and signs of the
times, but Vidal's don't often escape the confines of a literary
puppet show. Politicians walk into the story, unburden themselves
of speechy position-paper dialogue or elaborate
self-justifications, and then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Even though, as Vidal points out in his postscript, he actually
knew many of the people he writes about, the book's politicians
sound like refugees from a different kind of dissertation on
midcentury American history.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural figures come alive more successfully, especially those
to whom Vidal can comfortably ascribe intimate banter. And even
Parker Tyler, the scarily intense film critic who loomed large in
the author's ``Myra Breckinridge,'' shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Through Peter Sanford, an observer and writer who is Vidal's
contemporary, the book gets a glimpse of Marlon Brando in ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' (two of Peter's friends find the play ``a
total realignment of the sexes''), meets the divine Dawn Powell
(who bristles at Hemingway's inflated reputation) and hears Paul
Bowles' catty assessment of Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new world, isn't it?'' says Peter, acknowledging the
creative homosexual culture that Vidal evokes with affection. ``Or
the old world,'' a friend tells him, ``better understood.''
</P>
<P>
   It should surprise no one that the tangential figure who is most
memorably summoned here is Vidal himself, in the midst of enjoying
a golden age of his own. The book postulates that the years between
1945 and 1950 were a hurricane's eye of promise and peacetime
between World War II and the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   They were also the years in which the author made his auspicious
arrival on the literary scene with ``Williwaw'' (1946) and
especially ``The City and the Pillar'' (1948), and he glides into
the proceedings with winking assurance. ``My mother insists that
Gore writes just like Shakespeare,'' says one character at a party.
And with this, ``Vidal shook his head sadly. `I could never manage
those rhyming couplets at the end of scenes.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a surprisingly deft and eloquent grace note to this true
magnum opus, Vidal suddenly fades forward to the millennium,
gliding past the success of his currently revived 1960 play ``The
Best Man'' and away to his home in Ravello, Italy, in a condition
that he characterizes as ``ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes over the role of first-person narrator, holds forth on
such present-day forces of historical change as the Internet, and
otherwise contemplates a world of change. He settles some last
scores and offers a final assessment of Roosevelt's shrewdness: ``I
admired him quite as much as I deplored him.'' And he engages in a
conversation with Peter, who refers to this novel's version of
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You made him up,'' says Peter. ``Then you made me up, too. How
does it feel to play god?'' This much is clear at the end of
Vidal's huge, defining seven-book undertaking: He knows the answer.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GOLDEN AGE'
</P>
<P>
   By Gore Vidal.
</P>
<P>
   467 pages. Doubleday. $27.5O.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
