<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BAPTIST-DISPUTE-NYTR-     09-27 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-DISPUTE-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BAPTISTS MAY STRIP NATIONAL FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARY McMULLEN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ In the first blow of what could become a new
round of discord in the Southern Baptist Convention, the executive
board of the Baptist General Convention of Texas has voted to strip
Southern Baptist seminaries and agencies of $5.3 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts are contained in a proposed budget for 2001 that must
be ratified at the state convention's annual meeting Oct. 30-31.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas board left intact more than $17 million in funding for
two Southern Baptist missions agencies, but Tuesday's vote would
eliminate funding the convention's moral-concerns agency, end
funding of five of the convention's six seminaries and give only
token support to the convention's administrative arm, the executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Martin, a spokesman for the Baptist General Convention of
Texas, said the board approved the cuts because Texas Baptists are
unhappy with the theological direction of the Southern Baptist
Convention and are concerned that Southern Baptist leaders were not
allowing other views to be heard, especially in seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a continuing dissent on the part of Texas
Baptists. We have not moved. We're still traditional Baptists,''
Martin said. ``It's the SBC that's moved _ they've moved away from
us.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one observer says the action could portend a split in
the country's largest Protestant church, which claims 15.8 million
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a state convention that's denominationalizing itself.
It's potentially the ninth largest denomination in the nation,''
said Bill Leonard, dean of the divinity school at Wake Forest
University in Winston-Salem, N.C., and a Baptist historian.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist General Convention of Texas is the largest of the
state conventions affiliated with the Southern Baptists, claiming
about 2.8 million members and 5,000 churches. It contributed $22
million to the Southern Baptist Convention in 1999, more than any
other state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders denounced the proposed cuts as an
effort by out-of-touch Texas Baptist leaders to create their own
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Land, president of the ethics and religious
liberty commission, the SBC's moral-concerns agency, said the board
is composed of Texas leaders who lost out in the denomination's
internal struggles 15 to 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their festering discontent is beginning to take organizational
form,'' he said. ``They're trying to build their own kingdom. We'll
see if they can persuade a majority of Baptist churches to go along
with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paige Patterson, president of Southeastern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C. and past president of the
Southern Baptist Convention, said if the budget is ratified, the
Baptist General Convention of Texas would lose a number of large
and influential churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a revolting development,'' Patterson said. ``The only
thing that surprises me is that they have misread their own
churches. If they believe that 5,000 churches are going to go along
with them, they're badly mistaken. They're going to find out these
churches consider themselves Southern Baptists first and Texas
Baptists second.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson and Land _ both native Texans _ expressed confidence
rank-and-file congregations in Texas would make up any shortfall by
giving funds directly to the national headquarters, bypassing the
state convention, which retains 67 percent of contributions from
local churches.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended cuts range from $345,000 for the ethics and
religious liberty commission to almost $1 million for the Southern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky. Southwestern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth would still receive
about $875,000 from the state convention, but that is almost half
the $1.5 million the Texas group budgeted for the school this year.
The schools and agencies face losses in operating revenue ranging
from 6 to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas executive board recommended reallocating the money to
``Texas missions priorities.'' The $4.3 million diverted from
seminaries would go instead to three theological schools run by the
Baptist General Convention of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While the action by the Texas executive board was not a
surprise, both sides agree that it represents a new eruption of a
20-year-old battle in the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Theological conservatives took control of the convention and its
agencies in the mid-1980s, claiming that biblical authority was
being undermined in Southern Baptist seminaries due to modern
methods of historical research. Opponents, generally identified as
``moderates,'' argued that conservatives' insistence on biblical
inerrancy robbed individuals of the traditional Baptist principle
of freedom to interpret the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptists have distanced themselves from the national
convention in recent years. After the disputes of the 1980s, the
state convention voted to reduce the funds it forwarded from
congregations to the Southern Baptist Convention. And last November
the Texas convention rejected an amendment to the Baptist Faith and
Message, a statement of beliefs, that stated in part ``a wife is to
submit herself graciously to the servant leadership of her
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Texas Baptists feuded with national leaders over
questions of doctrine and whether those doctrines should be
enforced in the agencies and organizations of the Southern
Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   At the Southern Baptist Convention's annual meeting in June in
Orlando, the convention approved revisions to the Baptist Faith and
Message. Several Texas Baptists argued against the revisions,
saying they made the statement inflexible and similar to a creed,
something Baptists have traditionally rejected.
</P>
<P>
   While not binding on individuals or local churches, the Baptist
Faith and Message has been used by Southern Baptist seminaries and
agencies as a loyalty test and a condition of employment. A study
committee formed last year by the Baptist General Convention of
Texas reported Sept. 13 that faculty members at one seminary were
prohibited from criticizing the statement, even in private.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, of Wake Forest Divinity School, said theology may have
been the cause of the crisis 20 years ago but has become secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about liberal theology,'' he said. ``There are
pretty conservative churches in Texas. It's about how theology is
enforced. The revisions to the Baptist Faith and Message looked
like enforced theology. Texans have this independent streak, and
they've resisted this for 20 years.'' Leonard noted that another
state convention, the Baptist General Association of Virginia, took
a similar action to the one proposed in Texas several years ago,
but less money was less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is under huge stress. It's still intact, but every
year it's a little less intact,'' he said. ``This is not to say the
Southern Baptist Convention is going to disappear, but it's
increasingly more a clearinghouse than the tightly connected
convention it once was.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is a member of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
