<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IMMIGRATION28-COX     09-27 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS FAIL TO ADVANCE RESIDENCY BILL FOR IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    260&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a vote along party lines, the Senate on
Wednesday rejected Democratic efforts to consider allowing more
undocumented Central American and Haitian immigrants to apply for
legal residency.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-43 vote came on a motion by Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., to let the Senate attach the Latino and Immigrant Fairness
Act as part of a bill to expand the number of H-1B visas for
foreign workers with high-tech skills.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would allow undocumented immigrants who arrived in
the United States between 1972 and 1985 to apply for permanent
residency status. It also would grant refugees from Haiti,
Guatemala, El Salvador and Honduras the same rights as Cuban and
Nicaraguan refugees in applying for permanent residency status.
</P>
<P>
   A third provision would have allowed immigrants living with
their families in the United States to remain in this country while
awaiting a decision on their residency status.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, with support from President Clinton, have vowed to
try adding the measure to other legislation, such as a pending
appropriations bill to finance the Commerce, Justice and State
departments, beginning next week.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech industry, which strongly backs the popular bill to
create tens of thousands of new H-1B visa slots, did not want the
bill to include the controversial amendment on undocumented
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., had earlier used his
leadership powers to keep the Fairness Act separate from the visa
bill, and Daschle failed Wednesday to get the Senate to overrule
that move.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., crossed party lines on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On another immigration-related matter, a group of Democratic
senators introduced a bill Wednesday that would allow legal
immigrants convicted of minor crimes to avoid mandatory
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would overturn provisions of the 1996
Immigration Act that require mandatory deportation of any legal
immigrant convicted of a crime that carried a potential sentence of
one-year or more, even if the person never spent a day in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Under that law, ``homicide and bouncing a check are
indistinguishable,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., the bill's
primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., called the 1996 law ``a major
blot on the American legal system'' and noted that judges do not
have any discretion to avoid deportation of legal residents who may
have committed very minor crimes decades ago and have since turned
their lives around and married American citizens and have
American-born children.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he hoped to attach the legislation to other
immigration-related measures pending in the Senate. The House has
passed a more restrictive version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would restore the legal situation for
deportation based on prior criminal activity to the way it existed
prior to enactment of the 1996 law.
</P>
<P>
   Persons would be liable for deportation only if that was a
penalty at the time the crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would allow those people who already have been
deported to apply for re-admission to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Citizens and Immigrants for Equal Justice:
www.angelfire.com/tx/equalrights/
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
