u f BC-GUCCI-SHARES-NYT &LR;      09-27 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-SHARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ORDERS REVIEW OF DECISION IN SALE OF GUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Reviving a battle between two of Europe's biggest
luxury-goods groups that had seemed resolved, a Dutch court on
Wednesday ordered a review of a decision last year that had allowed
the sale of a $3 billion controlling stake in Gucci Group to
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute of France.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci, which is based in the Netherlands for tax reasons, but
operates out of Italy, had agreed to the deal with Pinault to
thwart a hostile bid by the luxury-goods maker LVMH-Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton, which had earlier acquired a sizable stake in Gucci.
The decision last year diluted the LVMH stake to about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision last year, a lower Dutch court criticized
Gucci's management for its handling of the battle against LVMH,
controlled by the French billionaire Bernard Arnault, but refused
to stop the deal with Pinault or to order an investigation of
Gucci's management procedures, as LVMH had demanded.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH had protested that Gucci's deal with Pinault diluted LVMH's
share in Gucci and denied it a seat on the Gucci board, something
LVMH had sought. By contrast, Pinault secured the right to nominate
four of Gucci's nine board members.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision opened the door for LVMH to refile its case
against Gucci and Pinault, which is controlled by Arnault's
archrival, the French billionaire Francois Pinault.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, LVMH said it would seek a full court
investigation of Gucci's handling of the LVMH bid, the annulment of
the deal with Pinault, and ``appropriate measures to remedy the
harm caused by the improper conduct of Gucci's management.'' But
the possibility of appeals and counterappeals made any early
solution to the smoldering conflict unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The skirmish with LVMH, which pits two of France's richest and
most powerful businessmen against each other, has cost Gucci's
management time and money. Still, the decision Wednesday nudged
Gucci's share price up 3 percent, to 117.70 euros, on speculation
that Gucci, already a darling of investors, might again have its
share price driven up as the target in a revived bidding war
between LVMH and Pinault.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in LVMH, which has already amassed about 1 billion euros,
or $880 million, in capital gains from the appreciation of its
Gucci shares, rose by more than 2 percent, to 85 euros. Shares in
Pinault, which controls one of France's biggest department-store
chains, fell almost 3 percent, to 198 euros.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH has always insisted it would do nothing to harass Gucci, so
as not to jeopardize the value of its Gucci stake. Yet LVMH has
three other legal challenges pending in the Netherlands, one
demanding annulment of the Pinault deal and another seeking damages
or a court order requiring that Pinault bid for all Gucci shares. A
third case seeks the annulment of decisions taken at a Gucci
shareholder meeting last year approving the Pinault deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH, in its statement, said that if fresh hearings led to a
cancellation of the Pinault deal, it would seek a solution ``in the
interest of all shareholders that would enable Gucci to continue to
execute its strategy, while remaining entirely independent.'' It
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Serge Weinberg, Pinault's chief executive, said that nothing in
Wednesday's decision ``posed an obstacle to the pursuit of the
development of the Gucci group.'' He added, ``We are extremely
confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
