<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TESTAVERDE AND GROH HAVE SCORE TO SETTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (On Pro Football)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It should come as no surprise that New York Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde rather uncharacteristically spoke out
about his benching by coach Al Groh in the game against the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers. Because for months now, rather quietly, the
relationship between the two men has become quite chilly.
</P>
<P>
   Groh and Testaverde did not hit it off right from the beginning,
said several Jets players, and they have grown further apart.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons has nothing to do with Groh. Testaverde was
close to Bill Parcells and remains so. Testaverde always respected
how Parcells treated veteran players by not abusing their bodies
with tough, physical practices.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where the tensions between Groh and Testaverde have
their origin, said players. Groh's training camp practices were
brutal, and Testaverde went to Groh early in the summer, suggesting
that he ease up. The practices remained extremely physical.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, some players went to Parcells to
complain about Groh's practices. Parcells stayed out of the
dispute, players said, because Parcells felt it would be unfair to
Groh to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is among the veterans who believe Groh was running
difficult practices so he could establish himself as a tough coach,
several Jets said. Perhaps Groh was trying to grab the attention of
the players away from Parcells, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Groh's intentions, those harsh training camps seem to
be paying off. The Jets have been a tremendous fourth-quarter team
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, who has struggled early in games this season, ranks
second in the National Football League with a 122.7 rating in the
fourth quarter. The Jets' late comeback against the Buccaneers on
Sunday marked only the second time in 30 years that a team has won
a game after trailing by at least 10 points with less than two
minutes remaining. John Elway and the Denver Broncos did it against
the Kansas City Chiefs in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ignoring players can be dangerous. When Dick
Vermeil coached the St. Louis Rams, some veteran players complained
about harsh practices. Vermeil changed his ways, and in doing so
unified the team.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jets are 4-0 and have completed only a quarter of
their regular-season schedule, Testaverde has already been taking
heat from the fans and the news media for his overall play, which
has been poor at times.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off an Achilles' tendon injury and the departure of
Keyshawn Johnson, a top wide receiver, Testaverde has a 49.7
completion percentage and a dismal 64.7 quarterback rating.
</P>
<P>
   What irks Testaverde is that he believes he is getting the blame
for much of the Jets' offensive woes when some of the problems are
not his fault, Jets players said. Testaverde also wishes that Groh
would publicly back him.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Testaverde said of his one-series benching: ``I just
kept saying to myself, he's making a big mistake taking me out.
Because I really believe the fourth quarter belongs to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Jets said that sometimes the coaching staff had made
mistakes by putting the wrong personnel on the field in certain
situations. Wide receivers have sometimes run the wrong routes. But
most of the blame for the offense's struggles goes to Testaverde.
The quarterback believes he is being hung out to dry by Groh, the
players said, when Groh could make it clear that Testaverde is
often not to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The players said, for example, that wide receivers had run poor
routes several times in the Tampa Bay game. But most fans would not
know that the receivers were to blame when Testaverde lofted an
errant pass. They would assume that the bad pass was the
quarterback's fault.
</P>
<P>
   When he played for six years in Tampa Bay at the beginning of
his professional career, Testaverde thought he was often blamed for
mistakes that were not his doing. He did not discuss this in
public. But he intends to make his feelings known now, several Jets
said, which explains why he spoke up after Groh benched him for a
series against the Buccaneers. Make no mistake about it: Testaverde
wanted to do well in front of the Buccaneers fans, in a stadium
where he had often been booed.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's main beef with Groh? Testaverde wants everyone to
be accountable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Groh wanted to trade wide receiver Johnson
was that Groh feared the kind of public display that Testaverde put
on this week. But if what Jets players say is true, then Testaverde
has a right to be upset.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed now is one of those smart-mouthed Parcells
tirades. There were times when reporters would ask Parcells
questions about a struggling player, and Parcells would get nasty
with the reporters in support of the player. Those eruptions were
sometimes contrived, but they worked, because the player felt
Parcells was backing him up in public.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions between Groh and Testaverde do not seem to have
reached a critical point. There will likely be a meeting between
the two men soon to work out their differences. If the team keeps
winning, Testaverde's remarks will be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a reconciliation is needed. The Jets are 4-0 for the
first time in their history. The Jets have a bye this week, and
after they play Pittsburgh next week, they will probably be 5-0.
Things are going too well for Testaverde and Groh not to patch up
their differences. They need each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get some things resolved,'' Testaverde said this
week of the entire team. ``I'd like to share some of these things
with you, but it's probably better that I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Just share them with the man who matters: the head coach. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
