<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL OPERATIONS AND COMPUTER PORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is an AGP port, and what are PCI slots used for in a
computer?
</P>
<P>
   A. AGP stands for Accelerated Graphics Port, and it is a place
on your computer's motherboard for the system's videocard. PCI
stands for Peripheral Component Interconnect, and it refers to a
different type of slot on the motherboard for things like network
cards or cards to connect photo scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Videocards are also sometimes installed in PCI slots, but many
computers manufactured within the past few years are using the AGP
option. That is because the AGP can communicate directly with the
computer's main memory, while a videocard that is plugged into a
PCI slot shares time with other cards plugged into adjacent PCI
slots.
</P>
<P>
   Cards that plug into PCI slots can help you expand your
computer's capabilities, like the ability to connect to an Ethernet
network. PCI slots enable ``plug and play'' installation.
</P>
<P>
   Industry Standard Architecture slots are an older type of card
slot, but most computers are still made to include ISA slots on
their motherboards. They are commonly used for adding parallel or
serial port expansion cards, and sometimes sound cards or internal
modems.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the meaning of the Windows error message ``This
program has performed an illegal operation and will be shut down''?
Am I doing something wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. You're not doing anything wrong or against the law, despite
what the error message says. The message means that the program in
question is having a problem. The ``illegal operation'' designation
covers a wide range of errors, and it may take some time, patience
and troubleshooting to pinpoint the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The most common causes of an illegal operation include a problem
between that program and a software driver in your operating system
or a memory-management problem between the program and one open in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   Problems and conflicts with different dynamic-link library
files, or DLLs, that are added to your system when you install
software programs can also cause illegal operation errors. Hardware
conflicts, defective RAM chips and program bugs can also cause the
error.
</P>
<P>
   To pinpoint the cause, ask yourself some questions: Has this
program always worked but is now crashing out of the blue? Has
anything, like new hardware devices or software, been added lately?
If you can trace the advent of the problem to a specific event, it
may help narrow down the likely suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The System File Checker, Version Conflict Manager and Dr. Watson
utilities included in Windows 98 might help you track the source of
your problem.
</P>
<P>
   To find these programs, go to the Start menu, then to Programs,
Accessories and System Tools. Open the System Information program
and look under the Tools menu to find the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The System File Checker can restore damaged system files, while
Dr. Watson records what your computer was doing when it crashed and
may offer suggestions as to why. The Verson Conflict Manager keeps
a tab on which system files were updated or replaced during a
software or hardware installation.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft keeps a vast library of technical articles on its Web
site at support.microsoft.com/search. You can search the site for
``illegal operation,'' along with the names of your suspect
software or hardware, and you might find the solution to your
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions will vary depending on the combination of factors, but
you may have to do things like uninstalling and reinstalling
programs or downloading and installing software patches for your
system to put a stop to the illegal-operation errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
