<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet Appliance Eliminates Hard Drive
</P>
<P>
   Imagine upgrading your computer's operating system by simply
popping out a CD-ROM and replacing it with a new one: no muss, no
fuss, no scrambled software drivers and bald spots from pulling out
hair.
</P>
<P>
   This is the idea behind a new kind of Internet appliance called
the New Internet Computer, or NIC. The basic model is priced at
$199 and is aimed at schools and consumers that would like to add
Internet access around the house without nicking too much from the
family budget.
</P>
<P>
   Although it lacks an internal hard drive and isn't a
full-fledged computer, the NIC has enough hardware under the hood
to make it more robust than a simplified Internet appliance. (It is
made by New Internet Computer Co., which was started by Larry
Ellison, chief executive of Oracle Corp.; Gina Smith, a former
technology columnist and television host, is New Internet Computer
Co.'s chief executive.)
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet appliances will allow users to send e-mail only
with the maker's designated provider and do basic Web browsing, but
the NIC allows the use of existing e-mail accounts and includes the
latest version of Netscape Navigator and common browser plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Since it doesn't have a hard drive for storage, the NIC will
allow users to log on to shared application servers and do things
like word processing over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The NIC's Linux-based operating system runs from a CD-ROM inside
a computer with a 266-MHz Pentium-class processor, 64 megabytes of
RAM and a 56-kilobits-per-second modem. The NIC can also connect to
the Internet with an Ethernet card and comes with two USB ports.
The $199 computer doesn't come with a monitor, but a 15-inch
display can be bought from the company for $129 and everything is
available at www.thinknic.com.
</P>
<P>
   While it may not be able to replace a regular desktop computer
system, the NIC's lower price and its potential to free users from
the technical-support hot line make the middle ground look like an
awfully nice place to explore.
</P>
<P>
   You've Got Mail (cc: the Mario Brothers)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with 10-year-olds is that they're disorganized,
they're constantly late and they've always got their heads buried
in some video game when they should be doing homework.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a new cartridge for the GameBoy, they've run out
of excuses for their poor behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Shark MX from Interact Accessories is an application that
enables the GameBoy to send and receive electronic messages to and
from any other e-mail account.
</P>
<P>
   The Shark MX also comes with an address book, a calendar and a
calculator so that owners can figure out how much of their day is
devoted to Donkey Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Not much larger than a typical game cartridge, the Shark MX can
connect to Interact's servers through any regular phone line.
</P>
<P>
   After setting up an e-mail account at Gamesharker.com, players
can use their well-muscled thumbs to compose e-mail messages on an
onscreen keypad.
</P>
<P>
   The device is $39.99 and comes with 30 free minutes of
connection time. Each 60 minutes of additional time is $6, and the
calls to Interact's servers are toll free _ cheaper than a
BlackBerry pager or a Palm VII and a lot less likely to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   A Study of the Wired World Finds Dropouts and No-Shows
</P>
<P>
   If the Internet is the information superhighway, a substantial
number of American adults are avoiding the on-ramp, according to a
recent survey sponsored by the Pew Charitable Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which is based on random telephone interviews with
about 2,000 adults, shows that half of American adults do not have
Internet access and that 57 percent of those people have no
interest in going online.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people over 50 with no Internet access, 74 percent say
they have no plans to get access. Cost is not the major stumbling
block, according to the survey. Instead, many older Americans say
they simply do not see the value in logging on. By contrast, 65
percent of those under 50 say they plan to go online someday but
that they worry about the costs of computers and access.
</P>
<P>
   About 13 percent of all nonusers are what the researchers call
Internet dropouts. They were once online, but no longer have
access. ``It's a mystery in some cases, because they don't want to
say why they dropped out,'' said Lee Raine, director of the
research. But some respondents said that a significant event, like
losing a job, had caused them to give up Web access.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results are part of the Pew Internet and American
Life Project, an effort to collect, analyze and publish data on
Internet use. The results are available at www.pewinternet.org.
</P>
<P>
   Color Choices for Headphones Make Them iMacs for the Ears
</P>
<P>
   How far is all this Macintosh-inspired translucence going to go?
Apparently the design folks at Sony believe that the iMac look
should be extended to their latest offering in lightweight
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Called W.EAR (no, the period between the W and the E is not a
typo), these cleverly crafted headphones, ideal for use with
portable music devices, come with interchangeable shells in 12
translucent colors. Beneath their skins, the headphones, which cost
$30 each and come with two sets of shells (extra shells cost $6 a
pair), sport some impressive engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Sony spokesmen said that W.EAR headphones used highly efficient
Neodymium magnets that help pump out 104 decibels of sound pressure
from a single watt of input power. The W.EAR headphones also have a
gold-plated plug at the end of the copper cord to reduce electrical
resistance so the headphones can take advantage of whatever music
player they happen to be plugged into.
</P>
