<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: AMERICAN CHARGED AS SPY
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors formally filed espionage charges against Edmond
Pope, the 54-year-old former U.S. Navy captain arrested in April
while buying plans for a Russian torpedo propulsion system. A trial
was set for next month. A lawyer for Pope, who runs a company
specializing in foreign marine equipment, said the system is a
decade old and had previously been exported. Pope faces 20 years in
prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: NORWEGIANS TO DIVE TO KURSK
</P>
<P>
   Russia plans to hire Norwegian divers this week to recover the
bodies of 118 crewmen from the nuclear submarine Kursk, which sank
last month, said Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov. Recovery work
could start by Oct. 10, he added. But in a letter, 78 relatives of
the crewmen urged the government to proceed slowly, lest the
recovery work claim still more lives.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL LASHES OUT
</P>
<P>
   A tearful Helmut Kohl addressed a ceremony marking next week's
10th anniversary of German reunification, attacking Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer for
``betraying'' Germans by having given up on the move. Kohl, in a
speech to a conservative research group, read out remarks made by
the two men against reunification in the months before the Berlin
Wall fell. Kohl, disgraced after a campaign fund scandal last year,
has not been invited to speak at an official Unity Day event in
Dresden on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: FERRY TOLL RISES
</P>
<P>
   The death toll rose to 63 in the sinking of a ferry that ran
aground near the island of Paros in the Aegean Sea on Tuesday
night. Rescue teams continued to search for at least nine missing
passengers from ferry, which had more than 500 people aboard. The
government called the tragedy inexplicable, and the ship's captain
was held pending a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA
</P>
<P>
   VOTE BEING CONSIDERED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien is considering calling an election
in November, a few days after the U.S. elections. Chretien, whose
term expires in 2002, reportedly feels his chances of winning a
third term were bolstered by an internal Liberal Party poll
indicating that many Tory voters in Ontario are migrating to the
Liberals, shunning the nation's new conservative party, the
Canadian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SWITCH TO LIBERALS
</P>
<P>
   In the latest erosion of Canada's small parties, the Liberals
gained another opposition member as Rick Laliberte, a New
Democratic Party legislator from Saskatchewan, switched allegiance
to the ruling party. This month, two Tory Conservative legislators
joined the Liberals. In Parliament the Conservatives have 15 seats,
the New Democrats 19, the Bloc Quebecois 44, the Canadian Alliance
58, and the Liberals 160.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAPPED STAR'S PLEA
</P>
<P>
   The movie idol Rajkumar, 72, who was kidnapped eight weeks ago
by the notorious bandit Veerappan, has asked his fans in the
southern state of Karnataka not to shut down the state and its
capital, Bangalore, on Thursday, according to an emissary who has
been negotiating for his release. In a statement, the emissary said
that Rajkumar had said that a general strike ``will inconvenience
the general public, and I do not want you to cause any trouble to
either the government or the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
