<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 1.
It includes a Part 2 on television.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moving in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ESSAY (Undated) _ Watching television is thought to be
cultural anthropology, mindless escapism, emotional solace or a
source of news, sports and occasionally art. But it is rarely
embraced for doing all these things at once. Yet that variety, and
the way the parts feed one another, is where television gets its
immense social power. Caryn James defends the medium, lambastes
people who regard it with condescension and criticizes it expertly.
``Even at its worst it can be dreadful in a fascinating way,'' she
writes. 1700 words. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SEASON-ROCKEFELLER (Undated) _ The new season's crop of
television shows is transmitting a puritanical message: the pursuit
of wealth breeds immorality _ or, at the least, extreme vulgarity.
On ``Bull,'' the new TNT series, the founder of an investment
banking firm is a schemer. The hotshot stockbrokers in ``The
Street'' on Fox break up their day with quickies. On NBC's
``Titans,'' an heir to an aeronautics fortune discovers that his
former lover is about to become his stepmother _ and she's pregnant
with his baby. None of these fictional concoctions, however,
compete in the morality and melodrama department with ``The
Rockefellers,'' PBS' juicy series on American capitalism's royal
family. This two-part program, which begins Oct. 16, serves up
money lust, religion fervor, philanthropic penance, sexual
impropriety and bigamy. By Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JAZZ-BURNS (Undated) _ ``Jazz,'' due on PBS on Jan. 8, is one
of the most highly anticipated programs of the new television
season. It took six years for Ken Burns, veteran of ``Civil War''
and ``Baseball,'' to assemble 2,400 stills, 2,000 film clips, 75
interviews and 500 pieces of recorded music. But it was impromptu
details _ an interviewee snapping his fingers or singing _ that
Peter Watrous finds the most exciting. Then, he writes, the
original recording wafts onto the soundtrack, in time with the
talking head. What might have been merely nostalgia or scholarship
becomes history. By Peter Watrous. With photograph.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WOLF (Los Angeles) _ Dick Wolf is the busiest producer on
television. He has four series running, including ``Law and
Order,'' it's spinoff, ``Law and Order: Special Victims Unit,'' the
new ``Deadline,'' a show about a crusading newspaper columnist and
``Arrest and Trial,'' which starts on the same night as
``Deadline.'' Another spinoff of ``Law and Order'' is in the works.
``I'm a crime junkie,'' Wolf said in an interview with Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   With photograph.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GIDEON-BRAUGHER (Los Angeles) _ Actresses inspire Andre
Braugher more than actors, because he believes weakness is almost
bred out of men. That's why he has never seen Hamlet played as the
coward he believes he is. Braugher is starring in his second
television series, ``Gideon's Crossing,'' a hospital drama on ABC.
He plays Dr. Ben Gideon, a character based on Dr. Jerome Groopman,
a Boston physician who chronicled his clinical experiences in the
1997 book ``The Measure of Our Days.'' While the role isn't exactly
Hamlet, the character appears to be complex enough to keep
Braugher's fires fed for now. By Terrence Rafferty. With
photograph.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORSON-WELLES-COMEBACK (New York) _ Fifteen years after his
death, Orson Welles _ boy genius, film pioneer, theatrical
innovator and portly outcast _ is experiencing a comeback. ``RKO
281,'' a documentary about the making of ``Citizen Kane'' is out on
video. ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' a movie by Tim Robbins tells the
story of Welles' production of a pro-union musical in the 1930s.
``The Big Brass Ring,'' a screenplay he wrote years ago, was made
into a movie starring William Hurt. Even the U.S. Postal Service
has issued a stamp in his honor. Amazon.com lists 45 different
titles about him. (It lists 34 about William Randolph Hearst.) Now
comes ``War of the Worlds,'' a new play at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music. ``It's kind of artistic necrophilia,'' said a former
collaborator. By Jonathan Mandell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EVE (New York) _ Fifty years ago, the movie ``All About
Eve,'' starring Bette Davis as Margo Channing opened at the Roxy in
New York and became an instant classic. The film won six Academy
Awards. In a newly restored 50th-anniversary print, the movie will
be shown for one week, starting Oct. 6 at Film Forum in Manhattan.
Mel Gussow, who over the years has interviewed Davis; Joe
Mankiewicz, the films writer and director, and Darryl Zanuck, its
producer, tells all about ``All About Eve.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-YANG (Undated) _ ``Yi Yi,'' which will be shown on
Wednesday at the New York Film Festival, is the first of Edward
Yang's seven features to reach American theaters. Set, like all his
films, in middle-class Taipei, ``Yi Yi'' provides an engaging
introduction to Yang's fictional universe, in part because of its
bemused approach to family life. He has been compared with
Michelangelo Antonioni and Jean-Luc Godard and his 1991 film ``A
Brighter Summer Day'' is considered one of the modern era's
greatest Chinese-language films. By Godfrey Cheshire. With
photograph.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GIRLFIGHT (New York ) _ Like more traditional boxing movies
before it, ``Girlfight'' is about ``an outsider who enters a world
where she does not belong and finds a place for herself,'' said the
director Karyn Kusama. The film, which opened Friday, is the story
of a sullen, gum chewing, muscular girl from the underclass, played
by Michelle Rodriguez, who literally fights her way into the ring.
It could be a metaphor for Kusama's bout with studios as she tried
to get financing. John Sayles came up with $1 million for Kusama,
his former baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY-JAPAN-FUKUHARA (New York) _ ``Shinzo and Roso
Fukuhara: Photographs by Ginza Modern Boys, 1913-41,'' at Sepia
International presents for the first time in New York the work of
two brothers who played early roles in the formation of Japanese
modernist photography. Shinzo and Roso Fukuhara's father founded
Shiseido, the cosmetics company and Shinzo was obligated to follow
his father as company president. He pursued photography only as a
sideline yet still found time to found a photography magazine and
to promote the use of photography in advertisements for his
company. Roso Fukuhara's work was not published in his lifetime,
yet he was a pioneer of photographic modernism: a rather startling
combination. By Vicki Goldberg.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-CONNER (San Francisco) _ For more than four decades Bruce
Conner has been concerned with undermining everything you ever
thought you knew about who or what it is to be an artist. Museum
curators and critics describe him as ``paranoiac'' and
``impossible.'' The work in his traveling exhibit opening at the
Los Angeles Museum of Contemporary Art next Sunday is so disparate
that one critic called it a ``group show.'' Amei Wallach finds him
polite and outspoken. ``Some people are visual illiterates and they
work in museums,'' he says. By Amei Wallach.
</P>
<P>
   PORTRAIT-WASHINGTON (New York) _ Many people have seen the
large, heroic portraits of George Washington, but few have seen the
miniature that will go on auction at Christie's in New York in
January. The watercolor in a gold locket depicts Washington, not as
a man of authority, but as Martha Washington's husband. It has
impeccable provenance. All its past owners are known and Washington
himself recorded the sitting in his journal on a Saturday in 1789:
``Sat for Mr. Ramage near two hours to-day who was drawing a
miniature Picture of me for Mrs. Washington.'' It is expected to
sell for $600,000 to $900,000
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SIMON-N'DOUR (Undated) _ Paul Simon and Youssou N'Dour
have racked up ample mileage and countless collaborators over the
last decades as they made their musical reflexes grapple with
foreign stimuli. On their new albums, they are back on home ground,
but irrevocably changed. ``If you don't know where you're heading
anymore/Go back to where you come from,'' N'Dour sings on his new
album, ``Joko (The Link).'' ``Carry me home, my teacher, carry me
home,'' Simon sings on his new ``You're the One.'' By Jon Pareles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LINDBERG (Undated) _ ``Cantigas,'' a work by Magnus
Lindberg will be played by the Cleveland Orchestra next week at
Carnegie Hall and Deutsche Grammophon has released a CD of his
``Aura'' and ``Engine.'' This activity puts the spotlight on the
42-year-old Finnish composer. By Paul Griffiths. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-GRAHAM-DEADMAN (San Francisco) The American mezzo-soprano
Susan Graham, fresh from John Harbison's ``Great Gatsby'' at the
Metropolitan Opera, opens Saturday in Jake Heggie's ``Dead Man
Walking'' at the San Francisco Opera. The opera, with a libretto by
the playwright Terrence McNally, is based on Sister Helen Prejean's
book of the same name, which also inspired a movie. It tells of
Prejean's attempts to save the soul of a murderer sentenced to
death. The opera `` makes you go places you might not ordinarily
go,'' says Graham in an interview with David Mermelstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `t') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This weeks Travel Section is devoted to fall and winter cruises.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE-TRENDS (Undated) _ This year is shaping up as a
record for the cruise industry with the number of passengers
possibly exceeding 7 million. A major reason is the many low fares.
The reason for such bargains is not a mystery: Almost 80 new ships
joined the North American fleet during the 1990s, and 52 more are
scheduled by 2005. To offset the low fare, some lines have added
more charges on board and have come up with even more competitive
cruises. Coming up is a floating health club from Canyon Ranch and
nearly 2,000 short cruises. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-CRUISE-REFUNDS (Undated) _ On Sept. 14, with
2,800 passengers aboard five vessels in the Bahamas, Cozumel,
Mexico, and Nova Scotia, Premier Cruises was shut down, seized by
creditors. For Betsy Wade, this was more than a news story. In June
she was a Premier passenger when the air conditioning failed on the
Big Red Boat en route to Nova Scotia. Passengers were put on a bus
and sent back to New York. Ever since then she had been trying to
get a refund. Now she finds she is in a really big boat _ 7,000
passengers are due refunds. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE-SENIORS (Undated) _ In her youth, Barbara
Delatiner confesses to a bias against
if-this-is-Tuesday-it-must-be-Copenhagen trips. As for a cruise,
for ``mature'' travelers, she was concerned it would resemble a
floating retirement home. Twelve days after boarding the Norwegian
Dream, she disembarked with mixed feelings. She enjoyed the
pampering aboard ship, preferred having a cabin to living out of a
suitcase on a land tour and had some memories that will last a
lifetime. But she found the time on shore rushed to the point she
figured out she had about five seconds per painting at the
Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, Russia. By Barbara Delatiner.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-STEAMBOAT (UNDATED) _ One blast of the American Queen's
whistle is all it took to evoke the romance of the paddleboat.
Glenn Collins said the trip exceeded his expectations in almost
every respect. There were nightly entertainments, day trips to
plantations, and most of all the mighty Mississippi itself. By
Glenn Collins
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-CARIBBEAN-FAMILY (Undated) _ The Ocean Princess bills
itself as ``the Love Boat,'' but for 19 members of one clan it was
the family boat. By Christopher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-PANAMA (Undated) _ Starting in October, vacationers who
would have seen Panama only from a ship's railing will be able to
go ashore when Panama inaugurates Colon 2000, a $45 million cruise
ship port on the Caribbean entrance to the canal. Backers of Colon
2000 hope to lure tourists ashore with the promise of duty-free
shopping, music and folk dancing at a two-story,
190,000-square-foot mall, scheduled to open in June. By David
Gonzalez. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) - Deals on travel to Scotland, Quebec
and Morocco. By Joseph Siano.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Answers to questions about Outward Bound
Courses for Women; dance lessons in Dublin and geneaology research
in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Items on the fuel surcharge in the
U.S.; an art noureau show at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington; and a new resort in Frisco, Texas.
</P>
