<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      09-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEART KNOWS RACISM BEFORE THE HEAD
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of white people are slow. We don't get it right away. Our
antenna doesn't work as well as non-whites on some matters.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Jewish and have experienced anti-Semitism, you might
understand it. But WASP-style whites, the white-bread kind, don't
generally live with knowledge that we could be bullied just because
of our color or ethnicity. We're not on guard ourselves, so we're
often slow to make a fuss when something happens to a non-white.
</P>
<P>
   It's not because we don't see a wrong's been committed. We get
it when we think about it, but we don't recognize it right away.
And we never see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   I guess if you don't live with a certain fear in your gut, you
have to rely on your head and that takes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no excuses, we were slow on the Wen Ho Lee case. It took
a long time for the public and the media to get outraged about the
unfairness of locking up an American scientist for being a possible
Chinese spy, holding him for nine months in solitary and in leg
irons, threatening him with death for espionage and then dropping
58 counts against him, after he pleaded guilty to one.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lee is a martyr to government bungling and big-time racial
profiling. Some whites don't get racial profiling, which is really
old-fashioned bigotry. Usually we learn it in a secondhand way.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican-born Georgina, who has lived half of her life in
California, tells about buying mascara at a Sacramento drugstore,
getting home to realize it was the wrong color and returning to
make an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   This is a simple annoyance but no problem, you would think. But
if you look like Georgina, which means you are lovely,
well-dressed, look like you can afford mascara but you are not
white, nothing can be assumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I know you bought this here?'' the clerk asked.
Georgina produced the receipt. ``How do I know you didn't find it
on the floor and are pretending it's yours?''
</P>
<P>
   Georgina returned with her husband, the European-American
professor, and got her mascara exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's racial profiling,'' Georgina says.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican-American teen-ager who lives in a small Sonoma County
town has been on edge since he was in middle school. People assume
he's a troublemaker, he says. Why? Look at me, he says. He's brown.
Now he's also big and tall. Store clerks follow him with their
eyes. Security cops walk behind him at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   A white woman married to an African-American is learning about
racial profiling through their older son. He attends a prestigious
East Coast university in a large city, where he's studying pre-med
and Spanish; but when he comes back to his hometown in Sonoma
County, he has to be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas he parked at the junior college intending to take
a run on the track course, when an officer stopped him and asked
what he was doing. Going for a run, he said. The officer said OK,
but would he first pull up his shirt for him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you know why he asked that. I didn't. I asked his mother,
and she said the cop was looking for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   I'm stupid on these things. Maybe it's because I have daughters
and no one in my family, that I know of, has ever been stopped and
made to prove he or she wasn't armed. Maybe, too, it's because I so
admire the young man in question and remember when he was a little
boy, resisting bedtime, playing his violin at the top of the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   How dare that cop?
</P>
<P>
   His mother was ready to file a report. ``As a white person, I
wanted to make a stink.'' But her son said it wasn't worth it.
Besides, he had only a few days before he went back to the city,
where there are lots of African-Americans. Still, he purposely
stayed away from First Night activities to avoid any potential
hassles.
</P>
<P>
   The college student has learned to be compliant and real polite
when stopped by police. When asked for his ID, he knows to avoid
sudden movements and makes a point of saying he is only reaching in
his pocket for his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids have to deal with something that could never happen to
me,'' says their mother. Is it fair that they could be stopped for
no apparent reason and that they have to use more caution than
other people? ``All I know is that it's a fact of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   I've heard of grade school teachers who help students understand
how prejudice works by having the class divide up by hair and eye
color. Then they are treated differently _ how often they're called
on, how they're disciplined _ solely because of their black hair or
green eyes. Maybe we adults should try that.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing as how we're living in a state and a nation that is
rapidly changing its looks, we'd better start getting it.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
