<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-TAPE0928-COX     09-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAPE0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign calls focus of FBI debate tape theory
'ridiculous'By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The George W. Bush presidential campaign,
dissatisfied with the FBI investigation of the debate preparation
tape that was shipped to the opposition, believes the feds suspect
a Bush scheme to sabotage the upcoming presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McKinnon, whose firm Maverick Media does Bush's TV ads,
said Wednesday that questions asked of his staff by FBI agents show
``they had a theory that somebody mailed this as a way to blow up
the debates, which is a ridiculous notion.''
</P>
<P>
   Yvette Lozano, a Maverick Media employee questioned by the FBI,
said the two agents who quizzed her for 90 minutes posited the
sabotage theory based on the notion that a stolen tape might
provide a convenient out for a candidate not eager to debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the agents said, 'It could be that you sent this
information because you didn't want the debates to happen,''' said
Lozano, who denied having anything to do with the clandestine
mailing of the debate preparation materials to the Al Gore camp.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Justice Department spokesman Carole Florman on
Wednesday offered no response.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ongoing investigation and we just aren't talking
about the investigation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first presidential debate between Bush and Democratic foe
Gore is Tuesday in Boston. Two other debates are set for later in
the month.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, Bush debate preparation material _ including a
videotape of a mock debate session _ showed up in the mail at the
office of former U.S. Rep. Tom Downey of New York. At the time,
Downey's role in the Gore campaign included portraying Bush in mock
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Downey turned the material over to the FBI. Last Thursday and
Friday, five people at Maverick Media, including McKinnon, were
interviewed by federal agents. McKinnon said the line of
questioning made it clear the agents are operating under the theory
that the Bush campaign orchestrated the mailing of the debate
materials as part of a scheme to delay or cancel the debates.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which initially favored a different debate
schedule other than the one that eventually prevailed, has made no
such efforts, spokeswoman Mindy Tucker noted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous and people in politics know the only people
who'd be interested in getting this kind of information to the Al
Gore camp would be somebody who supports Al Gore's campaign,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in a Tuesday interview on ``Larry King Live,'' supported
that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you it's not one of my supporters,'' he said.
``Somebody who is for me is not going to be sending tapes to the
Gore campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lozano, an administrator at Maverick Media, said her interview
with the FBI included questions about a downtown Post Office
videotape that the FBI agents said showed her mailing a package two
days before the debate materials showed up at Downey's office.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano said she did not immediately recall what she had sent
that day. After some thought, she recalled it was pants being
returned to The Gap by McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said something along the lines of, 'We don't think it was
pants. You were not mailing pants.'''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said Wednesday it was his pants that were in the
package.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano, 30, offered to be fingerprinted and take a polygraph
exam. The agents returned last Friday for the fingerprints and a
few more questions. No polygraph exam has been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was horrified,'' McKinnon said of the questioning of
Lozano by the FBI. ``They flat out asked her if she did it and
said, `What if we found your fingerprints on the package?' and
asked her to confess. It was really an unpleasant experience for
her and for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After initially expressing confidence that the FBI would get to
the bottom of the matter, Bush officials now are questioning the
progress of the probe. Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director
has wondered aloud about why the FBI hasn't paid some attention to
Gore headquarters in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Gore campaign suspended a junior staffer, Michael
Doyne, who had told a friend that the Democrats might have a
``mole'' at Bush headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the FBI and the federal law enforcement agencies would
follow up on that boast by looking at computer hard drives (at Gore
headquarters) to determine whether in fact there is any substance
to those comments,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Mark Fabiani said Wednesday that the FBI has not
contacted Doyne. Fabiani has said the Gore campaign is confident
the FBI will figure out how the tape wound up at Downey's office.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's firm has been a natural subject of questions because
of his former ties to the Democratic Party. McKinnon never worked
for a GOP candidate until he signed on for Bush's gubernatorial
re-election bid in 19998. He previously had worked for Democratic
Govs. Mark White and Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon met Lozano when she worked as a Richards volunteer in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said he offered to take a polygraph exam after federal
investigators asked him if he mailed the package or instructed
anyone else to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more anxious that anybody for the FBI to resolve this
because they have, through this leak, cast a horrible cloud over
innocent people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
