<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-     09-27 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-0928 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL'S NETANYAHU, CLEARED OF BRIBERY, READIES FOR EXPECTED
POLITICAL COMEBACK
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein
Wednesday said he would not indict former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on corruption charges. The move raised expectations of a
comeback for the charismatic politician known for his combative
style and hard line on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was in Atlanta Wednesday representing an Israeli
company at a telecommunications convention. His Jerusalem office
said he was to return Thursday, cutting short his trip.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared an end was coming to the ``time out'' from politics
that Netanyahu announced after being trounced in elections in May
of last year. The prospect of a return of ``Bibi,'' as Netanyahu is
known here, sent a sizzle through the political ranks and on
Israeli radio talkshows.
</P>
<P>
   His possible re-entry poses a threat to embattled Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, who may face a call for new elections amid a stalled
peace process and defections of political allies.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, 50, is a right-winger Israelis tend to either love or
love-to-hate, reflecting in part the deep left-wing, right-wing
divide among Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   His three-year-term was marked by hard bargaining with
Palestinians, which often brought him to loggerheads with the
Americans mediating the peace process. It also saw several cycles
of Israeli-Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
   He was almost indicted in 1997 in a case revolving around
political cronyism. His infighting with presumed allies, and also
reportedly with his wife Sara, was constant grist for political
junkies. But, he cast himself as the defender of Israel's
underclass, and protector of Israeli land.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, opinion polls show Netanyahu even with Barak, who won
the election last year by 56 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Netanyahu fairing better than hawkish former Gen.
Ariel Sharon, current leader of Netanyahu's Likud Party. That
standing could be crucial, as Barak opponents vow to call for new
elections soon after the Israeli parliament reconvenes Oct. 29. The
elections could be held early next year.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Israel the possible revival of Netanyahu
opened up the old rifts between those who see the Palestinians as
possible peace partners and those who see them as eternal enemies.
The split was also between those who view Netanyahu as a persecuted
defender of the weak or a just corrupt politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good for Israel. He won't sell out the land,'' said
mini-bus driver Elisha Levy, 47. ``When he is prime minister again
(Palestinian President Yasser) Arafat will feel sick, and that is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned he can go to jail,'' said paint
factory owner David Shullman, 50. ``Netanyahu is a specialist at
getting into trouble and a specialist at getting out of it. In any
other country he would be too embarrassed to try to get back into
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just the ongoing investigation that seemed to keep
Netanyahu's political prospects on hold. That ended Wednesday when
Rubinstein decided not to indict Netanyahu after a yearlong police
probe.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation included allegations of bribery and kickbacks.
It centered on $100,000 in home improvement work Netanyahu received
from a contractor, and official gifts received as prime minister
that police said Sara and Benjamin Netanyahu kept.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein, in a 22-page opinion, said there was insufficient
evidence to win a conviction in court against either Netanyahu or
his wife. But, he said Netanyahu's conduct was ``not a proper way
to run a government.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office issued a statement praising Rubinstein's work
and, with the start of the Jewish New Year Friday night, said ``we
understand Mr. and Mrs. Netanyahu's feeling of relief and wish them
a happy new year.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak ally, Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, instead highlighted
the criticism in Rubinstein's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court will not decide the fate of Netanyahu, the public
will,'' he told Israeli television. ``A person such as this cannot
be the leader of a party in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Likud Party leader Sharon dismissed any worries that Netanyahu
will return with plans to capture the party leadership. He focused
attention on Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Benjamin Netanyahu will now have the time to join us in
our battle against the dangers that the Barak government brings,
and to bring down the government,'' he said, vowing to maintain the
party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.haaretzdaily.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
