<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-CONNER-$ADV01-2TA     09-27 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-CONNER-$ADV01-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNDERMINE' IS BRUCE CONNER'S PET WORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kan., Calif., Minn.)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By AMEI WALLACH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Artists all over the world, in the late 1950s
and early 1960s, began scouring the streets and newsstands of
Tokyo, Duesseldorf, Paris, Moscow, New York and San Francisco for
junk materials or pop motifs. Everything that the stringent rules
of Modernism had pronounced unworthy of artmaking seemed newly
alluring: comic books, trash, a tarnished spoon, a stuffed goat,
words on a page. Artists and critics called this work anti-art,
Fluxus, neo-Dada, Beat, Nouveau Realisme, Gutai. The artists' aim
was to sabotage any accepted definition of art and vandalize its
boundaries. As Robert Rauschenberg once put it, they wanted to work
in the gap between art and life.
</P>
<P>
   For Bruce Conner, though, debunking the meaning of art was never
enough. His fixation for more than four decades has been with
undermining everything you ever thought you knew about who or what
it is to be an artist. Anyone who thinks he knows who Conner is
from his assemblages in the Whitney Museum's ``Beat Culture'' show
in 1995 will be flummoxed by the traveling exhibition ``2000 B.C.:
The Bruce Conner Story, Part II,'' organized by the Walker Art
Center in Minneapolis. It opens at the Los Angeles Museum of
Contemporary Art next Sunday and remains on view through Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Part II is ``Not a Retrospective,'' as the impossible-to-read
medallion embossed on the first page of the catalog informs you,
with Conner's customary barbed tomfoolery. After all, the
exhibition is missing all but one of the more than 300 paintings
Conner has made and all of the photographs. Those might find their
way into a Part I, if there ever is one, or maybe some future Part
VII.
</P>
<P>
   The current Part II is an installation of 174 sculptures,
assemblages, films, collages, prints, drawings and photograms so
disparate that David Bonetti, reviewing the exhibition's San
Francisco stop at the M.H. de Young Museum for The San Francisco
Examiner this summer, likened it to ``a group show.''
</P>
<P>
   This pleases Conner. ``I never wanted to get locked into a style
of work that I would be identified with to the point that I
couldn't do anything else,'' he said one recent morning as we sat
in the dining area of his tiny and tidy house, in front of a window
overlooking rooftops of this city where he arrived from Wichita,
Kan., more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that his films are required viewing in film
schools and his assemblages place him as a pivotal figure in the
San Francisco renaissance of the 1960s. ``I've already been
typecast as a filmmaker and sculptor,'' he complains. ``What I want
to do is change.''
</P>
<P>
   I have been warned about Bruce Conner by curators and critics
who know him. They say he is ``paranoiac,'' ``difficult'' and
``impossible to deal with.'' They regale me with stories of nasty
scenes and aborted retrospectives. Even curators who are unabashed
fans of the work and consider it shamefully underestimated told me
he was apt to throw me out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Conner, it is true, has hardly a charitable word to say about
museum personnel, with the exception of Peter Boswell, the primary
organizer of ``2000 B.C.'' He has even more choleric _ and
sometimes more believable _ stories about curators, critics and
printmakers than they have about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are visual illiterates and they work in museums,''
he says. (At the moment, the museum Conner is in disagreement with
is New York's Museum of Modern Art, over its handling of his
assemblage sculptures ``Child'' and ``The Box.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the man in front of me is as courteous and contained as the
farmer in ``American Gothic,'' whom he resembles in the severity of
his blue eyes, even when he's being funny, and the thinness of his
nose. Conner is 67, but his stamina and hours have been drastically
limited since 1984, when he was discovered to have a liver ailment
that could have killed him within a matter of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of these constraints,'' he says, ``because of what it
takes to cajole, threaten and try to coerce museums and galleries
to present my work in the way I want it to be,'' he declared
himself an Anonymous Artist a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   When he can, between bed rest and the demands of a traveling
exhibition, he makes collages at his 35-by-40-inch drawing table in
the front room that serves as his studio. He doesn't sign them, he
doesn't claim them, which means he doesn't have to photograph,
measure, mat, frame or label them. He sends them to friends. If a
friend calls to thank him for the work, he denies he had anything
to do with it, according to his ``12-step program for Anonymous
Artists.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest act of subterfuge in Conner's ongoing
confrontation with artistic identity. He sees his role as similar
to that of an experimental novelist _ not to expose his soul but to
create and undercut narratives through absurdity and surprise.
Toward this end, like the Soviet-born artist Ilya Kabakov, he has
invented fictional characters to make his work. He created an
artist stuck in the vocabulary of the Surrealist artist Max Ernst
and gave him the name of his movie star friend Dennis Hopper for
the etchings that constituted ``The Dennis Hopper One Man Show'' in
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He has signed prints with thumbprints and imprinted
photosensitive paper with his body in his stunning series of
``Angel'' photograms. But a signature is something else. ``For me
looking at a painting with a big signature on it was like a big
commercial,'' he says. So he signed his work only on the back.
</P>
<P>
   When his New York dealer, Charles Alan, objected, he signed with
the finest pen he could find, in as tiny letters as he could
manage, on the most obscure area of the painting. Then he would
send his dealer a map with which to find the signature. Twice
during the 1960s he put a moratorium on signing altogether. He told
Alan to forge his signature but didn't get any cooperation. Then
Conner sent him a signature stamp, which Alan declined to use and
returned to Conner. So Conner made an assemblage out of the stamp
and presented it to Marcel Duchamp at a lecture, with the request
that Duchamp return it to Alan. Months later, Duchamp's wife took
it to Alan in the middle of a blizzard.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   For Conner, as for other artists of his generation, a great many
ideas descended from Duchamp's readymades of 1915 _ objects easily
found in everyday life, like a shovel or a urinal, which the artist
declared to be art by signing them. Conner was frustrated, however,
in his attempts at persuading Alan to organize a two-person show
with Duchamp. Conner's idea was to paint the walls and sculpture
stands in the same white as they were before he repainted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be my contribution, and I would not sign it,''
Conner tells me. ``So I would make this work that I didn't sign,
and, on the walls and sculpture stands, Marcel Duchamp would show
the work that he did sign but didn't make.''
</P>
<P>
   This antic sensibility, laced with apocalyptic dread, informs
the first and most celebrated of Conner's films, the 12-minute
black-and-white ``A Movie'' of 1958. Born in 1933 in Kansas, Conner
was 12 when Hiroshima was bombed, and draft age when the Korean War
brought the bomb scare and bomb shelters home to a complacent
America.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb is the protagonist of ``A Movie,'' which takes its
inspiration from the Marx Brothers' ``Duck Soup'' and from Conner's
childhood passion for making adult secrets visible. In movies, the
viewer is not supposed to see the flashing numbers leading to the
beginning of the film. But Conner spliced this countdown leader
with girlie footage that a friend had found in Kansas, of a nude
taking off her stockings. To this he added discarded footage from a
camera store of a submarine captain spying through a periscope then
firing away, ostensibly at the nude. Before long an underwater
atomic bomb explodes and waves capsize surfers, sailors, fish, a
battleship. Then ``The End'' flashes intermittently on screen, with
its double meaning of the end of the film and the end of the world.
The bomb dematerializes in light. The words ``Bruce Conner'' flash
large, long and often, the ego of the creator as big as the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Movie'' and the films that followed have been credited with
influencing MTV. ``Not my fault,'' Conner says when asked.
</P>
<P>
   Such political savagery became a mark of the horrific, erotic
assemblages he made out of debris left behind by the poor blacks
displaced by San Francisco's urban renewal. He studded the
assemblages with Salvation Army jewelry and throttled them with
nylon stockings.
</P>
<P>
   The relationships are intimate, if not always apparent, between
the films, the assemblages, the dense black-and-white felt-tip pen
drawings of the late 1960s and the compulsively ordered ink-blot
drawings of the 1990s. The common thread is conflict: between black
and white, light and shadow, flesh and spirit, the object and the
reason for making it. In every medium Conner wants the eye to be in
constant movement and so misled by the next thing it sees that,
when it returns to the first, it sees something altogether
different.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is never to be pinned down. Never to give in
to that dread signature style. It has been worth the struggle. In
his youth, Bruce Conner might not have been the artist Robert
Rauschenberg was, but it has served Conner's long career to keep
things small, vagrant and aberrant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
