<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GOVERNMENT-ECONSCENE-     09-27 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNMENT-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: FEAR OF BIG GOVERNMENT NOT JUSTIFIED BY U.S.
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JEFF MADRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush has finally made government the issue of the
presidential campaign. After wasting months focusing on Al Gore's
character, he returned to what was always the Republicans' meat and
potatoes. As president, Gore would give you big government, Bush
now emphasizes. But if voters elect him instead, Bush says, he
would continue to tame Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is picking up, of course, from the legacy of President
Reagan, who was determined to bench government as long as he could.
Reagan helped make entrepreneurialism and profits respectable
again, which was no small achievement. And some deflation of
government was no doubt deserved. In the 1960s and '70s, advocates
of progressive actions underestimated how difficult such tasks as
reducing poverty and revitalizing the inner cities really were, and
did not take sufficient care to develop new policies that would be
effective. Americans also overestimated the nation's potential
affluence. Remember guns and butter?
</P>
<P>
   But the oversimplified fear of big government has been damaging
and does not accurately reflect American history. On the crucial
role of government in the nation's economic success, our past is
unambiguous. Beginning with Jefferson's presidency, the federal
government may have resisted building a national system of roads,
but by the 1820s the states picked up the ball. Led by New York,
the states invested millions of dollars, which was big money then,
in new canals, and New York even made loans to business. Where
would the early economy have been without these canals?
</P>
<P>
   In those same years, federal laws were passed to protect the
rights to the ownership of property for millions of Americans,
including squatters, even though it violated the sanctity of the
contracts the nation's rich landowners held. To Hernando de Soto, a
Peruvian development specialist and author of ``The Mystery of
Capital'' (Basic Books), America's far-seeing protection of
property rights was a key to economic success.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Civil War, there was a pitched battle over whether
primary education should remain private, but public education
thankfully prevailed, and America became the best-educated nation
in the world. Now, economists believe educational attainment is the
foremost economic resource of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1800s, the federal government aggressively
subsidized the building of the railroads. After a couple of decades
of a simplistic Social Darwinian ideology of ``survival of the
fittest'' at the end of the 19th century, the progressives
established regulations that made competition fairer and protected
workers from abusive hours and labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, local governments built much-needed high
schools. In the 1930s, Social Security and unemployment insurance
were introduced over the vehement objections of conservatives. And
after World War II, the federal government was responsible for the
highway system, the GI Bill of Rights, the Pentagon-sponsored
research that resulted in the Internet, and civil rights
legislation that helped bring African-Americans into the economic
fold.
</P>
<P>
   The record is plain: government has done many things awfully
well. And beyond the historical evidence, there is also strong
statistical support for the idea that government investment has
produced substantial returns. Professor Ishaq Nadiri, an economist
at New York University, has developed with colleagues a provocative
model of public investment that is widely accepted. Their research
shows that the return on federal transportation investment, for
example, has been every bit as strong as the returns on private
investment in recent years (and even stronger in the past) because
such investment benefits society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Economic theory is consistent with Nadiri's findings. Private
investors will systematically underinvest in areas in which such
social returns exceed private returns because the individual
companies themselves will not enjoy all the benefits. Good theory,
then, tells us that investments in public goods, from roads, sewers
and airports to research and education, cannot be completely
entrusted to private markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Reagan era began, America has largely neglected many
of these areas. Of course, government will make mistakes (so does
business). But consider that federal investment in transportation,
research and development and education and training has fallen to
only 1.7 percent of GDP, 30 percent lower than it was in 1970. At
former levels, it would have been roughly an additional $100
billion of spending a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new economy is also creating new needs that are going unmet.
Paying down the nation's debt is apparently our priority, but
two-worker families desperately need quality day care. The
information age requires even better education, but according to
Richard Rothstein and Karen Hawley Miles, schools have increased
spending per pupil since the late 1960s at a rate only 1 percent a
year above inflation, behind the previous pace and not enough to
keep up with spending elsewhere in the economy. What does the low
level of teachers' salaries say about our society? Nancy Folbre, an
economist at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, argues
that such caring professions, including nursing and caring for the
elderly, are themselves public goods that require serious
government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   And, although deregulation and privatization have been useful,
regulatory vigilance cannot simply be relaxed across the board as
the economy changes. What are we to make of deregulation in a time
when tire companies neglect safety standards, and the number of
product recalls continues to set records? Despite the dangerous
collapse of the hedge fund Long-Term Investment Capital two years
ago, no new requirements for public disclosure of financial
information are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Both business and government have vital roles in the economy,
and always have. But for many people, government has become an
us-vs.-them issue. For the sake of the nation's economy, the next
president should realize that the government is us. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
