<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3932 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-$ADV01-C     09-27 2282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAPSTER, MP3 LAWSUITS CAN'T STOP A MUSIC INDUSTRY REVOLUTION
 &HT;    With ONLINE-CHANGE and ONLINE-TIMELINE. Moving in (f) financial
and (e) entertainment categories for release Sunday, Oct. 1.
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When Napster Inc. goes back to court this week,
singer-guitarist Nial McGaughey won't be among the many musicians
cheering for the judges to put the online music site out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey and his heavy-metal band, 3D House of Beef, estimate
they reach thousands of listeners each day through Napster and
similar Internet sites, people they wouldn't be able to reach any
other way.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Oakland, Calif., band doesn't make any money letting
online listeners swap songs such as ``White Hog Slaughter'' and
``Heard You Were Dead'' for free, but the exposure certainly
results in some CD sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``When music gets played on the radio, isn't (that) giving it
away?'' McGaughey, 31, wrote in an e-mail interview. ``What about
when it gets played at clubs?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course that's not what other, more established musicians and
the major record labels behind them say. Backed by the powerful
Recording Industry Artists Association (RIAA) and musicians such as
Metallica and rapper Dr. Dre, major record labels have sued Napster
and competitor MP3.com Inc., claiming the companies' infringement
of music copyrights cost them billions in lost profits.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San
Francisco is scheduled to hear Napster's appeal of an injunction
that would put it out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome of this case and similar lawsuits, the
business of making, distributing and buying music is going to be
different in many ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ It's changing for musicians. Little-known bands like
McGaughey's can distribute their music over the Internet _ with or
without Napster and MP3.com _ on their own, bypassing record
companies that have traditionally been the mainstay of the music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Better-known musicians have to operate in the knowledge that any
fan with a computer and Internet access no longer has to pay to
hear their music. Some are taking the offensive. To thwart piracy,
the Canadian band Barenaked Ladies recently flooded the Internet
with fake songs that contained little more than marketing pitches
for its newest album.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's changing for the record companies. Not long ago, artists
who wanted to make it big had to sign with a major label, and
listeners had to buy it from the label. Now recording companies,
their grip on artists loosening, are scrambling to implement their
own Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's changing for listeners. Last year, ``MP3,'' the format
used to compress and move music files on line, replaced ``sex'' as
the most searched-for term on the Internet. Even if Napster and
MP3.com disappear, other software programs _ Gnutella and Rapster
are two of the most popular _ will let people go on exchanging
music easily.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't downloaded any music yet, you probably will when
faster Internet connections make it much easier. And even if you
can't imagine listening to listen to music on your computer instead
of your stereo, you may have already heard some music over the
Internet. Some retailers and radio stations use downloaded music in
their stores and on their late-night broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's changing for the Internet companies. Once a small band of
self-professed renegades, online music companies are getting
legitimate or changing the way they do business.
</P>
<P>
   When Walmart.com launches a downloadable music service early
next year, it will do so with licensing agreements in hand from
major record labels. Even MP3.Com, which once slammed the major
labels as irrelevant, now has licensing deals with four of them.
Like other online music companies, MP3.com also is pushing into new
markets, such as selling monthly subscriptions to non-stop music
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there's a lot of controversy, but the controversy is
about different legal issues, it's not about the opportunities,''
MP3.com Chairman Michael Roberston said in a recent interview.
``The bottom line is that delivering music digitally is so
efficient that it's going to revolutionize everything.''
</P>
<P>
   History replays itself
</P>
<P>
   Of course, technology has been revolutionizing the music
industry almost since the first recording. And usually, there has
been plenty of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1930s, in radio's heyday, many record companies
refused to allow stations to broadcast their music. That's why some
radio networks started their own shows and did live broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Record companies ``were afraid people wouldn't buy records any
more if they could hear the music for free,'' explained Emory
University sociology professor Tim Dowd, echoing the complaints of
modern-day recording executives about Napster and MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Recording companies continued to be stingy with their music up
until 1942, when Capitol Records broke from the pack and declared
that radio play actually helped its sales, Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   Later home recording drew the ire of the big labels _ first
cassettes, then digital audio tapes, and now CD ``burners.'' The
industry says it loses $1.5 billion or more a year to home taping.
</P>
<P>
   At least when it came to cassettes, the record labels were
right. ``The record companies went into a big slump'' in late
1970s, Dowd said. ``One of the things that pulled them out was the
CD, which gave them a new form of recording that cassettes couldn't
rival.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with MP3 is that the masses, with the help of the
Internet, learned how to use it before the recording companies did.
</P>
<P>
   The technology actually has its roots not in music, but in
television. In 1992, a contract research group in Germany that was
searching for ways improve the sound of high-definition television
broadcasts discovered how to compress audio files. The technology
became a standard of the Moving Picture Experts Group known as MPEG
1 Layer 3, or later, MP3.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Robertson, a former computer advice columnist who
had started several other companies with little success, founded
MP3.com Inc. here in March 1998, computer and music enthusiasts
around the world were already swapping MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford University, in a harbinger of what was to come, a
student put more than 100 songs on a Web server and an estimated
2,000 people a day logged on to download free tunes, clogging the
university's Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's company was the first to make a sizeable business
out of housing and downloading songs. But even though MP3.com had
thousands of songs available on line (today it claims more than
600,000), big record labels paid little public attention to the
company, largely because most of the artists were little-known
bands.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, MP3 technology got the recording industry's
attention in a big way. Diamond Multimedia Inc. introduced a
portable MP3 player that could play downloaded music like a
Walkman. The RIAA filed suit seeking to keep Diamond from releasing
its Rio player, but it failed. Rio's popularity soared.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months later, the RIAA would try again to stop the
spread of MP3 music. This time, they focused on a 19-year-old
Northeastern University dropout named Shawn Fanning.
</P>
<P>
   Buying time
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, Fanning moved to the heart of technology,
Silicon Valley, to commercialize a revolutionary new file exchange
software program he wrote to help him and his friends exchange MP3
files. The nappy-haired teen reportedly used one of his own
nicknames in calling his company Napster Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is a file-sharing site that lets users find and download
music that's stored on other users' computer hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   It dramatically widened the sources for music files beyond those
on the MP3.com site. MP3.com says visitors to its site are simply
accessing music from CDs they already own, but record companies
claim the music files are illegal copies that MP3.com made and
stored on its servers, and that many of its users are otherwise
sharing music that they don't own.
</P>
<P>
   Napster became an overnight sensation. With it, anybody with
Internet access and a CD-ROM drive can exchange digitized music,
whether it's copyrighted or not. The file trading software became
so popular at colleges and universities that it clogged Internet
systems and shut down servers. Fanning became something of a pop
idol, even getting a spot on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Record companies got angry.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, the RIAA and 17 major labels filed suit
against Napster, claiming its 20 million users cost them more than
$700 million in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the recording industry's five biggest labels also
sued MP3.com. All but one of those has settled, but damages from
the still-pending suit by Universal Music Group could cost MP3.com
$118 million or more. A judge is scheduled to decide final damages
in the MP3.com case next month.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the record labels claimed the companies violated
copyrights held by them and their artists.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason why the record companies filed suit,
according to some critics. They simply wanted to buy some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about trying to slow it down,'' said Heath Terry, who
follows Internet trends for the Credit Suisse First Boston
investment banking firm, which was the lead underwriter in
MP3.com's July 1999 initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recording industry right now is terrified,'' he said.
``They just want everybody to stop and give them time to figure it
out, and they're going to throw up whatever roadblock they can to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes, fast and slow
</P>
<P>
   So far, the roadblocks seem to be working, and the record
companies have used their time wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Since filing their suits against Napster and MP3.com, nearly
every major record label has started a major Internet initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Sony Music Entertainment and Universal Music Group
announced they would develop an online subscription-based music
service. In July, EMI Group started offering 100 digital albums for
sale through online retailers. In September, Warner Music Group
announced plans to put more than 1,000 albums for sale on the
Internet beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Napster and MP3.com, where thousands of tunes can
be downloaded daily (and for free), the music industry's offerings
are paltry. And industry executives admit they have been slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated process,'' said RIAA spokesman Doug Curry.
``It's much easier for someone to upload thousands of CDs and put
them online for free as opposed to changing 60 years of a large
industry's practices overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some musicians and Internet companies are changing virtually
overnight, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rock bands Primitive Radio Gods and Arrested Development
recently agreed to pre-release songs from upcoming CDs on Napster
to generate interest in the new discs. Popular California punk band
Offspring last month announced it would post its entire new CD on
the Internet, but later reneged under pressure from their recording
label, Sony.
</P>
<P>
   Other artists may soon start using the recording labels'
newfound vulnerability as leverage when negotiating contracts or
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will in fact kind of create a free agency for the artist if
the Internet becomes a safer place for the artist to be,'' said
talent agent Ron Stone, who represents musicians including Bonnie
Raitt, Ziggy Marley and Tracy Chapman. ``There are going to be some
artists ... who will use the Internet to create new relationships
with record companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the organizers of a group called Artists Against
Piracy, Stone detests Napster and other online companies that don't
pay royalties to musicians. But he, and many of the musicians he
represents, aren't opposed to digital distribution of music _ as
long as they get paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not opposed to Napster technology, we're opposed to the
Napster business model,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Some online music companies are, in fact, changing their
business models.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com recently launched subscription channels that let
subscribers listen to nonstop classical or children's tunes, much
like digital cable music channels, for a monthly fee. Its new
retail business already has about 100 stores and restaurants as
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to pay, we'll write the check and we'll move on,''
MP3.com's Robertson said, referring to the possibility of costly
damages in its lawsuit. ``Technology marches forward. And as we're
a technology company, we must seize the opportunities as they come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   None of what the companies are doing really matters to music
fans like 21-year-old Juan Pieterse, a third-year college student
in South Africa. Pieterse claims he hasn't bought a CD in two
years, but he has downloaded countless tunes over the Internet
using Napster and other services.
</P>
<P>
   If Napster gets shut down this week, he'll likely just go to
another file-sharing system, such as Gnutella, to get free copies
of songs from favorite bands like Metallica, REM and Offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, one does not need to be a rocket scientist to
download or upload illegal copies of songs,'' Pieterse wrote in an
e-mail interview.
</P>
<P>
   Pieterse is the kind of music listener that the major record
labels fear most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people who will purchase CDs in the future,'' he
wrote, ``are people who don't have portable MP3 players or PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe's e-mail address is bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
