<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ONLINE-TIMELINE-$ADV0     09-27 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TIMELINE-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With ONLINE-MUSIC. Moving in (f) financial and (e) entertainment
categories for release Sunday, Oct. 1.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW THE ONLINE MUSIC CONTROVERSY MUSHROOMED
</P>
<P>
   1992
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the Fraunhofer Institute, a contract research group,
creates a new technology for compressing sound files. Originally
developed for high-definition television transmissions, the
technology would become a standard of the Moving Pictures Experts
Group. It would later become known as MPEG 1 Layer 3, or MP3. That
same year, U.S. lawmakers pass the Digital Audio Home Recording
Act, which would later become the center of controversy over
copyrighted music and video.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   Still little known outside the realm of techies, MP3 starts to
create controversy. In California, a computer science student puts
more than 100 songs on a Web server connected to Stanford
University's computer system. An estimated 2,000 people a day visit
the site, substantially slowing the school's Internet connection.
Recording industry executives start to express concern over the
format and its uses, but say they don't see it as competition.
</P>
<P>
   March 1998
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robertson, a San Diego consultant who once wrote a local
computer magazine column called Mr. Mac, starts MP3.com Inc.,
capitalizing on the growing interest in MP3 music files.
</P>
<P>
   October 1998
</P>
<P>
   As Diamond Multimedia Inc. prepares to release its Rio portable
MP3 player, the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)
files suit to try to stop it. The suit fails, and the Rio soars in
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   July 1999
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com Inc. goes public at $28 per share. It reaches $105
before ending the first day's trading at $63.31. (Currently, it
trades at less than $4 a share.)
</P>
<P>
   August 1999
</P>
<P>
   College student Shawn Fanning drops out of Northeastern
University in Massachusetts and moves to Silicon Valley to try and
make a business out of a revolutionary new file-exchange software
program he wrote. He calls the company Napster Inc.
</P>
<P>
   December 1999
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen record companies and the Recording Industry Artists
Association sue Napster, claiming that the company and its 20
million users have violated music copyrights, costing the companies
more than $700 million in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 21, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Five major record labels file suit against MP3.com in New York,
claiming the company infringed on their copyrights with its
MyMP3.com service, which lets users post their CDs in online
``music lockers.''
</P>
<P>
   April 28
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in New York rules that MP3.com has violated
music companies' copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   May 1
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment and Universal Music Group announce a
joint venture to develop a subscription-based downloadable music
program, the biggest move yet by record labels to get into the
online game.
</P>
<P>
   May 3
</P>
<P>
   The copyright fight turns personal. Metallica drummer Lars
Ulrich helps deliver to Napster the screen names of 335,000 users
he claims is stealing the band's music. Napster later blocks access
of the users.
</P>
<P>
   May 5
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com announces it has reached a licensing agreement with BMI,
one of the five labels that had sued. Under the agreement, MP3.com
will pay royalties to the label for songs that are downloaded from
its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   May 23
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by litigation, venture capitalists pump $15 million
into Napster. Hank Berry, a partner in the lead VC firm, Hummer
Winblad Venture Partners, becomes acting CEO.
</P>
<P>
   May 30
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com launches a retail music division to sell music to
stores, restaurants and other retailers over the Internet. The move
is one of several by MP3.com to diversify.
</P>
<P>
   June 9
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com reaches licensing agreements with two other record
labels that had sued, Warner Music Group and BMG Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   July 11
</P>
<P>
   Congress holds hearings on digital music. Chief executives of
Napster and MP3.com testify, as do recording industry executives
and musicians such as Ulrich and Byrds co-founder Roger McGuinn.
The Senate Judiciary Committee later opts not to take any
substantial action.
</P>
<P>
   July 26
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in San Francisco approves the RIAA's request for
an injunction and orders Napster to shut down in two days. The
company's site is flooded with users seeking to download thousands
of free songs before its scheduled closing.
</P>
<P>
   July 28
</P>
<P>
   Napster surprisingly is granted a temporary reprieve from the
injunction. In New York, MP3.com reaches a licensing agreement with
EMI. The settlement leaves Universal Music Group as the lone
holdout among record labels that had sued in January.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 1
</P>
<P>
   Universal Music Group begins testing ``bluematter,'' a program
it hopes will supply digital music, video and photograph technology
to paying Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6
</P>
<P>
   A New York judge finds that MP3.com ``willfully'' violated
Universal's copyrights, setting the stage for what could be $118
million or more in damages. MP3 says it will appeal and also steps
up settlement talks with Universal. The judge is expected to decide
the final amount of damages in November.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11
</P>
<P>
   Research firm Media Metrix Inc. says Napster is the Internet's
fastest-growing software application. Also, Warner Music Group
announces plans to team up with Internet company RealNetworks Inc.
to put more than 1,000 of its artists' albums and singles on the
Internet beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 2
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel in San Francisco is scheduled to begin
hearing Napster's appeal of the injunction and decide whether the
company can stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
