<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Sept. 27. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The night supervisor for
The New York Times News Service is Ned Kilkelly; phone:
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927; e-mail: kilkelly(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A vast crowd of at least
200,000 converged on central Belgrade Wednesday for a rally to show
support for opposition candidate Vojislav Kostunica. (Summary from
wires.) By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ After deliberating for six
months, Israel's attorney general has found insufficient evidence
to prosecute former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on corruption
charges, clearing the way for a possible political comeback by the
charismatic rightist leader. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-PARENTS (Westland, Mich.) _ As they shopped for
milk at Kroger's, ate ice cream at the Westland Mall or sat in the
bleachers at the Westland Sports Arena, most of the parents
interviewed here agreed that it was their responsibility _ and not
that of the president, Congress or even Hollywood _ to filter what
reaches their children. The candidates, they suggested, should save
their breath for the economy and health care. Yet all of the
parents conceded that they regularly crossed or blurred the borders
between acceptable and unacceptable content. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   PARTIES-SOFTMONEY (Undated) _ The national Republican and
Democratic party organizations are outspending both special
interest groups and the Bush and Gore campaigns on television in
the presidential election, a trend that political analysts say is
transforming the parties this year from supporting players into the
chief advertising agents for the candidates. In fact, this this
year, if the trend continues, the advertising campaigns will have
been financed largely by the unregulated soft money donated to the
parties by corporations and wealthy individuals. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEW-TEACHER (New York) _ In July, Donna Moffett abandoned her
comfortable longtime job as a legal secretary near Wall Street to
be one of 320 ``teaching fellows'' _ people with little or no
teaching experience, hired by Schools Chancellor Harold Levy to
fill chronic vacancies in the system's most troubled schools. In
her first weeks of school, Moffett is learning that teaching is
only part of her job description _ for now, an achingly small part.
Already she is grappling with tardiness and discipline problems,
often spending far more time on ``classroom management,'' as
veteran teachers call it, than lessons. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PIPELINE (Inuvik, Northwest Territories) _ For three
decades, geologists probing beneath the Arctic Ocean near here and
offshore Alaska have mapped the largest known untapped reserves of
natural gas in North America _ 165 trillion cubic feet, seven times
as much as the United States will consume this year. But, with gas
prices low, indigenous opposition high and environmental issues
looming, energy companies never sought to build pipelines to send
the gas south to heat homes and to generate electricity. This is
changing as fast as it takes to read a home heating bill. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLING (Sydney, Australia) _ In perhaps the greatest
Olympic wrestling upset ever, Rulon Gardner of the United States, a
first-time Olympian, beat Russia's heavyweight, Alexander Karelin,
ending the Russian's string of three straight gold medals. By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT-OLY 2,3,4,5,7.
</P>
