<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3938 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-CASESALES0928-CO     09-27 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CASESALES0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola hints at better things
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Coca-Cola appears to be delivering on some Wall Street
expectations that business will improve globally later this year,
although growth at home remains a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest soft drink company said Wednesday that case
volume, a key indicator of the amount of product moved to retailers
and other customers, is expected to rise about 4 percent in the
third quarter. That compares with 7 percent in the second quarter
and 3.5 percent during the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results this time around are in line with Wall Street
estimates, and that was reflected in another gain for Coke's stock.
The company's shares, which are up 10 percent over the past five
trading days, closed Wednesday at $55.63, up 69 cents.
</P>
<P>
   But in North America, which accounts for 38 percent of the
company's operating revenue, there was practically no growth in
case sales. By comparison, volume was up 1 percent in the second
quarter and 2 percent in the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The region, which includes the United States and Canada, has
suffered fallout from a series of price increases that retailers
and consumers have found hard to swallow. The company also faces
the challenge of lackluster growth in its core cola brands as
consumers embrace more noncarbonated alternatives such as juices,
teas, sports drinks and water.
</P>
<P>
   But President and Chief Operating Officer Jack Stahl indicated
Wednesday that North America's overall case sales results belie the
fact that performance is improving in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite volume softness earlier in the quarter, the company's
North American business has improved in the latter part of the
quarter based on our marketing activities,'' Stahl said. Analyst
Bill Pecoriello of Sanford C. Bernstein also said U.S. beverage
volume growth improved in September, for both Coca-Cola and rival
Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's 26 directors worldwide are rewarded for innovative
marketing campaigns that connect with local consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Beverage Digest analyst John Sicher said the industry should
expect ``a lot more activity'' from Coke in product innovation,
advertising and marketing, which should help its performance in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would anticipate North American volume beginning to show
signs of improvement in the fourth quarter and into next year,''
Sicher said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But on CNBC, beverage analyst Caroline Levy of UBS Warburg said
she remains ``cautious'' about the company because of its North
America performance.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the world, case sales rose and estimated 7 to
8 percent in its Asia Pacific region; 3 to 4 percent in the Africa
and Middle East group; and 4 to 5 percent in both the Latin America
and Europe/Eurasia groups.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch acknowledged that the weak euro
``obviously has put some pressure'' on business in the company's
second-largest market. But he added that stronger currencies
elsewhere have helped offset any negative currency impact in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Coca-Cola said it expects global case sales to grow 5
percent for this year _ although it had earlier projected 5 to 6
percent growth _ and 6 to 7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company will report third-quarter earnings in mid-October.
Wall Street expects Coca-Cola to report per-share results of 41
cents, compared with 32 cents in the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
