r p BC-BAXTER0928-COX     09-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate could be pivotal to vice-presidential candidates -
big-time
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sense, both major-party candidates for vice president are
hedging their bets this year.
</P>
<P>
   After the special circumstances of his retirement package from
Halliburton Co. became an embarrassment to the campaign, Republican
Dick Cheney announced this month he will forgo stock options,
recently worth $3.6 million, whose value could be affected by the
next administration. He will also sell and transfer into a blind
trust the remainder of the stocks and options in the package,
recently worth $13.6 million - if he's elected.
</P>
<P>
   His action was a response to potential charges of direct
conflict of interest, but Cheney will still benefit from the
Halliburton board's decision to waive its right to penalize him for
retiring early, and the former oil industry executive will be well
set, no matter what happens in November.
</P>
<P>
   Along similar lines, Sen. Joe Lieberman is having difficulty
severing ties to his old job. In fact, unlike Cheney, he hasn't
retired from it.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman remains on the ballot as a U.S. Senate candidate in
Connecticut, and a swing through his home state last weekend was
officially designated a Senate campaign trip. With the majority in
the Senate now thought to be in play, Lieberman's Democratic
colleagues are becoming increasingly vocal about their desire for
him to step aside for another Democrat, so the state's Republican
Gov. John Rowland doesn't get the chance to appoint Lieberman's
successor if he's elected vice president. Lieberman has said folks
back home are telling him they want a special election next year,
but Rowland has already nixed that idea.
</P>
<P>
   There's a debate on the calendar in the Connecticut race, two
weeks after Lieberman's Oct. 5 debate with Cheney in Danville, Ky.
If Lieberman opts to skip it -- and if he has not by then stepped
out of the race -- his long-shot Republican opponent, Waterbury
Mayor Philip Giordano, will have the right to say Lieberman isn't
giving Connecticut voters a fair chance to compare them.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Lieberman is more focused at the moment on his forum
next week. Vice-presidential debates, though they never been
decisive, have produced some of the more memorable lines of recent
elections. There was Bob Dole's condemnation of ``Democrat wars''
in 1976, Lloyd Bentsen's dismissive ``Senator, you're no Jack
Kennedy,'' in 1988, Adm. James Stockdale's plaintive ``Why am I
here?'' at the 1992 debate in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Coming two days after the first presidential debate, in a race
that is a dead heat, the Cheney-Lieberman debate potentially could
matter more than previous vice-presidential face-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who followed Dan Quayle knows the loneliness of the
less-favored running mate, even on a ticket that is doing well.
Cheney arrived on an airport tarmac in Detroit this week to find no
reporters had shown up for his stop, which bespeaks how literally
he is in that position.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman has been held up as a brilliant selection,
Cheney has repeatedly struggled. Even his innocuous response to
George W. Bush's on-mike comment about a reporter, ``Oh yeah...big
time,'' may have done more subliminal damage than Bush's off-color
remark. It typed Cheney as a yes-man, compared to Lieberman's
reputation for independence.
</P>
<P>
   That gives the Republicans the potential advantage of a double
set of reduced expectations going into next week's debates: Bush
isn't expected to be as knowledgeable as Al Gore, and Cheney isn't
expected to be as obviously an asset to his ticket as Lieberman.
Bush will get two more chances with Gore, but for Cheney, next week
is the contest. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
