r s BC-OLY-TRACK-SIDE1-COX     09-27 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-SIDE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Third time not a charm as injured Devers pulls up lame in
100-meter hurdles
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - If you thought she'd break down in tears, forget about
it. Not in public with the cameras running, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   No, Gail Devers was as stoic as palace guard after she was
denied for a third time an Olympic medal, let alone gold, in the
100-meter hurdles. Devers, an overwhelming favorite, pulled up
coming off the fourth hurdle in the semifinals Wednesday and
crashed violently through the fifth barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old was brought to a halt by a torn left hamstring,
just the latest in an injury-plagued career. Devers went to the
start line nursing hamstring and sciatic nerve injuries sustained
during an Aug. 25 meet in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking me, `Is my dream over? You're 34,''' said
Devers, who relocated to Atlanta after the 1996 Olympics. ``It
doesn't mean that. It's just one day, one race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each hurdle I went through I felt it more, end of story. End
of Olympics this year for Gail Devers. You guys want me to give you
some kind of big sob story or drama. There isn't any.''
</P>
<P>
   What her injury did do, though, is further weaken an already
shaky 400-meter relay squad, which earlier saw Inger Miller
withdraw from the 100 and 200 with a tender hamstring. It's
significant because of Marion Jones' quest for five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   In Devers' absence from the hurdles' final, Olga Shishigina won
the gold and Glory Alozie of Nigeria, whose boyfriend was struck
and killed by a car while on a training run three weeks ago, took
home the silver
</P>
<P>
   That's real life. What happened to her on the track pales by
comparison, Devers said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is just the latest in a string of adversities that have
shadowed her career, starting with a well-documented bout with
Graves' disease. At the 1992 Barcelona Games, she was en route to
gold when she stumbled over the final hurdle. A horrific start cost
her a medal in Atlanta, where she was nosed out for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Devers has two Olympic gold medals in the 100-meter sprint, but
she's without a medal in her signature event, the hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   After her latest disappointment, Devers walked matter-of-factly
off the track. No pained grimace on her face. No words of anger or
doom.
</P>
<P>
   Snake-bitten? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luck had nothing to do with it,'' Devers said. ``It's fate.
It's simply somebody else's turn to shine. That's why I'm not
sitting up here crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end. I know if I weather the storm the sun is
going to shine again.''
</P>
<P>
   An MRI detected the muscle tear after the meet in Brussels, and
Devers said a subsequent MRI revealed the tear had worsened after
she ran two rounds of the hurdles Monday. She felt the pain coming
out of the blocks in the semis and it became more severe with each
passing hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could make it through this,'' she said. ``I
thought I was tougher than tough. That I could make the final and
run till my leg fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Couch, another local hurdler, went out in the other
semifinal race after finishing sixth. Couch has been bothered by an
abdominal strain and spent more time receiving treatment than
training since the Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Couch didn't react well to the starter's gun, and spent the race
playing catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I panicked over the first hurdle and stood up,'' said Couch, a
Stone Mountain resident. ``Instead of getting out and pushing and
pushing, I was trying to catch people. You can't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my injury, we didn't train and I took a gamble. I
took a good gamble, but it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
