<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-27 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOILA, AND MORE: BLACK READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the epiphanies that have smitten book publishing lately,
the most interesting is not the future of the e-book or
print-on-demand or online publishing. Rather it is that there is a
large and growing citizenry of black people who buy books and are
greedy for reading material relevant to them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's column was about a small, new publishing house that
next month will start selling a series of short, provocative pulp
fiction paperbacks, violent and sexual, aimed at black urban
youths, the literary equivalent of hip-hop videos. A captivating
and roguish idea. But something far more extraordinary is happening
in book publishing. Suddenly there are five imprints in major book
publishing companies committed to publishing new lines of fiction
(not romances) and nonfiction by black writers on black subjects,
and three of them have started up this year. Of course, this is
about money, not the sudden awakening of social consciousness in a
business in which African-Americans as editors and writers haven't
counted, with only the occasional exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite that touch of realism, Anita Diggs, the
African-American director of One World Books, a Random House Inc.
imprint, said, ``It's extraordinary, it's great, it's wonderful and
it's book publishing history.'' One World was founded in 1992 to
publish books by and about African-Americans, Hispanics and Asians,
though most of its books are about blacks. ``There's a lot of money
in this area,'' Diggs said. ``We can't write them and publish them
fast enough. Blacks are buying fiction at a rate we just can't keep
up with. What we need now is more black sales reps, more blacks in
marketing.'' One World publishes hardcover and trade and mass
market paperbacks. It produces about 10 books a year but expects to
go to 15 to 20 by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   I would posit that the idea that African-Americans, other than
perhaps those who were college professors, would buy books in great
numbers penetrated the thinking of book publishers only relatively
recently. The voila came in 1992 with the publication of ``Waiting
to Exhale'' (Viking), Terry McMillan's irreverent, rollicking novel
about the friendship of four black women in Phoenix. The book
became a huge best seller in hardcover and paperback, with more
than three million copies sold worldwide, and then was a hit movie.
</P>
<P>
   Karen R. Thomas, executive editor of the new Dafina Books
imprint at the Kensington Publishing Corp., said, ``I think there
was a lot of suspicion that `Waiting to Exhale' was a fluke, maybe
it was one book people wanted to read, but it was so successful
that publishers began to realize that it wasn't a fluke; that there
was a craving out there by blacks for quality books that speak to
them.'' Dafina will publish books in all formats and most genres,
although not romance. Its first two books, in trade paperback, came
out this month. They are ``Souls of My Sisters: Black Women Break
Their Silence, Tell Their Stories and Heal Their Spirits,'' written
and edited by Dawn Marie Daniels and Candace Sandy, and a novel,
``Lookin' For Luv'' by Carol Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five imprints, only Amistad Press was started before
McMillan's novel. Its founder and publisher, Charles Harris,
created a publishing program that included books by Arthur Ashe,
the late tennis star who invested in the company, and Susan Taylor,
the editor of Essence magazine. Harris also started the Amistad
Literary Series, which did literary studies of Langston Hughes,
Richard Wright, Alice Walker and Toni Morrison, among others,
edited by Henry Louis Gates Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Last year HarperCollins acquired Amistad, and Harris remained as
the imprint's editorial director. ``Book publishers lagged behind
the rest of the entertainment industry in its interest in black
Americans,'' Harris said. ``I think there's now a realization that
to a great extent African-Americans are purchasing books, and are
important consumers for publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there a real increase in the purchasing or simply a new
awareness that African-Americans buy books in greater numbers than
was supposed? Although it's inferential, it's probably a real
increase. If so, why? One reason is that even before the new
imprints, in recent years there have been more books written and
published for black Americans. Furthermore, Opra Winfrey's book
club has noticeably increased the sales of books not only by and to
whites, but by and to blacks also. Moreover, there is an ever
growing black middle class, and it's the middle class that supports
the book industry.
</P>
<P>
   Random House Inc. has three of the black imprints. Besides One
World Books, it has two new black imprints:, Strivers Row, headed
by Melody Guy, which will publish its first three novels in
January, and Harlem Moon, headed by Janet Hill, which will continue
to acquire and edit hardcover African-American books for Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   Harlem Moon will specialize in black fiction and nonfiction
trade paper originals, with the first ones scheduled for next fall.
``I also want to do a line of classics, with introductions, to get
that work to larger audiences,'' Hill said. This year, too, Denise
Stinson, a black literary agent, founded an imprint with Warner
Books called Walk Worthy Press, which will specialize in hardcover
Christian commercial fiction and nonfiction, starting with three
novels to be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   Now if all this sounds promising, there are, within publishing,
African-Americans who point out that many black authors in recent
years started out in self-publishing and had to hawk their own
novels not only in black bookstores but also in beauty parlors and
other places where books are not usually sold. The fear is that
because so many of the books that will be published by these five
imprints will be paperbacks, the publishers are getting a good buy
at bargain prices. That is because paperbacks traditionally mean
smaller author advances and smaller marketing and advertising
budgets and smaller book tours, if any. In essence, the critics say
that the authors will be doing much of the same heavy hauling they
did when they were self-published. One African-American in
publishing said, ``This is boot camp for black writers.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside, of course, is the commitment of major mainstream
publishers to black writers and to African-Americans who want to
read books that connect to their lives. ``Black is beautiful'' was
a slogan in full glory in the 1960s. It's taken book publishers
about 40 years to catch on. Well, at least they've gotten as far as
``Black is pretty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YOUNG-PLAYWRIGHTS-NYT     09-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-PLAYWRIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE TOLD BY AN INGENUE: THEATER SHOWCASE RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An Eisenhower-era mother with a penchant for eating
cat food. Her daughter, who is so obsessed with getting a puppy
that she simply barks as an introduction. And the mysterious Dr.
Phallus, an erudite quipster whose sole mission in life is to
educate the hero about his true sexual desires (as if the Judy
Garland poster was not signal enough).
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the dramatic inventions on display during this
month's Young Playwrights Festival, which has returned after a
three-year hiatus to stage the work of a clutch of precocious
playwrights.
</P>
<P>
   This year's slate, which runs through Saturday at the Cherry
Lane Alternative Theater, at 38 Commerce St. in Greenwich Village,
includes four one-acts in a range of genres, from Caroline Noble
Whitbeck's absurdist comedy ``Woof,'' to Gemma Cooper-Novack's
story of young love, and death, ``I'm Coming In Soon.'' Also
represented are a coming-of-age tale (Adam Feldman's ``A Mind of
Its Own'') and Sherry Ou-yang's sweetly surreal family comedy
``Fish-Eye View.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival was founded in 1981 by Stephen Sondheim as a means
of developing new voices for the theater. In its first 15 years it
produced the early works of writers like Kenneth Lonergan (``The
Rennings Children''), Jonathan Marc Sherman (``Women &AMP; Wallace''),
and Rebecca Gilman (``Always Open'').
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997 the festival ran into financial trouble and was
forced to cancel that year's series of productions planned for the
Joseph Papp Public Theater. Now, after three years of fund-raising
and with the help of supporting grants from Universal Pictures and
the Douglas Cramer Foundation, the festival has returned, with a
slimmed-down budget and at a new location.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winners were culled from submissions received during
the festival's lengthy hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd forgotten I'd submitted it,'' said Whitbeck, a 21-year-old
Harvard senior, who submitted ``Woof'' when she was 18. ``I'd
assumed I'd never hear from them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the chosen writers Whitbeck says she began writing
when she was very young, scribbling poetry and short stories while
still in grade school. Cooper-Novack says she first submitted a
play to the festival when she was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a theater brat,'' said Cooper-Novack, now 18. She said
her fascination with plays began when her mother, a theatrical
casting agent, was explaining what various show people did.
</P>
<P>
   ``She mentioned the director,'' she recalled. ``And I said, `Is
he the one who makes up the story?' And she said, `No, that's the
playwright.' And I thought, `Wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   The others said they came to writing slightly later. Ou-yang,
22, who was born on Taiwan and grew up in Honolulu, said that her
play developed out of a single scene written when she was 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the attention span for more than 30 pages,'' she
said, laughing. ``But this just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitbeck began work on ``Woof,'' about that cat-food-nibbling
mother and dog-crazy daughter, as part of a playwriting class in
her freshman year of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher wanted us to do a student-teacher play, but I
couldn't,'' she said. ``But mother and daughter? I went off.'' Her
teacher gave her a B, but the festival gave her this year's opening
slot.
</P>
<P>
   Each play receives a complete production cycle, including a
professional director and dramaturge, an audition process,
production meetings, weeks of rehearsal, a preview period and of
course an opening night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gives you a feeling of being omnipotent,'' said
Feldman, 21, a drama writing student at Purchase College of the
State University of New York. ``I mean when you see actors you've
seen on Broadway coming into audition for you _ a little
21-year-old _ that's as about as omnipotent as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their early success, only Feldman seems completely sold
on the idea of a theater career. Ou-Yang is studying international
relations at Boston University, and Whitbeck is majoring in
classics at Harvard. Cooper-Novack, meanwhile, is pursuing a double
major of anthropology and linguistics at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their eventual destinies, Sheri Goldhirsch, the
festival's artistic director, says the experience is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A poem or short story you can do alone, and it's done,'' she
said. ``A play really isn't finished until it's onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
