<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RACE-OHIO28-COX     09-27 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-OHIO28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel discussion on race a hot topic
 &HT;    By Erik Clark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Ohio _ ``Race is a sensitive issue to talk about,''
Ohio Civil Rights Commission
</P>
<P>
   Director Melanie Mitchell said. ``But we must be able to talk
about it to have progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was the keynote speaker yesterday at the fourth meeting
of ``Racial Legacies and Learning: How to Talk about Race,'' a
series of public discussion sessions at Miami University Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective communication doesn't happen overnight,'' Mitchell
told an audience of educators, business leaders and government
officials at the Harry T. Wilks Conference Center. ``It takes a
little tact, a little training, but most of all, a little effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell suggested ways to breach the subject of race and
discrimination in communities, at work, and in schools. She said
peer study circles are a way to tie personal experiences with
racial discrimination to larger
</P>
<P>
   community-wide issues that can then be tackled together.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses _ especially those undergoing significant racial
change _ can use ``cultural assessments'' that carefully study the
true occupational culture in a workplace and identify ways to make
it more accepting of diversity, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often things are done a certain way simply because that's
the way it has always been done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For educators, Mitchell said, the Ohio Civil Rights Commission
developed a
</P>
<P>
   curriculum that incorporates diversity acceptance training into
preparation
</P>
<P>
   for proficiency tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the curriculum is to reach children at a time when
their
</P>
<P>
   opinions and values are still being formed,'' she said. ``We
firmly believe
</P>
<P>
   that children are not born to be bigots.'' But to teach
acceptance to children, teachers must often come to terms with
their own racial biases, Mitchell cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   As minority populations boom, Mitchell said, ``there's no time
like the
</P>
<P>
   present for people to try to reach out and connect with people
who are
</P>
<P>
   different than themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the panel discussion that followed centered around how
to best serve Hamilton's own growing minority population.
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Mary Jacobs, principal of Jefferson Elementary School
in Hamilton, said she's seen the Hispanic population at her school
jump in the last few years from one or two children to nearly 25
percent of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a great deal of difference, but then again it
doesn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus is still the same. Every child that comes through
the door has to
</P>
<P>
   be prepared to pass proficiency at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Sparks, owner of The Station, a Hamilton convenience
store, said she's noticed more Spanish-speaking customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (English speakers) are going to have to learn how to speak
Spanish as
</P>
<P>
   well,'' she said. ``When a community changes, you have to change
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Ivy Price, a student at Miami University Hamilton and
president of the university's Minority Action Committee, who got
the loudest applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out into the community,'' she said, ``instead of
just sitting up here and talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
