<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-27 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HILLARY CLINTON TOPS 50 PERCENT IN NEW YORK POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton has pulled farther ahead of Republican
Rep. Rick Lazio in the New York Senate race, reaching the 50
percent support level for the first time, according to a poll
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by the Quinnipiac University Polling Institute in
Hamden, Conn., showed Clinton, the Democratic candidate, leading
Lazio 50 percent to 43 percent. The numbers represent a small gain
for Clinton from the last Quinnipiac poll on Sept. 12, which put
her ahead of Lazio 49-44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the 50-percent mark provided a psychological boost for
Clinton, who evokes strong positive and negative feelings among New
York voters _ both for her controversial role as first lady and her
taking up residence in New York just before announcing her
candidacy for Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this race is going to be close, but it's nice to hit
the big five-oh,'' Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan said: ``Polls have been all over
the place, so we don't pay much attention to them. Essentially,
there's no change from the last Quinnipiac poll.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton holds a commanding lead in New York City, 67-29 percent,
while Lazio leads 53-40 percent in the suburbs, the poll found.
Lazio represents a district on Long Island in suburban Suffolk
County.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the race may be in normally Republican upstate New
York, where Lazio leads Clinton 46-44 percent, a statistical tie.
New York pollster John Zogby has said that in order to win, Lazio
has to beat Clinton upstate by 10 percentage points or more.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 889 likely voters in New York was conducted from
Sept. 20-25. The poll has a margin or error of 3.3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac poll showed that although voters trust Lazio more
and harbor suspicions about Clinton, they prefer the first lady on
the issues. Asked which candidate is trustworthy and honest, 61
percent said Lazio and 45 percent said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But by a 67-29 margin, voters said a candidate's stand on issues
is more important than personal qualities. On the issues, 59
percent said that Clinton shares their views. And 51 percent said
Lazio shares their views.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leads Lazio by a 61-34 margin on the health care issue,
and by a 58-38 margin on education, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, much less well known than Clinton, had hoped to score a
convincing blow against the first lady earlier this month in a
televised debate. Lazio was aggressive, walking up to Clinton's
podium at the end of the debate to get her to sign a pledge to not
accept television ads financed by political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   But the Quinnipiac poll suggested the strategy had not succeeded
in swaying voters. Respondents who said they had watched the debate
declared Clinton the winner by a margin of 44-34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``manages to excite people for or against her,'' said
Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac institute.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll pointed to poll results showing 52 percent of likely
Clinton voters strongly favoring her and nine percent supporting
her because they dislike Lazio. Among likely Lazio supporters, 46
percent were strongly enthusiastic and 28 percent said their
support was based on dislike of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Commission on Presidential Debates announced that only
Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush would appear
in three debates scheduled for next month. The announcement was a
blow to Green Party candidate Ralph Nader and Patrick Buchanan of
the Reform Party, who have been fighting for a place in the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   _ New surveys showed Bush, the Republican candidate, reversing
his slide in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll of likely voters gave Bush a 46-44
edge over Gore, a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll of likely voters gave Bush a six-point
lead, 48-42 percent. The margin of error is four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The polls represented good news for the Bush, who has struggled
since the Democratic convention in Los Angeles last month gave Gore
an edge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore stumped in Iowa, telling senior citizens in the town of
Altoona that while his prescription drug plan would cover all of
the nearly 40 million Medicare beneficiaries, Bush's plan would
leave seniors at the mercy of health insurers and managed care
companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Winifred Skinner, 79, told Gore she searches
roadside ditches for soft drink cans. She collects the five-cent
deposit to help pay her prescription costs.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore asked her how much she money she collected, Skinner
responded: ``You're not going to tell the government, are you?''
Gore hugged her.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush spent Wednesday in California, visiting a Catholic
elementary school in south-central Los Angeles to ward off
Democrats' characterizations that he favors the wealthy. The
Republican candidate told teachers and students at the Ascension
Catholic School that their institution was a ``beacon of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had spent part of Tuesday courting wealthy donors at
fund-raisers in California. His appearances raised $1.4 million for
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Washington, the chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, said a victory
by Gore would not necessarily spell doom for the Republican
majority in Congress. Davis pointed to the 1988 election, where
then-Vice President George Bush won the White House but the
Democratic majority grew in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you re-elect a regime, you tend to re-elect all the
elements of that including Congress,'' Davis said, explaining that
voters seeking continuity in a Gore administration would feel
comfortable also voting to keep the Congress in Republican hands.
</P>
<P>
   John Del Cecato, spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, pointed to statements Davis made earlier this
year that Bush's coattails would enable the Republicans to retain
their slim 12-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like the toughest job Tom Davis has is convincing
himself,'' Del Cecato said. ``They're charging toward an election
in reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
