<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-LADN-     09-27 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVYWEIGHTS MAKE A MOVIE THEY CAN BE PROUD OF
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN- (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Screenwriter Gregory Allen Howard left Los Angeles four years
ago after selling a script about the life of boxer Muhammad Ali to
Columbia Pictures. (It still hasn't been made.) Howard wanted to
escape Los Angeles and its racial tensions and find a place that
was not only racially integrated, but residentially integrated as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't riot against your neighbor,'' Howard, an
African-American, says.
</P>
<P>
   Howard moved to Alexandria, Va., a small city near Washington,
D.C., where he has a number of relatives. Howard, 38, says he was
immediately struck by the city's complete integration. It wasn't
Utopia, but Howard found the sense of racial harmony ``highly
unusual.'' In getting to know his new neighbors, he asked them
about the source of the city's unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me it was a high school football team that brought
the city together, the 1971 T.C. Williams Titans,'' Howard says.
``And that reminded me of something a neighbor of (civil rights
leader) Andrew Young once said, that high school football did more
to integrate America than the civil rights movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard loved the story and wrote a screenplay, ``Remember the
Titans,'' that celebrates (and sometimes overstates and sometimes
outright fictionalizes) the team's achievements in unifying
Alexandria. The movie hits theaters today and is notable for a
couple of reasons that go beyond its source material. ``Remember
the Titans'' marks a rare foray by big-bang producer Jerry
Bruckheimer into the realm of social issues, and it's also a
continued attempt by Disney to redefine what their Walt Disney
Pictures label will represent to audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer bought the script after nearly every other studio
and television network had rejected it. Howard initially pitched
the idea, and when he failed to find any takers, he went ahead and
wrote the script, spending several months interviewing the coaches,
team members and acquiring the life rights of those involved. There
were still no takers until Chad Oman, production president of Jerry
Bruckheimer Films, called.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's in the hands of Jerry Bruckheimer, this
action-adventure guy, who I figured was going to hate it,'' Howard
says. ``I mean, the movie didn't have any explosions; it didn't
have any asteroids. So I was shocked when he called and said he
loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Explains Bruckheimer: ``I'm a sucker for anything that shows the
triumph of the spirit and grabs at your heartstrings. I know people
look to me to make the 'Pearl Harbors' and 'Armageddons,' but I
like to get explosions of emotion on the screen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans'' has plenty of that. The movie, directed by indie
filmmaker Boaz Yakin (``Fresh,'' ``A Price Above Rubies'') bears
Bruckheimer's distinct stamp in its crowd-pleasing emotionalism,
melodrama and soundtrack, which seems to feature just about every
Top-40 Motown hit ever written. But then, as star Denzel Washington
notes, ``this is a positive story about people who came through
hard circumstances with flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Washington plays Coach Herman Boone, who, as a
result of state immigration, is selected to run T.C. Williams'
successful high school football program, replacing the team's
popular white coach, Bill Yoast (Will Patton). The community is
outraged, and the team's white players threaten to boycott. Yoast
initially resigns, but returns to the program to prevent a team
walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Boone must somehow integrate the team's new African-American
players with the incumbent white athletes. And even if he can
manage that, he must then win over parents, school board members
and, most importantly, Yoast, still stinging from his sudden
demotion. That he succeeded is a given -- otherwise, this movie
wouldn't exist. That the events didn't quite happen as shown in the
movie is also a given. This is Hollywood history after all.
</P>
<P>
   What remains true is this: The real-life coaches have stayed
friends to this day, and their good-natured banter suggests an old
married couple who respect each other despite their significant
personality differences. When Boone remarks that Washington has
coached his sons in football (his oldest son now plays for Campbell
Hall High School in North Hollywood) and ``secretly wants to be a
full-time coach,'' Yoast retorts: ``I think he'd make a lot better
coach than you would an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   But the genial Yoast, a true Southern gentleman in every sense
of the word, becomes serious when speaking of Boone's
accomplishment with the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone could have had a heyday with the football side
of it, given the talent we had there,'' says Yoast, who like Boone,
is retired. ``But you can have the best talent in the world and not
win. He brought the team together. He taught them the meaning of
respecting each other's differences.''
</P>
<P>
   And those are the kinds of life lessons that Disney chairman
Peter Schneider would like to see characterize movies that bear the
Walt Disney Pictures imprint. Howard's original ``Titans'' script
featured the kind of locker room language one would expect in a
high school football movie (see ``Varsity Blues''). Schneider asked
Bruckheimer to nix the profanity, along with several racial
epithets, mandating that the film come in with a PG rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were adamant about that,'' director Yakin says. ``They
were looking for a definite upbeat quality, a certain sensibility.
That's a challenge that I enjoyed. When you have a story that has
intense racism and violence, how do you make it a film for all ages
and still keep the emotions strong? How do you make it a genuine
family film, but in the best sense, where the it will be
interesting enough for adults?''
</P>
<P>
   Yakin, though, says he isn't in any hurry to ``become a poster
boy for Gore-Liebermann.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty colorful vocabulary myself,'' Yakin says. ``My
parents usually cringe when I walk in the door. So I don't want to
say that movies shouldn't have profanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' he adds, with a laugh, ``my next movie is going to
be filled with four-letter words.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, though, loves that he has finally made a movie that
he can show to all four of his kids. (Washington has four children,
ages 17, 13 and 9-year-old twins.) ``They've been on me to make
something like this for years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruckheimer, a man whose career has been made at divining
moviegoers' tastes (``Top Gun,'' ``Beverly Hills Cop,''
``Flashdance,'' ``ConAir,'' etc., etc.), believes the PG rating is
not only appropriate given the material, but will enhance the
movie's commercial prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was always looking for movies I could take my
daughter to on a Saturday morning,'' Bruckheimer says. ``And this
one, I think, will have a great impact on children. It goes to show
that even with all the politicians' talk, maybe Hollywood can do
some good, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
