<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3966 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-GIDEON-$ADV01-ART-     09-27 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GIDEON-$ADV01-ART-2TAKES-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THOROUGHLY A DOCTOR AS HE WAS A COP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
Terrence Rafferty is the critic at large for GQ magazine. 
 By TERRENCE RAFFERTY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``So far, we've had kidney cancer, breast cancer,
prostate cancer, leukemia and myelofibrosis,'' says Andre Braugher,
reciting the dire list with remarkable equanimity. He is referring,
fortunately, not to his personal medical history but to the ordeals
undergone weekly by the patients of Dr. Ben Gideon, the hero of the
new ABC hospital drama ``Gideon's Crossing,'' which has its
premiere on Oct. 10. Playing Gideon, he says, involves ``a steep
learning curve,'' and, judging by the professional coolness with
which he is now rattling off the names of life-threatening diseases
and risky, radical therapies, it appears that he's negotiating that
daunting curve with ease: Six weeks into production of ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' Braugher sounds uncannily like a real doctor, able to
speak the unspeakable trippingly on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher's fluency with medical terminology is a product of his
own scrupulous professionalism: Immersing himself in the language,
techniques and manner of a high-powered, research-oriented
physician so that he can approximate (for the viewer and for
himself) the experience of seeing the world through Gideon's eyes
is his job, for as long as the series stays on the air. And, he
says, ``I'm a lover of this profession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like getting out of bed and going to work _ going to
rehearsals when I'm doing a play, or going to the set every day
when I'm shooting a movie or a series,'' he says. ``Not every day,
maybe, but essentially I like the challenge of discovering the
truth of the behavior and the inner lives of all these
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   I meet Braugher at the poolside restaurant of a West Hollywood
hotel on one of his rare days off from filming ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' and I'm immediately struck by how relaxed and
unpretentious he is. (He actually introduces himself _ as if I
might not recognize him otherwise _ and then, very considerately,
suggests moving the table so my New York skin won't get burnt to a
crisp by the midday L.A. sun.) Over lunch, the conversation flows
smoothly enough that I never have to consult the questions I've
prepared. Because Braugher, whose acting style is invariably
described by journalists as ``intense,'' has been so successful at
portraying wary, tightly wound, uncompromising characters _ notably
Frank Pembleton, the implacable Baltimore police detective he
played for six years on ``Homicide: Life on the Streets'' _ I'm
pleasantly surprised by his looseness and amiability.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   (I didn't really expect Pembletonian disdain from him, but the
relationship between an actor and a journalist can be
uncomfortable; I'm always relieved not to be treated like a suspect
in a senseless killing.)
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Homicide'' was never a ratings colossus, Pembleton is
the role most people identify Andre Braugher with; he won a couple
of Emmys for it, and his departure in 1998 (a year before the show
went off the air) made entertainment-page news. He points out to me
that his six seasons of ``Homicide'' represent half of his working
life: He completed his studies at Juilliard only a dozen years ago.
When Braugher auditioned for the series, he had already appeared in
an important supporting role in the film ``Glory'' (1989), and had
begun to make a name for himself in the theater, but his reading
took the executive producers, Barry Levinson and Tom Fontana, by
surprise; they were, Fontana remembers, ``blown away by his
presence.'' Fontana also vividly recalls the power of the first
episode in which Braugher and Kyle Secor (as Pembleton's partner,
Tim Bayliss) grilled a suspect in the homicide division's stark,
cheerless interrogation room. ``I was so inspired by the chemistry
between Andre and Kyle that I went off and wrote an episode in
which the whole hour was an interrogation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pembleton's crafty, systematic demolitions of suspects'
defenses quickly became the signature scenes of ``Homicide,'' and
Braugher _ one of the lesser-known members of the series' initial
ensemble, which included Ned Beatty, Yaphet Kotto, Jon Polito and
Richard Belzer _ became, as if by a process of natural selection,
the show's undisputed star. He knows that Pembleton was a great
part. ``You couldn't figure out whether he was a villain or a
hero,'' Braugher says. ``Even his partner could never quite
decide.'' But he got restless. Fontana recalls: ``At a certain
point Andre said to me, `I feel like I've done the interrogation
room. The character's too smart, too on his game.' So I said, `What
if he had a stroke?' And he said, `Let's do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The diminishment of the ace detective's intellectual acuity and
verbal dexterity _ his proudest possessions _ gave the actor the
sort of challenge he needed to keep him on the show a while longer.
(He played Pembleton's affliction and recovery with a subtlety
uncommon in dramatic portrayals of disability.) Eventually, though,
as ``Homicide'' approached its 100th episode, Braugher decided that
``we'd told all the stories we possibly could, and it was time for
me to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, however, he would spend just two months of the
next year at home with his wife, Ami Brabson (who played
Pembleton's wife on ``Homicide''), and their two small sons. ``I
was afraid of being too closely associated with a single
character,'' says Braugher, who is 37. ``I'd seen it happen before,
and to people I thought were admirable actors. I felt I was in a
race to get as much material out there as I could that was
different from Frank Pembleton; I didn't want to play another
aggressive, manipulative, self-absorbed prima donna for a while.''
To implement his ``I'm not Pembleton'' program, Braugher in rapid
succession took on film roles as a sweet-natured karaoke-singing
drifter (in the recently released ``Duets''), a thoughtful hit man
(in ``A Better Way to Die''), an elegant gangster (in ``Thick as
Thieves''), a secretive, sexually confused lawyer (in ``It's the
Rage'') and an idealistic priest coaching a black high school
basketball team in the segregated South of the early '60s (in the
made-for-cable movie ``Passing Glory''). He also found time to
direct a segment of the Showtime anthology ``Love Songs.'' All that
furious activity must have helped him distance himself from
Pembleton _ enough, at least, to allow him to play another homicide
detective (albeit a conspicuously less fearsome one) in Gregory
Hoblit's ingenious time-travel movie ``Frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
