<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-GIDEON-2NDTAKE-ART     09-27 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GIDEON-2NDTAKE-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: ``Frequency.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braugher probably didn't need to run quite so grueling a race in
order to re-establish his versatility. Everybody knew already.
Fontana, Hoblit and Paul Attanasio, the creator of both
``Homicide'' and ``Gideon's Crossing,'' each at some point uttered
the words ``He can do anything.'' Attanasio went further: ``He's
also game to do pretty much anything. You can throw any acting task
at him. He's like one of those ninja masters, taking on seven guys
at once and dispatching them all.''
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, in fact, that the frenzy of Braugher's
post-``Homicide'' career has less to do with proving something to
producers and directors than with proving something to himself.
Between the six-year grind of the series and his duties as a
husband and father _ which he takes extremely seriously _ he has
had to scale down an enormous creative ambition. When I ask him
what roles he dreams of playing, he says: ``Every one of
Shakespeare's heroes, and eventually every one of Shakespeare's
clowns.'' We spend quite a lot of our long poolside lunch,
actually, talking not about television or movies, but about
``Macbeth,'' ``Coriolanus,'' ``Henry V'' and, especially,
``Hamlet,'' which was the play that got Braugher into the acting
business in the first place. He was only marginally involved in
theater during his high school years in Chicago. But in his
freshman year at Stanford, he was persuaded by a friend to try out
for a production of ``Hamlet'' that had just lost its Claudius. He
got the part, and, he says, ``It was the most fun I'd had lately.
And at the end of the evening the audience applauded _ I mean, I
don't think we were very good, but they applauded. I was
electrified.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of our meeting, Braugher launches into a theory
about how the Prince of Denmark should be played, complete with
detailed refutations of several scholarly interpretations of the
character. A couple of hours later he returns to the theme again,
while he's explaining to me why actresses like Alfre Woodard and
Meryl Streep inspire him more than male actors do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actresses are vastly more interesting to me,'' he says. ``What
happens with men is that there's a code of behavior that crushes
various aspects of the masculine personality. There's behavior
that's forbidden: Weakness is despised, absolutely. For example _
to get back to my fixation on `Hamlet' _ I've never seen an actor
playing Hamlet who has dared to be a coward. And I say `dared'
because cowardice is something that people recoil from, and you
risk losing the sympathy of the audience. But if you don't deal
with the issue of cowardice, the character can't make sense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clearly this is an actor with intellectual and emotional energy
to burn, and the role of Ben Gideon, while it isn't exactly Hamlet,
appears to be complex enough to keep Braugher's fires fed for now.
(And for whatever reasons, the movies have so far failed to provide
him with a role commensurate with his talent.) The character is
based on Dr. Jerome Groopman, a Boston physician who chronicled his
clinical experiences in the 1997 book ``The Measure of Our Days.''
``We were looking for an actor who could combine strength and
command and toughness with real emotional depth and warmth,''
Attanasio says. ``Andre is one of the few who could do that. I
wrote the character as a white, Jewish man, like Groopman, and cast
an African-American actor _ and the character never changed.'' If
the author of ``Henry V'' had seen Braugher's performance of that
title role in Central Park in 1996, he might have said something
similar.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher says, ``This is a role that I felt I had to rise to
meet; it's quite a challenge.'' The script, he says, was exciting
enough to make him do something he profoundly did not want to do _
leave his new home in New Jersey and commit himself to several
months of shooting in Southern California. It probably helps,
though, that the role not only stimulates his creative imagination
but also satisfies a personal ambition: ``I want to show my sons
images of black men in America who are fundamentally intelligent,
articulate, decent men. Sometimes I feel as if I have a duty to
combat the ritual demonization of African-American males.''
</P>
<P>
   That Braugher can deliver such a high-minded declaration without
sounding the least bit sanctimonious augurs well for his portrayal
of Gideon: It's likely that the actor will rise to meet this noble
character without allowing his feet to leave the ground. The role
might even lay to rest the uneasy ghost of Frank Pembleton. In
``Gideon's Crossing,'' Andre Braugher is once again playing a
tenacious and sharp-witted investigator, but this character is
searching for more elusive truths than Pembleton ever did, and
confronting destructive forces that can't be cajoled or browbeaten
into giving up their secrets.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, this part should have enough depth and variety
to keep Braugher's restless imagination occupied while he readies
himself for the Macbeth, the Coriolanus, perhaps the Hamlet in his
future. As he obviously understands, in an actor's life the
readiness is all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
