<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OPERA-GRAHAM-DEADMAN-     09-27 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-GRAHAM-DEADMAN-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEAD MAN WALKING':   A STAR MEZZO ROLE FINDS A STAR MEZZO TO SING
IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Calif., N. Mex., Texas, France) 
(For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
David Mermelstein writes about music for The New Criterion. 
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The American mezzo-soprano Susan Graham has for
the better part of a decade impressed audiences with her creamy
singing and chiseled characterizations, sharing the stage with
stars like Renee Fleming, Thomas Hampson and Dawn Upshaw, and
consistently earning reviews as strong as theirs. In December,
Graham gained new prominence in John Harbison's ``Great Gatsby'' at
the Metropolitan Opera. Now she is ready for her close-up, at the
center of another new work, Jake Heggie's ``Dead Man Walking,''
which opens on Saturday at the San Francisco Opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead Man Walking,'' with a libretto by the playwright Terrence
McNally, is based on Sister Helen Prejean's book of the same name,
which also inspired a 1995 movie that earned the actress Susan
Sarandon an Oscar. It tells of Prejean's attempts to save the soul
of a murderer sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is confrontational, Graham said last month, during
rehearsals here at the War Memorial Opera House. ``It makes you go
places you might not ordinarily go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead Man Walking'' is the first opera by Heggie, who has
mostly written art songs for reigning divas, especially the
mezzo-soprano Frederica von Stade. Graham, who had never sung any
of his songs, said she was surprised when Heggie approached her
about his opera, and daunted by the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jake told me of the project over a cup of coffee in the
summer of 1997, I dissolved in tears,'' she recalled. ``I said, `I
can't do it.' But Jake persuaded me otherwise. He told me that
because of my reaction to the description, I'd be perfect for the
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Heggie had his heart set on Graham nearly from the start. ``I
originally offered the role to Flicka,'' Heggie said, referring to
von Stade, ``but she declined in favor of someone younger. And so
Terrence and Patrick Summers, who will conduct, and I immediately
thought of Susan. We were after a Janet Baker type.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Stade will sing the supporting role of the killer's mother
and has only kind words for Graham, whose career echoes her own.
``I think the world of Susan,'' she said. ``Everybody does. She has
a terrifically warm voice, but it's also incredibly clear.'' Von
Stade describes Graham as ``sano,'' Italian for ``healthy'' or
``wholesome,'' a term not often applied to opera singers.
</P>
<P>
   For McNally, a longtime opera enthusiast, Graham's naturalism is
an asset. ``She is one of those opera singers who don't sound like
opera singers,'' he said. McNally collaborated with the composer
Robert Beaser on one act of the trilogy ``Central Park,'' which had
its debut last year, but ``Dead Man Walking'' represents his first
full-scale libretto. ``When Susan sings, it's like she's talking,''
he added. ``Her expression is so unforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 40, speaks excitedly of playing the protagonist in a new
opera, an honor seldom accorded a mezzo. ``I normally play Eve
Arden,'' she said. ``I don't usually get to play Bette Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hurdles. ``To portray a living person is a special
challenge,'' Graham said. ``And the music is not as simple as it
sounds. Part of it is very middle range, speech rhythms and the
like. But it is never on a beat, and was very hard to learn,
because it goes against what you hear in the orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the incendiary issues at the heart of the opera.
``Dead Man Walking'' deals with the death penalty, and debates
forgiveness and redemption for killers. Its themes are the stuff of
heated arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both positions are represented with great intensity,''
Graham said. ``But Sister Helen is decidedly against the death
penalty, and she gets more air time, so there is a slant in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who was born in Roswell, N.M., moved to Midland, Texas,
when she was 13. She attended Texas Tech University in Lubbock and
earned a master's degree in opera performance at the Manhattan
School of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is light for a mezzo, her lyric timbre possessing
something of a soprano's brightness; she could never be mistaken
for a contralto. Her signature roles include Cherubino in Mozart's
``Nozze di Figaro,'' Octavian in Strauss' ``Rosenkavalier,''
Charlotte in Massenet's ``Werther'' and, recently, Iphigenie in
Gluck's ``Iphigenie en Tauride.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's performances in ``Rosenkavalier'' have won special
praise, as at the Met in January. ``It was as if suddenly everyone
had discovered that Octavian is the title character in this
opera,'' Graham said. Bernard Holland, in The New York Times,
praised her ``clear, assertive voice,'' adding that she ``looked
the perfect Octavian.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Graham's physique received mention. A
handsome woman who stands 5 feet 10 inches (not 6 feet, as
sometimes reported), she cuts an excellent figure on stage.
Although artists can take little credit for what nature bestows,
Graham has used her stature to enrich her portrayals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that matters most to me is realism,'' she said. ``I
don't care if I'm playing a 17-year-old boy, an unhappily married
woman or a nun.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham first gained wide recognition three years ago, with her
debut solo recording, a Berlioz recital from Sony Classical, which
included ``Les Nuits d'Ete.'' The Sunday Telegraph of London called
it ``one of the finest recorded performances of Berlioz's evocative
and haunting song cycle.'' Graham acknowledged that ``it was some
sort of turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Sony issued her collection of perfumed songs by
Reynaldo Hahn, also well received. Von Stade termed the record ``my
idea of sensational singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is now under exclusive contract to the French label
Erato, which recently released her CD of songs by Ned Rorem. Erato
has also issued a live recording of Handel's ``Alcina'' at the
Paris Opera with Graham, Fleming and the soprano Natalie Dessay.
Future discs will offer opera arias by Mozart and Gluck, and
selections from French operettas.
</P>
<P>
   As Graham looks beyond ``Dead Man Walking,'' she sees, among
other things, the challenging role of Dido in a production of
Berlioz's ``Troyens'' at the Theatre du Chatelet in Paris in 2004.
``That's the goal, the Everest,'' she said. ``It's the closest you
get to singing Wagner without singing Wagner. It contains lyricism,
vulnerability, pain and nobility.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written about the recent proliferation of
high-profile mezzos, a list that always starts with Cecilia Bartoli
and includes singers like Vesselina Kasarova, Jennifer Larmore and
Anne Sofie von Otter. Never, surely, have more of them
simultaneously occupied a place in the public consciousness. Yet
Graham is unfazed by what some might consider competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of mezzos throughout my career,'' she
said. ``But everyone has her own specialty. Only Vesselina and Anne
Sofie overlap somewhat with me, and so much neglected material has
been rediscovered.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Graham is probably right. Changing conditions require
recalibrated expectations. With new operas like ``Dead Man
Walking'' favoring mezzos over sopranos, this voice type has
obviously attained increased status. As Graham put it, ``I guess
we're Eve Arden no more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
