<HEADER>
A3975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOHLS-COWBOYS0928-COX     09-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COWBOYS0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overhaul Cowboys from the top down
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ So where do the Cowboys go from here other than
the obvious?
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, that's the only relevant question that
remains after a 1-3 start has them bunking with the Bengals and
Bears and Patriots and Chargers of the NFL. Division cellar
dwellers all.
</P>
<P>
   The future is a scary proposition, and we're not talking
October. It's a won't-fill-Bill Romanowski's-prescriptions kind of
scary. As anyone can see, the Cowboys do not have the next Troy
Aikman or the next Emmitt Smith or the next Michael Irvin in place.
They don't even have the current Joey Galloway in place, and they
might not have the next head coach in place. It's not unthinkable
that Jerry Jones will pull the plug on Dave Campo and hire his
fifth head coach in his 13 seasons as Dallas' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Actually dating from Barry Switzer's final season in 1997, if he
makes a change, the next Dallas head coach would be No. 4 in five
years. That's a heckuva track record. Wonder who made all those
coaching decisions. The two men Jones has fired since Jimmy Johnson
haven't been in demand for other head coaching vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   With all the apparent errors and without heirs apparent to the
three franchise players that brought Dallas three Super Bowl
championships, Jones is worse than hamstrung. Without a first-round
draft pick next spring, he is downright destitute. When you throw
in the fact he's already $20 million over the salary cap, his club
might not compete for another Super Bowl before, say, 2005. The
Houston Texans might get there before Jones' Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Stoerner, I'm sorry, is not the next Aikman. Michael Wiley
makes you long for Sherman Williams. Raghib Ismail is too brittle
to be considered a future All-Pro receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are searching for answers. Some of Campo's staff
were at work at 3 a.m. Monday. That always sounds impressive, but
maybe they need more sleep. Have any of you done your best work in
the dead of night?
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the Cowboys are, they could hope Michael Vick, a
sophomore, stays in school one more season so they can draft the
multi-dimensional Virginia Tech quarterback in 2002. The Cowboys
look as though they would hold up their end of the bargain and be
first-draft-pick-bad again next year because Aikman will be another
year older and, sadly, several brain cells lighter; Smith will be
running behind Grandpas Erik Williams and Mark Stepnoski; and no
one can predict Galloway's post-knee injury ability, not that we
saw much of his pre-knee injury ability.
</P>
<P>
   Wane McGarity, bless his heart, can get hurt in the shower.
Dexter Coakley is having a miserable year after inking a big
contract, practically the only Dallas linebacker to ever be so
rewarded. Phillippi Sparks seems like a colossal waste of $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   As former Cowboys and current San Francisco 49ers linebacker Ken
Norton Jr. said Sunday, ``That's a very proud organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowed and proud.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the only workable plan that I can see. Bite the
bullet, Jerry, and fire . . . yourself. Hey, Daniel Snyder would
fire you.
</P>
<P>
   Get a real live 24/7 general manager who knows the league, who
knows talent, who will be more concerned with building a real NFL
team and not just pacifying Aikman and doing his bidding at every
turn. That way, the Cowboys might actually improve and Jerry can go
about the business of being the team spokesman, the one role he
clearly loves.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is the only owner in the league who also is his team's
president and general manager, although there's Oakland's Al ``Just
sue, baby'' Davis. Since he's been in charge of the draft without
Johnson, three of Dallas' first seven picks are no longer with the
team. Of the others, one is non-factor, third-string cornerback
Dwayne Goodrich. Defensive ends Greg Ellis and Ebenezer Ekuban are
good, but they're part of the line that has been overrun by, uh,
future Hall of Famers Duce Staley and Charlie Garner. The other
first pick was tight end David LaFleur, Aikman's personal choice
and largely ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Jones should seriously evaluate removing Larry Lacewell, his
director of scouting. With his input starting with the 1993 draft,
43 of Dallas' 52 picks made the team but the only stars are
offensive tackle Larry Allen and linebacker Dexter Coakley. There
are some players like Randall Godfrey, Flozell Adams and Eric
Bjornson sprinkled in, but there are far too many players like
Stepfret Williams and Sherman Williams, Shante Carver and Edward
Hervey. Allen is the only player drafted during the Lacewell era
who has played in a Pro Bowl. That's one player out of 52
selections.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at Jimmy's drafts between 1989 and 1993, you're
blinded by the Aikmans, Letts, Woodsons, Johnstons, Stepnoskis,
Tolberts, Marylands and Emmitt, Kevin and and Darrin Smiths. Ain't
hardly a miss in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   What other options are there for Dallas? Whom can you trade?
Emmitt? Maybe. Aikman? No way. Safety Darren Woodson? Certainly,
but Dallas wouldn't get a first-round pick for him. You'd get value
for value with Allen, but losing the best tackle in the game
wouldn't help Dallas any. Pro Bowl left tackles don't grow on trees
or in Dallas any more. In reality, probably only Allen, Woodson,
Coakley and Ellis have legitimate trade value.
</P>
<P>
   No, there's only one concrete solution that could start to patch
up the Cowboys, and it starts at the top. Overhaul is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
