<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-YANG-$ADV01-ART-     09-27 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-YANG-$ADV01-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POETRY OF MIDDLE CLASS LIFE PLAYED OUT IN TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 1) 
 (Attn: Fla., Calif., Wash.)  
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
Godfrey Cheshire is the film editor of the The New York Press. 
 By GODFREY CHESHIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Taiwanese director Edward Yang, who accompanied his film
``Yi Yi'' (``A One and a Two'') to the Telluride Film Festival last
month, was almost through answering questions after a screening
when a middle-aged woman took the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know your previous work, and I wasn't sure I wanted
to sit through a three-hour movie,'' she told him. ``But I was
completely swept away by it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was not the first to say so. Yang, 53, has heard many
variations on this compliment since May, when he won the best
director prize at the Cannes International Film Festival for ``Yi
Yi.'' But at Telluride, the praise seemed charged with an unspoken
question: Given the power and mastery of Yang's work, why is his
name unfamiliar to American moviegoers?
</P>
<P>
   The answer has to do in part with money. Since the mid-1980s,
Yang and a contemporary, Hou Hsiao-hsien, have been regarded as
leaders of the New Taiwanese Cinema, their films earning acclaim on
the international festival circuit. Yet the movies' critical
success sometimes led the producers to set prices for American
rights at levels that distributors considered too high to be
commercially viable. Thus few Americans saw them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, with the Taiwanese film industry in trouble, the
situation has changed, with prices falling in the last couple of
years. Last year, most of Hou's films were released, and the
response from critics and cinephiles alike was exultant. Now it is
Yang's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yi Yi,'' which will be shown on Wednesday at the New York Film
Festival at Lincoln Center and then open at the Film Forum on
Friday, is the first of Yang's seven features to reach American
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Set, like all his films, in middle-class Taipei, ``Yi Yi''
provides an engaging introduction to Yang's fictional universe, in
part because of its warm, bemused approach to the daunting flux of
family life. Opening with a wedding and closing with a funeral, the
story follows the wavering paths of a middle-aged couple, their two
children and assorted problematic relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Yang wryly describes N.J. Jian (Wu Nienjen), the tale's
businessman paterfamilias, as resembling ``Taiwan at the present
moment: high-tech, hard-working and sometimes depressed.'' While
N.J. deals with professional difficulties at his computer company
and the surprise reappearance of his first love, his wife, Min-Min
(Elaine Jin), takes up with a religious cult.
</P>
<P>
   Distracted by their separate concerns, the couple interact only
glancingly with their children, a 12-year-old (Kelly Lee) on the
brink of her first serious crush, and a mischievous,
proto-philosophical 8-year-old (Jonathan Chang), who gives people
photos of the backs of their heads so they can glimpse ``the half
they don't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Yang's filmmaking does something similar. With its elegantly
distanced compositions and quiet gravity, his style heightens the
stillness that frames every action, the silence that gives meaning
to words. In fact, the film's narrative is built around the mute,
motionless figure of Min-Min's mother, who early in the story
suffers an accident that puts her in a coma. When doctors advise
the family members to talk to her as often as possible, they are
obliged to examine their own lives for subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   The lanky, youthful-looking Yang notes that the film's narrative
kernel was inspired by an incident in the 1980s, when a friend's
father was similarly incapacitated. ``We went and saw him,'' he
said, ``and I was overwhelmed by the idea that the doctors said the
family had to talk to the father. Because in that situation, you
have to be honest. I went home with the structure of a story about
family, in which everyone has to confess.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took nearly 15 years before Yang felt he was
emotionally ready to tell the story. By then, the concern with
family had merged with a complementary interest: he also wanted to
speak about the many lives of one individual, about the stages of
``life itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of telling a story about someone from birth, through
growing up, getting to middle age and then dying, ``a linear
process,'' he continued, ``this structure represents every age with
a different character.''
</P>
<P>
   Yang's own life has been as variegated as that suggested by his
characters. Born in China, he moved to Taiwan with his parents when
he was a child. He said his earliest memory was of trying to draw
the figure of a man and wondering why his efforts were so crude.
Though an inspiring college teacher gave him the idea of a career
in the arts, his parents, who now live in the United States, urged
a more practical course. So he earned a graduate degree in
electrical engineering from the University of Florida. After a
brief stint studying film at the University of Southern California,
Yang _ who peppers his conversation with references to Michael
Jordan and other basketball heroes _ moved to Seattle and worked in
a lab that designed computers for undersea vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   On his 30th birthday, he said, he woke up and decided it was
time to change his life. Inspired by Werner Herzog's film
``Aguirre, the Wrath of God,'' he moved back to Taiwan and began
working as a screenwriter. After directing a successful short film,
he made the first of three intricately ambitious features that
critics labeled the Urban Trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   With their complex, probing visions of a society struggling with
urban anomie and the lures of money and success, the films _ ``That
Day on the Beach'' (1983), ``Taipei Story'' (1985) and ``The
Terrorizers'' (1986) _ earned him comparisons to Michelangelo
Antonioni and Jean-Luc Godard. In the following decade, Yang gave
the same themes a comic spin in two idiosyncratic satires, ``A
Confucian Confusion'' (1994) and ``Mahjong'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1991, however, with his fourth film, that he secured
his place in international cinema. Drawn from Yang's own memories
of adolescence and of a famous crime of the early '60s, the film,
``A Brighter Summer Day,'' titled after an Elvis Presley lyric,
paints a startlingly grave picture of teen-agers roiled by sex,
imported rock 'n' roll and gang warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Often cited in critical compilations of the best films of the
1990s, ``A Bright Summer Day,'' at four hours Yang's most
expansive, is considered one of the modern era's greatest
Chinese-language films.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the film never made it beyond occasional festival
appearances in the United States. Finally, with ``Yi Yi,'' a more
intimate, open-hearted epic, Yang's meditations on time and Taiwan
will have their day in American theaters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
