<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-LINDBERG-$ADV01     09-27 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LINDBERG-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A PATH TROD BY SIBELIUS AND MAYBE EVEN HAYDN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Ohio, Calif., Finland, France)  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the great crowd of composers working at the moment, the
spotlight of current events falls just now on the brilliantly
accomplished Magnus Lindberg.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening at Carnegie Hall, the Cleveland Orchestra,
conducted by Christoph von Dohnanyi, will play the new orchestral
piece it commissioned from him, ``Cantigas.'' Deutsche Grammophon,
meanwhile, has released a CD offering ``Aura,'' an earlier piece of
his for big orchestra, and ``Engine,'' for a smaller ensemble, both
in performances conducted by Oliver Knussen.
</P>
<P>
   Lindberg, who was born 42 years ago in Helsinki, has played a
central role in the renaissance of Finnish music that came along a
century after Sibelius. Among his student friends was Esa-Pekka
Salonen, now the music director of the Los Angeles Philharmonic,
and the two gained a lot of their important early musical
experiences performing in Ears Open, an exploratory ensemble, with
other young musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Lindberg is also a contemporary of the Finnish composer Kaija
Saariaho, and like her, he went to Paris in the 1980s to work at
Ircam, Pierre Boulez's electronic music institute, and meet the
French composers, notably Gerard Grisey and Tristan Murail, who
were associated with ``spectral'' music: music with extreme, dense
and rich harmonies composed on the model of the overtones in
natural resonances.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lindberg belongs to a wider community of
composers. Like such American colleagues as John Adams, Augusta
Read Thomas, Peter Lieberson and Gerald Levinson, he has been
finding ways to recapture the drive, colorfulness and amplitude of
music just before modernism. This has been one of the strongest
tendencies in the music of the last 20 years, to join hands with
Mahler, with early Stravinsky, with Ravel or _ in Lindberg's case,
especially _ with Sibelius.
</P>
<P>
   The link with Sibelius seems to irk Lindberg a little, no doubt
because he does not want to be defined as a Finnish composer,
working within a narrow national tradition. Yet the connection is
unmistakable. There are points in ``Aura'' and ``Engine'' where one
feels, as powerfully as in Sibelius, the swell of harmony striving
to erupt from underneath, to break through to a point of
culmination. And it is in speaking about Sibelius that Lindberg is
most eloquent about his own music.
</P>
<P>
   ``While his language was far from modern, his thinking, as far
as form and the treatment of materials is concerned, was ahead of
its time,'' Lindberg has said. ``In his last symphonic works the
development and thematic work are particularly interesting. Each
theme gives rise to another, according to genuine cycles of
metamorphosis. The work _ the whole work _ is in perpetual
evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like ``Aura,'' or like the new ``Cantigas.''
Lindberg does not use themes; he remains too committed to his
modernist background for that, too unwilling to abandon altogether
his student enthusiasm for Karlheinz Stockhausen, Luciano Berio and
Milton Babbitt. But his music conveys a feeling of continuous,
urgent movement onward, thanks in particular to the way each
emphatic harmony presses forward into the next. The music is filled
with strong arrows of direction and gleaming points of arrival. It
also draws at times on the dynamo of pulsation and reiteration,
inherited from Minimalism, and, more rarely now, on the force of
flung blocks of tone, of strident dissonances, reminiscent of
Edgard Varese.
</P>
<P>
   Varese was a more prominent model in the work that made
Lindberg's reputation when he was still in his mid-20s: ``Kraft''
(1983-85), a piece of heavy metal for symphony orchestra with
percussion soloists. From there Lindberg turned to investigating
the softer substances in his musical makeup _ the sea foams and the
thick carpets _ and developing a virtuosity in orchestral writing
that few of his contemporaries can rival.
</P>
<P>
   He also turned out to have a rare sense of humor. Though his
music will often suggest immense machines in sound, what those
machines are prone to produce is pure comedy. Like Stravinsky,
Lindberg appreciates the clowning capabilities of bassoons _ in the
first movement of ``Aura,'' for example _ and the big climax of
that work's second movement comes with Oriental gong crashes that
sound at once weird and jokey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aura,'' in four movements, both is and is not a symphony. ``I
believe the overall form of `Aura' would make it appropriate to
call the piece a symphony,'' Lindberg has written. ``Still it is
not a symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of its playfulness and its luminous high color.
For symphonies that are such fun, one has to look back to Haydn;
for symphonies so gorgeous, to Scriabin. Lindberg _ who likes to
think of himself as a classicist, and whose music cheerfully
overturns all notions of musical history as progressive _ stands
somewhere between those composers, or to the side, with Sibelius
and Stravinsky flanking him.
</P>
<P>
   With him, as with other contemporary artists, the magic window
into the past is the computer, and what it shows has a glowing
unreality. His father was a computer engineer, and Lindberg grew up
with computers in the house, able to program with as much facility
as he could play the piano. Though he has now and again used
computer techniques of electronic sound synthesis _ whether in
preparing music on tape or in making instrumental parts to be
played on keyboard synthesizers _ his most regular recourse to the
digital world has been to help him in handling harmonic
progressions.
</P>
<P>
   A personal harmonic labyrinth, built up over the years, has
given him the means to parallel what Haydn and Scriabin could
accomplish with the language of tonality that had stored itself in
their internal hard drives. The computer provides a cleaner memory.
Diving into it, Lindberg can come up with the athletic and assured
strategies of music performed entirely on traditional instruments.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Cantigas,'' the labyrinth is entered at the
door of one of the most elementary intervals: the perfect fifth _
the bare fifth that was the basic concord of medieval music. The
title alludes to this, to the ``cantigas,'' or songs, of medieval
Spain, but it also suggests that the work is composed of songs
happening now, in the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In half a minute, at the start, the music has zoomed from the
simple fifth of the 12th century, sung by a solo oboe, to a
piling-up of fifths that make a modern 10-note chord, swung forward
as the first marker in the harmonic journey.
</P>
<P>
   From that point the music is off, careering with Lindberg's
characteristic ebullience and propulsion, often at the energetic
high speeds that are also typical of his music. There are moments
for reflection, too, and for perhaps a new and firmer melodic
definition. By the end, the oboe, now playing with its companion,
has learned to sing a far more extravagant kind of song: the kind
of song, maybe, that will come in the opera Lindberg has long been
promising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
