<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS AND THE INTERNET: NOT NECESSARILY A 'LOVE' MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release September 27, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might get the impression that teens find the World Wide Web
to be as essential as oxygen. But a recent study conducted by Youth
Intelligence of 350 14- to 18-year-olds from around the country
revealed that they prefer human interaction and communication.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong; teen-agers like the Internet. They can talk
to six friends at once, never bother with a library and download
tunes rather than harass their parents to drive them to the local
music store.
</P>
<P>
   However, 71 percent of the teens we surveyed said that the
Internet was overrated. As one 15-year-old girl from New York
commented, ``I go to all these sites and they say I don't have the
right programs so I can't see anything on the screen; then I try to
download the program and it crashes my computer. The way I look at
it, get back to me when it really works!''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with the Internet is that most American
households don't have fast enough connections to download complex
programs. As one 16-year-old male from Dallas explained, ``I try to
look at movie trailers and stuff, but it takes like 40 minutes to
download one, and half the time it doesn't work anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   And until every household has the luxury of two phone lines or
DSL, chatter-happy teens may not find that digital dialogue can
replace the real thing. Almost three-quarters of the teens in our
survey said they would rather talk on the phone than use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, what teens do like about the Internet is that it makes
it easier for them to keep in touch with friends and get
information. When asked if this technology makes their life easier,
91 percent said yes. This doesn't mean that they necessarily find
the Internet ``fun.'' As one 18-year-old male college student in
North Carolina explained, ``I see the Internet as my generation's
combination Encyclopaedia Britannica and stationery. It makes
finding out information so easy and I can keep in touch with people
more often. But is it like the coolest thing I've ever seen? No
way. It's still got a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And while e-tailers are trying to convince investors that teens
are the Internet's shopping gold mine, it was no surprise to us to
hear that 91 percent of those surveyed would still rather shop at
the mall than on-line.
</P>
<P>
   Many teens view the Internet as a sort of constantly updated
catalog. They scour sites for sneakers, clothing, album release
dates and other hot items, but often still want to lay their hands
on the goods before putting their cash on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the Internet might cast a wider net than the
average teen's mall, the wait time may be a drawback. As one
15-year-old female from Minneapolis confessed, ``I like to check
out what's new and hot on-line, but I want to go to the mall and
get it right then, not wait like a week for it to arrive. The only
time I buy stuff on-line is if I know I can't get it in my area.''
</P>
<P>
   The one aspect of the Internet where teens find that the reality
does seem to live up to the hype is in music. Teens love the access
they have to lyrics, songs, tour dates and every piece of
information they can find about their preferred tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers have always been passionate about music, but the
Internet allows them to pursue their interest even if their
favorite group hasn't made it to the Hot 100. Although the Napster
controversy will undoubtedly change the future of music on the Web,
it may not mean the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study that Youth Intelligence conducted for MTV of
300 Gen Xers and Whyers, age 14-30, who have trendsetting taste in
music, 25 percent stated that being able to download music has
increased the number of CDs they've purchased, while 63 percent
said that this had had no effect on their buying. The ability to
download may be the easier way of simply sampling music.
</P>
<P>
   So though teens like the Internet, they don't love it. It may
not be until the computer is fully integrated into their world with
one box for their TV, phone and Web access, that they will fully
accept this technology. Even then, given what we know about teens
and their social behavior, it's more likely to be a necessity than
what they consider to be a nifty distraction.
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crudup in ``Almost Famous''
</P>
<P>
   The relaunched boo.com
</P>
<P>
   Teen Vogue
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
