<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-JAZZ-BURNS-$ADV01-     09-27 1689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JAZZ-BURNS-$ADV01-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING AMERICA'S STORY THROUGH AMERICAN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1) 
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the documentary filmmaker Ken Burns announced his plans for
a series on jazz, Matt Glaser, a violinist who had played on the
soundtracks of Burns' ``Civil War'' and ``Baseball,'' started
pestering him about being included in the new film. Burns ignored
him. Glaser insisted. Finally he came to Burns' apartment one night
and pressured him into hearing his spiel about one of Louis
Armstrong's recordings of ``Lazy River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and did this extraordinary thing, talking and
singing while the music was going,'' Burns said, ``and immediately
I knew that we were on to something new, something that had never
been filmed before.'' Burns asked if Glaser could repeat his
performance in front of a camera for ``Jazz.'' Remembering the
evening, Burns said, ``He's making it come alive and I was jumping
around in ecstasy and Matt's saying, `I told you so, I told you
so.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz,'' a 10-night, 19-hour documentary that is one of the
most highly anticipated programs of the new television season, is
full of moments like Glaser's, striking concatenations of word,
music and image. One of the film's commentators will be citing a
piece of music, maybe snapping his fingers to mark off the time and
singing the melody and part of a solo to underscore a point. It can
seem a bit goofy: seeing and hearing someone sing alone before the
camera, a weirdly intimate and separate experience from the way the
piece is usually heard. Then the original recording wafts onto the
soundtrack, in time with the talking head. What might have been
merely nostalgia or scholarship becomes history.
</P>
<P>
   These convergences might seem serendipitous. But as with jazz,
in which years of study are required to reach a level where a
performance feels natural and unstudied, Burns' moments are the
product of planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new level of filmmaking, and I had to hold off using it
too much,'' he said. ``We're making room for the music and
listening to it on a level we haven't before. There are two
parallel tracks, and we're performing a quantum act by merging
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, which took six years to complete _ and which is
already a subject of controversy in the provincial world of jazz _
will be broadcast on PBS beginning Jan. 8. Burns is calling it the
final chapter of an American trilogy that began with ``The Civil
War'' and continued with ``Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he had heard jazz _ he ran a record store in the late
1960s, and his father had been a jazz fan _ he was always more
interested in popular music, rock and rhythm and blues. But once he
began working on the film, he often found jazz and all of its
ramifications overwhelming. ``On a larger level, I began to
understand that an instinct I had had about jazz was right, that it
was a very accurate prism through which you could see refracted
tendencies of my country,'' he said. ``I found what I wanted, but I
didn't expect jazz's story to be so rich. On every level _
mythological, sensual, political and social _ it informed me about
who we are as a people. I didn't expect to learn so much.''
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly touched by Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed my life, he made me a better person,'' Burns said.
``I had a popular view of Armstrong, but I had no idea how central
he was to American music, and simply how great he was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz,'' reflecting the propensities of Burns and his writer,
Geoffrey C. Ward, subscribes solidly to the Great Man theory of
history. The film investigates in some depth the lives of
Armstrong, Duke Ellington, Jelly Roll Morton, Sidney Bechet, Bix
Biederbecke, Billie Holiday, Charlie Parker, Miles Davis and John
Coltrane, among others. The biographical stories circle around,
repeating and commenting on one another in a cycle leading from the
turn of the last century to the present. More than anything, the
stories keep leading back to race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this film because I'm interested in race,'' Burns
said. ``Race is the soul of the country, and nowhere is it more
evident than in jazz, where a music came out of the black community
and with great generosity was shared with the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the documentary, race and heroism intersect. For
black musicians, heroism was a matter of maintaining elegance and
creativity under the constant pressure of demeaning and dangerous
laws and practices that could reduce them to the status of
children. A commentator quotes Duke Ellington as saying, after an
insult, ``I put the energy I would have used in pouting and went
off and wrote some blues.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have been extraordinarily generous to white
musicians, trying to show exactly how difficult it was for them to
renounce mainstream white culture and ally themselves aesthetically
and emotionally with black culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ken asked me about Paul Whiteman,'' said Gerald Early,
the black essayist and scholar whose commentary is a major part of
the documentary, ``I was a bit stunned, because I didn't want to
reduce the argument to `Well, whites stole everything,' which has
already been said. So it forced me to think a bit more about the
subject, to look at what sort of work Whiteman had done to get
where he was, and the sort of honesty with which he approached his
study. Then you find something essentially American in the position
of white musicians also.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, a longtime colleague of Burns' who was a co-writer of
``The Civil War'' and ``Baseball,'' said that he dived into the
project in part to erase a series of myths that he feels have
infected jazz since its inception. ``I hope that the notion that
all jazz musicians are the same, human, comes across in what we
made,'' Ward said. ``I try to make these musicians people, black
and white.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns mixes filmed performances and interviews with stills,
moving from generalizations about the intersection of culture,
music and the American community to specific personal anecdotes.
Prominent among the commentators are the critics Stanley Crouch,
Gary Giddins and Gene Lees, the historians James Lincoln Collier,
Albert Murray and Phil Schaap and the musicians Dave Brubeck,
Charlie Haden, Jon Hendricks, Arvell Shaw, Clark Terry and,
particularly, Wynton Marsalis.
</P>
<P>
   One commentator tells a story about Ellington's ability to
provoke fights between his sidemen, then put them together in a
duet, where their anger would bring out an intense performance. As
the anecdote is being told, stills show what looks like Ellington
doing exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   In the six years Burns and his crew spent working on the film,
they assembled 2,400 stills, 2,000 film clips, 75 interviews and
500 pieces of recorded music.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It took literally millions of decisions,'' Burns said. ``This
whole documentary is a detective story. We'd go to an archival
source and find 40 shots we could use, though we'd only have the
place for one. Or we'd hear about some stills and spend months
looking for them, only to find nothing. Or we'd find something and
the owners would want a ransom, hundreds of times more than we
normally pay for things, which was often heartbreaking. Or we'd
have to convince somebody. For instance, I pestered Norman Granz,
who owns some rare footage of Charlie Parker, and finally he
relented and was generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard work, and you never know if you're asking a source
the right questions, or if they're holding a gem back for whatever
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Burns had to face the cantankerous world of jazz, where critics,
academics and musicians are divided into hostile camps that can
make the Balkans seem like a cradle of good will. It's a world that
can divide along any number of lines: the relative virtues of white
and black musicians; whether swing and blues are central to the
music; whether the term ``jazz'' has any real meaning. Some critics
can't stand jazz that doesn't subscribe to rules; others feel music
that doesn't break rules is worthless. Among these experts there is
an almost pathological lack of generosity. Burns waded right into
the middle of all this, choosing which advice to take and which to
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had assembled all our advisers and put them into one
room, a fight would have broken out,'' Ward said. ``It's not a
documentary that will make jazz experts particularly happy. There's
something missing for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   For Early, what was missing was soul jazz: Burns ignored his
suggestion to include this '50s movement that merged elements of
black popular music and church culture with jazz, one of the last
moments when jazz maintained a large black audience. For Marsalis,
the trumpeter and artistic director of Jazz at Lincoln Center, who
is the documentary's primary talking head, what was missing was an
attack on fusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why he treated fusion and the avant-garde the way
he did,'' Marsalis said. ``He let the interviewers deal with it.
But if it were up to me I would have taken the movements on.''
</P>
<P>
   In what is likely to be Burns' most controversial choice, the
documentary dwells on the first 60 years of the music, leaving the
years from 1960 to the present to be covered in the final two
hours, a fact that is already bouncing around the jazz world and
angering many. Jazz has exploded with new movements in those 40
years, and if it lost its footing as a popular music, it did not
become any less prolific. But the decision, right or wrong, was the
result of careful consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have used another 12 hours to cover from 1960 to the
present,'' Ward said. ``We chose to focus on the earlier years and
not follow all of jazz's later tributaries. With Ellington and
Armstrong and Bix Biederbecke you have titanic figures, terribly
important figures. You have to give them their due.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he saw the modern era, and the definition of a
contemporary pantheon, as the province of current critics. ``That
being said, I'd hold the final episode as an honorable view of
what's gone on,'' he said. ``But I'm not in the business of making
judgments about the present. I simply don't know if there are
contemporary figures as important as Armstrong or Miles Davis, who
belong in the Mount Rushmore of jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to the chagrin of many in the jazz world who see him as
contentious and narrow-minded, Marsalis is, in Early's words, the
documentary's Virgil, guiding the audience through the labyrinth of
jazz history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Wynton after a speech I gave at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art in 1991,'' said Burns. ``It was a meeting of the minds.
Later, when he heard that I was doing a documentary on jazz, he
told me, `I'll do anything you need.' In one way he's the backbone
of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he didn't worry that Marsalis' viewpoint would
dominate the documentary. ``I choose these influences, but I'm a
very strong filmmaker and I want to borrow from all these stories.
And finally I make the decisions about what goes into the
documentary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marsalis sees the documentary as yet another way of advancing
jazz's cause in its birthplace. ``I just hope the nation embraces
the music after watching the documentary,'' he said. ``I would hope
that the nation developed a deeper relationship with the music,
with something that we all have in common. I hope young people
embrace it. Jazz doesn't need to be exaggerated about. The lives of
Miles Davis and Louis Armstrong were real; these are great figures.
There's a lot to learn there about ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SAMSON-OPERA-REVIEW-N     09-27 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSON-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAMSON ET DALILA': LOINCLOTHS, LONG LOCKS AND LUST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Metropolitan Opera's 1998 production of
Saint-Saens' ``Samson et Dalila'' returned to the house on Tuesday
night, having already acquired the feel of a dusty and familiar old
show.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the producer, Elijah Moshinsky, and the
set and costume designer, Richard Hudson, have not tried to capture
the licentious and exotic aspects of this proudly conservative
French composer's take on the Old Testament tale. The stage is
filled with hanging scrims and sliding panels brush-stroked with
lurid reds and oranges, like Abstract Expressionist paintings.
Huge, spiky pinkish cones, weird-looking things, are meant to
represent temples and palaces in ancient Gaza. And the Met must
have sent audition notices to every gym and actors' studio in town
to recruit the roster of muscled male extras who portray the Nubian
slaves in loincloths.
</P>
<P>
   But injecting vitality into this second-rate opera is a
director's challenge. Despite a couple of disarming arias and some
crowd-pleasing music in the bacchanalian dance scene, the score is
mostly a tepid, awkward melodrama. For all their efforts, Moshinsky
and Hudson manage only to put a theatrical gloss on an essentially
inert work.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the opera contains two vocally juicy roles, and the Met has
brought back two veterans from the production's premiere to sing
them: the tenor Placido Domingo and the mezzo-soprano Denyce
Graves. Domingo, nearing 60, is singing better than opera buffs
have any right to expect. He has to work more audibly than before
to sustain his voice, and his softened legato passages sometimes
have a leathery quality. But he seems to be responding to the
understandable diminishing of his vocal resources with heightened
intensity. The poignant timbre of his sound is unchanged, and his
notes are fearlessly dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's hard to deepen Saint-Saens' one-dimensional
characterization, Domingo tried his best to project Samson's crisis
of realization: as he loses his physical strength and berates
himself for so foolishly succumbing to Dalila's allure, he regains
the faith that has grounded his life.
</P>
<P>
   Graves is surely one of the loveliest Dalilas ever, and the
dusky richness and vibrancy of her voice were essentially present.
But she seemed to be singing somewhat tentatively. There were dry
patches in her phrasing, and notes not placed quite as she wanted
them. Perhaps she was having a slightly off night; she should
rebound fully later in the run.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting cast was strong. The robust-voiced Russian
baritone Sergei Leiferkus was the menacing High Priest of Dagon;
the German bass Rene Pape brought his stentorian voice to the role
of the Old Hebrew. And the sturdy German bass-baritone Falk
Struckmann portrayed the hectoring Philistine Abimelech.
</P>
<P>
   The admirable conductor Mark Elder tried to draw from the score
every bit of delicacy and nuance to be found in it. The opening
chorus for the oppressed Israelites is a pointlessly academic
fugatto, but under Elder the orchestra and chorus certainly let you
hear the intertwining lines clearly. And he brought dash and color
to the bacchanalian scene. Though with all those scantily clad male
and female dancers gyrating about the stage and simulating
copulation, who was listening?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
