<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-HOUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OF STYLE
</HEADLINE>
bc-DESIGN-HOOLYWOODHOUSE Hollywood's not-so-humble abode opens its elegant gates 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
 
BY BARBARA DeWITT 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the '20s, an invitation to a barbecue at Charles
Toberman's Hollywood manse was no paper-plate picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Mr. Hollywood,'' the developer of 36 major Hollywood
landmarks -- including the Egyptian, Chinese and El Capitan
theaters, as well as the Roosevelt Hotel and the Hollywood Athletic
Club -- threw lavish parties that perpetuated the glitz and glamour
of Hollywood's golden era. At his 15,000-square-foot estate, Villa
Las Colinas, guests were known to play golf on his nine-hole
course, frolic in the indoor pool (a miniature version of the
Hearst Castle pool), and play billiards before dining on tables
decorated with swan-shaped ice sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Invitations to those private soirees behind iron gates were
rare, but now through Oct. 29, the public can catch a glimpse of
Hollywood's heyday.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen as Design House 2000 by the Assistance League of Southern
California, the Toberman estate -- designed by architects George
Vernon Russell and Norman W. Alpaugh in 1924 -- represents the
grandeur of the city's best homes. For the tour, the grounds and 29
rooms have been renovated and redecorated to reflect its original
spirit by a team of more than 30 area interior designers working
around the clock for several months with the cooperation of the
home's current owner, movie producer Kenny Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   Every room -- the eight bedrooms, eight bathrooms, four
kitchens, wine cellar, billiard room, cigar room, breakfast nook
that sports a mural inspired by Pompeii, private phone booths and
music room, to name a few -- graciously re-create a vintage '20s
feel.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it off, Los Angeles designers Peggy McClennan and
Chris Tourney added a room by turning an old garage on the terraced
grounds into a theater where guests watch the stars on the screen
while sitting under the stars above.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the owner's concept,'' they say, ``to create a true
'Cinema Paradiso' film effect that includes remote lighting that
allows the lights to dim and the drapes to open as the movie
begins.'' And to help carry out the theme, the designers added
leather ``smooch booths'' and scratch-coat plaster walls for
guests' signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the main house, where the tour actually begins, guests
meander on the front terrace with its Italian pottery and fountain,
then enter through heavy wooden doors into the foyer noted for a
grand spiral staircase with the 12 signs of the zodiac painted by
Dale Zimmerman on the ceiling, inspired by a 17th-century map of
Johann Bayer.
</P>
<P>
   To the left is the living room, where Los Angeles designers
Tiffany Farha and Joy Stowell have created a romantic young
Hollywood ambience. Using the assigned Design Home color palette of
soft shades of sage, olive, ochre and amber, Farha says she and
Stowell focused on the yellow hues for the room. They used tufted
sofas to represent Old Hollywood and slipper sofas to represent the
new, and then covered them with an assortment of round and envelope
pillows trimmed with beads and handmade tassels with a Middle
Eastern motif.
</P>
<P>
   As the pair put the finishing touches on the room, Farha
explains, ``We made a conscious effort to design the room with
glamour but enough energy for a young person, so we used four
ottomans pushed together to work as a coffee table. It's a new idea
that also provides additional seating that can be moved if
necessary. And if it seems spare, that's the idea, as the
decorating theory that less is more is back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Key accessories, say Farha and Stowell, are large trays that
create one important area by holding a group of collectibles. ``The
tray we used is wooden, but a piece of glass, a big silver or
copper tray or even a sushi tray will work. And speaking of Asian
accessories, there's something very relaxing about them, so we used
several classic Asian accents such as a jade water buffalo and a
Buddha head,'' Farha adds.
</P>
<P>
   Past the living room, guests can enter the spacious music room
facing yet another fireplace with a huge bar at the left and a
grand piano at the right. Designers Holly Higbee-Jansen of
Camarillo and Helene Lotto of Westlake Village have kept the colors
here as soft as Italian clay, with glints of gold and Old World
art, and French doors framed by chenille fabric also seen in the
sofa. ``It's my favorite room in the house because it's so
inviting. 'Come sit with me and talk' is the feeling I get here,''
says Assistance League President Katie Osterloh.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the music room with its view of Hollywood, is the ladies
retreat covered in toile de Jouy fabric, a type of French fabric
with printed pastoral scenes. The fabric from Pierre Deux of
Beverly Hills, was applied to the walls, as well as bed coverings
and curtains by Gail LeVine to create a tiny jewel of a room
accented with an antique French dressing table covered with crystal
perfume bottles and a sterling hair brush set.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the library that speaks volumes about design
integrity. Here, at the end of the foyer, and up a few steps, is a
regal retreat that's lacquered in deep jade over woven raffia. The
color, says designer Jill Kollmar of Beverly Hills, was inspired by
Casa Guidi, the home of Robert and Elizabeth Barrett Browning in
Florence, Italy, and it plus the soft flickering sconces and
candelabras set the mood for this somewhat sensual room that houses
nearly 1,000 vintage leather-bound books.
</P>
<P>
   Adding more Florentine flavor is a massive gilt horse's head, a
vividly colored Persian rug, an eclectic combination of chintz and
leather chairs, and stained-glass windows adorned with toile de
Jouy swags.
</P>
<P>
   After touring the many rooms, guests will no doubt be ready to
relax and reminisce in the tented Alfresco Cafe in the
English-themed gardens of the villa.
</P>
<P>
   ---DESIGN HOUSE 2000 &QL; 
What: Home and garden tour of Villa Las Colinas sponsored by the
Assistance League of Southern California. Where: Hollywood; call
number below for exact location. When: Tour continues through Oct.
29 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday. Perks: Alfresco
Cafe, boutiques, informal modeling. Rules: Guests are requested to
wear flat shoes, only. Strollers, cameras and backpacks are not
permitted. Note: Home is not handicapped-accessible. Tickets: $20
each; call (818) 509-3898 or (323) 993-1097. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
