<HEADLINE>
GENETIC DIFFERENCES DETAILED, A STEP TOWARD DISEASE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers have catalogued about 800,000 genetic differences
among humans, tiny hereditary variations that make people tall or
squat, black or white, fat or slim, and may also reveal the
underlying causes of the diseases that plague them.
</P>
<P>
   The development marks a significant step in the mammoth effort
to take the newly-mapped human genome and translate the 3
billion-letter Book of Life into concrete medical advances.
</P>
<P>
   But where the genome project essentially identified the 99.9
percent of the genetic code that all humans share, the new effort
is ferreting out the slight differences that not only give rise to
unique traits but determine, in great part, what diseases they may
face.
</P>
<P>
   And implicit in this search for differences, said scientists, is
the fact that humans are, genetically speaking, quite similar,
rendering notions of race and ethnicity moot.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper in the current Nature, researchers at the Whitehead
Institute/MIT Center for Genome Research in Cambridge, Mass. detail
the innovative approach they used to identify these genetic
differences, called single nucleotide polymorphisms or SNPs for
short. And they report that they have identified about a tenth of
all suspected SNPs (pronounced ``snips''), enough that scientists
and biomedical companies will be busy for years using the data to
pinpoint the genetic roots of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying these roots is expected to cause a sea change in
medicine, shifting its focus from ameliorating the effects of
diseases to altogether shutting them off by striking at their
genetic cores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now we've been treating symptoms. SNPs will help shed
light on the basic mechanisms of disease,'' said Eric Lander, head
of the Whitehead Institute.
</P>
<P>
   All of the SNP data will be available free on-line to
researchers. The work was the product of the SNP Consortium, a
group of pharmaceutical companies and universities. The
federally-funded Human Genome Project has also identified about a
half-million SNPs.
</P>
<P>
   The SNP data has been flowing out of these institutions for
months, and already has produced fruit. In a breakthrough announced
Tuesday, researchers in Chicago and Houston identified a gene
associated with Type 2 diabetes, which affects 14 million
Americans. The researchers examined a group of Mexican-Americans
from Texas that have a high incidence of Type 2 diabtetes, and
noticed most shared the same SNPs. Using the SNPs as guideposts,
they zeroed in on the guilty gene.
</P>
<P>
   At the Whitehead Institute alone, SNP-based research into the
genetic roots of several mental illnesses, asthma, heart disease
and inflammatory bowel disease is ongoing. Almost every major
disease is being approached similarly at laboratories worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Isolating the genes behind a disease does not guarantee a cure.
The gene for cystic fibrosis has been known for a decade but no
treatment has been forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 million suspected SNPs, the Whitehead Institute-led
effort is likely to stop its work once about a fifth have been
identified. Individual researchers and companies will work on the
rest, as they seek to better understand specific diseases. The
current SNP data gives them a general idea of where on the vast
genome to look.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Variagenics Inc., just a stone's throw from the
Whitehead Institute in Kendall Square, is using the SNP method to
research cancer, cardiovascular disease and other diseases
associated with aging. Using the SNP Consortium data as a starting
point, they identified thousands of other SNPs on the narrower
portions of the genome their work is focused on.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Dykes, vice president for research at Variagenics, noted
that SNP-based science is in its infancy: most companies and
researchers have the capability to do studies that examine only a
handful of SNPs but the majority of diseases are suspected to
involve hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to predict which will bear fruit first,'' said
Dykes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
