<SLUG> BC-AIDS-IMMUNITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY TREATMENT CAN SHORTEN AIDS DRUG REGIMEN, RESEARCHERS FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ HIV-infected patients who begin drug treatment early
enough can restore their own disease-fighting systems to the point
where they can at least temporarily stop taking the life-saving
drugs, researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That finding offers dramatic hope to those vigilant enough to
catch the disease at its beginning stages, making it more essential
than ever for individuals at risk to watch for telltale signs. And
it offers critical clues to rebuilding the shattered immune systems
of those with full-blown AIDS, suggesting they someday might mount
their own defense against the deadly virus.
</P>
<P>
   All eight patients in the study were able to suppress the virus
for at least a few months after they went off the drug therapy, and
five of the eight still are off after more than eight months. The
research was spurred by hopes raised by four men who have survived
HIV for more than 20 years, including Robert Massie, an Episcopal
priest who was the Democratic nominee for lieutenant governor in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first definitive evidence that the immune system
can work against this virus. . .it offers an incredible hope,''
says Dr. Eric Rosenberg, an infectious disease specialist at
Massachusetts General and lead author of the study published the
current journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bigger hope is that we can get smart enough to figure out
how to translate these findings into effective therapy for those
with chronic infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading AIDS researchers around the world responded
enthusiastically to the Massachusetts findings. ``It's extremely
logical and very encouraging, it looks like this approach is
working,'' said Dr. Andrew McMichael, professor of immunology at
the University of Oxford. ``The hope is that with a little
assistance the immune system might be able to control the infection
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's subjects are even more enthused, saying it is a
psychological relief to know their body is battling the virus on
its own and a physical relief to be off drugs whose side effects
range from nausea to nightmares. ``Now my body is controlling
this,'' says Mike Burns, a 38-year-old Boston executive who has
been off his anti-AIDS drug cocktail for nearly a year now as part
of the Massachusetts General experiment and has barely any virus
detectable in his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeroing in on the immune system is attacking the heart of the
disease, which as its name _ human ``immunodeficiency virus,'' _
suggests works by undermining the body's disease-fighting network.
The Massachusetets General researchers use military models to
explain how they have approached their task.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a virus invades the body, whether it's measles, flu or
HIV, the immune system generates a set of ``T helper cells''
programmed to respond to that virus. The cells act like an army
general, orchestrating the body's counterattack. What makes HIV an
especially ferocious enemy, however, is that it kills off the
AIDS-specific generals before they can launch their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Massie and other long-term survivors the generals not
only were alive and well, they were there is large numbers beating
back the virus, a fact that intrigued the Massachusetts General
researchers and encouraged them to find ways of rescuing generals
in other HIV patients. In a paper published in 1997 they reported
that they had done just that in six patients. All were detected at
an early stage, and all used the three-drug cocktail for AIDS to
build a shield over the generals so they could effectively lead an
attack against the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years the scientists have taken their
research a step further, weaning a group of patients from the drugs
to see if the generals really can fight off the disease on their
own. Results on a preliminary patient were encouraging enough that
doctors enrolled eight others. While the virus initially spiked in
all eight, requiring most to resume their drugs, all eventually
were able to control the virus on their own. One later had to go
back on drugs and two others opted to, but the remaining five are
approaching a year without drugs and with very low levels of the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed you can manipulate the immune system to get control
of the virus, at least transiently. We don't know yet whether these
subjects who are off the therapy will do well over the next 20
years but they appear to be doing great now,'' said Dr. Bruce
Walker, senior author of the study and director of the Partners
AIDS research center at Massachusetts General.
</P>
<P>
   This study makes even clearer how important it is for anyone who
might be exposed to HIV to watch for early symptoms, since it is
vital that drug treatment be launched before their immune systems
are badly damaged. Early signs of infection often mirror those of
mononucleosis or the flu, and include fever, sore throats, swollen
glands, and splotchy red rashes. The collection of symptoms
generally is serious enough to require patients to miss work,
although they all disappear relatively quickly and further signs of
AIDS may not turn up for as long as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone does have symptoms like those and is at any risk at
all of HIV, they should alert their health care provider and that
provider should always think of HIV,'' warned Rosenberg. ``I can't
begin to tell you how many patients have come to us after seeing
two or three other providers who never thought of this diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings offer immediate hope to a limited group of HIV
patients, suggesting they may someday be able to stop taking the
potent drugs that can produce diarrhea, fatigue, tingling around
the mouth, nausea and, in some cases, protruding bellies, humped
backs and rising levels of a dangerous form of cholesterol. The
Massachusetts General researchers warn, however, that the drugs are
life-saving and no one should go off them until further research is
done and their doctors say it is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The study also raises other longer-term hopes _ that, for
instance, a new generation of ``generals'' can be trained in people
who have been infected for long enough that their current T helper
cells have been wiped out. It also it teaches scientists enough
about the level of immunity needed to battle the virus that they
have a more precise target to aim for in trying to develop a
vaccine against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Still, huge leaps will be required to help those Americans with
long-term infection, not to mention the 95 percent of infected
individuals who live in poor countries where drug therapies are too
expensive and early detection is even tougher to realize. Even in
the developed world, larger studies will be needed that compare
this treatment approach to others and to see how long patients can
stay off the drugs without the virus coming back, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those limits, said Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the
National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, ``this still
is an important proof of the concept that you can indeed enhance
the immune response to HIV in a selected group of people. It's an
important observation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
