r l BC-MOODSPA-TEX     09-27 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOODSPA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET MAKEUP; THE ``NOW WOMAN'' WANTS MORE _ NOW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CATHERINE NEWTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trend-spotters, soothsayers and pundits take note: Paula McClure
and her Mood Spa just may be the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no. This isn't a story about the luxurious
soak-away-your-troubles spot that the former Emmy-winning co-host
of ``Good Morning Texas'' opened almost two years ago in the heart
of Dallas' tony Uptown district. It isn't about that spa's high-end
massages and exfoliations and oxygen-boosting facials and seaweed
body wraps that have attracted the likes of Sharon Stone, Erykah
Badu and Charley Pride. This isn't even about the line of mood
candles (dubbed Balance, Creativity and Uninhibited) and other
take-home spa products that the aromatherapy-schooled McClure
developed for her clientele.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of a smart, thirtysomething businesswoman and
what she realized as she sat at the front door of that spa every
day for a year and became, as she says, ``everyone's best
girlfriend.'' What she understood is this: The women seeking refuge
in Texas Pecan Peppermint Sugar Scrubs wanted more. Way more than
quick-fix, feel-good pampering. They wanted a feeling of control
over their lives. They wanted to feel empowered.
</P>
<P>
   So busy spa owner McClure got busier. And one year and two weeks
later, she had A Plan. This is the story of that Plan, which, if it
succeeds, would make McClure the Mary Kay-meets-Oprah of the
millennium. This is the story of McClure and her vision and why her
new personal growth company, also called Mood Spa, just may be the
Next Big Thing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This begins like many interviews. Two women, wearing suits, face
each other across a modern, clean-lined desk. The office is simply
decorated. The desk holds a laptop on one end, a phone, a few
well-organized papers and a ``Wall Street Journal Weekend Journal''
article on ``The New-Economy Family.'' The simple shelves on one
wall display photos and awards (some for McClure's television work,
one from the Justice Department commending her for her outstanding
participation this spring in Women's History Month). There's also a
collection of books, not so well-organized and giving the
impression of being in use. ``Women's Bodies, Women's Wisdom. The
Complete Book of Essential Oils and Aromatherapy. Low-fat Lies. The
Joy of Simple Living.''
</P>
<P>
   McClure is polite. Very professional and TV-personality poised.
I'm set to go over the basic background information on her life.
She grew up in Dallas and went to Southern Methodist University.
She began her career as an anchor and weather reporter for Fox,
then became a celebrity correspondent on ``Entertainment Tonight.''
Then it was six years on the fashion and beauty beat for ABC's
``The Home Show.'' Then more TV in LA. Gigs on ``Lifestyles of the
Rich and Famous'' and ESPN's ``Lifestyle Magazine.'' Appearances on
``Murphy Brown'' and ``The Garry Shandling Show.'' Movie roles,
including the news anchor in ``Total Recall.'' Check. Check. Check.
Nod. Nod. Nod. A lifetime in television that ended in 1998 when
McClure married retired Army Maj. Gen. Hugh G. Robinson,
megabusinessman and A.H. Belo Corp. board member, and left her
position at WFAA's ``Good Morning Texas'' to open the spa. (Belo is
WFAA's parent company.)
</P>
<P>
   But then McClure's assistant comes in the room with a videotape
_ and the mood at the Mood Spa corporate office shifts
dramatically. He has McClure's demo tape, the one that she'll send
around the country to prove to news producers and other television
big shots that McClure is good on camera, that she'll be a good
interview as she promotes her Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaaaaaah!'' McClure wails as the tape begins to roll on her
office television, showing snippets of McClure with Oprah Winfrey
(who raves about the Mood Spa concept) and McClure with Barbara
Walters (the ``GMT'' interview that led to McClure's Emmy).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate seeing myself on TV!'' McClure screams, covering her
face and laughing, and suddenly she's not a big-shot TV
personality, she's someone just like, well, me.
</P>
<P>
   And the interview takes its first surprising step toward
becoming a girlfriends' chat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, McClure is painting a picture for me. It's a
team of thousands upon thousands of strong, happy women across the
country, driving the black Range Rovers they've earned through
their success in Mood Spa System sales. They are the Mary Kay
ladies of the millennium, getting women together to talk about
moods, talk about mood spa products _ and, most of all, talk about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They are Mood Spa party hostesses, the front line in the Mood
Spa empowerment network that McClure has envisioned and made
happen.
</P>
<P>
   They are the big-dream part of the Plan.
</P>
<P>
   And how will she get there?
</P>
<P>
   McClure's got a product: a 30-day plan with a mood journal and
four inspirational tapes that takes women step by step through the
process of creating what she calls ``a mood of balance.'' She's got
a high-powered president. Barbara Hyder was most recently CEO of
e-commerce giant Gloss.com and a former regional president at Mary
Kay known for her ability to drive sales and profits. McClure's
also got an infomercial and an interactive Web site (''It's my
beeebeee!'' McClure says, as she calls up the site on her laptop)
and has begun to take the mood show on the road with the Paula
McClure Life Balance Seminar Series.
</P>
<P>
   But all this is just the necessary skeletal frame for McClure's
new creation. What will give it life _ propel the Mood Spa System
beyond the quotidian sea of inspirational chatter in which America
is swimming _ is that McClure is plugged squarely into the
zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   Self-help is, of course, in. Home parties a la Pampered Chef are
in. Balance is in. And life makeovers are way, way in. (Personal
coach Cheryl Richardson, author of the 1998 bestseller ``Take Time
for Your Life'' (Broadway Books, $13) appeared this week on ``The
Oprah Winfrey Show'' pitching her newest offering: ``Life
Makeovers'' (Broadway Books, $21.95). Richardson is also the head
of Winfrey's dream team charged with producing a new series for
Oprah called ``Lifestyle Makeovers.'') And heaven knows that Oprah
is as in as you can get, assuring success to most everything she
touches. And McClure is onto all of these things, including, of
course, Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Home spas are also in. Faith Popcorn,
guru of business and personal trends, assures us in her new book
``EVEolution: The Eight Truths About Marketing to Women''
(Hyperion, $24.95) that such pampering products are in for women of
the future, using this formula: X (more stress) and Y (more cash)
equals Z (more ways to relax). The savvy millennial marketer,
Popcorn writes, will anticipate what women want before they have to
ask. And women, she says, want to relax. And connect. Connection is
in.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-coms (ivillage, oxygen, chickclick _ and now moodspa) where
women share their ideas are in. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As McClure explains her Plan, I begin to understand that events
in the cosmos may indeed be lined up to assure her success. But a
funnier thing happens in our two-hour, two-woman forum.
</P>
<P>
   We get off-topic. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   We discover we're two 38-year-old working women with a lot in
common. We talk about dumping toxic friends, pleasing our fathers,
overworking, men, taking career chances, learning to say no, men,
mutual friends, her former elementary school that my kids now
attend, a mutual literary agent friend, interracial relationships _
and did I say men? We're talking about the things that try to knock
us off balance in our personal lives _ and the solutions we've
found for keeping our own selves intact.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's been by design and McClure is the ultimate
saleswoman or simply because McClure is ``onto something,'' she has
proven her point.
</P>
<P>
   She does know what women want.
</P>
<P>
   Women want to connect.
</P>
<P>
   And when I leave the interview, carrying my new black Mood Spa
bag and feeling almost as energized as if I've been through the spa
itself, which is visible across the street through McClure's office
window, I know it's more than the effect of the Creativity candle
we've had burning during our girlfriendy chat. I feel empowered.
</P>
<P>
   What can the Mood Spa System give women?
</P>
<P>
   A chance to connect with each other, to chat about life and love
and relationships and whatnot, away from the planned PTA meetings
and soccer-game sidelines and Bible studies and book clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Kay can give women blue eye shadow,'' McClure says with a
laugh. ``I can give them no blue days!''
</P>
<P>
   And if that's true, I don't need to be the one to tell you.
</P>
<P>
   McClure's Mood Spa will be the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
