<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANIC-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OF PANIC HOPES TO PREVENT TRAGEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GARETH COOK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the world, wherever large groups gather, people have
witnessed the mysterious power of panic.
</P>
<P>
   In July 12 people died at a soccer match in Zimbabwe. A month
earlier, nine fans were crushed to death at a Pearl Jam concert in
Denmark. And several times in the last decade, Muslim pilgrims
making the holy journey to Mecca have metamorphosed into sprawling,
deadly human stampedes _ all seemingly without reason.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a team of scientists say they have built a powerful
computer program that, for the first time, solves the mystery of
how crowds move under pressure, a program that will help architects
and emergency planners prevent panics in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past studies, which tried to understand the mentality of
the mob, the new simulation suggests that human traffic jams are
almost as predictable as the motion of the planets. The human
tendency to follow the crowd, and to push when stressed, can
unleash forces powerful enough to bend steel or topple brick walls,
the authors say, unless architects redesign public spaces to create
a smooth flow of people even when they panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an elegant and important study,'' said Seth Lloyd, an
associate professor of mechanical engineering at MIT. ``It will
even save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As the world grows more crowded and connected, scientists are
increasingly confronted with complex phenomenon _ stock market
crashes, traffic jams that arise for no clear reason _ which emerge
when large numbers of individuals interact. The crowd study is part
of an ambitious attempt undertaken over the last decade to harness
cheap computing power to decipher the forces that drive these
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest surprise is that panic and human behavior can be
understood in terms of a physics model,'' said Dirk Helbing, one of
the researchers who developed the program, which is described in
current journal Nature. ``Before people believed that interactions
in crowds could only be understood in psychological terms.''
</P>
<P>
   In one famous example, after 11 fans were crushed to death at a
1979 Who concert in Cincinnati, the incident was blamed on ``mob
psychology,'' on mind-altering drugs, and even on a strong vein of
uncaring in the youth of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But the new research argues that the blame lies elsewhere.
Researchers know that, if people are brought close together, they
tend to push on each other. They also know that people have a
tendency, especially in emergencies, to follow others near them, on
the assumption that those around them know more.
</P>
<P>
   When Helbing programmed these kinds of pedestrian forces into a
computer, the result is a flowing dance of flickering dots, each
representing a person trying to make their way.
</P>
<P>
   In one scenario, as people in a room start to push too hard at
an exit, the screen shows a kind of human turbulence develop, and
it takes more time for the dots to escape. In another simulation,
Helbing reported that the number of people able to leave a ``smoky
room'' dropped from 74 to 58 as the tendency to herd, called the
``panic parameter,'' increased.
</P>
<P>
   An even more unexpected result, Helbing said, was that a
well-placed narrow column in front of an exit allowed more people
to escape because people in the back of a crowd could not place as
much pressure on those trying to get out. It's an architectural
concept, he said, that he hopes to patent.
</P>
<P>
   Helbing, a professor at the Dresden University of Technology in
Dresden, Germany, built the simulation in cooperation with two
Hungarian researchers, Illes Farkas and Tamas Vicsek.
</P>
<P>
   One scientist criticized the study for not refining the model
with more precise observations of how pedestrians interact.
</P>
<P>
   ``These parameters need to be calibrated against data,'' said
Moshe E. Ben-Akiva, an MIT professor who has spent years gathering
that kind of information on Boston drivers for a simulation of
traffic flows through the Central Artery. Gathering that data, he
said, ``is the really hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ben-Akiva said that one of his colleagues, an
analyst with the New York state government, has set up a video
camera to record the streams of people that form in Grand Central
station during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers, said MIT's Lloyd, are exploring how herding
phenomenon _ where information is limited, and people follow the
decisions of others _ could help explain everything from the flow
of Internet traffic to the sudden popularity of Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   For fires, though, the theoretical work has produced a piece of
practical advice. The mistake most people make is to follow the
biggest group, Helbing said, which can draw them into dangerous
traffic jams. But it would also be a mistake to completely ignore
what others are doing, because someone else might discover a good
exit before you do. Instead, he said, the best thing to do is to
``follow small groups.''
</P>
<P>
   That is advice, he said, which could work just as well for
picking movies, or cars, or a place to live. The biggest rewards,
he said, come to those who watch trends closely, but aren't afraid
to buck them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
