</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PIPELINE-ART-1205(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PIPELINE IS EXPECTED TO CARRY ARCTIC GAS TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Canada)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INUVIK, Northwest Territories _ For three decades, geologists
probing beneath the Arctic Ocean near here and in offshore Alaska
have mapped the largest known untapped reserves of natural gas in
North America: 165 trillion cubic feet, seven times as much as the
United States will consume this year.
</P>
<P>
   But with gas prices low, indigenous opposition high and
environmental issues looming, energy companies never found a way to
build pipelines to send the gas south to heat homes and to generate
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   This is changing as fast as it takes to read a home heating
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale prices for natural gas have doubled over the last
year, and industry analysts expect that the 55 million Americans
who heat their homes with gas will pay 25 percent to 40 percent
more than they did last winter. And with the Department of Energy
forecasting that demand for natural gas in the United States will
rise by 40 percent in the next two decades, prices may go higher
still.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, native groups that once opposed development of
the big gas fields near here now see chances for economic
development, and are campaigning for royalties and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After a winter of planning and politicking, energy companies,
pipeline operators and Indian tribes expect to announce next spring
plans to build a subterranean pipeline, or possibly two, to carry
Arctic gas to North America's pipeline grid.
</P>
<P>
   Building two pipelines, one from Alaska along the Trans-Alaska
oil pipeline and Alaska-Canada Highway, and the other from Canada's
Northwest Territories, along the Mackenzie River valley, would cost
$10 billion and take seven years.
</P>
<P>
   While pipeline company executives say they are confident they
can finance and engineer the projects, environmental problems
remain unresolved and some conservation groups vow to oppose the
plans. Development also portends radical change for isolated places
like this one-stoplight town, where sled dogs' barks herald the
long arctic night and the northernmost road in North America trails
off into tundra.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments in favor of tapping the gas fields echo those heard
three decades ago, when the United States debated building the
Trans-Alaska Pipeline to move crude oil south from Prudhoe Bay. The
theme is self-reliance in energy in a world buffeted by higher oil
prices orchestrated by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't dependent on OPEC for gas,'' said K. Terry Koonce,
president of Exxon Mobil Production Co. ``Gas is up to us Americans
to bring about.''
</P>
<P>
   Often called a ``continental commodity,'' natural gas consumed
in the United States comes from North America and is delivered by
pipelines. Canada, which doubled its exports to the United States
in the 1990s, now supplies 16 percent of U.S. consumption, and
Canadian executives expect exports to the United States to grow by
50 percent this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, as brownouts hit California and electricity bills
jumped in New York, consumers and politicians started demanding new
power plants. But with natural gas the fuel of choice for 90
percent of power plants now built in the United States, few people
asked the follow-up question: With demand already outstripping
supply, where is this gas for these plants going to come from?
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy predicts that consumption will increase
to 31.5 trillion cubic feet a year by 2020, largely because it is a
relatively clean fuel. Gas, when burned, produces only one-third
the carbon dioxide for each unit of energy of coal, and two-thirds
as much as oil.
</P>
<P>
   While high prices led energy companies to double their
exploration efforts in the United States over the last year,
industry executives do not expect production in the lower 48 states
to pace consumption. Energy companies and consumer groups see
arctic reserves as crucial to meet future needs.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who bitterly opposed the Trans-Alaska oil
pipeline in the 1970s, are split over building gas pipelines in the
Arctic. Greenpeace opposes them, saying Americans should wean
themselves off fossil fuels and invest the billions of dollars it
would take to build pipelines in alternative energy sources like
solar and wind.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups, recognizing that gas pollutes less than oil, plan
to focus on reducing the environmental impact of the lines by
pushing to have them follow the existing Alaska oil pipeline and
the Alaska-Canada highway.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada and the United States, federal and local authorities
will have to approve drilling plans and pipeline construction, but
industry executives said the rising price of gas makes their case
for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, consumers are going to make a lot of
pressure to have this gas flow to the lower 48,'' said Michael E.
Phelps, president of WestCoast Energy Inc. WestCoast is working
with TransCanada PipeLines Ltd. to build a gas pipeline from Alaska
to Alberta, Canada, where it would tie into existing lines south to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some development has already begun, particularly in Alaska,
where companies have been pumping oil from under Prudhoe Bay for
over two decades and sending it south through the Trans-Alaska
Pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, too, has moved ahead. Chasing what Canadians call
``frontier gas,'' the first pipeline nosed ``North of 60'' in May.
This small link, connecting gas fields in Fort Liard, Northwest
Territories, to the continent's pipeline grid, crossed a
psychological barrier, the 60th Parallel, a line on maps that
separates the settled southern provinces from frontier northern
territories.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada's first commercial gas development north of the Arctic
Circle, Inuvik Gas Ltd. started pumping natural gas one year ago to
houses in this town of 3,500 people on the banks of the Mackenzie
River.
</P>
<P>
   The company is jointly owned by Enbridge Inc. and AltaGas
Services Inc. of Calgary and Inuvialuit Petroleum Corp. The
Inuvialuit company is wholly owned by the Inuvialuit people, one of
two main native groups in this corner of the Canadian Arctic. Their
participation represents an about-face in native attitudes about
energy development here.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, tribal chiefs up and down the Mackenzie River
Valley spoke out against any gas or oil development and obtained a
court-imposed 10-year moratorium that stopped work during the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no offices for our chiefs, no telephones,'' recalled
Stephen Kakfwi, a member of the Dene tribe who fought the pipelines
25 years ago. ``Of our people, 75 percent were trappers. They
weren't involved in the process. We had no understanding of the way
that the government of Canada worked. We had no business
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, the federal and territorial
governments settled virtually all native land claims in the valley,
giving tribes legal standing to negotiate rents and royalties.
Today, tribes own drilling companies and negotiate exploration
royalty payments with multinational companies. Kakfwi is now
premier of the Territory.
</P>
<P>
   In January, chiefs of all 30 tribes in the region unanimously
approved a joint statement ``to build a business partnership to
maximize ownership and benefit of a Mackenzie Valley pipeline.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Their representatives, the Aboriginal Working Group, which is
seeking a majority stake in a pipeline, has hired the aboriginal
banking unit of the Bank of Montreal to secure job guarantees, job
training, service contracts and rent payments from pipeline
companies. In May, Kakfwi flew to Calgary, Alberta, where he
pitched the pipeline to the Canadian Energy Pipeline Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed? We are now in control, the majority of the
territorial legislature is aboriginal,'' Kakfwi said in
Yellowknife, the territorial capital. ``The nations have got their
own land back. They have businesses. They have money.''
</P>
<P>
   With energy company engineers studying three possible routes
from the Arctic Ocean to existing pipelines in Alberta, some
environmentalists question spending billions of dollars to
perpetuate North America's dependency on fossil fuels. They stress
that arctic gas would only feed U.S. needs for less than one
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drilling for new oil, or putting in natural gas pipelines, is
not how we are going to get energy security,'' said Melanie Duchin,
a member of Greenpeace. ``Rather than opening up a fossil-fuel
frontier, such as trying to drill for these immense natural gas
reserves, the money should go for developing renewable energy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Canadian Arctic, however, Greenpeace has little
credibility with aboriginal leaders. They say the group's anti-fur
campaigns destroyed their traditional hunting and trapping
economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people were Stone Age people 30 years ago,'' Kakfwi said.
``We have embarked on a journey and we can't turn back. To say,
`You should be a happy little tree hugger, choking rabbits, while
everyone else exploits your diamonds and gas' _ no, I don't think
so.''
</P>
<P>
   In her office a block from Inuvik's stoplight, Nellie J.
Cournoyea, chairman of the Inuvialuit Regional Corp., dismissed
environmentalists' objections. ``If these people want to be useful,
they should start cleaning up the south, stop the pollution that is
damaging to the arctic wildlife and environment,'' she said,
referring to windborne soot and smog.
</P>
<P>
   With northern native support solid and southern consumer support
expected to solidify after this winter's home heating bills go out,
the race is now on to to see who builds an arctic gas pipeline
first.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14, rival companies presented proposals in Washington
for a pipeline through Alaska to the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, which is run by Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska.
Forrest Hoglund, chairman of Arctic Resources Co. of Houston, said
the multibillion-dollar race to build a gas line out of the Arctic
was the 21st-century ``equivalent of the first railroad to
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Alaskans are eager to see a gas pipeline built, because oil
production on the North Slope near Prudhoe Bay dropped by half in
the 1990s. As royalties dwindle, Alaskans face big tax increases in
five years if there is no gas development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska is extremely interested in getting the gas out,''
Koonce, the Exxon Mobil executive, said after testifying in
Washington. ``Frankly, we are, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Eskew, a spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, said
the Republican presidential candidate did not have a position on
the pipeline proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of an Alaskan route said they could start pumping gas
south in six years. They said they could work so quickly because
permits and an international regulatory framework have existed
since the late 1970s to place a gas pipeline parallel to the
Trans-Alaska oil pipeline, and then east, along the Alaska-Canada
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, improved telecommunications, high-speed
mechanized welding and the use of rock saws to cut permafrost have
combined to make pipeline building faster and cheaper than ever,
said Phelps, the executive at WestCoast, one of the companies
planning to build a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The route using the Alaska pipeline and highway makes sense,
because you are not dividing the wilderness any further; you are
using existing corridors,'' said Charles M. Clusen, an Alaska
policy analyst for the Natural Resources Defense Council, a New
York-based environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for BP Amoco, one of the largest gas owners in
Alaska, have said they expect to make a decision on building a gas
pipeline by the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1,700-mile Alaska-Yukon route, with a price tag around
$8 billion, would leave the Canadian arctic gas reserves stranded.
</P>
<P>
   To link the two reserves, other companies have proposed a
second, $3 billion pipeline up the Mackenzie River valley and 300
miles west to Prudhoe, 15 feet below the floor of the Arctic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Although this route could provide cheaper gas to consumers,
environmentalists oppose a submerged line, saying it could endanger
caribou and polar bear populations. Many Alaskans oppose a
submarine pipeline because it would deprive their towns and cities
of piped natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   In March, four major companies that own gas in the Canadian
Arctic _ Imperial Oil Ltd., Gulf Canada Resources Ltd., Shell
Canada Ltd. and Mobil Oil Canada Ltd. _ plan to release results of
a feasibility study for a Mackenzie Valley pipeline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
