<SLUG> BC-FLEET-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY FLEETBOSTON-SUMMIT BANCORP DEAL IN THE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Terrence Murray, the shopaholic chief executive of
FleetBoston Financial Corp., has reportedly settled on his next big
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Fleet is in acquisition talks with New Jersey's
Summit Bancorp swirled in banking cirles Wednesday, sending Fleet
shares lower but giving Summit's a boost for the second day in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies declined to fuel the speculation with any
comments, but analysts who cover the industry were happy to stoke
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies are being very quiet about this, almost
strangely so, which suggests to me a high probability that the
talks are serious,'' said Steven Wharton, who covers Fleet for
Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. ``Besides, it's a deal that would make sense
for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Summit's 500 branches and $39 billion in assets are scattered
throughout Connecticut, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania. That fits
nicely with Fleet's 1,200 branches and $180 billion in assets in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   There is some overlap between the two companies in New Jersey,
which would give Fleet a chance to save money by consolidating
operations. UBS Warburg analyst Mike Poldwick figures that a
combined Fleet/Summit could operate in the state with costs 20
percent lower than the two manage separately.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, the largest bank in New England, would also become the
biggest bank in New Jersey with the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleet likes to be the big player in a market, and it's almost
at a point where it needs to fish or cut bait in New Jersey,''
Poldwick said. ``That problem would be instantly solved if this
deal goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Summit has also made far less money from bank fees than most of
its competitors, which has weighed on its stock price for years.
Analysts said they expect Fleet, which drew protests locally when
it increased fees after taking over BankBoston Corp. last year, to
similarly boost fee revenues if it acquires Summit.
</P>
<P>
   From Summit's side of the coin, the advantages of a potential
deal are easier to see and quicker to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Since word of the negotiations leaked Monday, Summit has seen
its stock price jump from $27.75 to $34.31 _ a 24 percent increase.
Jason Goldberg, who covers Summit for Lehman Brothers, said Fleet
would probably have to pay $37 to $39 per share to acquire its
smaller rival, giving shareholders yet another pop.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldberg cautioned that the deal could still fall through if
the companies can't agree on price. A decade of consolidation in
the banking industry came to a screeching halt in the past couple
of years, he said, primarily because too many banks paid too much
money to make deals happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are a lot more careful these days about the
numbers,'' Goldberg said. ``This deal makes sense at the right
price, but I certainly wouldn't count it as a sure thing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet shares fell nearly 5 percent Tuesday, but recovered
Wednesday to close at $39, up 31 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
