<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-OBJECTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MUSEUM-CLASS HOUSE THAT POST TOASTIES BUILT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Why, you live like a queen, don't you?'' was the
comment of Queen Maude of Norway to Marjorie Merriweather Post.
Post did indeed, and she filled Hillwood, her home-museum at 4155
Linnean Avenue NW, which has just reopened, with a battalion of
royal objects. Her collection of imperial Russian art from the 18th
and 19th centuries is the greatest in the world outside Russia, and
she had one of the leading U.S. collections of Sevres porcelain,
much of it commissioned by Catherine the Great.
</P>
<P>
   Her 19th-century red Aubusson rug was a gift from Emperor
Napoleon III of France to the ill-fated Emperor Maximilian of
Mexico. Post lore has William Randolph Hearst (another American
with a castle complex) as a onetime owner of the rug. But somehow
it ``never got to San Simeon,'' said Ann Odom, the chief curator
and deputy director of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Hillwood, which Post bought in 1955, after her third divorce,
sits on 25 acres at the edge of Rock Creek Park. Half the grounds
are wooded and half are formal gardens. Besides the main house,
which was shut for a three-year, $9 million renovation including
some of the grounds, there are a dacha with Russian artifacts and
an Adirondacks lodge with American Indian material.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great party house,'' said Frederick J. Fisher,
director of what is now the Hillwood Museum. ``She was a great
entertainer in Washington, with one room designed for movies and
dances.''
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Merriweather Post was born into a family that became
wealthy from Postum, Grape-Nuts and Post Toasties. She married and
divorced, in succession, a New York lawyer named Edward Close; E.F.
Hutton, the stockbroker (and father of her daughter Dina Merrill,
the actress); Joseph E. Davies, a Washington lawyer; and Herbert A.
May, a Pittsburgh industrialist. She took back her maiden name
after the last divorce, but kept the ``Mrs.'' When she died in
1973, her fortune was estimated at $200 million, the equivalent of
$769 million today.
</P>
<P>
   After husband No. 3, Davies, was appointed ambassador to the
Soviet Union, Post's collection of Russian furnishings and objets
d'art grew. Hillwood's two-story entrance hall is lined with
Russian portraits. ``They are almost all of the czars and czarinas,
talking to each other, having nice conversations,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Odum said, ``She had a fascination for porcelain and had
collected Sevres.'' Bulk purchases were needed: Post hauled out the
Sevres for her frequent dinner parties for 30.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the Post collection are its 90 works by Faberge,
especially Easter eggs, but also boxes, clocks, a walking-stick
handle made of gold, nephrite, diamonds and rubies and an ashtray
of silver, enamel and quartz that does not seem ever to have felt
the stub of a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   In the Icon Room is a large pink Faberge egg given by the last
czar, Nicholas II, to his mother in 1914. It is made of gold,
diamonds and pearls and decorated with enamel. Inside pearl-lined
frames are allegorical paintings, after Francois Boucher, depicting
the arts and the sciences. Fisher calls it ``the last of the really
beautiful eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of Hillwood, there is a present from Polina S.
Zhemchuzhina, the wife of Prime Minister Vyacheslav M. Molotov and
a Soviet official herself. As a parting gift, she allowed the
couple to choose from the Kuskovo ceramics museum. What they liked
were two vases made in 1836 at the Imperial Porcelain Factory in
St. Petersburg. They are 27 inches high and gilded to imitate gilt
bronze, with painted landscapes on their sides. Soviet officials
were probably sorry to see the couple leave, since Post bought much
imperial porcelain for her collection.
</P>
<P>
   Her divorce from Davies in 1955 forced her to split her Russian
collection with him, so she began buying replacements. After Davies
died in 1958, she bought pieces from his estate.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of her life, Post decided that her collection
should some day be made available to the public in a museum of the
decorative arts, and Hillwood was renovated with that in mind. She
consolidated pieces that had been at her 54-room triplex at 92nd
Street and Fifth Avenue in Manhattan, which was described in the
1920s as the largest apartment ever built, and at her Mar-a-Lago
estate in Palm Beach, Fla., (now in Donald Trump's hands), and put
them in Hillwood.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds around Hillwood are as carefully laid out as the
public spaces inside the main house. A formal Japanese garden (as
yet unrestored) was designed by Shogo Myaida, a Japanese-born
landscape architect, who designed the gardens at the 1939-40 New
York World's Fair, Jones Beach and the Brooklyn Botanic Garden. At
Hillwood, he deployed stone lanterns, tiny wooden bridges and a
stone pagoda. A parterre garden has also been rejuvenated with a
new fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Another garden, in the formal French style, has a ring of rose
bushes surrounding wax begonias and boxwood, which set off a 3-foot
pink stone pedestal topped by a 10-foot column. It is Post's
memorial, and her ashes are there.
</P>
<P>
   Those ashes are near a putting green (she had one at each of her
residences) and a planting of ivy. Even that has a claim to
grandeur. A nearby sign states, ``This ivy is from Buckingham
Palace, London, England.''
</P>
<P>
   Tours of the house and garden are by reservation only
(refundable deposit required: $10; those over 65, $8; students and
those under 18, $5). Only 250 people a day are allowed to visit the
museum, which is in a residential neighborhood; (202) 686-5807.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
