<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THAT'S LIFE' NEEDS MORE APPEAL TO BE A MUST-SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That's Life,'' a rare foray into musical comedy, lasted a
single season on ABC in the late '60s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a more conventional blue-collar sitcom by the same name
tanked after a few episodes and the star of the show, Gerry Red
Wilson, died later that year.
</P>
<P>
   If the third time is indeed a charm, the latest series to be
titled ``That's Life'' should bring CBS untold acclaim and fabulous
riches. If, on the other hand, the third time is merely
confirmation of a never-ending pattern, the players on ``That's
Life'' might want to be sure their resumes are updated and their
insurance premiums paid.
</P>
<P>
   One good sign: Lydia DeLucca isn't one to embrace
predestination. She has spent most of her 32 years fulfilling
expectations that weren't necessarily hers, and now she has decided
it's time to take control and make life happen on her own terms,
not her parents' or anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia is the main character in ``That's Life.'' A spunky woman
from a working-class Italian-American family, she has been dating
the same loser for eight years, works in a New Jersey barroom
pouring drinks for other losers, and desperately wants to avoid
ending up in the loser line herself. Her solution is to dump her
fiance and enroll in college on the theory that her mind is a
terrible thing to waste on a guy named Lou Buttafucco (Sonny
Marinelli), who only asked her to marry him after his microwave
went on the fritz and he figured he might score a new one if he got
engaged to Lydia and her friends threw her a bridal shower.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Paige Kent (``Jenny,'' ``Stark Raving Mad'') makes Lydia
accessible and likable, yet ``That's Life'' has the arm's-length
appeal of someone you enjoy seeing occasionally but wouldn't want
to pal around with.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia would probably blame her parents in such a situation. So
would I. Not that Ellen Burstyn and Paul Sorvino are bad actors.
Heaven knows the TV schedule could use more performers of their
caliber. But the pilot script has Burstyn and Sorvino firing blanks
into the scenery, creating characters that are like those life-size
cardboard cutouts you find in party-supply stores: good for one
laugh and then relegated to a far corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Life'' is more successful when Lydia is in school,
coping with the incredulous students who figure she must be a
divorcee on the make, or sparring with a prickly professor (Peter
Firth) over whom she holds enormous sway because of his
indiscriminate drinking habits.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Lydia's moments with her confused but supportive best
friends will resonate with anyone who's ever been the family
iconoclast struggling to make her own way. (They also may cause
viewers to wonder why Debi Mazar, who plays beautician Jackie
O'Grady, wasn't cast in the lead role. She's much more convincing
as a girl from the Jersey suburbs.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS is giving ``That's Life'' a nice launch this Sunday, right
after the season premiere of ``60 Minutes,'' probably because its
regular day and time _ Saturday at 8 _ is the TV equivalent of a
poke in the eye. If all those ``60 Minutes'' viewers who are
expecting to see ``Touched by an Angel'' at 8 o'clock aren't too
annoyed to find something else in its place, the thinking goes that
perhaps they'll sit back and enjoy ``That's Life'' and make plans
to tune in again on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, well, that's life in the suburbs, where the third
time is a charm only if the neighbors bother to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S LIFE
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: Series premiere of hourlong comedy/ drama about a
32-year-old woman who flouts convention and family tradition to
enroll in college
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Heather Paige Kent, Ellen Burstyn, Kristin Bauer, Peter
Firth, Kevin Dillon, Sonny Marinelli, Paul Sorvino and Debi Mazar
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Sunday night
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: CBS
</P>
<P>
   RATING: TV-PG
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
