<SLUG> BC-FLEET-QUICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TRYING A CLICKS-AND-MORTAR APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ FleetBoston Financial Corp. is seeking to expand in the
investment advice business.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston banking group has merged the 215 investment brokers
from its branches into its Quick &AMP; Reilly discount brokerage unit.
Quick &AMP; Reilly has 118 walk-in investor centers nationwide and 460
sales representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet said none of its brokers, who provide full-service
financial advice, will lose a job.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Fleet said, is to appeal both to investors who want
personal advice and to do-it-yourself investors who prefer to trade
online or over the phone, without input from a broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to this, we were a transaction-driven discount broker,''
said Don Froude, president of Quick &AMP; Reilly. ``We are looking to
be a much more advice- and judgment-driven firm.''
</P>
<P>
   With its new approach, Fleet is looking to exploit two sweeping
trends in the investment arena: the boom in online trading and the
rising demand for advice by wealthy investors.
</P>
<P>
   The company is embracing the clicks and bricks strategy that has
propelled industry giants, such as Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., Fidelity
Investments, and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities. Under
that strategy, the company will offer investors stocks, bonds,
mutual funds, and annuities, both remotely or in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The online brokerage space has evolved beyond simple, cheap
trades,'' said Matt Carrick, an analyst with Gomez Advisors. ``The
firms with the physical branches, the firms that can provide the
added planning and advice element, are one step ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is not the only company moving to expand its physical
presence in the era of the Internet. DLJ Direct recently opened a
walk-in center in Florida. E-Trade, which stepped up competition in
the online trading arena, this month opened its first office in a
Target department store in Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Quick &AMP; Reilly is the nation's fourth-largest discount broker,
behind Schwab, Fidelity, and TD Waterhouse. It has $41 billion of
assets in 1.3 million customer accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Not all investment firms have found walk-in centers to be
profitable. Dreyfus Corp. last year closed some 25 investor centers
to focus on broker sales of its funds instead of direct sales.
</P>
<P>
   Froude said profits aren't at issue in the Quick &AMP; Reilly branch
operation. ``We know it's a profitable strategy,'' he said.
``Very.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
