<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ZEN-FASHION-ART-2TAKE     09-27 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEN-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING A NEW FASHION FLAG ON THE WEB: THE REPUBLIC OF ZEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER HELLMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORTE MADERA, Calif. _ Zen is an upfront influence at the office
of ZoZa, a new fashion company set for its Web debut in
mid-October. Shoes are to be removed at the entrance and placed in
cabinets. A hefty Chinese gong stands ready to call meetings, and
there's a large empty swath of carpet for the staff's morning yoga
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ZoZa's high-tech stretchy clothes feature a symbol from the I
Ching that means both ``contemplation'' and ``mountain.'' Floating
across the screen at www.zoza.com will be a mini-swirl of
snowflakes; click on it for a kernel of Zen wisdom, like, ``Be
present, not tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Ziegler calls these aphorisms ``mind crackers.'' He and his
wife, Patricia, as ZoZa's co-founders, have even signed on a
genuine Zen master as consultant: Norman Fischer, retired abbot of
the San Francisco Zen Center, the largest of its kind in America.
``I have absolutely nothing to offer ZoZa,'' Fischer said, ``which
is what the Zieglers really love!''
</P>
<P>
   Zen minimalism is a far cry from the amusing, flashy icons of
Banana Republic, the Zieglers' first business, with its full-size
in-store giraffes and jungle jeeps poking through the display
windows. The couple began a retailing revolution 22 years ago a few
miles away in Mill Valley, with safari-style clothing stylishly
tweaked by Mrs. Ziegler, a former San Francisco Chronicle
illustrator, and promoted by a nifty catalog written by her
husband, an ex-Chronicle reporter. Hearing their name for the
business, a friend advised: ``Bad choice. You'll be picketed by
people from small hot countries.''
</P>
<P>
   No protesters picketed that first outpost in 1978, or at any of
the thundering herd of stores to come, jet-assisted by the wildly
popular movie ``Raiders of the Lost Ark.'' When the Zieglers
abruptly resigned in 1988, selling their interest in Banana
Republic, by then a unit of Gap Inc., it had 110 stores and was
ringing up annual sales of a quarter billion dollars. But customers
tired of the Indiana Jones look. Relations between the Zieglers and
the Gap's founder, Don Fisher, soured when the couple insisted on
publishing a travel magazine and began selling travel books in
their shops. (Fisher reportedly said that if he'd wanted to sell
books, he'd have bought Rand McNally.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem,'' Ziegler said, ``was that Patricia and I
were fundamentally unemployable.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in their 50s, the Zieglers are hitched to a speedy urban
rhythm with an accent on easy movement required by his dirt biking
and her daily yoga routine, which includes bends that even a tree
boa might envy. They're not averse to a touch of functional
elegance and even sophistication. The endless safari days are past.
</P>
<P>
   The Zieglers came away from the Gap divorce feeling tattered by
their far-from-smooth ride to moguldom. They retreated to the
foothills of Mount Tamalpais above Mill Valley, to a shingled
house, circa 1929, they have renovated _ doubling its interior
space and adding an aerie that is now a workout room. The project
cost $2 million; today the house is worth an estimated $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd first driven up to the place at night,'' Mrs. Ziegler
recalled. ``It reminded us of the Ahwannee Lodge in Yosemite
National Park, where we loved to stay. But the main thing is the
way the house was cradled by the mountain. We were pretty intimate
with the hiking trails up there. You could reach them directly out
the back door of this house without stepping on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Those trails were the Zieglers' first priority. A distant second
was the unobstructed view of San Francisco, 10 miles off. Often
fogged in by morning, the city scintillates like a distant jewel
box by night from the south-facing windows.
</P>
<P>
   Those ample windows, with their original steel frames, had also
caught Mrs. Ziegler's offbeat eye. ``They reminded me of windows in
artists' lofts in old industrial buildings,'' she explained. (In
the renovation, she looked far and wide to locate a firm that still
fabricated steel windows.) She oversaw much of the redesign, from
the minimalist redwood baseboards (she thought stock ones were
``too fancy'') to the new cedar shingles on the facade. The
Zieglers elected to use a labor-intensive, technique, a throwback
to the Arts and Crafts movement: hand-dipping each shingle in an
oil-based stain and then letting it air dry. The result, worthy of
Greene &AMP; Greene, is shingles that will shrink evenly as they age.
</P>
<P>
   The couple have filled the house with Mrs. Ziegler's paintings
and with folk art _ snakes and other reptiles preferred. Once,
while climbing in the Peruvian Andes, Mrs. Ziegler was suddenly
enveloped by a giant shadow. Looking up, she saw a gliding adult
condor, its wingspan easily twice her own length. Back home, she
sketched a condor's head and had it carved into the living room's
redwood beams. Wild creatures also abound in Mrs. Ziegler's
paintings. A tiny watercolor on a stairway wall shows elephants
dimly seen in a nocturnal march, their tusks reflecting moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Banana Republic, the Zieglers assumed they'd
be full-time homebodies and parents to Zio, now 12, and Aza, 8.
Even when Revlon came calling, asking the couple to start a new
line of natural cosmetics, they stayed put. When Aza's
third &UR; - &LR; grade teacher asked the class to describe what their
parents did, she reported that her mother painted and ``my daddy
rides his dirt bike in the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They studied Zen in the quiet time after Banana Republic, and
traded in their espresso machine for a teapot. ``We were attempting
to live our lives by sips instead of slurps,'' Ziegler said. Fine
tea was harder to find locally than fine coffee. So, with a young
business partner, the Zieglers created a new company in 1991,
naming it the Republic of Tea. The labels for the company's metal
tea canisters, handsome and practical, were painted by Mrs. Ziegler
while she was confined to bed during her second pregnancy. They
still incorporate the squat, black family teapot.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler named the teas and wrote the canister copy as
beguilingly as he had written Banana Republic's catalog. (In 1999,
the trade magazine Catalog World named Banana Republic's catalog
the best ever.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the company was sold to a Midwestern beverage bottler.
The Zieglers, who'd gotten this company up and running without ever
leaving home, celebrated the sale by buying the house next door and
converting it into a painting studio, play area and meditation
center.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had no intention of starting a third business. But
then, last summer, they got a phone call from Edward Strobin, their
old chief operating officer at Banana Republic _ and a loyalist in
their struggle with the Gap. ``Everyone else is making a bundle
with Internet start-ups,'' Strobin said. ``Why should we be left
out?''
</P>
<P>
   Last February, infused with $12 million by Softbank, the
Japanese venture capital giant, in return for a 20-percent stake in
the company, ZoZa was born. The Zieglers, who are majority
shareholders, say they ``seeded'' the company, but refuse to
disclose their investment. The couple insist they would never have
committed to a new business without Strobin to handle daily
operations. But they lost him in July to a swiftly attacking
cancer. ``It was too late to put on the brakes,'' Ziegler said.
``We had 40 people working for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ZoZa is a word that, like the names of the couple's children, is
a pure Zieglerism. Like Banana Republic, the company is spun out of
the couple's lifestyle of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The clothing _ 56 pieces in all _ is entirely made from the
newest hi-tech performance fabrics from Japan and Italy. Everyone
knows the mantra _ these are the fabrics that wick away sweat,
breathe, stretch with the body _ and the Zieglers are hardly unique
in upthinking them. But they found most true tech clothing too big,
too shapeless or too tight for spiffy segues from office to
see-and-be-seen bistro.
</P>
<P>
   ZoZa's declared mission is to bring maximum refinement of cut,
style and finish to a washable ready-to-wear line: ``Patagonia
crossed with Prada,'' is how one hopeful ZoZa marketing executive
puts it. Well, not quite. But there is a floor-length evening gown
with an oval cutout in back and a mermaid-like sweep back from the
feet. Seams wander with the wearer's curves, which are cradled in
built-in underwear. Made from Lycra swimsuit fabric, it comes
bundled in a small mesh sack. Stuff it into the glove compartment
in the morning on the way to work and pull it out, unwrinkled, to
slip on just before party time. If you get tossed in the pool, just
start swimming. The gown can even be washed in its sack.
</P>
<P>
   ZoZa seams attempt to go where the body goes _ especially in
enticing places like the small of the back. ``Patricia puts seams
where they have never gone before, but where they always should
have been,'' said Gale Parker, ZoZa's design director, formerly
head designer for Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan to sell ZoZa only as Web wear has been
scrapped. The first ZoZa ``walk-in Web site''is planned for later
this year in Mill Valley. Customers will be able to try on the
clothes, then order from in-store computers. An old-fashioned paper
catalog, sized like a CD case, is also pending, and there has been
interest from two retail giants to form a strategic alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Daniele Clutier, director of fashion research at the Institut
Francais de la Mode, in Paris, viewed the ZoZa Web site. ``Like
Banana Republic, ZoZa seems to promise fashion with a soul and a
strong personality,'' Clutier said. ``Postmodernist theory tells us
that we humans need meaningfulness, which we try to derive partly
from consumer objects, especially clothes. So it seems good for
ZoZa to have something to say beyond `We're nice and
fashionable.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is a tense time for the Zieglers, with Patricia getting out
the clothes and Mel working on the next round of financing. The
pair preserve their calm with a 30-minute commute to their new
``Zen house,'' situated on a bluff over the Pacific Ocean at
Stinson Beach. ``You won't see the house,'' Ziegler warned. ``It's
behind a redwood fence with a hidden gate.''
</P>
<P>
   After the elaborate, art-filled Mill Valley manse, the Zen
house, marked by a single Japanese lantern, comes as a bit of a
shock. It's a small place, sparsely furnished, with a garage that
has been converted to an art studio. But all artwork has been
banished. Mrs. Ziegler motioned to the big windows with their
sweeping vistas of the ocean and muscular hills where evergreen
trees alternate with straw-colored meadows. ``Those are our
paintings,'' Mrs. Ziegler said.
</P>
<P>
   The Zieglers insist that, if not for its relative isolation,
they'd prefer to live now full time in the ``squalor'' of the Zen
house rather than in the grander Mill Valley home. ``The difference
in the two homes is like the difference between Banana Republic and
ZoZa,'' Mrs. Ziegler explained. ``The Mill Valley is about romance.
It's hard to maintain. The Zen house is simple and really
functional, like ZoZa clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   On a bright late summer day, the Zieglers prepared to head to
San Francisco. Zio, Aza and a friend had already piled into the
rear of the family station wagon. Ziegler said, ``It's fun to be
working for ourselves again after years of working for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ziegler pointed to a large black duffel bag stuffed with
samples of ZoZa wear. ``Sometimes, something just coagulates in
midair,'' she said, ``and people say: `That's it! That's the spirit
of the age!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The cybercurtain is about to go up on ZoZa. Clicking rather than
clapping will determine whether, once again, the Zieglers can
transmute the spirit of this high-tech age into clothes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
