<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux approaches scoreless streak with same aplomb as he
pitches
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Poised on the brink of personal history, Greg Maddux
has prepared himself for the occasion with the same pomp and
circumstance that has made him one of baseball's most uncommon
characters.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. He spits. Then he pitches
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' Maddux said, his singular way of acknowledging
the 36-1/3-inning scoreless streak he takes into tonight's
Atlanta-New York finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. It's cool but that's it. It's nice to
have. It's better than talking about giving up 30 or 40 runs in 30
innings, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   So much for a rendezvous with destiny. There have only been
three longer scoreless streaks since 1988, when Orel Hershiser set
the major league record at 59 innings. Maddux can also win 20 games
for just the third time (and second as a Brave) in his remarkable
14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   And in keeping with his pulse-less approach to each game, the
streak, the 20 wins might as well belong to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to (win 20). Who wouldn't?'' he said. ``But I'll try
to pitch good and if I get it, great. If not, I'll get ready to
pitch in the playoffs. There's not a whole lot of options.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox and Maddux were still unsettled Wednesday on
how long Maddux might pitch, weighing his personal accomplishment
and the team's pursuit of the NL's best record against preserving
Maddux for the playoffs. But be sure Maddux's ambivalence about
tonight is not shared around the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 he gave up a career-high 258 hits last year and some
baseball minds felt the league had caught up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the middle of so-called struggling last year when
everyone was wondering what's going on, he can't literally turn it
up a notch because he's always at that perfect level,'' John Smoltz
said. ``But he's turned it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just right on. He's not making any mistakes at all. I
don't know if he'll tell you but he makes a lot of mistakes, just
like all of us do. But because of his perfection, he gets away with
them because the hitter doesn't expect it. Right now, he's just
pole-vaulted into an incredible run.''
</P>
<P>
   From June 19 through Aug. 18, Maddux won just four times in 12
starts. The Cy Young race was running without him while the Braves
stumbled through their worst August in 10 years. But since Aug. 22,
he is 6-1 while his ERA has plummeted to 2.91.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having him dealing like this is a huge lift,'' shortstop Walt
Weiss said. ``We got a couple of aces but when one of them is
throwing up zeroes, there's a domino effect that strengthens the
whole rotation. He's been just dominating.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is more wide-eyed than catcher Paul Bako, who assumed the
Maddux account July 22 and has been stunned that every pitch - the
two-seam fastball, the cutter, the slider, the change-up - is
working at peak efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys generally pitch to their strengths, but his strength is
using all those pitches,'' Bako said. ``He can go after a hitter in
any given way. He doesn't get a lot of credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   A 20th win would not only be the seconding speech for his Cy
Young candidacy, it would make the third time Maddux and Glavine
had won 20 or more in the same season. There have only been 15
staffs in the last half-century with twin 20-game winners. Only one
tandem (Warren Spahn and Lew Burdette in 1958 and 1959) were able
to repeat the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux and Glavine would be the first to do so three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have two guys win 20, you have to have a good team, you
need some good pitching and you need some luck,'' said John
Burkett, who with Billy Swift had 20-win years in San Francisco in
1993. ``You do it three times, that kind of throws luck out the
window, doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
