<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Netanyahu tries his hand as high-tech spokesman
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Benjamin Netanyahu, veteran of covert operations,
White House summits and global diplomacy, came to Atlanta this week
to talk technology.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial former prime minister of Israel was at the
Telco Systems booth Wednesday on the show floor of Networld+Interop
at the Georgia World Congress Center. Massachusetts-based Telco is
now a unit of BATM Advanced Communications, an Israeli company that
bought Telco from World Access of Atlanta and hired Netanyahu as a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Voted out of office in May 1999, Netanyahu declined Wednesday to
answer political questions except to say that he increasingly gets
them. ``I get asked a lot if I will re-enter politics and I
wouldn't have expected to be asked that so soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu won a chance at a political comeback Wednesday when
Israel's attorney general refused to prosecute him on corruption
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Police had suspected Netanyahu and his wife of conspiring with a
government contractor in a kickback scheme, illegally keeping
gifts, and obstructing justice, and they recommended the former
leader be tried. But in a statement, Attorney General Elyakim
Rubinstein cited ``difficulties with the evidence'' in making a
conviction of Netanyahu and his wife, Sara, unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   For Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who soundly defeated Netanyahu in
May 1999 elections, the announcement comes at a sensitive time.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's far-reaching peace proposals have lost him majority
support in Parliament, and Netanyahu's hard-line Likud party hopes
to force him out once Parliament reconvenes Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate that Prime Minister Ehud Barak would
handily defeat Netanyahu's successor as leader of the Likud Party,
Ariel Sharon. However, polls show Barak and Netanyahu in a dead
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu came to prominence as a spokesman for the Israeli
government, and he smiled when asked about his shift to corporate
front man. ``First of all, I had to make a living, and I was
approached by Zvi. We started working together _ It is a superb
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Zvi Marom, BATM founder and chief executive, is one of the
richest men in Israel. Shares of BATM have rocketed from less than
$2 to about $100 in two years.
</P>
<P>
   David LeBeau, Telco president, said the combination makes more
business sense than ownership by World Access. ``They are a service
provider and we sell to service providers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said the mesh of Israeli and U.S. culture has been
effective. ``We are aggressive, and they are aggressive. We both
want to win. And they are fast. If they don't know what to build
they'll build it anyway and then we'll tweak it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow contribued to this story
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
