<SLUG> BC-REUNITED0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Germany upbeat about reunification, says consul in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Next week, Germans will celebrate the 10th anniversary
of the reunification of their country.
</P>
<P>
   Their initial euphoria has long since given way to reality.
Tearing down the Berlin Wall was surprisingly easy. Creating a
unified people after decades of separation has proven more of a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from a visit to his country this month, Germany's
Atlanta-based consul general, Heinrich-Peter Rothmann, assessed the
situation in an interview this week. Here is an excerpt edited from
his comments:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the mood of the people you talked with on your trip?
</P>
<P>
   A: I found two things remarkable. First, the progress made in
Berlin (once again the seat of Germany's government). In every
respect, the city really is coming back to life. The other thing
for Germany in general is clearly a positive climate. We have a
reputation for seeing everything in a rather pessimistic way, but
in this case I think everybody shared the view that economically
it's going ahead. The new German government, half-term in its
electoral stage, has come forward with a few important reforms. We
have tax reform. ... The business community is now quite in line
with the government, ... (which) is a Social Democratic-Green
coalition and was seen in the beginning from the economic sector
with maybe some reservations. These have gone away. The business
community is quite satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On Tuesday, Germany will observe the 10th anniversary of
reunification. What has gone right and what has gone not so well
about that process of reuniting the former West and East Germany?
</P>
<P>
   A: Overall, we have accomplished very much. If you go and look
for yourself today at East Germany, as I have done, you will see
that the country has been transformed. We have not only built roads
and railroads but we've built cities, which were crumbling in the
old (Communist) system. We also have put in an infrastructure. For
instance, all of East Germany today has an optic fiber
communication network, which we don't even have in West Germany.
(But) there are still problems. Unemployment is probably the worst
... around 18 percent in East Germany and less than 9 percent in
the former West Germany. And there is no doubt that this money
coming out of West German pockets going over will still have to
flow for quite a while. Many of the politicians have also conceded
that when the unification came about they were too optimistic. Even
former Chancellor (Helmut) Kohl has very recently recognized that
he was too optimistic about the economic progress that East Germany
would make. This was, of course, a state-run economy that
functioned within the economy of the East bloc. We thought we could
just mend or repair or restructure it, but the East German economy
was so structurally inefficient that we had to tear it down in
order to rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Attention generally focuses on the changes in East Germany,
but has the former West Germany also been changed by reunification?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it has been transformed indirectly in the way that we
have become more conscious that we have to share, that we have
become more conscious of our own history, and we have become more
conscious maybe also in the sense that we see ourselves not only as
... German ... but as European. This has made West Germany more
aware of the need to integrate ... East Germany not only into West
Germany but into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a perception that there's been some increase on the
fringes of Germany in anti-immigrant and ultra-right activity.
</P>
<P>
   A: You only have to open the papers to see this, especially in
East Germany. One very strong reason is economic. If you have an
unemployment at 18 percent and a lot of young people unemployed,
this creates unrest, and people have a tendency to look for
scapegoats. And, then, they will say it is the foreigners that take
our jobs. n East Germany you had a kind of isolation that was
lifted at once when the Wall fell. The country became open.
Foreigners streamed in for the first time. And it's normal that you
turn against the weakest or somebody weaker than you and look to
him for a scapegoat for your own misery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is the government responding?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is unanimity between all political factions and the
major societal institutions like the church, labor unions, teacher
unions, all groups of life, that we should respond to this
actively. It's a difficult question often because a lot of what we
call the skinhead movement is, of course, a protest movement. It's
first economic but it's secondly also a youth phenomenon. You know,
if you tell your children to cut their hair shorter, they will
probably let it grow even longer. They know that nothing is more
hurtful to Germany than to be seen again as a country that does not
respect minorities. And since they are frustrated about the
government, they try to use this as a potential for provocation.
When they commit criminal acts ... we will react very hard. If you
kill somebody, if you hurt somebody, the courts will do their work.
But there is a layer in between that is not criminally definable,
and there the response has to be very flexible. It has to be in a
way that they understand. There are many people sitting together,
sociologists, youth psychologists, making programs. We have to work
through them, through the schools. But it's an endeavor that will
take time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: American investment is being welcomed as eastern Germany
rebuilds. We're also seeing a good bit of German investment in the
U.S. South. How do you see the economic relationship going?
</P>
<P>
   A: The economic relationship is going the right way, which means
it is ever increasing. (The United States and the European Union)
are becoming more and more equal partners. Sure, we have
differences. Those are little clouds in the blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Germany was involved in the NATO campaign against Yugoslavia
last year and still is involved in the Kosovo peacekeeping mission.
How significant is that for your people?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very significant. A large part of the German population
that voted Green and the younger people that voted predominantly
Green were totally against any German involvement. The idea that
German troops would be seen again on the same territory where they
had done their bloody work in the Second World War was for many,
especially young people, unimaginable. But the Kosovo war changed
this. We want to be a fully sovereign and equal player in the
Western alliance and in the group of nations that shares the same
belief in freedom and democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
