<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON, SAMSONOV TO PLAY IN LAST THREE EXHIBITION GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No rest for the tardy.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins forwards and former holdouts Joe Thornton and Sergei
Samsonov _ both 21 and with matching three-year, $5.35 million
contracts _ reported for work Wednesday at the FleetCenter nearly
three weeks late. Soon after they punched in, supervisor Pat Burns
announced that he planned to have them make up for lost time by
playing in the crush of three games that wrap up the exhibition
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins play the Florida Panthers Thursday at the
FleetCenter, the Pittsburgh Penguins Friday at the Providence Civic
Center, and the Buffalo Sabres back in Boston Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' Samsonov said. ``We had a good
workout today. We'll see how it goes. I felt pretty good today. Of
course, it's going to be different during games. I don't really
know what to expect. I feel like I'm in good shape. Let's see.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov worked out with a junior team in Lawrence and Thornton
with a team back home in Ontario while their teammates were in
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they're out of shape,'' Burns said. ``They haven't
skated for three weeks with an NHL team. They say they were skating
every day and that's good. But we'll see after day two, three,
four, what kind of shape they're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton _ he'll be the big guy wearing No. 19, having traded in
his No. 6 _ knows he and Samsonov are looking at a lot of work in a
short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be difficult,'' Thornton said. ``I've got a
practice under my belt today. We'll have the morning skate. My wind
is going to be a little off. My timing will be a little off. But
hopefully we'll get ready for the first regular-season game (a week
from Thursday night against Ottawa). I'm glad we're both here
together and I wish Anson Carter was here as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's common sense,'' Burns said. ``We have two guys who were
two of our top three scorers last year and at one point they
weren't supposed to be here and you put them on your team and it
makes your club a lot better, no doubt about that. Plus, they're
older. They're more experienced. They're NHL players now. It just
brings that much more to the table for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Carter, who continues to hold out?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's another player that, if he can get in here, he's an NHL
player,'' Burns said. ``He's a 20-goal scorer. He can help us. But
he's not here. You just can't worry about him.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, what Burns can worry about is getting Thornton
and Samsonov ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, during a skating session to close practice, Burns
got on Thornton's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw how red my face was after practice,'' Thornton said.
``He was giving it to me a little bit. I'm just glad to be skating
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as they will be, Thornton and Samsonov were thrown directly
into the mix Wednesday. Samsonov was on a line with Jason Allison
and Lee Goren, and Thornton was with Brian Rolston and Mike Knuble.
</P>
<P>
   There's no time for messing around, Burns said. The opener is
fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no more cautious than the first day of training camp,''
Burns said. ``What do we do the first day of training camp? We
scrimmage. Well, there you go. We have three scrimmages in three
nights, plus it's against NHL teams. I don't have time to be
cautious and I don't think they want to be cautious. We'll play
them all weekend. Put them in right away. It's no worse than coming
into camp and scrimmaging. You want to get in shape, play the
games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
