<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-JAPAN-FUK     09-27 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-JAPAN-FUKAHARA-$ADV01-2TAKES-(Trims)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE PATHFINDERS ROMANCING THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Mass., Japan)  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``East is East, and West is West, and never the twain
shall meet'' may be good poetry, but it's a limited world view.
Eastern and Western religions, cultures and arts have mixed and
married and traded ever so profitably with each other for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (Then, of course, there's actual trade, where meeting means less
than money.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Gandharan sculpture absorbed Greek artistic impulses from
Alexander the Great and turned them into something indisputably
Indian. Remnants of Greek mythology made their way across trade
routes and ended up clinging to Japanese deities or religious
figures. Eighteenth-century Europeans drank Chinese tea from real
or ersatz Chinese cups in rooms wallpapered with Chinese scenes. A
British monarch decided that his gamboling would have a certain je
ne sais quoi if housed in a delightfully inauthentic Indian palace
in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   It's common knowledge that Western art borrowed heavily from
Japan in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. It's less well
known that the West repaid the loan with interest. (END OPTIONAL
TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Japan, abruptly introduced to foreign customs and culture after
the mid-19th century, raced to remake itself as a modern nation,
which included adapting Western modes of representation. The
Japanese learned photography from Western photographers, then
modeled their own imagery on examples of Western painting and
photography. ``Shinzo and Roso Fukuhara: Photographs by Ginza
Modern Boys, 1913-41,'' at Sepia International in Chelsea (through
Oct. 14), presents for the first time in New York the work of two
brothers who played early roles in the formation of Japanese
modernist photography.
</P>
<P>
   This show of more than 100 images and some printed material is
sponsored by Shiseido, the cosmetics company, which has also
financed an exhibition on the role of cosmetics in art at the Grey
Art Gallery at New York University. ``Ginza Modern Boys'' was
selected from the Shiseido Corporate Museum collection by Noriko
Fuku, who wrote the accompanying catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Shinzo and Roso Fukuhara's father founded Shiseido, and Shinzo
(1883-1948), as the oldest surviving son, was obligated to follow
his father as company president. He could pursue photography only
as a sideline yet did so with an energy and effectiveness that
might be envied by many a full-time practitioner. In the early
1920s he and his brother organized an amateur photographers' group,
he founded a photography magazine that once featured female
Japanese photographers (a previously undiscovered species), and he
was the first to try to formulate a theory of photography in Japan.
By the '30s, he was promoting the use of photography in
advertisements for his company.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s Shinzo Fukuhara denounced Pictorialist photography
for imitating painting. His own photography, most of it destroyed
in the great earthquake of 1923, began to shift from a dreamy,
soft-focus Impressionism _ an isolated stroller whose face is
obscured by shadow, bridges that melt under massed tones of gray _
to more rectilinear arrangements of stairs and pilasters and walls.
</P>
<P>
   The work of the '30s is sharp and geometric enough for entry
into the modernist club yet never insistently or strictly stripped
down; Shinzo always harbored an affection for soft effects, tonal
gradations, ragged shadows, blurred backgrounds. Other Japanese
photographers went much farther down the modernist road than either
of the Fukuharas.
</P>
<P>
   Roso Fukuhara (1892-1946), the younger brother, did not have to
work and seems to have pretty much devoted himself to his camera.
His style is more spare and unsparing than Shinzo's (and to my mind
lovelier as well as more challenging). A single, calligraphic
branch of wisteria loops down before an empty sky to meet a small,
blurry patch of leaves rising up in the distance. The imprint of
tradition is often, and beautifully, evident in his landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Fuku's catalog says that Roso Fukuhara's work was not published
in his lifetime, yet he was a pioneer of photographic modernism: a
rather startling combination.
</P>
<P>
   He played with space in cunning ways. In ``Sangatsudo'' (1938),
he photographed a roof in the lower half of the frame, then an
oddly shaped section of sky, bounded on the upper edge by a line of
silhouetted dentils that appear to hang down. In fact they are
protruding from the edge of another roof so close that the
photographer (and, by extension, the viewer) must be standing
underneath it.
</P>
<P>
   As Fuku spells out, the Fukuharas' work illumines the
interchange of Japanese and Western styles. A bit of background
first: after the Meiji Restoration of 1868, the Japanese were so
determined to westernize that they consulted European constitutions
before devising one of their own and introduced the study of
Western culture in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese artists, hugely impressed by the realism of European
painting (and dumbfounded by that of photography), examined Western
styles intently. An art school with Italian instructors opened in
Japan in the 1870's; an exhibition of English photography was held
in 1892. The Ginza district of Tokyo became the center of arts and
modern life, a place where the most up-to-date (meaning, basically,
westernized) Ginza modern boys hung out with Ginza modern girls.
</P>
<P>
   While the Japanese were trying to learn Western ways of
representation, Japanese prints were casting a spell on
Impressionism, Art Nouveau and painters like Mary Cassatt and Edgar
Degas. Influences kept flowing back and forth. By the first decade
of the 20th century, it was clear that Alfred Stieglitz, Edward
Steichen and other photographers knew Japanese prints and equally
clear that Japanese photographers knew Impressionist paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-cultural influences were so strong in Japan that they
threatened to overwhelm the traditional arts, and a Westerner made
some of the first efforts to rescue them. Ernest Fenellosa, an
American, went to Japan in 1878 to teach philosophy, and he took a
hand in trying to preserve the country's traditions without giving
up the new-found sense of contemporaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Now the story gets a little complicated. In 1890, Fenellosa was
appointed the first curator of Japanese art at the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts; there, he introduced Arthur Wesley Dow, an American
artist, to Japanese prints. Dow wrote an artists' manual
emphasizing Japanese principles of composition and taught art at
the Pratt Institute and Columbia University in New York from 1895
to 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Shinzo Fukuhara, who earned a degree in pharmacology at Columbia
in 1912 and was interested in combining Western innovation with
Japanese tradition, came to admire the American photographer Alvin
Langdon Coburn, who had studied Japanese art at a school founded by
Dow and had added Japanese tradition to Western innovation. Shinzo
often published Coburn's work opposite his own in his magazine, and
his photographic group mounted an exhibition of Coburn's
photographs in Japan in the early '20s. What may have been
particularly appealing in Coburn's art was an element of
familiarity, an attitude and intent the Japanese recognized as akin
to their own.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, the great Kanto earthquake devastated Tokyo and spurred
the Japanese to modernize at a breakneck pace. Tokyo rebuilt with
concrete, steel and skyscrapers. Photography magazines and
photographically illustrated magazines proliferated, making Western
imagery ever more available; the Japanese were especially intrigued
by Laszlo Moholy-Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1931, ``Film und Foto,'' the international photography
exhibition organized in Stuttgart, Germany, traveled to Tokyo and
Osaka. Japanese photographers tried out the mechanical,
architectural, graphically ordered styles the West had already
initiated in honor of the machine age and were included more and
more often in exhibitions in the West.
</P>
<P>
   If the show at Sepia is representative, the Fukuhara brothers,
born in the 19th century, clung to landscape and details of
traditional buildings. At their most modern, they never quite
relinquished their ties to Japanese art of the past. They were
capable of circumventing the camera's built-in perspective system
to produce spaces more like those of Japanese screens and scrolls.
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Japanese art conceived of empty spaces as positive rather than
negative, not merely what is left over between and around objects
but every bit as important as solid matter. In Shinzo Fukuhara's
``Light With Its Harmony 8: Pond'' (1924), a tree with leaves that
might have been brushed on arcs slowly, horizontally across the top
of the frame. The water enclosed by the lines of trunk and branch
occupies two thirds of the picture space. Within those lines the
pond fairly tilts up on the surface of the image as water so often
does in Japanese art, and its outlined shape appears to lean
against the curve of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sea at New Year'' (1937), the reciprocal spaces of silvery
ocean and sky are separated by irregular hills that are subtly
darker but no more solid than the atmosphere and dissolve into
swaths of mist. A tiny boat hovers on the surface of the picture
like a splotchy swipe of diluted ink.
</P>
<P>
   In Roso Fukuhara's ``Kamikochi'' (1937), a great flourish of
mist between background mountains and frothy trees up front assumes
a shape at least as strong and commanding as that of the mountains.
In ``Miscanthus'' (1933), reedlike stems, as taut and straight or
elegantly scribbled as pen strokes, stand up before mountain ranges
so pale and delicate that they function as tonal washes applied to
a vertical backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures like these, immediately recognizable as ``Japanese''
but encompassing the dual discoveries of the ancient East and the
modern West, strike me as the most beautiful in the show.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan underwent chaotic changes in the 1920s and '30s _
modernization, industrialization, militarization _ Shinzo and Roso
Fukuhara continued to produce images of peace and quiet that
negotiated alliances between the old dispensation and the new. In
their way they denied what much of the world still believed: that
the twain would never meet.
</P>
<P>
   The twain insist on meeting and have done so repeatedly in the
realm of art, sitting on an endless loop of intercontinental,
interhemispherical influences, where East keeps sliding into West
and veering off to north or south or directions not yet mapped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
