u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-CLINTON-BO     09-27 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SUPPORTS `EXPRESS WILL OF THE SERBIAN PEOPLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton accused embattled Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic Wednesday of trying to steal the
election from the opposition, and said the United States would
stand behind the Serbian people in their apparent quest to oust the
international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly appears from a distance that they had a free
election and somebody's trying to take it away from them,'' Clinton
told reporters in the Rose Garden before leaving for a fundraiser
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Europe and the United States should do is to
support the express will of the Serbian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was apparently stunned at opposition candidate
Vojislav Kostunica's strong showing in Sunday's elections, Clinton
administration officials and Balkan analysts said, and is trying to
buy time by insisisting on a runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know how to deal with this,'' said Kurt Bassuener,
a Balkan expert with the US Institute of Peace in Washington. ``He
did not expect to get hammered, apparently.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking an exit strategy, Milosevic is cornered.
</P>
<P>
   He could give himself up and go to The Hague for trial as a war
criminal, hardly an appealing option for the man accused of causing
the deaths of tens of thousands in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He could go into internal exile in Serbia. But while Kostunica,
himself a Serb nationalist, has said he will not turn Milosevic
over to the International War Crimes Tribunal, Milosevic would not
be safe in his own land, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin to think that going to The Hague becomes a better
option than it looked a few weeks ago,'' since Milosevic would be
in danger of assassination, said Jim Hooper of the International
Crisis Group.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic could try to find a sympathetic country to give him
asylum. The most likely candidates would be Belarus and Iraq, a
White House national security official said, but even those rogue
nations wold probably not risk the international outrage by giving
Milosevic sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the United States look the other way if another nation
offers to take in the Yugoslav strongman. ``We've made it clear
there's no deal,'' said the national security official.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Milosevic with no easy way out, and Balkan-watchers
fear that with nothing to lose, Milosevic may create greater havoc.
</P>
<P>
   The West's greatest worry, a Clinton administration official
said, is that Milosevic will try to cut a deal with the opposition
under which he takes the title of President of Serbia, based on the
Socialist Party's domination of the Parliament, while leaving the
grander title of Yugoslav President to Kostunica. Yugoslavia
comprises Serbia, including the southern province of Kosovo, and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The White House strategy is to wait, making comments supportive
of democracy and free elections, while not appearing to dictate to
Serbia, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica cannot rule effectively if he appears to be kow-towing
to the West, which is still hated by many Serbs for NATO's bombing
campaign last year. Long-isolated and beaten down during four
regional wars and a trade embargo, Serbians need to be allowed some
dignity and a sense that they are making their own future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is not taking any sides,'' the official
said. ``We're just playing wait-and-see.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Yugoslavia's foreign minister, Zivadin Jovanovic,
Wednesday accused Western powers of using foreign and Yugoslav
media to destablize the country, and Russia warned against any
international intervention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
