<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4048 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-370&AMP;     09-27 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI AUTHORITIES END PROSECUTION OF NETANYAHU
</HEADLINE>
  (With NETANYAHU-U.S.) 
By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After deliberating for six months, Israel's attorney
general on Wednesday said he had found insufficient evidence to
prosecute former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on corruption
charges, clearing the way for a possible political comeback by the
conservative leader.
</P>
<P>
   In a 22-page decision released Wednesday night, Attorney General
Elyakim Rubinstein said that he had rejected a police
recommendation of last March that Netanyahu and his wife, Sarah,
face criminal charges of bribery, fraud and theft.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein said that he had closed the case because he did not
foresee ``a reasonable chance of conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   But, with biting language, Rubinstein condemned Netanyahu for
``improper'' conduct and said that the ``picture before us'' had
given prosecutors ``an ill feeling.'' He acknowledged that the
state attorney, Edna Arbel, had disagreed with his conclusion,
urging indictment on some charges.
</P>
<P>
   In an investigation that began over a year ago, the police
suspected the Netanyahus of conspiring with a contractor in an
illegal kickback scheme, of stealing gifts to the state and of
obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahus denied wrongdoing, claiming persecution by
political enemies and, after the media was alerted to raids of
their home, by an overly zealous police force.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Netanyahu will now return to politics,
seizing the momentum to re-establish himself at the head of a
rudderless right wing. But associates say that he will not make a
decision immediately, waiting instead to see if the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations produce a deal that could
shore up Prime Minister Ehud Barak's tenuous hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Barak released a statement saying that he respected the attorney
general's decision, understood the Netanyahus' ``feeling of
relief'' and wished the couple a happy New Year. Rosh Hashana, the
Jewish New Year, starts Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta on business, Netanyahu, who has spent the last year
as a consultant to Israeli high-tech companies, declined to comment
on the attorney general's decision, which was expected on Thursday,
or on his political future. He said only that he was ``relieved,
relieved, relieved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this summer, Netanyahu described the
investigation as ``wrenching'' and ``scarring.'' He said that his
sons, 5 and 9 years old, had been taunted at school. ``We've been
in very dire straits,'' he said in August. ``For the boys, going to
school and hearing other kids saying, `Your father's a thief, your
mother's a criminal.' It's been very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   For three tumultuous years, Netanyahu led Israel at the helm of
a religious and nationalist coalition that was perceived
internationally as obstructionist to peace. He stepped down from
politics on the night in May 1999 that Barak, who ran on a
peacemaking platform, overwhelmingly defeated him.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the right wing has been splintered, incapable of
mounting an effective opposition to Barak, even as the prime
minister's government has teetered on the edge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even though Netanyahu disappointed many followers
and alienated many political colleagues while in office, nostalgia
has grown for his telegenic political skills.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Netanyahu neck-in-neck with Barak _ far stronger as a
candidate than Ariel Sharon, the former general and defense
minister who took his place atop the Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, 72, has indicated that he will seek to retain the
leadership, and several younger Likud officials have said that they
are considering a bid for the post when party primaries are held.
But Netanyahu, 50, could change their plans by throwing his hat
back in the political ring.
</P>
<P>
   The hint of a return by Netanyahu, in fact, could push Sharon to
consider joining a unity government with Barak to keep himself from
being shunted aside. But that is likely only if the present
Israeli-Palestinian deadlock continues.
</P>
<P>
   Associates Wednesday urged Netanyahu to make a quick decision.
Reuven Rivlin, a Likud lawmaker, said that Netanyahu, if he intends
a comeback, should ``return to activity immediately and put an end
to this whispering campaign and to a postponement that could cause
the Likud serious damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eitan, a Likud legislator who was a sharp critic of
Netanyahu's leadership, cautioned the party against romanticizing a
politician ``responsible for the largest electoral drubbing the
Likud has ever known, and for the early dissolution of the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Likud won only 19 seats in the election that Netanyahu lost,
seven less than Barak's One Israel/Labor faction and two more than
the ultra-Orthodox Shas party.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time that Rubinstein declined to indict
Netanyahu because of what he said was insufficient evidence while
sharply criticizing his comportment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, while Netanyahu was prime minister, the police
suggested that he stand trial on corruption charges in a case that
involved a supposed deal between Netanyahu and the former Shas
leader, Aryeh Deri, who is now in prison on a corruption
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The police believed that Netanyahu had agreed to appoint an
attorney general, Roni Bar-On, who would be sympathetic to Deri in
exchange for the Shas party's support for the so-called Hebron
interim agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Gearing up for a possible challenge by Netanyahu, One
Israel/Labor Party leaders were quick to recall that case Wednesday
night. ``I think that it is only in a country like Israel that
after two particularly critical public reports there can still be
talk about a political comeback,'' said Ophir Pines Paz, the One
Israel faction chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the police said the Netanyahus had ``illegally
removed'' gifts to the state of Israel, including candelabras,
silverware and carpets, when they left the prime minister's
residence. They also said that the Netanyahus had accepted up to
$100,000 worth of free services from a contractor, who later billed
the state for the private work.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Rubinstein said it was ``improper behavior for a
governing officials'' to ``amass great debt'' to a ``private
individual,'' the contractor, who was interested in nurturing a
relationship with the prime minister and his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
