<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   Hooter's Tour wings it on website
</P>
<P>
   The Peachtree-City based Hooter's Tour, whose 2000 season ends
this weekend at White Water Country Club in Fayetteville, touts
itself as more than a training ground for the PGA Tour. Still, it
has been a place where players such as Lee Janzen, John Daly, Jim
Furyk and Tom Lehman have honed their games before moving up. The
tour's web site is geared more toward providing information to
aspiring players and sponsors than fans, but there are statistics,
rankings and tournament results. There are links to golf coverage
on other sites, as well as to the tour's namesake restaurant, where
you can find photos and information on its wings and waitresses.
</P>
<P>
   www.ngahooterstour.com
</P>
<P>
   Circular logic applies at racing site
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's ``That's racin''' cliche didn't come about because
predicting race outcomes was an exact science. That's not to say
that some people don't try, though. There are fantasy leagues
devoted to the sport, and sites that provide statistics from tracks
and events with a history-as-handicapping lean. Speed FX breaks
down the Autocare 500 at Martinsville Speedway with driver averages
since 1990 or '95, and Jeff Gordon heads both lists. That may make
him the favorite Sunday, but not a lock when 43 cars start trading
paint on the half-mile.
</P>
<P>
   www.speedfx.com
</P>
