<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-GIRL-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      09-27 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GIRL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIMSICAL `GIRL ON THE BRIDGE' GIVES SUBTLE PLEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 HOUSTON CHRONICLE 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wondrously filmed, wryly amusing French romance ``The
Girl on the Bridge,'' a cabaret knife thrower picks a suicidal
woman as his next target.
</P>
<P>
   When Gabor, the knife thrower (Daniel Auteuil), tries to
convince the sad Adele (Vanessa Paradis) not to leap off a bridge
into icy waters below, he wants to save her and perhaps himself.
Gabor has knowledge of suicidal impulses.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning hardly hints at the luscious, playful, if rather
thin movie that follows. Directed at a sprint by Patrice Leconte
(``Monsieur Hire,'' ``Ridicule''), with vividly colorful dialogue,
``The Girl on the Bridge'' is an extravagant entertainment on a
tiny, by American standards, scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Girl on the Bridge'' (``La Fille sur le Pont''), in French
with English subtitles, is an un-Hollywood romantic comedy. There
are no laughs, yet a whimsical air dominates every moment. There
are no traditional love scenes between the principals, yet the
sexual tension is, quite literally, cut with a knife. A week after
seeing the film, its plot points may fade, but the movie's sensual
atmosphere will linger.
</P>
<P>
   Gabor claims he is on the bridge that frigid night to recruit
``targets'' among would-be jumpers. Adele may want to end her life
_ at 22 years old, she has had nothing but bad luck in her
desperate promiscuity _ but the idea of the knives brings fear to
the pit of her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit anybody,'' Gabor promises, ``in the stomach.''
He insists she has the luck they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the thrower that counts,'' he says. ``It's the
target. You have a special gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabor's own gift, besides steady hands and intense eyes that
seem to see other times and places, is spotting luck. Yet he's a
man with a mysterious past that hints of huge sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could smile sometimes,'' says Adele, who finds amusement
in her own sorrows.
</P>
<P>
   Together, their luck changes dramatically, at least at first.
When the manager at a sunny Monaco resort rejects their act, Gabor,
thinking on the spot, says he throws blind.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting performance, with frightened but excited Adele
pinned to a wall behind a sheet, is just the first of several
bravura scenes in which Leconte's brilliant blending of editing,
direction, acting and music creates a surreal and intensely sensual
cinematic experience.
</P>
<P>
   The throwing scenes are suspenseful. They are also amusingly
over-the-top, a confident director playing to an audience he trusts
to recognize the tongue-in-cheek quality and savor the melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Leconte makes sure we can't mistake the sexual excitement
between Gabor and Adele as his knives pierce the wall closer and
closer to her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I want,'' an aroused Adele says to Gabor after a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now?'' he asks, knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now. Anywhere,'' she says, and they rush off to another
encounter with the flashing knives.
</P>
<P>
   This is not for the literal-minded. Adele can hit 0 at a
roulette table five times in a row when her luck is hot, while
Gabor, banned from the casino, can see and guide her hands by ...
what? telepathy? She and Gabor literally talk to each other when
hundreds of miles apart as though it were natural.
</P>
<P>
   The casting is perfection, especially Auteuil (``Jean de
Florette,'' ``Manon of the Spring'') as Gabor. His craggy,
experienced face whispers of a thousand tragic nights hidden behind
those piercing eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Paradis possesses the correct hopeful contrast and, once Gabor
transforms Adele into his assistant, she gains an ethereal quality
missing in early scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's most static scene is the first, in which Adele
explains her unlucky past to a mysterious panel of out-of-focus
listeners. The rest of the movie, the camera zips and tilts and
even spins.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is beautifully shot in black-and-white by Jean-Marie
Dreujou, in glorious if briefly glimpsed European locations. It is
greatly enhanced by an evocative soundtrack of European and
American music.
</P>
<P>
   There is little real story, and the ending is pat. This is a
movie for viewers who value visual style and joyously wallow in
atmosphere. For those, it's near perfection. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Girl on the Bridge'' &QL; 
Starring: Daniel Auteuil, Vanessa Paradis &QL; 
Director: Patrice Leconte &QL; 
Screenwriter: Serge Frydman &QL; 
Opening: today &QL; 
