<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-GAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS CELEBRATE DISCOVERY OF NATURAL-GAS DEPOSIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yasser Arafat traveled 19 miles off the Gaza coast
Wednesday to light the first flare stack over a major offshore
deposit of natural gas, proclaiming it ``a gift from our God to our
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, celebrating the multibillion-dollar discovery of what
industry officials confirmed was a major gas deposit, said the
deposit would provide ``a strong foundation for a Palestinian
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gift from our God to our people, to our children, to
our women, to our people inside and outside, to our refugees and
those who are living here on our land,'' the Palestinian leader
declared. The deposit is considered to be more than enough gas to
meet Palestinian needs for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat gave a signal to the foreign crew to light the flare atop
the floating platform, and gas from the test well burned overhead.
Reciting a passage from the Koran, he echoed a divine promise that
the ``weak and dispossessed of today'' will become the ``leaders
and heirs'' of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The BG Group of London, which won a concession in November from
Arafat's Palestinian Authority to drill in the 2,000-foot-deep
waters off the Gaza Strip, said Wednesday that this first Gaza test
well was flowing at a strong 37 million cubic feet a day, more than
in any of eight recent offshore gas strikes in nearby Israeli
territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made an extremely good discovery,'' Timothy Forbes,
who runs BG operations in North Africa and the Middle East, told
reporters in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government, despite criticism from rightist
opposition leaders, has tacitly permitted the exploration effort,
renouncing any sovereignty over the Mediterranean waters directly
off the Gaza Strip. One Israeli gas-exploration consortium,
contending that the Palestinian Authority lacks the legal status to
grant energy exploration permits, has sued in Israeli courts to
block the Gaza drilling.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said BG could not confirm reserve figures until it
had further analysis of the drilling information next month. Yet
even by conservative estimates, they said, the mile-deep deposit
known as Gaza Marine 1 should more than satisfy projected
Palestinian electric-power needs for 10 to 20 years, with enough
left over for possible sale to Israeli or other foreign customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the key messages here today,'' said Hugh
Miller, who manages the Palestinian and Israeli concessions of BG.
``There will be gas available for export. And from my conversations
with Palestinian officials, including President Arafat, it is clear
that they have no interest in just sitting on a gas surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   At current prices, the value of the strike was estimated at $2
billion to $6 billion, depending on pressure, quantity and other
variables. It could take two to three years and $250 million to
build the pipelines and other installations needed to deliver the
gas onshore, Palestinian officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A domestic Palestinian gas supply could eventually eliminate
spending on electricity and household fuels that are now imported
from Israel, and exports would provide a needed source of dollars.
The gas industry ``will prove to be one of the main economic
cornerstones for a future independent state of Palestine,''
predicted Said Khoury, president of the Consolidated Contractors
Co. of Athens, Greece, the minority partner in the project.
</P>
<P>
   The BG Group plans to drill at least one more test well off Gaza
while continuing explorations in adjacent concessions in Israeli
waters, executives said. Some of the larger potential gas reserves
identified by geologists lie underneath the division between
Israeli and Palestinian waters. The boundary has never been
precisely delineated.
</P>
</TEXT>
