<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH21-TECH21-SFC     09-27 1967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH21-TECH21-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
WIRELESS NET ACCESS SPEEDS UP (COLUMN) &HT;    By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   An announcement last week from Metricom Inc. marked a milestone
in the history of data communications in the Bay Area and beyond:
For the first time, wireless Internet access is available at high
speeds here.
</P>
<P>
   At 128 kilobits per second, the Los Gatos company's newly
enhanced Ricochet service is more than twice as fast as a
conventional modem _ and more than 10 times the speed of other
wide-area wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   The company also rolled out the high-speed service in Baltimore,
Dallas, Houston, Philadelphia, Phoenix and, on a limited basis,
Manhattan. Atlanta and San Diego have had it since June. Seattle
and Washington, D.C., as well as 15 airports and various university
campuses across the country also have Ricochet service, although
for now those areas are still limited to a nominal 28 Kbps.
</P>
<P>
   Metricom's plan goes a long way toward solving the two big
problems with the old Ricochet service. With coverage in only three
metropolitan areas, it wasn't something most mobile professionals
could count on as an overall solution for Internet access on the
road. And with actual throughput of no more than 22 or 23 Kbps _ at
least in my experience as a Ricochet subscriber of more than two
years' standing _ it was adequate for e-mail but barely tolerable
for surfing a Web that's increasingly laden with ads, graphics,
animation and other bandwidth-devouring doodads.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the new service brings a new problem: price. The
old Ricochet was $29.95 a month, a rate that struck me as fairly
reasonable, even though I didn't use the service most days. But the
new plan, offered through several service providers, will be priced
about $70 per month.
</P>
<P>
   That rate, obviously, will limit the market severely _ aside
from Internet millionaires with nothing else to do with their
money, I think only salespeople and others who really need constant
access to online data will be able to justify the price.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's the opening of a new era, and it puts Metricom at
least 18 to 24 months ahead of the big boys in telecommunications.
It'll be interesting to see whether they can capitalize on the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVE NEW WORLD: Meanwhile, eager entrepreneurs keep thinking of
clever new things to do with mobile phones. Consider this sampling
of initiatives just from the last few weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Handspring, as you probably saw last week, finally announced the
long-awaited phone module for its Visor line of Palm OS-based
personal digital assistants. Considering its $299 price _ not
counting the cost of Visor itself _ and its dependence on a network
(GSM, or Global System for Mobile communications) that's relatively
undeveloped in the United States, I'm not sure how successful the
VisorPhone will be. But even if unit volumes are limited, the
device could go a long way toward popularizing phone-based text
messaging in the United States. (It's already one of the hottest
technology trends in Europe and Japan.)
</P>
<P>
   And if it succeeds, it's bound to inspire a new wave of
competing phone-PDA hybrids. Early efforts in this direction _
IBM's Simon, the Nokia 9000 Communicator and Qualcomm's pdQ _ were
so clunky and overpriced, they gave the idea a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   But once users see how much easier it is to do messaging on a
device like the Visor _ with a relatively large screen, handwriting
recognition and onscreen soft keyboards _ than on a conventional
phone with just a 12-key dial pad, I bet both users and vendors
will be willing to take a second look. I'll bet Motorola's
disclosure today of a deal with Palm won't be the last such
alliance this year.
</P>
<P>
   LightSurf Technologies of Santa Cruz, the latest venture of
longtime tech heavyweight Philippe Kahn, showed off its first
product at this month's DemoMobile 2000 conference in Pasadena: a
thumb-sized digital camera that clipped on to a next-generation
phone from Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Using a patent-pending wireless acceleration technology and
back-end image-management system, the phone quickly transmitted
images from the camera and automatically posted them on a special
Web site where they could be viewed and downloaded by anyone with a
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, the United States is merely beginning to catch up
with Japan, where similar devices are apparently already a
sensation. My own guess is that the idea won't take off here until
the wireless phone networks offer significantly greater bandwidth,
but with luck that should happen in a couple of years _ especially
if Metricom starts to put some real competitive pressure on the
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   FunMail, a startup in Pleasanton, Calif., is developing an
``animated instant messaging'' service for I-Mode. Users send a
short text message to the FunMail Web site (www.funmail.com), where
a ``text-to-animation engine'' automatically generates a
cartoon-like sequence based on key words in the text; once the
sender approves, the text and animation are sent together to the
intended recipient, either on another I-Mode phone or on any
browser-equipped computer.
</P>
<P>
   The service is already available (and about to enjoy a major
upgrade) for desktop computer users, and company officials say
they'll have it running before long on additional phone formats.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia, the Finnish phone giant, introduced a new GSM phone
called the 3310, which features extended support for online chat
(including built-in libraries of pictures and smiley icons),
graphical ``screen savers,'' four built-in games and a new feature
that makes the phone vibrate at critical moments in game play.
</P>
<P>
   RealTimeTouch, a division of Design Systems Research and
Development in Alpine (San Diego County), went Nokia one better _
conceptually, at least _ with word of technology it says will
enable wireless devices to ``send and receive instantaneous,
person-to-person touch transmissions.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, according to the news release, ``a husband and wife
who have been notified of a crisis (might) speak to each other via
cellular telephone. In order to reassure his wife, the husband
squeezes his phone. His wife immediately feels her husband's touch
as the phone expands in her hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Web site (www.realtimetouch.com) takes this idea _
for which RealTimeTouch says it has patents pending in more than
100 countries _ considerably further. Among other descriptions of
possible applications of the technology, it says business owners
could seal deals by shaking each other's cell phones; teen idols
could virtually ``hold the eager, outstretched hands of their
excited fans''; and politicians and religious leaders could
``convey trust and sincerity (by) touching millions of viewers
during interactive television, Web-based, and live performances.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology, according to the company, could even
``revolutionize current military strategies'' and health care,
possibly making ``the difference between life and death for an
infant'' starved for physical attention.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke to Craig Linden, CEO of RealTimeTouch, who explained
that all this would begin with phones that, like the Nokia 3310,
simply have programmable vibrators. The next step, he said, will be
adding special transducers that expand or contract parts of the
phone on receipt of a coded ``touch transmission.'' Then would come
new devices capable of much more varied and extensive movements _
for example, remote-controlled teddy bears, physical-therapy
devices and military machines. In effect, they'd be
phone-controlled robots.
</P>
<P>
   Linden even has a trademark on the term ``CyberHugs.'' The
imagination runs wild ...
</P>
<P>
   TIME TRAVEL: Yesterday marked an important date for commuters to
or from the Peninsula and the South Bay, not to mention Giants fans
from those areas: Caltrain made major changes to its schedule,
adding 10 new trains on weekdays and four on Saturdays. To
``improve reliability'' _ that is, to give you a slightly more
realistic idea of how long your trip will really take _ the agency
is also adding four to eight minutes to the weekday San Jose-to-San
Francisco timetable and a whopping 25 minutes on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even if you're a regular rider (as I used to
be), the schedule information you carry in your head probably isn't
much good anymore, and at least for a while most users will be
checking the new timetable frequently. Caltrain will be happy to
give it to you on paper, but if you don't have it yet or don't want
to carry one more document, technology can help.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true for owners of Palm handhelds, thanks to a
local programmer named Rob Barnes: He has ust updated his nifty
little Caltrain Schedule app, which will show you arrival and
departure times for any two stops you select.
</P>
<P>
   The program is free, and the new version takes up just 23
kilobytes of memory, only a third as much as the old one. You can
download it from Baynes' personal site
(www.members.home.net/rbaynes/palm/) or from Palm Gear H.Q., the
leading online library for Palm OS software (www.palmgear.com).
</P>
<P>
   If you're into this sort of thing, check back regularly for
updates _ Baynes has plans to add lots of new features.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Gear also has a Caltrain map in a format you can display on
your Palm, provided you've installed FireViewer (formerly Image
Viewer) _ just search for ``caltrain map.'' Be careful, though,
about another schedule app called CalTrain 1.2: Its database is now
out-of-date, and author Anand Rajaraman says he can't spare the
time to update it (though he'll make his source code available if
someone else wants to).
</P>
<P>
   BART riders, by the way, can also keep that system's timetable
in hand with BART Scheduler, a Palm OS program by Mike Wittman. It
has some nice extras, such as an option to show only trains that
allow bikes. It's at Palm Gear, too, or at Wittman's site
(www.cs.berkeley.edu/wittman/bart-scheduler/).
</P>
<P>
   An aside: The availability of so much specialized software like
this is one of the best arguments for the Palm platform _ the
Pocket PC camp is going to have a hard time catching up even if its
hardware is superior. Just this month Palm said its count of
registered developers has topped 100,000. Microsoft won't say how
many developers have committed to Windows CE, but it's clear that
the number is only a small fraction of Palm's total.
</P>
<P>
   On the transportation front, though, you're not out of luck even
if you don't have a Palm or compatible device _ with a PC, a Mac, a
Pocket PC or (presumably) anything else with a Web browser, you can
find the new Caltrain timetable, plus schedules for dozens of other
Bay Area transportation services, at www.transitinfo.org, a
convenient central site supported by the Metropolitan
Transportation Commission. For hard-core schedule junkies, the site
even lets you sign up for e-mail alerts about future timetable
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The slickest high-tech schedule service is reserved for riders
of the Muni's five Metro lines and the 22-Fillmore trolley bus, as
well as Emeryville's Emery-go-Round shuttle service. An Emeryville
company called NextBus Information Systems runs a site
(www.nextbus.com) that estimates when the next bus will arrive at
the stop you select, based on actual, real-time location
information transmitted from GPS devices installed on the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As The Chronicle's Ed Epstein reported last month, the free
service is now available not only on conventional Web browsers, but
also on mobile phones with Internet and text-messaging
capabilities, on the Palm VII and Palm V devices with OmniSky
wireless modems and on selected two-way pagers, including Research
in Motion's Blackberry line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-24-00 2217EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
