<SLUG> BC-NETANYAHU-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU, IN ATLANTA, IS ALL SMILES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Mich)  (With ISRAEL-NETANYAHU)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA, _ Benjamin Netanyahu was among a crowd of techies here
Wednesday, trying his best to pitch the merits of an Israeli
telecommunications company while being repeatedly interrupted by
calls on his cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, story's breaking,'' he said with a satisfied grin.
``It's a nice story to break.''
</P>
<P>
   He was all smiles, dressed in a dark suit and checkered tie. But
Netanyahu, who was at a technology convention here this week to
generate press for Telco Systems, spilled no news himself.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he remained strategically mum about his exoneration.
Asked how he felt about the Israeli attorney general's decision not
to prosecute him after a yearlong investigation, Netanyahu would
say only, ``relieved, relieved, relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called in for interrogation, the public investigation
began one day after Rosh Hashanah,'' he added. ``It was formally
closed a day before Rosh Hashanah.'' The formal decision by the
Israeli attorney general was to be announced Thursday, and Rosh
Hashanah, the Jewish New Year, begins Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting inside a conference room at CNN headquarters here,
Netanyahu declined even to say who he was on the phone with. ``Just
people from Israel,'' is all he would offer.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to reflect on the impact of the latest developments
on the Likud Party, or its Labor opponents. And he remained
teasingly reticent about whether he plans to return to politics,
insisting that he wished to speak to his family and his lawyers
first.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu had been scheduled to speak with a stream of
reporters, most of them covering technology, later in the day. But
he canceled those plans, took a private plane to Ann Arbor, where
he was to give a talk at the University of Michigan, and then was
to catch an El Al flight from New York to Israel Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to talk about it once I go there,'' Netanyahu
said of his potential political plans. ``I'd like be there in
Israel to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he insisted, he had not even seen the text of the
report, only had its highlights read to him over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   By whom?
</P>
<P>
   A smile and a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the former prime minister revealed nothing of his plans,
his current boss, Zvi Marom, chief executive officer of Telco's
parent company, BATM Advanced Communications, did, predicting that
Netanyahu would likely return to politics.
</P>
<P>
   If Netanyahu demurred on questions about his political opponent,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Marom repeatedly lashed out on his
behalf. ``When a witch hunt happens and you don't get a witch, you
have yourself a martyr,'' he added. ``He will be forced into
politics. His popularity is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was at the Telco Systems booth in the subbasement of
the convention center Wednesday morning at 11 a.m. when news came
over his cellphone. Marom said he watched his face relax. ``He
looked at me. I looked at him and we knew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
