A4075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DENMARK-EURO-NYT &LR;      09-27 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENMARK TO VOTE ON WHETHER TO ADOPT EURO AS ITS CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark _ Denmark, pursuing an odd calling as the
barometer of Europe's mood, holds its fourth referendum in less
than a decade on Thursday on what degree of integration with the
European Union the country desires.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the question being put to just over 4 million voters
is whether Denmark should follow 12 other countries of the
15-member Union and join a shared European currency, the euro. But
the real issue in the vote may be summed up otherwise: it's the
politics, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish currency, the krone, is pegged to the euro and has
followed the currency's 25 percent slide against the dollar over
the last 21 months. This link will be maintained whatever the
outcome of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But even if this arrangement ties Denmark irrevocably to
Europe's economic fate, many Danes are concerned about adopting a
currency they see as a political symbol of a push for a European
superstate in which the identity of small nations like Denmark
would be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countries should have their own borders, their own defense and
their own currency, but all of this is being eroded by attempts to
create a United States of Europe,'' said Peter Skaarup, a member of
the right-wing Danish People's Party. ``If we give up the krone, we
won't be masters in our own house any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fears have bolstered the ``No'' campaign, and most opinion
polls suggest that Danes will reject the euro. The vote, however,
is too close to call, with at least 10 percent of the electorate
undecided, and the government of Social Democratic Prime Minister
Poul Nyrup Rasmussen is placing its faith in a last-minute swing in
favor of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Other European governments will be watching closely. The
weakness of the euro since its introduction in 1999 has been tied
partly to a market perception that the will does not exist in the
European Union to pursue the sort of political integration that
would bolster the currency.
</P>
<P>
   A Danish rejection of the euro would inevitably reinforce such
sentiments at a time when the European Central Bank, with support
from the United States and Japan, has already felt obliged to
intervene in support of the currency. Any prospect of Britain and
Sweden adopting the euro would also recede.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll published on Wednesday showed 47 percent of Danes
against the euro and 41 percent in favor. A poll by the National
Statistics Office gave the anti-euro camp an even wider victory,
with 51.7 percent voting ``No'' and 41.3 percent ``Yes.'' Only one
survey, by the Vilstrup polling center, gave a narrow victory to
supporters of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Jorn Thulstrup, a pollster who has followed the national mood
closely and was predicting a month ago that Denmark would accept
the euro, said he had now reluctantly concluded that the country
would reject it. ``It looks very negative,'' he said. ``There are
irrational fears that if we are in the euro, pensions would decline
every time the euro slips.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fears are unfounded in that the krone already tracks the
euro's rate against the dollar. In fact, it seems clear to most
analysts that Denmark's currency _ and so people's real incomes _
would be more vulnerable to a speculative attack if the country
opts to stay out.
</P>
<P>
   But the fears about pensions reflect anxiety among Danes that
adopting the euro would open the way to outside domination in the
form of an insistence that Denmark cut its taxes, scale back its
welfare state and deregulate its economy along the lines that
markets generally favor.
</P>
<P>
   One result of all the crosscurrents is the opposition to the
euro by both the left and the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing an unholy alliance of right-wing nationalists
concerned about our identity and left-wingers worried about
economic freedom,'' said John Iversen, a spokesman for the Social
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The government has argued that Denmark will be strengthened by
being inside the group of European nations that, in any event,
dictate the broad course of monetary policy here. And it has
insisted, but without convincing evidence, that this message is
getting through and that the euro will be adopted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
