<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-JONES0928-COX     09-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JONES0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones stays a step ahead of turmoil
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - When she heard her name booming over the loudspeaker,
Marion Jones smiled and waved to the crowd at Olympic Stadium like
a woman with nothing on her mind except running fast, then jumping
far.
</P>
<P>
   Jones blocked out the turmoil in her private life Wednesday long
enough to reach the semifinals in the 200-meter dash and the finals
of the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I love to be; I love to be out there in front of
the fans,'' said Jones, who eased up for second place in her
second-round race with a time of 22.50 seconds. She then met the
qualifying standard on her first and only long jump. ``I love to be
in front of the lights. It kind of gets my mind off everything.
There's so much going on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after her husband, shot-putter C.J. Hunter, cried at
a news conference and denied he had taken performance-enhancing
drugs, Jones' quest for five gold medals continued without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-meter semis and final will be today, with the long jump
final Friday. The two relay finals will take place Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think the support has been incredible and I think
that's the reason I'm able to get through this,'' said Jones, who
said she had her family in Sydney and the public behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have e-mailed, and Jones said one message read, ``C.J.,
Marion, you're in our prayers and we believe in you 100 percent.
Prove them all wrong. Go out there and win all your golds.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Kipketer didn't win his gold Wednesday. The Kenyan
native, who missed the 1996 Olympics because he had just become a
Danish citizen, couldn't catch German Nils Schumann in the 800
meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is better than nothing,'' said Kipketer, whose time
of 1:45.14 was .06 behind Schumann. ``I'm 90 percent happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Olga Shishigina won the women's 100-meter hurdles, followed by
Glory Alozie, the Nigerian whose fiance was killed when he was
struck by a car before the Olympics. A gleeful Melissa Morrison of
the U.S., was the happiest bronze medalist Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former sprinter Irina Privalova of Russia won the 400-meter
hurdles with a time of 53.02. Privalova won the bronze in the 100
meters in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Pole vault legend Sergei Bubka, who no-heighted in Barcelona,
did the same here. He passed the first four heights, then missed
three times at 18-8.
</P>
<P>
   John Capel of the U.S. and Darren Campbell of Great Britain have
the fastest qualifying time in the men's 200 meters at 20.13
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Huffins, an assistant track coach at Georgia Tech, is
leading the decathlon entering Thursday's final five events.
``Everything was solid, but nothing was great,'' said Huffins, who
scored 4,554 points to lead Great Britain's Dean Macey by only
eight points. ``I'm looking for fireworks tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Jones, who conserved her energy Wednesday. She had two
rounds of the 200 meters, winning her heat in the morning with a
time of 22.75 seconds, followed by some rest and then the evening
race that was ``the easiest 22.50 I have ever run.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jones put on the brakes, Melinda Gainsford-Taylor of
Australia edged her by .01. Beverly McDonald of Jamaica had the
fastest qualifying time, 22.44.
</P>
<P>
   Only 64 minutes later, Jones had to get ready to long jump. She
qualified for the final on her first jump, 22 feet, 3 inches, then
didn't take her other two attempts. Heike Drechsler of Germany had
the best jump in her group of 22-5 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do the first jump and get home,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Hunter are staying at a local hotel but have switched
rooms with another athlete so they won't be disturbed by telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, I said today was going to be my most difficult day,
even though it's not difficult to run 22.7 and 22.5, and then to
come back and get that qualifying mark,'' Jones said. ``As you all
know, I've had difficulty with my qualifying jump. So to come out
this evening and to pop a qualifying jump on my first jump, I'm
pleased with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones initially thought she had fouled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `What?'' she said. ``I turned around expecting a
red flag. But no worries at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the controversy engulfing her husband, she said, ``I'll deal
with it all after the Sydney Games are done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
