<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRICELINE-OUTLOOK-NYT     09-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE SHARES FALL ON WORD THAT SALES WON'T MEET FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in the online retailer Priceline.com fell more than 40
percent Wednesday after the company said its sales in the third
quarter would be as much as 11 percent below analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The company attributed the shortfall to slow sales of airline
tickets _ its signature product, which still account for 87 percent
of its sales. Priceline lets customers offer a set price for a
ticket on the condition that the company can specify the time of
the flight and the airline.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, sales have been hurt because of the
$20 surcharge that the airlines imposed on each round trip to cover
higher fuel costs and because of schedule disruptions at United
Airlines. Moreover, rather than sell more tickets through
Priceline, the airlines chose to have their own fare sales in
September, the company said. To compensate, Priceline encouraged
its customers to make lower bids for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail message sent to customers last week, for example,
sounded an increasingly desperate tone as it described Priceline's
``first ever airline ticket sale.'' It suggested that customers bid
as little as $99 for tickets. ``No reasonable offer will be
refused!'' the e-mail message said.
</P>
<P>
   The only effect of these promotions, the company said Wednesday,
was to reduce revenue even further. They did not increase overall
sales volume, as hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline said that ticket sales in the quarter ending this
month would be $20 million to $25 million less than its sales in
the quarter that ended in June. Even though the company has had as
many customers bidding this quarter, the airlines made available
fewer seats and the average ticket price declined.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the company said it expected revenue in the third
quarter to be $340 million to $345 million. Analysts had estimated
revenue of $360 million to $380 million. In the second quarter, its
revenue was $352 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company estimated that it would lose about 1 cent a share,
the same as it lost in the second quarter, excluding various
noncash charges. As a result, analysts no longer expect the company
to post its first profitable quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several analysts who had been bullish on Priceline _
including Henry Blodget of Merrill Lynch and Anthony Noto of
Goldman, Sachs _ downgraded the stock Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``While consumers may go to Priceline because of high airline
prices or because of concerns about reliability, Priceline may not
be in a position to fill that demand profitably when they are
negatively affected by macroeconomic factors such as higher fuel
costs and any competitive promotional pricing activity,'' Noto
wrote to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Fay Landes, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein, who has been
among Priceline's harshest critics, said the news emphasized the
flaws in the company's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call,'' she said. ``They have a business
that targets cheapskates, and it's hard to make money off them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, the company is vulnerable to being able to
get access to the airline tickets it needs, in the face of the
airlines' own discounting and other competing Internet sites.
``They don't have control of their supply,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline did say that its revenue from other categories _
including bidding for hotel rooms and long-distance telephone calls
_ would grow by 20 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's shares fell $7.89 to $10.75, a record low,
Wednesday. As recently as March, the company's shares were at $104,
giving it a value higher than any airline. Now the company is
valued at $1.8 billion, a relatively modest multiple of 1.4 times
the company's projected $1.3 billion in revenue for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of other Internet travel companies fell on the news.
Travelocity, which has an extensive partnership with Priceline,
fell $2.50, to $12. Expedia, which also runs a name-your-own-price
service, fell by 25 cents, to $14.75.
</P>
<P>
   And stocks of other big Internet companies, which have nothing
to do with airline tickets, also fell sharply on the news. Ebay's
shares dropped $7.19, to $63.50. Amazon.com shares fell $1.88, to
$37.88. And Yahoo, fell $12.06, to $90.38.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
