A4093 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-BARENAKED-REVIEW     09-27 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BARENAKED-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BARENAKED' SURE TO PLEASE GROUP'S FANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 HOUSTON CHRONICLE 
 
For fans of the band Barenaked Ladies, ``Barenaked in America'' is
like an elaborate postcard from the road, full of ``wish you were
here'' delights and highlights.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But beyond fans, it's hard to imagine much audience for this
lively yet limited documentary directed by former teen heartthrob
Jason Priestley (``Beverly Hills 90210'').
</P>
<P>
   At best, these impish, eclectic pop-rockers from Toronto may
grow on the noninitiated _ as people, if not as music makers. After
all, they come across as hard-working, tight-knit and indifferent
to star trips.
</P>
<P>
   But for music and history, ``Barenaked in America'' _ though
well shot and edited _ is a mixed bag.
</P>
<P>
   Musical performances are rarely sustained until the end, and
though the film is filled with interviews of the band and its crew,
it's only a sketchy look at the group's formation and growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barenaked'' is really more of a personality portrait, with the
dominant personalities being singer-guitarists Ed Robertson and
Steven Page.
</P>
<P>
   As shown in concert footage, the latter is a superb vocalist _ a
hearty but controlled belter with a high range _ and both are
buoyant, bouncing, fun-loving showmen, stamping this group with
their irreverent yet never mean-spirited humor.
</P>
<P>
   They're also family men, so the usual rock regimen becomes
``sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll _ hold the sex and drugs.'' (Well,
they do admit a fondness for drink.)
</P>
<P>
   The film's biggest window to their lives is a 1998 tour in
support of the album ``Stunt,'' which provides several songs in
fragments (``Alcohol,'' ``Who Needs Sleep?'').
</P>
<P>
   Between gigs, we see the lads' silly attempt to attract
President Clinton outside the White House and their singing of the
American national anthem at a Philadelphia Flyers hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   They also perform on Conan O'Brien's ``Late Night'' show,
followed by a stiff and seemingly staged meeting backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Tour-bus footage is mundane, but tour stops can be illuminating,
especially an eventful trip to New York. There, the band gets
combative about a video shoot that doesn't go well (for ``It's All
Been Done'').
</P>
<P>
   This candor also extends to trivia, such as determining the
guys' favorite ``Sesame Street'' characters _ as if we care.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the ``too-much-information'' category: Robertson
declaring he could ``grow rice between my toes'' and the band
discussing pre-concert urination rituals.
</P>
<P>
   But amid this larkish if not gonzo behavior comes stellar
musicianship, a hard drive to entertain and one sobering
revelation: the diagnosed leukemia of keyboardist Kevin Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the band to seek treatment, his heroic return to
the stage at film's end brings gravity and soulfulness to an
otherwise airy if not empty-headed affair, especially given the
strong finishing-kick performance of ``Brian Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   At such times, we can almost forget the band is Canadian. But
Priestley, who's also Canadian, seems self-consciously fixated on
it.
</P>
<P>
   We're constantly reminded the Ladies are Canadian, often in
tiresomely nationalisitic ways. There's even an assertion that
Canada discovered the Beatles months before the United States, as
if that matters, even if it's true.
</P>
<P>
   Yet then we're expected to embrace the Ladies as guys who just
happen to be Canadian but, more importantly, are a great band.
</P>
<P>
   We understand: Being Canadian means everything _ yet it's
irrelevant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Barenaked in America'' &QL; 
Starring: Barenaked Ladies &QL; 
Director: Jason Priestley &QL; 
Not rated, but includes profanity and brief nudity &QL; 
Running time: 90 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B-  &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
