<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-REMEMBER-TITANS     09-27 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMEMBER-TITANS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT; 
A STORY TO REMBER, A FILM TO FORGET
</HEADLINE>
bc-REMEMBER-TITANS
cc,78p3  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
A story to 'Remember,' a film to forget &QL; 
By Bob Strauss &QL;
<P>
   Make speech. Throw ball. Make another speech. Win game.
Everybody sing golden oldie. Make speech again.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   End racism.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the formula by which all things get along in
``Remember the Titans,'' an inspirational sports/tolerance
entertainment that, if nothing else, deserves some kind of trophy
for most bogus ``true story'' ever filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Purporting to tell the tale of a just-integrated Alexandria,
Va., high school football team's perfect 1971 season, this
sanitized slice of social consciousness has its heart in the right
place, at least for such a determined exercise in abject
commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   But while the anti-hate message the film relentlessly throws in
our faces -- when it's not busy with the equally vital task of
pumping us up to cheer for pre-ordained gridiron victories, anyway
-- is unassailably admirable, it would have been much more so if we
could believe a second of the film actually happened in the manner
depicted. The situations are so predictable, the characters such
limited stereotypes and the lessons presented so generic that it
all feels like calls from a screenwriting playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington is all hardcase determination (and
unfortunately little more) as Herman Boone, the coach brought in
from South Carolina to take over the forcibly bused team at T.C.
Williams High. This displaces the institution's beloved veteran
coach, Bill Yoast (Will Patton), a fair-minded, churchgoing widower
whose excitable 9-year-old daughter Sheryl (Hayden Panattiere, who
will charm as many people as she'll irritate) knows more about
football than he does.
</P>
<P>
   Though he abhors the thought of playing second fiddle, Yoast
agrees to coach defense when his white players risk their college
careers by refusing to suit up for anyone else. In no time, Yoast
and Boone realize that their love of the game and commitment to
their young charges transcend color barriers. Although Yoast quite
rationally questions Boone's exhaustive training methods -- which
seem less appropriate preparation for varsity athletics than for an
amphibious landing at Haiphong (and that's one more reference to
the then-raging Vietnam conflict than you'll get from the movie) --
he goes along with Boone's orders that black and white athletes
bunk and talk with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Once school actually starts amid angry parental protests, the
football squad is, if not a perfect picture of harmony, at least a
comparatively shining example. In a subplot that eventually goes
the manipulative way of ``Brian's Song,'' the team's white captain
(Ryan Hurst) and most Afrocentric member (Wood Harris) become the
closest of friends. Other meaningful positions are filled by a fat
white transfer (Ethan Suplee) who seems incapable of even noticing
anybody's color and the California hippie transfer (Kip Pardue),
dubbed ``Sunshine,'' whose ta'i chi approach to quarterbacking
proves invincible -- and, get this, who just might happen to be
gay!
</P>
<P>
   There are a few hallway fights, a broken window or two and some
shady conspiring among the district's old boys to drive Boone out
of his job (no uttering of the most common bigoted epithet, though,
at distributor Disney's insistence; the unrealistic absence, while
a lovely ideal, only makes you hear the bad word louder in your
imagination). But none of these fumbles could begin to block the
momentum of the Titans' relentless rush to the state finals and to
love, peace and happiness for all.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably missing from any corner of this Washington suburb is
the least evidence of drug use, homegrown hair, teen-age sexuality
or any of the other myriad forms of youthful rebellion that were
evident in even the deepest South by the '70s. What's specifically
off -- and too bad for the movie's mythmakers, but at least one
unquiet journalist out there is a T.C. Williams Class of '71 alumna
-- is the fact that the school was actually integrated in the
mid-1960s, rendering race an all but moot issue there by the year
of the miracle season.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for all its infuriating Jerry Bruckheimer-production
reductiveness and falsity, ``Remember the Titans'' does do one
thing ineluctably well. Although all the details in Gregory Allen
Howard's script and shortcuts in Boaz Yakin's direction feel wrong,
the film captures the genuinely inspiring, adaptable spirit with
which much of the segregated South, after decades of violent
opposition, so thoroughly accepted equality once forced to. I saw
it happen at my Florida high school in the early '70s, and while
the real process was both more difficult and in some ways more
graceful than that shown in ``Remember the Titans,'' it was the
same kind of beautiful, hard-won thing.
</P>
<P>
   One small expression of school pride, though, if you'll kindly
indulge: We did it despite a football team that well and truly
sucked. &QL; 
-----``REMEMBER THE TITANS'' &QL; 
Rated PG: mild violence, racism, children in jeopardy &QL; 
The stars: Denzel Washington, Will Patton, Wood Harris, Ryan Hurst,
Kip Pardue. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Boaz Yakin. Written by Gregory Allen
Howard. Produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and Chad Oman. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 53 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
