<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield restaurant down for count
 &HT;    By Tinah Saunders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chef John Akhile stood in an empty dining room
Wednesday morning, surveying what had been Holyfield's New South
Grill.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, county marshals guarded the upscale restaurant that
bears the name of boxer Evander Holyfield. They had served eviction
papers earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who lent his name to the business and was a primary
investor, was in Sydney for the Olympic Games and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomas Jorgensen, property manager for the Sandy
Springs, Ga., building, Akhile had not paid rent in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Akhile was a partner, general manager and the man who wrote the
checks. The award-winning chef came to Atlanta's attention at
Buckhead's Azalea and later at the Galleria's Waverly Grill. But
his reputation was not enough to make a success of Holyfield's,
which opened in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had the business,'' Akhile said. ``We did everything
right. We had the demographics that showed people in Sandy Springs
ate out, and we did the community things you are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's demise saddened Sandy Springs business leaders
who commended Akhile for his community involvement. ``He did so
many things to help (the community) out,'' said Donna Gathers,
executive director of the Sandy Springs Business Association. ``He
hosted meetings at little or no cost.'' She said the restaurant's
location, set back between two office towers, made it hard for
potential customers to find.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
