<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-FASHION0928-COX     09-27 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FASHION0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athletes view showmanship as part of sport
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - In Olympic track and field, it is no longer just about
winning, but also how you look as you win. The lanes have been
turned into runways, the athletes models of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about appearances now. From styled hair to audacious
jewelry to painted fingernails to makeup to funky sunglasses to
alluring gear. All of it to make an impression beyond the display
of skill. My, how times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   How much? Even the Russian female athletes, whose stern, stiff
look once symbolized their country's iron-fisted government, bring
a softer, more appealing look with styled hair, makeup and
lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are entertainers,'' said 100-meters gold medalist Maurice
Greene. ``It's a show. So... ''
</P>
<P>
   So, many of them dress like performers. Or like they want to be
seen. Or both. Greene wears gold necklaces and rings and an
earring. His Nike spikes _ resplendent with an array of crossing
colors _ were valued at $100,000 after he tossed them into the
stands following his victory last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I know that, I should get them back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greene's showmanship pales in comparison to hurdler Gail
Devers. Here's a woman with the entire arsenal: heavy makeup, long
blue nails, silver hoop earrings, bright red shoes, a necklace with
a charm on it and the coup de grace _ a silver chain around her
waist, part of which dangles under her shorts and on her thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the late Florence Griffith Joyner did not have this
in mind when she elegantly dominated the 1988 Seoul Olympics.
Griffith Joyner said at the time that being gorgeous made her feel
good, which made her run faster
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance was marked by flowing hair, extended, painted
nails, facial blush, eyeliner and lipstick. She readied herself as
if she was going to a social event.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the point where track is now has been a gradual
progression that has reached an apex. Runners don expensive,
high-tech sunglasses _ even at night. There is enough jewelry, much
of it gaudy, to reflect a Mr. T Starter Kit.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes often do not even match the outfit. Rather, they match
the athlete's need to be seen. Michael Johnson, who sprinted to
Olympic lore in Atlanta in 1996 in his metallic gold spikes, had
another pair (with a brazen red Nike swoosh) for his 400-meter
conquest this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need more of that,'' U.S. 1,500-meter semifinalist
Gabe Jennings said. ``The sprinters, in particular, are the glamour
guys. They rip off their warm-ups and strut around, like `Look at
me.' But we need more of it. It helps with the connection to the
fans. We have to realize that we're performing. This is our
opportunity to connect with the fans. We have to make a race an
entire experience, and that includes looking good to go with
performing good.''
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, is the credo. The women pole vaulters, for
instance, attracted catcalls for their two-piece outfits during
competition that looked more like what the beach volleyball players
wear. Tight-fitting tops and high-cut shorts. Sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Couch, the 100-meter hurdler who lives in Stone Mountain,
recalls an event in Barcelona that typifies pre-race preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the bathroom, in the mirror,'' she recalled. ``All
the athletes. We were putting on makeup. And we just started
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a performance when you go out there and run. If you look
good, you feel good. And when you feel good, you race good.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch wore a funky hairdo with a silver ring and diamond stud
earrings. ``Sprinters are very individualistic,'' she said. ``With
me, Nike gives us such an array to choose from, which is good
because we all have our own tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all have fallen into the fashion-conscious wave. U.S.
hurdles bronze medalist Melissa Morrison sported blue Oakley
sunglasses during her races and two diamond studs in each ear. But
that was it. Her hair was in pigtails and she wore no makeup or
lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   She did have a pair of custom-made Reeboks _ one shoe was blue,
the other red. However, they were abandoned for a pair of old
Reeboks after her first qualifying heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad because Reebok made them for me,'' she said. ``But
they were uncomfortable. That's mostly what I'm into. Comfort. I
don't put much thought into what I wear. If others do _ and they
certainly do, as you can tell _ that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I have on clothes, I can run. Now, if I'm running
naked, then I've got a problem.... The way things are, that might
not be a problem for some others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2030EDT &QL; 
