<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-GIRLFIGHT     09-27 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLFIGHT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BALANCE OF STRENGTH, SENSITIVITY
</HEADLINE>
bc-GIRLFIGHT (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
 &HT;    By GLENN WHIPP 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ``Girlfight'' is both familiar and fresh. It's a classic
Hollywood underdog story given a shot in the arm by its unknown
star, Michelle Rodriguez, who delivers a performance that makes for
a great combination punch -- it's volatile and vulnerable,
masculine and feminine. Even when the movie runs a good 20 minutes
too long, it's never dull, at least not when Rodriguez is on screen
weaving her magic.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez isn't the only new talent on display. Karyn Kusama
makes her writing and directing debut with ``Girlfight,'' and while
the movie has its share of uncertain and predictable moments, it's
clearly the work of a good storyteller with a sharp eye for detail.
The directing award she won at Sundance was deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez plays Diana Guzman, a tough teen-ager living in the
Brooklyn projects who finds herself swimming in a steady stream of
trouble. Teachers and classmates don't understand her and her
clueless father (Paul Calderon) ignores her. Diana wears a mask of
toughness to protect her from the contempt and cruelties of her
world as well as the self-loathing and doubts that come with being
an adolescent.
</P>
<P>
   Diana's life changes after she discovers boxing. Her younger
brother,Tiny (Ray Santiago), is taking lessons at the local gym,
not because he wants to, but because his father wants to squelch
Tiny's artistic dreams and see him adhere to old definitions of
manhood. But it's Diana, not the sensitive Tiny, who becomes
enthralled by the energy and excitement of the ring, and soon she's
stealing money and pawning her meager possessions to pay for
training lessons.
</P>
<P>
   At the gym, Diana meets Hector (Jaime Tirelli), a Panamanian
immigrant who agrees to train her, and, in the process, becomes a
surrogate father. She also begins a wary friendship with a handsome
young boxer, Adrian (Santiago Douglas), which blossoms into a kind
of Romeo-and-Juliet romance. Diana's father remains unaware of his
daughter's new hobby and new love; his ignorance does not translate
into bliss, however.
</P>
<P>
   In its training and athletic scenes, ``Girlfight'' plays like
``Rocky'' and a host of other sports films that feature an underdog
facing long odds. But Kusama invests other sections of the movie --
particularly the guarded relationship between the young innocents
-- with such authenticity that we can forgive lapses of
predictability. She's aided enormously by the charisma of her two
young leads. Douglas is a find in his own right, a perfect balance
of strength and sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Girlfight'' belongs to Rodriguez, who gives Diana a
compelling combativeness borne out of heartfelt desperation. Kusama
found the 21-year-old actress at an open casting call, and you
can't imagine anyone else playing the part. In her brief bio,
Rodriguez says she aspires to be an action hero. With
``Girlfight,'' she's already there and then some. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
``GIRLFIGHT'' &QL; 
(Rated R:for language) &QL; 
-The stars: Michelle Rodriguez, Jaime Tirelli, Santiago Douglas,
Ray Santiago, Paul Calderon. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Karyn Kusama. Released
by Screen Gems. &QL; 
-Running time: 2 hours. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
