</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    12 writers split Southern pool of prize money
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a week for literary prizes. The Atlanta-based
Southern Regional Council announced three winners of the Lillian
Smith Book Awards, and the Lannan Foundation handed out $700,000 to
nine authors.
</P>
<P>
   Evan S. Connell, whose 1984 ``Son of the Morning Star''
eloquently retells the story of George Armstrong Custer, was
awarded a $100,000 lifetime achievement award from the Lannan
Foundation. Other winners are poets Herbert Morris and Jay Wright;
fiction writers Robert Coover, David Malouf, Cynthia Ozick and
Leslie Marmon Silko; and nonfiction authors Bill McKibben and Carl
Safina.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of the Lillian Smith Book Award, named for the Georgia
civil rights pioneer and author of ``Strange Fruit,'' are Michael
Keith Honey for ``Black Workers Remember: An Oral History of
Segregation, Unionism and the Freedom Struggle''; Andrew M. Manis
for ``A Fire You Can't Put Out: The Civil Rights Life of
Birmingham's Reverend Fred Shuttlesworth''; and Lawrence N. Powell
for ``Troubled Memory: Anne Levy, the Holocaust, and David Duke's
Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be presented at a noon luncheon Nov. 17 at the
Sheraton Colony Square. A young writers workshop will be held in
conjunction with the awards at 10 a.m., featuring Atlanta authors
Melissa Fay Greene (``Praying for Sheetrock'') and Anthony Grooms
(``Trouble No More''). Information: 404-522-8764, Ext. 28, or
www.southerncouncil.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's in a name? It's clear by now that Oprah Winfrey likes
books with women characters who triumph over seemingly
insurmountable obstacles. Apparently she also is partial to
characters named Ruth. The talk show queen's 37th book club
selection is ``Drowning Ruth'' (Doubleday, $23.95) by debut
novelist Christina Schwarz. An earlier Oprah selection was Jane
Hamilton's ``The Book of Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in Wisconsin at the end of World War I, Schwarz's novel
focuses on Amanda Starke, a Lutheran farmer's daughter who returns
to the family farm after being seduced and shamed. When Amanda's
brother-in-law returns from the war, he finds his wife dead of
mysterious circumstances and his young daughter, Ruth, in Amanda's
care. Amanda will tell him nothing about the night his wife drowned
or about what happened to her parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other media: Nelson DeMille has sold the movie rights for ``Up
Country,'' the sequel to ``The General's Daughter.'' The catch is,
DeMille hasn't finished the book yet. Publishers Weekly reports
that Paramount has paid seven figures for the synopsis alone. John
Travolta has agreed to star again as U.S. Army investigator Paul
Brenner. ... British author Frederick Forsyth is following in
Stephen King's electronic footsteps with ``Quintet,'' a series of
five new stories that will be offered in eBook format at the Online
Originals site at www
</P>
<P>
   .onlineoriginals.com.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
