<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-LIVING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.28.00
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris and John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Fate of VH1 shows just a click away
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Senior surfers are tune-ing up
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Privacy concerns power creative answers
</P>
<P>
   SHOWING OFF: Thumbs up or thumbs down? VH1 is giving viewers a
chance to go online and decide the fate of five new series. At 8
p.m. Friday, viewers can tune into ``VH1 Feedback,'' watch the
entire shows and then go to the network's Web site and decide which
programs should stay and which ones should go. The nominees:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``EveryNight'': A hip musical late-night talk and variety show
.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Reunion'': Former bandmates who have parted ways get a
second chance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fish 'n' Clips'': Two offbeat fish, Lemmy and Sparkles,
comment on music videos in a mix of animation, live action and
music.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Radical Recut'': Music videos are recut with reality footage
from police chase videos, hidden security cameras and more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``break.through'': New musical acts get a chance at national
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   www.vh1.com
</P>
<P>
   GRAY MATTERS: Don't be surprised if Grandma asks to borrow your
MP3 player for bingo night. Contrary to perceptions that online
music sharing is confined to the skateboard-and-body-piercing
crowd, there's new evidence that older people also are downloading
their favorite tunes or accessing music from other sites. Media
Metrix reports 6.8 million unique visitors 50 and older went to
music-related sites in June, up 92 percent from 3.55 million a year
earlier. That's more than twice the average growth for such sites
in same period. Also, the older crowd represented 17 percent of the
traffic on music-sharing Web sites in June.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE OR FALSE: A survey of 700 adult Internet users shows their
concerns over privacy and the safety of personal data causes 23
percent to regularly provide false information when visiting Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by SpectraCom.Inc., also found:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  92 percent said they sometimes refuse to provide personal
information, with more than a quarter saying they frequently
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About eight out of 10 are somewhat or very comfortable
providing their e-mail addresses, education, marital status, ethnic
origin and hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Only 7 percent are comfortable providing a Social Security
number.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  16 percent are OK with providing a bank account number.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 40 percent say they're somewhat or very comfortable
providing their credit-card numbers online.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the next logical question: Can you survey
participants who already have admitted that they lie online?
</P>
