<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE NEXT NEW THING ON YOUR INTERNET DASHBOARD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL TORCHIA AND MATT CARROLL   c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past five years, the creative breeding ground of the
Internet has changed our lives with a dizzyingly long list of
innovations: browsing, e-mail, online auctions, day trading,
instant messaging, Napster. While not all consumers have used
everything, most have become dependent on at least one.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been an altogether smooth ride. People have thrown up
their hands in frustration after wandering in the Internet
wilderness searching for, say, the cheapest airline ticket. Or they
have cringed at the idea of handing over personal information to
anonymous online vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the problems that have spawned the next big thing on
the Net, one that is expected to give more power to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon: software applications that will search the Net for
you, comparison shopping for a used car, and taking into account
your desire for something with CD player and six cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   Another application will search out blue-chip stocks with solid
earnings that will appeal to your conservative financial views. And
a third will alert the local oil dealer with the best price around
that you are low on heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   These separate applications _ and others that collect specific
information on everything from stamp collecting to medical records
_ will be viewed through one overarching, personal ``dashboard''
that will display all the information that has been collected.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard program will also jealously protect a consumer's
personal and financial privacy by releasing just the data needed to
make a purchase, and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   These changes will flip the traditional business model on its
head. Until now, companies have told consumers what was available
and at what price. Now a customer's software will tell a company
what the consumer wants and what price the person is willing to
pay. Interested companies will need to scramble to fulfill that
need.
</P>
<P>
   Leverage will shift to a new type of proactive consumer _ a
``prosumer,'' perhaps? This consumer _ no longer locked into any
one particular company _ will be empowered to pick and choose based
on criteria they establish, and it will be up to companies to meet
it.
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces of this are available now and more are coming.
ByAllAccounts.com of Woburn, Mass., which was launched in July,
offers consumers a single place to monitor and analyze financial
data. The idea is to help individuals, who might have portfolios
with a half-dozen or more financial companies, pull that
information together, said L. Patrick Gardner, co-founder and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Users set up online accounts with the company, which collects
the information from the companies where the user keeps accounts.
The software offers tools to measure investment performance and can
send alerts when there are important changes.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like this allow consumers to gain more control. With
information centralized, consumers can more easily measure their
own financial health, as well as more easily measure the
performance of the financial institutions that are caring for
users' investments. Gardner sees this as just a start, and ``the
next step is to offer guidance or advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Another startup, VigilTech.com in Acton, Mass., has built
software that searches the Internet to provide desktop information
on specific topics to business users, said Gidi Cohen, founder and
chief executive officer. Users can create their own custom
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our technology takes input from the user and then adapts as it
scours the Internet, to provide information to the desktop on what
you need and want, when you need and want it,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have developed software that makes it easy for
buyers to comparison shop. Frictionless Commerce of Cambridge,
Mass. sells its software to sites such as Lycos.com, which uses it
in its comparison shopping section, said Robert H. Guttman,
co-founder and chief technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   The software can be used to find the best prices on everything
from car seats to laptops; from printers to in-line skates. ``We
have pieces of software that crawl the Web and find pieces of
information,'' Guttman said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is just the beginning. These companies, or new
companies, will push this concept into new directions. The end
result will be greater ease for users in finding what they need.
</P>
<P>
   Changes are also being driven by concerns about protecting
personal privacy. People have read about online thefts of credit
card numbers and the recent bankruptcy fight over Toysmart.com, in
which supposedly protected personal data about customers may be
tossed on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Pattie Maes, an associate professor at MIT's Media Lab, is
acutely aware of the concerns people have over protecting their
personal data. Maes founded Firefly Network Inc., which was one of
the first companies to commercialize technology for building
profiles of its users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it has to be the user that has control,'' she
said. While obstacles remain from legal to cultural, the time is
right for consumers to grab much greater control of their own data,
she said. ``It is a real need right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that personal profile data is sold to other
companies without your knowing it. There is no reason, she says,
that users should not be able to use their own data to negotiate
better deals.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, some of the new software fulfills old business
ideas called ``sense and respond.'' It's not an original online
idea. It is, for example, what oil companies have done for years by
counting degree days and thus knowing when to fill a customers'
tank before it is empty.
</P>
<P>
   But online companies can carry the idea a step further. What if
consumers didn't lock into one particular oil company? What if they
bought from whichever dealer happened to have the lowest price? And
what if this all happened automatically?
</P>
<P>
   That's the promise of the new era in software. Soon it will
suggest we transfer money to a new bank with higher interest rates
on CDs, look through our doctor's computer to get the results of
the latest lab test, get test scores from school, and maybe catch a
note from the baseball coach about how Junior needs to work on
ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   We're not quite there yet. But it's where smart consumer
companies are headed. They know that we, the consumers, want _ make
that, deserve _ the ultimate in customer experience. Smart
companies will work hard to find out exactly what consumers want,
educate them about their product or service, and then provide it
when asked. It's the next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Paul Torchia is a managing director for Scient Corp. in Cambridge.
Mass. Matt Carroll is a Globe reporter, and designed the
newspaper's first Intranet site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-26-00 1343EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
