<HEADLINE>
WEB SLOW TO RESHAPE POLITICAL REPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  c.2000 The Boston Globe 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Web hasn't changed political news coverage much _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   That's the view among political professionals, Web specialists,
and political reporters who have watched the rise of the new medium
with varying degrees of enthusiasm and concern.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some are disappointed. For years, the Web has been seen
as a technology that could reinvigorate democracy, by creating
direct communication channels among the governed and by opening
dialogue with public officials. To date, it has blurred the lines
between news organizations and political Web sites, as both compete
to offer information to voters and to fact-check the claims of
opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, a host of start-up companies calling themselves
``democracy portals'' want to serve the same market. At
Grassroots.com, for instance, users can read about Senator Joseph
I. Lieberman's predictions on voter turnout or read comments on
George W. Bush's environmental voting record from a Gainesville,
Fla., nurse using the screen name ``RationalMind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately sites like these promise to ``make national politics
truly national,'' according to Governor Jim Gilmore of Virginia.
Gilmore, a Republican, has emerged as one of the Web's biggest
boosters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC;  But even Gilmore says he can't name an example in which an
online news item or coverage on the the Web has altered the
dynamics of his campaigning and governing. The most persistent
questions still come from reporters from traditional news
organizations, and their output remains the most widely read source
of information for most voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beginning the process of the application of the
Internet to the political process,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, reporters from traditional news organization,
like the Dallas Morning News, whose questions have created the most
difficulties for Bush. In contrast, the most talked-about Web
journalism this year was probably a piece by Dan Savage, a writer
for Salon.com. In his piece, ``Stalking Gary Bauer,'' Savage
described licking office doorknobs in an effort to spread a cold
and derail the conservative candidate's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Early expectations for the Web were probably too lofty. One
basic problem is that slow connections for most viewers limit the
Web's ability to offer compelling video. ``The concepts are true,
that the Web will change things,'' said Dana Milbank, who writes
about politics for The Washington Post. ``But the promise hasn't
been realized. It will have a profound effect on politics, but not
in this cycle. Probably in the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Perhaps the most significant impact of the Web has been to
bring print media into a constant-news mindset, a change
cable-television news had already forced on the networks. Now
newspapers and magazines are also pressing their reporters to write
quick, short versions of their stories for the Web during the day,
much as newspapers used to update themselves with afternoon
editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of a news cycle is almost passe,'' said Jeff
Zeleny, who covered the Iowa caucuses for the Des Moines Register
and now writes for the Chicago Tribune. ``I found myself filing
Internet updates and posting stuff from the trail all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention to the Web's impact on politics began in earnest
during the 1996 election cycle, the first time both major
presidential candidates invited users to visit their campaign
operations online. Since then, operatives have proved the Web can
be used as an effective campaign tool in specific instances.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the impeachment proceedings against President
Clinton, for instance, even Republicans acknowledged the
Democratic-leaning site, MoveOn.org, which drew 500,000 signatures
and pledges of $13 million to urge Congress to move on to weightier
topics. During his campaign for president, Senator John McCain
often mentioned his Web site; in the two days after his victory in
the New Hampshire primary, he raised $1 million with the help of
his Web site, according to PoliticsNow.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-26-00 1403EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
