<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
 INFORMIX MOVE REFLECTS EAST-WEST COAST TENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM   c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTBOROUGH, Mass. _ When Informix announced in August that it
would move its headquarters here from posh Menlo Park, Calif., the
bicoastal headlines could not have been more different.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, readers of the San Jose Mercury News were
told, ``Informix Bows Out of Silicon Valley.'' In the East, the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette's headline celebrated the
cross-country move and the creation of ``About 100 Jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Informix a defeated company, exiting with its tail between
its legs? Or is it a corporate hero, creating jobs in this edge
town outside the Interstate 495 arc?
</P>
<P>
   In the longstanding rivalry between the Bay State and the Bay
Area for the gold medal in cutting-edge technology, the title still
belongs to Silicon Valley. But what may be most significant about
Informix's decision to move its headquarters east is what it says
about the shifting relationship between east and west.
</P>
<P>
   There have been others. In recent months, PlanetRX.com, InsWeb
Corp., Performance Polymer Technologies, and Galil Motion Control
have decamped from Silicon Valley altogether. Travelocity,
Pets.com, and Egghead.com have joined Informix in moving some
company divisions out of the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Informix executives say that being in Westborough amounts to a
25 percent reduction in rent, based on the terms of their lease. If
they were to pay today's market rates, the differential would be
even greater, over 60 percent, said Tony Riggio, the company's
director of public relations.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Silicon Valley's cachet continues to attract as many
technology companies as it loses. And Informix isn't technically
leaving California. Though its corporate headquarters will be in
Westborough, the majority of its workers will remain on the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really just moving two exits down the road,'' said Peter
Fiore, president of Informix's services and consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Informix, which is battling flat revenues and disappointing
earnings, is effectively splitting the company in two. One company
_ Informix Software, headed by James D. Foy _ will be based in Palo
Alto. The other, a yet-to-be-named e-business consulting and
services firm headed by Fiore, will be based in Westborough.
</P>
<P>
   Which coast is getting the better half of Informix?
</P>
<P>
   Some would say it's Silicon Valley, which is getting the part of
the company that generates $800 million in annual sales, or 85
percent of the comany's total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Others would argue it's Massachusetts. While the Westborough
subsidiary is forecast to have just over $120 million in sales this
year, it is expected to grow 80 percent to 100 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay State will also be home to the parent company, Informix
Corp., which ended up in Massachusetts when it acquired
fast-growing Ardent Software in March for $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new chief executive, Peter Gyenes, was president
of Ardent, and half of Informix's senior management team also came
from the Westborough-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though Ardent was the company being acquired, their key
managers turned out to be very sharp and capable,'' said Hurwitz.
As a result, the locus of leadership shifted towards Massachusetts,
she said. ``The talent for the more dynamic part of their business
turned out to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Silicon Valley, ground zero for all things
futuristic, is ending up with the slow-growing technology business,
while Massachusetts, once known for its dying minicomputer
industry, is ending up with the cutting-edge firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that both coasts win in this,'' said Fiore,
downplaying the competition. ``They each get a company.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But what's different is that Massachusetts is
clearly back in the race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham, a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley, visited
Massachusetts last week. She can be reached by e-mail at
pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-26-00 1406EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
