 &HT;    EDS: This version replaces the earlier version.
 &HT;    Tonight's main attraction is Marion Jones
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's no doubt about the highlight of tonight's
telecast: Marion Jones' attempt to win her second gold medal of the
Games. Adding to the intrigue is the challenge offered by
Australia's national heroine Cathy Freeman. The rest of the
prime-time lineup pales in marquee value to this showdown, but the
men's 200 meters, long jump and decathlon are more than bit
players. Americans Coby MIller, Floyd Heard and John Capel Jr. all
reached the semifinals and have a chance to contend for a medal in
the 200. Georgia Tech assistant coach Chris Huffins ranks among the
leaders going into the conclusion of the decathlon, while Tucker
High graduate Dwight Phillips is the lone U.S. hope in the long
jump The late-night telecast will feature Georgian Shareef
Adbur-Rahim and his NBA mates facing Russia in a quarterfinal
basketball game, and MSNBC (TV 33) has the gold-medal match in
women's soccer between the U.S. and Norway. The last look at tennis
stars Venus and Serena Williams in action will be on CNBC, which
has their doubles gold-medal match against the Netherlands' Kristie
Boogert and Miriam Oremans.
</P>
