<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-NAPSTER-2TAK     09-27 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-NAPSTER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO STOLE MY INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN   c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the beginning of the summer, a copy of an unreleased single
from Madonna's upcoming album ``Music'' found its way onto Napster,
the popular file-swapping service. Needless to say, the Material
Girl was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   And she was not alone. As the summer wore on, illicit copies of
other forms of entertainment appeared all over the Internet.
Bootleg versions of such movie blockbusters as ``Gladiator'' and
``Me, Myself, and Irene'' popped up on networks like Scour Exchange
and Gnutella shortly after their release in theaters. And the
hottest book of the season, ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire,'' was traded illegally online within hours after it hit the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, file sharing isn't just for music anymore. Virtually
anything that can be reduced to digital bits is becoming a
commodity, and the entertainment and publishing industries are
grappling with ways to protect copyrighted material at a time when
the very notion of intellectual property is being challenged. Even
the needlepoint industry is running scared: Ladies who stitch
samplers are trading patterns online, and one pattern publisher,
South Carolina-based Pegasus Originals, has reported a 40 percent
drop in revenue since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tension is building between the old economy copyright owners _
the record labels, movie studios, and publishing houses _ and the
new economy entrepreneurs who are constantly inventing new ways to
distribute content. Meanwhile, consumers are rapidly embracing the
new technology even as the entertainment industry is frantically
trying to curtail its spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a turf war going on over the hearts and minds of
consumers and the way they use content,'' says Eric Sheirer, media
and entertainment analyst for Forrester Research. ``The content
industry and the technology industry are battling it out, and they
really can't both win. Their interests are not aligned.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the content industry appears to be winning _ at least in
the courts. Two weeks ago, a federal judge ruled that MP3.com
violated the copyrights of Universal Music Group by offering its
CDs for play over the Internet and ordered potentially crippling
damages that could hit $250 million. Last month, the Motion Picture
Industry Association of America scored a victory when a federal
judge ruled that it is illegal to publish DeCSS, a program used to
crack antipiracy features on DVDs. And in July, a federal judge in
San Francisco issued an injunction to shut down the wildly popular
Napster service; the order is on hold pending appeal, and the case
returns to the courts next month.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the court rulings, the concept of file-sharing is
becoming ingrained in the public consciousness. Users, particularly
college students and young professionals, are growing accustomed to
easy access to music sampling services, and litigation only seems
to increase Napster's hold on the popular imagination. For
instance, traffic to Napster.com surged the week after the court
ruling, according to Media Metrix, the New York-based market
research firm that measures Internet usage. And in July, Napster
hit Media Metrix's list of the top 50 US digital media and Web
properties; the service currently claims to have more than 20
million users.
</P>
<P>
   So can tens of millions of people be wrong? ``You can't impose a
law that is not morally upheld by the vast majority of people,''
says Internet activist John Perry Barlow, cofounder of the
Electronic Freedom Foundation. ``And you can't impose a standard
that can be broken _ and just about all of them can.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just an economic battle between those who hold that
information should be free and those who claim they ought to be
paid for content. There are enormous cultural implications to the
debate as well. There is nothing new about file sharing; early
adopters have been sharing digital photographs (albeit, mostly
pornography) and text files since the early days of bulletin board
services. But now that file sharing has become mainstream, the
technology creates enormous potential for previously unheard voices
to reach the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Unsigned record artists, independent filmmakers, and unknown
novelists are all using the Internet to get their products seen and
heard by the public, creating new niche markets and forging offbeat
cultural communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge cultural advantages to allowing or facilitating
Internet distribution of these materials,'' says Harvard Law School
professor William Fisher. ``It expands the set of authors who can
reach the media and reduces the grip on popular culture by a small
number of dominant American companies. It would be a tragedy if the
opportunity for the communication of these materials were lost
because of excessive protectionism.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, artists must have some incentive to
create their work in the first place. ``Unless we can come up with
alternative arrangements for compensating creators, those
incentives will be eroded, and we'll be throwing out the baby with
the bath water,'' Fisher adds. ``And that is an equal tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the dilemma. How do you encourage the cultural
diversification made possible by the Internet while also ensuring
that artists get paid for their work? Some in the entertainment
industry insist that the immediate solution lies in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to make it very clear that stealing is wrong, and
we will not hesitate to go to the courts,'' says Jack Valenti,
president of the Motion Picture Association, which is suing
Scour.com, the company that runs a popular multimedia search engine
and file-swapping service.
</P>
<P>
   But most legal scholars _ and a growing number of executives in
the entertainment industry _ contend that the lawsuits are a waste
of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the large verdict against MP3.com, lawsuits
aren't a very good way to make money,'' says Mark Lemley, a
professor of intellectual property law at the University of
California at Berkeley law school. ``If we are going to get a
solution, it is going to come from the content industry being
willing to make the leap into online distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the content companies have claimed all along that
they plan to come out with systems that enable consumers to
purchase and hear music online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see litigation as the be-all and the end-all,'' says
Hilary Rosen, president and CEO of the Recording Industry
Association of America, the umbrella group representing the music
industry in the cases against Napster, MP3.com, and Scour. ``I see
it as an important tool in sending a message to venture capitalists
that the way to support innovation is to respect the creative
interests. But I am also very clear that the music business has to
evolve, and it is in everybody's interest to create a legitimate
online music business.''
</P>
<P>
   But the music industry, in particular, tends to move with the
speed of an oil tanker negotiating a narrow inlet. And so far, its
online efforts have been less than spectacular. EMI, Sony, and
Universal Music Group recently entered the digital download
business, offering a limited number of albums for sale online. But
consumers used to the ease of Napster haven't exactly raced to
check out these offerings, and the few consumers who have tried to
buy digital music from the major labels have experienced technical
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that there have been growing pains, and
some initial starts have been awkward,'' concedes Rosen. ``Everyone
is doing the best they can, and there is a will and a path and a
huge amount of investment going into doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the technical problems, the music industry has
suffered a backlash since it took on Napster and other file-sharing
services. After the heavy metal band Metallica sued Napster, its
own fans ridiculed the band and its leader, drummer Lars Ulrich,
posting parodies of the band online and vowing to boycott their
albums.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the book industry wants to learn from the music
industry's mistakes and avoid a public relations embarrassment. As
a group, the book publishers haven't been as aggressive in taking
their case to the courts, for a number of reasons. The book
audience is older than the popular music audience, and piracy is
not as prevalent _ yet. Likewise, electronic reading devices are
still a novelty embraced primarily by early adopters.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the book industry is sitting back idly.
``We are watching the litigation very closely,'' says Allan Adler,
vice president of legal and government affairs for the Association
of American Publishers. Last month, the association launched an
anti-piracy Web site and announced a strategy to promote legal,
protected books for sale online.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one author, science fiction writer Harlan Ellison,
says the industry isn't doing enough to ward off piracy. His books
and stories are routinely traded online, and he has sued individual
Web site operators as well as Internet service providers, including
America Online, that he claims facilitate piracy. He won a case
against an individual pirate, but he has been unsuccessful so far
battling the big ISPs in the courts. Ellison sees a sense of
urgency in dealing with the problem and has one word to describe
publishers who have yet to take legal action: ``Dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
NYT-09-26-00 1409EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
