<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS HEAR EXECUTIVES TESTIFY ON CHILDREN AND MOVIE VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs to rewrite and add information; story grows by about 720
words.)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican and Democratic politicians on Wednesday
intensified their criticism of the way violent movies are marketed
to children, as eight Hollywood executives appeared before a Senate
committee and tried to explain their companies' actions and
differed on whether they would continue to market R-rated films to
children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a new industry policy announced Tuesday to limit
that kind of marketing, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said, ``My
friends, that language is not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, the movie companies set a ``goal of not
inappropriately specifically targeting children'' in advertising
and promoting R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand this language,'' said McCain, chairman of
the commerce committee. ``I think it's filled with loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic
vice presidential candidate, said the language of the movie
industry's policy ``almost suggests that one could appropriately
specifically target children in their advertising of R-rated films,
and that's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Capitol Hill, Lynne Cheney, whose
husband, Dick, is the Republican nominee for vice president,
accused the Democrats of talking out of both sides of their mouths
_ criticizing Hollywood ``with a wink and a nudge'' and then
soliciting money from the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The eight executives at the hearing of the Senate Commerce
Committee were asked one by one whether they would promise not to
market R-rated films directly to children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the executives said they would, and four said they would
not, insisting that some R-rated movies were appropriate for
teen-agers younger than 17 who went with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Under the industry's voluntary code, children under 17 are not
supposed to be admitted to movies rated R unless they are
accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who would not take the pledge, Mel Harris,
president and chief operating officer of Sony Pictures
Entertainment, said it was a ``judgment lapse'' for his company to
try to advertise a film with violent scenes on a children's
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Harris defended Columbia Pictures, a subsidiary of Sony, in
another instance when children aged 9 to 11 were interviewed as
part of the test marketing of a violent R-rated movie. But Harris
said the studio would stop using under-age children in focus groups
unless they were accompanied by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate hearing was called in response to the Federal Trade
Commission report released Sept. 11 that the vast majority of
adult-rated movies, recordings and electronic games were marketed
to children.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of the morning-long hearing, Sen. Sam
Brownback, R-Kan., told the movie executives: ``You've really got
to help us out. Parents are really struggling out there. You are
part of the solution and part of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It was left up to the movie studios whom to send to testify
Wednesday, and those who appeared were not the highest ranking
executives. For instance, Robert Iger, the president of Walt Disney
Co., testified instead of the more prominent chairman, Michael
Eisner, and Harris testified for Sony instead of the chairman, John
Calley.
</P>
<P>
   Without being asked, Harris gave an explanation of two instances
described in a front-page article in The New York Times on
Wednesday in which movies with violence made by Columbia Pictures
were marketed to young children.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the studio tried to advertise ``The Fifth
Element,'' a science-fiction thriller starring Bruce Willis, on
Nickelodeon, a network with an audience mostly 12 years old and
younger. The network refused to accept the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our advertisement buyers went astray,'' Harris said. ``That
was a judgment lapse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, researchers hired by the company interviewed
50 9- to 11-year-old children to evaluate concepts for the sequel
to ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' a tale of a serial slasher
who wielded an ice hook.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the producer was surprised to learn from the
researchers that a large number of young children went to that
movie, and he was interested in their views. In preparation for the
sequel, ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,'' researchers
called the parents of children who had seen the first movie, asked
their permission to speak with the children and then interviewed
the children on the telephone, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the procedure was acceptable since the
parents gave permission, but he promised that children under 17
would not be used again in test marketing by his company unless
their parents were actually with them.
</P>
<P>
   The executives from Disney, DreamWorks SKG, 20th Century Fox
Film Corp. and Warner Bros. pledged not to appeal directly to
children under 17 in advertisements of R-rated films. In addition
to Harris, executives from Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Studios, Paramount
Pictures and Universal Studios refused to take that pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Snider, chairman of Universal, said her studio certainly
would not ``market R-rated films to 12-year-olds,'' but she said
many R-rated movies were ``suitable for mature teen-agers to see
with their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris McGurk, vice chairman and chief operating officer of MGM,
said his studio would release two R-rated movies about World War II
next year that ``could be of great value to mature teens.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At another hearing on a different topic on the other side of the
Capitol, an awkward moment occurred when Rep. Steve Largent,
R-Okla., out of the blue asked Gerald M. Levin, chairman of Time
Warner, whether he thought the media promoted violence.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, whose son, Jonathan, a schoolteacher, was killed in New
York in 1997 by a former student, responded that he doubted that
Largent had actually experienced violence as a personal tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   y
</P>
