<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ANTHROPOLOGY-BOOK-ART     09-27 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHROPOLOGY-BOOK-ART-1210(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK ATTACKS SCIENTISTS WHO STUDIED BRAZIL INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif., Pa., Brazil, Venezuela)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD and SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A book about anthropologists working with isolated Indians in
Amazonia has touched off a raging storm in the profession, reviving
scholarly animosities, endangering personal reputations and, some
of the parties say, threatening to undermine confidence in
legitimate practices of anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, ``Darkness in El Dorado: How Scientists and
Journalists Devastated the Amazon,'' Patrick Tierney, a journalist,
presents evidence showing that in 1968 anthropologists, supported
by the former Atomic Energy Commission, inoculated several
communities of the Yanomami Indians with a measles vaccine. He
suggests that this experiment possibly contributed to the epidemic
of the disease that broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds, perhaps thousands'' of people died in a population
of little more than 20,000, the author reported.
</P>
<P>
   This is the most inflammatory of several cases described by
Tierney as examples of careless and perhaps unethical behavior by
anthropologists and filmmakers who visited and studied the
Yanomami. Living in the Amazon basin of southern Venezuela and
northern Brazil and having virtually no contact with the outside
world until the 1950s, the Yanomami have become to social
scientists models of what primitive Stone Age cultures must have
been like.
</P>
<P>
   Some anthropologists who have read the book or a summary of the
allegations joined the attack, urging the American Anthropological
Association or some other scientific body to undertake a thorough
investigation of the ``imminent scandal.'' They expressed concern
that the allegations would make it more difficult to gain
permission to conduct field work in many countries and win the
trust of subjects of their studies.
</P>
<P>
   Others who are familiar with some of book's contents insisted
that the allegations were either unfounded or exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of project was Dr. James V. Neel, a specialist in
human genetics at the University of Michigan and member of the
National Academy of Sciences, who died in February.
</P>
<P>
   A young protege of Neel and a junior member of the 1968
expedition was Dr. Napoleon A. Chagnon, now an emeritus professor
of anthropology at the University of California at Santa Barbara.
He denied the allegations, calling them part of a ``long vendetta
against me'' by some of the critics. ``No Indians that we gave the
vaccine to died,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   As charges and countercharges raced back and forth over the
Internet and telephone in the last 10 days, several prominent
anthropologists have sprung to Chagnon's defense, saying the
implied charges were not credible.
</P>
<P>
   Medical scientists said they doubted that the vaccine itself
could have caused a widespread outbreak of measles or directly
caused so many deaths, even among people with little resistance to
the disease, like the Yanomami. They said it was more likely that
carriers of the disease had introduced it to the villages at about
the same time that the vaccination program was under way.
</P>
<P>
   International health workers worried that a suspicion of
unethical practices related to the measles outbreak, even if proved
untrue, would raise more obstacles to vaccination programs that are
needed to control infectious diseases, particularly in Third World
countries where approval of such campaigns is already being
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney's book is to be published by W.W. Norton on Nov. 16 and
is scheduled to be excerpted in The New Yorker next week. Only
galley proofs of the book have been available so far. A spokesman
said that Tierney was declining all interviews until the book's
publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not rush to judgment, especially since the book
hasn't been published yet,'' Dr. Louise Lamphere, president of the
anthropological association, said in an interview. ``In case
violations did occur, we're going to have to find some way to deal
with them. It's not like anthropologists are doctors or attorneys
who can have their licenses revoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barbara Johnston, chairwoman of the association's human
rights committee, said she was organizing a panel discussion on the
book on Nov. 16 at the association's annual meeting in San
Francisco. Tierney has agreed to participate, but Chagnon said in a
widely circulated e-mail message that he would decline. ``She is
inviting me to a feeding frenzy in which I am the bait,'' he
complained.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Tierney wrote that Neel's Yanomami vaccine project
was a continuation of the Atomic Energy Commission studies on the
effects of radiation on human subjects, which the scientist had
participated in since the end of World War II. The commission
wanted thousands of Yanomami blood samples to determine genetic
mutation rates in a population completely uncontaminated by
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Neel had established an international reputation for discovering
the genetic nature of thalassemia, a form of anemia that occurs
among those of Greek or Italian descent, and demonstrating that
sickle-cell anemia is a protective adaptation against malaria. Both
were major research insights.
</P>
<P>
   But Neel also espoused some controversial views. According to
the book, Neel believed that there was such a thing as a
``leadership gene,'' and that a genetically isolated society like
the Yanomami would be an ideal place to study this, presumably as
the result of dominant men having more chances than lesser ones to
reproduce their genes and pass on their leadership qualities.
</P>
<P>
   In the book Tierney does not reach a conclusion about the motive
for the vaccine experiment. But in a long letter summarizing the
book's allegations, two anthropologists, Dr. Terence Turner of
Cornell University and Dr. Leslie E. Sponsel of the University of
Hawaii, speculated that a likely motive for spreading the measles
epidemic _ if the harshest allegations are correct _ might have
been to support Neel's genetic theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible,'' Turner and Sponsel wrote, that Neel
``thought that genetically superior members'' of these isolated
groups ``might prove to have differential levels of immunity and
thus higher rates of survival to imported diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Turner and Sponsel said there appeared to be no written
text or recorded speech by Neel to back up this contention, they
noted that the book raised questions about why the anthropologists
never explained why the vaccine was used, even after earlier
evidence emerged linking the inoculations to the cause or spread of
the epidemic. Tierney also reported some evidence that he said
showed that the research team might have abandoned some of the
epidemic victims without treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the allegations are proven true, it will mean crimes
against humanity have been committed,'' Turner said in an
interview. He and Sponsel were cited by Tierney as sources of
``comments and encouragement'' in preparing the book.
</P>
<P>
   Chagnon, however, said the vaccinations were a ``humanistic,
very humane activity on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Glenn Smith, an anthropologist at the University of
California at Davis and a former colleague, said: ``I knew Jim Neel
for nearly 30 years and what people are saying about him sounds
like a witch hunt. I can assure you he didn't think the Yanomami
had a gene for headmanship. That is preposterous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tierney emphasized that the vaccine used was a strong live-virus
strain, known as Edmonston B. Medical scientists said that the
World Health Organization had issued advisories in 1965 that the
vaccine should be used with caution, accompanied by doses of gamma
globulin. An improved vaccine was available by 1968 but was not
used by the anthropologists.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William H. Foege, a former director of the Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta, said: ``Edmonston B was one of the
first measles vaccines, and was strong and sometimes caused severe
reactions that were like a light case of measles. But I would be
very surprised if the vaccine caused a death, particularly death in
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the controversy heated up last week, Dr. Susan Lindee, a
science historian at the University of Pennsylvania who is
researching a biography of Neel, examined some of the scientist's
field notes for 1968 and other papers and said she found evidence
contradicting Tierney's view of certain events.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the book, Lindee said, Neel had permission from the
Venezuelan government to carry out the vaccine program. When an
epidemic was declared, these notes showed, Neel provided medicines
to the affected villages and their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that he attempted to discourage anyone
from providing treatment,'' Lindee said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Ferguson, an anthropologist at Rutgers University at
Newark, N.J., and author of ``Yanomami Warfare,'' published in
1995, said he thought Tierney's book was ``largely accurate in
reporting the facts, but there are also opinions and
interpretations, and that's where it gets much more debatable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-ESSAY-$ADV01-2TAKE     09-27 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ESSAY-$ADV01-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BEST VIEW OF TELEVISION, USE A WIDE LENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, a party to celebrate the start of a cable arts
channel was held at the home of an art collector. The walls were
lined with canvases by Jasper Johns and other contemporary painters
whose work museums would be happy to have. Yet any idea that this
event signaled an easy coexistence of high art and mass media was
short-lived. When it was time for a toast, the hostess announced
without a trace of irony or self-consciousness, ``We're not
television people, m husband and I, but we figure it's not going
away so we might as well support an arts channel.''
</P>
<P>
   As if that quaint, condescending comment were not bad enough _
making it seem that we had stepped into a time warp and landed in
the 1950s _ the next was truly jaw-dropping. The chairman of the
new channel said he agreed, and justified his decision to wallow in
this declasse medium with a cliche: ``If you can't beat 'em, join
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to dismiss their remarks as the lingering snobbery
of a dying breed, and to some extent that's just what they were.
But their attitudes are also not as rare as you might think. They
are extreme versions of the many wrongheaded approaches to
television, which range from the dismissive on one side to the
happy-go-lucky on the other. Images that pigeonhole the medium
dominate any conversation about it; in these views, watching
television is thought to be cultural anthropology, mindless
escapism, emotional solace or a source of news, sports and
occasionally art. But it is rarely embraced for doing all these
things at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that variety, and the way the parts feed one another, is
where television gets its immense social power. A fresher, more
realistic way to understand and appreciate television is to stop
regarding it through a narrow lens, and instead to embrace its
breadth.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who does not watch television cannot possibly understand
mainstream American culture. That may be disappointing news to art
collectors who wish we lived in Renaissance Italy, but there it is.
We live in a vast, messy society, and television mirrors who we are
in all our contradictions, complexities and uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just as there used to be people who proclaimed that they
watched only PBS, now there are people who claim to watch only HBO
(for ``The Sopranos,'' of course, and not ``G-String Divas'' and
other sex-filled late-night shows. There is even unmistakable
self-loathing displayed on television itself. ``It's not TV, it's
HBO,'' goes the idiotic slogan for the best channel there is.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's TV, you ninnies, it's just good TV. But that is a
concept the marketing people obviously think won't convince the
upscale audience they mean to attract. The slogan TNT uses for its
original films, ``The best movie studio on television,'' also
attempts to borrow some luster from the movies, even though the
increasingly homogenized film world no longer has much glory to
share.
</P>
<P>
   A wider embrace of television, taking the medium on its own
terms, is more revealing. Paradoxically, only such a broad view can
cut to the heart of our multifaceted society, a place where pop
culture and high art, reality and fiction, news and television's
shaping of it, meet. Whether you're watching television as an
escape at the end of a tiring day or seeking out sociological
clues, those activities come to the same thing; the sociology seeps
in by osmosis.
</P>
<P>
   Without going out of its way, television provides a constantly
updated chart of what mainstream America thinks. The several Emmys
recently awarded to the sitcom ``Will and Grace,'' including best
comedy and best supporting actor for Sean Hayes as Will's friend
Jack, offer a staid, traditional sign of approval. The show's
popular success tells us that Americans will watch the story of a
gay man and his female best friend. But ``Will and Grace'' also
hints (here is its nasty secret) that it is safe to create a
stereotypical flouncing gay man in Jack, who can reassure viewers
that their prejudices are true. Even programmers' attempts to gauge
what America is ready for indicate how the zeitgeist is perceived.
In the end, the show's easy acceptance said one thing; if it had
created an outcry, that would have meant something else.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular shows of recent years, there is no single
``reality'' reflected by television, but several provocative
versions of how we think about real life. From ``The X-Files'' we
learn that we live in a country in which people are deeply
suspicious of the government's truthfulness; in the alien-hunting
Mulder and the rational Scully we see the dramatized tension
between belief and skepticism. From ``The West Wing'' we learn that
viewers long for a president like the one Martin Sheen plays, more
upright and heroic than we are ever likely to have in life, and
that this longing can coexist with a tough-minded acknowledgment of
political horse-trading. ``E.R.'' tells us to expect doctors who
are dedicated and selfless, whatever messy personal problems are
nagging at them that day; life tells us those expectations are
insanely idealized.
</P>
<P>
   While networks and critics crow about so-called quality shows (a
favorite, meaningless buzzword), pedestrian and even outright bad
shows are revealing, too. The ordinary ``Drew Carey Show'' offers a
middle-American, overweight, unglamorous hero, a comfort to average
people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Look even briefly at more respected art forms and you find
creators who genuinely like television, are influenced by it and
make it a significant part of their work. David Foster Wallace's
story ``My Appearance,'' about an actress who is a guest on the old
``Late Night With David Letterman,'' is a sophisticated work about
the ironic turn our society has taken, a failing marriage and the
masks we wear every day. Dave Eggers' acclaimed novelistic memoir,
``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius,'' is loaded with
television references, including an account of his failed audition
for MTV's ``Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   These writers represent just two of the generations (those in
their 30s and their 20s) who grew up with television. The
pioneering video art of the older Nam June Paik began when the VCR
was an alien concept. Such artists embrace television as an
important, imperfect part of American culture, without looking down
on it or losing their critical judgment.
</P>
<P>
   It is perceptive of them to incorporate the medium in their
work, because even as the explosion of channels creates a more
fragmented television universe, what we know and how we know it is
shaped more than ever by television. Political campaigns are no
longer simply staged with the evening news in mind; they are
made-for-Oprah or made-for-Larry King events.
</P>
<P>
   Television now creates cultural moments as much as it reflects
them. The prepackaged Olympics, which end today, and the annual
ritual of the Academy Awards transcend what the athletic contests
or the Hollywood awards would be if the cameras stayed away. The
details of the O.J. Simpson trial, the JonBenet Ramsey murder, the
Monica Lewinsky scandal and the Elian Gonzalez custody fight have
invaded the public conversation in a way that would never have
happened without cable news channels. (Though the Internet is
rapidly gaining ground, it has not yet become pervasive enough to
claim that kind of grip.)
</P>
<P>
   Even our language has been shaped by television. Catch phrases
enter and leave the language, understood even by people who don't
watch the shows that spawned them. They are marks of what has
captured the public imagination: the simplistic ``final answer''
from the cheery ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''; the overwrought
fatalism of ``the tribe has spoken'' from the cutthroat
``Survivor''; the ``yada, yada, yada'' tribute to the joys and
neuroses provoked by life's ordinary details in ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that television is important doesn't mean that
everything it does is good. Most of it is dreadful, but even at its
worst it can be dreadful in a fascinating way.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A vapid mini-series like ``The Sixties,'' with its laughably
hollow image of a volatile decade, demonstrates how television can
reduce history to a meaningless montage of film clips, music and
colorful costumes, defanging a whole era to make it palatable for
television and buyers of the soundtrack CD. Yet, by giving us what
the '60s was not, by creating a caricature historians can rail
against, ``The Sixties'' perversely contributes something to the
conversation. That is not the ideal contribution, but it matters.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with junk television (apart from boredom) is
that its critics can use it to demonize the whole medium. Movies,
especially, love to make television the easy scapegoat, in films
like ``The Truman Show,'' which suggests people cannot escape the
medium's evil control.
</P>
<P>
   As the current political debate about marketing violent
entertainment to children illustrates, condemning an entire
industry is more a political convenience than an idea rooted in the
vast range of what television presents every day.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of watching television is more complex than
either the politicians or the Hollywood executives, both full of
narrow self-interest, admit. Blinkered opinions that damn
television for its Jerry Springer excesses or foolishly overpraise
it for half-witted sitcoms are both off base.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Television's highest achievements do not define it any better
than its lowest. ``The Sopranos,'' which has the depth of character
of genuine art, is like a gift, rare in any medium. It is as
distant from most junk on television as a Kurosawa film is from a
Hollywood action movie or a Toni Morrison novel from a Danielle
Steel romance. Yet no one dismisses film and novels in general just
because popcorn movies or beach books outweigh true art. No one
would dream of saying, in a regal tone, ``We're not book people, my
husband and I.''
</P>
<P>
   Television people are everywhere, watching everything, realizing
(as only people with a solid grasp of American culture can) that
the highbrow-lowbrow divisions so often imposed on television are
nonsensical. It's not HBO; it's TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
