<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-BUSINESS0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.28.00
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ MTVi group cuts 25% of work force
</P>
<P>
   _ i2Go teams up with GM in music deal
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft, Bosch plan navigation system
</P>
<P>
   _ More filters made to worker Net access
</P>
<P>
   _ Ad agency returns to cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING TO SING ABOUT: MTVi Group is cutting 25 percent of its
jobs, or 105 positions, at the online music entertainment company.
The cuts follow a net loss of $46.4 million on revenue of $18.2
million, according to regulatory filings. They also follow the
merger of the company's parent, Viacom Inc., with CBS Inc. MTVi's
operations include youth-oriented VH1.com, MTV.com and SonicNet. It
was recently redesigned to lure more views and advertisers. The
cuts reportedly were in editorial, technology and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC TO GO: Speaking of music, Atlanta-based i2Go, which
develops mobile audio technology, has created a co-branded Web site
with General Motors that allows new car owners to download music
and news programs from the Internet, then take it in their cars
``to go.'' As part of the GM ``Sound Values'' marketing program,
i2Go also built a special-edition digital audio player that will be
given to GM customers who buy Pontiac Grand Am, Sunfire, GMC Jimmy
or Sonoma models to download the music and information.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTING TRAFFIC: Speaking of cars, Microsoft Corp. plans to
jump onto the bandwagon of companies that are developing car
navigational systems. The software maker is teaming up auto-parts
maker Robert Bosch GmbH to develop systems for in-vehicle
navigation and Internet access. The products, using Windows CE
software, will be sold to automakers under Bosch's Blaupunkt brand.
Ford Motor Co. and PSA Peugeot Citroen announced a similar
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROLLING ACCESS: San Diego-based Websense Inc. has created a
new Internet filter to help companies control what sites employees
can access. According to eMarketer research, the average worker
spends 12 hours a week on the Net, compared with 2.5 for home.
Websense's goal is to enable IT administrators to conserve network
bandwith, discourage employees from using company time for personal
pursuits and mitigate employers' legal liability. The company's
Premium Group 1 software allows companies to control access to
online brokerage sites, free software downloads, sites that charge
users instant messaging services and bandwith-intensive ads.
</P>
<P>
   www.websense.com
</P>
<P>
   WESTWAYNE'S BACK: Atlanta's largest ad agency, WestWayne, has
been silent in cyberspace for much of the year for a redesign. That
finally changed this week with the relaunch of www.westwayne.com.
The agency serves clients that include Publix, Russell Athletic and
NAPA Auto Parts. WestWayne even has its own interactive division.
But what WestWayne didn't have was an active Web site from March
through September, making it one of the area's few sizable ad
agencies without a forum on the Internet. The highlights include
staples of most ad agency sites, including a client list and case
studies of ad campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   WHO NEEDS 'EM? In the wake of more online layoffs, like those at
MTVi Group and Hollywood.com, a portal that cut 50 employees this
week, it's no surprise that fewer Net companies are using
headhunting services. A survey by the Association of Executive
Search Consultants found a 12.5 percent drop in searches for
executives at e-commerce and online media companies in the second
quarter, which are the most recent data available. That compared
with a 14 percent increase in executive searches across all other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo (YHOO), down 12% at $90.38. The company broke important
investor support at $99.50 and $99.75, its May and August bottoms,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com (AMZN), down 5% at $37.88. The Washington Post ran a
front-page story critical of the company's pricing methods.
</P>
<P>
   VerticalNet (VERT), up 8% at $32.63. The Web site owner gained
on a Lehman Brothers ``buy'' rating, although Robinson Humphrey
downgraded the stock to ``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One (CMRC), up 1% at $75.94. The e-commerce solutions
provider benefited from news of an expanded partnership with
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.28.00
</P>
