u s BC-GLF-DUVAL28-COX     09-27 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval closer to playing shape
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Upright again and finally off his back, an
energized and easygoing David Duval walked into the interview room
at the Buick Challenge Wednesday. Greeted in the doorway by his
former Georgia Tech teammate, Stewart Cink, he offered a summary of
his condition after a two-month absence from the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, Duval will get the question so many times, he'll
wish it was embroidered on his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite all the way there, but I might not be until
maybe June,'' Duval told him.
</P>
<P>
   Usually it's a laid-back week for Duval at Callaway Gardens. But
not when you've been sidelinedwith a strained lower back ligament
since Aug. 4. Each day will be a proving ground. On Tuesday came 16
holes in a practice round, which brought some strange stiffness,
but nothing to deaden his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not necessarily fit right now golf-wise,'' said Duval, who
when healthy is among the PGA Tour's fittest players, ``because I
haven't been doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the $2.3 million tournament commences at the Mountain
View Course, it will be Duval's first full round of golf since
Sunday at the British Open, when the world winced as he struggled
through a four-shot stay in the Road Hole bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
