A4164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG0928-     09-27 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blacks may protest students' vote to repaint Rebel flag
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAPOOSA, Ga. _ Students at majority-white Haralson County
High School voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to restore a painted
Confederate flag to the outside of the gym in time for their
homecoming game Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a homecoming game.
</P>
<P>
   Some black athletes are talking of staging a boycott, according
to Superintendent Greg Hunt, who told school board members this
week that minority players were unhappy over the Rebel flag's role
in their school.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, black students in the marching band could join
the protest, said Anne Williams, whose middle school-age daughter,
Angelica Griffin, plays in the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the football players decide to boycott, then we will
support them,'' Williams said. ``To me, and to many other black
people, the flag represents bondage.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, vandals painted over the flag, which locals said
has been on the gym wall more than 30 years. The school's nickname
is the Rebels, and the mascot is a cartoon Confederate general.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was among parents called to the west Georgia school
Wednesday to help count ballots after the student body voted
whether to repaint the flag on the gym.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote, she said, was 861 students for restoring the
flag; 150 against; and 14 who wrote ``I don't care'' on their
ballots. The racial makeup of the school was about 93 percent white
and 6 percent black last spring, according to the state Department
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she and other parents were surprised the all-white
school board allowed students to decide such a sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   High schoolers, she said, are too young to appreciate the
negative connotations vested in Confederate symbols.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really just thinking, `This is my school's mascot and
I don't want it to change,' '' Williams said. ``I'm sure if they
understood, the vote would have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   School board member Dianne Hamil said she thought the students
should be allowed to decide ``because it's the children's school.''
Board members said a countywide committee will be formed to study
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Anthony, 17, an 11th-grader, said he voted to restore the
flag. ``I'm not a racist or anything like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When results of the vote were announced, students broke out in
cheers, Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other students flew large Rebel flags from their vehicles
as they drove off campus Wednesday. Students also leaned from
windows of school buses, waving smaller flags and chanting,
``Rebels! Rebels!'' Some of the younger black children on the buses
chanted happily along with the others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
