<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRAZIL-SOCCER-ART-(TR     09-27 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SOCCER-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL ROCKS SOCCER, SENDING BRAZIL INTO SHOCK
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Also being filed in `s' news file.) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Even in their worst moments, Brazilians
had their prowess in soccer to sustain them, as celebrated in four
World Cups. But the passion has suddenly become a sorry symbol,
with the coach of the World Cup team accused of corruption and
several star players under investigation for tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the nation is suffering a crisis of identity and
its team is in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   After having lost only one qualifying match in the entire
70-year history of the World Cup, the Brazilian squad has lost to
Paraguay 2-1 and to Chile 3-0 and tied with Colombia and Uruguay,
results regarded here as shameful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we sunk to the point of being humiliated by Paraguayans
and Chileans?'' the columnist Arthur Dapieve asked recently in the
daily O Globo.
</P>
<P>
   The defeats have ``revived our national inferiority complex,''
he added, since soccer and music are the two reasons ``for us
Brazilians to be proud and look down on the rest of humanity from
above.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trials of the playing field are hardly the only reason
that Brazilians are calling for the head of Wanderley Luxemburgo da
Silva, coach of the national team. His former secretary, Renata
Moura Alves, says that Luxemburgo was involved in a series of
illegal schemes, from clandestine payments from the sale of player
contracts to money laundering and the purchase of apartments,
paintings and luxury automobiles through dummy companies to avoid
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Federal tax authorities say that they are hot on Luxemburgo's
trail and that he may owe as much as $1 million in back taxes and
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Luxemburgo himself has said ``the problem is being resolved''
and has vowed that ``the course of the case will not affect the
exercise of my profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of all this on the national psyche is hard to
overestimate. As the newsmagazine Epoca noted recently, ``Here in
the land of soccer, the post of coach of the national team can be
just as prestigious as that of president of the republic.''
</P>
<P>
   During the most repressive period of the 21-year dictatorship
that ended in 1985, the coach at the time, Joao Saldanha, was one
of the few people who dared publicly to defy the military. Before
the 1970 World Cup, when Gen. Emilio Medici pressed Saldanha to
choose certain players that were favorites of his, the coach
replied, ``I promise not to tell him how to run the country if he
promises not to tell me how to run the team.''
</P>
<P>
   In Luxemburgo's case, even his age is now in doubt. He says he
is 45, but documents recently uncovered by news organizations here
show his real age to be 48. The age differential is important
because it indicates that as a young man Luxemburgo was still
playing youth-level soccer when he should have been playing as an
adult. That is a violation of both Brazilian and international
rules because it is unfair competition and if detected can result
in fines or suspension of a player or an entire team.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Police have said they want to question Luxemburgo
about possible perjury on his return from Sydney, where he was
coaching an Olympic squad that is younger and less experienced than
the World Cup team. Brazil's Olympic team was eliminated on Sept.
23 after upset losses to South Africa, 3-1, and to Cameroon, 2-1 in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   For the average fan, the most serious of the accusations is that
Luxemburgo may have named some players to the national team in
return for payments from their agents. Because of the prestige of
being on the squad, the market value of such players would soar,
and they would be able to command higher transfer fees when later
sold to European teams, with a percentage of the money allegedly
going to Luxemburgo.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Brazilian Soccer Federation, Ricardo
Teixeira, has said that action will be taken against Luxemburgo
only if it can be proved he was involved in the purchase and sale
of players.
</P>
<P>
   But some commentators maintain there is only one plausible
explanation for some of the quirky player choices he has made. One
cartoon shows Luxemburgo with those questionable picks and has him
asking, ``You didn't think I was doing this for free, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Eurico Miranda, a director of the Vasco da Gama soccer team
here, noted recently: ``Evanilson was a name that nobody even knew
how to pronounce. Nonetheless, he was picked for the national team
and soon afterward was sold to a German team'' for a reported $7
million.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Luxemburgo has said that all the accusations against him not
related to the tax case are false and are intended to get him
fired. Before heading off for the Olympics, where Brazil has never
won the gold medal in soccer, he appeared on a popular television
program to plead with the public to ``let me do my job'' and to
proclaim his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this is all over, they're going to say it was all a lot
of nonsense, and it will be understood that nobody proved anything
against me because there was nothing to be proved,'' he said.
``They're treating me like I'm a crook, but I'm not a crook.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Luxemburgo has also been fighting with some of the team's
most popular players, including the star striker Romario, hero of
Brazil's 1994 World Cup victory and now in line to become the
second leading scorer in team history, after Pele.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are no good need no help in destroying themselves,''
Romario said recently after the coach left him off the Olympic
squad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Romario himself, along with Ronaldinho, Roberto Carlos and
at least four other members of the World Cup team, is also being
investigated for possible tax evasion, federal authorities have
said. That is a surprising new attitude, the humorist Luis Fernando
Verissimo wrote recently, in a country where soccer and those who
play it have long enjoyed ``a sweet irresponsibility, without
obligations and without punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Brazilian team won the 1994 World Cup in the United
States, for example, players, coaches and executives brought back
several tons of household and electronic appliances, computers and
other luxury goods. When they landed and customs officials demanded
they pay duty, they threatened to boycott the official
celebrations, and top government officials were forced to intervene
to get the customs department to relent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is healthy, therefore, that the soccer business is finally
being seriously investigated and that adult behavior is being
demanded,'' Verissimo wrote. For too long, he added, players and
management alike ``have counted on the tender tolerance given to
children playing at being grown-ups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
