</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Luxemburgo has also been fighting with some of the team's
most popular players, including the star striker Romario, hero of
Brazil's 1994 World Cup victory and now in line to become the
second leading scorer in team history, after Pele.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are no good need no help in destroying themselves,''
Romario said recently after the coach left him off the Olympic
squad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Romario himself, along with Ronaldinho, Roberto Carlos and
at least four other members of the World Cup team, is also being
investigated for possible tax evasion, federal authorities have
said. That is a surprising new attitude, the humorist Luis Fernando
Verissimo wrote recently, in a country where soccer and those who
play it have long enjoyed ``a sweet irresponsibility, without
obligations and without punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Brazilian team won the 1994 World Cup in the United
States, for example, players, coaches and executives brought back
several tons of household and electronic appliances, computers and
other luxury goods. When they landed and customs officials demanded
they pay duty, they threatened to boycott the official
celebrations, and top government officials were forced to intervene
to get the customs department to relent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is healthy, therefore, that the soccer business is finally
being seriously investigated and that adult behavior is being
demanded,'' Verissimo wrote. For too long, he added, players and
management alike ``have counted on the tender tolerance given to
children playing at being grown-ups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
