<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ELECTIONS-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL SAYS MILOSEVIC HAS LITTLE TIME TO ACCEPT DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: In 3rd graf, sub brackets for double parenthesis, which are
not transmittable to some newspapers.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Buoyed by an enormous demonstration of
more than 200,000 of his supporters, who filled downtown Belgrade
on Wednesday night to celebrate his apparent victory as Yugoslav
president, Vojislav Kostunica said Slobodan Milosevic had only a
short time left to recognize the will of the Yugoslav people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is now no way out for him,'' Kostunica said in
an interview, as the crowds gathered. ``This is a situation that
cannot last long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica has rejected the idea of running against Milosevic in
a second round, set for Oct. 8, saying preliminary official figures
showing him with less than 50 percent of the vote are fraudulent.
((Early on Thursday, the Federal Election Commission ruled that a
runoff on Oct. 8 was needed because neither candidate won 50
percent.))
</P>
<P>
   ``People know I won these elections,'' Kostunica said in the
interview. ``Why should I accept Milosevic's offer of a second
round? People won't understand it and will feel that I'm betraying
them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, to the massed and happy crowd, shouting and
swaying under a clear night filled with stars, Kostunica said: ``We
tell them from this place that there is no second round. There is
no market in votes.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned Milosevic that he had ``less than 24 hours'' to
recognize the real results of the elections, because the Federal
Election Commission must issue its final findings by Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been silent since the vote on Sunday, making no
appearances of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the crowd _ one of the largest in memory here _ was
a message to Milosevic, too, backed by other large rallies in towns
like Novi Sad, where 35,000 gathered, and Nis, with 25,000. In
addition, 15,000 rallied in Kragujevac and 10,000 in Kraljevo.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments were also passing the word to Milosevic that
his options were fast running out, senior Western officials said in
telephone interviews on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They told Milosevic through his intermediaries that he had a few
days to renounce power and leave the country without difficulty, to
settle where he would, but that if he delayed, he could face arrest
and a trial in The Hague on war crimes charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``His choice is to fight or make a graceful exit,'' a senior
Western official said. ``His only hope of avoiding The Hague is to
say, publicly and irrevocably, that he's leaving, and to go on his
own resources somewhere.'' If he were to leave, Russia and Belarus
appear to be possible destinations.
</P>
<P>
   No Western country would publicly bless an arrangement like
this, the officials stressed, given Milosevic's indictment by the
war crimes tribunal in The Hague, a creation of the U.N. Security
Council. ``But there are enough people indicating, to the extent
he's listening, that he has a little time to make a dignified exit
without interference,'' another senior Western official said. ``We
want him to hear it loud and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The representatives of a number of Western nations left Belgrade
before the NATO bombing began last spring, and from a distance have
been lobbying the Serbs to overturn Milosevic, with offers to end
economic sanctions and provide aid.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, Kostunica said Milosevic could cling to power
now only through repression. ``Politically he has no future, and
I'm not sure he can count on repression, either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the situation is becoming clear to them, and we see
the panic that they feel,'' he said. ``It's why I say there will be
no revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to help Milosevic to the correct decision,
Kostunica said, is ``by being very firm and sending a message to
the people around him, who are already afraid, that there will be
no revanchism and no revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Kostunica told the crowd that he was sure of
his victory, given their strength, and he had a message for the
army and the police, who did not interfere on Wednesday night.
``Our message to the army and the police is that we are one,'' he
said. ``The army and the police are part of the people; they exist
to protect the people, not one man and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd shouted, ``He's finished!'' about Milosevic,
Kostunica asked, ``Why would our army, which was so courageous last
year against NATO, be afraid now of one man?''
</P>
<P>
   People in the crowd were happy but slightly unsure that
Milosevic was beaten. There was a sense of self-discovery and
suspense, caught in an historical tide that had not yet reached its
peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's finished, because of the people here,'' said
Ivana Petrov, a 25-year-old medical student. ``We hope he'll go.
But he won't go so easily. Things here can't change that fast, even
if he does go.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandar, a middle-aged man who would not give his surname,
said the atmosphere was fantastic. ``But you never know what the
authorities here can do,'' he said. ``We've had big rallies in
Belgrade before.'' But then he brightened. ``Now, though,'' he
said, ``all of Serbia is like this.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife broke in, saying, ``I think he's finished, and we are
very, very happy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were small signs on Wednesday that the government's
attitudes might be shifting. In the state-run newspaper Politika,
there was an article by the state-run news agency, Tanjug, that
reported fairly and accurately about the news conferences of the
democratic opposition, in which Kostunica supporters cited their
own polling evidence that he had won an outright victory in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, state television ran a straight report of a
news conference by the opposition leader Zoran Djindjic, although
it came after the airing of an interview with Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic, who blamed the international media and NATO
propaganda for deluding the voters.
</P>
<P>
   For Milosevic, calling the elections proved to be a blunder; his
term extended to next July, but he called the elections early,
apparently hoping to cement and extent his hold.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic, the army chief of staff who supports
Milosevic, gave an interview in which he said the army would stay
out of politics. He said that Milosevic ``will never order the army
to intervene against the people'' and that the army would ``respect
the choice'' of Yugoslavs in presidential elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
