<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-LEE-NYT &LR;      09-27 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-LEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYER THREATENED `SLOW DEATH MARCH' IN LEE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal prosecutor in the Wen Ho Lee case told a
Senate subcommittee Wednesday that a defense lawyer's threat to
turn a trial into a ``long, slow death march'' that would force the
government to reveal highly classified nuclear weapons data made
the government more willing to reach a plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said prosecutors should not have
been worried by combative remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had told me they were going to put me on a long,
slow death march, I would have told them, `Let's start walking,'''
said Specter, a former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law known as the Classified Information Procedures Act,
or CIPA, defense lawyers are allowed to try to persuade a judge
that a defendant must divulge secrets to obtain a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a private meeting that we had in late May,'' the
prosecutor, Norman C. Bay, the U.S. attorney in Albuquerque, N.M.,
said of the discussion with an unidentified defense lawyer. ``He
said, `My guy is not going to take any charge in the indictment,
and if you don't like that, I'm going to put you on a long, slow
death march under CIPA.'''
</P>
<P>
   The fear of exposing nuclear secrets at a trial was cited by the
director of the FBI, Louis Freeh, as a critical factor that led the
government to settle the case. In a plea bargain reached on Sept.
13, Lee pleaded guilty to a single count of the 59-count indictment
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers have insisted that they were not threatening the
government but were simply insisting on the public airing of
evidence that, they said, would exonerate Lee at a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Senate Judiciary subcommittee hearing came one day
after Freeh and Attorney General Janet Reno testified about the Lee
case at another Senate hearing, the beginning of what is expected
to be a lengthy congressional review of the investigation and the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the hearings have not settled the complaints about the
government's conduct, nor have they silenced specific criticisms of
the prosecutors' actions, including their insistence on keeping Lee
behind bars for 278 days before he was released.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has urged Reno to appoint a
special counsel to review the Lee case. The Justice Department and
the FBI have opened internal inquiries into the case, led by their
separate in-house ethics units.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer has said that an outside investigation would be
preferable as ``the surest route to a creditable and complete
analysis of the troubling questions the public legitimately has
with the way the Department and the FBI conducted the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's supporters have also expressed support for an independent
inquiry. Cecilia Chang, the founder of WenHoLee.org, an online
organization ``advocating justice'' for Lee, said Wednesday that
Reno and Freeh, in their testimony on Tuesday, had failed to
justify their actions in the case and presented ``tattered reasons
to justify this politically motivated witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter pressed the witnesses on whether the government could
have obtained a cooperation agreement with Lee much earlier.
Specter cited complaints expressed by the judge in the case, James
A. Parker, who said that the prosecutors failed to engage in early
settlement negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bay said prosecutors had sought Lee's cooperation. He quoted
from an Aug. 4, 1999, letter written by John J. Kelly, the former
U.S. attorney, to Lee's lawyer, saying, ``I assure you that I have
absolutely no desire to prosecute an innocent man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have used what tools prosecutors have to try to gather all
the facts,'' Kelly said in his letter. ``Those facts establish your
client's guilt. If additional facts that only he can provide would
explain his actions and point to his innocence, I would sincerely
like to know that before embarking on a course of action that will
have a profound impact on many people. Once again, I extend to you
the invitation to have your client tell his side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers were highly critical of the government's
determination to keep Lee in jail as he awaited trial. He was
confined in a county jail in Albuquerque under solitary conditions
like those imposed on maximum security prisoners. At times, Lee was
manacled with wrist, waist and ankle chains, and a light was always
on in his cell.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh have said that they were unaware of the harsh
conditions, and on Wednesday their aides said that neither Lee nor
his lawyers complained during his confinement. In recent days,
Lee's lawyers have criticized the ``egregious pretrial conditions
imposed on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay provided a letter from Raymond Sisneros, the sheriff of
Santa Fe County, N.M., to Samuel Montoya, the county manager,
describing a visit Sisneros made to Lee's cell in March for the
purpose of asking about Lee's confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than being incarcerated he had no complaints,'' the
March 10 letter said, adding that ``his only request was for
additional fruit at the evening meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay also said that the light in Lee's cell that remained
switched on during the night was not a bright light. ``I'm told
that the light was a dull blue light,'' Bay said, ``kind of like a
night light, in Dr. Lee's room and that the jail would use that
just to make sure that if someone walked by and looked inside his
cell that they could make sure that he was there and that he was
doing OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
