<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-FLEETBOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT BANCORP SAID TO DISCUSS ACQUISITION BY FLEETBOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By RIVA D. ATLAS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summit Bancorp, the largest bank in New Jersey, is in talks to
be acquired by FleetBoston Financial Corp., executives close to the
discussions said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The executives would not disclose the terms of the deal, but
analysts estimated the bank could be sold for $7 billion, or $40 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Summit, which is based in Princeton, rose $3.56
Wednesday, to $34.31, and are up 25 percent this week on
speculation of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Summit, with just $39 billion in assets and more than 500
branches, would be a small bite for Fleet, which has assets of $181
billion. But the deal could help Fleet increase its market share in
the New York area, a goal of Fleet's chief executive, Terrence
Murray. Summit controls 15.6 percent of New Jersey's deposits, more
than double the share of Fleet, which has had a presence in the
state since it bought NatWest Bancorp in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both sides declined to comment, although the Fleet
spokesman noted that the company was no longer distracted by its
$13 billion merger a year ago with BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger is complete,'' said James Mahoney, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In another deal pending in the New York area, Fleet has agreed
to invest $250 million should North Fork Bancorp succeed in its $2
billion hostile bid for Dime Bancorp. In return, North Fork, which
is scheduled to decide Thursday whether to proceed with its
takeover bid, has promised to sell 17 Dime branches to Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years people have been talking about Fleet and Summit,''
said Lawrence Cohn, an analyst with Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``Fleet is at
a size in this market where either they need to get bigger or get
out.'' With one-third of Summit's branches in the suburbs of New
York City, Fleet could market to an affluent customer base products
sold by its subsidiaries, the high-technology investment banking
firm Robertson Stephens and the discount broker Quick &AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Summit has been seen as a takeover target since at least 1992,
when a predecessor company was the target of a proxy fight by
Chilmark Capital, a money management firm in Saddle River, N.J.,
which owned 10 percent of the stock. At the time, it was the
largest bank holding company to fend off a proxy fight, a Summit
spokeswoman said. Eight years later, the pool of potential
acquirers has narrowed considerably, noted Neil Weisman, president
of Chilmark, who sold his stock soon after his proxy battle failed.
``Fleet is the logical choice,'' Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   The investment bank Merrill Lynch has been trying to drum up
interest from other potential buyers, executives close to the deal
said, but the list of banks whose stock price is strong enough to
afford the deal and with a presence in the New York area is fairly
small. First Union Corp., which was said to be interested when
Weisman was lobbying for Summit's sale, would most likely have
antitrust problems if it tried to acquire Summit. In the late
1990s, First Union greatly expanded its presence in the area with
the acquisition of CoreStates Financial Corp. and First Fidelity
Bancorp, Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to clients Wednesday, Judah Kraushaar, a Merrill Lynch
analyst, said, ``The main issue for Fleet in judging potential
investor reaction will be whether a deal with Summit waters down
Fleet's efforts to move away from traditional banking and towards
higher valuation businesses'' like investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has already said it is evaluating a partial spinoff of
Robertson. So far, investors do not seem too concerned: Fleet's
shares closed at $39, up 31 cents. A spokesman for Merrill declined
to comment on the firm's role in the deal; Kraushaar did not return
calls. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
