<SLUG> BC-PIERCE-STAB-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN STABBING OF CELTIC PIERCE IN CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR AND STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One of three suspects in the nightclub attack on
Celtics star Paul Pierce was taken into custody Wednesday night
just hours after police publicly identified three men wanted for
the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hurston, who allegedly bashed Pierce in the head with a
bottle as the Celtic played pool in a Theater District nightclub
early Monday, was met at Logan International Airport when he
returned voluntarily from New York to face a charge of assault and
battery with a dangerous weapon, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for Hurston, 31, of the city's Dorchester section,
told reporters his client is too short to have reached Pierce's
head, even with a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, John Swomley, who also represents the rap group Made
Men, said Hurston is a lifelong friend of Made Men member Raymond
``Ray Dog'' Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Made Men ``are disheartened Mr. Hurston has been sucked into
this,'' Swomley told reporters outside the Area A police station.
``They are as confident as I he had nothing to do with the assault
on Mr. Pierce.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other men are still being sought with warrants for assault
with a knife, William Ragland, 28, of the city's Roxbury section,
and Trevor Watson, 34, of Boston, indicating that both allegedly
took part in the knifing that left Pierce with multiple wounds
moments after he walked into the Buzz Club/Europa for a party early
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Superintendent Margaret O'Malley, of the department's
Bureau of Investigative Services, said she believed the three men _
all of whom O'Malley said are known to police in Boston and in the
region _ may have fled the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three individuals may be dangerous,'' O'Malley said at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Police denied that they were actively seeking to question
Michael McNeill, as reported in the Globe Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McNeill, who has ties to Made Men, may have been at the club
during the stabbing, a police source said, but he is not believed
to be a primary witness, and police are not actively seeking to
interrogate him.
</P>
<P>
   Based on information provided to the Globe from a separate
police source, the Globe reported Wednesday that investigators
wanted to question McNeill in connection with the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley made no reference to McNeill at the press conference.
Efforts to reach McNeill have been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley would not comment on the motive for Pierce stabbing, or
whether any of the suspects had ties to Made Men.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the stabbing, Made Men members Raymond ``Ray
Dog'' Scott and Marco Ennis acknowledged being at the club at the
same time as Pierce. But they adamantly denied any involvement in
the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley said eyewitness descriptions and cooperation from the
public helped police identify the three suspects named Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A man named Trevor Watson was with Scott at suburban South Shore
Plaza in June 1999 when two Braintree police officers stopped and
questioned them after a Macy's sales clerk suspected them of using
a stolen credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The card in fact belonged to Scott, who filed criminal charges
against the officers who arrested him. The officers were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Watson received a 20-year suspended sentence for a 1986 armed
robbery. In 1995 he was convicted as a felon in possession of a
firearm and served a five-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The second man charged in the Pierce stabbing, Ragland, has 16
convictions spanning eight years, including robbery and three
separate assault convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Hurston, who is charged with attacking Pierce with a bottle, has
no known criminal history. But the Dorchester man was the victim of
a crime in 1990, when he was shot in front of a lounge after an
argument with another man in the early morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley would not comment on whether Pierce knew the suspects
or if he had been able to identify them through photographs.
</P>
<P>
   A close friend of Pierce who was with him at the time of the
stabbing, Derrick Battie, insisted Tuesday that neither Pierce nor
the two friends who were with him knew the stabbers.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino said Wednesday Pierce had just arrived
at the club when a fight began and his attackers began stabbing
him. ``He was only at the club 10 minutes,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Pierce could be released from New England Medical
Center in the next day or two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff Writers Andy Dabilis and Shira Springer contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
