<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCUSES REPUBLICANS OF IRRESPONSIBLE SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton bragged Wednesday that the
government had a bigger budget surplus than ever before and then
accused congressional Republicans of trying to devote much of the
money to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned, frankly, about the size and last-minute nature
of this year's congressional spending spree,'' Clinton said as he
announced revised White House projections showing a federal budget
surplus of more than $230 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The annual standoff over the enactment of 13 spending bills
needed to keep the government running is once again down to the
wire, though Congress is poised to extend the time limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is due to vote on a stop-gap spending measure on
Thursday that would keep government agencies functioning until Oct.
6, seven days beyond the official end of the fiscal year at
midnight Saturday. The House approved the temporary spending bill
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded angrily to the president's suggestion that
they are acting irresponsibly in supporting increases in the
budgets of some domestic programs. They say it was their actions
that brought about the surpluses now being trumpeted by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's volley of words came the same day he sent his chief of
staff, John Podesta, and Jack Lew, the director of the Office of
Management and the Budget, to Capitol Hill to speed up negotiations
on the thorny issues on some of the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta and Lew spent much of their time meeting with Republican
and Democratic negotiators from the House and Senate who are
attempting to reach a compromise on an $18 billion measure to
finance the Interior Department and other agencies, including the
National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and some in Congress complained that
the Interior spending bill has been loaded up at the last minute
with a raft of amendments known as riders.
</P>
<P>
   A number of these amendments _ including one that would halt
studies on the feasibility of tearing down a number of dams in the
Pacific Northwest, a move championed by environmentalists to allow
salmon a free run to their upstream spawning areas _ have been
pushed by Sen. Slade Gorton, a Washington Republican who is locked
in a tight re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also hanging up the bill is debate over a provision to establish
a $45 billion trust fund over a 15-year period to conserve land for
recreation and wilderness areas. The provision, known as the
Conservation and Reinvestment Act, would not be subject to the
vagaries of the annual budgeting process, but instead would be
funded by royalties from offshore oil drilling.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the heads of appropriations subcommittees who
control the money for the Interior Department fear they would lose
power and have joined with several lawmakers from western states to
oppose the provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Senator Gorton disagrees with its goals,'' said
an aide to the senator, speaking of the conservation provision.
``He disagrees with the fact that it creates an entitlement. And
that says this is more important than education or health care.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Interior Department spending measure remains stalled,
negotiators report some progress on the approximately $55 billion
transportation spending measure. That bill, which provides money
for air traffic controllers, highways and mass transit systems, has
been hung up in a House and Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Progress on the measure has been blocked by disagreement over,
among other things, a provision requiring that states adopt more
stringent standards on the amount of alcohol a driver must consume
to be considered drunk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SOUVENIR28-COX     09-27 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOUVENIR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some souvenirs getting pricey
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Olympic souvenirs are taking on a new and costly
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The price tags on anything worn by high-profile Olympic athletes
are skyrocketing, driven by fanatical sports enthusiasts and
Internet auctions, as well as by the standard brick-and-mortar
shops.
</P>
<P>
   There's a $186,000 price tag in Australian money for gold-medal
sprinter Maurice Greene's gold-plated running shoes, according to
the Daily Telegraph. He threw one of the specially made Nike shoes
into the crowd after winning the 100-meter finals.
</P>
<P>
   Track clothes worn by Australian 400-meter gold medalist and
cauldron lighter Cathy Freeman are worth thousands of dollars. An
autographed photo commands up to $200.
</P>
<P>
   On an online charity auction, the goggles worn by the heroic
Equatorial Guinea swimmer, Eric ``The Eel'' Moussambani, were
listed for up to $3,800. Moussambani barely finished his 100-meter
freestyle event but delighted the crowd with his effort.
</P>
<P>
   Online bidding reached $3,760 for the swimming cap of American
Misty Hyman.
</P>
<P>
   Other expensive items include gold boxing kangaroos thrown into
the crowd during the Opening Ceremonies, Olympic volunteer uniforms
and Olympic torches.
</P>
<P>
   In general, signed items command much higher prices. And values
could fall after the Games end and interest in them wanes.
</P>
<P>
   Most Wanted Memorabilia
</P>
<P>
   --Maurice Greene's running shoes: $186,000
</P>
<P>
   --Olympic Torch: $4,000
</P>
<P>
   --Goggles from heroic Equatorial Guinea swimmer Eric ``The Eel''
Moussambani: $3,800
</P>
<P>
   --American Misty Hyman's swim cap: $3,760
</P>
<P>
   --Australian Bill Kirby's signed swimsuit: $2,550
</P>
<P>
   --Jamaican tracksuit: $1,500
</P>
<P>
   --Australian women's gymnastics signed T-shirt: $385
</P>
<P>
   --Bahama's swim cap: $370
</P>
<P>
   --Athlete's medals: $300
</P>
<P>
   --Opening Ceremonies commemorative cases: $300
</P>
<P>
   Note: Prices are in Australian dollars, which are worth about 55
cents in U.S. currency.
</P>
