<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STRIPCLUB-MOB0928-COX     09-27 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIPCLUB-MOB0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strip club owner arrested, organized crime captain indicted
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal authorities intensified their prosecution of
the Gold Club, arresting the strip club's owner and indicting an
alleged high-ranking captain of the Gambino organized crime family.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the moves appeared to fizzle Wednesday, at least
temporarily, when a federal magistrate allowed club owner Steve
Kaplan to remain free on bond. U.S. Magistrate E. Clayton Scofield
III said prosecutors' allegations that Kaplan ordered government
witnesses assaulted and intimidated were ``somewhat problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want Kaplan's $2 million bail revoked and the club
owner held in custody until trial, set for February. But Scofield
said Kaplan can remain free, at least until an evidentiary hearing
on the allegations is conducted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and 16 others are charged with participating in a
sweeping racketeering conspiracy, including illegal ties to
organized crime, money laundering, prostitution, loansharking,
credit card fraud and police corruption. Kaplan also is accused of
paying Gold Club dancers to perform sexual favors for high-profile
professional athletes to heighten the club's profile.
</P>
<P>
   Michael DiLeonardo, also known as ``Mikey Scars,'' was named in
the amended indictment, which includes new charges unsealed
Wednesday. He is accused of being a member of New York's Gambino
crime family who extorted money from Kaplan's clubs.
</P>
<P>
   One defendant, a former Gold Club dancer, has pleaded guilty in
the case. Jana Pelnis, known by the stage name ``Frederique,'' is
cooperating with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents unsealed Wednesday, FBI Special Agent Frank
Graziano detailed allegations that Kaplan had government witnesses
attacked, intimidated and followed.
</P>
<P>
   In December, a witness was followed out of the federal
courthouse by a Kaplan associate, who struck her in the face after
she refused follow his orders, Graziano said. This former Gold Club
employee lost two teeth because of the assault and went into
hiding, moving from hotel to hotel, in fear for her safety, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano also accused Kaplan, 40, of intimidating and trying to
contact other government witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan appeared to be caught by surprise Tuesday evening at his
attorney's office when federal agents arrested him. Wearing faded
jeans and a windbreaker, he appeared agitated as he was led
handcuffed into the courtroom Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Kaplan's lawyer, Steve Sadow, said he
can refute every one of the prosecution's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   As for the witness who claims to have been assaulted, Sadow
said, ``Mr. Kaplan had nothing to do with it.'' Sadow said he has
talked to the person who allegedly struck the witness and ``he said
it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadow disclosed that Kaplan's defense team has conducted an
``aggressive'' investigation of the federal charges, amassing tape
recordings of more than 200 witnesses. Some of these recordings
were acquired covertly, with the defense team using friends of the
witnesses who were wearing hidden microphones, Sadow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have their words on tape,'' Sadow said. ``When we sent a
friend out, these witnesses thought they were talking to a friend.
They weren't saying what the government wanted to hear, they were
saying what the truth is.'' Sadow said he has tape recordings that
will rebut the indictment as well as the recent allegations that
Kaplan intimidated witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   As for Monday's hearing, Sadow said, ``Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Art Leach said Judge Scofield's concerns
about the new allegations are not the final word.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like the evidence is there,'' Leach said. ``We
wouldn't have filed the motion if we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Kaplan left the courtroom, DiLeonardo, alleged to
be a top captain in the Gambino crime family, entered and pleaded
not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for the judge to take the bench, DiLeonardo leaned back
in his chair at the defense table and joked with FBI agents,
talking mostly about baseball. He was allowed to remain free on
bond pending trial, after putting up his $1.5 million Staten
Island, N.Y., home as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses DiLeonardo, 45, of taking extortion
payments from Kaplan since 1994. DiLeonardo gave the money to the
Gambino family, which then provided protection to Kaplan's strip
clubs in Florida and Atlanta, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   DiLeonardo also is charged with extorting $100,000 in 1995 from
the owners of Scores, an adult entertainment nightclub in New York.
When the FBI began investigating Scores and its ties to organized
crime, Kaplan allegedly paid off an ex-manager of the nightclub
with cash and sexual favors from Gold Club dancers. In return, the
former employee agreed not to implicate DiLeonardo in the federal
probe, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows a much closer relationship between Kaplan and the
Gambino family, a much closer relationship between Kaplan and
organized crime,'' Leach said of the new charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan's ties to the Gambino family are merely geographical,
not criminal, Sadow said. ``Mr. Kaplan happens to live in the same
school district as John Gotti Jr.,'' Sadow said, referring to the
acting boss of the Gambino family. ``Their kids go to school
together. Their wives know each other.'' Kaplan has homes in
Atlanta and Oyster Bay, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti frequented a nude dance club Kaplan once owned in Boca
Raton, Fla., Sadow said. ``He was treated like any other
customer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
