<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER PRESSURE, PUTIN POSTPONES MILITARY CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Facing opposition from his military commanders,
President Vladimir Putin postponed plans Wednesday to cut the armed
forces by a third and said ``there will be no wholesale, massive
reductions of the Russian armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin sounded a note of frustration at a meeting of his National
Security Council with top military commanders present, saying, ``We
spend colossal resources on the military, and we allow the military
budget to be wasted on peripheral issues that have nothing in
common with either the army's combat readiness nor with its direct
supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he added, ``we don't have the right'' to make
``mechanical'' reductions in forces, but rather need to streamline
the efficiency of the military. And, he added, ``we cannot any
longer simply provide for the army's needs without also providing
training with high technology and modern equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks seemed to undercut statements this month by Defense
Minister Igor D. Sergeyev that Russian military ranks would be cut
between 2001 and 2003 to 850,000 from the present level of 1.2
million, a reduction of just under one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said the issue of Russia's national defense could not be
addressed ``by sheer enthusiasm'' in the budget-cutting process,
although he said the country was still spending far too much on the
military establishment inherited from the Soviet Union. Military,
law enforcement and security services represent about 35 percent of
the Russian budget.
</P>
<P>
   He said the leaders of all departments with military units had
raised objections to the reduction plans disclosed by Sergeyev.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov and Sergei Ivanov, secretary to
the security council, recommended Wednesday that Putin put off any
decisions until November.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the recommendation, Putin said, ``Measured, calm
and smooth work is needed to optimize the country's entire military
machine.'' He added, ``It will take time to formulate decisions and
work out their format.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that despite the need to make budget reductions, ``our
army must be mobile, effective, flexible and combat capable.'' But
he added, ``This does not mean that we have to follow the path of
mechanical reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's remarks surprised some experts, coming as they did after
the sinking of the nuclear submarine Kursk on Aug. 12 and the
generally poor performance of the Russian military in two
inconclusive campaigns against the rebellious republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The public perception that poor maintenance and safety standards
in the Russian fleet contributed to the loss of the Kursk's
118-member crew created strong political momentum for military
reform, including additional cuts in standing forces, which have
declined to 1.2 million today from more than 2 million a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Putin realizes that the only way he can eventually get
a military that can do the job is to cut it drastically,'' said
Dmitri Trenin, a former military officer and deputy director of the
Moscow Carnegie Center.
</P>
<P>
   Trenin said he believed that Putin's decision to postpone his
first round of cuts was more tactical than strategic. ``He prefers
caution and nonconfrontation in dealing with the military,'' he
said. ``Everyone knows that there is political support for
improving defense, and that means cutting forces.''
</P>
<P>
   William E. Odom, a retired American general and longtime analyst
of the Soviet and Russian military, expressed some doubt that Putin
could carry through with significant cuts to forces or to the
defense budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Putin's public statements about foreign policy
and the military, they all have the element of saying Russia must
be a strong military power,'' Odom said. ``Well, he is now being
hoisted on that petard because Russia does not have the money to
have a strong military.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Putin, as a former KGB officer and director of its
successor agency, the Federal Security Service, is particularly
indebted to the military and security services for political
support, and the war in Chechnya was a critical factor in Putin's
political rise.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Kremlin meeting, Ivanov, the security adviser,
said Putin's decision was intended to give the military six more
weeks to ``calculate once again all the economic parameters of the
reforms that will be carried out pretty soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-TAX-ART-2TAKES     09-27 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TAX-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM EUROPE, CREATIVE TAXATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Europe is rushing to tear down borders, but the Internet
is toppling some of them even faster, making life distinctly
uncomfortable for European policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   A big source of that discomfort is the threat of lost tax
revenue, because European nations depend far more on taxes on
consumption than the United States does. So in contrast to the
United States _ where a federal commission failed to agree on how
states should tax basic electronic commerce and mail-order sales
like books, consumer electronics and other products _ European
officials are pushing hard to adopt a seemingly narrow but
potentially far-reaching proposal to ensure that digital products
bought in Europe over the Internet do not escape taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the legislation proposed in June by the European
Commission, the Brussels-based executive arm of the 15-nation
European Union, defines digital products like software and video
programming downloaded by computer as services rather than goods.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to insure that such transactions face the
value-added tax, an elaborate system begun in Europe in which
purchases are taxed at each stage from production to final sale.
(However lucrative, it is a system that politicians in the United
States have shied away from.)
</P>
<P>
   Normally in Europe, services would be taxed in the country of
origin, meaning that European nations would gain no tax revenue
from services flowing in from the outside. But this bill, which has
stirred controversy not only on the Continent but among
high-technology companies in the United States, would require
companies outside Europe with sales here of such services exceeding
100,000 euros, or about $88,000, to register in one European
country for the purpose of paying value-added taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are significant. In 1999, European e-commerce sales
were $3.4 billion, or less than one-half of 1 percent of total
sales. But by some estimates, such sales in Europe may rise as high
as 12 percent of the total in the next few years. And while sales
of digital products from outside Europe are only a small fraction
of that, policy-makers _ even more than their counterparts in the
United States _ are fretting over possible lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the United States, where relatively few people
pay state sales taxes on Internet purchases, European governments
already impose national value-added taxes on goods sold over the
Internet within Europe. The tax rates and the list of goods covered
vary from country to country. For services sold by European
companies within Europe, the VAT is paid by the selling company in
its home country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, European governments already tax e-commerce more
than the United States does. The Internet Tax Freedom Act, passed
by Congress in 1998, created a moratorium on sales taxes on
e-commerce across state lines until 2001, and anti-tax forces in
Congress have tried, so far unsuccessfully, to extend the
moratorium until 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has sought to coordinate Internet tax policies with
the Europeans through the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development in Paris. At an OECD conference in Ottawa in 1998, the
Europeans and the United States agreed on a list of principles for
treating digital goods as services rather than manufactured
products, to avoid customs duties on their delivery, and on
jurisdiction in case of eventual taxation.
</P>
<P>
   But in Europe, the issue is considered a pressing one. European
governments depend for roughly 40 percent of their total revenue on
value-added taxes, while state sales taxes in the United States
make up only about 25 percent of total state tax revenue. The
budget of the European Commission is financed almost entirely by
the VAT.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe as in the United States, governments are also coming
under pressure from traditional retailers that must collect taxes
on all their sales _ taxes that Internet providers can skirt. The
American software producer Symantec, for instance, which sells its
Norton Utilities software to Europeans in several languages through
its Web site, encourages customers to download the software
directly, saying that there is ``no value-added tax, shipping or
export charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, serious obstacles face the proposed European legislation,
and enactment is far from certain. For one thing, the bill will not
become effective unless it is approved and enacted into national
law by all 15 members of the European Union. It also needs to pass
in the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   So difficult is the debate expected to be that Thomas Tindemans,
a tax expert in the Brussels office of the law firm of White &AMP;
Case, said the delays would probably produce ``a de facto
moratorium.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the debate complex is that the proposed legislation
affects not only software but also other electronic services like
pay-for-use radio and television broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The path the Europeans have taken is not unlike the one Congress
chose in July, when it passed legislation to resolve the issue of
how to tax cellular phone use in the United States. Under the new
rules, cell phones have a ``primary service area'' in which the
telephone user pays state and local user taxes. But unlike the U.S.
legislation, the broader European measures face bitter opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The European legislators are treading a thin line. National
governments _ at pains to see their industries close the gap with
the United States, where Internet use by business and consumers is
ahead of Europe's _ do not want to impose extra burdens. Yet
officials in Brussels also worry that inaction could encourage
individual countries to take unilateral action to prevent tax
erosion. Tindemans of White &AMP; Case said the goal appeared to be
``to force debate at the European level and try to coordinate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial criticism has been intense. In the United States, the
Software and Information Industry Association, a trade group,
assailed the draft as ``fatally flawed.'' Mark Bohannon, the
group's general counsel, said the measure would be unenforceable
because it is often impossible to tell where a customer is in
cyberspace. He called the proposed law a step backward from
international agreements not to tax the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, just about every interest group seems unhappy. At
Eurocommerce, a trade organization for wholesale and retail
distributors, officials are preparing a catalog of objections,
including ones to the plan to set the threshold at 100,000 euros.
They say that would discriminate against small European companies
that already pay the tax while their small rivals abroad would not.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the trade group hopes to use the issue as a cudgel to
force governments to harmonize value-added tax rates at lower
levels, arguing that the proposal encourages foreign companies to
register in countries with little or no VAT for digital products,
like Britain, where the rate on some items is zero, rather than,
say, Sweden and Denmark, where the uniform rate is 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the theory,'' said the chief tax adviser at
Eurocommerce, Dimitris Kalogeras. ``The practice is quite
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Tengberg, chief executive of a company called Buyonet,
could not agree more. When Tengberg, a former mechanical engineer
with Exxon, set up his company in 1997 to sell software on the Web
and to help other companies do likewise, he established
headquarters in Sweden, but registered it in Seattle. The company
sells all its products to Europe from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Buyonet's main competitors, Tengberg explained in an interview,
are American companies like Beyond.com that enable European
customers to download their products without paying the value-added
tax. If Buyonet added Sweden's 25 percent rate to its prices, he
said, ``people just would not buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tengberg, one of the most outspoken opponents of the
legislation, called it ``primitive and impossible to enforce.'' The
authorities in Europe, he argues, would have no power to force
American companies to register. And if American authorities
cooperated, he said, many companies would simply move the computers
used to deliver their products ``to Uruguay, Burkina Faso or
Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a digital world,'' he went on, ``where you deliver from
doesn't matter. A buyer in Bahrain gets the same service as a buyer
in Philadelphia. It's a beautiful fact, but for the tax man it's a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Therese Torris, a tax specialist at Forrester Research BV,
regards such comments as nonsense. So far, the market for directly
downloaded digital products consists mainly of software sales to
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large companies have no incentive for tax evasion,'' she said,
relying on governments for assistance in matters like anti-piracy
and copyright protection. Small businesses may seek to evade taxes,
she said, ``but it's not in the interest of big companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they have a problem,'' Torris added, ``they go to the
government and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   She said European and American governments face a formidable
challenge when digital goods are delivered online and paid for
directly over the Internet. But she also said that the problem was
purely technical and that companies specializing in tax-collection
software were already providing solutions. Taxware International,
for instance, recently began marketing software to track European
value-added taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Buydens, a tax specialist at the OECD, said Europe's
value-added tax system could more readily be adjusted than what
exists in the United States, where 7,000 tax jurisdictions create a
minefield of differing sales tax rates, and there are contrasting
definitions of taxable and nontaxable items.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, Europe will have to make some changes,'' he
said. ``In the United States, the discussion is about the system
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tengberg of Buyonet said that he, like many other executives
of businesses operating in cyberspace, believes that the Internet
ultimately spells the end of the European value-added tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works in a physical market,'' he said. ``It doesn't work
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
