<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-BAILIS-BOS &LR;      09-27 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BAILIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN S. BAILIS, 54; HEALTH CARE PIONEER, OF BREAST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Smart, brassy, sometimes profane, Susan S. Bailis rose
from social worker to top hospital administrator, then quit to
build New England's biggest nursing home company, which was sold in
1996 for $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   She dressed in silk and Armani, threw dinner parties, and, in
her husband's words, ``ferociously devoted time'' to her family,
cooking the food for her son's bar mitzvah over several weeks and
stashing it in the freezer, one lasagna at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with breast cancer in 1992, her reaction was typical:
She launched a foundation to fund research of the disease's
environmental causes and kept right on working, taking her cell
phone with her to chemotherapy. Only in recent weeks did the
illness manage to keep her in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Bailis died Wednesday at her home in suburban Belmont,
surrounded by family and friends. She was 54.
</P>
<P>
   Word that Bailis was slipping away rippled through the diverse
arenas where she had made a mark: her alma mater, Brandeis
University, one of many institutions where she was a trustee; the
health care world, where she was known as a fierce negotiator on
behalf of elder care; the community of breast cancer researchers
and advocates, who called her a pioneer, but knew that Bailis,
never one for sentimentality, hated to be called ``courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, even as friends made farewell visits to Bailis's
home, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center named her to its board
of trustees. It was no symbolic gesture, said trustee Jordan
Golding, who told Bailis's husband, Larry, of the decision: The
hospital needed her help at a time of financial challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, family, friends and business associates
described a woman who was at once feisty and nurturing, idealistic
and pragmatic; one of those individuals who has a lasting effect on
nearly everyone she encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has this sparkle in her eye that tells you this is a woman
who you don't want to mess with,'' said Julia G. Brody, executive
director of the Silent Spring Institute in Newton, whose research
into preventable causes of breast cancer is backed by the Susan S.
Bailis Breast Cancer Research Fund. ``She's got ideas and she's
going to carry them out.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those ideas was figuring out what environmental factor _
pesticides, perhaps, or plastics, or any of the myriad products
women use _ might be contributing to the rising incidence of breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with the disease getting a lot of public attention,
the majority of research focuses on drugs and diagnosis, lucrative
areas for companies that fund studies.
</P>
<P>
   In a fund-raising video for Silent Spring, Bailis, dark-haired
and elegant, uses the language of a businesswoman to explain the
problem: Looking for environmental causes won't make anyone rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, what we may find may be costly to the economy,''
she says, slightly raising one eyebrow. ``Therefore, the
traditional funding sources are not highly incented to fund this
kind of research.''
</P>
<P>
   So, even though it would not help cure her own cancer, that's
where she chose to throw her weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the legacies I would like to leave,'' she says on the
video, ``is that I did something that will make a difference for
the women and their daughters that come after me.''
</P>
<P>
   That willingness to leave the beaten track reminds Bailis's
husband of how she got onto the marching band at A.B. Davis High
School in Mount Vernon, N.Y., where the couple met on the cast of
``Pirates of Penzance.''
</P>
<P>
   She played the viola, an instrument that was out of place on the
football field. So she agreed to play the glockenspiel, Larry
Bailis said, ``doing what it takes to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bailis was the youngest daughter of Sanford Solender, a
Jewish community leader, and his wife, Ethel, a violinist. Her
brother, Stephen Solender, now is head of United Jewish
Communities.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Brandeis in 1967 and got a master's degree in
social work from Simmons College _ where she later became
chairwoman of the board of trustees _ all the while helping Larry
get through graduate school at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been supporting me ever since,'' said Larry Bailis, now
an associate research professor at Brandeis's Heller School.
</P>
<P>
   They have two children. Kathryn, 25, who teaches middle school
at Noble &AMP; Greenough, and David, 21, studies ethnomusicology at
Reed College, although he has been studying at the Berklee School
of Music to be near his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Bailis's high-powered career didn't stop the family from
spending weekends together in Rhode Island and taking yearly trips.
Larry Bailis recalled his wife waiting for business packages in the
Greek islands, in Ireland, at the Sheraton Great Wall Hotel in
China, and then heading off for some family time.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning as a social worker at New England Medical Center,
Bailis rose to be associate director. In that role, she hired Alan
Solomont, who ran his family's long-term care company, to operate a
pediatric nursing home for the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Solomont admired her tough negotiating skills, and in 1985 she
quit to help him build the ADS Group into the state's largest
elder-care company, managing 5,000 beds at 60 sites with nearly
$100 million in revenue. In 1996, they sold the company to
MultiCare, which was quickly bought by Genesis Health Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care chief executive Charles Baker said
Bailis often held him to the fire on Medicare reimbursement rates
when he was state secretary of health and human services.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was good at separating the issues _ which at times were
very contentious _ from the people,'' he said, choking up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Solomont, who became close friends with Bailis, said she swore
``like a sailor,'' yet managed not to sound crude. At the same
time, he said, she was a nurturing manager, setting up a
scholarship fund for the largely female work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in our company would walk on hot coals for her,'' said
Solomont. ``She would say, `These are poor women taking care of
poor women and we have to look out for them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bailis became involved in breast-cancer advocacy when another
close friend, Ellen Parker, helped found the Massachusetts Breast
Cancer Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1992, Bailis apologized to a state official for being
off her game in a meeting. She had been diagnosed with breast
cancer that day, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   After chemotherapy, she thought she had it beat. But in 1995,
her doctor found tiny tumors had metastasized to her bones and
lungs. She told her husband, ``I guess we're not going to grow old
together after all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a book of essays by people with breast cancer, Bailis used
typically direct, staccato phrases to describe how she and Solomont
broke the news to colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I planned to go on with my life and my work. I'm a
fighter. I told them they could talk to me about it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She hated being called a survivor,'' Parker said. ``She didn't
want to be the poster girl for feel-good cancer things. If you have
breast cancer and you go out to dinner, people say you're
courageous. It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailis described telling President Clinton about her illness at
a White House breakfast, saying, `` `I think you can relate to that
since your mother died of it.' He became completely and totally
riveted on me. I said the word `breast' in the White House. I knew
damn well what I was doing. Everyone except the president was
uncomfortable. . . . He threw his arms around me and said, `Hang in
there!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bailis made her last public appearance in July, showing up using
a walker for a meeting of Governor Paul Cellucci's health-care task
force. The governor suggested nursing home beds could be converted
to elderly housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole room turned to Susan,'' recalled Ned Morse,
president of the Massachusetts Extended Care Federation. She
``politely but firmly'' told him why his idea was all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vintage Bailis,'' said Morse.
</P>
<P>
   Later, kept comfortable by her doctor Roger Lang, Bailis had
time for sweet conversations with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Parker said she asked Bailis, ``Are you really scared,
scared about dying?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `No, Ellen _ do you think that's very odd?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Not from you.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
