<HEADER>
A4213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER-EARN     09-27 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER-EARNINGS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENT SAYS CHRYSLER UNIT WILL POST A THIRD-QUARTER LOSS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is short separate on Daimler-Chrysler   investing in
China . )  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ DaimlerChrysler AG said Wednesday that its
Chrysler car group would report a loss in the third quarter _ the
first such loss since a recession in the United States nine years
ago _ and that Chrysler's highly respected design chief, Thomas C.
Gale, would retire at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither announcement had been entirely unexpected, they
provided new evidence that DaimlerChrysler remains deeply divided
between its U.S. and German car companies long after their historic
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Gale, 57, is the latest in a long series of top Chrysler
executives to bail out of the company since the merger two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas T. Stallkamp, Chrysler's former president and the top
American working on integration of the two companies, quit last
year after his relations with German executives soured.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Eaton, Chrysler's former chairman, who had been a
co-chairman of DaimlerChrysler, retired in March, earlier than
expected. Many others below the top ranks have left as well.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler attributed Chrysler's anticipated third-quarter
loss to extremely stiff price competition in the United States and
the costs of bringing new models to the market quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But the company insisted that Chrysler would again turn
profitable in the last quarter of the year and asserted that total
operating profits this year would match those of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That would be better than many analysts had been fearing,
because rumors have been circulating for weeks that the entire
company might report a loss and that full-year profits would
decline sharply. Reflecting the relief, shares in DaimlerChrysler
rose 2.6 percent in Frankfurt to 52.8 euros or about $46.62. In New
York, shares rose 94 cents to $45.94.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the loss at Chrysler is extraordinary given the
company's reputation for profitability during the mid-1990s. It is
the first such loss since an $82 million shortfall in the third
quarter of 1991 _ and that was a recession year, in contrast to the
flush economic times in the United States now.
</P>
<P>
   Investor concern about Chrysler is reflected in the shares of
the parent company, which have still lost more than half their
value since they peaked at $108 in January 1999. And the basic
problems confronting Chrysler are not over. Though the retro-styled
PT Cruiser has been a runaway hit, other models are getting stale
and need to be revamped.
</P>
<P>
   In a determined effort to hold its market share, Chrysler has
torn into its profit margins by spending vast sums on discount
programs and other incentives to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining its predictions for the rest of the year,
DaimlerChrysler said that Chrysler would lose about $530 million in
the third quarter of this year but would post an overall profit for
the year of about $1.7 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Juergen Schrempp, the chairman of DaimlerChrysler, has already
announced plans for billions of dollars in cost-cutting moves
during this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   But the company is looking for additional cuts, while also
trying to speed up the introduction of new models and expand
production of the PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Chrysler, Mercedes has continued to post healthy
gains. Even though the German market for midpriced cars shriveled
this year, largely because of a flood of nearly new used cars on
the market, Mercedes sales increased slightly in Germany and about
4.5 percent worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Even the much-criticized Smart, the snub-nosed two-seat vehicle
that was a flop, has bounced back. Its sales jumped 67 percent
through August, to 69,500 cars.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Gale had been widely expected, but it could
be an important loss. Having spent 33 years at Chrysler, Gale
oversaw the design of cars ranging from popular Chrysler Intrepid
sedan to the Dodge Viper, an eye-catching muscle car that helped
jazz up Dodge's dusty image.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about Gale's departure spread as soon as it became clear
that Stallkamp was on his way out as president. Earlier this year,
when asked in an interview about his intention to stay with the
company, he carefully avoided making any long-term commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Gale strongly implied he had indeed begun planning
his departure about that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jim Holden took his position as president, I agreed to
stay on and see the future product plan through, while continuing
to build the team to succeed me,'' Gale said. ``Now that both of
those processes are complete and we're in the next phase of
development, it's time for me to step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gale will be replaced by Richard O. Schaum, who has been in
charge of engineering platforms _ the basic chassis and components
that are common to many different car models. Trevor M. Creed, who
was recently promoted to senior vice president in charge of design,
will be responsible for the more visible aspects of exterior and
interior styling.
</P>
<P>
   Gale also said there are no plans to replace him on the
13-member DaimlerChrysler management board. His departure would
leave a 12-member board _ nine from Daimler and three from
Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
