<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-MOM0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman's mom, son visit Florida
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ She is a master kibitzer, a protective
parent, and to the Democratic faithful, something of a doting
Jewish queen mother in a wheelchair throne.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Lieberman _ mother of vice presidential candidate Sen.
Joe Leiberman _ came to town Wednesday and continued a family
whistle-stop tour that has included South Florida visits from the
candidate, his wife, his daughter, and now his son and mother.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed in her wheelchair by grandson Matthew, 33, Marcia
Lieberman signed autographs and encouraged the almost entirely
over-65 crowd at three appearances to vote for ``the party that
gave us Social Security and Medicare and . . . the party that will
give us free prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke in the morning at the Plumbers &AMP; Pipe Fitters Union
Hall, swung by the Morse Geriatric Center for a little tuna salad
and a quick press conference and then hit Century Village.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, 85, told about 200 seniors at the union hall that she
was totally shocked in August when Vice President Al Gore picked
her son to be his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much of a surprise as it was to the country, it was that
much of a surprise to us,'' Lieberman said. ``I have to tell you
that most of all, as much as we hear about Joe running for vice
president, that it's because of the vice president's courage to
break the barrier of having a Jewish young man run as his mate.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was largely of the same mind. ``When Gore can have the
chutzpah to pick a Jewish man and the polls show he's running so
much ahead, that's something,'' said David Grossberg, 82. ``I
didn't think I would see it in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeling her way through the Leonard and Sophie Davis Atrium and
the Jack and Pearl Resnick Pavilion and The Shapiro Family
Auditorium and Chapel at the Morse Geriatric Center, Lieberman
shook hands with dozens of other people in wheelchairs and passed
out ``Seniors for Gore and Lieberman 2000'' buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman, who lives in Connecticut, has been making public
appearances in senior centers across that state for years. The
senator is said to call his mother every day.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Lieberman has earned a reputation as something of a
character. She recently mailed brown paper-wrapped care packages to
the reporters covering her son's campaign. In the packages:
Tylenol, lip balm, tissues, an apple, bagel chips, a news clipping
on her son, candies, a pair of plastic sunglasses, and postcards
for reporters to write home to their own mothers. Also included, a
handwritten note imploring the recipients to ``Please be good to my
son!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
