<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-IRA-FLORIDA0928-COX     09-27 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRA-FLORIDA0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge questions guidelines before sentencing gunrunners
 &HT;    By John Pacenti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ A prosecutor warned ``the world is
watching'' and a federal judge questioned the wisdom of lawmakers
as he sentenced three Northern Ireland gunrunners to less than five
years in prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons, sent hidden in toys and other goods, were meant for
use by the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Their gun dealer, Edward Bluestein, was put on probation for two
years, including six months of house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   So ended the emotional case that brought the turmoil of Northern
Ireland into a South Florida courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The stiffest sentence handed down by U.S. District Judge Wilkie
D. Ferguson was four years and eight months to Connor Claxton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person can be sentenced to life for having $400 worth of
crack cocaine, then this sort of offense ought to get the death
penalty,'' Ferguson said in reference to Claxton's case.
</P>
<P>
   Later the judge said he didn't really think the defendants
should get the death penalty but only wanted to point out that
lawmakers seem to have their priorities askew regarding gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also told Bluestein, who testified against the
gunrunners, that ``much of the proliferation of firearms in this
community is caused by licensed dealers.'' Bluestein, 57, said he
no longer is in the business. He suffered heart failure and stood
in front of the judge huffing and puffing, grabbing onto the
lecturn for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my doctor I can't live like this anymore,'' said
Bluestein, who has been out on bond. ``I think I was in jail for
the last year.'' The judge told Bluestein _ who spent less than a
day in jail _ that he had no idea what it was like to be locked up.
</P>
<P>
   Bluestein admitted to selling the gunrunners 43 weapons for
shipment overseas. He agreed to break gun-reporting laws by
reporting only a few of the guns in exchange for a $50-a-gun fee.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government did fail in its main task to convict the
three gunrunners _ Claxton, Anthony Smyth and Martin Mullan _ of
the most serious charges of terrorism and conspiracy to commit
murder and maim persons in a foreign land, which could have put the
men in prison for life. They were found guilty of weapons
transporting crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe in some great degree the world is watching what
we do,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Scruggs. ``It is
unacceptable to bring their problems to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Smyth's girlfriend, Siobhan Browne, also admitted to purchasing
guns. She already has been sentenced to 20 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor put the number of guns Wednesday at 118 that the
men intended to ship in Tonka trucks, empty VCRs and other items to
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be here today except for the situation I grew up in
in my country,'' Claxton told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth and Mullan received three-year sentences and Smyth has to
pay a $3,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Irish nationals have already spent 14 months in
federal jail. Irish-American organizations raised more than
$100,000 for defense costs. Supporters outside the courthouse,
weunrunners to less than five years in prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons, sent hidden in toys and other goods, were meant for
use by the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Their gun dealer, Edward Bluestein, was put on probation for two
