   ``I wouldn't be here today except for the situation I grew up in
in my country,'' Claxton told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth and Mullan received three-year sentences and Smyth has to
pay a $3,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Irish nationals have already spent 14 months in
federal jail. Irish-American organizations raised more than
$100,000 for defense costs. Supporters outside the courthouse,
wearing green ribbons, compared the men to George Washington,
revolutionaries fighting against British rule. Scruggs, the
prosecutor, said one of the gunrunner's relatives threatened him
after the verdict. He also said he received thank yous from the
Royal Ulster Constabulary, the police in Northern Ireland, which
has lost 300 officers to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These weapons were going to be used to kill them. They told us
we saved lives,'' he said.
</P>
