<P>
   (NYT12) BLACKTOWN, Australia -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- OLY-HOLLEY-BOS
-- The U.S. Olympic women's softball team developed angst over a
three-game losing streak against Japan. They ignored the sports
psychologist and his mini-toilet for them to flush after bad games.
The United States has the best softball team in the world and on
Tuesday night, it walked away with several souvenirs. Members of
the U.S. Olympic women's softball team walk the flags around the
playing field after a gold medal win against Japan. At left is Leah
O'Brien-Amico. At center is the pitcher Lisa Fernandez with raised
arm holding flag. At right is Crysti Bustos. Player next to
Fernandez is Laura Berg. (Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAMBRIDGE. Mass. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- BIOTECH-DOPING-BOS
-- Many pharmaceutical companies spend years developing a drug to
treat a serious medical condition. Then athletes take the drugs and
use them to boost their performance. But as reports and rumors
circulate, the companies find themselves in the spotlight,
defending their public images, fielding complaints about a lack of
controls, and balancing social and corporate responsibilities. The
Biopure Corp. in Cambridge, Mass. poured 16 years into Hemopure, a
product that could drastically reduce the need for blood
transfusions. Rumors are that it is the next big performance
booster. Dan Rose, a manufacturing technician works in Biopure's
purification room. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- WIRELESS-WEB-MEDIA -- Media
Metrix estimates that nearly 7.4 million households in the United
States now have devices like cell phones, pagers and personal
digital assistants, otherwise known as PDAs, that can pluck data
from the airwaves. And although there are no reliable overall
figures, people in the industry say that only a small percentage of
users with Web-ready devices actually exploit that feature. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONDON -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- U.S.-FUNDS-BRITAIN -- As
London is seeing the greatest cultural expansion in its history, a
list of many of the largest donors enabling this growth reads like
a who's who of American philanthropy. American money accounted for
nearly 30 percent of all the individual financing for the $214
million Tate Modern in London, the first new national museum in
Britain in 100 years and its first devoted solely to modern art.
The Tate, formerly the site of the Bankside Power Station on the
south bank of the River Thames, as it was being converted in
November, 1999 to a museum. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- RUSSIAN-OBJECTS-4 --
Hillwood, Marjorie Merriweather Post's home-museum in Washington,
is filled with a battalion of royal objects. Her collection of
imperial Russian art from the 18th and 19th centuries is the
greatest in the world outside Russia, and her estate has one of the
leading U.S. collections of Sevres porcelain, much of it
commissioned by Catherine the Great. View of the French Parterre
gardens from Post's bedroom window at the Hillwood Museum and
Gardens. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
