<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- WEB-BOGEYMAN-BOS --
Devin Hosea, the 30-year-old founder and president of Predictive
Networks Inc., is the boyish face behind what some consider the
Internet's latest threat to consumer privacy. A digital wizard who
learned how to crack software code by age 10, Hosea has been
drawing fire from consumer advocates who say his technology takes
online surveillance to new heights. Hosea's start-up company in
Cambridge, Mass. has developed software that builds digital
``silhouettes,'' or profiles, of Internet users, after tracking
their clicks across the Web. (Pam Berry/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN --
Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, meets
with students at the Ascension School, Wednesday. From left: Jose
Ramirez, 12, Ramiro Coyt, 10, and Jesus Jaimes, 11. Rejecting
attempts to portray him as a champion of the wealthy, Bush visited
an inner-city school Wednesday to call for safer classrooms and
increased spending on character lessons. (Ozier Muhammad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ALTOONA, Iowa -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN-1 --
Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate,
kisses Winifred Skinner, of Des Moines, Iowa, after she explained
how she has to collect cans off the street in order to earn enough
money to feed herself and pay for her prescription drug bills each
month, Wednesday at the Greater Altoona Community Service Campus.
Gore questioned rival George W. Bush's commitment to Medicare
during his campaign stop Wednesday and declared ``it is time'' to
help 13 million senior citizens get prescription drugs. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
