The stony ruins of a 19th-century steel mill that gave the town its
start. Remote, economically depressed, and cursed with lousy
weather, Lithgow is worlds away from the designer skyscrapers and
sun-splashed beaches of Sydney. And yet, for all its hard-luck
veneer, Lithgow is as proud, as captivated, and as unabashedly
excited about the Olympics as Sydney. (Mark Landler/The New York
Times)
