<SLUG> BC-GLF-GLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMAN BACK WANTING MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final Los Angeles-area tour event of the year returns to
Wilshire Country Club next month, when Joe Inman takes aim at a
third consecutive title in the Senior PGA Tour competition known
this year as the SBC Senior Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Wilshire has been like a second home to Inman, who was an upset
winner twice there for his only two senior victories after coming
in both times hoping only to play well enough to secure his tour
card for another season.
</P>
<P>
   His victims at Wilshire amount to a who's who of the Senior
Tour, including runner-up Lee Trevino and two-time defending
champion Gil Morgan in 1998, when the event was known as the
Pacific Bell Senior Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Inman shot a closing 65 in the final Pacific Bell
Senior Classic to finish two strokes ahead of Dave Stockton and
Bruce Summerhays in a field that included player of the year Bruce
Fleisher and senior superstar Hale Irwin, plus Trevino and Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Inman might have to hold off the broadcast booth as
well, with announcer-turned-contender Gary McCord waging a season
stretch run to earn a title defense of his Senior Tour
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The funny and fun-loving McCord, a nonwinner during 25 years on
the regular tour but a megastar at corporate outings, showed how
well he has aged last year by winning the season-ending Senior Tour
Championship. But McCord needs a top-31 finish on the 2000 season
earnings list to return to the Tour Championship and entered this
week 38th with five tournaments remaining _ including the
season-ending Wilshire event, Oct. 27-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will play as much as I have to to get in,'' he said. ``A win
would probably be enough to get me in.''
</P>
<P>
   If he needs the win at Wilshire, McCord is in the right area.
His first Senior Tour win came in Southern California, at last
year's Toshiba Classic in Newport Beach. Although the colorful CBS
analyst says he never dreamed of even talking about winning on the
regular tour, the victory at Newport Beach changed his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the first one made me realize I could do it,'' he
said. ``Then, winning the Tour Championship clinched it. I never
got over that hump on the regular tour. I didn't win there for a
billion years. Now, all I think about is winning and having fun
while I'm doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Information: (213) 480-3232.
</P>
<P>
   __ G'bye Shark, g'day Tiger: Scenic Sherwood Country Club in
Thousand Oaks, which has hosted Greg Norman's Shark Shootout since
1989, will be without that event this year following the Shootout's
move to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Area golf fans, however, won't miss a chance to see Sherwood's
splendor or top pros this fall, as the Tiger Woods Foundation
Williams World Challenge fills the November gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams event, which will include Woods and 11 of the
world's top players, is scheduled the week of Nov. 27-Dec. 3 and
has already attracted No. 3 in the world David Duval, reigning
Masters champion Vijay Singh and defending Williams champion Tom
Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman won by three strokes over Duval in last year's 72-hole
stroke-play competition at Scottsdale, Ariz. This year's winner
earns $1 million from a $3.5 million purse that makes the event one
of the richest of the offseason. It is also the major fund-raiser
for the Tiger Woods Foundation, which has used golf to interact
with more than 60,000 young people across America.
</P>
<P>
   Information (714) 816-1806.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Roger Gunn, the former Lake Lindero pro
now instructing at Tierra Rejada in Moorpark, has been named
clubfitter of the year by the Southern California PGA. . . . David
Berganio of Sylmar ranks among the top 10 in three categories on
the Buy.com Tour, including sixth in scoring average (70.19). He
also is third in greens in regulation and fourth in total driving.
. . . Jason Gore of Valencia is seventh in Buy.com Tour driving at
296.0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Waldorf/Lehman fund-raiser: PGA Tour players Lehman and Duffy
Waldorf will conduct a clinic and 9-hole exhibition Saturday at
Robinson Ranch, benefiting Santa Clarita-area junior golf and
Bethlehem Lutheran Church in Canyon Country. Eddie Merrins, UCLA's
NCAA-championship coach who coached Waldorf during his 1985 College
Player of the Year season at UCLA, also will participate.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 661/252-0622.
</P>
<P>
   __ Club champions championship: Wood Ranch in Simi Valley,
Woodland Hills CC and Sunset Hills CC in Thousand Oaks will host
the annual SCGA Tournament of Club Champions Dec. 11. The
competition, divided into three flights based on handicap index, is
open to club champions from all Southern California courses.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sponsorship: The 11-year-old Southern California PGA Golf
Expo, the annual spring golf show run so successfully by the
section that it funded the SCGPA's new twin-course home at Oak
Valley, will operate next year as an alliance project of SCPGA and
International Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   The name will stay the same and the Expo will continue to be
managed by the SCPGA, but the partnership makes the Southern
California event the largest public golf show in the western U.S.
and part of IMG's National Golf Expo Series, which includes shows
in Ohio, Illinois and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 SCPGA Expo is scheduled for March 2-4 at the Pomona
Fairplex. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The annual three-tour team competition formerly known as the
Diners Club Matches will return this year to Pelican Hill GC as the
Hyundai Team Matches. Jack Nicklaus-Tom Watson (Senior PGA Tour),
Fred Couples-Mark Calcavecchia (PGA Tour) and Juli Inkster-Dottie
Pepper (LPGA Tour) will defend titles in the Dec. 15-17 event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
