</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- NY-BARBARA-STREISAND --
Barbra Streisand's farewell concerts at Madison Square Garden this
week were officially sold out within hours, but the true story is
closer to ``I Can Get It for You Wholesale.'' The concerts
Wednesday and Thursday night were officially sold out within hours.
But plenty of tickets were being offered by brokers over the
Internet on Wednesday at prices ranging from $500 to $1,500 or
more. The face value of the tickets was $125 to $1,500, with VIP
tickets going for $2,500, including dinner. (Michelle V. Agins/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- NY-PUBLIC-SPACES -- Most
privately owned public spaces in New York City, created in a
tradeoff that was meant to give pedestrians a little extra
breathing room as developers got extra-large buildings, have failed
in some way, large or small, a new study has found. Chained gates
contradict a sign in the public plaza of an apartment complex in
Midtown. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT -- Working
with natural stone can be a rewarding experience because a project
finished in stone has a rustic charm that is unmatched in any other
building material. Stone is easy to work with because it requires
minimal dressing and shaping, although gathering and positioning
stones calls for a lot of muscle and sweat. (Ed Lipinski/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- NY-NEW-TEACHER -- Donna
Moffett abandoned her comfortable longtime job as a legal secretary
on Wall Street to be one of 320 ``teaching fellows'' -- people with
little or no teaching experience, hired by Schools Chancellor
Harold Levy to fill chronic vacancies in the system's most troubled
schools. In August, the fellows took a crash course in teaching and
eight hours of certification exams. In these first weeks of school,
Moffett is learning that teaching is only part of her job
description -- for now, an achingly small part. Moffett with her
first grade students earlier this month. (Ozier Muhammad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) HOLLYWOOD -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- ADV. FOR OCT. 1 --
TV-GIDEON-BRAUGHER -- Actresses inspire Andre Braugher more than
actors, because he believes weakness is almost bred out of men.
That's why he has never seen Hamlet played as the coward he
believes he is. Braugher is starring in his second television
series, ``Gideon's Crossing,'' a hospital drama on ABC. He plays
Dr. Ben Gideon, a character based on Dr. Jerome Groopman, a Boston
physician who chronicled his clinical experiences in the 1997 book
``The Measure of Our Days.'' While the role isn't exactly Hamlet,
the character appears to be complex enough to keep Braugher's fires
fed for now. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- - ADV. FOR
OCT. 1 -- FILM-YANG -- ``Yi Yi,'' which will be shown on Wednesday
at the New York Film Festival, is the first of Edward Yang's seven
features to reach American theaters. Set, like all his films, in
middle-class Taipei, ``Yi Yi'' provides an engaging introduction to
Yang's fictional universe, in part because of its bemused approach
to family life. Yang has been compared with Michelangelo Antonioni
and Jean-Luc Godard and his 1991 film ``A Brighter Summer Day'' is
considered one of the modern era's greatest Chinese-language films.
(Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- ADV. FOR OCT. 1 --
FILM-GIRLFIGHT -- Like more traditional boxing movies before it,
``Girlfight'' is about ``an outsider who enters a world where she
does not belong and finds a place for herself,'' says director
Karyn Kusama. The film, which opened Friday, is the story of a
sullen, gum chewing, muscular girl from the underclass, played by
Michelle Rodriguez, who literally fights her way into the ring. It
could be a metaphor for Kusama's bout with studios as she tried to
get financing. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- OLY-TRACK-COX --
For race horses and race drivers, the inside lane is the place to
be. For hurdlers, it's a less attractive, more complicated
location. U.S. Olympic runner Angelo Taylor, was less than thrilled
Wednesday when he learned he would start from Lane 1, on the inside
of the 400-meter hurdles race at the Olympic Games. Taylor wins the
men's 400-meter hurdles. Second place went to Somayli Hadi Souan,
far right, and third place went to Herbert Llewellyn, far left.
(Joey Ivansco/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- GLENN-MATH-COX-2 -- The
nation should spend more than $5 billion a year to raise the
``unacceptable'' performance of the ``scandalously underpaid'' math
and science teachers to world standards, a national commission
reported on Wednesday. Former Sen. John Glenn, the ex-astronaut is
chairman of the National Commission on the Teaching of Science and
Math in the 21st Century. The report entitled ``Before It's Too
Late,'' cited often-used statistics from the mid-1990s that show
most Americans emerge from high school with less knowledge of math
and science than most students their age in other nations. Glenn
stands next to ``Friendship 7,'' the first spacecraft that carried
him into space 38 years ago. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- GLENN-MATH-COX --The
nation should spend more than $5 billion a year to raise the
``unacceptable'' performance of the ``scandalously underpaid'' math
and science teachers to world standards, a national commission
reported on Wednesday. Former Sen. John Glenn, the ex-astronaut is
chairman of the National Commission on the Teaching of Science and
Math in the 21st Century. Today, too few students learn as much
about math and science as is necessary to protect the nation's
prestige, good jobs, military security and competitive position in
a global, networked economy, the commission said. Glenn, standing
before ``Friendship 7,'' the first spacecraft that carried him into
space, thumbs through the report. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- KITCHEN-REMODEL -- At age
89, Will Machado, an interior designer gave himself an inspiring
present: a minimalist Zen kitchen that is warm, serene and
efficient. He wanted a kitchen that was easy to walk around, and he
demolished a wall separating the kitchen from the living room. ``I
wanted to simplify my life,'' he says, but even with a $30,000
budget (including demolition) he had to make trade-offs. He loves
wood for its warmth and tactility, and he hired Stephen Iino, a
cabinetmaker, to execute his design in ash and maple. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CORTE MADERA, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- ZEN-FASHION-3
-- Zen minimalism is a far cry from the amusing, flashy icons of
Banana Republic, Mel and Patricia Zieglers' first business, with
its full-size, in-store giraffes and jungle jeeps poking through
the display windows. Zen is an upfront influence at the office of
ZoZa, a new fashion company set for its Web debut in mid-October.
Ziegler and his wife, Patricia, as ZoZa's co-founders, have even
signed on a genuine Zen master as consultant. The Zieglers' Arts
and Crafts home in Corte Madera, Calif. (Fred R. Conrad/The New
York Times)
</P>
