<P>
   (NYT18) CORTE MADERA, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- ZEN-FASHION-1
-- Zen minimalism is a far cry from the amusing, flashy icons of
Banana Republic, Mel and Patricia Zieglers' first business, with
its full-size, in-store giraffes and jungle jeeps poking through
the display windows. Zen is an upfront influence at the office of
ZoZa, a new fashion company set for its Web debut in mid-October.
Ziegler and his wife, Patricia, as ZoZa's co-founders, have even
signed on a genuine Zen master as consultant. The Zieglers in Zoza
clothing. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BOSTON -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- BUSH-DEBATES-2 -- In the
first debates Bush did not have to do much. Not one of the six
Republican candidates got more than 15 minutes to respond to a
question. Two months later, Bush was suddenly a font of
interjections and rebuttals, as if he had to rush to fit in all
that he had to say. As he approaches what is almost certainly the
most important debate of his political career, a first encounter
with Vice President Al Gore in Boston next week, it is impossible
to know which incarnation of Bush will show up. Workers carry in
equipment on Wednesday to the site of next week's debate between
Bush and Gore at the University of Massachusetts. (Tom Landers/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- BUSH-DEBATES-1 -- In
the first debates Bush did not have to do much. Not one of the six
Republican candidates got more than 15 minutes to respond to a
question. Two months later, Bush was suddenly a font of
interjections and rebuttals, as if he had to rush to fit in all
that he had to say. As he approaches what is almost certainly the
most important debate of his political career, a first encounter
with Vice President Al Gore in Boston next week, it is impossible
to know which incarnation of Bush will show up. Bush and Sen. John
McCain during a in March. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN-2
-- Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, is
flanked by his wife Laura and Cardinal Roger Mahoney during an
address to students at the Ascension School, Wednessday. Rejecting
attempts to portray him as a champion of the wealthy, Bush visited
the inner-city school Wednesday to call for safer classrooms and
