<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARGAS' MOVE LEAVES `WHAT-IFS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news that Michigan's Justin Fargas asked for a switch to the
secondary could only cause head-shaking from those who watched the
former Notre Dame High star become the No. 1-rated prep tailback in
the nation three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And make the same people wonder what would have happened if
Fargas had stayed home instead of going to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   __ He might be splitting time at tailback with DeShaun Foster at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ He might be working on his third year starting for USC.
</P>
<P>
   __ He would not be playing in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   __ He would not have suffered a career-threatening injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to dissuade him from moving, but he told me he
absolutely wants to make the move,'' Michigan coach Lloyd Carr
said. ``I'm excited because he's excited. I think Justin will be an
outstanding defensive back.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps UCLA coach Bob Toledo was right when he said two weeks
ago that Fargas could start at cornerback for the Bruins. But
before breaking his leg two years ago, Fargas was on track to
become a spectacular back for the Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried as hard as we could to get him,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said, after hearing Fargas was switching positions.
</P>
<P>
   The injury drastically altered Fargas' career and makes those
who saw him play in high school sound silly today: They know how
good he was and how good he could have been if he had not been
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Fargas isn't the only California phenom to switch positions.
Last year, D.J. Williams of Concord De La Salle was considered the
top prep player in the nation and projected to be a linebacker at
the school of his choice.
</P>
<P>
   Williams showed little interest in staying home and signed with
Miami. He was quickly moved to fullback and is starting to make the
transition to college. Williams had two carries for 10 yards and
caught three passes for 54 yards against West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Williams played on special teams in the loss at Washington, and
in the season-opening victory over McNeese State, he had one carry
for 2 yards and one reception for 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us a huge shot and made three or four big plays in the
first half that gave us first downs,'' coach Butch Davis said. ``He
was a big infusion in the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams suffered a hip injury against West Virginia and is
uncertain for this week's game against Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fan control: After Oregon fans abused UCLA players after last
week's game in Autzen Stadium, extra security precautions are being
taken for this week's game against archrival Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) could be a real problem,'' Oregon athletic director Bill
Moos said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Anti-Aggies: Texas Tech defensive tackle Kris Kocurek, who
grew up a Texas A&AMP;M fan, put this week's meeting with the Aggies in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we beat them, and only them, then I would consider it a
good season,'' Kocurek said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Boz is back: Before Oklahoma's game at Rice, the Sooners'
1985 national-championship team was honored, which allowed former
All-America linebacker Brian Bosworth to address the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my goodness. It was amazing,'' junior linebacker Rocky
Calmus said. ``I saw him and my eyes lit up, just like a little
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Calmus went out and recorded 14 tackles with a fumble recovery
against the Owls.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad Ten: Michigan State's 27-21 victory over Notre Dame was
the first victory by a Big Ten team this season in six games
against a ranked nonconference opponent.
</P>
<P>
   __ Must-see TV: It came as a shock to no one that Minnesota
coach Glen Mason switched starting quarterbacks, benching redshirt
freshman Asad Abdul-Khaliq in favor of junior college transfer
Travis Cole for this week's Illinois game.
</P>
<P>
   But Mason told the media Sunday he was making the change and
didn't inform his quarterbacks until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my girlfriend's house and my roommate called me and
told me I was starting,'' Cole said. ``I guess he saw it on TV or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Times have changed: Florida State quarterback Chris Weinke
matched former Miami quarterback Gino Torretta for the fourth-most
consecutive wins (24) by an NCAA Division I-A quarterback in the
Seminoles' 31-0 victory over Louisville last week.
</P>
<P>
   Torretta just happened to be in Tallahassee working the game for
ESPN2. It was his first trip to Doak Campbell Stadium since leading
Miami past Florida State 17-16 in the 1991 ``wide-right'' game. The
Hurricanes went on to win the national championship that season.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Seminoles' last loss at home. Their 48-game
unbeaten streak is the longest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of changes,'' Torretta said. ``They've
added 20,000 seats in here, so I know it's a lot louder. We always
used to say at Miami that they added seats because they couldn't
beat us. Boy, the shoe's on the other foot now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
