<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GENERAL-CINEMA0928-CO     09-27 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-CINEMA0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shakeout hits General Cinemas
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Cinemas appears to be closing at least three
of its five metro Atlanta theater locations in yet another sign of
trouble for an overbuilt industry.
</P>
<P>
   General Cinema and other theater chains are plagued by a glut of
movie screens nationwide. Columbus-based Carmike Cinemas filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in August and has since closed
about a half-dozen metro Atlanta locations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for General Cinema declined to comment on the
chain's plans, but real estate brokers say the company is marketing
a block of theater sites in the area. General Cinema's parent
company, GC Cos., has said it is contemplating a bankruptcy filing
to restructure debts.
</P>
<P>
   The chain is also closing a number of theaters in other markets,
including 11 theaters in Florida. General Cinema, with 130 theaters
and nearly 1,100 screens nationwide, announced plans last year to
unload some of its older, smaller theaters in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a six-screen General Cinema was torn down at
a metro Atlanta mall to make way for an expansion. Chris Carlaw of
Rouse Co., part owner of the mall, said there are no plans to build
a replacement theater for at least two years, the time he thinks it
will take for the industry shakeout to level out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is to halt any conversations until consolidation
has played out,'' said Carlaw, development director with the
Maryland-based company. ``There will be some survivors and some
that will get swallowed up. We think the prudent approach is to sit
on the sidelines and let it play out.''
</P>
<P>
   Many chains are building 14-, 16- and 18-screen megaplexes
featuring steeply tiered stadium seating, advance ticket sales and
valet parking. But nice as they are, the megaplexes are
overwhelming the industry with more screens than it can handle.
</P>
<P>
   If General Cinemas declares bankruptcy, it would join Carmike,
United Artists and Edwards Cinemas in seeking protection from
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Regal Cinemas, the largest U.S. theater chain, said last month
it had begun seeking relief from bank agreements. Loews Cineplex
Entertainment Corp. has warned it might default on its debt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
