<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaning on family, friends helps Taylor hurdle to gold
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Just as soon as the momentum of a full-throttle,
leaning finish played out, Angelo Taylor dropped to his knees on
the Olympic track that more than ever looked the color of Georgia
clay.
</P>
<P>
   He folded his hands, bowed his head and gave his thanks, not
knowing that his last lunge had indeed held off the surprise Saudi,
Hadi Souan Somayli, and that his night was golden.
</P>
<P>
   What a solitary figure he was, this one kneeling soul on the
floor of the 103,000-seat house. But whatever other doubts Taylor
took with him to prayer, one thing he knew for certain: No one
makes it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Before the world's best 400-meter hurdler took his mark, he had
been better buttressed than most storm shelters. All day, friends
and family kept filling his head with positive messages and
soothing vibes. They changed the oil, tuned the engine and rotated
all four tires on his ego.
</P>
<P>
   And Taylor had needed it. Not winning his semifinal heat had put
him at the mercy of a draw for his final lane assignment. His
number came up ``one,'' the most inside and undesirable lane they
make. Taylor hadn't run from Lane 1 in three years, failing to
advance in a semifinal then. He'd have to lean that long, thin
frame of his into the steepest of turns and dig that much harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why they put you in No. 1, don't you?'' posed his
mother, Subrena Glenn-Everett. ``That's because you are No. 1.''
Taylor had met with his assembled family the morning of the final.
They prayed then, too. His mother gave him a verse of scripture to
slip into his running shoe come race time.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor called Derrick Adkins, the 400-meter hurdle Olympic
champion in 1996 and Georgia Tech teammate. He took calls from his
old high school coach, Napoleon Cobb and former assistant Vincent
Elder. Another call from Tech coach Grover Hinsdale. Just 90
minutes before the final, Terrence Trammell, the 110-meter hurdle
silver medalist, filled his ear with more inspiring tidings.
</P>
<P>
   You're the fastest man in the race, don't forget that, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane 1 is ideal, since you're such a closer.
</P>
<P>
   Others have won from there (the last being John Akii-Bua in
1972, in world-record time).
</P>
<P>
   Just run contained and in control, and attack those last three
hurdles down the straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   If the 21-year-old Taylor didn't do something spectacular with
this race, it wouldn't be for lack of support. ``They helped me
believe I could win out of Lane 1,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came this great voice from above. It wasn't the Almighty's
answer to Taylor's prayer, but the next best thing. Angelo Taylor
was proclaimed Olympic champion. Everything he was told had came
true. He did run in perfect control, his timing over the opening
hurdles as good as it had been all summer. He stormed through the
finishing hurdles, contorting his face almost beyond recognition
with the effort. He ran the field into the ground at the end. He
won in an excruciating lean. All in a personal-best 47.50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, Greece's King Constantine was hanging a
gold medal from his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the epitome of the best,'' said Taylor's mother, taking
superlatives to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   A most amazing thing has happened over one three-day period in
Australia. Two kids from the same high school a half a world away
watched an Olympics in their hometown in 1996 and decided they were
going to be running in the next one. Not just some Olympics, the
next Olympics, no matter how young they were. Improbably, Trammell
and Taylor were as good as their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes more and more incredible the more it settles in,''
said Cobb, the high school track coach who made the pilgrimage here
to witness the ultimate payoff to a life's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two kids a year apart at the same school go gold-silver in the
same Olympics? I think your chances are better of hitting the
lottery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There had to be a heavenly convergence of family and coaching to
get these two to a medal platform in the same Games. And Atlanta
can long debate the legacy of its Olympics, but it will always have
the accomplishment of two native sons to point to.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have grown up watching all those Olympics, to have seen
them in my hometown and then to be a part of them. It's hard to put
into words,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the Olympic Games at home had to be a factor,'' Cobb
said. ``I still remember both of them telling me after they had
seen their events in Atlanta that they were going to be in the 2000
Olympics. That had to give them the motivation . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
