<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACK-MAIN0928-CO     09-27 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-MAIN0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panther Pride in hurdles
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ When he picked up his cell phone, Angelo Taylor didn't
know what to make of the over-the-top banter ringing in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Here he was, an hour from the race of his life, prone on a
massage table, and Terrence Trammell was calling from inside the
Olympic Stadium, trying to pump him up like they were back in high
school and Buck Godrey was sending them out against their fiercest
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Lane 1, killer tight turns . . . nearly impossible to bring home
the gold from there?
</P>
<P>
   Panther Pride, baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crazy,'' laughed Taylor, basking in the glow of his
Olympic gold-medal run in the 400-meter hurdles. ``He was more
hyped than I was. He said a lot of things, like `bring it home to
Atlanta. Not just any medal _ the gold.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As it played out, Trammell had it all right. Nothing could keep
Taylor from his gold medal Wednesday. Not even the almost
disastrous, unlucky draw of having to navigate his angular,
6-foot-3 frame around the inside lane.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor put metro Atlanta's Southwest DeKalb High School in the
history books _ joining Trammell as the first high school teammates
to win track medals at the same Games _ dipping smartly at the
finish line to eke past Hadi Souan Somayli of Saudi Arabia before a
packed Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first ever Olympic medal for the Saudis, and it's
expected Somayli earned himself a king's ransom.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, Taylor shot a quick glance to his right at his
rival, and then cupped his hands while dropping to his knees in
prayer. ``I didn't know who won the race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell's silver medal sprint two days earlier in the 110-meter
hurdles. And it followed up on the gold medal effort in Atlanta
four years ago by training partner Derrick Adkins _ both under the
tutelage of Georgia Tech coach Grover Hinsdale, officially crowning
him the top intermediate hurdler coach.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor won in a personal-best 47.50 seconds, a blink of an eye
better than Adkins' clocking of 47.54 in Atlanta. Not surprising,
it was also the fastest time ever run out of Lane One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't I tell you, man,'' screamed Trammell, hugging Taylor as
he came off the track, draped in the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lane One, baby,'' Taylor shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell had phoned Taylor at the adjacent warmup track,
determined to pump up his spirits about the draw of the inside
lane, which hadn't launched a winner since John Akii-Bua at the
1972 Munich Games.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they were joined near the finish by Taylor's fiance
Tangela Wobbleton, brother Corey and sister Alexandria _ all with
``Go Angelo'' painted in blue on their face. They abandoned their
seats deep in the upper-deck to stand along the rail on the first
turn during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to find a way to get down and see my brother run,'' said
Corey Taylor, a hurdler himself at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The support system was on full alert all day leading to the
race. Hinsdale called from Atlanta, exhorting Taylor to be
particularly careful to hold his form on the curves so the
centrifical force wouldn't pull him away from the inside rail and
eat up valuable time.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor spent the day holed up in the athlete village, selling
himself on the idea that location wouldn't be his demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he'd shock the world,'' Trammell said of his final
words. ``I told him he was in Lane One, because it represents
first-place. I know my boy, and he wasn't going to let anything as
simple as Lane One stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did he win the gold medal from Lane One, he ran a
(personal-best) from Lane One. That shows the world it doesn't
matter where you put Angelo Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Taylor managed to turn Lane One to his advantage. He
normally ends up in a middle-of-the-track lane, where his patented
late surge is in full view of the opposition. Because the lanes are
staggered and one starts further up the track than the others,
Taylor ran invisible to the field until the lanes evened down the
backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   He also caught a break when Somayli messed up his steps as he
approached the 10th and last hurdle. When he pulled back coming off
the hurdle, Taylor pounced and used his tremendous closing surge to
capture gold.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was so spent that rather than jogging a victory lap, he
walked around the oval. But in the end, Southwest DeKalb had its
second Olympic medal and Taylor also positioned himself for another
in the 1,600-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on championship teams in high school,'' Taylor said
of he and Trammell's success here. ``Winning is nothing new to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Both were talents the day they walked through the school door.
Together, they helped bring state titles in football and track.
Trammell was the top high school track athlete in the country his
senior year. Later, they earned national college track athlete of
the year _ Trammell twice.
</P>
<P>
   For years ago, Taylor only watched the Olympics after just
missing to qualify for the trials as a high school senior. That
summer, he and Dwight Phillips, his roommate who is in the
long-jump final Thursday, were part of a 1,600-meter relay that
broke the Junior Olympic record.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 21, came here as the gold-medal favorite, though wiser
for a humbling experience at last summer's World Championships. In
a first-round race, he miscalculated the automatic qualifer to the
next round _ thinking it was the top four finishers when it was
three _ and never had the chance to win his medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching the final last year and knowing it should have been
mind, I took it to heart,'' Taylor said. ``But having the gold in
Seville or this, I'll take this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
