<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOSS-LARGESS-570&AMP;ADD-     09-27 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSS-LARGESS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARTING GIFT FROM THE BOSS WHO CARED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Colo., Calif., Ill.)   By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Much has been made of the fringe benefits of working
for a dot-com company _ the free cappuccino, the concierge services
and the lucrative stock options.
</P>
<P>
   But for one day last week, working the production line for a
company that makes floor wax and carpet cleaner brought the perk of
a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 19, Charlie Butcher, 84, the chairman of the
family-owned Butcher Co. in Marlborough, Mass., handed out bonus
checks to his 325 employees that totaled $18 million, a hefty chunk
of his proceeds from selling the company the day before. ``Some of
the folks are big, strong, strapping machine operators, and they
just filled up with tears,'' said Paul P. McLaughlin, the company's
president. ``They would just throw their arms around Charlie and
give him a big hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Ouellette, 42, who has been an administrative assistant
for over 10 years, would not disclose her share, but she did say
that the checks were weighted according to seniority and salary.
She estimated that each worker received at least $1.50 for every
hour worked over the years. The average works out to over $55,000
each. ``Charlie really wanted to take care of the hourly folks and
people who put in a lot of years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The employees knew of the impending sale and had heard rumors
that they might be receiving a bonus. Still, they had no hint of
the size _ which for some totaled more than a year's salary _ until
Butcher and his wife, Jane, flew out from their Colorado home to
close the deal with Johnson Wax Professional and hand out the
checks. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Rutherford, 41, has worked on the production floor for 22
years, and has never had such a windfall. ``I was just shocked,''
she said. ``I went over and hugged him and his wife. I couldn't say
anything, I was too nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, her hand was steady enough to take the check to the car
dealership the same day, where she bought the blue Jeep she had
been eyeing. Her 15-year-old daughter now has the bedroom furniture
she had been promised.
</P>
<P>
   For Butcher, this may be the biggest lump sum of bliss he has
delivered in his career, but he said employee satisfaction had been
a shrewd business strategy for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are happy in their jobs, they are at least twice
as productive,'' he said in a phone interview from his home in
Colorado, explaining his belief in higher starting salaries,
flexible work weeks and freedom for people to change jobs if they
are unhappy. That, he said, leads to fewer mistakes, better
production and more money for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that other businesses will follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful, easygoing philosophy,'' he said. ``At the
same time, I get the pleasure of being thought of as a neat guy.''
</P>
<P>
   About 130 employees are based in Marlborough, about 30 miles
west of Boston, with the rest in plants in Compton, Calif., and
Alsip, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   William Taylor, president of the Alsip division who has worked
for the company for 15 years, said that Butcher would act as a
unique cheerleader for the sales team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell them, `I want you guys to make me money, because
I'm going to give it right back to you,''' he said. ``They would
say, `Yeah, yeah.'''
</P>
<P>
   To their surprise, it was true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange feeling,'' Taylor said. ``To me and to others,
we felt like it was far more than we actually deserved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Butcher's grandfather, Charles Butcher, an installer of parquet
floors in many of Boston's grand homes, founded the company in
1880. His product was a paste wax called Boston Polish, which is
still respected in Martha Stewart's circle. But when Charlie
Butcher took over the company from his father and uncle in the
1950s, he turned it into a competitive player in the commercial
cleaning business.
</P>
<P>
   Butcher retired as chief executive in the 1970s and moved to
Colorado, although he often flew back for sales meetings and the
company-wide parties, picnics and barbecues that Butcher is known
for.
</P>
<P>
   His employees know him as unabashedly affectionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he spoke to people on the phone, from executive level all
the way down, he would end the conversation with `I love you,'''
Suzanne Smethurst, now in her 14th year with the finance
department, said. ``We all grew to understand that it was a sincere
and heartfelt remark.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, the chairman decided to sell the company this year,
partly to free up money for the Lazy Eight Foundation, a charitable
research organization that he founded three years ago, and partly
because he did not have the capital to make necessary changes in
the company's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   He ruled out a stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I went public I wouldn't be able to give out $18
million,'' he said. ``Investors are very tight with their money. If
investors understood how much good it does to have happy, loving
and productive employees, they would agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he told the employees of his intention to sell this summer,
it sent ripples of anxiety through the tight-knit company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I wasn't going to have a job,'' Rutherford said. ``I
didn't know who was going to buy us. It was kind of
nerve-racking.''
</P>
<P>
   But Butcher was, as usual, looking out ``for all the cars in the
parking lot.'' Although he said other companies offered him more
money, he chose to deal with the spinoff of S.C. Johnson &AMP; Son
Inc., another family-owned company with a 114-year history of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   J. Gary Raley, the president for North American operations at
Johnson Wax, based in Sturtevant, Wis., said the plan was to let
Butcher Co. operate independently, with the same name and
employees. As a welcome-to-the-family gesture, he has sent each
worker a basket filled with Pledge, Glade and Windex products.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the unexpected gain is as good as spent, workers said,
mentioning things like televisions, college trust funds, vinyl
siding and long-overdue prescription eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the money, they said, parting with Charlie will be
bittersweet.
</P>
</TEXT>
