<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-CAMPAI     09-27 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY PARENTS SAY ISSUE OF VIOLENCE IN MEDIA WILL NOT INFLUENCE
THEIR VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich.)   (Eds: CORRECTS ``Kroger's'' to ``Kroger'' thruout)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAND, Mich. _ Overwhelmed by the competing proposals in a
tight presidential race, Michael Horst grabbed a sheet of paper
during the evening news the other night and drew a line down the
middle. He wrote ``Gore'' on the left, ``Bush'' on the right, and
then rated the candidates' positions, drawing a plus sign in the
Bush column next to capital punishment and a minus sign next to the
Texas governor's education record.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere did he mention an issue that has been the focus of
much moralizing on the campaign trail: sex and violence in movies
and popular music, and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Though Horst, 39, said he had agonized over how his 11-year-old
daughter and 8-year-old son were being affected by the seepage of
nudity and mayhem into what they watch and hear, he stressed that
he wasn't looking to politicians for answers. It was, he said,
something he could best grapple with on his own, however
imperfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't feel anything they say on this is going to
influence me one way or the other,'' said Horst, a theft prevention
manager for the Rite Aid chain of drugstores. ``What decision they
make is not going to affect what my children see.''
</P>
<P>
   Horst's sentiments echoed through more than a dozen other
interviews with parents of adolescents in Westland, a solidly
middle-class suburb of Detroit that, like the rest of this state,
is considered a battleground in the presidential race. Neither
Republicans nor Democrats dominate here _ Westlanders supported
President Clinton, a Democrat, in 1992 and 1996, and Gov. John
Engler, a Republican, in 1994 and 1998 _ and nearly everyone
interviewed said that they had not decided who they would vote for
in November.
</P>
<P>
   But as they shopped for milk at Kroger, ate ice cream at the
Westland Mall, sat in the bleachers at the Westland Sports Arena or
even waited for an adjustment at Shunkwiler Chiropractic, most
parents agreed that it was their responsibility _ and not that of
the president, Congress or even Hollywood _ to filter what reaches
their children. The candidates, they suggested, should save their
breath for the economy and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all of the parents conceded that they regularly crossed or
blurred the borders between acceptable and unacceptable content.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Palise, 44, a homemaker whose husband is a tool-and-die
maker at the Ford plant in Rawnsonville, said that she tried to
shield her son Anthony, 12, from nudity and bad language in movies.
But the other day, after skimming a review of ``The Watcher'' to
gauge its appropriateness for her son, she decided to take him to
see the R-rated film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was about a serial killer,'' she said,
loading groceries into her customized van. ``I thought it was about
a stalker.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Palise regretted asking Anthony to come along, he was
ambivalent. ``I fell asleep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That even the sturdiest dams erected by parents can occasionally
spring holes was obvious as Phyllis Blackman shopped for gospel
records at Record Town in the Westland Mall with her 16-year-old
daughter, La Toya Hamilton. Blackman said she had a zero-tolerance
policy against rap _ unless it was the feel-good rap of the
Hollywood star Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't play the stupid stuff in the house,'' the mother
said.
</P>
<P>
   But as La Toya sought out a compact disc by the gospel singer
Yolanda Adams, an artist whom both mother and daughter adore, the
daughter said she also enjoyed the music of the slain rapper Tupac
Shakur, which, she admitted, is layered with references to ``sex,
bad-mouthing of some females, violence and killing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she had it,'' the mother said. ``It's not something she
continues to listen to on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Horst, the Rite Aid manager, said he ``blew my cork''
when he discovered that his 8-year-old son had seen a PG-rated
``Austin Powers'' video at a friend's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything with Austin Powers has a sexual connotation, and I
got hit with a lot of questions an 8-year-old shouldn't be
asking,'' Horst said, watching from a bench at the arena as the boy
scrimmaged with his ice hockey team, the Westland Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Horst said he doesn't hesitate to allow his son to watch
the explosion-laden ``Terminator'' movies, which star Arnold
Schwarzenegger, and he took the boy and his 11-year-old sister to
see ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That had a moderately explicit scene,'' Horst said. ``My
daughter asked me, Dad, what are they doing? I said, He's an
artist. He's painting her. They're not actually doing any intimate
acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Horst, a self-described conservative who is a registered
Republican, and Palise and Blackman, both Democrats, said they
considered themselves ``strict.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost none of those interviewed here said that they wanted
Washington to censor Hollywood, or even Hollywood to censor itself.
The one pledge that they hoped Hollywood would make would be to
swear off marketing violent fare directly to teen-agers, the
subject of a congressional hearing Wednesday, and a Federal Trade
Commission report earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking against more regulation of Hollywood, the parents
repeatedly cited their belief in freedom of speech, and said they
themselves often enjoyed material that they'd prefer their children
not see.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Obsniuk, 48, a mail carrier whose children are 12, 14 and
16, said that any attempt by Washington to rein in Hollywood would
be ``a waste of time.'' As his youngest child, Jenna, twirled on
the ice during a skating lesson, Obsniuk described how he and his
wife, Debbie, an elementary school secretary, enjoyed watching
programs like ``The Sopranos,'' the bloody and often sexually
charged mob drama on HBO. But he said that they were careful to
change the channel whenever their children entered the room.
</P>
<P>
   Having voted for President Clinton in 1996 and 1992, and George
Bush in 1988, Obsniuk said he was undecided between Al Gore and
George W. Bush. But he said that his assessment of the economy, and
of which candidate presented the best chance for continued
prosperity, would drive his thinking.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the bleachers nearby, Kevin Beahon, 47, a quality
control inspector at the Ford national parts depot in Livonia, said
that he was eminently qualified to screen what reaches the eyes and
ears of his 13- and 16-year-old sons, and 7-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Beahon, a likely Bush voter who has barred his two younger
children from watching adult-oriented cartoons like ``The
Simpsons'' and ``South Park,'' said he had gotten pretty good at
navigating the music Web site Napster. When someone left a note on
the front door for his 13-year-old son, Stephen, imploring him to,
``Get Your Roll On,'' Beahon was puzzled. Stephen told his dad that
his friend was using the title of a song by a rap act called Big
Tymers to urge him to get going to a party.
</P>
<P>
   Beahon went straight to the Internet to retrieve the song, and
after listening to its rapid-fire references to oral sex, male
genitalia, adultery and prostitution, he concluded: ``This is the
crudest thing I've ever heard.'' Though he admits he can't control
what his son hears outside the home, he told the boy: ``I don't
want to ever hear that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he added: ``I don't think a president should be
delving into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Westland residents are fairly well educated, with many
working in the skilled trades or middle management at auto plants
in surrounding communities, few of those interviewed said they
recognized the name of Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Gore's running mate.
And fewer still were aware that, among the candidates on the two
national tickets, Lieberman has waged the loudest campaign against
what he describes as Hollywood's shrinking mores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me the name again, because I'm good with names and I'll
be sure to remember it,'' said one undecided voter and parent, a
saleswoman at a furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent, Tracy Hart, 34, whose presidential vote seesawed
from Michael Dukakis, a Democrat, in 1988, to George Bush in 1992
and then to President Clinton in 1996, was one of the only people
interviewed here who lamented that the issue of sex and violence in
Hollywood was ``not one of the major issues on the forefront, in
terms of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   As they loaded their car outside Kroger, her daughter, Hillary,
11, quickly corrected her mother, invoking the name of Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?'' said Hart, a single mother who is an
administrator at a physical therapy and rehabilitation clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, citing an article in the Time magazine spinoff
``Time for Kids,'' responded: ``He doesn't think kids should be
able to go to R-rated movies and he thinks bad music is bad. He
wants to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said the mother: ``Well, maybe we know who we're voting for
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
