<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, SEPT. 28 
</HEADLINE>
  EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SPANISH-RADIO-NYT (moved Tuesday, September 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, September
26 about the first all-news Spanish-language radio station in the
New York region misstated the transmitter power of the station,
WNNY-AM (1380), and others in the region. WNNY has a signal of
5,000 watts, not megawatts. The much larger WCBS-AM (880), WINS
(1010), and WADO-AM (1280) have signals of 50,000 watts, not
megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT (moved Monday, September 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
25 about the benefits of drinking milk, misstated the sponsorship
of an advertising campaign against milk. It was produced by People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, not by the Physicians
Committee for Responsible Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HIP-HOP-AUDIENCE-NYT (moved Tuesday, September 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, September
26 about viewers' responses to the ``Hip-Hop Nation'' exhibition at
the Brooklyn Museum of Art referred incorrectly to materials used
by the artist Chris Ofili for his collage of the Virgin Mary in the
museum's recent show ``Sensation.'' Along with paper, oil paint,
glitter and resin, the artist used elephant dung, not cow dung.
</P>
</TEXT>
