u f BC-SWAP-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      09-27 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAP-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NEWS CORP. AND LIBERTY MEDIA COMPLETE ASSET SWAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   News Corp. and Liberty Media Group confirmed Wednesday that they
had agreed to a complex stock and asset swap in which Liberty Media
would increase its stake in News Corp. and News Corp. would pick up
Liberty's Gemstar-TV Guide International holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar-TV Guide provides electronic program guides like VCR
Plus and develops and licenses proprietary technologies primarily
for consumers. It also owns TV Guide and TV Guide Online.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hatch, who follows News Corp. and Liberty Media for SG Cowen,
said he liked the deal because it should help News Corp. rapidly
deploy the programming guides on the digital satellite platforms
that it is consolidating around the world. That strategy, he said,
should ultimately enhance the value of both News Corp. and Liberty,
which will own a stake in the business after it is spun off.
</P>
<P>
   However, one analyst who requested anonymity was less
enthusiastic, saying that News Corp. was effectively paying a high
price for Liberty's 21 percent stake in Gemstar. The addition would
increase its total interest to 43 percent. Much of Gemstar's value,
the analyst said, is in patents that have yet to be tested.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corp., is intent on moving
ahead with the purchase, some analysts said, because it would
strengthen his hand in a bid for General Motors' Hughes Electronics
unit. Hughes owns DirecTV, the satellite TV service. News Corp. is
planning to spin off Sky Global Networks, its big international
satellite operation for pay TV, Internet and data services and is
interested in adding a U.S. satellite business to it.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is strategically important now because it helps put a
valuation on Sky Global of about $38 billion shortly before its
public offering, which is expected to take place by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Liberty would swap roughly 86.5 million
shares of Gemstar. At Wednesday's closing price of $72.94, the
value of the shares would total about $6.3 billion. Liberty would
also contribute some of its interest in South American cable
businesses worth around $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the company would receive 121.5 million nonvoting
News Corp. American depository receipts. They closed Wednesday at
$47.38, for a total value of $5.79 billion. That stake represents
80 percent of the payment the News Corp. plans to make, giving the
entire Gemstar stock purchase a value of around $7.2 billion.
Liberty's chairman, John C. Malone, has agreed to take the balance
in Sky Global stock worth $1.4 billion. And Liberty will get
roughly $400 million in additional Sky Global stock in exchange for
the South American cable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty will, therefore, receive a total of $1.8 billion in the
satellite business' stock. News Corp. said Wednesday that Liberty's
total payment in Sky Global stock would equal 4.8 percent of Sky
Global's total value, giving the business a total value of about
$38 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty also agreed to buy $500 million of Sky Global stock in
the initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the companies involved in the deal all rose Wednesday.
Gemstar was up $4.38 at $72.94 ; News Corp.'s regular American
depository receipts climbed $2.69, to $56.50; and Liberty Media
closed up 50 cents at $18.88.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, which is a tracking stock of AT&AMP;T, is a collection of
programming assets that Malone assembled as he was building his
cable empire.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch of SG Cowan said two-thirds of the value of Liberty Media
was in publicly traded equities, many of which have dramatically
declined in the past 52 weeks. Liberty's holdings in Sprint-PCS,
for example, has sunk to $7 billion from its high of $14 billion
last March.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty also has interest in Liberty Digital, which had a value
of $16 billion last January but which has since sunk to about $4
billion. Its stake in Time Warner Inc., which had been worth as
much as $12 billion, is now worth $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said Liberty also had stakes in private cable programming
companies like Discovery Communications, owner of the Discovery,
Learning and other cable TV channels. Investors have been concerned
about the impact of advertiser spending on revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The swap of its holdings in Gemstar, whose stock price has
soared over the past year, does little to immediately enhance
Liberty's value. But Malone was apparently eager to increase
Liberty's stake in News Corp. from 6 percent to roughly 18 percent
of the company. That stake would make him the largest holder of
nonvoting shares. It would not, however, give him voting rights or
a seat on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch said in a conference call Wednesday that he would like
to have Malone on the board. But Malone's powerful role at AT&AMP;T
might be a barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty is effectively controlled by AT&AMP;T, and regulators could
take issue with Malone sitting on the board of AT&AMP;T, now one of the
nation's largest cable operators, as well as on the board of News
Corp., the parent of Sky Global, which has a competing
direct-to-home satellite service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
