<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCC0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norwegians likely to be tougher this time
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The shock of a 2-0 drubbing at the hands of the United
States in the opening game of the Olympics on Sept. 14 had barely
set in for Norway coach Per-Mathias Hogmo when he expressed
gratitude the margin wasn't even larger.
</P>
<P>
   Equally surprised were the Americans, who had dropped three
games to Norway this year and who have a losing record all-time
against their Norwegian rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not look like the Norway team that we know,'' said
forward Tiffeny Milbrett, who scored the first goal and ran laps
around the unnerved Norwegian defense.
</P>
<P>
   Norway recovered to beat China and move out of group play, then
received the gift of an own goal with 10 minutes to play against
Germany in the semifinals for a 1-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   When they meet on Thursday at the Sydney Football Stadium for
the gold medal, it will be the second time in the five major
international women's tournaments that the U.S. and Norway have
slugged it out at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans beat Norway in the finals of the first Women's
World Cup in 1991, then Norway pulled off a surprise in the World
Cup semifinals four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the U.S. has prevailed, winning the first Olympic
gold medal in 1996 and its second World Cup last summer. Even with
the loss last week, Norway leads the series 14-13-1, and the teams
are tied 3-3-1 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been gaining confidence as they have gone along in the
tournament,'' U.S. coach April Heinrichs said. ``I have thought for
several months now that we were on a collision course with
Norway.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. beat Brazil 1-0 Sunday in a sloppily played semifinal
game, but found a way to endure. Mia Hamm scored a clutch goal for
the Americans, but their occasionally sputtering attack could be
cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   In their group match in Melbourne, the Norwegian offensive
combination of Marianne Pettersen and Hege Riise was marked out
effectively by a U.S. defense that has sparkled throughout the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Gro Espeseth and goalkeeper Bente Nordby are among the
best in the world at their positions, but they didn't have an
answer for Milbrett, the most consistent U.S. scorer, the first
time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this game is going to be completely different,''
Milbrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
