<HEADER>
A4255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH-BASEBALL0928     09-27 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-BASEBALL0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hop, skip and jump for victory
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - He and his teammates had made their victory lap around
the ballpark like a bunch of laughing, hollering, got-no-cares
schoolboys. The had hopped and jumped, zig-zagged between each
other, waving their American flags as the ``U-S-A...U-S-A...U-S-A''
chants rained down on them from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   They passed beneath the outfield scoreboard that still burned
their 4-0 gold medal victory over Cuba into the Sydney night. They
passed the place in left-center where his home run had cleared the
fence. They tromped over the spot just inside the left field line
where he had made his dramatic, diving catch to end the game. And
then they had trotted past the opponents' dugout, where the
red-uniformed Cubans - their Olympic reign so unexpectedly ended -
stood sullen and slumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played in the World Series, but who cares,'' said
Mike Neill, the 30-year-old American left-fielder. ``Right now this
is huge. This is my World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. players stood on the medal stand and each took his
turn bowing forward so the gold medal could be draped over his
head, you noticed Neill had the left side of his white warm-up
jacket pulled up over his ear. He looked like he was hiding
something, but as you watched him chatter and smile, you soon
realized he was talking on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my mom back in Greensboro, N.C.,'' he'd explain a bit
sheepishly later on. ``I wanted her to know what happened and I
wanted her to hear the national anthem when it was played.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the crowd and all, it was hard carrying on a
conversation. I told her I hit a home run and we won. She thought I
meant I hit THE home run to make us win. I kept trying to tell her,
'No, Mom, it was just a regular homer. ``
</P>
<P>
   When he heard what Neill had said, American manager Tommy
Lasorda - a regular red, white and blue Uncle Sam when it came to
spouting his team's Olympic gospel - shook his head and pushed away
the idea like he was sending back a skimpy bowl of pasta.
</P>
<P>
   ``People asked me about the home run (Kirk) Gibson hit when we
beat the A's in the World Series,'' the former Los Angeles Dodgers
manager said. ``That was dramatic. It made all the Dodgers fans
happy. But to me this was bigger. I felt more excited for Mike
Neill and the team than I did with that first one. To me this was
bigger than the World Series. Today, Dodgers fans were happy and
San Francisco fans were happy and Cincinnati, too. Today the whole
United States of America can be happy.
</P>
<P>
   `` And it all goes back to Neill. His home run set the tone for
the night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban team - a power in international baseball for nearly 30
years - had won Olympic gold in 1992 and 1996, the only two Games
where baseball had been a medal sport. Even though their team is
now aging and its ranks have been thinned by recent defections, the
Cubans were heavily-favored to win the 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   They had beaten the Americans, 6-1, in a nasty prelim game on
Saturday that had been filled with angry words, a beanball, a
spikes-high slide into American catcher Pat Borders and some
roughhouse tactics by U.S. first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz. After
subduing the Americans once, it was figured the Cubans would do it
again Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always the best team that wins or the strongest guy
who wins the fight,'' Lasorda said. ``It's usually the team that
wants it more than the other and tonight that was our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one wanted it more than Neill.
</P>
<P>
   He has played professional baseball for 10 years and has had
very few minutes in the spotlight. A career minor leaguer, he got
only one brief invite to the big leagues when the Oakland As called
him up in 1998. He played six games, got 15 at bats and then
dislocated his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he healed, the window had long closed. He was back
in minor league ball and no longer considered a prospect. That's
why the As offered him to Team USA to play in the Pan American
Games last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Used as a sub most of that tournament, he suddenly became the
hero when he came off the bench to hit the run-scoring single in
the 10th inning that beat Mexico and sent the U.S. to the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months later, Oakland waived him and in the
offseason, he managed to catch on with the Seattle Mariners.
Playing for their Triple A club in Tacoma, he again was not
destined for the big leagues and was given to Lasorda to help fill
the Olympic roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought Major League baseball didn't give us a good
team,'' Lasorda said. ``Well look what guys like Mike Neill did.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of his three home runs in the Olympic tournament was
in the opener, a 13th inning blast to beat Japan. Wednesday night
Neill bookended the masterful pitching performance of right-hander
Ben Sheets with the solo homer in the first and the diving catch of
Yasser Gomez' fast-falling liner down the line at game's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of us are nobodies,'' Neill said. ``But we all
believed in each other and lifted each other up. That's the best
thing I'm taking home from here.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the only thing.
</P>
<P>
   He reached into his back pocket and fished out a baseball.
``This is the one I caught and I wasn't going to let it go,'' he
said proudly. ``This ball is special.''
</P>
<P>
   He held it admiringly, he rubbed it and then he shoved it
securely back into his hip pocket. It meant baseball's best times
and he had waited a long time to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
