<HEADER>
A4256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-MARION0928-COX     09-27 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MARION0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones' drive for five keeps her focused
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The longest day of Marion Jones' Olympics
used to be easy enough to identify. It would be Wednesday, Sept.
27, targeted for months in advance, with an ambitious schedule of
two 200-meter preliminary heats and a round of long jump
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, that's more than any athlete since Carl Lewis would
care to bite off. Getting those hamstrings up and humming three
times in one day, taking the heart and the mind into express-train
mode three times and then backing them off quickly onto a quiet
sidetrack, that's one challenge. Being the best in the world at
every event you try, that's the other.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Marion skip lightly through this killer schedule,
however, put a new perspective on a truly Olympian quest for five
gold medals. Her longest day wasn't Wednesday at all.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a day spent with two cheering fan clubs in excess
of 100,000, which was the announced Stadium Australia crowd for the
evening session of track and field and the morning session, too.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, that was the day that wouldn't end, beginning as it did
with Marion's husband C.J. Hunter fingered by the International
Amateur Athletic Federation as a steroid cheat in shot put
competition earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was Tuesday, when Marion stepped into a Sydney hotel
banquet room that proved insufficient to hold all the reporters who
wanted to hunt down Hunter. Yeah, that was a pretty lousy day, too,
with her 330-pound hubby crying on camera and nobody really
swallowing what he said, which was that an iron supplement with
insignificant amounts of a banned substance called nandrolone that
C.J. says wasn't listed on the label.
</P>
<P>
   If having Johnnie Cochran in the room was supposed to be a
comfort for Marion, that didn't work too well either. All O.J.'s
lawyer did was introduce the probability of a numbingly technical
defense that could stretch on for months. Strengthened the
perception that C.J.'s got something to hide, too.
</P>
<P>
   What rhyme might Johnnie invent to turn the positive test
results into a joke? Perhaps ``If the nandro was hidden,
suspension's forbidden,'' or ``If the supplement's iron, it's the
wrong man you're trying.''
</P>
<P>
   All this for a world champion shot putter who says he'd like to
quit competing but then nobody would be willing to pay for him to
travel around the world with his famous track-star wife.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mess all right, but Marion had an escape route, at least
temporarily. She'd go to the stadium. She'd make short work of her
longest competitive day and busy herself with running and jumping
and winning, the three things that nobody yet has been able to make
troublesome for Marion.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. watched her from the media section of the stands Wednesday
morning, peeping with the enemy. In Marion's first 200-meter heat,
at 11:09 a.m., she was the sixth-fastest qualifier - 22.75 seconds
_ while running on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I don't have anybody in my heat tonight that wants
to run fast,'' Jones said, greeting reporters on her way off the
track with the same gracious smile she wore before the C.J.
scandal. ``I just want to take it easy but I will do what I have to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   A light meal, a quick nap and it was time to climb back into the
car for Sydney Olympic Park. She did run into someone who wanted to
run fast, but not nearly fast enough. Marion drew Australia's
Melinda Gainsford-Taylor in her Round 2 heat, which went off
promptly at 7:01 p.m. Jones broke out easily and settled into
something just above a trot over the last 10 meters. That gave the
Aussies something to cheer about as Gainsford-Taylor came
barrelling past in 22.49, one-tenth of a second faster than Marion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, I let up a bit too much,'' Jones said, all but
snickering about it. ``Everything that's happened in the last
couple of days, I've pushed it into the back of my head. It's all
about business now. I'd like to make my qualifying jump on my first
jump tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it, she did just that. Some ninety minutes
after Marion's second and final 200-meter heat, she took one smooth
sprint down the runway and one elegant flight into the long-jump
pit. No world record, but no foul, either. Her 6.78-meter effort,
slightly over 22 feet, was good enough to slide into Friday's final
without breaking a real sweat. Good enough, too, to rank third
overall behind 1992 gold medalist Heike Drechsler of Germany and
1996 silver medalist Fiona May of Italy, two single-minded
champions who jump for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all my days in Sydney, this has been the hardest,'' said
Jones, ``but I came away healthy and happy. Overall, it's been a
very good day for me. I just wanted to do the first jump and go
home. I can conserve energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the C.J. question is tossed her way at the end of what
has proved to be her most casual day at the Olympics, not the
craziest. Again the smile and the easy answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment,'' she said, ``I'm just concentrating on running
and jumping. It keeps my mind off everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Steers our minds back toward the track, too, and there is where
Marion will make her mark. Whether her spouse is a louse or
unfairly accused ceases to be a question the moment the starting
gun sounds, as it will tonight in the semifinals and final of the
200.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Marion turn what was supposed to be her longest
day into a lark, I'm more convinced than ever that this drive for
five will strike gold on every count. The only thing that can stop
her is a dropped baton or some other such nonsense in the two
relays at the end of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   The busier the better for Marion, that's the blessing here.
Under the circumstances, it's ideal that she has no more days off.
That all but guarantees the girl with the laughing feet will go on
and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
