<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-WRESTLING0928-COX     09-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farm-boy dreamer topples giant
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Rulon Gardner was an overweight child. Kids called him
``Fatso,'' or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the time he grabbed a branch at a Boy Scouts outing
and chased an older boy who teased him, Gardner never fought back.
He always has been able to achieve a state of calm that shuts out
external forces.
</P>
<P>
   That aptitude served him well against Alexander Karelin, an
almost mythical figure who is the uncontested all-time greatest
Greco-Roman wrestler. Of all the gold medals being doled out in
Sydney, none was regarded a certainty as much as Karelin's fourth
straight in the Olympic heavyweight (286-pound) class.
</P>
<P>
   But the former farm boy from a Wyoming town, where the major
mode of transportation is the tractor, can fight all right. Put him
in a singlet, give him some coaches, and point the way to the mat:
He can whup anyone.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he did Wednesday, leveling a legend 1-0 for the
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a rough life,'' said Gardner, 29. ``Been an underdog
every step. One thing I learned _ don't ever quit. If you believe
it in your mind, the body can do great things.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the youngest of Virginia and Reed's nine children in
Afton, Wyo. (pop: 1,200). He wrestled with his four brothers, one
now deceased. He hauled bales of hay, milked cows and cleared rocks
off the field so crops could grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst,'' said Reed Gardner, 70, wrapped in an
American flag. ``That job (with the rocks) has driven more boys off
the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Rulon Gardner, 29. ``Hauling rocks was actually fun,''
he said. ``We'd throw them in the truck, and they'd go ding.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, young Gardner wanted to flee the farm life, so he reached
for sports as his ticket out. With a barrel chest that makes him
``look like I ate a little kid,'' he went to the University of
Nebraska on a full ride for wrestling. He would have played on the
Cornhuskers' esteemed line had football offered more than a partial
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Gardner could not blame him for leaving. ``Owning a farm in
the U.S. is tough now,'' he said. ``We're not making any money.
We've struggled at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the Gardner kids moved away to college
educations and decent jobs, they could afford the trip to Sydney.
Mom and Dad are part of the 16-member entourage only through the
generosity of the community, which chipped in for their expenses.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the Games himself, Gardner had to conquer his first
legend, four-time Olympian Matt Ghaffari, at the U.S. Trials. For
all of Ghaffari's brilliance, he was 0-22 lifetime against Karelin.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner had confronted Karelin once, falling 5-0 in 1997, but
the match was scoreless after six minutes of regulation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of frightened me to feel the strength he had,''
Gardner said. ``It was like pushing a horse or a cow. The only
problem is, (Karelin) is a little quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``I had this certain calm that was weird. I don't think
I've ever felt more like wrestling in my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Even against the menacing Karelin, a man right out of a
super-hero comic book? Who weighed 15 pounds at birth? Whose feats
of strength seem concocted? Whose trademark reverse body slam sends
foes flying feet-over-heels? Who had not lost a significant match
in 13 years? Who had allowed one point in a decade?
</P>
<P>
   ``I treat every wrestler the same,'' Gardner said. ``I don't
care if it's a junior high kid in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   To discourage stall tactics and passivity, Greco-Roman
instituted a rule since the Atlanta Games. If the first of two
periods is scoreless, the second begins with one man clinching
another's chest. If the clincher does not tally a point within a
minute, his opponent earns one.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin was applying a clinch when Gardner induced him to
release it. The tactic resulted in a point.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the lead, however, he was drawn into a three-minute
overtime because neither wrestler had accumulated the necessary
three points.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't matter. ``Rulon wrestled a perfect match against the
greatest of all time,'' said the U.S. coach, Dan Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner celebrated with a cartwheel. But he spoke reverently
later of Karelin. ``I still think he's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Not today. For eight minutes, 55 seconds, the man whose
nicknames include ``The Experiment'' could not decipher Gardner.
So, with five seconds left, he bent over in a stance of surrender
and fought no further, mumbling a few words in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Rulon Gardner, the Wyoming farm boy, doesn't speak the language.
But he took a stab at the translation.
</P>
<P>
   And what does he believe the baddest dude on the planet said?
</P>
<P>
   ``I give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
