<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TECHNOLOGY BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MTV CUTTING ONLINE JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said Wednesday that it would cut the staff at MTVi Group,
the Internet division of MTV Networks, by 105 positions, or 25
percent. The company also postponed plans for a spinoff of the
year-old MTVi, whose 22 Web sites include MTV.com, VH1.com and
Sonicnet.com. A spokesman said that the 105 layoffs were part of a
move to consolidate the music sites and that MTVi's revenue is
expected to nearly double this year from $19.9 million in 1999. But
some analysts saw the move as a product of the market's cooling
toward Web companies that focus on digital entertainment. ``This
makes you notice how even major entertainment companies are
struggling to create successful online entities,'' said Stacey
Herron, an analyst at Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   SENATORS RAISE AOL CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee on telecommunications, trade and consumer
protection convened Wednesday to discuss interactive television.
But with Stephen M. Case, chairman of America Online, present,
questions turned to issues standing in the way of the proposed
AOL-Time Warner merger. Members of the committee tried to tackle
thorny topics like whether Time Warner should be required to open
its cable network to all Internet service providers as a condition
of the merger and whether AOL would share its popular instant
messaging services. Case sought to assuage concerns, noting that
many Internet service providers are waiting until after the merger
to negotiate for access to Time Warner's cable systems and saying
the messaging technology could be compatible with other systems.
</P>
<P>
   BRICKS AND CLICKS CONVERGENCE?
</P>
<P>
   In another effort to bring together Internet and traditional
retailing, a company named in Los Angeles is introducing a series
of prepaid cards to be sold in retail stores that enable the card
holders to buy merchandise on the Web sites of e-commerce
companies. J. Michael Boh, chief executive at Prepay.com, described
the cards as a cost-effective method for dot-coms to acquire
customers as they ``search for ways offline to drive people
online.'' The cards can be used like gift certificates, entitling
the users to buy merchandise on the Web sites of dot-coms like
Aboutgolf.com, Beautyscene.com and Cigar.com. Boh said Prepay.com
would begin national sales of the cards through large retail chains
in late October.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC SITES DRAW AD SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   In what may be seen as a silver lining to the legal clouds
hovering over Internet music sites, data gathered by the
advertising measurement service AdRelevance suggests that the sites
have benefited from increased ad revenue in the wake of publicity
surrounding this sector. During the two weeks after the July 26
injunction against the music file-sharing service Napster,
advertising revenue at about 23 music sites monitored by
AdRelevance jumped 39 percent. Although for most music sites, the
spike was short-lived, a few, like Spinner.com and Sonic.Net, had
sustained increases in advertising revenue through early September.
But Napster itself does not stand to benefit from the effect, since
its Web site does not carry advertisements.
</P>
</TEXT>
