A4262 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-OLYTRAK-LADN-(SLA     09-27 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYTRAK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVERS DENIED ONCE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SYDNEY, Australia _ Gail Devers stopped in mid-interview, as
abruptly as she had done minutes earlier in mid-race.
</P>
<P>
   A giant scoreboard at Olympic Stadium was showing a head-on
replay of Devers' 100-meter hurdles semifinal. She stared at the
screen and when she saw herself run through the fifth hurdle, she
blinked. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   It took all her composure Wednesday to watch history repeating
itself. In the 1992 Olympic final in Barcelona, the former UCLA
standout clipped the last hurdle and stumbled out of the lead and
fell to fifth. But at least she finished.
</P>
<P>
   Devers knew she was doomed this time, though she did her best
not to show it. She went through the motions in warmup and tried to
ignore the twinges that told her the tear in her left hamstring was
getting worse, not better.
</P>
<P>
   She stepped into the blocks and tried to shake the injury out.
But a few strides into her semifinal race, she felt it. The pain
grew more pronounced with every hurdle she cleared. After the
fourth one, she could take it no more. Devers ran through the fifth
hurdle and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   The best year of Devers' career would not complete her, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, the woman who has dominated the sprint hurdles for
the past decade, who posted seven of the 10 fastest times this year
and lowered her own American record, is 0-for-the-medals in four
Olympic hurdling appearances. Her best finish in the event was a
fourth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somebody else's turn to shine,'' a philosophical Devers
said later in a post-race, post-mortem. ``That's why I'm not
sitting up here crying. I have to keep everything in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Devers' demise throws opened the window of opportunity for
Nigeria's Glory Alozie, who is competing here with a lithe spirit
and a heavy heart. Her fiance, 400 meters runner Hyginus Anayo
Anugo, was struck by a car here and killed two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alozie ran a front-running 12.68 in her semifinal heat, the
third- fastest time recorded in these Games behind Devers' 12.62 in
the first round and Olga Shishigina's 12.66 in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, in the final, Shishigina edged Alozie for the gold, 12.65
to 12.68. Melissa Morrison, Devers' U.S. teammate, took the bronze
in 12.76.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys want me to give you some sob story,'' said Devers in
a tone that made it clear she wasn't inclined to cooperate. ``I had
a slight tear in my hamstring. I was hoping to run through it. But
I felt it getting worse with every hurdle. End of story. End of
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Devers, 33, incurred the injury earlier this month at a meet in
Brussels and had to pull out of her last pre-Games tuneup, in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't have to run here. Goodness knows other athletes have
pulled out of these Games with flimsier excuses than the cellophane
paper on which the results of Devers' MRI were printed.
</P>
<P>
   Devers never considered not trying. She kept trying to convince
herselfthat this calamity would end happily, just like all of Lucy
Ricardo's escapades do in the ``I Love Lucy'' episodes Devers
devours in her free time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like it was my job and my duty to come in here and give
it my best shot,'' Devers said. ``This is the Olympic Games. This
is what you work for for four years. I wanted to chase after my
dream. That's what I tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Her dream isn't dead, she said, it's just on pause. She was
adamant that retirement is not yet in her vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to use the R-word one time. I still have it on
the shelf,'' Devers said. ``At 33, I've run faster than I ever have
in my life. Why would I retire? Just because I didn't get a gold
medal in the 2000 Olympics doesn't mean I don't have other goals
that can come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Her No. 1 goal? That's easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I have not had is one season that's injury-free,''
Devers said. ``That's my goal for next season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
