<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BAPTIST-HNS &LR;      09-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Baptists in Texas, national groups vie
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By RICHARD VARA
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Relations between Texas Baptists and the Southern Baptist
Convention reached a crisis stage Wednesday after state leaders
proposed yanking $5 million from the national convention's
seminaries and two of its agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The 220-member executive board of the Baptist General Convention
of Texas is recommending a new budget for 2001 that redirects $4.3
million away from six nationally funded seminaries, including
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth. The
proposed budget also cuts nearly $1 million in Texas funds to the
national group's executive committee and its Ethics and Religious
Liberty Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be reallocated to three seminaries affiliated
with the Texas convention _ Baylor University's Truett Theological
Seminary in Waco, Logsdon School of Theology in Abilene and
Hispanic Baptist Theological Seminary in San Antonio _ and other
Texas ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Board members approved the proposals by an overwhelming vote
Tuesday. The budget will be decided by delegates to the state's
annual convention Oct. 30-31 in Corpus Christi. The budget actions
of the state convention, controlled by Baptist moderates, may be a
step toward disengaging from the 15.7 million-member national
convention, which is controlled by conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptists proposed the cuts in reaction to what they called
a ``doctrinaire fundamentalism'' in the seminaries' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles Wade, executive director of the Texas
convention, said the feeling is that leaders of the denomination's
conservative movement have gone too far with changes in the
seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In seeking to eliminate the perceived problem of liberalism,
they have willingly sacrificed liberty,'' he said, adding that
liberalism ``has never been a problem in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist General Convention of Texas is the largest of the
state conventions affiliated with the Southern Baptists, claiming
about 2.7 million members and 6,000 churches. It contributed $22
million to the Southern Baptist Convention in 1999, more than any
other state convention. The proposed budget leaves intact more than
$17 million in funding for two Southern Baptist missions agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received news of this development with extreme
disappointment and profound regret,'' said the Rev. Morris H.
Chapman, president of the national convention's executive
committee. ``It represents nothing less than a breach of the
historic relationship the Southern Baptist Convention has had with
the BGCT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fractious elements in Texas have driven an extremely poor
decision that is bad for the (state convention), bad for the
Southern Baptist churches in Texas, bad for the (national
convention) and bad for the common mission causes dear to our
hearts,'' Chapman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Campbell, pastor of Houston's Westbury Baptist
Church and chair of the state's seminary study committee, said the
proposed budget would cap contributions to the six seminaries at $1
million. The money would be divided according to the number of
Texan students enrolled at each seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern, which has produced many Texas pastors and
ministers, would receive the bulk of the funds, about $750,000, he
said. It would get $1.5 million under the current state funding
formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seminaries have shifted theologically,'' Campbell said,
adding that the schools are governed by fundamentalist trustees who
interfere with curriculum content and faculties. The national
convention is moving away from Baptist doctrines such as the
individual's freedom to interpret Scriptures, local church autonomy
and basic beliefs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This week's recommendation is part of a 20-year bitter
theological dispute between conservatives and moderates in the
denomination. Texas has irked the national convention leaders by
developing its own educational-materials department and
establishing a missions program, competing with similar national
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paige Patterson, president of Southeastern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C., and past president of
the Southern Baptist Convention, predicted that if the budget were
ratified, the Baptist General Convention of Texas would lose a
number of large and influential churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a revolting development,'' said Patterson, a native
Texan. ``The only thing that surprises me is that they have misread
their own churches. ... They're going to find out these churches
consider themselves Southern Baptists first and Texas Baptists
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle news services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
