<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      09-27 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CHALLENGING BUSH TO BAR SOFT MONEY FOR ADS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore challenged Gov. George
W. Bush Wednesday to agree to ban the use of unregulated party
money on television and radio advertising for the rest of the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his offer Wednesday morning in separate telephone
calls to Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen. Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., the authors of legislation that would ban so-called soft
money contributions altogether. On Tuesday night, Bush told CNN's
Larry King in a nationally televised interview that he was unlikely
to accept such a pact because he did not trust the Democrats to
abide by it.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday night, a Bush spokesman, Ari Fleischer,
said, ``I just doubt that somebody who has recognized no
controlling legal authority over his campaign fund raising is going
to abide by a handshake now.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Democrats have raised far less soft money than the
Republicans and because Bush had all but declined before Gore
announced his acceptance, the vice president's offer would seem to
bear little political cost.
</P>
<P>
   But Feingold, in a telephone interview, said he remained hopeful
that a similar agreement between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep.
Rick Lazio, the candidates for U.S. Senate in New York, would
ultimately help press Bush to accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the momentum on something like this builds, it's hard avoid
it,'' Feingold said. ``We see a real sea change occurring in the
use of soft money. It's finally getting the taint it deserves.''
McCain could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his offer on a campaign day when both he and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, spent considerable effort
rebutting one of the very advertisements that the Democrats would
propose to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Medicare policy at a community center in Altoona,
Iowa, the vice president railed against a Republican National
Committee commercial that he said had mischaracterized his plan for
a prescription drug benefit under Medicare. Lieberman, speaking at
a center for the elderly in Milwaukee, made the same charge.
</P>
<P>
   After a week when some polls have shown Bush gaining ground, it
was the first public indication that the Republican ads had
succeeded in placing the Democrats on the defensive. ``Our message
is getting through on Medicare, particularly in paid media,'' a
Bush aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's soft-money challenge to Bush builds on a similar position
taken by the vice president in March, when he proposed that both
campaigns forgo those contributions and campaign through frequent
debates rather than television advertising. While acknowledging at
the time that he was an imperfect messenger because of his role in
the Clinton administration's fund raising, Gore said he would make
campaign finance reform a priority of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But with no agreement reached at that point, both parties have
raised huge sums this year. The Republican National Committee
collected $153 million through Aug. 31 while the Democratic
National Committee raised an estimated $80 million to $100 million,
party officials said. Much of that money is soft.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket has been on a fund-raising tear for the
last five weeks. Wednesday night, less than eight hours after
issuing his challenge, Gore attended two fund-raisers in Washington
that raised $3.5 million for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidential campaigns have ended their own fund-raising
as a condition for receiving $68 million apiece in public
financing. But the parties can continue to raise unlimited sums,
with few restrictions on the size of individual gifts, and much of
that money can be spent on advertising that directly promotes the
candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McCain and Feingold sent a letter to Gore and Bush
encouraging them to join Clinton and Lazio in swearing off
advertising financed with soft money. After speaking to the two
senators this morning, Gore released a letter to them announcing
his acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Bush-Cheney campaign will take the same action with the
Republican National Committee, I will call upon the Democratic
National Committee to cease all soft-money radio or television
advertising that aims to influence the presidential election,'' he
wrote. ``And I will also call on all independent organizations to
do so as well.''
</P>
<P>
   When King asked Bush whether he would accept such an
arrangement, he responded, ``Probably not, but I'd have to see what
it says.'' He added, ``I don't trust him, to be frank with you.''
In his appearance in Altoona and a subsequent rally in Des Moines
Wednesday, Gore emphasized his prescription drug coverage plan as a
means of setting the policy stage for his first debate with Bush,
next Tuesday in Boston. Beginning Saturday, Gore plans to devote
three days to debate preparation in Sarasota, Fla., where Gore also
practiced for his 1996 vice-presidential debate with Jack F. Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman both raised objections Wednesday to the
Republican Medicare advertisement, which charges that Gore's
prescription drug proposal would require seniors to join ``a
government HMO.'' New Republican mailings to elderly voters in
crucial states make a similar charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what that refers to?'' Gore asked Wednesday. ``That's
the way they describe Medicare. There's no big government HMO.
That's the way they describe Medicare. Medicare's not an HMO. You
get to choose your doctor. You get to choose your pharmacy. You
have the choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
