<SLUG> BC-GORE-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore hammers away on Medicare
 &HT;    VP warns seniors about Bush's plan
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTOONA, Iowa _ Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore hammered
on the Medicare theme for the third day Wednesday, warning Iowa
seniors that George W. Bush's plan would leave out 95 percent of
those who need prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its first phase, our opponent's plan provides no help at
all to any senior who makes more than $14,600 a year,'' Gore told
Iowans at a community center in Altoona and a rally in Des Moines.
``You can see why they want to point fingers in the other direction
when their plan leaves out 95 percent of the people who need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder the group that seems most excited about the other
plan is the pharmaceutical companies,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign also released a letter the vice president sent
to Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russ Feingold, D-Wis., praising
their proposal earlier this week to ban soft money from the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a stance he has taken since March, Gore wrote that if
his Republican opponent, George W. Bush, will agree to the
proposal, ``I will call upon the Democratic National Committee to
cease all soft money radio or television advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said that although Bush has so far
declined to ban soft money, ``maybe he will suddenly have an
epiphany and see the light'' now that McCain, a Republican who has
been pushing for campaign finance reform, is speaking out again on
the issue. A similar deal was sealed last week by New York senate
candidates Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But a deal on the presidential campaign level seemed unlikely.
Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer called Gore's proposal ``nothing
new.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same tactic that Al Gore tried in March when he
said he would forgo soft money while he was raising millions of
dollars in soft money,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   So-called soft money, contributed to parties by individuals,
corporations and special interest groups, is supposed to be used to
push issues rather than individual candidates, with no limit on the
size of donations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, during a town hall meeting on prescription
drug coverage, Gore told about 200 retirees in Altoona that too
many seniors have to choose ``between filling their prescriptions
and filling their shopping carts.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his $253 billion Medicare plan, he said, ``If you decide
to participate, you can go to your own local pharmacy and get all
the medicine your doctor prescribes for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Medicare plan would cover half the cost of prescription
medicine up to $5,000 annually, and would provide catastrophic
coverage so that no Medicare beneficiary would have to pay more
than $4,000 a year for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would offer incentives to private insurance
companies to provide prescription benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' Gore said. ``You get to see your doctor,
and your doctor is the one who decides what medicine is right for
you. No HMO or insurance company can overrule your doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then took questions from the audience and listened to their
frustrations. One retiree, Winifred Skinner, said she is forced to
collect aluminum cans for the 5-cent deposit to supplement her
limited income so that she can pay for medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take welfare. I don't take food stamps,'' she told
Gore. ``I'm a proud person. I want to work and earn what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
