<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAOUL BERGER, 99, CONTROVERSIAL SCHOLAR OF U.S. CONSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass., Ill.)   By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raoul Berger, a widely read and widely debated authority on the
U.S. Constitution, died Sept. 23 at his home in Concord, Mass., his
wife, Patricia, said. He was 99.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's interpretation of the framers' intentions thrilled
liberals when he castigated President Richard M. Nixon's assertions
of executive privilege in an effort to keep information from
Congress in the Watergate case and appalled them when he wrote that
the Supreme Court had overstepped its authority in ordering the
racial desegregation of the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote seven books and more than 100 articles covering such
topics as impeachment, executive privilege, judicial review and the
death penalty, thrusting himself to the center of the incessant and
tortuous national debate on constitutional interpretations. He did
it with a style that inspired the author Garry Wills in 1974 to
speak of his ``exuberance of pugnacious learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Law was Berger's second career. In the 1920s and 1930s he was a
violinist who appeared as a soloist with the Cleveland Symphony,
served as second concertmaster with the Cincinnati Symphony and was
first violinist with the Cincinnati String Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   But making a living in classical music was no easier then than
now, so he went to medical school. When he saw his first cadaver,
he knew his future was in law. He graduated from Northwestern
University's law school at 34, the oldest in his class. His largest
achievement, writing learned and influential books, began in 1969,
when at 68 he published his first book, ``Congress vs. The Supreme
Court.'' At 97, he was still writing articles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Israel Shenker, a reporter for The New York Times,
wrote: ``Raoul Berger thinks of himself as a Dutch housemaid
sweeping the dark corners of the Constitution. Impeachment, for
example, was a dark corner until Mr. Berger wrote the first
comprehensive book about it. Now the dust is flying around
executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every few months he lays his broom aside long enough to
testify before a Congressional committee, transforming himself from
Dutch housemaid into Dutch uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the forward to Berger's 1997 book, ``Government by Judiciary:
The Transformation of the Fourteenth Amendment,'' an expanded
edition of the 1977 version, the historian and legal scholar
Forrest McDonald wrote that Berger presented his recurring thesis:
while it is often necessary to go beyond the text of the
Constitution and its amendments to gauge the authors' intent, it is
wrong to assume ``ideas derived from `natural rights' dogmas or
other external values.''
</P>
<P>
   This strict constructionist view led Berger to a conservative
position on the scope of the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th
Amendment. He said his research showed that the sole purpose of the
amendment was to prevent freed slaves from being shackled again
after the Civil War. Therefore, he criticized basing such
wide-ranging decisions on the amendment as those involving school
desegregation, abortion rights and the principle of one man, one
vote.
</P>
<P>
   These strongly expressed views have drawn the wrath of those who
believe the Constitution grows and changes organically, including
Justice Thurgood Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Kunstler, a civil rights and liberties lawyer,
accused Berger of ``a coldly sophisticated attempt to roll back the
clock to the America of 1787 insofar as constitutional law is
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Berger won liberal accolades for his attack on
Nixon for invoking ``executive privilege'' in the Watergate case.
Berger told a Senate committee in 1973: ``You don't need more
hearings, you need gumption. You'll be treated like office boys
until you stand up and kick them in the slats.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he wrote in The Yale Law Journal that Nixon's
impeachment defense was based on ``instant history'' and ``sheer
effrontery.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger called himself a moderate Democrat, and it sometimes
pained him that ``my conclusions are not infrequently at war with
my predilections.'' But it did not stop him. His advice was that
the people should change the Constitution rather than stretch its
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, he said that the constitutional sleuth is much
like the classical musician who strives to ``search for and lay
bare the meaning that is imprisoned in the little black dots which
weave their way across the music staves.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger was born in Russia on Jan. 4, 1901, and brought to the
United States at the age of 4. He had been named Raoul after a
character in Meyerbeer's opera, ``The Huguenots.'' As a youth, he
studied music in New York and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   After abandoning his musical career for law school, he practiced
in Chicago for two years. In 1938, he joined President Franklin D.
Roosevelt's New Deal as special assistant to the attorney general,
and held other posts. In 1946 he retired from government and for
the next 16 years practiced law in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, at 61, be began his teaching career as a law professor
at the University of California at Berkeley. Several years later,
he moved to Harvard, where he became the Charles Warren Senior
Fellow in American Legal History.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was not until he embarked on his journey as a
constitutional scholar that he began rising to greatness,''
McDonald wrote.
</P>
<P>
   His other books were ``Impeachment: The Constitutional
Problems'' (1973), ``Executive Privilege: A Constitutional Myth''
(1974), ``Death Penalties: The Supreme Court's Obstacle Course''
(1982), ``Federalism: The Founders' Design'' (1987) and ``The
Fourteenth Amendment and the Bill of Rights'' (1989).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Berger is survived by his son, Carl,
and two granddaughters. A daughter, Andrea Kalodner, died several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Berger never ducked an intellectual battle. When law reviews
bristled with critical reviews of his ``Government by Judiciary,''
he wrote 40 articles and one book-length rebuttal in response.
Quoting the philosopher John Locke, he said no response meant
victory was ``adjudged not to him who had the truth on his side,
but by the last word in the dispute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
