<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS &LR;      09-27 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Inner-city school a `beacon' for Bush
 &HT;    Candidate credits community effort for safer classrooms
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ George W. Bush on Wednesday found what he called a
``beacon of hope'' in a violence-prone section of this city from
which to promote the role of faith-based groups in teaching
children how to behave.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Roman Catholic Archbishop Roger Mahoney, the
Republican presidential nominee and Texas governor held a rally on
the parking lot of Ascension Catholic School, located across the
street from a public elementary school where a fifth-grade teacher
was shot five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Alfredo Perez, survived. The incident helped spark
a community-renewal effort that organizers say is a showcase for
the cooperative efforts of public, charitable and faith-based
partnerships in developing safe classroom environments in the inner
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I came to this school is because I love to
highlight beacons of hope, centers of excellence that challenge the
odds,'' Bush said, against a backdrop of Hispanic and
African-American schoolchildren who welcomed him to South Central
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said that the neighborhood around Ascension Catholic
School and the Figueroa Street School, where Perez taught,
experienced more than 20 drive-by shootings over the past three
months. But he said the two schools themselves are now safe places
for children to learn.
</P>
<P>
   He said students at both schools ``now enjoy and benefit from a
safe school environment, counseling services, health screening,
after-school care, extended-learning opportunities and the security
of a supportive community.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, who delivered the invocation at the beginning of the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles last month, also has
invited Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee, to visit
the two schools. But Gore hasn't responded.
</P>
<P>
   Perez attended Wednesday's rally but didn't speak.
</P>
<P>
   Bush used the occasion to promote his educational priorities,
including ``zero tolerance'' for disruptive behavior in the
classroom and a greater role for church-based groups in
after-school care and mentoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Perez was struck by a shot fired from outside his
school, Bush said that classrooms need to be ``safe havens''
offering all children an opportunity to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he appreciated the discipline and behavior standards
imposed by Catholic schools and wanted similar standards to be
adopted in all public schools. He cited Texas' system of
alternative schools to which disruptive students can be
transferred.
</P>
<P>
   While in Los Angeles, Bush was greeted by the latest Los Angeles
Times Poll, which showed him with a national lead of 6 percentage
points over Gore, mainly because of a gender gap.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted Saturday through Monday, indicated Bush was
favored by 48 percent of likely American voters, compared with 42
percent for Gore. Although Gore had a 7-point lead among women, the
Texas governor had a 22-point lead among men.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times Poll, which had a margin of error of plus
or minus 4 percentage points, gave Bush a wider lead than other
surveys released this week. But other polls either show Bush with a
slight edge or indicate the race is even after Bush had trailed
Gore during most of the period since the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
