u p BC-UTAH-DEMS-NYT &LR;      09-27 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEMOCRAT WHO DOESN'T ADVERTISE IT LEADS IN HOSTILE TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In this overwhelmingly Republican state,
Democrats have to tread carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the 1st Congressional District, Kathleen
McConkie-Collinwood is bringing in the president on Saturday to
help her sagging efforts against the Republican incumbent, James V.
Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, not the real president. Utah residents do not especially
like President Clinton. Her guest is Martin Sheen, the actor who
plays a president on ``The West Wing'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheen's appearance is worth noting. As a cautionary tale
about what it means to be a Democrat in Utah, it illustrates how
carefully many Democrats package themselves to achieve any measure
of elective success.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the 2nd District, which includes part of Salt Lake City
and adjoining suburbs, Jim Matheson, the Democrat running for
Congress, has made no such overture to presidents of any kind. He
has one advantage that McConkie-Collinwood lacks: widespread name
recognition as the son of a former _ and immensely popular _
two-term Democratic governor, Scott M. Matheson.
</P>
<P>
   It is a major reason that polls show Matheson far ahead of the
Republican candidate, Derek Smith, in a race to fill an open seat.
Smith defeated the two-term incumbent, Merrill Cook, in a rowdy
Republican primary this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But even here in the one region of Utah where Democrats can be
found in significant numbers, Matheson has tailored his campaign to
play down his party affiliation and loyalties to suit a district
that has swung back and forth over the last two decades but never
far from core centrist values that Utahans hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy appears to be working. The latest poll, conducted
for Salt Lake's Deseret News and KSL-TV, the NBC affiliate, and
released last Sunday showed Matheson leading Smith, a
self-described conservative, by 46 percent to 32 percent, well
outside the margin of sampling error of 7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   That was encouraging news for the Democratic Party, which is
counting on a Matheson victory as one of several turnovers that
Democrats need to regain control of the House. The current
breakdown is 222 Republicans, 210 Democrats, 2 independents and 1
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   But if Matheson is elected and follows through on his campaign
promises, House Democrats should not necessarily count on blind
loyalty from him. For example, he says he does not support the
registration and licensing of guns, a proposal Vice President Al
Gore favors and most Republicans oppose, and he contends that
Gore's plan to include prescription medicine as a Medicare benefit
may be too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Matheson said he disagreed with the way the Clinton
administration had used the Antiquities Act to create national
monuments, a position held by legions of Republicans throughout the
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Democrat; I don't deny that,'' he said in an interview
here this week. ``At the end of the day, everybody knows your party
affiliation, and that's fine. But I would like to emphasize an
approach that goes beyond singular partisan politics for how to
address public policy. I would like to get away from the partisan
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Matheson's campaign literature underscores what he calls a
``common-sense approach'' to solving problems. One brochure says,
``I'll reach across party lines, work with everyone and do what is
right.'' Nowhere does it identify him as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Matheson, 40, a former energy company consultant, sought
out high-profile Democrats to visit the district on his behalf.
Only one of national stature has, Sen. Russell D. Feingold of
Wisconsin, a friend since their days at Harvard, and no one else is
expected. At one campaign event this week, Matheson greeted voters
at the home of his close friend Eric Leavitt, a Republican and the
younger brother of Utah's Republican governor, Michael O. Leavitt,
who is supporting Smith.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Smith, 35, who built a successful high-tech
company, has shared a stage only with members of his own party, a
steady stream of stalwarts that includes Speaker J. Dennis Hastert,
Rep. Dick Armey, the majority leader, and Rep. Tom Delay, the
majority whip. More are coming, Smith said, including Sen. John
McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   For Matheson, the accent on policy, not politics, is vital to
win support from the fast-growing number of suburban voters in a
district that President George Bush and Bob Dole carried in the
last two presidential elections and that Gov. George. W. Bush of
Texas is expected to win this year.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, it has given Smith a convenient way to
argue, in effect, that if voters support moderate or even
Republican positions they should vote for a Republican, not a
Democrat reaching for the political center. And besides, he
emphasized, even Utah Democrats act like Washington Democrats after
they win election.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, even though he supports traditional
Republican issues in his fight for the middle, it won't matter much
what he feels about them,'' Smith said of his opponent. ``The
Democratic leadership is going to determine the issues that see the
light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he expected to overtake Matheson in the closing weeks
of the campaign as voters became more familiar with him and his
policy positions, like supporting tax cuts and education reform
that provides more local control over spending federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee is helping with
nearly $1 million for television advertisements, about four times
what the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee is spending
for Matheson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closing,'' Smith said, mindful of a Salt Lake Tribune
poll three weeks ago that failed to mention party affiliation and
showed Matheson leading by 27 points. ``He has a famous last name,
but when Republican and independent voters become more familiar
with me, I think they'll come over to my camp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
