<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MOVIEVIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      09-27 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 VIOLENCE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Tinseltown talk draws no applause
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hollywood executives pledged Wednesday to reduce
their marketing of violent movies to children, but their proposals
drew skepticism from senators concerned that profits drive the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Amid bitter criticism of their advertising practices, eight
movie moguls said they will take steps to ensure their efforts to
entice adults to the theater are not misdirected at children. But
they stopped short of promising an absolute end to the
controversial advertising, saying that some violent movies carry
inspirational messages that should be marketed to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., assailed what he called the
industry's half-hearted attempts. Pressing the executives to ``work
a little more assiduously'' to monitor their advertising, McCain
said Congress will be keeping a close watch on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of your business lies in your hands,'' said McCain,
who invited the executives to appear before the Senate Commerce
Committee, which he chairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the executives said they will end the test
marketing of violent R-rated films to children under age 17, unless
the child's parent is at the movie screening. They also said they
will not show coming attractions of violent, R-rated films before
audiences awaiting the start of a G-rated movie, which is aimed at
all ages.
</P>
<P>
   The executives' appearance before the Commerce Committee
followed the release of a Federal Trade Commission report Sept. 11
that found widespread and aggressive marketing of violent movies to
children. For example, the FTC found advertising of the films
during television shows popular with children, including ``Xena:
Warrior Princess'' and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pervasive advertising to youngsters belies the industry's
efforts to help parents monitor what children see and hear by
rating the age-appropriateness of its products, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the FTC's findings, the executives stressed their
concern about exposing underage viewers to violent movies. Five of
the company officials noted that they themselves are parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all appreciate the challenges of raising children today,''
said Paramount Pictures' Motion Picture Group Vice Chairman Rob
Friedman. ``I work hard to meet these challenges, at least in part
by helping (my) children make decisions regarding what movies and
television programs they watch, what music they hear and what games
they play. That's our job as parents, and we take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The others making note of their children were Fox Filmed (CQ)
Entertainment Chairman Jim Gianopulos, Warner Bros. President Alan
Horn, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Vice Chairman Chris McGurk and Universal
Pictures Chairman Stacey Snider.
</P>
<P>
   In their joint pledge, the executives said they will each
appoint a corporate officer to regularly review their companies'
marketing efforts for violent films to ensure they are not
``inappropriately specifically targeting children.''
</P>
<P>
   They also said they will do more to encourage theater owners to
comply with industry guidelines barring the admittance of children
under age 17 to R-rated movies without a parent. But the executives
declined to say what specific action they would take.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptical Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, tried to prod
the executives into beefing up their efforts. She suggested that
Congress might pass a law to prohibit them from allowing children
under age 17 from attending R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   Although such a law might violate constitutional free-speech
rights, Hutchison told the executives they should regard her
comments as ``a signal across the bow'' that Congress is seriously
considering what it can do to help parents protect children from
the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are throwing up their arms in frustration,'' Hutchison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney President Robert Iger, however, cautioned the
senators against regulating advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would object vehemently if the government steps in'' and
tells the industry what it can and cannot distribute to viewers, he
said. ``It is not appropriate for the government to make
programming decisions for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In defense of advertising, Sony Pictures Entertainment President
Mel Harris said marketing violent films to youngsters is valid when
the movies' message is uplifting. Parents, not government
officials, should be the arbiters of what is appropriate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Harris said his company's recent R-rated release
``The Patriot,'' contained graphic depictions of war but also an
inspiring message about the American Revolution that many parents
would welcome their children experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Harris, DreamWorks SKG executive Walter Parkes said his
company's R-rated drama ``Saving Private Ryan'' won praise from
parents and educators for its depiction of the violent heroism of
the Normandy invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Committee members agreed that much of what the movie
industry produces has merit but said company leaders must do more
to ensure that their advertising is directed at parents and not
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're part of the solution,'' Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan.,
told the executives, ``and part of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., said ``violence pays.'' However,
he added that perhaps federal regulators can stifle advertising of
violent films to children the same way they legally block obscene
material from being shown on television.
</P>
<P>
   The movie executives had spurned Commerce Committee Chairman
McCain's invitation to attend an earlier hearing on the advertising
issue, prompting the Arizona Republican to fire off a second round
of appearance requests, which they accepted.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
