<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILITARY-HNS &LR;      09-27 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Military units ready to fight, but at `high risk,' officers say
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MICHAEL HEDGES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tip of America's war spear remains sharp, but
the supporting shaft has been greatly weakened by budget cuts and
the demands of numerous overseas deployments, top officers told
Congress Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If forced to fight two major wars at the same time, the U.S.
military would be at a ``high risk,'' Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Combat units forming the military's spearpoint have been kept
ready to fight by sacrificing what Shelton described as the shaft
of the spear: support unit readiness, new equipment and upgraded
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk associated with the most demanding scenario (of wars
in two places, like Korea and Iraq) has increased over the past
several years,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take us longer to respond to hostilities. In turn,
this can mean territory lost and more potential for a longer fight
and increased casualties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has been particularly hard hit by shrinking
budgets during the time when they were mounting bombing campaigns
in Kosovo and Iraq, said Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall combat readiness of our combat units is down 23
percent since 1996,'' he said. The average aircraft in the Air
Force is now 22 years old, and aircraft will average 30 years old
by 2015, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate hearings came in a politically charged
atmosphere, as presidential candidates George W. Bush and Al Gore
have continued to spar over the issue of the military's readiness
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has criticized the Clinton-Gore administration, claiming it
has eroded the effectiveness of the military with budget cuts while
increasing far flung peace-keeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has responded by saying the military reductions started
under Bush's father, former President George Bush, but noted that
the U.S. military remained by far the strongest on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearings Wednesday, both candidates said their
positions were supported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's testimony supported Governor Bush and Secretary
Cheney's assessment of our military forces today, and the need for
new leadership to prepare and transform our military for future
generations,'' said Dan Bartlett, a Bush spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our troops are overdeployed, morale is low, and Governor Bush
has a plan to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore team saw it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony of the joint chiefs confirmed that what Al Gore
and Joe Lieberman have been saying about military readiness is
right, that America does have the greatest military in the world,''
said Jano Cabrera, a Gore spokesman. ``George Bush's claims of a
military in decline were not supported by the joint chiefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Charts used by the joint chiefs at Wednesday's hearings showed a
sharp decline in military spending which began after the collapse
of communism and continued after the Persian Gulf War, which were
the final years of the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Spending has remained at roughly 1993 levels throughout the
Clinton-Gore years, while military deployments in places such as
Somalia, Bosnia and Kosovo have put added strain on the military,
the generals testified.
</P>
<P>
   The military had a budget for $295 billion for this year. Of
that, $60 billion was for procurement _ buying and maintaining
weaponry, from ships and planes to artillery and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Military budgets began falling from Reagan-era peaks of roughly
$325 billion a year, when the Cold War ended and politicians in
both parties began talking about a ``peace dividend.''
</P>
<P>
   The size of the military has been reduced from 1,913,750 people
on active duty to 1,371,500.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said the military supported Congressional Budget Office
estimates that an increase of $30 billion a year in procurement,
and about another $30 billion in general annual budget increases,
would be necessary to return the military to a strength needed to
assure ``overwhelming superiority'' in possible combat scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The top leaders of the Army, Navy, Marines and Air Force assured
Congress that combat units such as Army and Marine divisions, Navy
carrier battle groups and fighter and bomber squadrons are ready to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the much more numerous parts of the military that
supply, support and reinforce the first-strike units are in worse
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we reduce our discussions to sound bites we talk only
about the first to go forward, the first to fight, and as I say
they are ready,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you look below these depths you find there are many
other units that are vitally important to war fighting,'' Shelton
said. ``They are not as ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The heads of the four branches of the armed services described
what one called a ``death spiral.'' They said money was being taken
out of weapons procurement and infrastructure maintenance to assure
units deployed to places such as Kosovo, Bosnia and the Persian
Gulf are at peak fighting condition.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, planes, ships and helicopters got older, support
units were thinned and bases became worse places to live and work,
they said. Shelton said such ``robbing of Peter to pay Paul'' is
``mortgaging our future readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
