<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DESPITE UPS AND DOWNS, SURVEYS SHOW RACE IS TIED 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANET ELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After watching his opponent's popularity rise in the polls over
the last month, Gov. George W. Bush got a dose of good news over
the last few days. The momentum is now his, with three new
nationwide polls showing that he has regained some of the ground he
lost to Vice President Al Gore. Bush seems to have the edge in at
least two of the polls. But is it real?
</P>
<P>
   The basic fact is, no one is ahead. When the polls are looked at
together, the presidential race is so close that it is impossible
to give either candidate an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got his most encouraging news from The Los Angeles Times,
which reported Wednesday that thanks to a 22-point advantage among
men, Bush was now leading Gore, 48 percent to 42 percent. But since
the margin of sampling error is plus or minus 4 percentage points,
the findings have to be considered a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three out of four people interviewed said the
coming debates would affect their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Polls differ in the samples they use, the questions they ask,
the ways they interpret the numbers and the ways they report the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some polls report the preferences for all registered voters,
which represents the views of about 80 percent of all American
adults. But based on voter turnout in years past, not all 80
percent are going to vote in November, so some polls use a series
of questions to determine who is most likely to vote. This group
accounts for about 50 percent of all adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup/CNN/USA Today poll is reporting the results of a
daily tracking poll, which involves taking separate national
samples for each of three days and averaging them. Each day, they
add a new sample and drop the oldest one. Tracking polls usually
are very short, often with as few as 10 questions. Other recent
polls, like those of Newsweek and The Los Angeles Times, use one
sample over several days and have much longer questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   Not all polls word their questions the same way _ even on the
most basic question. When asking voters whom they now support, some
polls use only the names of the presidential candidates while
others include the names of the vice-presidential candidates as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the margin of sampling error, which unavoidably
occurs from randomly sampling the active residential telephone
exchanges across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points,
for example, refers to 3 percentage points on each candidate's
number. So in a hypothetical race where there is a two-point gap,
say of 44 percent for John Smith and 46 percent for Bill Jones, the
race could be as far apart as 41 percent for Smith and 49 percent
for Jones, or the advantage could fall to Smith, 47 percent to 43
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Gallup/CNN/USA Today poll reported a nationwide
telephone tracking poll taken Sept. 24-26, with 696 likely voters.
Gore was the choice of 44 percent of the respondents, while Bush
was the choice of 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton Survey Research Associates took a nationwide telephone
poll for Newsweek from Sept. 20 to Sept. 22 with 766 likely voters.
In that poll Gore was the choice of 47 percent and Bush was the
choice of 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Los Angeles Times poll, the two have a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. When the polls
are averaged, Gore has 44 percent and Bush has 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing to keep in mind is that when pollsters ask
people about their votes, they usually ask whom they would vote for
``if the election were being held today.'' But nearly six weeks
will pass, and many polls will be taken before anyone votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
