<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW-TEACHER-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOVICE'S HARD LESSON: BRINGING ORDER TO A CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On her fourth day as a teacher, Donna Moffett would
not _ could not _ stop smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that only eight of her 21 first-graders had shown up
on time to follow her, ducklinglike, from the schoolyard to her
muggy second-floor classroom at Public School 92 in Brooklyn. Or
that one little boy, with rumpled curls and a sullen gaze, rolled
his eyes and disparaged her every move.
</P>
<P>
   Moffett, 45, peppy and crisp in a navy dress, forced herself to
keep smiling, even when the 6-year-olds booed her choice of a
second story to read out loud. Even when, as the children lined up
for lunch, one of the more impulsive students dropped to the
ground, attached herself to Moffett's ankles and shrieked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be polite, show respect and use our inside voices,''
she said, reciting her newly minted class rules. ``We will work
hard and come to class prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffett, who entered teaching on Sept. 7 with hardly any
preparation at all, has a bumpy ride ahead. In July, she abandoned
her comfortable longtime job as a legal secretary near Wall Street
to be one of 320 ``teaching fellows'' _ people with little or no
teaching experience, hired by Schools Chancellor Harold Levy to
fill chronic vacancies in New York City's most troubled public
schools. In August, the fellows took a crash course in teaching and
eight hours of certification exams.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to teaching was a bold move for Moffett, a sensitive and
meticulous woman who has spent most of her adult life performing
administrative tasks in orderly offices. She is used to a 9-to-5
schedule, a comfortable salary and a quiet, childless existence. So
why take this frightening leap?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leading a pleasant life with very little risk,''
Moffett, a petite woman with curly brown hair, said last week.
``This school and these children, they may take everything I have.
But there's a really deep well in me, and it's time to draw on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she agreed to let a reporter observe her during this
uncomfortable first year because she believes so strongly in the
importance of teaching, and in the potential of the teaching
fellows program.
</P>
<P>
   Moffett was assigned to P.S. 92, a hulking brick building that
takes up almost a block in the Flatbush section, a working-class
neighborhood increasingly populated by Caribbean immigrants. The
state has been monitoring the school since 1989, long before
Moffett's pupils were born, and has repeatedly threatened to close
it. The school has been through five principals in five years.
Although scores on city and state standardized reading tests rose
sharply last year, nearly three-quarters of the students still read
below grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Moffett used to read these statistics in newspapers and discuss
them with civic-minded friends. Now she is discovering what the
numbers mean, up close and in painful detail.
</P>
<P>
   She is under tremendous pressure not only to start her young
charges reading and writing, but also to prepare them for the tests
that they will face in later grades _ tests that make or break
schools like P.S. 92. Yet Moffett has barely begun learning how to
teach. The teaching fellows program is paying her tuition for
weekly graduate classes at the City University of New York, which
will eventually lead to a master's degree in education. But most of
her lessons will come on the job, at a school that cannot afford to
allow many more mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope that all my students will be reading by the
end of first grade,'' she said two days before school started.
</P>
<P>
   But first, as experienced teachers warn repeatedly, Moffett's
students need to learn the classroom rules. She recited them
constantly during the first week of school, asking the children to
chime in. In addition to working hard and being polite, they are
expected to come to school by 8, to enter and leave the room
quietly, to sit in their seats and listen carefully, and to raise
their hands when they want to speak.
</P>
<P>
   But on Day 4, plenty of rules were still being broken. Students
lingered at the pencil sharpener and fooled around as Moffett took
attendance. Some straggled in as late as 8:40. As Moffett, still
smiling, went over the months of the year, Daysha, a restless,
bright-eyed girl, raced to the front of the room and grabbed the
chalk, ignoring Moffett's command to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   As the teacher dealt with the disruption, her aide, Ruth
Baptiste, asked Larry, the sullen boy, what month came after May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to guess?'' Baptiste asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' Larry replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' the aide persisted as horns honked incessantly outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's stupid,'' the boy grumbled, pounding his fist on
his desk.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid overcrowding in the cafeteria, first-graders at P.S. 92
go to lunch at 10:15. But on Day 4, Moffett held the girls back
because they would not line up quietly. After three attempts, they
still did not have it right.
</P>
<P>
   Her smile was growing tight.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When Donna Moffett graduated from Christopher Columbus High
School in the Bronx in 1972, her yearbook predicted she would
become a teacher. But family turmoil prompted her to drop out of
Lehman College during her sophomore year and leave home. She moved
to Boston, working as a secretary at Harvard, and then to Chicago,
where she helped run a feminist bookstore and worked for a lawyer
who had written domestic violence legislation for Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Moffett did not return to New York until 1989. Still lacking a
college degree, she joined Flemming, Zulack &AMP; Williamson, a
corporate law firm near Wall Street, where she was a legal
secretary for a senior partner. She attended night classes at
Baruch College, and in 1998 she received a bachelor's degree in
literature.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although she liked her job, Moffett said, she increasingly felt
as if she was not ``the kind of person I wanted to be,
character-wise.'' Her literature classes made her think a lot about
teaching, and last fall she took a graduate education course at
Hunter College. When a friend told her about the teaching fellows
program in July, she immediately sent for an application.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just seemed so much about it that seemed custom-tailored
for me and my circumstances,'' she said. ``I basically thought if I
didn't make a move and make a sacrifice, then I would have to
question my own authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffet will earn just under $37,000 this year, compared with her
previous salary of $60,000. That not only means fewer dinners out,
shopping trips and Broadway plays, but in all likelihood exchanging
her apartment in Chelsea for more modest quarters in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking to my students about rewards and
consequences, and the same is true for me,'' Moffett said after
receiving her first paycheck last week: $686 after taxes for two
weeks of work. ``One consequence for me is living with a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many first-year teachers in New York City, Moffett and
the other teaching fellows are not going it alone. She cannot stop
praising the support she is receiving from colleagues, including a
teacher with 15 years of experience who is Moffett's official
mentor. Some co-workers invite her to observe their classes, while
others share lesson plans and tips on discipline.
</P>
<P>
   By the second week of school, Moffett's techniques had evolved.
She spoke more loudly and succinctly. When necessary she scowled.
At lunch time, she did not insist on complete silence as the
students lined up. Her strategy the previous week _ holding the
students back when just one misbehaved _ was ``a big mistake,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to establish routines and reward good
behavior,'' she said. ``But I'm not allowed to keep these children
from their lunch. Everything here is on a schedule, and you have to
abide by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffett rises by 5 a.m. these days and often works on lesson
plans past midnight. Instead of staying at work as late as she
wants, she is kicked out of P.S. 92 by 5 p.m. for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Her students especially love the ``library,'' a corner of the
room where they sit on rubber place mats that Moffett brought in
and listen to a story before lunch. On Day 4, it was ``Jamberry''
by Bruce Degen, about a bear in search of berries.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a quiet girl named Paula read the book to herself,
pronouncing each word perfectly. Moffett has not yet determined how
many others can read, but she clearly has a long way to go toward
her goal of every student reading by June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how a teacher, no matter how committed, strong,
bright, creative, can do this alone,'' she said in a late-night
phone conversation. ``I feel as though I should not sleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
