<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELANGER'S STATUS UP IN THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Eric Belanger could be the Los Angeles
Kings' No. 1 center opening night in Washington D.C. or he could be
playing for the Minnesota Wild.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of holdout Jozef Stumpel continues to plague the
club's ability to plan for the regular season. Belanger, who scored
15 goals and 40 points last season for minor-league Lowell, Mass.,
is listed with Brad Chartrand on the Kings depth chart as the
first-line center.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger also is on a list of 10 players the Kings have made
eligible for Friday's waiver draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a calculated risk leaving Eric off the protected
list,'' said Kings GM Dave Taylor. ``We can lose only one player
and we don't think he will be the one.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger and Chartrand are not familiar names, but the club said
it is not ready to trade for a front-line center. Stumpel is
seeking a three-year, $9 million contract. The Kings are offering
$1.8 million less. He is playing in his native Slovakia, but if an
agreement is not reached by Oct. 5, Stumpel will be lost for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were able to protect 18 skaters and two goaltenders
for Friday's waiver draft, which also adds to confusion in goal.
</P>
<P>
   With injured Stephane Fiset (sprained left knee) not expected to
be ready for the Oct. 6 season opener, offseason acquisition Steve
Passmore will back up Jamie Storr. But Passmore, who played for
Chicago last season, also is on the waiver list and there is a good
chance he could be claimed.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Marcel Cousineau, who appeared in five games for
the Kings last season, would back up Storr until Fiset returns.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray is set on the second line of Bryan
Smolinski at center, Glen Murray at right wing and Luc Robitaille
at left wing. Although he wasn't pleased with the effort of the
second unit during exhibition games against San Jose and Phoenix,
Murray wants to keep them together.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he did the same, leaving Smolinski on the second
unit when Stumpel was injured and using journeyman Len Barrie
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when our first line went down, they really carried
the offense for us,'' Murray said. ``But I've told them they just
can't turn it on and off and expect to be there. I think it's best
to juggle the lines as little as possible. There is a need to
maintain some continuity, but they need to pick it up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, however, concedes that Robitaille, who led the team last
year with 36 goals and 74 points, could be moved back to the first
line if newcomer Tomas Vlasak falters.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: An MRI on the right index finger of Ziggy
Palffy revealed a small fracture at the tip. Palffy, who was struck
by a stick Saturday in Bakersfield, will not play Friday in San
Jose or Saturday in Las Vegas but is expected to be ready by the
start of the regular season. Fiset reported improvement in his left
knee, which he sprained Friday. Fiset is riding an exercise bike
and said he can walk without pain but has trouble climbing stairs
and could be a week from on-ice workouts.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles: The Kings are not expected to claim anyone
off the unprotected list. But just in case, they must be prepared
to drop a player from their protected list. Defenseman Peter Hogan,
who played 23 games for Lowell last season, would be that player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAIVERING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kings players eligible for Friday's NHL waiver draft. Teams can
protect 18 skaters and two goaltenders from a list of players with
more than 160 games of NHL experience. Players with less than three
years professional experience are exempt from the draft.
</P>
<P>
   C _ Eric Belanger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   D _ Philippe Boucher &QL;
</P>
<P>
   D _ Rich Brennan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LW _ David Hymovitz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RW _ Peter Lebetoullier &QL;
