<HEADER>
A4444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOCOMO-AOL PARTNERSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Japan's leading cellular phone company, NTT DoCoMo, and America
Online announced a widely expected strategic partnership Wednesday
that they said would propel the two companies into the forefront of
global wireless Internet services. DoCoMo will take a 42.3 percent
stake in AOL Japan and will feature AOL mail and Instant Messenger
on DoCoMo's i-mode service, the largest wireless Internet service
in the world, with more than 12 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will catapult AOL Japan, a laggard among
Japanese fixed-line Internet access providers, into a leading
position in the Japanese market and give AOL's content to wireless
users with a DoCoMo phone. Kiyoyuki Tsujimura, managing director of
global business development at DoCoMo, said the partners would
collaborate on new ways to integrate wireless and fixed-line
Internet services, so that, for example, a bidder in an online
auction could participate via mobile phone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS FINANCIAL SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Extending its Internet information service to wireless
distribution in Japan and Europe, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said
Wednesday that it planned to give its institutional customers
access to research, stock recommendations and financial news over
mobile telephones. Called Radar, the service is expected to become
more sophisticated and widereaching over time, so that a customer
might, for instance, be able to order a phone that would be able
communicate sudden movements in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL GAS INFLATION COULD HURT MEXICO
</P>
<P>
   A leading Mexican industrial group warned Wednesday that at
least 500 Mexican glass, steel and ceramic plants might be forced
to lay off 250,000 workers this winter because of rising natural
gas prices. The trade group, known as Canacintra, blamed the
state-run oil monopoly, Pemex, for raising natural gas prices in
the absence of competition. Pemex, which is expected to earn a
windfall from Mexican oil and gas production this year, said
increased demand had forced it to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL AIRLINE GOES FOR CARGO
</P>
<P>
   Varig, Brazil's leading airline, said Wednesday that it would
spend $100 million to spin off and expand its cargo unit into a
logistics company that will include distribution, delivery,
packaging and storage services. The new company, to be called Varig
Logistica, or Varilog for short, is expected to account for 30
percent of Varig's revenue, or about $500 million this year. The
company is expected to compete with FedEx and DHL, which have
stepped up investments in Latin America in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   RANK GROUP SELLING UNIT
</P>
<P>
   The British conglomerate the Rank Group said Wednesday that it
would sell its holidays division, which includes hotels and camping
parks, to the Bourne Leisure Group for as much as 700 million
pounds, or about $980 million. Privately held Bourne Leisure, which
runs parks throughout Britain, said it would pay 650 million pounds
upfront and an additional 50 million pounds in two years if Rank's
Butlin's resorts unit meets profit targets. Rank's shares rose 5.9
percent, to 161 pence, or about $2.24. Rank has been divesting
businesses, like Odeon cinema and a stake in Universal Studios
Escape, to pay down debt.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SPANISH UTILITY MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Endesa, the leading Spanish power company is in talks about a
possible merger with the country's second-largest electricity
producer, Iberdrola, which would create one of the biggest
utilities in Europe and be among the top 10 in the world. Spanish
government regulators are expected to examine the details closely
to ensure it does not violate competition rules. Earlier this year,
the government blocked a merger of the power companies Unin Fenosa
and Hidroelectrica del Cantabrico over antitrust concerns. Endesa
and Iberdrola control more than 80 percent of the electrical power
market and have a combined value of more than $31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEANS DELIBERATE ON DEALS
</P>
<P>
   European antitrust regulators met in Brussels Wednesday to
decide whether concessions submitted by Time Warner and its
proposed partners, America Online and the EMI Music Group, were
sufficient to allay European concerns that the planned deals would
choke competition in the Internet distribution of music. The
regulators, from the national antitrust agencies of the 15 European
Union members states, were expected to issue a recommendation
whether to accept or reject the concessions, or possibly to seek
further clarification from the companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEAK RESULTS AT BANK OF SCOTLAND
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring costs and provisions for bad debt contributed to
weaker-than-expected first-half earnings at the Bank of Scotland,
which recently lost to the Royal Bank of Scotland in a bidding war
for National Westminster Bank. Bank of Scotland shares fell 4.9
percent Wednesday, to 580 pence, or about $8.12, after the bank
said it had earned 469 million pounds, or about $657 million, in
the first half of the year, compared with 471 million pounds a year
earlier. The bank is facing pressure on its profit margins as
competition grows, and it has been the rumored target of takeover
speculation recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
