<HEADER>
A4446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INFLATION-ERROR-NYT     09-27 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFLATION-ERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ADJUSTS INFLATION RATE UPWARD FOR A SMALL ERROR
</HEADLINE>
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government said Wednesday that inflation rose a bit faster
in the first eight months of this year than it had previously
reported, a mistake whose correction means slightly higher payments
for recipients of Social Security and other federal benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And while economists said that the error, one-tenth of a
percentage point, was not large enough to significantly alter their
view of the nation's economic performance, it was nonetheless in
the direction of faster inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's acknowledgment by the Bureau of Labor Statistics
said that the Consumer Price Index rose 2.7 percent through August
of this year instead of the 2.6 percent it initially reported.
</P>
<P>
   It attributed the understatement to a recently discovered error
in software used to calculate the index's residential rent
component and a gauge for home ownership. Because these items
account for just over one-quarter of the index, this implies they
were understated by about four-tenths of a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the corrections were large enough to require
re-publication, the general pattern of consumer price behavior this
year was little affected,'' the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   But the bond market stumbled on the news, and economists did not
completely dismiss the error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dramatic, but this is an important component of the
CPI,'' a trend-setting one that fluctuates little from month to
month, said Jan Hatzius, an economist at Goldman, Sachs. ``It
reinforces the pattern of gradually accelerating core inflation
that we've seen and makes it even less likely the Federal Reserve
will be cutting rates anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Steinberg, a senior economist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
called the mistake too tiny to affect perceptions of inflation or
economic growth but said it was ``sort of amazing they could make a
mistake like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The errors were understood to involve double counting of
improvements in the quality of shelter, a process commonly used to
adjust the figures so that, say, a new generation of more costly
but better standard furnaces does not necessarily raise the
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics, which declined to elaborate on
its statement Wednesday, is expected to conduct a briefing on the
revision at 9:30 Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Social Security Administration said that a
rise of one-tenth point in the CPI for a full year would raise its
outlays by about $400 million, or an average payment increase of 74
cents a month for each of its 45.2 million elderly and disabled
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Many private contracts are also linked to the CPI as is the type
of government bond intended to be inflation-proof. The Treasury did
not respond to an inquiry about how inflation-indexed bonds would
be handled but the guess on Wall Street was that their value at
maturity would simply be increased accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Swonk, immediate past president of the National
Association for Business Economics, seized on the mistake to
complain of what she called chronic, severe underfinancing of
federal statistical agencies. ``Data appears to be the least
interesting and least provocative four-letter word in the English
language,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
