<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Correction of Data Shows Slightly Higher Inflation
</P>
<P>
   The government said that a software error caused it to slightly
underestimate inflation during the first eight months of the year.
Revision of the data means somewhat higher payments for recipients
of Social Security and other federal benefits. And while economists
said that the error, 0.1 percent, was not large enough to
significantly alter their view of the nation's economy, it was
nonetheless in the direction of faster inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Daimlerchrysler Loss Seen
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG said that its Chrysler car group would report
a loss in the third quarter _ the first such loss since a recession
in the United States nine years ago _ and that Chrysler's highly
respected design chief, Thomas C. Gale, would retire at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Drug-Cost Bill May Not Dent Industry Profit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If a bill allowing imports of low-priced prescription drugs
becomes law, drug companies will be able to use a myriad of tactics
to protect their profits, Wall Street analysts said, and keep the
amount of the drugs to a minimum. Consumer groups gave the plan a
tepid thumbs-up, saying they would continue to push elected
officials to do more to rein in drug prices, which are now the
leading cause of the nation's rising health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. and Liberty Media in Asset Swap
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. and Liberty Media Group confirmed Wednesday that they
had agreed on a complex stock and asset swap in which Liberty Media
would increase its stake in News Corp. and News Corp. would pick up
Liberty's Gemstar-TV Guide International holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Gas Pipelines Proposed
</P>
<P>
   Energy companies, pipeline operators and Indian tribes expect to
announce next spring plans to build one, and possibly two,
subterranean pipelines to carry Arctic natural gas to North
America's pipeline grid.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline Drops on Sales Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the online retailer Priceline.com fell more than 40
percent after the company said its sales in the third quarter would
be as much as 11 percent below forecasts. The company attributed
the shortfall to slow sales of airline tickets _ its signature
product, which still account for 87 percent of its sales. Shares of
Priceline fell $7.89, to $10.75.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Slump on Earnings Concern
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell as investors continued to be concerned about
third-quarter results. The Dow Jones industrial average declined
2.96 points, to 10,628.36. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 32.80
points, or 0.9 percent, to 3,656.30. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 0.64 of a point, to 1,426.57.
</P>
<P>
   Audit Firm's Inspections Criticized
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be issued Thursday, an MIT professor contends
that PricewaterhouseCoopers, the world's largest factory-monitoring
firm, does a shoddy job and overlooks many safety and wage
violations in plants overseas. Pricewaterhouse disputed the
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston in Talks to Buy Summit
</P>
<P>
   Summit Bancorp, the largest bank in New Jersey, is in talks to
be acquired by FleetBoston Financial, executives close to the
discussions said. Analysts estimated the bank could be sold for $7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sale of Global Crossing Unit Is Seen
</P>
<P>
   In a move that would advance its lead in the business of storage
and maintenance facilities for Web sites, Exodus Communications is
close to acquiring the Web-hosting division of Global Crossing for
about $6.5 billion in stock, people close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic Names a Coordinator
</P>
<P>
   Bruce S. Nelson, an executive with experience in the account,
creative and strategic realms of advertising, is being named to a
new top post at Interpublic Group. Nelson will coordinate efforts
to manage the increasingly diversified Interpublic units
specializing in interactive and direct marketing, public relations,
media services, research, programming and consulting as well as
traditional advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Favors Release of Tire Data
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled that the public should have access to
extensive information on tire technology that Firestone had to turn
over during a lawsuit over a fatal accident. The company said
releasing the documents would amount to giving up trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Air France Sues in Concorde Crash
</P>
<P>
   Air France said that it had sued Continental Airlines because it
believed a metal strip from a Continental DC-10 that fell onto a
runway led to the crash of its Concorde jet in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
