<HEADER>
A4459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NY     09-27 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON OFFERS DEBT-REDUCTION PLAN; LAZIO QUESTIONS ITS VALUE
</HEADLINE>
 By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Supported by Robert Rubin, the former secretary of
the Treasury Department, and Warren Buffet, the billionaire
investor, Hillary Rodham Clinton pledged Wednesday to protect the
federal budget surplus from Republican ``tax schemes'' by proposing
legislation to limit tax cuts and new spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, laying out one of her most detailed plans for the
budget surplus since entering the New York Senate race, proposed
mandatory ``debt-reduction caps'' that would make it more difficult
for Congress to use expected budget surpluses for cutting taxes or
paying for new programs.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan, similar in general terms to the one proposed by Vice
President Al Gore, goes further than Gore's by setting aside more
money for debt reduction and imposing legislative hurdles for
making exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan, 20 percent of the budget surplus each year
over the next 10 years, apart from money for Social Security and
Medicare, would be reserved for reducing federal debt. That would
create a pool of about $360 billion, her campaign staff estimated.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress wanted to spend that money or use it to offset tax
cuts, it would have to do so by a vote of three-fifths of the
members of both houses, she said. In addition, the estimated $2.7
trillion surplus in the Social Security and Medicare accounts would
be set aside for debt reduction, she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to her campaign staff's estimates, Clinton's proposal
would devote about $60 billion more over the 10 years for debt
reduction than would Gore's budget-surplus plan. Gore's plan also
does not require a three-fifths vote for breaking the spending and
tax cut limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put first things first and be conservative in how
we use this surplus and project our expenditures,'' Clinton said
during an economic forum at Columbia University, where Rubin and
Buffet offered their support for her plan. ``I would propose that
we set some limits on what we can do with the surplus and just keep
everybody on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans said the spending habits of Clinton and the
Democrats, not their party's proposed tax cuts, are the biggest
threat to the surplus. Rep. Rick Lazio, speaking in Newburgh after
touring a riverfront development project, suggested that Clinton's
policy proposals would leave little of the surplus left to apply
toward reducing the debt. He cited a report by the National
Taxpayers Union, a conservative group, that said her economic and
education plans would nearly wipe out the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it's fine rhetoric, but when you add up the numbers, it
doesn't add up,'' Lazio said. ``My economic plan would reserve
three-quarters of the surplus to protect Social Security and
Medicare, pay down the debt and also invest in some important
priorities, like education.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used her budget-surplus proposal as an opportunity once
again to criticize Lazio's tax plan, which she says would give back
too much of the projected $4.5 trillion surplus to taxpayers, and
which Rubin said would ``reject fiscal discipline.'' Speaking to an
audience of students organized by the university's College
Democrats club, Clinton said they must look beyond their immediate
self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent the day in the Hudson Valley, touring businesses and
the Newburgh waterfront and speaking at a business breakfast in
Rockland County. The visits were intended to highlight the
potential for his plan for improving the economy through an
increase in partnerships between the federal government and the
private sector, and through lower taxes that Lazio says will
stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here is we're demonstrating that there is one
candidate in this race who has got the capacity to build the kind
of partnerships that will be necessary to improve the quality of
life for New York,'' Lazio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
