<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-MCSORLEY-TRIAL-NY     09-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCSORLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McSORLEY SAYS HE WANTED TO FIGHT, NOT INJURE  
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Offering more reasons than
remorse, Marty McSorley testified Wednesday that his stick-swinging
against Donald Brashear in a game last year was little more than an
unfortunate accident between National Hockey League enforcers.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the questioning of his lawyer, Bill Smart, McSorley spent
the entire third day of his trial on the witness stand and attacked
the assault charge. At issue is whether violence in a hockey game
can constitute criminal assault, but McSorley labeled such a
confrontation as common when emotions on the ice run high.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley testified that he did not mean to smash Brashear's head
with the blade of his stick in a game last Feb. 21 and that a
combination of bad aim and bad luck, including the path Brashear
took, contributed to the seriousness of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley admitted wanting to provoke a second fight late in the
game _ McSorley, then a defenseman with the Boston Bruins, and
Brashear, playing for the Vancouver Canucks, had fought in the
first period _ and send a larger message to the Canucks that the
Bruins were playing until the final horn of a 5-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told him, `Donald, you're going to have to fight me
again,''' McSorley testified. ``He said: `We're up 4-0. I don't
have to fight you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brashear, 28, a wing who was in his seventh season in the NHL,
hit the back of his head on the ice after McSorley hit him, got a
concussion, lost consciousness briefly while on the ice and
suffered lapses in memory. He returned to play several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley received the biggest fine and suspension in NHL
history, $72,000 and the final 23 games of last season. McSorley,
now a free agent, must meet with Commissioner Gary Bettman if he is
to play again.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are scheduled for Thursday before Judge
William Kitchen of Provincial Court, who is expected to render his
decision on Friday. If convicted, McSorley could be sentenced to up
to 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Smart argued Wednesday that injuries to McSorley's left shoulder
and wrist affected control of his stick and caused him to miss his
target, which McSorley described as shoulder level, just above the
number on Brashear's right sleeve. McSorley, 37, has since had
surgery on his shoulder and said doctors recommended that his wrist
needs fusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think I was going to miss?'' he said. ``No, it never
entered my mind. I've never missed like that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hicks, the regional prosecutor for Vancouver, hammered on
McSorley's talent and work ethic, which have produced a 17-year
career in the NHL. Hicks also contended that as a veteran player,
McSorley should have easily adjusted to Brashear's change in
position on the ice, and noted that Brashear said he did not want
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley responded that his action was an instinctive move to
lure Brashear into another fight, then engaged in a heated exchange
with Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McSorley, are you responsible for your stick on the ice?''
Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do the best you can,'' McSorley said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks repeated the question in a firmer voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hicks, do you know how many guys get cut over the course
of the season?'' McSorley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McSorley,'' Hicks said, ``how many players get hit with a
stick across their head and get knocked unconscious during a
season?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been instances, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hicks accused McSorley of deliberately attacking Brashear
in anger, McSorley said, ``Mr. Hicks, that is absolutely not true
and there has been no indication of that in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley and Smart explained that McSorley's hands never came
together on his stick, a distinction to show he did not maliciously
grip the stick to use it as a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley testified that he intended to hit Brashear with the
shaft, a foot or so above the blade, in the manner of a
cross-check, and thought that was what he had done. The slow-motion
videotape, though, clearly showed McSorley striking Brashear with
the heel of the blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see, as Donald comes across me, the harder he cuts, the
more he bends his knees and the more he tilts his shoulder,''
McSorley said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, who is not expected to be called as a witness,
created a buzz outside the courtroom when he arrived at McSorley's
trial. At one point, deputies taped white paper over the small
courtroom window to keep a growing crowd from trying to catch a
glimpse of Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to support my friend,'' said Gretzky, who played with
McSorley on the Edmonton Oilers' championship teams of the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
