<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERPUBLIC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INTERPUBLIC NAMES COORDINATOR OF ITS DIVERSE UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A seasoned executive with experience in the account,
creative and strategic realms of agency operations is being named
to a new top post at Interpublic Group of Cos. in New York. The
executive, Bruce S. Nelson, will coordinate efforts to manage the
increasingly diversified Interpublic units specializing in
interactive and direct marketing, public relations, media services,
research, programming and consulting as well as traditional
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Nelson, as executive vice president and chief
marketing officer at Interpublic, is indicative of the growing
importance of nonadvertising holdings to the Madison Avenue giants.
About half of Interpublic's revenue for 2000 will be derived from
fields outside the creation of television commercials and print
advertisements, compared with about a third two years ago and less
than a quarter four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, just last week, Interpublic realigned its public
relations agencies to form a shop, Weber Shandwick Worldwide, that
will become the world's largest in revenue, at an estimated $320
million, overtaking the Burson-Marsteller unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam
Inc., which is being acquired by the WPP Group. Recent Interpublic
acquisitions in nonadvertising fields include Adair-Greene, a
health care communications agency; Brands Hatch, a sports marketing
company; Capita Technologies, an e-business company; Cassidy Co., a
public relations agency; NFO Worldwide, a research company; and
Waylon Co., a sales promotion agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry has migrated from advertising solutions to
integrated marketing solutions,'' said John J. Dooner Jr.,
president and chief operating officer at Interpublic. ``All the
different marketing disciplines need to be rationalized so the
impact clients are looking for will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Bruce's responsibilities will be to take a look at our
portfolio of brands to be sure they are positioned properly,'' he
added, ``examining how can and should they be put together.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 48, will report to Dooner, who is to become chief
executive at Interpublic on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a sense the top guy's behind this,'' Nelson
said, because his new job calls for him to roam across the
Interpublic organizational chart, seeking ways to encourage the
disparate units to cooperate with each other if so required by
clients.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on nonadvertising operations ``represents a different
business model that we think will be huge,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic will rank No. 2 among agency companies in billings,
at $47.1 billion, and No. 3 in revenue, at $5.1 billion, after WPP
completes its pending acquisition of Y&AMP;R. The principal Interpublic
divisions are Draft Worldwide, Initiative Media Worldwide, Lowe
Group and McCann-Erickson World Group.
</P>
<P>
   In joining Interpublic, Nelson is returning to advertising after
taking a year off to spend more time with his family, he said.
Nelson left Y&AMP;R in September 1999 after 18 months there as vice
chairman and chief knowledge officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he saw the light not to do that for very long,''
Dooner said, laughing, referring to Nelson's stint at the rival
agency company.
</P>
<P>
   During his time off Madison Avenue, Nelson said, he became
involved with the dot-com world, becoming a director of three
companies: Official Payments Corp., Pcsupport.com and Zeborg Inc.
He will continue on those boards after joining Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   Dooner said he knew Nelson from the time they both spent at
McCann-Erickson. Dooner worked there from 1984 until he left for
Interpublic in April, and Nelson worked there from 1979 until he
left for Y&AMP;R in 1998, holding posts that included group creative
director; co-leader of an agency within the agency named Ira
Madris, Bruce Nelson &AMP; Colleagues; director for worldwide accounts;
and worldwide director for strategic creative development.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson recalled that Dooner called him ``during the summer and
said: `It's a brand-new company, and we're looking forward to where
we're going to go. And with half our interests outside advertising,
they're of a size now that we need someone to look at our
portfolio.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know me'' at Interpublic, Nelson added, ``and
know I have sat in their seat or in the seat next to theirs, so
this is not a theoretical sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   While at McCann-Erickson, Nelson worked for and with marketers
like American Express, Coca-Cola and Nestle.
</P>
<P>
   Dooner said that in his new post, Nelson would ``also be
available for some clients that need marketing strategy help _ and
he's already getting calls.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
