<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXODUS-GLOBAL-CROSSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL CROSSING'S WEB HOST MAY BE SOLD TO RIVAL EXODUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.)  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that would advance its lead in the business of storage
and maintenance facilities for company's Web sites, Exodus
Communications is close to acquiring the Web host division of
Global Crossing for about $6.5 billion in stock, people close to
the companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' boards planned to meet to discuss the complex
transaction, which would potentially make Global Crossing, the
operator of a global fiber optic communications network, the
largest shareholder in Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   Although most points of the transaction have been agreed upon by
the two companies' management, it is not yet clear whether a
definitive agreement will be reached. Talks on a similar deal
collapsed in July.
</P>
<P>
   Within the cutthroat Web host business, the potential
transaction signals further consolidation. Similar to other parts
of the telecommunications industry, it is increasingly a business
of size and scale in which smaller companies are priced out of
contracts by large competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size is everything because a larger Web-hosting company can
offer a larger array of services at lower cost,'' said Fred Moran,
an analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``Exodus is at the head of the pack,
but it must have been feeling the heat lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Exodus and Global Crossing may have felt pressure to pursue a
deal after WorldCom acquired Intermedia Communications for about $6
billion in stock and debt earlier this month, giving WorldCom
control of Digex Inc., another large manager of Web sites.
Intermedia rejected offers from Exodus and Global Crossing before
accepting WorldCom's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the transaction being discussed by Exodus and Global
Crossing, Exodus would issue new shares valued at approximately
$6.5 billion to pay for Global Center, Global Crossing's Web site
host unit. Effectively, this would give Global Crossing a 20
percent stake in Exodus, making it the company's largest
shareholder, people close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in a part of the transaction potentially worth
billions of dollars, Exodus would designate Global Crossing as its
primary network carrier for 10 years, committing to buy at least
half of its network needs from the company, which is based in
Hamilton, Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   And in Asia, Exodus and Global Crossing would form a separate
venture with Asia Global Crossing, a company controlled by Global
Crossing with partners including Microsoft and Softbank of Japan.
Exodus would control two-thirds and Global Crossing one-third of
the venture, people close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   For Global Crossing, the deal would help save about $1 billion
needed to build out its own network of data centers where clients
store their Internet servers in vaults. The relatively dim
prospects in the short term for a public offering of shares in its
Global Center unit may also have contributed to its eagerness for a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   For Exodus, of Santa Clara, Calif., the transaction would allow
the company to have guaranteed access to Global Crossing's network
instead of seeking out capacity on the networks of other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus has more than 2.3 million square feet of Web host space
at more than 20 centers across the country, where clients like
Yahoo and eBay store their servers on racks in vaults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
