<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-STREISAND-CONCERT-NYT     09-27 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREISAND-CONCERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT STREISAND'S ALMA MATER, FUNNY GIRL IS AN UNKNOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (With STREISAND-CONCERT-REVIEW)  
 (Eds: 13th graf begin: ``Ron Gubernot...'' is cq. They are both
men)  
(DUPLICATION WARING: The following story is also being sent with an
``e'' category code) 
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They couldn't quite place the name. There was
something slightly familiar about the photo. As for naming their
favorite Barbra Streisand song, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say, the students at Erasmus Hall High School, the
alma mater of the famous Brooklyn girl who made good, were not
among those clamoring to fork over up to $2,500 to see the first of
her New York shows at Madison Square Garden, which has been billed
as Streisand's last round of concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Though Streisand's portrait (with permed hair, circa ``Yentl''),
is part of a hallway mural celebrating the school's bicentennial in
1987, Jennifer Lino, 15, and Karla Moncayo, 14, froze behind their
hot fudge sundaes when asked if they knew who she was, and looked
awfully like they were trying to avoid being called on in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who? Who's that?'' asked Stacey Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline William knew. ``Barbra Streisand, that lady, with the
funny nose,'' she told her fellow freshmen. ``She sings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who y'all talking about,'' Crystal Ulett said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline tried again. ``She's white. With the gold hair.'' She
did not mention the 26 platinum albums, two Oscars or eight Grammy
awards.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph was produced. ``You know her face from somewhere,
right?'' Jacqueline said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Garden Wednesday night, one woman told a television
reporter that her hands were shaking from excitement. She offered
to sing ``Papa'' for the evening news, but broke off nervously,
suddenly forgetting the words.
</P>
<P>
   Two couples, the Turners and the Margetts, paid $475 for each
ticket and flew in from Derbyshire, England, for the concert. They
almost hired a limousine to take them, said Marlaine Margetts,
until they realized that their room, at the Hotel Pennsylvania, was
right across the street from the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Robin and Victor Nekrasovas and Gloria and Steve Salmanowitz
came from Monroe, N.J. The ladies did not care that their $225
tickets weren't so good. ``We're sitting in Queens, actually,''
said Nekrasovas. `` `Evergreen' is my wedding song.''
</P>
<P>
   But the men were less enthusiastic. ``If somebody comes up and
offers me $1,000,'' said Salmanowitz, ``they can have my ticket.
I'm going to Nathan's.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gubernot, 51, had surprised Evan Myron, 41, with tickets for
their 20th anniversary. Myron knew what to expect, down to the set
list. ``I'm a Barbra person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone said they loved Barbra. For some people, tickets were a
dream come true. But Peter A. Ciarlo of Middlebury, Conn., said he
was just making his wife, Debbie, happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband loves the way she sings but he doesn't love her
politics,'' Ciarlo said of the singer, who is known to support many
liberal causes.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Flatbush, William had an idea how to help Streisand
raise her profile. Streisand, she said, should come back to her old
high school. ``Mariah Carey found time to go back to her old
school,'' Jacqueline said. (Streisand did give Erasmus $25,000 in
1994, one of the principals, Carolyn Wagner, said later.)
</P>
<P>
   But if Streisand did pay a visit to Erasmus, would anyone
recognize her?
</P>
<P>
   Karim Smith, 15, thought he knew who she was. ``She was in that
one with the three witches? The thing on the Disney Channel?''
</P>
<P>
   Um. Maybe he meant Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Garcia, 18, knew precisely. ``That lady with the big
nose? She got married and the wedding was private, and nobody could
go to it?''
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the concert Wednesday night included Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, Christie Brinkley, the model, and Rosie
O'Donnell, the talk show host. Many of those who clutched tickets,
like Sue Booker of Walsall, England, whose husband had surprised
her with tickets last Sunday, had never seen the legend live
before.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand did not strike out everywhere in Brooklyn. ``I like
her, she's a nice girl,'' said Sydney Adams, 45, as he shaved
sugarcane with a knife on the corner of Church and Flatbush
Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a man selling CDs on a folding table said he had sold
out of Barbra albums just that morning. ``I only had three,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Williams, 23, pulled her gospel-blaring earphones out of
her ears to talk while she was on her way to her work at a day care
center. Yes, she nodded, she had a Streisand album. ``The one with
the Jewish song on it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Erasmus, the spirit of the singer lived on.
</P>
<P>
   Ebony Hogue, a sophomore in Erasmus' humanities and performing
arts program, refused to be daunted by her lack of familiarity with
the superstar. ``You know her?'' said the teen-ager, who wants to
be an actor. ``You could hook me up with her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000927.0515 </DOCNO>
