<HEADER>
A4475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A CHALLENGE MADE AND DISMISSED
</P>
<P>
   Washington state's candidates for the U.S. Senate have gotten
into a spat over the use of so-called soft money by outside groups
in their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic aspirant, former Rep. Maria Cantwell, wants all
independent groups that have been advertising on her behalf, as
well as the Democratic Party, to cease doing so. She also wants the
Republican incumbent, Slade Gorton, to issue such a pledge himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather lose without the benefit of soft money than win
with it,'' Cantwell said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton said the vow amounted to a ``phony pledge'' because
the great majority of the campaign spending by Cantwell, who made a
fortune estimated at $40 million as an Internet executive, has come
from her own bank account.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Cantwell's appeal, Gorton challenged her to make a
different pledge: to agree that at least 70 percent of her campaign
money would henceforth come from individual contributors other than
herself. Cantwell countered: ``Unlike Senator Gorton, I have only
one special interest _ the interest of the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   GENTLE RIBBING BY GORE
</P>
<P>
   Like many politicians, Vice President Al Gore has a long memory.
On a trip to Iowa on Wednesday, it stretched back to last winter
when Gore was campaigning against former Sen. Bill Bradley in that
state's caucuses. Iowa's Democratic governor, Thomas J. Vilsack,
remained studiously neutral at the time, while his wife, Christie,
enthusiastically backed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech at a community center in Altoona on Wednesday,
Gore acknowledged the presence of Vilsack, who now travels
regularly with the vice president on his visits to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to seeing Christie a little bit later,''
Gore said. ``Now, I'm glad to see you, Governor. But I've never let
him forget that Christie had just a little bit better political
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   During Gore's discussion on Medicare, 79-year-old Winifred
Skinner, a retiree from Des Moines, rose to tell Gore that she
collects aluminum cans several hours a day because her Social
Security and pension benefits will not pay for both her living
expenses and her prescription costs of $230 a month. ``How much do
you earn a week?'' Gore asked. ``You're not going to tell the
government, are you?'' Skinner answered, sending both Gore and the
audience into convulsions of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   BIG MONEY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   With Election Day now less than six weeks off, fund-raising is
more frenetic than ever. Just Wednesday night, Vice President Al
Gore raised more than $3.5 million for the Democratic National
Committee, bringing his total take for the party in the last 16
days to nearly $25 million and his total take since January to more
than $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attended two events, starting with a reception at a
downtown Washington hotel for the Women's Leadership Forum. More
than 800 people, paying $125 each, contributed about $500,000. He
then took his motorcade to a dinner at the Washington home of Sen.
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., where about 300 people, paying a minimum
of $5,000 each, contributed more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   THE TRAVEL LOG
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore continued his swing through the Midwest, talking health
care in Iowa and questioning George W. Bush's commitment to
improving the system. Bush, meanwhile, continued to work the West
Coast, talking education in Los Angeles and questioning Gore's
commitment to improvement. At the end of the day, both headed for
home, Bush back to Austin and Gore back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The stats:
</P>
<P>
   Length of the Official Day: Gore, 14 hours; Bush, 12 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   States Visited: Gore, 2; Bush, 2
</P>
<P>
   Towns and Cities Visited: Gore, 3; Bush, 2
</P>
<P>
   Events: Gore, 3; Bush, 4
</P>
<P>
   Press Conferences/Interviews: Gore, 13; Bush 6
</P>
<P>
   Debate preparation: Gore, 0 hours; Bush hours 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Diners Visited/Unscheduled Drop-bys: Gore, 0; Bush 0
</P>
<P>
   Main message: Gore, strengthening Medicare; Bush, strengthening
schools.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   PATRICK J. BUCHANAN Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Green Bay, Wis., , and Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Washington
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH I. LIEBERMAN Washington
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER No scheduled events
</P>
</TEXT>
