<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-WESTNILE-DEATH-NYT     09-27 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WESTNILE-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST NILE CLAIMS FIRST KNOWN U.S. VICTIM THIS YEAR IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey officials announced Wednesday that an 82-year-old man
died of the West Nile virus two weeks ago, the first person known
to die of the disease in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe it is most likely that the man was bitten in
August. He fell ill on Sept. 3, was admitted three days later to
Mountainside Hospital in Montclair, and died there on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis of West Nile was delayed while blood and tissue
studies were conducted. The man had chronic illnesses as well,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Gov. Christie Whitman and other state
officials did not name the man, but said he lived in Little Falls.
he was identified as Anthony Opalka by The Herald News of West
Paterson, The Associated Press reported Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there have been four cases of West Nile in New Jersey
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would call this an epidemic,'' Dr. Eddy A.
Bresnitz, the deputy state commissioner of health, said Wednesday
at the news conference in Hackensack. ``I think what we do have is
an outbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   A 72-year-old woman from Bayonne also contracted the disease in
the last few months, but she is already home recovering, officials
said. The other human cases previously confirmed in New Jersey
involved a 43-year-old man from Jersey City and a 54-year-old man
with homes in Cliffside Park and Brooklyn, N.Y. Both men were
hospitalized for treatment and are recovering.
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests were performed on 18 other people in the state whose
illnesses resembled West Nile, but the results are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, West Nile has been diagnosed this year in 13
people, including a 73-year-old woman from Queens who the city
announced Wednesday was hospitalized but recovering. Among the
other cases, eight were treated and released and four remain
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of birds and other animals have contracted the disease
this year, so many that many health care officials have been
surprised that more human cases did not emerge. Theories about why
that is range from crediting state prevention campaigns to musing
about the weather: Did cold air keep people inside? Did the wet
summer keep birds around so mosquitoes were drawn to them instead
of to humans?
</P>
<P>
   While state officials never like to have any cases in their
areas, the New York region has fared far better than Israel, where
14 people have died of West Nile this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, West Nile killed seven people in the New York region
and severely sickened 55 others.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Wednesday that New Jersey would re-evaluate its
West Nile control plan, which has included spraying insecticide to
kill adult mosquitoes in every county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a disease that's going to be with us for
some time,'' Whitman said. ``And I intend after this season is over
to ask the relevant cabinet members, including the secretary of
commerce and economic growth, the secretary of agriculture, the
commissioner of health and senior services, to get together and to
reassess everything that we have done.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Insecticides have been sprayed this year in all five New York
City boroughs and in Westchester and Rockland Counties, on Long
Island and in Connecticut and New Jersey, though not always to the
satisfaction of New York City officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani complained earlier this year that
northern New Jersey and Nassau County were endangering public
health by not spraying aggressively enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
