<SLUG> BC-MRS-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST LADY HEADS WEST TO RAISE MONEY, BOTH HARD AND SOFT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Okla., Nev., Calif.) By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton began a three-day fund-raising trip
outside New York Wednesday with a visit to Oklahoma City, where her
host was a former state attorney general who came under scrutiny in
one of the fund-raising investigations involving her husband's
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then held an event in Las Vegas on Wednesday night, and
after that travels to the Los Angeles area for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, has criticized her for relying
heavily on contributions from Hollywood celebrities, a traditional
fund-raising source for Democrats, and at first, her aides would
not disclose the names of sponsors of the California events.
</P>
<P>
   They later acknowledged that one host would be Cher. The others
include the financier Marvin Davis and his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money from the fund-raising trip is expected to go
to Clinton's Senate campaign, but she also plans to collect soft
money for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York contest, she and her Democratic allies have
tentatively agreed not to spend soft money _ the largely
unregulated contributions collected by parties in an effort to
circumvent contribution limits _ under an arrangement with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, who headed West after addressing an economic forum
at Columbia University on Wednesday morning, has said she will
continue to raise soft money, which would be used to help other
Democrats, not her candidacy, as long as the New York arrangement
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Clinton has received about 60 percent of her campaign
contributions from out of state, more than Lazio or most Senate
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Lazio has a clear financial advantage in this race
because he has raised millions out-of-state with his insult-filled
direct mail,'' said Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for the Clinton
campaign. ``As a result, we have to work harder to be
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City Wednesday, the host for a fund-raising luncheon
for Clinton was Michael Turpen, the former state attorney general
and one of the state's most prominent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Turpen's fund-raising activities were examined by congressional
Republicans in 1997 after he raised a large donation for the
Democratic National Committee from an Indian tribe in Oklahoma that
has sought to reclaim federal land that the tribe believes was
stolen from it.
</P>
<P>
   Turpen had been hired as a lobbyist by the tribe, the
Cheyenne-Arapaho. He suggested to tribal leaders that they could
gain access to federal officials if they pledged a $100,000
donation to the Democrats, tribal leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders were soon invited to a lunch with President Clinton
at the White House, where they asked him for help on the land
issue. The president, according to the tribal leaders, said he
would look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The president ultimately took no action, and after the
circumstances surrounding the donation were publicized, the
Democratic National Committee returned the money. But Republicans
in Congress who investigated the affair called it part of a pattern
of Democratic fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, the spokesman for Clinton's campaign, said the
fund-raiser sponsored by Turpen Wednesday was ``perfectly legal and
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Turpen did not respond to two messages left for him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Clinton's campaign manager, Bill de Blasio, sent
a letter to the National Abortion Rights Action League, requesting
that it refrain from airing any advertising attacking Lazio for his
position on abortion, in deference to the agreement between the
Lazio and Clinton campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the group had initially chafed at the deal, arguing
that it interfered with their rights. After meeting Wednesday,
board members said they would unveil a new advertisement Thursday,
but pointedly did not say whether the advertisement would be aired.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said Wednesday night that it was likely that
NARAL would unveil the ad Thursday, expecting that it would be the
subject of news reports, but would not buy ad time in deference to
the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
