u a BC-OBIT-PADILLA-NYT &LR;      09-27 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PADILLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEBERTO PADILLA, 68, CUBAN POET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ohio, N.Y.)   By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heberto Padilla, an acclaimed Cuban poet whose criticism of
Fidel Castro's rule landed him first in jail and later in exile,
died Sept. 25 in Auburn, Ala., where he had recently become a
writer in residence at Auburn University. He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla was found dead in his apartment on Monday by a colleague
who went searching for him after he had missed three classes, a
university spokesman said. Police said that Padilla had died of
natural causes. Friends reported that he had had a history of heart
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla, an early supporter of the Castro revolution known for
his cool, ironic style, became famous abroad in 1971 when he was
jailed on charges of having ``plotted against the powers of the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be forever known as the first poet to have the stature
and courage to object to the repression of Fidel Castro's regime,''
said Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria, the Sterling professor of Spanish
and comparative literature at Yale University, and chairman of the
department of Spanish and Portuguese literature. ``And he suffered
immensely for it, not the least being his death in exile, alone in
Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1971 Padilla was released after a month of brutal
interrogation during which he was forced to make a humiliating
4,000-word public confession.
</P>
<P>
   His jailing and the ``confession'' that followed set off an
international protest as writers around the world, from Jean-Paul
Sartre to Alberto Moravia to Susan Sontag, rose to his defense: for
some left-leaning authors, it was the event that forever changed
the way they viewed Castro's Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   After 1971 Padilla's works were banned in his native country.
For the next nine years he managed to earn a living by translating
English poetry and ghostwriting. In 1980, after another campaign
led by Robert B. Silvers, editor of The New York Review of Books,
he was finally given permission by Castro to leave Cuba and join
his wife, other members of his family and the poet Belkis Cuza Male
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, ``Self-Portrait of the Other,'' published by
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux in 1990, Padilla recounted his last
conversation with Castro, a man he had known since his youth.
</P>
<P>
   After telling Padilla he was free to leave Cuba, Castro added:
``Stay as long as you want, and when you want to come back, give me
a call. If you are a true revolutionary, you will want to return.''
Castro went on to characterize those who dared to stray from
official orthodoxy. ``People who criticize a revolution may be
mistaken, they may be sincere, but they are dangerous
nonetheless,'' Castro was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla maintained a detached view of the Cuban leader, whom he
described in his book as an anachronism who had grown deaf to the
opinions of his own countrymen and was stuck like a fly in the
amber of an outdated Marxist-Leninism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 Padilla, then 27, had enthusiastically embraced the
revolution, which brought him back home from the United States,
where he had been working as a radio commentator and translater. He
became one of the founding editors of Lunes de Revolucion, a
literary journal, and worked for Prensa Latina, the Cuban news
agency, and Granma, the Cuban Communist Party newspaper, as a
foreign correspondent based in Moscow and London.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1968 his relations with the Castro government and its
cultural commissars had begun to sour, and he was recalled to
Havana. When his book of poetry, ``Out of the Game,'' won a
first-place prize in a literary competition, he and the book were
denounced by the Cuban Writers Union as ``counterrevolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two daughters, Giselle and Maria; two sons,
Carlos and Ernesto; a sister, Martha; a brother, Gilberto; and his
companion, Lourdes Gil, a faculty member at the New School
University (formerly known as the New School for Social Research)
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mazzotti, a professor of Latin American literature at
Harvard University, described Padilla as one of the Latin American
poets to develop a ``conversational'' style with strong visual and
sensual images that was to mark a break with earlier European
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrival in the United States, Padilla resumed work on
a novel, ``Heroes Are Grazing in My Garden,'' which he had begun in
Cuba but which had been confiscated by the authorities. The book
was published in 1983. In 1982 the first book-length collection of
his poetry, ``Legacies: Selected Poems,'' was published for the
first time in English. A book of new poetry titled ``A Fountain, a
House of Stone,'' was published in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   While living in Princeton, N.J., Padilla and his wife published
a literary journal, Linden Lane, that became a forum for young
Latin American writers. Padillo taught literature at a number of
institutions in the United States, including Ohio State University,
Bowdoin College and New York University's New York Institute for
the Humanities.
</P>
<P>
   At Auburn University, where he had begun working five weeks ago,
Padilla taught undergraduate courses in Spanish composition and
conversation, as well as a graduate seminar in Hispanic literature
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``His poetry reflected and reflected upon the ongoing historical
process,'' said Gonzalez Echevarria. ``But he proved Plato was
right when he said poets are not welcome in the republic when they
say uncomfortable things about the tyrants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
