<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY ON HIS MIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marques Anderson is in Westwood, but his heart is
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the Bruins' strong safety who will be sidelined
Saturday against Arizona State, will be thinking of his sister,
Andrea, over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   She is running a leg on the United States' 1,600-meter relay
team during the preliminary heats, which begin Friday night on the
West Coast. It is uncertain whether she will run in Saturday's
final should the U.S. qualify as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my sister are like best friends,'' said Anderson. ``I
hate missing that experience, but I've got obligations here.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's parents, Maurice and Susan, flew to Sydney on Monday.
They also have Marques' cell-phone number so he won't have to wait
for the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they better call,'' he said. ``I don't want them
to leave me out of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Been there, done that: When Ryan McCann was a senior at
Agoura High, he suffered the same injury that sidelined Cory Paus
for four games _ a separated throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   McCann said his was a second-degree separation, slightly worse
than Paus' injury. He missed 4 games and was able to return for the
final two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stiff,'' McCann said of his left shoulder. ``But I
played through it. I felt sore and I didn't have as much on the
ball. A week after, it was much better.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Krohn ill: Arizona State quarterback Jeff Krohn missed
practice Wednesday night because of flu symptoms, leaving his
status for Saturday's game in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   If Krohn is unable to start, the Sun Devils can turn to
fifth-year senior Ryan Kealy.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, a three-year starter, has thrown for 6,361 yards and 45
touchdowns. He missed spring practice after his fifth knee surgery
and was suspended during fall camp and the first two games for
testing positive for marijuana following a traffic stop by police.
</P>
<P>
   __ True Numbers: UCLA has used just three freshmen this season _
receiver and kick returner Tab Perry, reserve linebacker Brandon
Chillar and reserve cornerback Keith Short. Barring injuries, the
rest of the freshman class will redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, this would be the fewest number of freshman to play
since 1992, when quarterback Ryan Fien, running back Sharmon Shah
and tackle Jonathan Ogden all played.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
